WEBVTT

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:28.640
It is a truth universally acknowledged that a single man in possession of a good fortune must be in want of a wife.

00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:35.440
However little known the feelings or views of such a man may be on his first entering a neighbourhood,

00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:44.180
this truth is so well fixed in the minds of the surrounding families that he is considered the rightful property of someone or other of their daughters.

00:00:45.580 --> 00:00:51.840
My dear Mr. Bennet, said his lady to him one day, have you heard that Netherfield Park is let at last?

00:00:52.880 --> 00:01:00.420
Mr. Bennet replied that he had not, but it is returned she, for Mrs. Long has just been here and she told me all about it.

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:02.760
Mr. Bennet made no answer.

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:07.320
Do you not want to know who has taken it? cried his wife impatiently.

00:01:08.060 --> 00:01:11.660
You want to tell me, and I have no objection to hearing it.

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:14.160
This was invitation enough.

00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:22.800
Why, my dear, you must know Mrs. Long says that Netherfield is taken by a young man of large fortune from the north of England.

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:33.420
That he came down on Monday in a chasin four to see the place, and was so much delighted with it that he agreed with Mr. Morris immediately that he is to take possession before Mickelness,

00:01:33.880 --> 00:01:37.060
and some of his servants are to be in the house by the end of the week.

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:39.240
What is his name?

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:40.860
Bingley.

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:42.780
Is he married or single?

00:01:42.780 --> 00:01:44.940
Oh, single, my dear, to be sure.

00:01:45.140 --> 00:01:47.120
A single man of large fortune.

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:49.300
Four or five thousand a year.

00:01:49.580 --> 00:01:51.640
What a fine thing for our girls.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:53.700
How so?

00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:55.220
How can it affect them?

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:00.000
My dear Mr. Bennet, replied his wife, how can you be so tiresome?

00:02:00.280 --> 00:02:03.200
You must know that I am thinking of his marrying one of them.

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:06.120
Is that his design in settling here?

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:07.720
Design?

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:08.760
Nonsense.

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:10.020
How can you talk so?

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:16.880
But it is very likely that he may fall in love with one of them, and therefore you must visit him as soon as he comes.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:19.500
I see no occasion for that.

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:24.860
You and the girls may go, or you may send them by themselves, which perhaps will be still better.

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:30.500
For as you are as handsome as any of them, Mr. Bingley might like you the best of the party.

00:02:31.480 --> 00:02:32.840
My dear, you flatter me.

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:38.820
I certainly have had my share of beauty, but I do not pretend to be anything extraordinary now.

00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:44.320
When a woman has five grown-up daughters, she ought to give over thinking of her own beauty.

00:02:45.700 --> 00:02:49.580
In such cases, a woman has not often much beauty to think of.

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:54.740
But my dear, you must indeed go and see Mr. Bingley when he comes into the neighborhood.

00:02:55.740 --> 00:02:58.960
It is more than I engage for, I assure you.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:01.500
But consider your daughters.

00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:04.640
Only think what an establishment it would be for one of them.

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:09.180
Sir William and Lady Lucas are determined to go, merely on that account.

00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:11.980
For in general, you know, they visit no newcomers.

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:16.540
Indeed, you must go, for it will be impossible for us to visit him if you do not.

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:19.440
You are over-scrupulous, surely.

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:22.600
I dare say Mr. Bingley will be very glad to see you.

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:29.300
And I will send him a few lines by you to assure him of my hearty consent to his marrying whichever he chooses of the girls.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:33.140
Though I must throw in a good word for my little Lizzie.

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:35.740
I desire you will do no such thing.

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:38.100
Lizzie is not a bit better than the others.

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:42.760
I am sure she is not half so handsome as Jane, nor half so good-humored as Lydia.

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:45.400
But you are always giving her the preference.

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:49.380
They have none of them much to recommend, replied he.

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:51.940
They are all silly and ignorant like other girls.

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:55.040
But Lizzie has something more of quickness than her sisters.

00:03:56.480 --> 00:04:00.180
Mr. Bennet, how can you abuse your own children in such a way?

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:02.300
You take delight in vexing me.

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:04.800
You have no compassion for my poor nerves.

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:06.860
You mistake me, my dear.

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:09.160
I have a high respect for your nerves.

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:10.900
They are my old friends.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.820
I have heard you mention them with consideration these last twenty years at least.

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:17.600
Ah, you do not know what I suffer.

00:04:18.280 --> 00:04:22.720
But I hope you will get over it and live to see many young men of four thousand a year come into the neighbourhood.

00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:27.280
It will be no use to us if twenty such should come, since you will not visit them.

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:32.180
Depend upon it, my dear, that when there are twenty I will visit them all.

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:38.440
Mr. Bennet was so odd a mixture of quick parts, sarcastic humour, reserve and caprice

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:43.740
that the experience of three and twenty years had been insufficient to make his wife understand his character.

00:04:44.820 --> 00:04:47.020
Her mind was less difficult to develop.

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:52.620
She was a woman of mean understanding, little information and uncertain temper.

00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:57.040
When she was discontented she fancied herself nervous.

00:04:57.500 --> 00:05:00.420
The business of her life was to get her daughters married.

00:05:01.120 --> 00:05:03.960
Its solace was visiting and news.

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:10.140
Mr. Bennet was among the earliest of those who waited on Mr. Bingley.

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:15.820
He had always intended to visit him, though to the last always assuring his wife he should not go.

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:19.740
Until the evening after the visit was paid she had no knowledge of it.

00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:22.420
It was then disclosed in the following manner.

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:26.680
Observing his second daughter employed in trimming a hat, he suddenly addressed her with,

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:29.180
I hope Mr. Bingley will like it, Lizzie.

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:35.020
We are not in a way to know what Mr. Bingley likes, said her mother resentfully, since we are not to visit.

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:40.040
But you forget, Mama, said Elizabeth, that we shall meet him at the assemblies,

00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:42.720
and that Mrs. Long promised to introduce him.

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:45.820
I do not believe Mrs. Long will do any such thing.

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:51.440
She has two nieces of her own. She is a selfish, hypocritical woman, and I have no opinion of her.

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:57.860
No more have I, said Mr. Bennet, and I am glad to find that you do not depend on her serving you.

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:03.940
Mrs. Bennet deigned not to make any reply, but, unable to contain herself, began scolding one of her daughters.

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:06.800
Don't keep coughing so, Kitty, for heaven's sake!

00:06:07.060 --> 00:06:10.160
Have a little compassion on my nerves. You tear them to pieces.

00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:14.520
Kitty has no discretion in her coughs, said her father.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:16.080
She times them ill.

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:20.080
I do not cough for my own amusement, replied Kitty fretfully.

00:06:21.060 --> 00:06:22.740
When is your next ball to be, Lizzie?

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:24.940
Tomorrow fortnight.

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:29.580
Aye, so it is, cried her mother, and Mrs. Long did not come back till the day before,

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:33.740
so it would be impossible for her to introduce him, for she will not know him herself.

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:40.260
Then, my dear, you may have the advantage of your friend, and introduce Mr. Bingley to her.

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:45.140
Impossible, Mr. Bennet, impossible, when I am not acquainted with him myself.

00:06:45.460 --> 00:06:46.800
How can you be so teasing?

00:06:48.100 --> 00:06:49.720
I honour your circumspection.

00:06:50.180 --> 00:06:52.440
A fortnight's acquaintance is certainly very little.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:55.800
One cannot know what a man really is by the end of a fortnight.

00:06:56.560 --> 00:06:58.840
But if we do not venture, somebody else will.

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:02.780
And after all, Mrs. Long and her daughters must stand their chance.

00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:06.780
And therefore, as she will think it an act of kindness,

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:10.460
if you decline the office, I will take it on myself.

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:13.440
The girls stared at their father.

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:16.100
Mrs. Bennet said only, Nonsense, nonsense.

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:20.500
What can be the meaning of that emphatic exclamation, cried he?

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:24.520
Do you consider the forms of introduction and the stress that is laid on them as nonsense?

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:26.940
I cannot quite agree with you there.

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:28.420
What say you, Mary?

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:34.060
For you are a young lady of deep reflection, I know, and read great books and make extracts.

00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:38.380
Mary wished to say something sensible, but knew not how.

00:07:40.080 --> 00:07:44.380
While Mary is adjusting her ideas, he continued, let us return to Mr. Bingley.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.560
I am sick of Mr. Bingley, cried his wife.

00:07:48.500 --> 00:07:52.140
I am sorry to hear that, but why did you not tell me that before?

00:07:52.720 --> 00:07:55.920
If I had known as much this morning, I certainly would not have called on him.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:57.420
It is very unlikely.

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:02.200
But as I have actually paid the visit, we cannot escape the acquaintance now.

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:06.720
The astonishment of the ladies was just what he wished.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:09.360
That of Mrs. Bennet, perhaps surpassing the rest.

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:15.200
Though when the first tumult of joy was over, she began to declare that it was what she had expected all the while.

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:21.600
How good it was in you, my dear Mr. Bennet, but I knew I should persuade you at last.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:25.520
I was sure you loved your girls too well to neglect such an acquaintance.

00:08:25.780 --> 00:08:27.300
Well, how pleased I am.

00:08:27.300 --> 00:08:32.660
And it is such a good joke, too, that you should have gone this morning and never said a word about it till now.

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:37.480
Now, Kitty, you make off as much as you choose, said Mr. Bennet.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.620
And as he spoke, he left the room, fatigued with the raptures of his wife.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:45.720
What an excellent father you have, girls, said she, when the door was shut.

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:51.000
I do not know how you will ever make amends for his kindness, or me either, for that matter.

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:56.220
At our time of life it is not so pleasant, I can tell you, to be making new acquaintances every day.

00:08:56.220 --> 00:08:58.980
But for your sakes we would do anything.

00:08:59.860 --> 00:09:04.940
Lydia, my love, though you are the youngest, I dare say Mr. Bingley will dance with you at the next born.

00:09:06.100 --> 00:09:11.180
Oh, said Lydia Stoutly, I am not afraid, for though I am the youngest, I am the tallest.

00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:20.120
The rest of the evening was spent in conjecturing how soon he would return Mr. Bennet's visit, and determining when they should ask him to dinner.

00:09:22.780 --> 00:09:28.420
Not all that Mrs. Bennet, however, with the assistance of her five daughters, could ask on the subject,

00:09:28.780 --> 00:09:33.120
was sufficient to draw from her husband any satisfactory description of Mr. Bingley.

00:09:34.080 --> 00:09:40.300
They attacked him in various ways, with barefaced questions, ingenious suppositions, and distant surmises,

00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:47.480
but he eluded the skill of them all, and they were at last obliged to accept the second-hand intelligence of their neighbour, Lady Lucas.

00:09:47.480 --> 00:09:52.060
Her report was highly favourable. So William had been delighted with him.

00:09:52.360 --> 00:10:00.380
He was quite young, wonderfully handsome, extremely agreeable, and to crown the whole he meant to be at the next assembly with a large party.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:10.440
Nothing could be more delightful. To be fond of dancing was a certain step towards falling in love, and very lively hopes of Mr. Bingley's heart were entertained.

00:10:11.480 --> 00:10:21.380
If I can but see one of my daughters happily settled at Netherfield, said Mrs. Bennet to her husband, and all the others equally well married, I shall have nothing to wish for.

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:27.560
In a few days Mr. Bingley returned to Mr. Bennet's visit, and sat about ten minutes with him in his library.

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:35.680
He had entertained hopes of being admitted to a sight of the young ladies, of whose beauty he had heard much, but he saw only the father.

00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:44.640
The ladies were somewhat more fortunate, for they had the advantage of ascertaining from an upper window that he wore a blue coat and rode a black horse.

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:55.960
An invitation to dinner was soon afterwards dispatched, and already had Mrs. Bennet planned the courses that were to do credit to her housekeeping when an answer arrived which deferred it all.

00:10:56.600 --> 00:11:03.540
Mr. Bingley was obliged to be in town the following day, and consequently unable to accept the honour of their invitation, etc.

00:11:04.100 --> 00:11:11.240
Mrs. Bennet was quite disconcerted. She could not imagine what business he could have in town so soon after his arrival in Hertfordshire.

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:19.760
And she began to fear that he might be always flying about from one place to another, and never settled at Netherfield as he ought to be.

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:27.060
Lady Lucas quieted her fears a little by stating the idea of his being gone to London only to get a large party for the ball.

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:32.940
And a report soon followed that Mr. Bingley was to bring twelve ladies and seven gentlemen with him to the assembly.

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:45.020
The girls grieved over such a number of ladies, but were comforted the day before the ball by hearing that instead of twelve he brought only six with him from London, his five sisters and a cousin.

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:56.220
And when the party entered the assembly room it consisted of only five altogether. Mr. Bingley, his two sisters, the husband of the eldest and another young man.

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:07.620
Mr. Bingley was good-looking and gentleman-like. He had a pleasant countenance and easy, unaffected manners. His sisters were fine women with an air of decided fashion.

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:16.660
His brother-in-law, Mr. Hurst, nearly looked the gentleman, but his friend Mr. Darcy soon drew the attention of the room by his fine, tall person.

00:12:17.060 --> 00:12:26.200
Handsome features, noble mane, and the report, which was in general circulation within five minutes of his entrance, of his having ten thousand a year.

00:12:27.220 --> 00:12:33.040
The gentleman pronounced him to be a fine figure of a man. The ladies declared he was much handsomer than Mr. Bingley.

00:12:33.040 --> 00:12:42.000
And he was looked at with great admiration for about half the evening, till his manners gave a disgust which turned to the tide of his popularity.

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:47.580
For he was discovered to be proud, to be above his company, and above being pleased.

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:57.460
And not all his large estate in Derbyshire could then save him from having a most forbidding, disagreeable countenance and being unworthy to be compared with his friend.

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:02.740
Mr. Bingley had soon made himself acquainted with all the principal people in the room.

00:13:03.160 --> 00:13:11.020
He was lively and unreserved, danced every dance, was angry for the ball close so early, and talked of giving one himself at Netherfield.

00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:14.340
Such amiable qualities must speak for themselves.

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:24.260
What a contrast between him and his friend. Mr. Darcy danced only once with Mrs. Hurst, and once with Miss Bingley, declined being introduced to any other lady,

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:29.740
and spent the rest of the evening in walking about the room, speaking occasionally to one of his own party.

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:37.780
His character was decided. He was the proudest, most disagreeable man in the world, and everybody hoped he would never come there again.

00:13:38.840 --> 00:13:48.040
Amongst the most violent against him was Mrs. Bennet, whose dislike of his general behaviour was sharpened into particular resentment by his having slighted one of her daughters.

00:13:49.460 --> 00:13:54.280
Elizabeth Bennet had been obliged, by the scarcity of gentlemen, to sit down for two dances,

00:13:54.720 --> 00:14:00.940
and during part of that time Mr. Darcy had been standing near enough for her to hear a conversation between him and Mr. Bingley,

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:04.900
who came from the dance for a few minutes to press his friend to join it.

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:13.740
Come, Darcy, said he, I must have you dance. I hate to see you standing about by yourself in this stupid manner. You had much better dance.

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:19.980
I certainly shall not. You know how I detest it, unless I am particularly acquainted with my partner.

00:14:20.620 --> 00:14:30.480
At such an assembly as this it would be insupportable. Your sisters are engaged, and there is not another woman in the room whom it would not be a punishment to me to stand up with.

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:40.820
I would not be so fastidious as you are, cried Mr. Bingley, for a kingdom. Upon my honour I never met with so many pleasant girls in my life as I have this evening,

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:44.340
and there are several of them, you see, uncommonly pretty.

00:14:45.440 --> 00:14:52.220
You are dancing with the only handsome girl in the room, said Mr. Darcy, looking at the eldest Miss Bennet.

00:14:52.620 --> 00:15:02.080
Oh, she is the most beautiful creature I ever beheld. But there is one of her sisters sitting down just behind you who is very pretty, and I dare say very agreeable.

00:15:02.540 --> 00:15:04.940
Do let me ask my partner to introduce you.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:13.160
Which do you mean? And turning round he looked for a moment at Elizabeth, till catching her eye he withdrew his own and coldly said,

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:22.080
She is tolerable, but not handsome enough to tempt me. I am in no humour at present to give consequence to young ladies who are slighted by other men.

00:15:22.740 --> 00:15:27.580
You had better return to your partner and enjoy her smiles, for you are wasting your time with me.

00:15:28.620 --> 00:15:36.540
Mr. Bingley followed his advice. Mr. Darcy walked off, and Elizabeth remained with no very cordial feelings towards him.

00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:44.560
She told the story, however, with great spirit among her friends, for she had a lively, playful disposition which delighted in anything ridiculous.

00:15:46.180 --> 00:15:53.820
The evening altogether passed off pleasantly to the whole family. Mrs. Bennet had seen her eldest daughter much admired by the Netherfield party.

00:15:53.820 --> 00:16:04.060
Mr. Bingley had danced with her twice, and she had been distinguished by her sisters. Jane was as much gratified by this as her mother could be, though in a quieter way.

00:16:04.620 --> 00:16:10.800
Elizabeth felt Jane's pleasure. Mary had heard herself mentioned to Miss Bingley as the most accomplished girl in the neighbourhood,

00:16:11.320 --> 00:16:17.720
and Catherine and Lydia had been fortunate enough never to be without partners, which was all that they had yet learnt to care for as of all.

00:16:18.420 --> 00:16:25.080
They returned, therefore, in good spirits to Longbourn, the village where they lived, and of which they were the principal inhabitants.

00:16:26.100 --> 00:16:37.680
They found Mr. Bennet still up. With a book, he was regardless of time, and on the present occasion he had a good deal of curiosity as to the events of the evening which had raised such splendid expectations.

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:46.240
He had rather hoped that his wife's fuse on the stranger would be disappointed, but he soon found out that he had a different story to hear.

00:16:47.160 --> 00:16:57.460
Oh, my dear Mr. Bennet, as she entered the room, we have had a most delightful evening, a most excellent ball. I wish you had been there. Jane was so admired, and nothing could be like it.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:10.800
Everybody said how well she looked, and Mr. Bingley thought her quite beautiful and danced with her twice. Only think of that, my dear. He actually danced with her twice, and she was the only creature in the room that he asked a second time.

00:17:11.320 --> 00:17:24.320
First of all, he asked Mr. Lucas, I was so vexed to see him stand up with her. But, however, he did not admire her at all. Indeed, nobody can, you know, and he seemed quite struck with Jane as she was going down the dance.

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:29.900
So he inquired who she was, and got introduced, and asked her for the next two.

00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:39.000
Then the two-third he danced with Miss King, and the two-fourth with Maria Lucas, and the two-fifth with Jane again, and the two-sixth with Lizzie, and the boulanger.

00:17:39.560 --> 00:17:50.300
If he had any compassion for me, cried her husband impatiently, he would not have danced half so much. For God's sake, say no more of his partner. Oh, that he had sprained his ankle in the first place.

00:17:50.300 --> 00:18:00.880
Oh, my dear, I am quite delighted with him. He is so excessively handsome, and his sisters are charming women. I never in my life saw anything more elegant than their dresses.

00:18:01.560 --> 00:18:10.520
I dare say the lace upon Mrs. Hurst's gown... Here she was interrupted again. Mr. Bennet protested against any description of finery.

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:20.720
She was therefore obliged to seek another branch of the subject, and related with much bitterness of spirit, and some exaggeration, the shocking rudeness of Mr. Darcy.

00:18:21.700 --> 00:18:31.700
But I can assure you, she added, that Lizzie does not lose much by not suiting his fancy, for he is a most disagreeable horrid man, not at all worth pleasing.

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:42.180
So high and so conceited, that there was no enduring him. He walked here, and he walked there, fancying himself so very great, not handsome enough to dance with.

00:18:42.740 --> 00:18:48.200
I wish you had been there, my dear, to have given him one of your set-downs. I quite detest the man.

00:19:26.120 --> 00:19:32.160
When Jane and Elizabeth were alone, the former, who had been cautious in her praise of Mr.

00:19:32.300 --> 00:19:37.760
Bingley before, expressed to her sister just how very much she admired him.

00:19:38.900 --> 00:19:45.680
"'He is just what a young man ought to be,' said she,—sensible, good-humoured, lively,

00:19:46.180 --> 00:19:51.640
and I never saw such happy manners, so much ease, with such perfect good breeding.

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:58.240
"'He is also handsome,' replied Elizabeth, which a young man ought likewise to be if

00:19:58.240 --> 00:20:01.800
he possibly can. His character is thereby complete.

00:20:03.080 --> 00:20:08.220
"'I was very much flattered by his asking me to dance a second time. I did not expect

00:20:08.220 --> 00:20:09.040
such a compliment.'

00:20:10.740 --> 00:20:17.240
"'Did not you? I did for you. But that is one great difference between us. Compliments

00:20:17.240 --> 00:20:20.440
always take you by surprise, and me never.'

00:20:21.740 --> 00:20:26.760
"'What could be more natural than his asking you again? He could not help seeing that you

00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:31.780
were about five times as pretty as every other woman in the room. No thanks to his gallantry

00:20:31.780 --> 00:20:38.100
for that. Well, he certainly is very agreeable, and I give you leave to like him. You have

00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:39.520
liked many a stupider person.'

00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:42.700
"'Dear Lizzie!'

00:20:43.960 --> 00:20:49.900
"'Oh, you are a good deal too apt, you know, to like people in general. You never see a

00:20:49.900 --> 00:20:56.020
fault in anybody. All the world are good and agreeable in your eyes. I never heard you

00:20:56.020 --> 00:21:03.300
speak ill of a human being in your life. I would not wish to be hasty in censuring anyone,

00:21:03.620 --> 00:21:10.120
but I always speak what I think. I know you do, and it is that which makes the wonder.

00:21:10.600 --> 00:21:17.880
With your good sense, to be so honestly blind to the follies and nonsense of others, affectation

00:21:17.880 --> 00:21:24.280
of candour is common enough—one meets with it everywhere—but to be candid without ostentation

00:21:24.280 --> 00:21:29.540
or design, to take the good of everybody's character and make it still better, and say

00:21:29.540 --> 00:21:35.840
nothing of the bad, belongs to you alone. And so you like this man's sisters too, do

00:21:35.840 --> 00:21:39.720
you? Their manners are not equal to his.'

00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:46.060
"'Certainly not, at first. But they are very pleasing women when you converse with them.

00:21:46.640 --> 00:21:51.400
Miss Bingley is to live with her brother and keep his house, and I am much mistaken if

00:21:51.400 --> 00:21:55.560
we shall not find a very charming neighbour in her.'

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:00.900
Elizabeth listened in silence, but was not convinced. Their behaviour at the assembly

00:22:00.900 --> 00:22:06.820
had not been calculated to please in general, and with more quickness of observation and

00:22:06.820 --> 00:22:12.700
less pliancy of temper than her sister, and with a judgment too unassailed by any attention

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:20.060
to herself, she was very little disposed to approve them. They were in fact very fine

00:22:20.060 --> 00:22:25.200
ladies, not deficient in good humour when they were pleased, nor in the power of making

00:22:25.200 --> 00:22:33.080
themselves agreeable when they chose it, but proud and conceited. They were rather handsome,

00:22:33.560 --> 00:22:38.940
had been educated in one of the first private seminaries in town, had a fortune of twenty

00:22:38.940 --> 00:22:44.220
thousand pounds, were in the habit of spending more than they ought, and of associating with

00:22:44.220 --> 00:22:50.060
people of rank, and were therefore in every respect entitled to think well of themselves

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:57.980
and meanly of others. They were of a respectable family in the north of England, a circumstance

00:22:57.980 --> 00:23:02.380
more deeply impressed on their memories than that their brother's fortune and their own

00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:03.960
had been acquired by trade.

00:23:06.300 --> 00:23:11.420
Mr. Bingley inherited property to the amount of nearly a hundred thousand pounds from his

00:23:11.420 --> 00:23:18.740
father, who had intended to purchase an estate, but did not live to do it. Mr. Bingley intended

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:24.020
it likewise, and sometimes made choice of his county, but as he was now provided with

00:23:24.020 --> 00:23:29.240
a good house and the liberty of a manor, it was doubtful to many of those who best knew

00:23:29.240 --> 00:23:33.940
the easiness of his temper, whether he might not spend the remainder of his days at Netherfield

00:23:34.540 --> 00:23:37.220
and leave the next generation to purchase.

00:23:39.380 --> 00:23:45.340
His sisters were anxious for his having an estate of his own, but though he was now only

00:23:45.340 --> 00:23:50.540
established as a tenant, Miss Bingley was by no means unwilling to preside at his table,

00:23:50.940 --> 00:23:56.900
nor was Mrs. Hurst, who had married a man of more fashion than fortune, less disposed

00:23:56.900 --> 00:23:59.660
to consider his house as her home when it suited her.

00:24:01.920 --> 00:24:06.760
Mr. Bingley had not been of age two years when he was tempted by an accidental recommendation

00:24:07.220 --> 00:24:14.520
to look at Netherfield House. He did look at it, and into it for half an hour, was pleased

00:24:14.520 --> 00:24:19.740
with the situation and the principal rooms, satisfied with what the owner said in its

00:24:19.740 --> 00:24:26.820
praise, and took it immediately. Between him and Darcy there was a very steady friendship

00:24:26.820 --> 00:24:33.320
in spite of great opposition of character. Bingley was endeared to Darcy by the easiness,

00:24:33.880 --> 00:24:39.680
openness, and ductility of his temper, though no disposition could offer a greater contrast

00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:47.280
to his own, and though with his own he never appeared dissatisfied. On the strength of

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:56.800
Darcy's regard Bingley had the firmest reliance, and of his judgment the highest opinion. In

00:24:56.800 --> 00:25:03.160
the meantime, Bingley was by no means deficient, but Darcy was clever. He was at the same time

00:25:03.160 --> 00:25:09.460
haughty, reserved, and fastidious, and his manners, though well-bred, were not inviting.

00:25:10.500 --> 00:25:15.820
In that respect his friend had greatly the advantage. Bingley was sure of being liked

00:25:15.820 --> 00:25:19.960
wherever he appeared. Darcy was continually giving offence.

00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:26.960
The manner in which they spoke of the Meryton Assembly was sufficiently characteristic.

00:25:27.920 --> 00:25:34.000
Bingley had never met with more pleasant people or prettier girls in his life. Everybody had

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:40.820
been most kind and attentive to him, there had been no formality, no stiffness. He had

00:25:40.820 --> 00:25:45.920
soon felt acquainted with all the room, and as to Miss Bennet he could not conceive an

00:25:45.920 --> 00:25:52.600
angel more beautiful. Darcy, on the contrary, had seen a collection of people in whom there

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:58.620
was little beauty and no fashion, for none of whom he felt the smallest interest, and

00:25:58.620 --> 00:26:04.880
from none received either attention or pleasure. Miss Bennet he acknowledged to be pretty,

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:12.860
but she smiled too much. Mrs. Hurst and her sister allowed it to be so, but still they

00:26:12.860 --> 00:26:17.940
admired her and liked her, and pronounced her to be a sweet girl, and one whom they

00:26:17.940 --> 00:26:24.200
would not object to know more of. Miss Bennet was therefore established as a sweet girl,

00:26:24.540 --> 00:26:29.720
and their brother felt authorised by such commendation to think of her as he chose.

00:26:36.840 --> 00:26:41.580
Within a short walk of Longbourn lived a family

00:26:41.580 --> 00:26:47.760
with whom the Bennets were particularly intimate. Sir William Lucas had been formerly in trade

00:26:47.760 --> 00:26:52.940
in Meryton, where he had made a tolerable fortune and risen to the honour of knighthood

00:26:52.940 --> 00:27:00.160
by an address to the King during his mayoralty. The distinction had perhaps been felt too

00:27:00.160 --> 00:27:05.800
strongly. It had given him a disgust to his business and to his residence in a small market

00:27:05.800 --> 00:27:11.560
town, and, in quitting them both, he had removed with his family to a house about a mile from

00:27:11.560 --> 00:27:16.960
Meryton, denominated from that period Lucas Lodge, where he could think with pleasure

00:27:16.960 --> 00:27:23.140
of his own importance, and, unshackled by business, occupy himself solely in being civil

00:27:23.140 --> 00:27:29.060
to all the world. For, though elated by his rank, it did not render him supercilious.

00:27:29.600 --> 00:27:36.680
On the contrary, he was all attention to everybody. By nature inoffensive, friendly, and obliging,

00:27:36.940 --> 00:27:41.120
his presentation at St. James's had made him courteous.

00:27:43.060 --> 00:27:47.820
Lady Lucas was a very good kind of woman, not too clever to be a valuable neighbour

00:27:47.820 --> 00:27:54.800
to Mrs. Bennet. They had several children. The eldest of them, a sensible, intelligent

00:27:54.800 --> 00:28:02.760
young woman, about twenty-seven, was Elizabeth's intimate friend. That the Miss Lucas's and

00:28:02.760 --> 00:28:08.360
the Miss Bennet's should meet to talk over a ball was absolutely necessary, and the morning

00:28:08.360 --> 00:28:12.880
after the assembly brought the former to Longbourn to hear and to communicate.

00:28:14.980 --> 00:28:20.840
"'You began the evening well, Charlotte,' said Mrs. Bennet, with civil self-command

00:28:20.840 --> 00:28:24.780
to Miss Lucas. "'You were Mr. Bingley's first choice.'

00:28:26.620 --> 00:28:29.600
"'Yes, but he seemed to like his second better.'

00:28:31.180 --> 00:28:37.480
"'Oh, you mean Jane, I suppose, because he danced with her twice.' To be sure, that did

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:43.480
seem as if he admired her. Indeed, I rather believe he did. I heard something about it.

00:28:43.540 --> 00:28:48.840
But I hardly know what. Something about Mr. Robinson.'

00:28:48.840 --> 00:28:54.440
"'Perhaps you mean what I overheard between him and Mr. Robinson. Did not I mention it

00:28:54.440 --> 00:28:58.340
to you?' Mr. Robinson's asking him how he liked our

00:28:58.340 --> 00:29:02.500
Mariton assemblies, and whether he did not think there were a great many pretty women

00:29:02.500 --> 00:29:07.900
in the room, and which he thought the prettiest, and his answering immediately to the last

00:29:07.900 --> 00:29:14.140
question, "'Oh, the eldest Miss Bennet, beyond a doubt. There cannot be two opinions on that

00:29:15.800 --> 00:29:19.620
point.' "'Upon my word, well, that is very decided

00:29:19.620 --> 00:29:27.220
indeed. That does seem as if. But, however, it may all come to nothing, you know.'

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:33.920
"'My overhearings were more to the purpose than yours, Eliza,' said Charlotte. Mr. Darcy

00:29:33.920 --> 00:29:40.560
is not so well worth listening to as his friend is he, poor Eliza, to be only just tolerable.

00:29:41.760 --> 00:29:47.080
I beg you would not put it into Lizzie's head to be vexed by his ill treatment, for he is

00:29:47.080 --> 00:29:54.300
such a disagreeable man that it would be quite a misfortune to be liked by him. Mrs. Long

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:59.400
told me last night that he sat close to her for half an hour, without once opening his

00:29:59.400 --> 00:30:08.220
lips. "'Are you quite sure, ma'am? Is not there a little mistake?' said Jane. I certainly

00:30:08.220 --> 00:30:15.120
saw Mr. Darcy speaking to her. I, because she asked him at last how he liked Netherfield,

00:30:15.120 --> 00:30:20.340
and he could not help answering her, but she said he seemed quite angry at being spoke

00:30:20.340 --> 00:30:28.520
to. "'Miss Bingley told me,' said Jane, "'that he never speaks much, unless among his intimate

00:30:28.520 --> 00:30:35.880
acquaintances. With them he is remarkably agreeable.' I do not believe a word of it,

00:30:35.880 --> 00:30:42.000
my dear. If he had been so very agreeable he would have talked to Mrs. Long. But I can

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:48.200
guess how it was. Everybody says that he is eat up with pride, and I dare say he had heard

00:30:48.200 --> 00:30:54.480
somehow that Mrs. Long does not keep a carriage, and had come to the ball in a haque chaise.'

00:30:55.160 --> 00:31:00.480
I do not mind his not talking to Mrs. Long, said Miss Lucas, but I wish he had danced

00:31:00.480 --> 00:31:07.640
with Eliza. "'Another time, Lizzie,' said her mother, "'I would not dance with him, if I

00:31:07.640 --> 00:31:14.760
were you.' I believe, ma'am, I may safely promise you never to dance with him.'

00:31:15.800 --> 00:31:22.640
His pride, said Miss Lucas, does not offend me so much as pride often does, because there

00:31:22.640 --> 00:31:30.280
is an excuse for it. One cannot wonder that so very fine a young man, with family, fortune,

00:31:30.940 --> 00:31:37.140
everything in his favour, should think highly of himself. If I may so express it, he has

00:31:37.140 --> 00:31:39.300
the right to be proud.'

00:31:40.380 --> 00:31:46.860
"'That is very true,' replied Elizabeth, and I could easily forgive his pride, if he had

00:31:46.860 --> 00:31:47.900
not mortified mine.'

00:31:50.400 --> 00:31:56.800
"'Pride,' observed Mary, who piqued herself upon the solidity of her reflections, is a

00:31:56.800 --> 00:32:03.060
very common failing, I believe. By all that I have ever read, I am convinced that it is

00:32:03.060 --> 00:32:09.340
very common indeed, that human nature is particularly prone to it, and that there are very few of

00:32:09.340 --> 00:32:15.400
us who do not cherish a feeling of self-complacency on the score of some quality or other, real

00:32:15.400 --> 00:32:22.460
or imaginary. Vanity and pride are different things, though the words are often used synonymously.

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:29.180
A person may be proud without being vain. Pride relates more to our opinion of ourselves,

00:32:29.840 --> 00:32:33.380
vanity to what we would have others think of us.'

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:39.460
"'If I were as rich as Mr. Darcy,' cried a young Lucas, who came with his sisters,

00:32:39.960 --> 00:32:45.440
"'I should not care how proud I was. I would keep a pack of foxhounds, and drink a bottle

00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:47.120
of wine a day.'

00:32:47.740 --> 00:32:52.700
"'Then you would drink a great deal more than you ought,' said Mrs. Bennet, and if I were

00:32:52.700 --> 00:32:57.420
to see you at it, I should take away your bottle directly.'

00:32:57.420 --> 00:33:03.460
The boy protested that she should not. She continued to declare that she would, and the

00:33:03.460 --> 00:33:05.760
argument ended only with the visit.

00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:26.480
The ladies of Longbourn soon waited on those of Netherfield.

00:33:26.900 --> 00:33:28.720
The visit was returned in due form.

00:33:29.320 --> 00:33:33.720
Miss Bennet's pleasing manners grew on the goodwill of Mrs. Hurst and Miss Bingley, and

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:38.160
So the mother was found to be intolerable, and the young sisters not worth speaking to.

00:33:38.540 --> 00:33:42.600
A wish of being better acquainted with them was expressed towards the two eldest.

00:33:43.180 --> 00:33:48.060
By Jane this attention was received with the greatest pleasure, but Elizabeth still saw

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:53.120
superciliousness in their treatment of everybody, hardly accepting even her sister, and could

00:33:53.120 --> 00:33:58.420
not like them, though their kindness to Jane, such as it was, had a value as arising, in

00:33:58.420 --> 00:34:01.280
all probability, from the influence of their brother's admiration.

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:06.660
It was generally evident whenever they met that he did admire her, and to her it was

00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:10.780
equally evident that Jane was yielding to the preference which she had begun to entertain

00:34:10.780 --> 00:34:14.340
for him from the first, and was in a way to be very much in love.

00:34:14.780 --> 00:34:18.980
But she considered with pleasure that it was not likely to be discovered by the world in

00:34:18.980 --> 00:34:24.660
general, since Jane united, with great strength of feeling, a composure of temper and a uniform

00:34:24.660 --> 00:34:28.420
cheerfulness of manner which would guard her from the suspicions of the impertinent.

00:34:29.060 --> 00:34:31.180
She mentioned this to her friend Miss Lucas.

00:34:31.420 --> 00:34:36.580
"'It may perhaps be pleasant,' replied Charlotte, "'to be able to impose on the public in such

00:34:36.580 --> 00:34:40.800
a case, but it is sometimes a disadvantage to be so very guarded.

00:34:41.260 --> 00:34:45.880
If a woman conceals her affection with the same skill from the object of it, she may

00:34:45.880 --> 00:34:50.420
lose the opportunity of fixing him, and it will then be but poor consolation to believe

00:34:50.420 --> 00:34:52.060
the world equally in the dark.'

00:34:52.740 --> 00:34:58.320
There is so much of gratitude or vanity in almost every attachment that it is not safe

00:34:58.320 --> 00:34:59.700
to leave any to itself.

00:35:00.300 --> 00:35:05.420
We can all begin freely, a slight preference is natural enough, but there are few of us

00:35:05.420 --> 00:35:08.360
who have heart enough to be really in love without encouragement.

00:35:09.120 --> 00:35:13.260
In nine cases out of ten, a woman had better show more affection than she feels.

00:35:14.120 --> 00:35:18.780
Bingley likes your sister undoubtedly, but he may never do more than like her if she

00:35:18.780 --> 00:35:20.060
does not help him on.

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:24.540
But she does help him on, as much as her nature will allow.

00:35:24.980 --> 00:35:30.160
If I can perceive her regard for him, he must be a simpleton indeed not to discover it too.'

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:35.560
Remember, Eliza, that he does not know Jane's disposition as you do.

00:35:36.540 --> 00:35:41.660
But if a woman is partial to a man and does not endeavor to conceal it, he must find it

00:35:41.660 --> 00:35:42.000
out.

00:35:42.840 --> 00:35:45.100
Perhaps he must if he sees enough of her.

00:35:45.340 --> 00:35:50.140
But though Bingley and Jane meet tolerably often, it is never for many hours together,

00:35:50.140 --> 00:35:54.960
And as they always see each other in large mixed parties, it is impossible that every

00:35:54.960 --> 00:35:57.000
moment should be employed in conversing together.

00:35:57.320 --> 00:36:01.620
Jane should therefore make the most of every half hour in which she can command his attention.

00:36:02.200 --> 00:36:06.140
When she is secure of him, there will be more leisure for falling in love as much as she

00:36:06.140 --> 00:36:06.620
chooses.

00:36:07.660 --> 00:36:12.340
"'Your plan is a good one,' replied Elizabeth, where nothing is in question but the desire

00:36:12.340 --> 00:36:17.300
of being well married, and if I were determined to get a rich husband or any husband, I dare

00:36:17.300 --> 00:36:18.480
say I should adopt it.

00:36:18.480 --> 00:36:20.940
But these are not Jane's feelings.

00:36:21.180 --> 00:36:22.880
She's not acting by design.

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:28.080
As yet, she cannot even be certain of the degree of her own regard, nor of its reasonableness.

00:36:28.720 --> 00:36:30.600
She has known him only a fortnight.

00:36:31.240 --> 00:36:35.960
She danced four dances with him at Meryton, she saw him one morning at his own house,

00:36:36.200 --> 00:36:38.860
and has since dined with him in company four times.

00:36:39.240 --> 00:36:42.240
This is not quite enough to make her understand his character.'

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:45.640
"'Not as you represent it.'

00:36:45.640 --> 00:36:50.860
Had she merely dined with him, she might only have discovered whether he had a good appetite.

00:36:51.320 --> 00:36:56.800
But you must remember that four evenings have also been spent together, and four evenings

00:36:56.800 --> 00:36:58.040
may do a great deal.'

00:36:59.080 --> 00:37:03.660
"'Yes, these four evenings have enabled them to ascertain that they both like Vant-Une better

00:37:03.660 --> 00:37:08.660
than commerce, but with respect to any other leading characteristic, I do not imagine that

00:37:08.660 --> 00:37:09.560
much has been unfolded.'

00:37:10.760 --> 00:37:14.700
"'Well,' said Charlotte, "'I wish Jane success with all my heart, and if she were

00:37:14.700 --> 00:37:19.060
married to him tomorrow, I should think she had as good a chance of happiness as if she

00:37:19.060 --> 00:37:21.480
were to be studying his character for a twelve-month.

00:37:22.320 --> 00:37:25.420
Happiness in marriage is entirely a matter of chance.

00:37:25.920 --> 00:37:30.960
If the dispositions of the parties are ever so well known to each other, or ever so similar

00:37:30.960 --> 00:37:34.300
beforehand, it does not advance their felicity in the least.

00:37:34.820 --> 00:37:40.060
They always continue to grow sufficiently unlike afterwards to have their share of vexation,

00:37:40.060 --> 00:37:44.460
and it's better to know as little as possible of the defects of the person with whom you

00:37:44.460 --> 00:37:45.460
have to pass your life.'

00:37:46.200 --> 00:37:49.640
"'Make me laugh, Charlotte, but it's not sound.

00:37:49.920 --> 00:37:54.640
You know it's not sound, and you would never act this way yourself.'

00:37:55.220 --> 00:38:00.240
Occupied in observing Mr. Bingley's attentions to her sister, Elizabeth was far from suspecting

00:38:00.240 --> 00:38:04.260
that she was herself becoming an object of some interest in the eyes of his friend.

00:38:04.980 --> 00:38:08.120
Mr. Darcy had at first scarcely allowed her to be pretty.

00:38:08.660 --> 00:38:12.940
He had looked at her without admiration at the ball, and when next they met, he looked

00:38:12.940 --> 00:38:14.380
at her only to criticize.

00:38:15.180 --> 00:38:19.660
But no sooner had he made it clear to himself and to his friends that she hardly had a good

00:38:19.660 --> 00:38:25.020
feature in her face than he began to find it was rendered uncommonly intelligent by

00:38:25.020 --> 00:38:27.100
the beautiful expression of her dark eyes.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:33.060
To this discovery succeeded some others equally mortifying, though he had detected with a

00:38:33.060 --> 00:38:36.740
critical eye more than one failure of perfect symmetry in her form.

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:41.820
He was forced to acknowledge her figure to be light and pleasing, and in spite of his

00:38:41.820 --> 00:38:46.020
asserting that her manners were not those of the fashionable world, he was caught by

00:38:46.020 --> 00:38:47.080
their easy playfulness.

00:38:48.080 --> 00:38:49.840
Of this she was perfectly unaware.

00:38:50.240 --> 00:38:54.540
To her, he was only the man who made himself agreeable nowhere, and who had not thought

00:38:54.540 --> 00:38:56.140
her handsome enough to dance with.

00:38:57.200 --> 00:39:01.560
He began to wish to know more of her, and as a step towards conversing with her himself,

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:03.900
attended to her conversation with others.

00:39:04.700 --> 00:39:06.320
His doing so drew her notice.

00:39:06.800 --> 00:39:10.000
It was at Sir William Lucas's where a large party were assembled.

00:39:11.080 --> 00:39:16.160
"'What does Mr. Darcy mean,' she said to Charlotte, by listening to my conversation with Colonel

00:39:16.160 --> 00:39:16.660
Forster.

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:20.540
"'That's a question which Mr. Darcy only can answer.

00:39:20.920 --> 00:39:24.820
But if he does it any more, I shall certainly let him know that I see what he's about.

00:39:25.440 --> 00:39:30.720
He has a very satirical eye, and if I do not begin by being impertinent myself, I shall

00:39:30.720 --> 00:39:32.780
soon grow afraid of him.'"

00:39:32.780 --> 00:39:37.320
On his approaching them soon afterwards, though without seeming to have any intention of speaking,

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:42.040
Miss Lucas defied her friend to mention such a subject to him, which immediately provoking

00:39:42.040 --> 00:39:43.160
Elizabeth to do it.

00:39:43.420 --> 00:39:44.700
She turned to him and said,

00:39:45.360 --> 00:39:50.220
"'Did you not think, Mr. Darcy, that I expressed myself uncommonly well just now, when I was

00:39:50.220 --> 00:39:53.500
teasing Colonel Forster to give us a ball at Mariton?'

00:39:53.500 --> 00:39:57.440
"'With great energy, but it's always a subject which makes a lady energetic.

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:00.040
You are severe on us.'"

00:40:00.600 --> 00:40:03.980
"'It will be her turn soon to be teased,' said Miss Lucas.

00:40:04.620 --> 00:40:08.340
"'I am going to open the instrument, Eliza, and you know what follows.'

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:13.800
"'You are a strange creature by way of a friend, always wanting me to play and sing before

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:15.040
anybody and everybody.

00:40:15.600 --> 00:40:20.080
If my vanity had taken a musical turn, you would be invaluable, but as it is, I'd really

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:25.360
rather not sit down before those who must be in the habit of hearing the very best performers.'"

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:28.580
On Miss Lucas's persevering, however, she added,

00:40:28.660 --> 00:40:29.460
"'Very well.

00:40:29.460 --> 00:40:33.240
If it must be so, it must,' and gravely glancing at Mr. Darcy,

00:40:33.860 --> 00:40:36.940
"'There's a fine old saying, which everybody here is of course familiar with.

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:42.940
Keep your breath to cool your porridge, and I shall keep mine to swell my song.'"

00:40:42.940 --> 00:40:45.700
Her performance was pleasing, though by no means capital.

00:40:46.220 --> 00:40:50.120
After a song or two, and before she could reply to entreaties of several that she would

00:40:50.120 --> 00:40:55.340
sing again, she was eagerly succeeded at the instrument by her sister Mary, who, having

00:40:55.340 --> 00:40:59.640
in consequence of being the only plain one in the family, worked hard for knowledge and

00:40:59.640 --> 00:41:02.300
accomplishments, and was always impatient for display.

00:41:03.520 --> 00:41:08.420
Mary had neither genius nor taste, and though vanity had given her application, it had given

00:41:08.420 --> 00:41:12.660
her likewise a pedantic air and conceited manner, which would have injured a higher

00:41:12.660 --> 00:41:14.520
degree of excellence than she had reached.

00:41:15.400 --> 00:41:20.020
Elizabeth, easy and unaffected, had been listened to with much more pleasure, though not playing

00:41:20.020 --> 00:41:25.120
half so well, and Mary, at the end of a long concerto, was glad to purchase praise and

00:41:25.120 --> 00:41:29.520
gratitude by Scotch and Irish heirs at the request of her younger sisters, who, with

00:41:29.520 --> 00:41:33.920
some of the Lucas's and two or three officers, joined eagerly in dancing at one end of the

00:41:33.920 --> 00:41:34.200
room.

00:41:35.520 --> 00:41:40.320
Mr. Darcy stood near them in silent indignation at such a mode of passing the evening to the

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:44.920
exclusion of all conversation, and was much too engrossed by his thoughts to perceive

00:41:44.920 --> 00:41:48.540
that Sir William Lucas was his neighbor, till Sir William thus began,

00:41:48.980 --> 00:41:52.300
"'What a charming amusement for young people this is, Mr. Darcy.

00:41:52.580 --> 00:41:54.680
There's nothing like dancing, after all.

00:41:54.680 --> 00:41:58.440
I consider it as one of the first refinements of a Polish society.'

00:41:59.720 --> 00:42:04.260
"'Certainly, sir, and it has the advantage also of being in vogue amongst the less Polish

00:42:04.260 --> 00:42:05.320
societies of the world.

00:42:05.640 --> 00:42:08.340
Every savage can dance.'"

00:42:08.340 --> 00:42:09.720
Sir William only smiled.

00:42:10.400 --> 00:42:14.580
"'Your friend performs delightfully,' he continued after a pause, on seeing Bingley

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:15.200
join the group.

00:42:15.440 --> 00:42:19.400
"'And I doubt not that you are an adept in the science yourself, Mr. Darcy.'

00:42:19.400 --> 00:42:22.720
"'You saw me dance at Meryton, I believe, sir.'

00:42:22.720 --> 00:42:25.940
"'Yes, indeed, and received no inconsiderable pleasure from the site.

00:42:26.020 --> 00:42:28.420
Do you often dance at St. James's?'

00:42:28.420 --> 00:42:29.940
"'Never, sir.'

00:42:29.940 --> 00:42:33.480
"'Do you not think it would be a proper compliment to the place?'

00:42:33.480 --> 00:42:37.550
"'It is a compliment which I never pay to any place, if I can avoid it.'

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:42.660
"'You have a house in town, I conclude,' Mr. Darcy bowed.

00:42:43.260 --> 00:42:48.260
"'I had once some thought of fixing in town myself, for I am fond of superior society,

00:42:48.260 --> 00:42:53.400
but I did not feel quite certain that the heir of London would agree with Lady Lucas.'

00:42:53.400 --> 00:42:58.420
He paused in hopes of an answer, but his companion was not disposed to make any, and

00:42:58.420 --> 00:43:03.060
Elizabeth, at that instant, moving towards them, he was struck with the action of doing

00:43:03.060 --> 00:43:05.040
a very gallant thing, and called out to her,

00:43:05.080 --> 00:43:07.560
"'My dear Miss Eliza, why are you not dancing?

00:43:07.760 --> 00:43:12.600
Mr. Darcy, you must allow me to present this young lady to you as a very desirable partner.

00:43:12.880 --> 00:43:16.860
You cannot refuse to dance, I am sure, when so much beauty is before you.'

00:43:16.860 --> 00:43:22.060
And taking her hand, he would have given it to Mr. Darcy, who, though extremely surprised,

00:43:22.360 --> 00:43:24.000
was not unwilling to receive it.

00:43:24.360 --> 00:43:28.080
When she instantly drew back, and said with some discomposure to Sir William,

00:43:28.600 --> 00:43:31.240
"'Indeed, sir, I have not the least intention of dancing.

00:43:31.640 --> 00:43:36.380
I entreat you not to suppose that I move this way in order to beg for a partner.'

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:41.480
Mr. Darcy, with grave propriety, requested to be allowed the honor of her hand, but in

00:43:41.480 --> 00:43:41.740
vain.

00:43:42.180 --> 00:43:43.420
Elizabeth was determined.

00:43:43.420 --> 00:43:47.740
Nor did Sir William at all shake her purpose by his attempt at persuasion.

00:43:48.340 --> 00:43:52.760
"'You excel so much in the dance, Miss Eliza, that it is cruel to deny me the happiness

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:58.000
of seeing you, and though this gentleman dislikes the amusement in general, he can have no objection,

00:43:58.100 --> 00:44:01.120
I am sure, to oblige us for one half-hour.'

00:44:01.120 --> 00:44:04.640
"'Mr. Darcy is all politeness,' said Elizabeth, smiling.

00:44:05.540 --> 00:44:11.480
"'He is indeed, but considering the inducement, my dear Eliza, can we not wonder at his complacence,

00:44:11.480 --> 00:44:14.800
for who would object to such a partner?'

00:44:14.800 --> 00:44:16.820
Elizabeth looked archly, and turned away.

00:44:17.420 --> 00:44:21.400
Her resistance had not entered her with the gentleman, and he was thinking of her with

00:44:21.400 --> 00:44:24.660
some complacency, when thus accosted by Miss Bingley.

00:44:25.060 --> 00:44:27.320
"'I can guess the subject of your reverie.'

00:44:27.860 --> 00:44:29.280
"'I should imagine not.

00:44:29.600 --> 00:44:34.460
You are considering how insupportable it would be to pass many evenings in this manner, in

00:44:34.460 --> 00:44:37.820
such society, and indeed I am quite of your opinion.

00:44:37.820 --> 00:44:45.100
"'I was never more annoyed, the insipidity, and yet the noise, the nothingness, and yet

00:44:45.100 --> 00:44:47.600
the self-importance of all these people.

00:44:48.020 --> 00:44:51.680
Oh, what I would give to hear your strictures on them!'

00:44:51.680 --> 00:44:54.560
"'Your conjecture is totally wrong, I assure you.

00:44:54.660 --> 00:44:56.720
My mind was more agreeably engaged.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:01.400
I have been meditating on the very great pleasure which a pair of fine eyes in the face of a

00:45:01.400 --> 00:45:03.380
pretty woman can bestow.'

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:08.080
Miss Bingley immediately fixed her eyes on his face, and desired he would tell her what

00:45:08.080 --> 00:45:10.520
lady had the credit of inspiring such reflections.

00:45:11.380 --> 00:45:13.620
Mr. Darcy replied with great intrepidity.

00:45:14.680 --> 00:45:16.640
"'Miss Elizabeth Bennet.'

00:45:16.640 --> 00:45:18.780
"'Miss Elizabeth Bennet!'

00:45:18.780 --> 00:45:19.900
repeated Miss Bingley.

00:45:20.180 --> 00:45:21.780
"'I am all astonishment.

00:45:22.100 --> 00:45:23.920
How long has she been such a favorite?

00:45:24.180 --> 00:45:26.640
And pray when am I to wish you joy?'

00:45:26.640 --> 00:45:29.980
"'That is exactly the question which I expected you to ask.

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:32.160
A lady's imagination is very rapid.

00:45:32.160 --> 00:45:36.260
It jumps from admiration to love, from love to matrimony in a moment.

00:45:36.580 --> 00:45:38.100
I knew you would be wishing me joy.'

00:45:39.280 --> 00:45:43.480
"'Nay, if you are serious about it, I shall consider the matter is absolutely settled.

00:45:43.800 --> 00:45:48.260
You will be having a charming mother-in-law indeed, and of course she will always be at

00:45:48.260 --> 00:45:49.600
Pemberley with you.'

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:53.780
He listened to her with perfect indifference while she chose to entertain herself in this manner,

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:57.640
and as his composure convinced her that all was safe, her wit flowed long.'

00:46:19.160 --> 00:46:23.280
Mr. Bennet's property consisted almost entirely

00:46:23.280 --> 00:46:28.820
in an estate of two thousand a year, which, unfortunately for his daughters, was entailed

00:46:28.820 --> 00:46:33.940
in default of heir's mail on a distant relation, and their mother's fortune, though ample for

00:46:33.940 --> 00:46:39.320
her situation in life, could but ill supply the deficiency of his. Her father had been

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:44.380
an attorney in Meryton, and had left her four thousand pounds. She had a sister married

00:46:44.380 --> 00:46:48.540
to a Mr. Phillips, who had been a clerk to their father and succeeded him in the business,

00:46:48.800 --> 00:46:54.400
and a brother settled in London in a respectable line of trade. The village of Longbourn was

00:46:54.400 --> 00:46:59.320
only one mile from Meryton, a most convenient distance for the young ladies, who were usually

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:04.860
three or four times a week, to pay their duty to their aunt and to a milliner's shop just

00:47:04.860 --> 00:47:10.220
over the way. The two youngest of the family, Catherine and Lydia, were particularly frequent

00:47:10.220 --> 00:47:14.620
in these attentions. Their minds were more vacant than their sisters, and when nothing

00:47:14.620 --> 00:47:19.980
better offered, a walk to Meryton was necessary to amuse their morning hours and furnish conversation

00:47:19.980 --> 00:47:24.880
for the evening. And however bare of news the country in general might be, they always

00:47:24.880 --> 00:47:30.160
to learn some from their aunt. At present, indeed, they were well supplied, both with

00:47:30.160 --> 00:47:34.480
news and happiness, by the recent arrival of a militia regiment in the neighborhood.

00:47:34.760 --> 00:47:40.1000
It was to remain the whole winter, and Meryton was the headquarters. Their visits to Mrs.

00:47:41.220 --> 00:47:46.680
Phillips were now productive of the most interesting intelligence. Every day added something to

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:51.440
their knowledge of the officers' names and connections. Their lodgings were not long

00:47:51.440 --> 00:47:56.560
secret, and at length they began to know the officers themselves. Mr. Phillips visited

00:47:56.560 --> 00:48:01.620
them all, and this opened to his nieces a store of felicity unknown before. They could

00:48:01.620 --> 00:48:07.140
talk of nothing but officers, and Mr. Bingley's large fortune, the mention of which gave animation

00:48:07.140 --> 00:48:11.740
to their mother, was worthless in their eyes when opposed to the regimentals of an ensign.

00:48:12.520 --> 00:48:17.360
After listening one morning to their effusions on this subject, Mr. Bennet coolly observed,

00:48:17.360 --> 00:48:21.840
From all that I can collect by your manner of talking, you must be two of the silliest

00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:26.220
girls in the country. I have suspected it some time, but I am now convinced.

00:48:27.340 --> 00:48:32.280
Catherine was disconcerted and made no answer, but Lydia, with perfect indifference, continued

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:36.300
to express her admiration of Captain Carter, and her hope of seeing him in the course of

00:48:36.300 --> 00:48:38.900
the day, as he was going the next morning to London.

00:48:39.840 --> 00:48:44.700
I am astonished, my dear, said Mrs. Bennet, that you should be so ready to think your

00:48:44.700 --> 00:48:49.660
own children silly. If I wish to think slightingly of anybody's children, it should not be of

00:48:49.660 --> 00:48:57.440
my own, however. If my children are silly, I must hope to be always sensible of it. Yes,

00:48:57.440 --> 00:49:00.040
but as it happens, they are all of them very clever.

00:49:01.380 --> 00:49:06.380
This is the only point, I flatter myself, on which we do not agree. I had hoped that

00:49:06.380 --> 00:49:11.300
our sentiments coincided in every particular, but I must so far differ from you as to think

00:49:11.300 --> 00:49:13.660
our two youngest daughters uncommonly foolish.

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:18.920
My dear Mr. Bennet, you must not expect such girls to have the sense of their father and

00:49:18.920 --> 00:49:22.1000
mother. When they get to our age, I dare say they will not think about officers any more

00:49:22.1000 --> 00:49:28.540
than we do. I remember the time when I liked a red coat myself very well, and indeed I

00:49:28.540 --> 00:49:32.700
still do at my heart, and if a smart young colonel with five or six thousand a year should

00:49:32.700 --> 00:49:37.540
want one of my girls, I shall not say nay to him. And I thought Colonel Forster looked

00:49:37.540 --> 00:49:40.700
very becoming the other night at Sir William's in his regimentals.

00:49:41.820 --> 00:49:46.800
Mama, cried Lydia, my aunt says that Colonel Forster and Captain Carter do not go so often

00:49:46.800 --> 00:49:51.460
to Miss Watson's as they did when they first came. She sees them now very often standing

00:49:51.460 --> 00:49:52.700
in Clark's library.

00:49:53.500 --> 00:49:57.740
Mrs. Bennet was prevented from replying by the entrance of the footman with a note for

00:49:57.740 --> 00:50:01.420
Miss Bennet. It came from Netherfield, and the servant waited for an answer.

00:50:02.540 --> 00:50:06.480
Mrs. Bennet's eyes sparkled with pleasure, and she was eagerly calling out while her

00:50:07.060 --> 00:50:11.500
Well, Jane, who's it from? What's it about? What does he say? Well, Jane, make haste and

00:50:11.500 --> 00:50:12.800
tell us. Make haste, my love.

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:17.300
It is from Miss Bingley, said Jane, and then read it aloud.

00:50:18.360 --> 00:50:23.420
My dear friend, if you are not so compassionate as to dine today with Louisa and me, we shall

00:50:23.420 --> 00:50:27.760
be in danger of hating each other for the rest of our lives, for a whole day's tete-a-tete

00:50:27.760 --> 00:50:31.720
between two women can never end without a quarrel. Come as soon as you can on receipt

00:50:31.720 --> 00:50:34.840
of this. My brother and the gentlemen are to dine with the officers.

00:50:34.840 --> 00:50:36.960
Yours ever, Caroline Bingley.

00:50:37.960 --> 00:50:42.160
With the officers, cried Lydia. I wonder my aunt did not tell us of that.

00:50:43.300 --> 00:50:46.640
Dining out, said Mrs. Bennet, that is very unlucky.

00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:49.720
Can I have a carriage? Asked Jane.

00:50:50.580 --> 00:50:54.460
No, my dear, you'd better go on horseback because it seems likely to rain, and then

00:50:54.460 --> 00:50:55.580
you must stay all night.

00:50:56.820 --> 00:51:00.700
That would be a good scheme, said Elizabeth, if you were sure that they would not offer

00:51:00.700 --> 00:51:01.660
to send her home.

00:51:01.660 --> 00:51:06.340
Oh, but the gentlemen will have Mr. Bingley's chaise to go to Mariton, and the hearths

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:07.600
have no horses to theirs.

00:51:08.660 --> 00:51:10.220
I'd much rather go on the coach.

00:51:11.360 --> 00:51:15.180
But, my dear, your father cannot spare the horses, I'm sure. They're wanted in the

00:51:15.180 --> 00:51:16.580
farm, Mr. Bennet, are they not?

00:51:17.500 --> 00:51:20.280
They're wanted in the farm much oftener than I can get them.

00:51:20.900 --> 00:51:24.520
But if you've got them today, said Elizabeth, my mother's purpose will be answered.

00:51:25.200 --> 00:51:29.400
She did at last extort from her father an acknowledgment that the horses were engaged.

00:51:29.400 --> 00:51:34.140
Jane was therefore obliged to go on horseback, and her mother attended her to the door with

00:51:34.140 --> 00:51:36.320
many cheerful prognostics of a bad day.

00:51:36.900 --> 00:51:37.820
Her hopes were answered.

00:51:38.120 --> 00:51:40.460
Jane had not been gone long before it rained hard.

00:51:40.840 --> 00:51:43.760
Her sisters were uneasy for her, but her mother was delighted.

00:51:44.380 --> 00:51:46.920
The rain continued the whole evening without intermission.

00:51:47.280 --> 00:51:49.080
Jane would certainly not come back.

00:51:49.720 --> 00:51:54.620
This was a lucky idea of mine, indeed, said Mrs. Bennet more than once, as if the credit

00:51:54.620 --> 00:51:56.440
of making it rain were all her own.

00:51:57.160 --> 00:52:01.720
Till the next morning, however, she was not aware of all the felicity of her contrivance.

00:52:01.940 --> 00:52:05.820
Breakfast was scarcely over when a servant from Netherfield brought the following note

00:52:05.820 --> 00:52:06.500
for Elizabeth.

00:52:06.840 --> 00:52:12.060
My dearest Lizzie, I find myself very unwell this morning, which I suppose is to be imputed

00:52:12.060 --> 00:52:13.700
to my getting wet through yesterday.

00:52:14.340 --> 00:52:17.100
My kind friends will not hear of my returning till I'm better.

00:52:17.560 --> 00:52:20.020
They insist also on my seeing Mr. Jones.

00:52:20.340 --> 00:52:23.240
Therefore, do not be alarmed if you should hear of his having been to me.

00:52:23.240 --> 00:52:28.100
And, accepting a sore throat and a headache, there is not much the matter with me, yours,

00:52:28.320 --> 00:52:28.680
etc.

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:34.620
Well, my dear, said Mr. Bennet when Elizabeth had read the note aloud, if your daughter

00:52:34.620 --> 00:52:38.820
should have a dangerous fit of illness, if she should die, it would be a comfort to know

00:52:38.820 --> 00:52:41.720
that it was all in pursuit of Mr. Bingley and under your orders.

00:52:42.400 --> 00:52:44.040
Oh, I'm not afraid of her dying.

00:52:44.120 --> 00:52:47.180
People do not die of little trifling colds.

00:52:47.320 --> 00:52:48.720
She'll be taken good care of.

00:52:48.820 --> 00:52:51.060
As long as she stays there, it is all very well.

00:52:51.060 --> 00:52:53.380
I would go and see her if I could have the carriage.

00:52:54.1000 --> 00:52:59.700
Elizabeth, feeling really anxious, was determined to go to her, though the carriage was not

00:52:59.700 --> 00:53:03.700
to be had, and as she was no horsewoman, walking was her only alternative.

00:53:04.220 --> 00:53:05.560
She declared her resolution.

00:53:06.440 --> 00:53:11.220
How can you be so silly, cried her mother, as to think of such a thing in all this dirt?

00:53:11.620 --> 00:53:13.940
You will not be fit to be seen when you get there.

00:53:14.480 --> 00:53:17.360
I shall be very fit to see Jane, which is all I want.

00:53:17.360 --> 00:53:21.520
Is this a hint to me, Lizzie, said her father, to send for the horses?

00:53:22.220 --> 00:53:24.520
No, indeed, I do not wish to avoid the walk.

00:53:24.760 --> 00:53:27.560
The distance is nothing when one has a motive only three miles.

00:53:27.780 --> 00:53:28.920
I shall be back by dinner.

00:53:30.020 --> 00:53:34.900
I admire the activity of your benevolence, observed Mary, but every impulsive feeling

00:53:34.900 --> 00:53:39.640
should be guided by reason, and, in my opinion, exertion should always be in proportion to

00:53:39.640 --> 00:53:40.480
what is required.

00:53:41.660 --> 00:53:45.340
We will go as far as Meryton with you, said Catherine and Lydia.

00:53:45.980 --> 00:53:49.660
Elizabeth accepted their company, and the three young ladies set off together.

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:54.520
If we make haste, said Lydia as they walked along, perhaps we may see something

00:53:54.520 --> 00:53:56.120
of Captain Carter before he goes.

00:53:57.300 --> 00:54:01.020
In Meryton they parted, the two youngest repaired to the lodgings of one of the

00:54:01.020 --> 00:54:05.560
officer's wives, and Elizabeth continued her walk alone, crossing field after field

00:54:05.560 --> 00:54:09.720
at a quick pace, jumping over stiles and springing over puddles with impatient

00:54:09.720 --> 00:54:14.260
activity, and finding herself at last within view of the house, with weary

00:54:14.260 --> 00:54:18.120
ankles, dirty stockings, and a face glowing with the warmth of exercise.

00:54:19.240 --> 00:54:23.100
She was shown into the breakfast parlor, where all but Jane were assembled, and

00:54:23.100 --> 00:54:25.600
where her appearance created a great deal of surprise.

00:54:25.900 --> 00:54:29.440
That she should have walked three miles so early in the day in such dirty weather

00:54:29.440 --> 00:54:31.940
and by herself was almost incredible to Mrs.

00:54:32.160 --> 00:54:35.600
Hurst and Miss Bingley, and Elizabeth was convinced that they held her in

00:54:35.600 --> 00:54:36.440
contempt for it.

00:54:36.880 --> 00:54:40.480
She was received, however, very politely by them, and in their brothers'

00:54:40.800 --> 00:54:42.660
manners there was something better than politeness.

00:54:42.660 --> 00:54:44.480
There was good humor and kindness.

00:54:45.180 --> 00:54:45.440
Mr.

00:54:45.640 --> 00:54:47.180
Darcy said very little, and Mr.

00:54:47.400 --> 00:54:48.440
Hurst nothing at all.

00:54:48.900 --> 00:54:52.920
The former was divided between admiration of the brilliancy which exercise had

00:54:52.920 --> 00:54:57.600
given to her complexion, and doubt as to the occasions justifying her coming so

00:54:57.600 --> 00:54:58.240
far alone.

00:54:58.960 --> 00:55:00.900
The latter was thinking only of his breakfast.

00:55:01.480 --> 00:55:04.740
Her inquiries after her sister were not very favorably answered.

00:55:05.300 --> 00:55:09.500
Miss Bennet had slept ill, and though up was feverish, and not well enough to

00:55:09.500 --> 00:55:10.100
leave her room.

00:55:10.100 --> 00:55:15.060
Elizabeth was glad to be taken to her immediately, and Jane, who had only been

00:55:15.060 --> 00:55:18.620
withheld by the fear of giving alarm or inconvenience from expressing in her

00:55:18.620 --> 00:55:22.680
note how much she longed for such a visit, was delighted at her entrance.

00:55:23.180 --> 00:55:27.040
She was not equal, however, to much conversation, and when Miss Bingley left

00:55:27.040 --> 00:55:30.900
them together, could attempt little besides expressions of gratitude for the

00:55:30.900 --> 00:55:32.940
extraordinary kindness she was treated with.

00:55:33.600 --> 00:55:35.280
Elizabeth silently attended her.

00:55:36.060 --> 00:55:39.860
When breakfast was over they were joined by the sisters, and Elizabeth began to

00:55:39.860 --> 00:55:43.040
like them herself when she saw how much affection and solicitude they showed

00:55:43.040 --> 00:55:43.540
for Jane.

00:55:44.120 --> 00:55:48.060
The apothecary came, and having examined his patient, said, as might be

00:55:48.060 --> 00:55:51.520
supposed, that she had caught a violent cold, and that they must endeavor to

00:55:51.520 --> 00:55:54.900
get the better of it, advised her to return to bed, and promised her some

00:55:54.900 --> 00:55:55.600
drafts.

00:55:56.140 --> 00:55:59.760
The advice was followed readily, for the feverish symptoms increased, and her

00:55:59.760 --> 00:56:00.720
head ached acutely.

00:56:01.300 --> 00:56:04.1000
Elizabeth did not quit her room for a moment, nor were the other ladies often

00:56:04.1000 --> 00:56:08.660
absent, the gentlemen being out, they had, in fact, nothing to do elsewhere.

00:56:09.340 --> 00:56:13.360
When the clock struck three, Elizabeth felt that she must go, and very

00:56:13.360 --> 00:56:14.560
unwillingly said so.

00:56:15.100 --> 00:56:18.420
Miss Bingley offered her the carriage, and she only wanted a little pressing to

00:56:18.420 --> 00:56:22.540
accept it, when Jane testified such concern in parting with her, that Miss

00:56:22.540 --> 00:56:26.040
Bingley was obliged to convert the offer of the chaise to an invitation to

00:56:26.040 --> 00:56:27.680
remain at Netherfield for the present.

00:56:28.400 --> 00:56:32.540
Elizabeth most thankfully consented, and a servant was dispatched to Longbourn

00:56:32.540 --> 00:56:36.060
to acquaint the family with her stay, and bring back a supply of clothes.

00:57:10.880 --> 00:57:15.180
At five o'clock the two ladies retired to

00:57:15.180 --> 00:57:19.360
rest, and at half past six Elizabeth was summoned to dinner.

00:57:20.160 --> 00:57:24.720
To the civil inquiries which then poured in, and amongst which she had the pleasure of

00:57:24.720 --> 00:57:29.840
distinguishing the much superior solicitude of Mr. Bingley's, she could not make a very

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:30.880
favourable answer.

00:57:31.740 --> 00:57:33.740
Jane was by no means better.

00:57:34.400 --> 00:57:38.940
The sisters on hearing this repeated three or four times how much they were grieved,

00:57:39.280 --> 00:57:44.1000
how shocking it was to have a bad cold, and how excessively they disliked being ill themselves.

00:57:44.1000 --> 00:57:47.500
And then thought no more of the matter.

00:57:48.180 --> 00:57:53.280
And their indifference towards Jane, when not immediately before them, restored Elizabeth

00:57:53.280 --> 00:57:55.880
to the enjoyment of all her former dislike.

00:57:57.100 --> 00:58:02.200
Their brother, indeed, was the only one of the party whom she could regard with any complacency.

00:58:02.920 --> 00:58:08.780
His anxiety for Jane was evident, and his attentions to herself most pleasing, and they

00:58:08.780 --> 00:58:13.460
prevented her feeling herself so much an intruder as she believed she was considered by the

00:58:13.460 --> 00:58:13.740
others.

00:58:14.540 --> 00:58:17.760
She had very little notice from any but him.

00:58:18.420 --> 00:58:23.520
Miss Bingley was engrossed by Mr. Darcy, her sister scarcely less so.

00:58:24.060 --> 00:58:30.660
And as for Mr. Hurst, by whom Elizabeth sat, he was an indolent man, who lived only to

00:58:30.660 --> 00:58:36.1000
eat, drink, and play at cards, who, when he found her to prefer a plain dish to a ragu,

00:58:37.460 --> 00:58:39.200
had nothing to say to her.

00:58:40.680 --> 00:58:46.100
When dinner was over, she returned directly to Jane, and Miss Bingley began abusing her

00:58:46.100 --> 00:58:48.080
as soon as she was out of the room.

00:58:48.820 --> 00:58:53.780
Her manners were pronounced to be very bad indeed, a mixture of pride and impertinence.

00:58:54.220 --> 00:58:57.880
She had no conversation, no style, no beauty.

00:58:58.960 --> 00:59:01.080
Mrs. Hurst thought the same, and added,

00:59:01.580 --> 00:59:05.840
She has nothing, in short, to recommend her, but being an excellent walker.

00:59:05.840 --> 00:59:08.800
I shall never forget her appearance this morning.

00:59:09.160 --> 00:59:11.360
She really looked almost wild.

00:59:12.680 --> 00:59:14.540
She did, indeed, Louisa.

00:59:15.100 --> 00:59:17.200
I could hardly keep my countenance.

00:59:17.560 --> 00:59:19.600
Very nonsensical to come at all.

00:59:20.160 --> 00:59:24.720
Why must she be scampering about the country, because her sister had a cold.

00:59:25.380 --> 00:59:29.360
Her hair, so untidy, so blowsy.

00:59:30.280 --> 00:59:31.820
Yes, and her petticoat.

00:59:32.020 --> 00:59:34.160
I hope you saw her petticoat.

00:59:34.160 --> 00:59:37.500
Six inches deep in mud, I am absolutely certain.

00:59:38.040 --> 00:59:42.140
And the gown which had been let down to hide it, not doing its office.

00:59:43.440 --> 00:59:49.740
Your picture may be very exact, Louisa, said Bingley, but this was all lost upon me.

00:59:50.200 --> 00:59:54.780
I thought Miss Elizabeth Bennet looked remarkably well when she came into the room this morning.

00:59:55.220 --> 00:59:58.160
Her dirty petticoat quite escaped my notice.

01:00:00.100 --> 01:00:09.540
You observed it, Mr. Darcy, I am sure, said Miss Bingley, and I am inclined to think that you would not wish to see your sister make such an exhibition.

01:00:10.660 --> 01:00:11.700
Certainly not.

01:00:12.540 --> 01:00:22.460
To walk three miles, or four miles, or five miles, or whatever it was, above her ankles in dirt, and alone, quite alone.

01:00:22.720 --> 01:00:24.380
What could she mean by it?

01:00:24.380 --> 01:00:31.640
It seems to me to show an abominable sort of conceited independence, a most country town in difference to decorum.

01:00:32.480 --> 01:00:37.160
It shows an affection for her sister that is very pleasing, said Bingley.

01:00:38.860 --> 01:00:48.560
I am afraid, Mr. Darcy, observed Miss Bingley in a half whisper, that this adventure has rather affected your admiration of her fine eyes.

01:00:49.420 --> 01:00:51.460
Not at all, he replied.

01:00:52.120 --> 01:00:54.020
They were brightened by the exercise.

01:00:56.020 --> 01:00:59.1000
A short pause followed this speech, and Mrs. Hurst began again.

01:01:00.920 --> 01:01:03.940
I have an excessive regard for Miss Jane Bennet.

01:01:04.240 --> 01:01:08.980
She is really a very sweet girl, and I wish with all my heart she were well settled.

01:01:09.520 --> 01:01:15.820
But with such a father and mother, and such low connections, I am afraid there is no chance of it.

01:01:17.060 --> 01:01:21.100
I think I have heard you say that their uncle is an attorney on Meryton.

01:01:22.120 --> 01:01:25.400
Yes, and they have another who lives somewhere near Cheapside.

01:01:26.560 --> 01:01:30.920
That is capital, added her sister, and they both laughed heartily.

01:01:32.260 --> 01:01:39.560
If they had uncles enough to fill all Cheapside, cried Bingley, it would not make them one jot less agreeable.

01:01:40.470 --> 01:01:47.680
But it must very materially lessen their chance of marrying men of any consideration in the world, replied Darcy.

01:01:49.040 --> 01:01:54.640
To this speech, Bingley made no answer, but his sisters gave it their hearty assent,

01:01:55.100 --> 01:02:00.600
and indulged their mirth for some time at the expense of their dear friend's vulgar relations.

01:02:01.1000 --> 01:02:07.200
With a renewal of tenderness, however, they returned to her room on leaving the dining parlor,

01:02:07.380 --> 01:02:09.360
and sat with her till summoned to coffee.

01:02:10.020 --> 01:02:15.500
She was still very poorly, and Elizabeth would not quit her at all till late in the evening,

01:02:15.860 --> 01:02:17.1000
when she had the comfort of seeing her sleep,

01:02:18.080 --> 01:02:23.920
and when it seemed to her rather ripe than pleasant that she should go downstairs herself.

01:02:24.540 --> 01:02:30.660
On entering the drawing-room, she found the whole party at Lou, and was immediately invited to join them,

01:02:31.160 --> 01:02:34.340
but suspecting them to be playing high, she declined it,

01:02:34.640 --> 01:02:40.100
and making her sister the excuse, said she would amuse herself for the short time she could stay below with a book.

01:02:41.580 --> 01:02:43.840
Mr. Hurst looked at her with astonishment.

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:49.860
Do you prefer reading to cards, said he, that is rather singular.

01:02:51.280 --> 01:02:55.720
Miss Eliza Bennet, said Miss Bingley, despises cards.

01:02:56.160 --> 01:03:00.200
She is a great reader, and has no pleasure in anything else.

01:03:01.340 --> 01:03:05.440
I deserve neither such praise nor such censure, cried Elizabeth.

01:03:05.960 --> 01:03:09.500
I am not a great reader, and I have pleasure in many things.

01:03:10.680 --> 01:03:14.380
In nursing your sister, I am sure you have pleasure, said Bingley,

01:03:14.660 --> 01:03:18.220
and I hope it will soon be increased by seeing her quite well.

01:03:19.920 --> 01:03:25.760
Elizabeth thanked him from her heart, and then walked toward the table where a few books were lying.

01:03:26.460 --> 01:03:31.020
He immediately offered to fetch her others, all that his library afforded.

01:03:31.440 --> 01:03:35.140
And I wish my collection were larger for your benefit and my own credit,

01:03:35.480 --> 01:03:40.360
but I am an idle fellow, and though I have not many, I have more than I ever looked into.

01:03:41.920 --> 01:03:45.960
Elizabeth assured him that she could suit herself perfectly with those in the room.

01:03:46.860 --> 01:03:53.240
I am astonished, said Miss Bingley, that my father should have left so small a collection of books.

01:03:53.880 --> 01:03:57.180
What a delightful library you have at Pemberley, Mr. Darcy.

01:03:57.920 --> 01:04:00.360
It ought to be good, he replied.

01:04:00.620 --> 01:04:02.980
It has been the work of many generations.

01:04:04.420 --> 01:04:07.060
And then you have added so much to it yourself.

01:04:07.240 --> 01:04:09.180
You are always buying books.

01:04:09.980 --> 01:04:15.200
I cannot comprehend the neglect of a family library in such days as these.

01:04:16.760 --> 01:04:17.320
Neglect?

01:04:17.940 --> 01:04:22.540
I am sure you neglect nothing that can add to the beauties of that noble place.

01:04:23.340 --> 01:04:28.580
Charles, when you build your house, I wish it may be half as delightful as Pemberley.

01:04:29.620 --> 01:04:30.880
I wish it may.

01:04:31.940 --> 01:04:35.740
But I would really advise you to make your purchase in that neighborhood

01:04:35.740 --> 01:04:38.080
and take Pemberley for a kind of model.

01:04:38.600 --> 01:04:43.680
There is not a finer county in England than Derbyshire, with all my heart.

01:04:43.680 --> 01:04:46.900
I will buy Pemberley itself, if Darcy will sell it.

01:04:47.440 --> 01:04:50.460
I am talking of possibilities, Charles.

01:04:51.560 --> 01:04:57.320
Upon my word, Carolyn, I should think it more possible to get Pemberley by purchase than by imitation.

01:04:58.720 --> 01:05:03.1000
Elizabeth was so much caught with what passed as to leave her very little attention for her book.

01:05:04.480 --> 01:05:08.440
And soon, laying it wholly aside, she drew near the card-table

01:05:08.440 --> 01:05:13.320
and stationed herself between Mr. Bingley and his eldest sister to observe the game.

01:05:14.500 --> 01:05:18.580
Is Miss Darcy much grown since the spring, said Miss Bingley?

01:05:18.1000 --> 01:05:20.740
Will she be as tall as I am?

01:05:21.400 --> 01:05:22.640
I think she will.

01:05:23.080 --> 01:05:26.800
She is now about Miss Elizabeth Bennet's height, or rather taller.

01:05:28.140 --> 01:05:30.060
How I long to see her again!

01:05:30.500 --> 01:05:33.1000
I never met with anybody who delighted me so much.

01:05:33.1000 --> 01:05:39.640
Such countenance, such manners, and so extremely accomplished for her age.

01:05:40.220 --> 01:05:43.500
Her performance on the piano fort is exquisite.

01:05:44.880 --> 01:05:52.480
It is amazing to me, said Bingley, how young ladies can have the patience to be so very accomplished as they all are.

01:05:53.820 --> 01:05:55.720
All young ladies accomplished?

01:05:56.320 --> 01:05:58.540
My dear Charles, what do you mean?

01:05:59.280 --> 01:06:01.140
Yes, all of them, I think.

01:06:01.140 --> 01:06:04.960
They all paint tables, cover screens, and net purses.

01:06:05.280 --> 01:06:08.040
I scarcely know anyone who cannot do all this,

01:06:08.200 --> 01:06:11.1000
and I am sure I never heard a young lady spoken of for the first time

01:06:11.1000 --> 01:06:14.720
without being informed that she was very accomplished.

01:06:15.860 --> 01:06:21.760
Your list of the common extent of accomplishments, said Darcy, has too much truth.

01:06:22.220 --> 01:06:25.780
The word is applied to many a woman who deserves it no otherwise

01:06:25.780 --> 01:06:28.960
than by netting a purse or covering a screen.

01:06:28.960 --> 01:06:33.780
But I am very far from agreeing with you and your estimation of ladies in general.

01:06:34.520 --> 01:06:39.260
I cannot boast of knowing more than half a dozen in the whole range of my acquaintance

01:06:39.260 --> 01:06:40.920
that are really accomplished.

01:06:42.380 --> 01:06:45.320
Nor I, I am sure, said Miss Bingley.

01:06:46.700 --> 01:06:53.120
Then, observed Elizabeth, you must comprehend a great deal in your idea of an accomplished woman.

01:06:53.940 --> 01:06:56.440
Yes, I do comprehend a great deal in it.

01:06:57.400 --> 01:07:00.380
Oh, certainly! cried his faithful assistant.

01:07:01.140 --> 01:07:07.140
No one can be really esteemed accomplished who does not greatly surpass what is usually met with.

01:07:07.640 --> 01:07:12.780
A woman must have a thorough knowledge of music, singing, drawing, dancing,

01:07:13.200 --> 01:07:16.600
and the modern languages to deserve the word,

01:07:17.020 --> 01:07:22.280
and besides all this she must possess a certain something in her air and manner of walking,

01:07:22.780 --> 01:07:25.840
the tone of her voice, her address and expressions,

01:07:25.840 --> 01:07:28.800
or the word would be but half deserved.

01:07:29.880 --> 01:07:33.020
All this she must possess, added Darcy,

01:07:33.520 --> 01:07:37.480
and to all this she must yet add something more substantial

01:07:37.480 --> 01:07:40.920
in the improvement of her mind by extensive reading.

01:07:42.100 --> 01:07:46.560
I am no longer surprised at your knowing only six accomplished women.

01:07:46.1000 --> 01:07:49.460
I rather wonder now at your knowing any.

01:07:50.480 --> 01:07:55.300
Are you so severe upon your own sex as to doubt the possibility of all this?

01:07:56.040 --> 01:07:57.860
I never saw such a woman.

01:07:58.220 --> 01:08:04.820
I never saw such capacity and taste and application and elegance as you describe united.

01:08:06.400 --> 01:08:11.580
Mrs. Hurst and Miss Bingley both cried out against the injustice of her implied doubt

01:08:11.580 --> 01:08:16.060
and were both protesting that they knew many women who answered this description

01:08:16.060 --> 01:08:18.600
when Mr. Hurst called them to order,

01:08:18.900 --> 01:08:22.460
with bitter complaints of their inattention to what was going forward.

01:08:22.460 --> 01:08:26.120
As all conversation was thereby at an end,

01:08:26.680 --> 01:08:28.880
Elizabeth soon afterwards left the room.

01:08:30.500 --> 01:08:34.580
Elizabeth Bennet, said Miss Bingley when the door was closed on her,

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:39.440
is one of those young ladies who seek to recommend themselves to the other sex

01:08:39.440 --> 01:08:41.860
by undervaluing their own,

01:08:42.440 --> 01:08:45.740
and with many men, I dare say, it succeeds,

01:08:46.300 --> 01:08:51.320
but in my opinion it is a paltry device, a very mean art.

01:08:52.520 --> 01:08:57.040
Undoubtedly, replied Darcy, to whom this remark was chiefly addressed,

01:08:57.780 --> 01:09:03.980
there is a meanness in all the arts which ladies sometimes condescend to employ for captivation.

01:09:04.800 --> 01:09:07.880
Whatever bears affinity to cunning is despicable.

01:09:10.040 --> 01:09:16.080
Miss Bingley was not so entirely satisfied with this reply as to continue the subject.

01:09:17.700 --> 01:09:21.480
Elizabeth joined them again only to say that her sister was worse

01:09:21.480 --> 01:09:24.100
and that she could not leave her.

01:09:24.440 --> 01:09:27.140
Bingley urged Mr. Jones being sent for immediately,

01:09:28.160 --> 01:09:32.060
while his sisters, convinced that no country advice could be of any service,

01:09:32.640 --> 01:09:36.200
recommended and expressed to town for one of the most eminent physicians.

01:09:37.040 --> 01:09:38.820
This she would not hear of,

01:09:39.020 --> 01:09:42.240
but she was not so unwilling to comply with their brother's proposal,

01:09:42.240 --> 01:09:47.080
and it was settled that Mr. Jones should be sent for early in the morning,

01:09:47.480 --> 01:09:49.880
if Miss Bennet were not decidedly better.

01:09:50.940 --> 01:09:52.460
Bingley was quite uncomfortable.

01:09:53.120 --> 01:09:55.660
His sisters declared that they were miserable.

01:09:56.340 --> 01:10:00.080
They solaced their wretchedness, however, by duets after supper,

01:10:00.680 --> 01:10:03.740
while he could find no better relief to his feelings

01:10:03.740 --> 01:10:05.920
than by giving his housekeeper directions

01:10:05.920 --> 01:10:10.600
that every attention might be paid to the sixth lady and her sister.

01:10:14.580 --> 01:10:22.540
Recorded by Maureen O'Brien, Kettering, Ohio, November 14, 2005

01:10:53.860 --> 01:10:58.480
Elizabeth passed the chief of the night in her sister's room, and in the morning had

01:10:58.480 --> 01:11:03.300
the pleasure of being able to send a tolerable answer to the inquiries which she very early

01:11:03.300 --> 01:11:09.260
received from Mr. Bingley by a housemaid, and some time afterwards from the two elegant

01:11:09.260 --> 01:11:11.840
ladies who waited on his sister's.

01:11:11.940 --> 01:11:17.800
In spite of this amendment, however, she requested to have a note sent to Longbourn, desiring

01:11:17.800 --> 01:11:21.560
her mother to visit Jane and form her own judgment of her situation.

01:11:22.280 --> 01:11:27.360
The note was immediately dispatched, and its contents as quickly complied with.

01:11:28.160 --> 01:11:33.560
Mrs. Bennet, accompanied by her two youngest girls, reached Netherfield soon after the

01:11:33.560 --> 01:11:34.480
family breakfast.

01:11:35.580 --> 01:11:40.600
Had she found Jane in any apparent danger, Mrs. Bennet would have been very miserable.

01:11:41.240 --> 01:11:46.500
But being satisfied on seeing her that her illness was not alarming, she had no wish

01:11:46.500 --> 01:11:52.280
of her recovering immediately, as her restoration to health would probably remove her from Netherfield.

01:11:53.200 --> 01:11:57.500
She would not listen, therefore, to her daughter's proposal of being carried home.

01:11:58.260 --> 01:12:03.960
Neither did the apothecary, who arrived about the same time, think it at all advisable.

01:12:05.220 --> 01:12:09.920
After sitting a little while with Jane, on Miss Bingley's appearance and invitation,

01:12:10.460 --> 01:12:14.620
the mother and three daughters all attended her into the breakfast parlour.

01:12:15.460 --> 01:12:20.500
Bingley met them with hopes that Mrs. Bennet had not found Miss Bennet worse than she expected.

01:12:22.300 --> 01:12:24.800
"'Indeed I have, sir,' was her answer.

01:12:24.980 --> 01:12:27.560
"'She is a great deal too ill to be moved.

01:12:27.880 --> 01:12:31.100
Mr. Jones says we must not think of moving her.

01:12:31.300 --> 01:12:34.220
We must trespass a little longer on your kindness.'

01:12:36.100 --> 01:12:37.600
"'Remove,' cried Bingley.

01:12:37.720 --> 01:12:39.480
"'It must not be thought of.

01:12:39.560 --> 01:12:42.620
My sister, I am sure, will not hear of her removal.'

01:12:43.680 --> 01:12:48.300
"'You may depend upon it, madam,' said Miss Bingley, with cold civility,

01:12:48.700 --> 01:12:53.620
"'that Miss Bennet will receive every possible attention while she remains with us.'

01:12:54.600 --> 01:12:57.420
Mrs. Bennet was profuse in her acknowledgments.

01:12:58.220 --> 01:13:00.240
"'I am sure,' she added,

01:13:00.320 --> 01:13:04.400
"'if it was not for such good friends I do not know what would become of her,

01:13:04.540 --> 01:13:10.480
for she is very ill indeed, and suffers a vast deal, though with the greatest patience in the world,

01:13:10.480 --> 01:13:16.720
which is always the way with her, for she has without exception the sweetest temper I have ever met with.

01:13:17.080 --> 01:13:20.060
I often tell my other girls they are nothing to her.

01:13:20.820 --> 01:13:25.540
"'You have a sweet room here, Mr. Bingley, and a charming prospect over the gravel walk.

01:13:25.740 --> 01:13:29.220
I do not know a place in the country that is equal to Netherfield.

01:13:29.680 --> 01:13:34.480
You will not think of quitting it in a hurry, I hope, though you have but a short lease.'

01:13:35.640 --> 01:13:38.480
"'Whatever I do is done in a hurry,' replied he,

01:13:38.480 --> 01:13:43.380
and therefore if I should resolve to quit Netherfield I should probably be off in five minutes.

01:13:44.260 --> 01:13:48.520
At present, however, I consider myself as quite fixed here.'

01:13:48.520 --> 01:13:52.580
"'That is exactly what I should have supposed of you,' said Elizabeth.

01:13:53.120 --> 01:13:57.440
"'You begin to comprehend me, do you?' cried he, turning toward her.

01:13:57.960 --> 01:14:00.560
"'Oh, yes, I understand you perfectly.

01:14:01.900 --> 01:14:08.480
"'I wish I might take this for a compliment, but to be so easily seen through, I am afraid, is pitiful.'

01:14:09.120 --> 01:14:10.900
"'That is as it happens.

01:14:11.140 --> 01:14:18.040
It does not follow that a deep, intricate character is more or less estimable than such a one as yours.'

01:14:18.840 --> 01:14:20.160
"'Lizzie,' cried her mother,

01:14:20.400 --> 01:14:25.540
"'remember where you are, and do not run on in the wild manner that you are suffered to do at home.'

01:14:26.500 --> 01:14:29.940
"'I did not know before,' continued Bingley immediately,

01:14:29.940 --> 01:14:34.660
"'that you were a studier of character. It must be an amusing study.'

01:14:34.660 --> 01:14:40.540
"'Yes, but intricate characters are the most amusing. They have at least that advantage.'

01:14:41.440 --> 01:14:43.560
"'The country,' said Darcy,

01:14:43.680 --> 01:14:47.100
"'can in general supply but a few subjects for such a study.

01:14:47.380 --> 01:14:52.240
In a country neighbourhood you move in a very confined and unvarying society.

01:14:53.200 --> 01:14:59.700
"'But people themselves alter so much that there is something new to be observed in them for ever.'

01:14:59.700 --> 01:15:02.400
"'Yes, indeed,' cried Mrs. Bennet,

01:15:02.700 --> 01:15:05.280
offended by his manner of mentioning a country neighbourhood.

01:15:05.540 --> 01:15:11.240
"'I assure you there is quite as much of that going on in the country as in town.'

01:15:12.420 --> 01:15:19.060
"'Everybody was surprised, and Darcy, after looking at her for a moment, turned silently away.

01:15:19.060 --> 01:15:25.660
"'Mrs. Bennet, who fancied she had gained a complete victory over him, continued her triumph.

01:15:26.920 --> 01:15:33.900
"'I cannot see that London has any great advantage over the country, for my part, except the shops and public places.

01:15:34.180 --> 01:15:38.300
"'The country is a vast deal pleasanter, is it not, Mr. Bingley?'

01:15:38.300 --> 01:15:41.000
"'When I am in the country,' he replied,

01:15:41.040 --> 01:15:46.140
"'I never wish to leave it. And when I am in town, it is pretty much the same.

01:15:46.140 --> 01:15:50.140
"'They have each their advantages, and I can be equally happy in either.'

01:15:51.260 --> 01:15:54.120
"'Aye, that is because you have the right disposition.

01:15:54.420 --> 01:16:00.140
"'But that gentleman, looking at Darcy, seemed to think the country was nothing at all.'

01:16:01.000 --> 01:16:05.440
"'Indeed, Mama, you are mistaken,' said Elizabeth, blushing for her mother.

01:16:05.900 --> 01:16:08.020
"'You quite mistook Mr. Darcy.

01:16:08.200 --> 01:16:13.900
"'He only meant that there was not such a variety of people to be met with in the country as in the town,

01:16:13.900 --> 01:16:16.900
"'which you must acknowledge to be true.'

01:16:17.880 --> 01:16:20.400
"'Certainly, my dear, nobody said there were.

01:16:20.480 --> 01:16:26.140
"'But as to not meeting with many people in this neighbourhood, I believe there are few neighbourhoods larger.

01:16:26.400 --> 01:16:29.900
"'I know we dine with four-and-twenty families.'

01:16:31.040 --> 01:16:35.540
"'Nothing but concern for Elizabeth could enable Bingley to keep his countenance.

01:16:35.940 --> 01:16:42.120
"'His sister was less delicate, and directed her eyes toward Mr. Darcy with a very expressive smile.

01:16:43.400 --> 01:16:47.420
"'Elizabeth, for the sake of saying something that might turn her mother's thoughts,

01:16:47.960 --> 01:16:52.120
"'now asked her if Charlotte Lucas had been at Longbourn since her coming away.'

01:16:53.880 --> 01:16:56.280
"'Yes, she called yesterday with her father.

01:16:56.440 --> 01:17:00.500
"'What an agreeable man, Sir William is, Mr. Bingley, is not he?

01:17:00.800 --> 01:17:07.780
"'So much the man of fashion, so genteel and easy, he had always something to say to everybody.

01:17:07.780 --> 01:17:13.800
"'That is my idea of good breeding, and those persons who fancy themselves very important

01:17:13.800 --> 01:17:17.900
"'and never open their mouths quite mistake the matter.'

01:17:17.900 --> 01:17:20.200
"'Did Charlotte dine with you?'

01:17:20.780 --> 01:17:22.480
"'No, she would go home.

01:17:22.780 --> 01:17:25.740
"'I fancy she was wanted about the mince pies.

01:17:26.320 --> 01:17:30.720
"'For my part, Mr. Bingley, I always keep servants that can do their own work.

01:17:30.860 --> 01:17:33.240
"'My daughters are brought up very differently.

01:17:33.240 --> 01:17:39.640
"'But everybody is to judge for themselves, and the Lucases are a very good sort of girls, I assure you.

01:17:39.640 --> 01:17:41.900
"'It is a pity they are not handsome.

01:17:42.420 --> 01:17:48.240
"'Not that I think Charlotte's so very plain, but then she is our particular friend.'

01:17:49.540 --> 01:17:52.240
"'She seems a very pleasant young woman.'

01:17:52.980 --> 01:17:56.860
"'Oh dear, yes, but you must own she is very plain.

01:17:57.280 --> 01:18:02.300
"'Lady Lucas herself has often said so, and envied me Jane's beauty.

01:18:02.300 --> 01:18:10.520
"'I do not like to boast of my own child, but to be sure, Jane, one does not often see anybody better looking.

01:18:10.760 --> 01:18:12.740
"'It is what everybody says.

01:18:12.960 --> 01:18:15.680
"'I do not trust my own partiality.

01:18:16.380 --> 01:18:22.660
"'When she was only fifteen, there was a man at my brother Gardiner's in town so much in love with her

01:18:22.660 --> 01:18:26.920
"'that my sister-in-law was sure he would make her an offer before we came away.

01:18:27.560 --> 01:18:29.780
"'But, however, he did not.

01:18:29.780 --> 01:18:31.680
"'Perhaps he thought her too young.

01:18:32.300 --> 01:18:35.920
"'However, he wrote some verses on her, and very pretty they were.'

01:18:37.040 --> 01:18:41.280
"'And so ended his affection,' said Elizabeth impatiently.

01:18:41.280 --> 01:18:45.000
"'There has been many a one I fancy overcome in the same way.

01:18:45.200 --> 01:18:49.780
"'I wonder who first discovered the efficacy of poetry in driving away love.'

01:18:51.160 --> 01:18:56.000
"'I have been used to consider poetry as the food of love,' said Darcy.

01:18:56.000 --> 01:18:59.920
"'Of a fine stout healthy love it may.

01:19:00.360 --> 01:19:02.900
"'Everything nourishes what is strong already.

01:19:03.080 --> 01:19:06.840
"'But if it be only a slight thin sort of inclination,

01:19:06.940 --> 01:19:12.180
"'I am convinced that one good sonnet will starve it entirely away.'

01:19:12.980 --> 01:19:14.640
"'Darcy only smiled.

01:19:15.180 --> 01:19:21.660
"'And the general pause which ensued made Elizabeth tremble, lest her mother should be exposing herself again.

01:19:21.660 --> 01:19:25.220
"'She longed to speak, but could think of nothing to say.

01:19:25.380 --> 01:19:31.800
"'And after a short silence, Mrs. Bennet began repeating her thanks to Mr. Bingley for his kindness to Jane,

01:19:32.140 --> 01:19:34.800
"'with an apology for troubling him also with Lizzie.

01:19:35.280 --> 01:19:38.620
"'Mr. Bingley was unaffectedly civil in his answer,

01:19:38.840 --> 01:19:43.260
"'and forced his younger sister to be civil also, and say what the occasion required.

01:19:43.820 --> 01:19:47.420
"'She performed her part indeed without much graciousness,

01:19:47.420 --> 01:19:51.880
"'but Mrs. Bennet was satisfied, and soon afterwards ordered her carriage.

01:19:52.960 --> 01:19:56.880
"'Upon this signal the youngest of her daughters put herself forward.

01:19:57.200 --> 01:20:00.760
"'The two girls had been whispering to each other during the whole visit,

01:20:00.780 --> 01:20:04.300
"'and the result of it was that the youngest should tax Mr. Bingley

01:20:04.300 --> 01:20:09.320
"'with having promised on his first coming into the country to give a ball at Netherfield.

01:20:10.620 --> 01:20:13.660
"'Lydia was a stout, well-grown girl of fifteen,

01:20:13.660 --> 01:20:17.720
"'with a fine complexion and a good-humoured countenance,

01:20:17.940 --> 01:20:22.400
"'a favourite with her mother, whose affection had brought her into public at an early age.

01:20:22.860 --> 01:20:27.900
"'She had high animal spirits, and a sort of natural self-consequence,

01:20:28.080 --> 01:20:32.200
"'which the attention of the officers, to whom her uncle's good dinners

01:20:32.200 --> 01:20:37.040
"'and her own easy manners recommended her, had increased into assurance.

01:20:37.460 --> 01:20:42.180
"'She was very equal, therefore, to address Mr. Bingley on the subject of the ball,

01:20:42.180 --> 01:20:46.300
"'and abruptly reminded him of his promise, adding that it would be

01:20:46.300 --> 01:20:50.100
"'the most shameful thing in the world if he did not keep it.

01:20:50.860 --> 01:20:54.880
"'His answer to this sudden attack was delightful to their mother's ear.

01:20:55.620 --> 01:20:59.280
"'I am perfectly ready, I assure you, to keep my engagement.

01:20:59.560 --> 01:21:05.280
"'And when your sister is recovered, you shall, if you please, name the very day of the ball.

01:21:05.860 --> 01:21:09.180
"'But you would not wish to be dancing when she is ill.'

01:21:10.240 --> 01:21:12.560
"'Lydia declared herself satisfied.

01:21:13.380 --> 01:21:17.340
"'Oh, yes, it would be much better to wait till Jane was well,

01:21:17.360 --> 01:21:21.420
"'and by that time most likely Captain Carter would be at Meryton again.

01:21:21.540 --> 01:21:24.360
"'And when you have given your ball,' she added,

01:21:24.360 --> 01:21:27.460
"'I shall insist on their giving one also.

01:21:27.640 --> 01:21:32.580
"'I shall tell Colonel Forster it will be quite a shame if he does not.'

01:21:32.580 --> 01:21:35.540
"'Mrs. Bennet and her daughters then departed,

01:21:35.540 --> 01:21:38.560
"'and Elizabeth returned instantly to Jane,

01:21:38.920 --> 01:21:44.260
"'leaving her own and her relations' behaviour to the remarks of the two ladies and Mr. Darcy,

01:21:44.960 --> 01:21:50.220
"'the latter of whom, however, could not be prevailed on to join in their censure of her,

01:21:50.660 --> 01:21:55.540
"'in spite of all Miss Bingley's witticisms on Fine Eyes.'

01:22:05.540 --> 01:22:05.640
THE END

01:22:30.780 --> 01:22:32.800
This reading by Gord Mackenzie.

01:22:34.660 --> 01:22:39.420
Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen.

01:22:41.460 --> 01:22:44.280
The day passed much as the day before had done.

01:22:44.920 --> 01:22:50.220
Mrs. Hurst and Miss Bingley had spent some hours of the morning with the invalid, who

01:22:50.220 --> 01:22:55.720
continued, though slowly, to mend, and in the evening Elizabeth joined their party in

01:22:55.720 --> 01:22:56.440
the drawing-room.

01:22:57.240 --> 01:22:59.920
The Lou table, however, did not appear.

01:23:00.580 --> 01:23:06.700
Mr. Darcy was writing, and Miss Bingley, seated near him, was watching the progress of his

01:23:06.700 --> 01:23:10.400
letter and repeatedly calling off his attention by messages to his sister.

01:23:11.860 --> 01:23:17.720
Mr. Hurst and Mr. Bingley were at piquette, and Mrs. Hurst was observing their game.

01:23:19.520 --> 01:23:24.800
Elizabeth took up some needlework, and was sufficiently amused in attending to what passed

01:23:24.800 --> 01:23:26.500
between Darcy and his companion.

01:23:27.380 --> 01:23:33.600
The perpetual commendations of the lady, either on his handwriting, or on the evenness of

01:23:33.600 --> 01:23:39.120
his lines, or on the length of his letter, with the perfect unconcern with which her

01:23:39.120 --> 01:23:46.320
praises were received, formed a curious dialogue, and was exactly in union with her opinion

01:23:46.320 --> 01:23:46.940
of each.

01:23:48.000 --> 01:23:51.380
How delighted Miss Darcy will be to receive such a letter!

01:23:52.260 --> 01:23:53.420
He made no answer.

01:23:53.420 --> 01:23:56.340
You write uncommonly fast.

01:23:58.000 --> 01:23:58.920
You are mistaken.

01:23:59.580 --> 01:24:01.080
I write rather slowly.

01:24:02.760 --> 01:24:07.640
How many letters you must have occasion to write in the course of a year, letters of

01:24:07.640 --> 01:24:08.520
business, too!

01:24:09.000 --> 01:24:10.780
How odious I should think them!

01:24:11.700 --> 01:24:16.680
It is fortunate, then, that they fall to my lot instead of yours.

01:24:18.400 --> 01:24:21.500
Pray tell your sister that I long to see her.

01:24:22.080 --> 01:24:25.840
I have already told her so once, by your desire.

01:24:26.940 --> 01:24:29.060
I am afraid you do not like your pen.

01:24:29.360 --> 01:24:30.580
Let me mend it for you.

01:24:30.740 --> 01:24:33.460
I mend pens remarkably well.

01:24:34.340 --> 01:24:37.220
Thank you, but I always mend my own.

01:24:38.720 --> 01:24:41.820
How can you contrive to write so even?

01:24:42.600 --> 01:24:43.860
He was silent.

01:24:44.660 --> 01:24:50.040
Tell your sister I am delighted to hear of her improvement on the harp, and pray let

01:24:50.040 --> 01:24:55.520
her know that I am quite in raptures with her beautiful little design for a table, and

01:24:55.520 --> 01:24:58.820
I think it infinitely superior to Miss Grantley's.

01:24:59.720 --> 01:25:03.560
Will you give me leave to defer your raptures till I write again?

01:25:03.940 --> 01:25:06.360
At present I have not room to do them justice.

01:25:07.560 --> 01:25:13.440
Though it is of no consequence I shall see her in January, but do you always write such

01:25:13.440 --> 01:25:16.120
charming long letters to her, Mr. Darcy?

01:25:16.800 --> 01:25:22.100
They are generally long, but whether always charming it is not for me to determine.

01:25:23.420 --> 01:25:29.660
It is a rule with me that a person who can write a long letter with ease cannot write

01:25:29.660 --> 01:25:30.120
ill.

01:25:31.240 --> 01:25:35.960
That will not do for a compliment to Darcy, Caroline, cried her brother, because he does

01:25:35.960 --> 01:25:36.880
not write with ease.

01:25:37.100 --> 01:25:40.040
He studies too much for words of four syllables.

01:25:40.620 --> 01:25:41.800
Do not you, Darcy?

01:25:42.720 --> 01:25:46.520
My style of writing is very different from yours.'

01:25:46.520 --> 01:25:52.700
"'O,' cried Miss Bingley, Charles writes in the most careless way imaginable.

01:25:52.940 --> 01:25:56.420
He leaves out half his words and blots the rest.

01:25:57.500 --> 01:26:02.560
My ideas flow so rapidly that I have not time to express them, by which means my letters

01:26:02.560 --> 01:26:05.400
sometimes convey no ideas at all to my correspondence.'

01:26:06.620 --> 01:26:11.560
"'Your humility, Mr. Bingley,' said Elizabeth, must disarm reproof.'

01:26:12.560 --> 01:26:17.480
"'Nothing is more deceitful,' said Darcy, than the appearance of humility.

01:26:17.880 --> 01:26:22.180
It is often only carelessness of opinion, and sometimes an indirect boast.

01:26:22.820 --> 01:26:27.580
And which do you two call my little recent piece of modesty?'

01:26:27.580 --> 01:26:29.120
"'The indirect boast.

01:26:29.400 --> 01:26:34.340
For you are really proud of your defects in writing, because you consider them as proceeding

01:26:34.340 --> 01:26:40.040
from rapidity of thought and carelessness of execution, which, if not estimable, you

01:26:40.040 --> 01:26:41.600
think at least highly interesting.

01:26:42.260 --> 01:26:46.400
The power of doing anything with quickness is always prized much by the possessor, and

01:26:46.400 --> 01:26:49.700
often without any attention to the imperfection of the performance.

01:26:50.660 --> 01:26:55.680
When you told Mrs. Bennet this morning that if you ever resolved upon quitting Netherfield

01:26:55.680 --> 01:27:01.420
you should be gone in five minutes, you meant it to be a sort of panegyric of compliment

01:27:01.420 --> 01:27:01.920
to yourself.

01:27:02.360 --> 01:27:07.960
And yet what is there so very laudable in a precipitance which must leave very necessary

01:27:07.960 --> 01:27:12.840
business undone, and can be of no real advantage to yourself or anyone else?'

01:27:13.640 --> 01:27:19.200
"'Nay,' cried Bingley, "'this is too much to remember at night all the foolish things

01:27:19.200 --> 01:27:20.680
that were said in the morning.

01:27:21.280 --> 01:27:26.360
And yet upon my honour I believe what I said of myself to be true, and I believe it at

01:27:26.360 --> 01:27:26.840
moment.

01:27:27.380 --> 01:27:33.260
At least therefore I did not assume the character of needless precipitance merely to show off

01:27:33.260 --> 01:27:34.200
before the ladies.'

01:27:35.000 --> 01:27:36.720
"'I dare say you believed it.

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:41.060
But I am by no means convinced that you would be gone with such celerity.

01:27:41.600 --> 01:27:45.600
Your conduct would be quite as dependent on chance as that of any man I know.

01:27:45.980 --> 01:27:50.560
And if as you were mounting your horse a friend were to say, Bingley, you had better stay

01:27:50.560 --> 01:27:55.220
till next week, you would probably do it, you would probably not go, and at another

01:27:55.220 --> 01:27:56.380
might stay a month.'

01:27:57.640 --> 01:28:03.060
"'You have only proved by this,' cried Elizabeth, "'that Mr. Bingley did not do justice to his

01:28:03.060 --> 01:28:03.760
own disposition.

01:28:04.140 --> 01:28:07.220
You have shown him off now much more than he did himself.'

01:28:08.500 --> 01:28:14.020
"'I am extremely gratified,' said Bingley, "'by your converting what my friend says into

01:28:14.020 --> 01:28:16.120
a compliment on the sweetness of my temper.

01:28:16.740 --> 01:28:22.500
But I am afraid you are giving it a turn which that gentleman did by no means intend, for

01:28:22.500 --> 01:28:26.540
he would certainly think better of me if, under such a circumstance, I were to give

01:28:26.540 --> 01:28:29.720
a flat denial and ride off as fast as I could.'

01:28:31.040 --> 01:28:36.700
"'Would Mr. Darcy then consider the rashness of your original intentions as atoned for

01:28:36.700 --> 01:28:40.440
by your obstinacy in adhering to it?'

01:28:40.440 --> 01:28:43.400
"'Upon my word I cannot exactly explain the matter.

01:28:43.900 --> 01:28:45.260
Darcy must speak for himself.'

01:28:46.780 --> 01:28:51.600
"'You expect me to account for opinions which you choose to call mine, but which I have

01:28:51.600 --> 01:28:52.420
never acknowledged.

01:28:53.100 --> 01:28:58.200
Allowing the case, however, to stand according to your representation, you must remember

01:28:58.200 --> 01:29:03.120
Miss Bennet, that the friend who is supposed to desire his return to the house and the

01:29:03.120 --> 01:29:08.580
delay of his plan has merely desired it, asked it without offering one argument in favor

01:29:08.580 --> 01:29:09.480
of its propriety.'

01:29:10.800 --> 01:29:16.880
"'To yield readily, easily, to the persuasion of a friend is no merit with you?'

01:29:17.380 --> 01:29:21.920
"'To yield without conviction is no compliment to the understanding of either.'

01:29:21.920 --> 01:29:27.380
"'You appear to me, Mr. Darcy, to allow nothing for the influence of friendship and affection.

01:29:28.080 --> 01:29:33.480
A regard for the requester would often make one readily yield to a request, without waiting

01:29:33.480 --> 01:29:35.720
for arguments to reason one into it.

01:29:36.060 --> 01:29:39.960
I am not particularly speaking of such a case as you have supposed about Mr. Bingley.

01:29:40.660 --> 01:29:45.560
We may as well wait, perhaps, till the circumstance occurs before we discuss the discretion of

01:29:45.560 --> 01:29:47.000
his behavior thereupon.

01:29:47.660 --> 01:29:53.220
But in general and ordinary cases, between friend and friend, where one of them is desired

01:29:53.220 --> 01:29:58.320
by the other to change a resolution of no very great moment, should you think ill of

01:29:58.320 --> 01:30:03.340
that person for complying with the desire, without waiting to be argued into it?

01:30:04.640 --> 01:30:09.600
Will it not be advisable, before we proceed on this subject, to arrange with rather more

01:30:09.600 --> 01:30:14.340
precision the degree of importance which is to appertain to this request, as well as the

01:30:14.340 --> 01:30:18.040
degree of intimacy subsisting between the parties?'

01:30:18.040 --> 01:30:23.780
"'By all means,' cried Bingley, let us hear all the particulars, not forgetting their

01:30:23.780 --> 01:30:28.240
comparative height and size, for that will have more weight in the argument, Miss Bennet,

01:30:28.240 --> 01:30:29.440
than you may be aware of.

01:30:29.600 --> 01:30:34.360
I assure you that if Darcy were not such a great tall fellow in comparison with myself,

01:30:34.580 --> 01:30:36.620
I should not pay him half so much deference.

01:30:37.020 --> 01:30:43.480
I declare, I do not know a more awful object than Darcy on particular occasions, and in

01:30:43.480 --> 01:30:48.360
particular places, at his own house especially, and of a Sunday evening, when he has nothing

01:30:48.360 --> 01:30:50.240
to do.'

01:30:50.240 --> 01:30:55.700
Mr. Darcy smiled, but Elizabeth thought she could perceive that he was rather offended,

01:30:56.440 --> 01:30:58.040
and therefore checked her laugh.

01:30:59.140 --> 01:31:05.320
Miss Bingley warmly resented the indignity he had received in an expostulation with her

01:31:05.320 --> 01:31:07.280
brother for talking such nonsense.

01:31:08.580 --> 01:31:11.820
"'I see your design, Bingley,' said his friend.

01:31:11.980 --> 01:31:15.360
"'You dislike an argument and want to silence this.'

01:31:16.140 --> 01:31:17.580
"'Perhaps I do.

01:31:18.160 --> 01:31:20.060
Arguments are too much like disputes.

01:31:20.540 --> 01:31:25.200
If you and Miss Bennet will defer yours till I am out of the room, I shall be very thankful,

01:31:25.540 --> 01:31:28.160
and then you may say whatever you like of me.'

01:31:28.900 --> 01:31:36.280
"'What you ask,' said Elizabeth, "'is no sacrifice on my side,' and Mr. Darcy had much better

01:31:36.280 --> 01:31:38.700
finish his letter.'

01:31:38.700 --> 01:31:41.440
Mr. Darcy took her advice, and did finish his letter.

01:31:42.800 --> 01:31:47.820
When that business was over he applied to Miss Bingley and Elizabeth for an indulgence

01:31:47.820 --> 01:31:49.080
of some music.

01:31:49.860 --> 01:31:56.140
Miss Bingley moved with some alacrity to the pianoforte, and, after a polite request that

01:31:56.140 --> 01:32:01.340
Elizabeth would lead the way, which the other as politely and more earnestly negatived,

01:32:01.860 --> 01:32:02.940
she seated herself.

01:32:04.220 --> 01:32:09.180
Mrs. Hurst sang with her sister, and while they were thus employed Elizabeth could not

01:32:09.180 --> 01:32:15.420
help observing, as she turned over some music books that lay on the instrument, how frequently

01:32:15.420 --> 01:32:18.200
Mr. Darcy's eyes were fixed on her.

01:32:18.940 --> 01:32:24.760
She hardly knew how to suppose that she could be an object of admiration to so great a man,

01:32:25.200 --> 01:32:31.020
and yet that he should look at her, because he disliked her, was still more strange.

01:32:31.960 --> 01:32:37.440
She could only imagine, however, at last, that she drew his notice because there was

01:32:37.440 --> 01:32:44.440
something wrong and reprehensible according to his ideas of right than in any other person

01:32:44.440 --> 01:32:44.900
present.

01:32:46.080 --> 01:32:48.140
The supposition did not pain her.

01:32:48.780 --> 01:32:52.060
She liked him too little to care for his approbation.

01:32:53.220 --> 01:33:00.220
After playing some Italian songs Miss Bingley varied the charm by a lively Scotch air, and

01:33:00.220 --> 01:33:03.680
soon afterwards Mr. Darcy, drawing near Elizabeth, said to her,

01:33:03.960 --> 01:33:10.980
"'Do not you feel a great inclination, Miss Bennet, to seize such an opportunity of dancing

01:33:10.980 --> 01:33:12.160
a reel?'

01:33:12.860 --> 01:33:14.540
She smiled, but made no answer.

01:33:15.020 --> 01:33:18.460
He repeated the question with some surprise at her silence.

01:33:19.440 --> 01:33:24.600
"'Oh,' she said, "'I heard you before, but I could not immediately

01:33:24.600 --> 01:33:26.140
determine what to say in reply.

01:33:26.720 --> 01:33:31.300
You wanted me, I know, to say, yes, that you might have the pleasure of despising my taste.

01:33:31.980 --> 01:33:37.800
But I always delight in overthrowing those kind of schemes and cheating a person of their

01:33:37.800 --> 01:33:38.940
premeditated contempt.

01:33:39.500 --> 01:33:44.420
I have therefore made up my mind to tell you that I do not want to dance a reel at all,

01:33:44.780 --> 01:33:46.400
and now despise me if you dare.

01:33:48.380 --> 01:33:51.840
Indeed, I do not dare.'"

01:33:51.840 --> 01:33:57.020
Elizabeth, having rather expected to affront him, was amazed at his gallantry, but there

01:33:57.020 --> 01:34:01.540
was a mixture of sweetness and archness in her manner which made it difficult for her

01:34:01.540 --> 01:34:07.800
to affront anybody, and Darcy had never been so bewitched by any woman as he was by her.

01:34:08.680 --> 01:34:13.980
He really believed that were it not for the inferiority of her connections he should be

01:34:13.980 --> 01:34:15.000
in some danger.

01:34:16.260 --> 01:34:23.240
Miss Bingley saw, or suspected enough to be jealous, and her great anxiety for the recovery

01:34:23.240 --> 01:34:29.580
of her dear friend Jane received some assistance from her desire of getting rid of Elizabeth.

01:34:30.740 --> 01:34:36.820
She often tried to provoke Darcy into disliking her guest by talking of their supposed marriage

01:34:36.820 --> 01:34:39.560
and planning his happiness in such an alliance.

01:34:41.280 --> 01:34:46.580
"'I hope,' she said, as they were walking together in the shrubbery the next day, "'you

01:34:46.580 --> 01:34:52.120
will give your mother-in-law a few hints when this desirable event takes place as to the

01:34:52.120 --> 01:34:57.000
advantage of holding her tongue, and if you can compass it, do sure the younger girls

01:34:57.000 --> 01:35:03.320
of running after officers, and if I may mention so delicate a subject, endeavor to check that

01:35:03.320 --> 01:35:08.840
little something bordering on conceit and impertinence which your lady possesses.'

01:35:10.060 --> 01:35:14.360
"'Have you anything else to propose for my domestic felicity?'

01:35:15.180 --> 01:35:21.140
"'Oh, yes. Do let the portraits of your uncle and Aunt Phillips be placed in the gallery

01:35:21.140 --> 01:35:27.160
at Pemberley. Put them next to your great uncle the judge. They are in the same profession,

01:35:27.160 --> 01:35:33.860
you know, only in different lines. As for your Elizabeth's picture, you must not have

01:35:33.860 --> 01:35:40.360
it taken, for what painter could do justice to those beautiful eyes? It would not be easy

01:35:40.360 --> 01:35:48.040
indeed to catch their expression, but their color and shape and the eyelashes, so remarkably

01:35:48.040 --> 01:35:49.540
fine, might be copied.'

01:35:50.680 --> 01:35:55.360
At that moment they were met from another walk by Mrs. Hurst and Elizabeth herself.

01:35:56.820 --> 01:36:02.140
"'I did not know that you intended to walk,' said Miss Bingley in some confusion lest

01:36:02.140 --> 01:36:03.660
they had been overheard.

01:36:04.620 --> 01:36:09.800
"'You used us abominably ill,' answered Mrs. Hurst, running away without telling us that

01:36:09.800 --> 01:36:10.920
you were coming out.

01:36:12.080 --> 01:36:18.780
Then taking the disengaged arm of Mr. Darcy, she left Elizabeth to walk by herself. The

01:36:18.780 --> 01:36:24.440
path just admitted three. Mr. Darcy felt their rudeness and immediately said,

01:36:24.440 --> 01:36:28.440
"'This walk is not wide enough for our party. We had better go into the avenue.'

01:36:29.380 --> 01:36:34.420
But Elizabeth, who had not the least inclination to remain with them, laughingly answered,

01:36:35.320 --> 01:36:41.100
"'No, no, stay where you are. You are charmingly grouped and appear to uncommon advantage.

01:36:41.540 --> 01:36:46.060
The picturesque would be spoiled by admitting a fourth. Good-bye.'

01:36:46.940 --> 01:36:52.300
She then ran gaily off, rejoicing as she rambled about, in the hope of being at home again in a

01:36:52.300 --> 01:36:58.200
day or two. Jane was already so much recovered as to intend leaving her room for a couple

01:36:58.200 --> 01:36:59.520
of hours that evening.

01:37:06.380 --> 01:37:12.400
When the ladies removed after dinner, Elizabeth ran up to her sister, and seeing her well-guarded

01:37:12.400 --> 01:37:17.120
from cold, attended her into the drawing-room, where she was welcomed by her two friends

01:37:17.120 --> 01:37:22.740
with many professions of pleasure, and Elizabeth had never seen them so agreeable as they were

01:37:22.740 --> 01:37:27.940
during the hour which passed before the gentleman appeared. Their powers of conversation were

01:37:27.940 --> 01:37:34.000
considerable. They could describe an entertainment with accuracy, relate an anecdote with humor,

01:37:34.360 --> 01:37:36.960
and laugh at their acquaintance with spirit.

01:37:38.340 --> 01:37:43.800
But when the gentleman entered Jane was no longer the first object. Miss Bingley's eyes

01:37:43.800 --> 01:37:48.920
were instantly turned toward Darcy, and she had something to say to him before he had advanced

01:37:48.920 --> 01:37:55.960
many steps. He addressed himself to Miss Bennet with a polite congratulation.

01:37:56.880 --> 01:38:03.080
Mr. Hurst also made her a slight bow, and said he was very glad. But

01:38:03.080 --> 01:38:10.360
diffuseness and warmth remained for Bingley's salutation. He was full of joy and attention.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:17.000
The first half-hour was spent in piling up the fire, lest she should suffer from the change of

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:22.980
room, and she removed at his desire to the other side of the fireplace that she might be

01:38:22.980 --> 01:38:29.260
further from the door. He then sat down by her, and talked scarcely to anyone else.

01:38:30.140 --> 01:38:35.440
Elizabeth, at work in the opposite corner, saw it all with great delight.

01:38:36.300 --> 01:38:42.240
When the tea was over Mr. Hurst reminded his sister-in-law of the card table, but in vain.

01:38:43.220 --> 01:38:49.220
She had obtained private intelligence that Mr. Darcy did not wish for cards, and Mr.

01:38:49.300 --> 01:38:55.860
Hurst soon found even his open petition rejected. She assured him that no one intended to play,

01:38:56.360 --> 01:39:00.280
and the silence of the whole party on the subject seemed to justify her.

01:39:01.440 --> 01:39:07.460
Mr. Hurst had therefore nothing to do but to stretch himself on one of the sofas and go to sleep.

01:39:08.680 --> 01:39:14.300
Darcy took up a book. Miss Bingley did the same, and Mrs. Hurst, principally occupied

01:39:14.300 --> 01:39:19.600
in playing with her bracelets and rings, joined now and then in her brother's conversation with Miss

01:39:19.600 --> 01:39:27.300
Pennant. Miss Bingley's attention was quite as much engaged in watching Mr. Darcy's progress

01:39:27.300 --> 01:39:34.280
through his book as in reading her own, and she was perpetually either making some inquiry or

01:39:34.280 --> 01:39:41.900
looking at his page. She could not win him, however, to any conversation. He merely answered her

01:39:41.900 --> 01:39:48.400
question and read on. At length, quite exhausted by the attempt to be amused with her own book,

01:39:48.720 --> 01:39:54.620
which she had only chosen because it was the second volume of his, she gave a great yawn and

01:39:55.440 --> 01:40:02.720
how pleasant it is to spend an evening in this way. I declare, after all, there is no enjoyment

01:40:02.720 --> 01:40:10.200
like reading. How much sooner one tires of anything than of a book! When I have a house of my own,

01:40:10.460 --> 01:40:19.440
I shall be miserable if I have not an excellent library. No one made any reply. She then yawned

01:40:19.440 --> 01:40:25.540
again, threw aside her book, and cast her eyes round the room in quest for some amusement.

01:40:26.420 --> 01:40:32.260
When hearing her brother mentioning a ball to Miss Pennant, she turned suddenly towards him and said,

01:40:32.920 --> 01:40:39.480
By the by, Charles, are you really serious in meditating a dance at Netherfield? I would advise

01:40:39.480 --> 01:40:45.080
you, before you determine on it, to consult the wishes of the present party. I am much mistaken

01:40:45.080 --> 01:40:50.400
if there are not some among us who a ball would be rather a punishment than a pleasure.

01:40:51.480 --> 01:40:58.400
If you mean Darcy, cried her brother, he may go to bed if he chooses before it begins. But as for

01:40:58.400 --> 01:41:04.400
the ball it is quite a settled thing, and as soon as Nichols has made white soup enough I shall send

01:41:04.400 --> 01:41:11.680
round my cards. I should like balls infinitely better, she replied, if they were carried on in

01:41:11.680 --> 01:41:18.480
a different manner. But there is something insufferably tedious in the usual process of such a

01:41:18.480 --> 01:41:24.000
meeting. It would surely be much more rational if conversation instead of dancing were made the

01:41:24.000 --> 01:41:30.120
order of the day. Much more rational, my dear Caroline, I dare say, but it would not be near

01:41:30.120 --> 01:41:37.480
so much like a ball. Miss Bingley made no answer, and soon afterwards she got up and walked about

01:41:37.480 --> 01:41:45.220
the room. Her figure was elegant, and she walked well, but Darcy, at whom it was all aimed, was

01:41:45.220 --> 01:41:52.400
still inflexibly studious. In the desperation of her feelings she resolved on one effort more,

01:41:52.800 --> 01:42:00.280
and turning to Elizabeth said, Miss Eliza Bennet, let me persuade you to follow my example and take

01:42:00.280 --> 01:42:06.480
a turn about the room. I assure you it is very refreshing after sitting so long in one attitude.

01:42:07.900 --> 01:42:13.860
Elizabeth was surprised, but agreed to it immediately. Miss Bingley succeeded no less

01:42:13.860 --> 01:42:21.260
in the real object of her civility. Mr. Darcy looked up. He was as much awake to the novelty

01:42:21.260 --> 01:42:26.360
of attention in that quarter as Elizabeth herself could be, and unconsciously closed his book.

01:42:27.500 --> 01:42:34.160
He was directly invited to join their party, but he declined it, observing that he could imagine

01:42:34.160 --> 01:42:38.040
but two motives for their choosing to walk up and down the room together,

01:42:39.020 --> 01:42:42.180
with either of which motives his joining them would interfere.

01:42:44.040 --> 01:42:51.720
What could he mean? She was dying to know what could be his meaning, and asked Elizabeth whether

01:42:51.720 --> 01:43:00.080
she could at all understand him. Not at all was her answer, but depend upon it. He means to be

01:43:00.080 --> 01:43:04.840
on us, and our surest way of disappointing him will be to ask nothing about it.

01:43:05.800 --> 01:43:10.340
Miss Bingley, however, was incapable of disappointing Mr. Darcy in anything,

01:43:11.160 --> 01:43:15.200
and persevered therefore in requiring an explanation of his two motives.

01:43:16.440 --> 01:43:22.000
I have not the smallest objection to explaining them, said he, as soon as she allowed him to speak.

01:43:22.980 --> 01:43:27.780
You either choose this method of passing the evening because you are in each other's confidence,

01:43:27.780 --> 01:43:32.700
and have secret affairs to discuss, or because you are conscious that your figures appear to

01:43:32.700 --> 01:43:38.340
the greatest advantage in walking. If the first, I would be completely in your way,

01:43:38.780 --> 01:43:43.040
and if the second, I can admire you much better as I sit by the fire.

01:43:44.460 --> 01:43:50.300
Oh, shocking! cried Miss Bingley. I never heard anything so abominable.

01:43:51.060 --> 01:43:53.720
How shall we punish him for such a speech?

01:43:54.480 --> 01:43:58.660
Nothing so easy if you have but the inclination, said Elizabeth.

01:44:00.040 --> 01:44:06.440
We can all plague and punish one another. Tease him, laugh at him. Intimate as you are,

01:44:06.480 --> 01:44:14.040
you must know how it is to be done. But upon my honour I do not. I do assure you that my

01:44:14.040 --> 01:44:20.160
intimacy has not yet taught me that. Tease calmness of manner and presence of mind.

01:44:21.200 --> 01:44:24.320
No, no, feel he may defy us there.

01:44:25.680 --> 01:44:29.640
And as to laughter, we will not expose ourselves, if you please,

01:44:29.900 --> 01:44:34.400
by attempting to laugh without a subject. Mr. Darcy may hug himself.

01:44:35.760 --> 01:44:41.920
Mr. Darcy is not to be laughed at, cried Elizabeth. That is an uncommon advantage.

01:44:43.080 --> 01:44:49.100
An uncommon I hope it will continue, for it would be a great loss to me to have many such acquaintances.

01:44:49.100 --> 01:44:51.680
I dearly love a laugh.

01:44:53.700 --> 01:45:01.260
Miss Bingley, said he, has given me more credit than can be. The wisest and the best of men—nay,

01:45:01.340 --> 01:45:07.280
the wisest and best of their actions—may be rendered ridiculous by a person whose first object

01:45:07.280 --> 01:45:16.180
in life is a joke. Certainly, replied Elizabeth, there are such people, but I hope I am not one

01:45:16.180 --> 01:45:23.140
of them. I hope I never ridicule what is wise and good. Follies and nonsense, whims and

01:45:23.140 --> 01:45:29.820
inconsistencies, do divert me I own, and I laugh at them whenever I can. But these, I suppose,

01:45:30.040 --> 01:45:36.980
are precisely what you are without. Perhaps that is not possible for anyone. But it has been the

01:45:36.980 --> 01:45:42.040
study of my life to avoid those weaknesses which often expose a strong understanding to ridicule,

01:45:42.840 --> 01:45:50.340
such as vanity and pride. Yes, vanity is a weakness indeed.

01:45:51.280 --> 01:45:58.340
But pride, where there is a real superiority of mind, pride will be always under good regulation.

01:45:59.580 --> 01:46:01.780
Elizabeth turned away to hide a smile.

01:46:03.060 --> 01:46:09.960
Your examination of Mr. Darcy is over, I presume? said Miss Bingley, and pray what is the result.

01:46:09.960 --> 01:46:17.040
I am perfectly convinced by it that Mr. Darcy has no defect. He owns it himself for their disguise.

01:46:18.240 --> 01:46:24.900
No, said Darcy, I have made no such pretension. I have faults enough,

01:46:25.020 --> 01:46:31.980
but they are not, I hope, of understanding. My temper I dare not vouch for. It is,

01:46:32.300 --> 01:46:37.860
I believe, too little yielding—certainly too little for the convenience of the world.

01:46:38.560 --> 01:46:44.940
I cannot forget the follies and vices of others so soon as I ought, nor their offences against

01:46:44.940 --> 01:46:51.460
myself. My feelings are not puffed about with every attempt to move them. My temper would

01:46:51.460 --> 01:46:57.580
perhaps be called resentful. My good opinion once lost is lost forever.

01:46:58.380 --> 01:47:06.860
That is a failing indeed, cried Elizabeth. Implacable resentment is a shade in a character.

01:47:07.390 --> 01:47:15.020
But you have chosen your fault well. I really cannot laugh at it. You are safe from me.

01:47:15.940 --> 01:47:22.360
There is, I believe, in every disposition a tendency to some particular evil, a natural defect

01:47:22.360 --> 01:47:29.500
which not even the best education can overcome. And your defect is to hate everybody?

01:47:32.140 --> 01:47:37.540
And yours, he replied with a smile, is willfully to misunderstand them.

01:47:39.440 --> 01:47:44.200
Do let us have a little music, cried Miss Bingley, tired of a conversation in which she

01:47:44.200 --> 01:47:48.820
had no share. Louisa, you will not mind my waking Mr. Hurst?

01:47:50.360 --> 01:47:54.380
Her sister had not the smallest objection, and the pianoforte was opened.

01:47:55.020 --> 01:48:00.320
And Darcy, after a few moments recollection, was not sorry for it.

01:48:00.880 --> 01:48:05.760
He began to feel the danger of paying Elizabeth too much attention.

01:48:27.780 --> 01:48:28.420
XII.

01:48:29.820 --> 01:48:34.220
In consequence of an agreement between the sisters, Elizabeth wrote the next morning

01:48:34.220 --> 01:49:04.200
to beg that the carriage might be sent for them in the course of the day. But Mrs. Bennet, who had calculated on her daughters remaining at Netherfield till the following Tuesday, which would exactly finish Jane's week, could not bring herself to receive them with pleasure before. Her answer, therefore, was not propitious, at least not to Elizabeth's wishes, for she was impatient to get home. Mrs. Bennet sent them word that they could not possibly have the carriage before Tuesday.

01:49:04.200 --> 01:49:20.220
And in her postscript it was added that if Mr. Bingley and his sister pressed them to stay longer, she could spare them very well. Against staying longer, however, Elizabeth was positively resolved. Nor did she much expect it would be asked.

01:49:20.980 --> 01:49:36.820
And fearful, on the contrary, as being considered as intruding themselves needlessly long, she urged Jane to borrow Mr. Bingley's carriage immediately. And at length it was settled that their original design of leaving Netherfield that morning should be mentioned and their request made.

01:49:37.880 --> 01:49:58.480
The communication excited many professions of concern, and enough was said of wishing them to stay at least till the following day to work on Jane, and till the morrow their going was deferred. Miss Bingley was then sorry that she had proposed the delay, for her jealousy and dislike of one sister much exceeded her affection for the other.

01:49:59.280 --> 01:50:13.580
The master of the house heard with real sorrow that they were to go so soon, and repeatedly tried to persuade Miss Bennet that it would not be safe for her, that she was not enough recovered. But Jane was firm where she felt herself to be right.

01:50:14.300 --> 01:50:28.960
To Mr. Darcy it was welcome intelligence. Elizabeth had been at Netherfield long enough, she attracted him more than he liked, and Miss Bingley was uncivil to her, and more teasing than usual to himself.

01:50:29.680 --> 01:50:39.920
He wisely resolved to be particularly careful that no sign of admiration should now escape him, nothing that could elevate her with the hope of influencing his felicity.

01:50:41.280 --> 01:51:04.920
Sensible that if such an idea had been suggested, his behaviour during the last day must have material weight in confirming or crushing it. Steady to his purpose he scarcely spoke ten words to her through the whole of Saturday, and though they were at one time left by themselves for half an hour, he adhered most conscientiously to his book, and would not even look at her.

01:51:05.660 --> 01:51:12.580
On Sunday, after morning service, the separation, so agreeable to almost all, took place.

01:51:13.480 --> 01:51:32.420
Miss Bingley's civility to Elizabeth increased at last very rapidly, as well as her affection for Jane, and when they parted, after assuring the latter of the pleshate would always give her to see her either at Longbourn or at Netherfield, and embracing her most tenderly, she even shook hands with the former.

01:51:33.440 --> 01:51:36.880
Elizabeth took leave of the whole party in the livelier spirits.

01:51:38.380 --> 01:51:49.340
They were not welcomed home very cordially by their mother. Mrs. Bennet wandered at their coming and thought them very wrong to give so much trouble, and were sure Jane would have caught cold again.

01:51:50.200 --> 01:51:59.940
But their father, though very laconic in his expressions of pleasure, was really glad to see them. He had felt their importance in the family circle.

01:52:00.760 --> 01:52:08.680
The evening conversation, when they were all assembled, had lost much of its animation and almost all its sense by the absence of Jane and Elizabeth.

01:52:09.600 --> 01:52:21.640
They found Mary as usual deep in the study of thorough base and human nature, and had some new extracts to admire and some new observations of threadbare morality to listen to.

01:52:22.580 --> 01:52:30.880
Catherine and Lydia had information for them of a different sort. Much had been done and much had been said in the regiment since the preceding Wednesday.

01:52:31.920 --> 01:52:42.160
Several of the officers had dined lately with their uncle, a private had been flogged, and it had actually been hinted that Colonel Forster was going to be married.

01:52:45.780 --> 01:52:59.060
I hope, my dear, said Mr. Bennet to his wife, as they were at breakfast the next morning, that you have ordered a good dinner today, because I have reason to expect an addition to our family party.

01:53:00.160 --> 01:53:10.540
Who do you mean, my dear? I know of nobody that is coming. I am sure unless Charlotte Lucas should happen to call in, and I hope my dinners are good enough for her.

01:53:10.540 --> 01:53:13.920
I do not believe she often sees such at home.

01:53:15.160 --> 01:53:18.580
The person of whom I speak is a gentleman and a stranger.

01:53:20.180 --> 01:53:22.240
Mrs. Bennet's eyes sparkled.

01:53:23.080 --> 01:53:24.980
A gentleman and a stranger?

01:53:25.660 --> 01:53:27.600
It is Mr. Bingley, I am sure.

01:53:28.600 --> 01:53:31.880
Why, Jane, you never dropped a word of this, you sly thing.

01:53:32.400 --> 01:53:35.500
Well, I am sure I shall be extremely glad to see Mr. Bingley.

01:53:36.120 --> 01:53:44.540
But, good Lord, how unlucky! There is not a bitter fish to be got to-day. Lydia, my love, ring the bell, I must speak to Hill this moment.

01:53:45.880 --> 01:53:53.340
It is not Mr. Bingley, said her husband. It is a person whom I never saw in the whole course of my life.

01:53:54.180 --> 01:54:01.880
This roused a general astonishment, and he had the pleasure of being eagerly questioned by his wife and five daughters at once.

01:54:02.620 --> 01:54:07.520
After amusing himself some time with their curiosity, he thus explained.

01:54:08.740 --> 01:54:17.540
About a month ago I received this letter, and about a fortnight ago I answered it, for I thought it a case of some delicacy and requiring early attention.

01:54:18.620 --> 01:54:25.860
It is from my cousin Mr. Collins, who, when I am dead, may turn you all out of this house as soon as he pleases.

01:54:26.420 --> 01:54:33.760
Oh, my dear, cried his wife, I cannot bear to hear that mentioned. Pray do not talk of that odious man.

01:54:34.780 --> 01:54:40.120
I do think it is the hardest thing in the world that your estate should be entailed away from your own children,

01:54:40.640 --> 01:54:45.960
and I am sure if I had been you I should have tried long ago to do something or other about it.

01:54:47.300 --> 01:54:51.240
Jane and Elizabeth attempted to explain to her the nature of an entail.

01:54:51.240 --> 01:54:58.140
They had often attempted it before, but it was a subject on which Mrs. Bennet was beyond the reach of reason,

01:54:58.880 --> 01:55:08.300
and she continued to rail bitterly against the cruelty of settling an estate away from a family of five daughters in favour of a man whom nobody cared anything about.

01:55:09.500 --> 01:55:17.920
It certainly is a most iniquitous affair, said Mr. Bennet, and nothing can clear Mr. Collins from the guilt of inheriting Longbourn.

01:55:18.740 --> 01:55:24.880
But if you will listen to his letter, you may perhaps be a little softened by his manner of expressing himself.

01:55:26.340 --> 01:55:34.200
No, that I am sure I shall not, and I think it was very impertinent of him to write to you at all, and very hypocritical.

01:55:34.760 --> 01:55:41.280
I hate such false friends. Why could not he keep on quarrelling with you as his father did before him?

01:55:42.240 --> 01:55:47.350
Why, indeed, he does seem to have some filial scruples on that head, as you will hear.

01:55:54.980 --> 01:56:01.420
The disagreement subsisting between yourself and my late honoured father always gave me much uneasiness,

01:56:02.040 --> 01:56:07.280
and since I have had the misfortune to lose him I have frequently wished to heal the breach,

01:56:07.280 --> 01:56:14.580
but for some time I was kept back by my own doubts, fearing lest it might seem disrespectful to his memory,

01:56:15.000 --> 01:56:19.600
for me to be on good terms with any one with whom it had always pleased him to be at variance.

01:56:20.400 --> 01:56:21.320
There, Mrs. Bennet.

01:56:22.360 --> 01:56:25.080
My mind, however, is now made up on the subject.

01:56:25.540 --> 01:56:34.440
For having received ordination at Easter, I have been so fortunate as to be distinguished by the patronage of the right honourable Lady Catherine de Bourgh,

01:56:34.440 --> 01:56:41.420
widow of Sir Louis de Bourgh, whose bounty and beneficence has preferred me to the valuable rectory of this parish,

01:56:42.180 --> 01:56:47.620
where it shall be my earnest endeavour to demean myself with grateful respect towards her ladyship,

01:56:48.120 --> 01:56:53.560
and be ever ready to perform those rites and ceremonies which are instituted by the Church of England.

01:56:54.560 --> 01:57:02.960
As a clergyman, moreover, I feel it my duty to promote and establish the blessing of peace in all families within the reach of my influence,

01:57:03.740 --> 01:57:09.580
and on these grounds I flatter myself that my present overtures of goodwill are highly commendable,

01:57:09.940 --> 01:57:16.720
and that the circumstance of my being next in the entail of long-born estate will be kindly overlooked in your side,

01:57:17.220 --> 01:57:20.160
and not lead you to reject the offered olive branch.

01:57:21.080 --> 01:57:26.580
I cannot be otherwise than concerned at being the means of injuring your amiable daughters,

01:57:26.580 --> 01:57:36.280
and beg leave to apologise for it, as well as to assure you of my readiness to make them every possible amends, but of this hereafter.

01:57:36.980 --> 01:57:47.680
If you should have no objection to receive me into your house, I propose myself the satisfaction of waiting on you and your family Monday, November 18th by four o'clock,

01:57:47.680 --> 01:57:53.520
and shall probably trespass on your hospitality till the Saturday so night following,

01:57:54.240 --> 01:58:01.140
which I can do without any inconvenience, as Lady Catherine is far from objecting to my occasional absence on a Sunday,

01:58:01.860 --> 01:58:05.640
providing that some other clergyman is engaged to do the duty of the day.

01:58:06.760 --> 01:58:14.280
I remain, dear sir, with respectful compliments to your lady and daughters, your well-wisher and friend, William Collins.

01:58:16.000 --> 01:58:22.660
At four o'clock, therefore, we may expect this peacemaking gentleman," said Mr. Bennet as he folded up the letter.

01:58:23.520 --> 01:58:31.300
He seems to be a most conscientious and polite young man, upon my word, and I doubt not will prove a valuable acquaintance,

01:58:31.600 --> 01:58:35.820
especially if Lady Catherine should be so indulgent as to let him come to us again.

01:58:37.080 --> 01:58:45.480
There is some sense in what he says about the girls, however, and if he is disposed to make them any amends, I shall not be the person to discourage him.

01:58:46.120 --> 01:58:54.560
Though it is difficult, said Jane, to guess in what way he can mean to make us the atonement he thinks our due, the wish is certainly to his credit.

01:58:55.980 --> 01:59:00.080
Elizabeth was chiefly struck with his extraordinary deference for Lady Catherine,

01:59:00.800 --> 01:59:05.460
and his kind intention of christening, marrying and burying his parishioners whenever it were required.

01:59:06.740 --> 01:59:11.000
He must be an oddity, I think, said she. I cannot make him out.

01:59:12.080 --> 01:59:14.320
There is something very pompous in his style.

01:59:15.120 --> 01:59:18.920
And what can he mean by apologizing for being next in the entail?

01:59:19.780 --> 01:59:22.240
We cannot suppose he would help it if he could.

01:59:23.260 --> 01:59:25.760
Can he be a sensible man, sir?

01:59:26.520 --> 01:59:31.720
No, my dear, I think not. I have great hopes of finding him quite the reverse.

01:59:33.020 --> 01:59:39.760
There is a mixture of civility and self-importance in his letter which promises well. I am impatient to see him.

01:59:40.900 --> 01:59:46.120
In point of composition, said Mary, his letter does not seem defective.

01:59:46.560 --> 01:59:51.360
The idea of the olive branch, perhaps, is not wholly new, yet I think it is well expressed.

01:59:52.380 --> 01:59:57.680
To Catherine and Lydia, neither the letter nor its writer were in any degree interesting.

01:59:58.640 --> 02:00:02.340
It was next to impossible that their cousin should come in a scarlet coat,

02:00:02.680 --> 02:00:07.780
and it was now some weeks since they had received pleasure from the society of a man in any other colour.

02:00:08.920 --> 02:00:13.440
As for their mother, Mr. Collins' letter had done away with much of her ill-will,

02:00:13.740 --> 02:00:18.700
and she was preparing to see him with a degree of composure which astonished her husband and daughters.

02:00:19.920 --> 02:00:26.280
Mr. Collins was punctual to his time, and was received with great politeness by the whole family.

02:00:27.380 --> 02:00:31.640
Mr. Bennet indeed said little, but the ladies were ready enough to talk,

02:00:32.260 --> 02:00:37.580
and Mr. Collins seemed neither in need of encouragement nor inclined to be silent himself.

02:00:38.820 --> 02:00:42.180
He was a tall, heavy-looking young man of five and twenty.

02:00:42.840 --> 02:00:47.320
His air was grave and stately, and his manners were very formal.

02:00:47.320 --> 02:00:53.640
He had not been seated long before he complimented Mrs. Bennet on having so fine a family of daughters,

02:00:54.380 --> 02:01:00.220
said he had heard much of their beauty, but that in this instance fame had fallen short of the truth,

02:01:00.800 --> 02:01:06.240
and added that he did not doubt her seeing them all in due time well disposed of in marriage.

02:01:07.360 --> 02:01:10.760
This gallantry was not much to the taste of some of his hearers,

02:01:11.300 --> 02:01:15.820
but Mrs. Bennet, who quarrelled with no compliments, answered most readily.

02:01:16.660 --> 02:01:22.120
You are very kind, I'm sure, and I wish with all my heart it may prove so,

02:01:22.420 --> 02:01:26.500
for else they will be destitute enough. Things are settled so oddly.

02:01:27.360 --> 02:01:30.380
You allude, perhaps, to the entail of this estate?

02:01:31.340 --> 02:01:36.080
Ah, sir, I do indeed. It's a grievous affair to my poor girls, you must confess.

02:01:37.000 --> 02:01:42.220
Not that I mean to find fault with you, for such things I know are all chance in this world.

02:01:42.930 --> 02:01:47.400
There is no knowing how estates will go when once they come to be entailed.

02:01:48.260 --> 02:01:52.180
I am very sensible, madam, of the hardship to my fair cousins,

02:01:52.700 --> 02:01:57.760
and could say much on the subject, but that I am cautious of appearing forward and precipitate.

02:01:58.660 --> 02:02:02.520
But I can assure you, the young ladies, that I come prepared to admire them.

02:02:03.140 --> 02:02:07.380
At present I will not say more, but perhaps when we are better acquainted.

02:02:07.380 --> 02:02:12.920
He was interrupted by a summons to dinner, and the girls smiled on each other.

02:02:13.720 --> 02:02:16.820
They were not the only objects of Mr. Collins' admiration.

02:02:17.880 --> 02:02:23.080
The hall, the dining-room, and all its furniture were examined and praised,

02:02:23.700 --> 02:02:27.280
and his commendation of everything would have touched Mrs. Bennet's heart

02:02:27.280 --> 02:02:32.160
but for the mortifying supposition of his viewing it all as his own future property.

02:02:33.320 --> 02:02:36.240
The dinner too in its turn was highly admired,

02:02:36.820 --> 02:02:41.140
and he begged to know to which of his fair cousins the excellency of its cooking was owing.

02:02:42.200 --> 02:02:44.720
But here he was set right by Mrs. Bennet,

02:02:44.980 --> 02:02:49.240
who assured him with some asperity that they were very well able to keep a good cook,

02:02:49.260 --> 02:02:52.200
and that her daughters had nothing to do in the kitchen.

02:02:53.000 --> 02:02:55.860
He begged pardon for having displeased her.

02:02:56.240 --> 02:02:59.420
In a softened tone she declared herself not at all offended,

02:02:59.420 --> 02:03:03.860
but he continued to apologise for about a quarter of an hour.

02:03:31.820 --> 02:03:48.120
During dinner Mr. Bennet scarcely spoke at all, but when the servants were withdrawn, he thought it time to have some conversation with his guest, and therefore started a subject in which he expected him to shine, by observing that he seemed very fortunate in his patroness.

02:03:49.460 --> 02:03:55.320
Lady Catherine de Bourgh's attention to his wishes and consideration for his comfort appeared very remarkable.

02:03:56.000 --> 02:04:17.540
Mr. Bennet could not have chosen better. Mr. Collins was eloquent in her praise. The subject elevated him to more than usual solemnity of manner, and with a most important aspect he protested that he had never in his life witnessed such behavior in a person of rank, such affability and condescension as he had himself experienced from Lady Catherine.

02:04:18.220 --> 02:04:33.160
She had been graciously pleased to approve of both of the discourses which he had already had the honor of preaching before her. She had also asked him twice to dine at Rosings, and had sent for him only the Saturday before to make up her pool of quadrille in the evening.

02:04:34.200 --> 02:04:52.560
Lady Catherine was reckoned proud by many people he knew, but he had never seen anything but affability in her. She had always spoken to him as she would to any other gentleman. She made not the smallest objection to his joining in the society of the neighborhood, nor to his leaving the parish occasionally for a week or two to visit his relations.

02:04:52.560 --> 02:05:10.180
She had even condescended to advise him to marry as soon as he could, provided he chose with discretion, and had once paid him a visit in his humble parsonage, where she had perfectly approved all the alterations he had been making, and had even vouchsafed to suggest some herself, some shelves in the closet upstairs.

02:05:11.680 --> 02:05:22.940
That is all very proper and civil, I am sure," said Mrs. Bennet, and I dare say she is a very agreeable woman. It is a pity that great ladies in general are not more like her. Does she live near you, sir?

02:05:24.260 --> 02:05:30.060
The garden in which stands my humble abode is separated only by a lane from Rosings Park, her ladyship's residence.

02:05:31.540 --> 02:05:34.620
I think you said she was a widow, sir. Has she any family?

02:05:35.820 --> 02:05:40.380
She has only one daughter, the heiress of Rosings, and a very extensive property.

02:05:42.040 --> 02:05:49.220
Ah, said Mrs. Bennet, shaking her head. Then she is better off than many girls. And what sort of young lady is she? Is she handsome?

02:05:50.560 --> 02:06:03.120
She is a most charming young lady indeed. Lady Catherine herself says that, in point of true beauty, Miss de Bourgh is far superior to the handsomest of her sex, because there is that in her features which marks the young lady of distinguished birth.

02:06:03.600 --> 02:06:16.220
She is unfortunately of a sickly constitution which has prevented her from making that progress in many accomplishments which she could not otherwise have failed of, as I am informed by the lady who superintended her education and who still resides with them.

02:06:16.780 --> 02:06:22.660
But she is perfectly amiable and often condescends to drive by my humble abode in her little phaeton and ponies.

02:06:24.000 --> 02:06:27.460
Has she been presented? I do not remember her name among the ladies at court.

02:06:28.740 --> 02:06:37.760
Her indifferent state of health unhappily prevents her being in town, and by that means, as I told Lady Catherine one day, has deprived the British court of its brightest ornaments.

02:06:38.460 --> 02:06:46.800
Her ladyship seemed pleased with the idea, and you may imagine that I am happy on every occasion to offer those little delicate compliments which are always acceptable to ladies.

02:06:46.800 --> 02:06:58.080
I have more than once observed to Lady Catherine that her charming daughter seemed born to be a duchess, and that the most elevated rank, instead of giving her consequence, would be adorned by her.

02:06:58.580 --> 02:07:05.540
These are the kind of little things which please her ladyship, and it is a sort of attention which I conceive myself peculiarly bound to pay.

02:07:06.960 --> 02:07:13.040
You judge very properly, said Mr. Bennet, and it is happy for you that you possess the talent of flattering with delicacy.

02:07:13.700 --> 02:07:18.820
May I ask whether these pleasing attentions proceed from the impulse of the moment, or are the result of previous study?

02:07:20.440 --> 02:07:32.680
They arrive chiefly from what is passing at the time, and though I sometimes amuse myself with suggesting and arranging such little elegant compliments as may be adapted to ordinary occasions, I always wish to give them as unstudied an air as possible.

02:07:34.120 --> 02:07:51.780
Mr. Bennet's expectations were fully answered. His cousin was as absurd as he had hoped, and he listened to him with the keenest enjoyment, maintaining at the same time the most resolute composure of countenance, and, except in an occasional glance at Elizabeth, requiring no partner in his pleasure.

02:07:52.940 --> 02:08:03.760
By tea time, however, the dose had been enough, and Mr. Bennet was glad to take his guest into the drawing room again, and, when tea was over, glad to invite him to read aloud to the ladies.

02:08:04.920 --> 02:08:16.680
Mr. Collins readily assented, and a book was produced, but, on beholding it, for everything announced it to be from a circulating library, he started back, and begging pardon, protested that he never read novels.

02:08:17.720 --> 02:08:25.780
Giddy stared at him, and Lydia exclaimed. Other books were produced, and after some deliberation he chose Fordyce's sermons.

02:08:27.300 --> 02:08:35.500
Lydia gaped as he opened the volume, and before he had, with very monotonous solemnity, read three pages, she had interrupted him with,

02:08:35.500 --> 02:08:49.180
Do you know, Mama, that my Uncle Phillips talks of turning away Richard, and if he does, Colonel Forster will hire him. My aunt told me so herself on Saturday. I shall walk to Maryton tomorrow to hear more about it, and to ask when Mr. Denny comes back from town.

02:08:51.300 --> 02:08:59.020
Lydia was bid by her two eldest sisters to hold her tongue, but Mr. Collins, much offended, laid aside his book, and said,

02:08:59.720 --> 02:09:14.100
I have often observed how little young ladies are interested by the books of a serious stamp, though written solely for their benefit. It amazes me, I confess, for certainly there can be nothing so advantageous to them as instruction, but I will no longer importune my young cousin.

02:09:15.440 --> 02:09:26.320
Then, turning to Mr. Bennet, he offered himself as his antagonist at Backgammon. Mr. Bennet accepted the challenge, observing that he acted very wisely in leaving the girls to their own trifling amusements.

02:09:27.640 --> 02:09:34.620
Mrs. Bennet and her daughters apologized most civilly for Lydia's interruption, and promised that it should not occur again if he would resume his book.

02:09:34.620 --> 02:09:46.620
But Mr. Collins, after assuring them that he bore his young cousin no ill will, and should never resent her behavior as any affront, seated himself at another table with Mr. Bennet and prepared for Backgammon.

02:09:51.760 --> 02:10:04.260
Mr. Collins was not a sensible man, and the deficiency of nature had been but little assisted by education or society, the greatest part of his life having been spent under the guidance of an illiterate and miserly father.

02:10:04.800 --> 02:10:11.850
And though he belonged to one of the universities, he had merely kept the necessary terms, without forming at it any useful acquaintance.

02:10:13.010 --> 02:10:28.250
The subjection in which his father had brought him up had given him originally great humility of manner, but it was now a good deal counteracted by the self-conceit of a weak head, living in retirement, and the consequential feelings of early and unexpected prosperity.

02:10:29.050 --> 02:10:53.210
A fortunate chance had recommended him to Lady Catherine de Bourgh when the living of Hunsford was vacant, and the respect which he felt for her high rank, and his veneration for her as his patroness, mingling with a very good opinion of himself, of his authority as a clergyman, and his right as a rector, made him altogether a mixture of pride and obsequiousness, self-importance, and humility.

02:10:54.530 --> 02:11:09.950
Having now a good house and a very sufficient income, he intended to marry, and in seeking a reconciliation with the long-born family he had a wife in view, as he meant to choose one of the daughters, if he found them as handsome and amiable as they were represented by common report.

02:11:10.890 --> 02:11:23.690
This was his plan of amends, of atonement for inheriting their father's estate, and he thought it an excellent one, full of eligibility and suitableness, and excessively generous and disinterested on his own part.

02:11:25.530 --> 02:11:37.690
His plan did not vary on seeing them. Miss Bennet's lovely face confirmed his views, and established all his strictest notions of what was due to seniority, and for the first evening she was his settled choice.

02:11:38.470 --> 02:12:01.530
The next morning, however, made an alteration, for in a quarter of an hour's tete-a-tete with Mrs. Bennet before breakfast, a conversation beginning with his parsonage house, and leading naturally to the avowal of his hopes that a mistress might be found for it at long-born, produced from her, amid very complacent smiles and general encouragement, a caution against the very Jane he had fixed on.

02:12:02.470 --> 02:12:18.770
As to her younger daughters, she could not take it upon her to say, she could not positively answer, but she did not know of any prepossession. Her eldest daughter, she must just mention, she felt it incumbent on her to hint, was likely to be very soon engaged.

02:12:20.810 --> 02:12:33.730
Mr. Collins had only to change from Jane to Elizabeth, and it was soon done, done while Mrs. Bennet was stirring the fire. Elizabeth, equally next to Jane in birth and beauty, succeeded her, of course.

02:12:35.230 --> 02:12:44.810
Mrs. Bennet treasured up the hint, and trusted that she might soon have two daughters married, and the man whom she could not bear to speak of the day before was now high in her good graces.

02:12:46.670 --> 02:12:59.670
Lydia's intention of walking to Maryton was not forgotten. Every sister except Mary agreed to go with her, and Mr. Collins was to attend them at the request of Mr. Bennet, who was most anxious to get rid of him and have his library to himself.

02:13:00.410 --> 02:13:13.910
For thither Mr. Collins had followed him after breakfast, and there he would continue, nominally engaged with one of the largest folios in the collection, but really talking to Mr. Bennet, with little cessation of his house and garden at Huntsford.

02:13:15.070 --> 02:13:29.510
Such doings discomposed Mr. Bennet exceedingly. In his library he had been always sure of leisure and tranquility, and though prepared, as he told Elizabeth, to meet with folly and conceit in every other room of the house, he was used to be free from them there.

02:13:30.310 --> 02:13:42.630
His civility therefore was most prompt in inviting Mr. Collins to join his daughters in their walk, and Mr. Collins, being in fact much better fitted for a walker than a reader, was extremely pleased to close his large book and go.

02:13:44.450 --> 02:13:55.350
In pompous nothings on his side, and civil assents on that of his cousins, their time passed till they entered Maryton. The attention of the younger ones was then no longer to be gained by him.

02:13:56.070 --> 02:14:06.030
Their eyes were immediately wandering up in the street in quest of the officers, and nothing less than a very smart bonnet indeed, or a really new muslin in a shop window could recall them.

02:14:07.150 --> 02:14:17.330
But the attention of every lady was soon caught by a young man, whom they had never seen before, of most gentleman-like appearance, walking with another officer on the other side of the way.

02:14:18.410 --> 02:14:25.310
The officer was the very Mr. Denny concerning whose return from London Lydia came to inquire, and he bowed as they passed.

02:14:26.150 --> 02:14:44.770
All were struck with the stranger's air, all wondered who he could be, and Kitty and Lydia, determined if possible to find out, led the way across the street, under pretense of wanting something in an opposite shop, and fortunately had just gained the pavement when the two gentlemen, turning back, had reached the same spot.

02:14:45.850 --> 02:14:57.670
Mr. Denny addressed them directly, and entreated permission to introduce his friend, Mr. Wickham, who had returned with him the day before from town, and, he was happy to say, had accepted a commission in their corps.

02:14:58.530 --> 02:15:03.950
This was exactly as it should be, for the young man wanted only regimentals to make him completely charming.

02:15:04.930 --> 02:15:12.410
His appearance was greatly in his favor. He had all the best part of beauty, a fine countenance, a good figure, and very pleasing address.

02:15:12.410 --> 02:15:31.910
The introduction was followed up on his side by a happy readiness of conversation, a readiness at the same time, perfectly correct and unassuming, and the whole party was still standing and talking together very agreeably when the sound of horses drew their notice, and Darcy and Bingley were seen riding down the street.

02:15:33.210 --> 02:15:38.660
On distinguishing the ladies of the group, the two gentlemen came directly towards them and began the usual civilities.

02:15:40.000 --> 02:15:43.800
Bingley was the principal spokesman, and Miss Bennet the principal object.

02:15:44.940 --> 02:15:49.400
He was then, he said, on his way to Longbourn on purpose to inquire after her.

02:15:50.020 --> 02:16:05.700
Mr. Darcy corroborated it with a bow, and was beginning to determine not to fix his eyes on Elizabeth when they were suddenly arrested by the sight of the stranger, and Elizabeth, happening to see the countenance of both as they looked at each other, was all astonishment at the effect of the meeting.

02:16:06.580 --> 02:16:10.440
Both changed colour. One looked white, the other red.

02:16:11.860 --> 02:16:18.180
Mr. Wickham, after a few moments, touched his hat, a salutation which Mr. Darcy just deigned to return.

02:16:19.200 --> 02:16:25.680
What could be the meaning of it? It was impossible to imagine. It was impossible not to long to know.

02:16:27.440 --> 02:16:34.120
In another minute Mr. Bingley, but without seeming to have noticed what passed, took leave and rode on with his friend.

02:16:35.520 --> 02:16:50.440
Mr. Denny and Mr. Wickham walked with the young ladies to the door of Mr. Phillips' house, and then made their bows, in spite of Miss Lydia's pressing entreaties that they should come in, and even in spite of Mrs. Phillips' throwing up the parlour window and loudly seconding the invitation.

02:16:52.900 --> 02:17:19.140
Mrs. Phillips was always glad to see her nieces, and the two eldest, from their recent absence, were particularly welcome, and she was eagerly expressing her surprise at their sudden return home, which, as their own carriage had not fetched them, she should have known nothing about if she had not happened to see Mr. Jones' shop boy in the street, who had told her that they were not to send any more drafts to Netherland because the Miss Bennets were come away, when her civility was claimed towards Mr. Collins by Jane's introduction of him.

02:17:20.520 --> 02:17:36.040
She received him with her very best politeness, which he returned with as much more, apologizing for his intrusion, without any previous acquaintance with her, which he could not help flattering himself, however, might be justified by his relationship to the young ladies who introduced him to her notice.

02:17:37.200 --> 02:17:55.760
Mrs. Phillips was quite awed by such an excess of good reading, but her contemplation of one stranger was soon put to an end by exclamations and inquiries about the other, of whom, however, she could only tell her nieces what they already knew, that Mr. Denny had brought him from London, and that he was to have a lieutenant's commission in the Blankshire.

02:17:56.420 --> 02:18:14.480
She had been watching him the last hour, she said, as he walked up and down the street, and had Mr. Wickham appeared, Kitty and Lydia would certainly have continued the occupation, but, unluckily, no one passed windows now except a few of the officers, who, in comparison with the stranger, were become stupid disagreeable fellows.

02:18:15.580 --> 02:18:25.640
Some of them were to dine with the Phillipses the next day, and their aunt promised to make her husband call on Mr. Wickham and give him an invitation also, if the family from Longbourn would come in the evening.

02:18:26.580 --> 02:18:33.420
This was agreed to, and Mrs. Phillips protested that they would have a nice, comfortable, noisy game of lottery tickets, and a little bit of hot supper afterwards.

02:18:34.580 --> 02:18:39.060
The prospect of such delights was very cheering, and they parted in mutual good spirits.

02:18:39.880 --> 02:18:47.080
Mr. Collins repeated his apologies in quitting the room, and was assured with unwearying civility that they were perfectly needless.

02:18:48.740 --> 02:19:01.780
As they walked home, Elizabeth redolated to Jane what she had seen pass between the two gentlemen, but though Jane would have defended either or both, had they appeared to be in the wrong, she could no more explain such behavior than her sister.

02:19:03.000 --> 02:19:08.920
Mr. Collins, on his return, highly gratified Mrs. Bennet by admiring Mrs. Phillips's manners and politeness.

02:19:10.000 --> 02:19:23.680
He protested that, except Lady Catherine and her daughter, he had never seen a more elegant woman, for she had not only received him with the utmost civility, but even pointedly included him in her invitation for the next evening, although utterly unknown to her before.

02:19:24.500 --> 02:19:32.680
Something, he supposed, might be attributed to his connection with them, but yet he had never met with so much attention in the whole course of his life.

02:20:01.380 --> 02:20:04.320
PRIDE AND PREJUDICE by Jane Austen

02:20:04.320 --> 02:20:10.080
As no objection was made to the young people's

02:20:10.080 --> 02:20:15.620
engagement with their aunt, and all Mr. Collins' scruples of leaving Mr. and Mrs. Bennet for

02:20:15.620 --> 02:20:21.280
a single evening during his visit were most steadily resisted, the coach conveyed him

02:20:21.280 --> 02:20:26.440
and his five cousins at a suitable hour to Maryton, and the girls had the pleasure of

02:20:26.440 --> 02:20:31.900
hearing as they entered the drawing-room that Mr. Wickham had accepted their uncle's invitation

02:20:31.900 --> 02:20:38.540
and was then in the house. When this information was given, and they had all taken their seats,

02:20:39.260 --> 02:20:44.220
Mr. Collins was at leisure to look around him and admire, and he was so much struck

02:20:44.220 --> 02:20:49.740
with the size and furniture of the apartment that he declared he might almost have supposed

02:20:49.740 --> 02:20:56.360
himself in the small summer breakfast parlor at Rosings, a comparison that did not at first

02:20:56.640 --> 02:21:02.820
much gratification, but when Mrs. Phillips understood from him what Rosings was, and

02:21:02.820 --> 02:21:07.980
who was its proprietor, when she had listened to the description of only one of Lady Catherine's

02:21:07.980 --> 02:21:14.120
drawing-rooms, and found that the chimney-piece alone had cost eight hundred pounds, she felt

02:21:14.120 --> 02:21:18.580
all the force of the compliment, and would hardly have resented a comparison with the

02:21:18.580 --> 02:21:25.240
housekeeper's room. In describing to her all the grandeur of Lady Catherine and her mansion,

02:21:25.240 --> 02:21:30.740
with occasional digressions in praise of his own humble abode and the improvements it was

02:21:30.740 --> 02:21:36.980
receiving, he was happily employed until the gentleman joined them, and he found in Mrs.

02:21:37.180 --> 02:21:42.240
Phillips a very attentive listener, whose opinion of his consequence increased with

02:21:42.240 --> 02:21:47.420
what she heard, and who was resolving to retail it all among her neighbours as soon as she

02:21:47.420 --> 02:21:53.300
could. To the girls, who could not listen to their cousin, and who had nothing to do

02:21:53.300 --> 02:21:58.240
but wish for an instrument, and examined their own indifferent imitations of China

02:21:58.240 --> 02:22:05.300
on the mantelpiece, the interval of waiting appeared very long. It was over at last, however.

02:22:05.880 --> 02:22:11.880
The gentleman did approach, and when Mr. Wickham walked into the room, Elizabeth felt that

02:22:11.880 --> 02:22:16.760
she had neither been seeing him before, nor thinking of him since, with the smallest degree

02:22:16.760 --> 02:22:23.160
of unreasonable admiration. The officers of the shire were in general a very creditable

02:22:23.160 --> 02:22:29.600
gentleman-like set, and the best of them were of the present party, but Mr. Wickham was

02:22:29.600 --> 02:22:36.160
as far beyond them all in person, countenance, air, and walk, as they were superior to the

02:22:36.160 --> 02:22:42.060
broad-faced, stuffy Uncle Phillips, breathing port wine, who followed them into the room.

02:22:43.320 --> 02:22:49.400
Mr. Wickham was the happy man towards whom almost every female eye was turned, and Elizabeth

02:22:49.400 --> 02:22:55.740
was the happy woman by whom he finally seated himself, and the agreeable manner in which

02:22:55.740 --> 02:23:01.480
she immediately fell into conversation, though it was only on its being a wet night, made

02:23:01.480 --> 02:23:07.560
her feel that the commonest, dullest, most threadbare topic might be rendered interesting

02:23:07.560 --> 02:23:14.800
by the skill of the speaker. With such rivals for the notice of the fair as Mr. Wickham

02:23:14.800 --> 02:23:21.300
and the officers, Mr. Collins seemed to sink into insignificance. To the young ladies he

02:23:21.300 --> 02:23:26.960
certainly was nothing, but he had still at intervals a kind listener in Mrs. Phillips,

02:23:27.040 --> 02:23:33.260
and was by her watchfulness most abundantly supplied with coffee and muffin. When the

02:23:33.260 --> 02:23:38.440
card tables were placed he had the opportunity of obliging her in turn by sitting down to

02:23:38.440 --> 02:23:38.640
rest.

02:23:39.540 --> 02:23:45.100
"'I know little of the game at present,' said he, "'but I shall be glad to improve myself,

02:23:45.360 --> 02:23:51.020
for in my situation in life...' Mrs. Phillips was very glad for his compliance, but could

02:23:51.020 --> 02:23:57.740
not wait for his reason. Mr. Wickham did not play at wist, and with ready delight was he

02:23:57.740 --> 02:24:03.920
received at the other table between Elizabeth and Lydia. At first there seemed danger of

02:24:03.920 --> 02:24:11.040
engrossing him entirely, for she was a most determined talker. But being likewise extremely

02:24:11.040 --> 02:24:16.800
fond of lottery tickets, she soon grew too much interested in the game, too eager in

02:24:16.800 --> 02:24:23.620
making bets and exclaiming after prizes to have attention for anyone in particular. Allowing

02:24:23.620 --> 02:24:29.120
for the common demands of the game, Mr. Wickham was therefore at leisure to talk to Elizabeth,

02:24:29.120 --> 02:24:34.480
and she was very willing to hear him, though what she chiefly wished to hear she could

02:24:34.480 --> 02:24:41.680
not hope to be told, the history of his acquaintance with Mr. Darcy. She dared not even mention

02:24:41.680 --> 02:24:48.720
that gentleman. Her curiosity, however, was unexpectedly relieved. Mr. Wickham began the

02:24:48.720 --> 02:24:55.640
subject himself. He inquired how far Netherfield was from Maryton, and, after receiving her

02:24:55.640 --> 02:25:01.120
answer, asked in a hesitating manner how long Mr. Darcy had been staying there.

02:25:02.220 --> 02:25:08.220
About a month, said Elizabeth, and then, unwilling to let the subject drop, added,

02:25:08.820 --> 02:25:12.620
he is a man of very large property in Darbyshire, I understand.

02:25:13.640 --> 02:25:20.500
Yes, replied Mr. Wickham, his estate there is a noble one, a clear ten thousand per annum.

02:25:20.640 --> 02:25:24.980
You could not have met with a person more capable of giving you certain information

02:25:24.980 --> 02:25:30.420
on that head than myself, for I have been connected with his family in a particular

02:25:30.420 --> 02:25:37.860
manner from my infancy. Elizabeth could not but look surprised. You may well be surprised,

02:25:37.900 --> 02:25:43.740
Miss Bennet, at such an assertion, after seeing, as you probably might, the very cold manner

02:25:43.740 --> 02:25:47.720
of our meeting yesterday. Are you much acquainted with Mr. Darcy?

02:25:48.440 --> 02:25:53.840
As much as I ever wished to be, cried Elizabeth very warmly, I have spent four days in the

02:25:53.840 --> 02:25:57.120
same house with him, and I think him very disagreeable.

02:25:58.180 --> 02:26:04.880
I have no right to give my opinion, said Wickham, as to his being agreeable or otherwise. I

02:26:04.880 --> 02:26:11.540
am not qualified to form one. I have known him too long and too well to be a fair judge.

02:26:12.140 --> 02:26:18.080
It is impossible for me to be impartial. But I believe your opinion of him would in general

02:26:18.080 --> 02:26:24.000
astonish, and perhaps you would not express it quite so strongly anywhere else. Here you

02:26:24.000 --> 02:26:29.980
are in your own family. Upon my word, I say no more here than I might say in any house

02:26:29.980 --> 02:26:35.640
in the neighborhood, except Netherfield. He is not at all liked in Hertfordshire. Everybody

02:26:35.640 --> 02:26:41.020
is disgusted with his pride. You will not find him more favorably spoken of by anyone.

02:26:42.080 --> 02:26:47.840
I cannot pretend to be sorry, said Wickham, after short interruption, that he, or that

02:26:47.840 --> 02:26:53.460
any man, should not be estimated beyond their deserts. But with him, I believe it does not

02:26:53.460 --> 02:26:59.600
often happen. The world is blinded by his fortune and consequence, or frightened by

02:26:59.600 --> 02:27:06.400
his high and imposing manners, and sees him only as he chooses to be seen. I should take

02:27:06.400 --> 02:27:12.400
him even on my slight acquaintance to be an ill-tempered man. Wickham only shook his head.

02:27:13.380 --> 02:27:18.760
I wonder, said he at the next opportunity of speaking, whether he is likely to be in

02:27:18.760 --> 02:27:24.500
this country much longer. I do not at all know, but I heard nothing of his going away

02:27:24.500 --> 02:27:29.980
when I was at Netherfield. I hope your plans in favor of the Shire will not be affected

02:27:29.980 --> 02:27:36.140
by his being in the neighborhood. Oh, no, it is not for me to be driven away by Mr.

02:27:36.360 --> 02:27:42.900
Darcy. If he wishes to avoid seeing me, he must go. We are not on friendly terms, and

02:27:42.900 --> 02:27:48.000
it always gives me pain to meet him. But I have no reason for avoiding him, but what

02:27:48.000 --> 02:27:53.800
I might proclaim before all the world, a sense of very great ill-usage, and most painful

02:27:54.140 --> 02:28:01.160
at his being what he is. His father, Miss Bennet, the late Mr. Darcy, was one of the

02:28:01.160 --> 02:28:07.400
best men that ever breathed, and the truest friend I ever had, and I can never be in company

02:28:07.400 --> 02:28:13.560
with this Mr. Darcy without being grieved to the soul by a thousand tender recollections.

02:28:14.280 --> 02:28:20.020
His behavior to myself has been scandalous, but I verily believe I could forgive him anything

02:28:20.020 --> 02:28:25.740
and everything rather than his disappointing the hopes and disgracing the memory of his

02:28:25.740 --> 02:28:32.060
father. Elizabeth found the interest of the subject increase and listened with all her

02:28:32.060 --> 02:28:38.920
heart, but the delicacy of it prevented further inquiry. Mr. Wickham began to speak on more

02:28:38.920 --> 02:28:44.740
general topics, maryton, the neighborhood, the society, appearing highly pleased with

02:28:44.740 --> 02:28:49.920
all that he had yet seen, and speaking of the latter with gentle but very intelligible

02:28:49.920 --> 02:28:57.040
gallantry. It was the prospect of constant society and good society, he added, which

02:28:57.040 --> 02:29:02.600
was my chief inducement to enter the Shire. I knew it to be a most respectable, agreeable

02:29:02.600 --> 02:29:07.700
corps, and my friend Denny tempted me further by his account of their present quarters,

02:29:08.000 --> 02:29:14.200
and the very great attentions and excellent acquaintances maryton had procured them. Society,

02:29:14.200 --> 02:29:22.220
I own, is necessary to me. I have been a disappointed man, and my spirits will not bear solitude.

02:29:22.800 --> 02:29:30.280
I must have employment and society. A military life is not what I was intended for, but circumstances

02:29:30.280 --> 02:29:35.660
have now made it eligible. The church ought to have been my profession. I was brought

02:29:35.660 --> 02:29:40.700
up for the church, and I should at this time have been in possession of a most valuable

02:29:40.700 --> 02:29:48.360
living, had it pleased the gentleman we were speaking of just now. Indeed! Yes, the late

02:29:48.360 --> 02:29:55.040
Mr. Darcy bequeathed me the next presentation of the best living in his gift. He was my

02:29:55.040 --> 02:30:01.560
godfather, and excessively attached to me. I cannot do justice to his kindness. He meant

02:30:01.560 --> 02:30:07.040
to provide for me amply, and thought he had done it, but when the living fell, it was

02:30:07.040 --> 02:30:13.340
given elsewhere. Good heavens! cried Elizabeth, but how could that be? How could his will

02:30:13.340 --> 02:30:20.340
be disregarded? Why did you not seek legal redress? There was just such an informality

02:30:20.340 --> 02:30:26.200
in the terms of the bequest as to give me no hope from law. A man of honor could not

02:30:26.200 --> 02:30:32.020
have doubted the intention, but Mr. Darcy chose to doubt it, or to treat it as a merely

02:30:32.020 --> 02:30:38.900
unconditional recommendation, and to assert that I had forfeited all claim to it by extravagance,

02:30:39.400 --> 02:30:46.080
imprudence, in short, anything or nothing. Certain it is that the living became vacant

02:30:46.080 --> 02:30:51.540
two years ago, exactly as I was of an age to hold it, and that it was given to another

02:30:51.540 --> 02:30:57.200
man, and no less certain is it that I cannot accuse myself of having really done anything

02:30:57.200 --> 02:31:03.720
to deserve to lose it. I have a warm, unguarded temper, and I may have spoken my opinion of

02:31:03.720 --> 02:31:10.780
him and to him too freely. I can recall nothing worse, but the fact is that we are very different

02:31:10.780 --> 02:31:17.460
sort of men, and that he hates me. This is quite shocking. He deserves to be publicly

02:31:17.460 --> 02:31:24.900
disgraced. Some time or other he will be, but it shall not be by me. Till I can forget his

02:31:24.900 --> 02:31:31.640
father, I can never defy or expose him. Elizabeth honored him for such feelings, and thought

02:31:31.640 --> 02:31:34.140
him handsomer than ever as he expressed them.

02:31:35.080 --> 02:31:40.600
But what, she said after a pause, could have been his motive? What could have induced him

02:31:40.600 --> 02:31:48.060
to behave so cruelly? A thorough, determined dislike of me, a dislike which I cannot put

02:31:48.060 --> 02:31:54.380
a tribute in some measure to jealousy. Had the late Mr. Darcy liked me less, his son

02:31:54.380 --> 02:31:59.600
might have borne with me better. But his father's uncommon attachment to me irritated

02:31:59.600 --> 02:32:05.260
him, I believe, very early in life. He had not a temper to bear the sort of competition

02:32:05.260 --> 02:32:11.720
in which we stood, the sort of preference which was often given me. I had not thought

02:32:11.720 --> 02:32:17.780
Mr. Darcy so bad as this, though I have never liked him. I had not thought so very ill of

02:32:17.780 --> 02:32:23.580
him. I had supposed him to be despising his fellow creatures in general, but did not suspect

02:32:23.580 --> 02:32:30.420
him of descending to such malicious revenge, such injustice, such inhumanity as this.

02:32:31.880 --> 02:32:37.340
After a few minutes' reflection, however, she continued, I do remember his boasting

02:32:37.340 --> 02:32:43.140
one day at Netherfield of the implacability of his resentments, of his having an unforgiving

02:32:43.140 --> 02:32:53.560
temper. His disposition must be dreadful. I will not trust myself on this subject, replied

02:32:53.560 --> 02:32:59.540
Elizabeth was again deep in thought, and after a time exclaimed, to treat in such a manner

02:32:59.540 --> 02:33:06.020
the God-son, the friend, the favorite of his father. She could have added, a young man

02:33:06.020 --> 02:33:11.580
too like you whose very countenance may vouch for your being amiable. But she contented

02:33:11.580 --> 02:33:17.380
herself with, and one too who had probably been his companion from childhood, connected

02:33:17.380 --> 02:33:25.220
together, as I think you said, in the closest manner. We were born in the same parish, within

02:33:25.220 --> 02:33:30.820
the same park, the greatest part of our youth was passed together, inmates of the same house,

02:33:31.200 --> 02:33:36.960
sharing the same amusements, objects of the same parental care. My father began life in

02:33:36.960 --> 02:33:42.960
the profession which your uncle, Mr. Phillips, appears to do so much credit to, but he gave

02:33:42.960 --> 02:33:48.440
up everything to be of use to the late Mr. Darcy, and devoted all his time to the care

02:33:48.440 --> 02:33:55.580
of the Pemberley property. He was most highly esteemed by Mr. Darcy, a most intimate confidential

02:33:55.580 --> 02:34:01.180
friend. Mr. Darcy often acknowledged himself to be under the greatest obligations to my

02:34:01.180 --> 02:34:07.120
father's active superintendence, and when, immediately before my father's death, Mr.

02:34:07.120 --> 02:34:13.080
Darcy gave him a voluntary promise of providing for me, I am convinced that he felt it to

02:34:13.080 --> 02:34:17.560
be as much a debt of gratitude to him as of his affection to myself.

02:34:18.520 --> 02:34:25.440
"'How strange!' cried Elizabeth, "'how abominable! I wonder that the very pride of this Mr. Darcy

02:34:25.440 --> 02:34:31.480
has not made him just to you, if from no better motive that he should not have been too proud

02:34:31.480 --> 02:34:35.560
to be dishonest, for dishonesty I must call it.'

02:34:35.560 --> 02:34:41.260
"'It is wonderful,' replied Wickham, "'for almost all his actions may be traced to pride,

02:34:41.640 --> 02:34:47.720
and pride had often been his best friend. It has connected him nearer with virtue than

02:34:47.720 --> 02:34:53.720
with any other feeling, but we are none of us consistent, and in his behavior, to me,

02:34:53.960 --> 02:34:58.060
there were stronger impulses even than pride.'"

02:34:58.060 --> 02:35:05.700
Can such abominable pride as his have ever done him good? Yes, it has often led him to

02:35:05.700 --> 02:35:11.480
be liberal and generous, to give his money freely, to display hospitality, to assist

02:35:11.480 --> 02:35:18.660
his tenants, and to relieve the poor. Family pride and filial pride, for he is very proud

02:35:18.660 --> 02:35:25.120
of what his father was, have done this, not to appear to disgrace the family, to degenerate

02:35:25.120 --> 02:35:30.620
from the popular qualities, or lose the influence of the Pemberley House, is a powerful motive.

02:35:31.060 --> 02:35:37.940
He has also brotherly pride, which, with some brotherly affection, makes him a very kind

02:35:37.940 --> 02:35:43.540
and careful guardian of his sister, and you will hear him generally cried up as the most

02:35:43.540 --> 02:35:45.200
attentive and best of brothers.

02:35:46.080 --> 02:35:52.680
"'What sort of girl is Miss Darcy?' he shook his head. I wish I could call her amiable.

02:35:53.260 --> 02:35:59.180
It gives me pain to speak ill of a Darcy, but she is too much like her brother, very,

02:35:59.240 --> 02:36:06.060
very proud. As a child she was affectionate and pleasing, and extremely fond of me, and

02:36:06.060 --> 02:36:12.320
I have devoted hours and hours to her amusement, but she is nothing to me now. She was a handsome

02:36:12.320 --> 02:36:18.700
girl, about fifteen or sixteen, and, I understand, highly accomplished. Since her father's death

02:36:18.700 --> 02:36:25.840
her home has been London, where a lady lives with her, and superintends her education.'

02:36:25.840 --> 02:36:31.500
After many pauses and many trials of other subjects, Elizabeth could not help reverting

02:36:31.500 --> 02:36:37.300
once more to the first, and saying, "'I am astonished at his intimacy with Mr. Bingley.

02:36:37.820 --> 02:36:44.340
How can Mr. Bingley, who seems good humor itself, and is, I really believe, truly amiable,

02:36:44.340 --> 02:36:50.620
be in friendship with such a man? How can they suit each other? Do you know Mr. Bingley?'

02:36:50.620 --> 02:36:57.680
"'Not at all. He is a sweet-tempered, amiable, charming man. He cannot know what Mr. Darcy

02:36:57.680 --> 02:36:58.840
is.'

02:36:58.840 --> 02:37:05.720
"'Probably not, but Mr. Darcy can please where he chooses. He does not want abilities. He

02:37:05.720 --> 02:37:14.320
can be a conversable companion, if he thinks it worth his while. Among those who are at

02:37:14.320 --> 02:37:19.760
hand, he is a different man from what he is to the less prosperous. His pride never deserts

02:37:19.760 --> 02:37:27.960
him, but with the rich he is liberal-minded, just, sincere, rational, honorable, and perhaps

02:37:27.960 --> 02:37:32.460
agreeable, allowing something for fortune and figure.'

02:37:32.460 --> 02:37:37.460
The Whist party soon afterwards breaking up, the players gathered round the other table,

02:37:37.860 --> 02:37:44.000
and Mr. Collins took his station between his cousin Elizabeth and Mrs. Phillips. The usual

02:37:44.000 --> 02:37:49.700
inquiries as to his success was made by the latter. It had not been very great. He had

02:37:49.700 --> 02:37:55.540
lost every point, but when Mrs. Phillips began to express her concern thereupon, he assured

02:37:55.540 --> 02:38:00.740
her with much earnest gravity that it was not of the least importance that he considered

02:38:00.740 --> 02:38:05.400
the money as a mere trifle, and begged that she would not make herself uneasy.

02:38:06.780 --> 02:38:12.320
"'I know very well, madam,' said he, that when persons sit down to a card table, they

02:38:12.320 --> 02:38:17.800
must take their chances of these things, and happily I am not in such circumstances as

02:38:17.800 --> 02:38:23.200
to make five shillings any object. There are undoubtedly many who could not say the same,

02:38:23.680 --> 02:38:29.060
but thanks to Lady Catherine de Borg, I am removed far beyond the necessity of regarding

02:38:29.060 --> 02:38:32.980
little matters.' Mr. Wickham's attention was caught, and after

02:38:32.980 --> 02:38:38.700
observing Mr. Collins for a few moments, he asked Elizabeth in a low voice whether her

02:38:38.700 --> 02:38:42.420
relation was very intimately acquainted with the family of de Borg.

02:38:43.840 --> 02:38:49.160
"'Lady Catherine de Borg,' she replied, has very lately given him a living. I hardly know

02:38:49.160 --> 02:38:53.740
how Mr. Collins was first introduced to her notice, but he certainly has not known her

02:38:53.740 --> 02:39:00.140
long. You know, of course, that Lady Catherine de Borg and Lady Anne Darcy were sisters,

02:39:00.580 --> 02:39:04.980
consequently, that she is aunt to the present Mr. Darcy.'

02:39:05.460 --> 02:39:10.640
"'No, indeed, I did not. I knew nothing at all of Lady Catherine's connections. I never

02:39:10.640 --> 02:39:16.420
heard of her existence till the day before yesterday. Her daughter, Miss de Borg, will

02:39:16.420 --> 02:39:21.940
have a very large fortune, and it is believed that she and her cousin will unite the two

02:39:22.740 --> 02:39:28.140
estates.' This information made Elizabeth smile, as she thought of poor Miss Bingley.

02:39:28.740 --> 02:39:34.360
"'Vain indeed must be all her attentions, vain and useless her affection for his sister,

02:39:34.740 --> 02:39:38.900
and her praise of himself, if you were already self-destined for another.'

02:39:40.720 --> 02:39:46.520
"'Mr. Collins,' said she, speaks highly both of Lady Catherine and her daughter, but from

02:39:46.520 --> 02:39:51.760
some particulars that he has related of her ladyship, I suspect his gratitude misleads

02:39:51.760 --> 02:39:57.320
him, and that in spite of her being his patroness, she is an arrogant, conceited woman.'

02:39:58.280 --> 02:40:03.760
"'I believe her to be both in a great degree,' replied Wickham. "'I have not seen her for

02:40:03.760 --> 02:40:09.280
many years, but I very well remember that I never liked her, and that her manners were

02:40:09.280 --> 02:40:16.420
dictatorial and insolent. She has the reputation of being remarkably sensible and clever, but

02:40:16.420 --> 02:40:21.680
I rather believe she derives part of her abilities from her rank and fortune, part

02:40:21.680 --> 02:40:27.020
from her authoritative manner, and the rest from the pride for her nephew, who chooses

02:40:27.020 --> 02:40:31.980
that everyone connected with him should have an understanding of the first class.'

02:40:33.360 --> 02:40:38.120
"'Elizabeth allowed that he had given a very rational count of it, and they continued talking

02:40:38.120 --> 02:40:43.360
together with mutual satisfaction till supper put an end to cards, and gave the rest of

02:40:43.360 --> 02:40:49.000
their share of Mr. Wickham's attentions. There could be no conversation in the noise of Mrs.

02:40:49.220 --> 02:40:55.360
Philip's supper party, but his manners recommended him to everybody. Whatever he said was said

02:40:55.360 --> 02:41:01.620
well, and whatever he did done gracefully. Elizabeth went away with her head full of

02:41:01.620 --> 02:41:06.900
him. She could think of nothing but of Mr. Wickham, and of what he had told her all the

02:41:06.900 --> 02:41:12.560
way home. There was not time for her even to mention his name as they went, for neither

02:41:12.560 --> 02:41:19.240
Lydia nor Mr. Collins were once silent. Lydia talked incessantly of lottery tickets, of

02:41:19.240 --> 02:41:25.260
the fish she had lost and the fish she had won, and Mr. Collins, in describing the civility

02:41:25.260 --> 02:41:30.080
of Mr. and Mrs. Phillips, protesting that he did not in the least regard his losses

02:41:30.080 --> 02:41:36.040
at Whist, enumerating all the dishes at supper, and repeatedly fearing that he crowded his

02:41:36.040 --> 02:41:41.280
cousins, had more to say than he could well manage before the carriage stopped at Longbourn

02:41:41.280 --> 02:41:42.040
House.

02:41:50.060 --> 02:41:54.080
Elizabeth related to Jane the next day what

02:41:54.080 --> 02:41:59.440
had passed between Mr. Wickham and herself. Jane listened with astonishment and concern.

02:41:59.880 --> 02:42:05.240
She knew not how to believe that Mr. Darcy could be so unworthy of Mr. Bingley's regard,

02:42:05.800 --> 02:42:11.540
and yet it was not in her nature to question the veracity of a young man of such amiable

02:42:11.540 --> 02:42:17.800
appearance as Wickham. The possibility of his having endured such unkindness was enough

02:42:17.800 --> 02:42:23.120
to interest all her tender feelings, and nothing remained therefore to be done but to think

02:42:23.120 --> 02:42:28.840
well of them both, to defend the conduct of each, and throw into the account of accident

02:42:29.590 --> 02:42:36.500
whatever could not be otherwise explained. They have both, said she, been deceived, I

02:42:36.500 --> 02:42:43.120
dare say in some way or other, of which we can form no idea. Interested people have perhaps

02:42:43.120 --> 02:42:48.800
misrepresented each to the other. It is, in short, impossible for us to conjecture the

02:42:48.800 --> 02:42:54.940
causes or circumstances which may have alienated them, without actual blame on either side.

02:42:56.160 --> 02:43:01.160
Very true indeed, and now, my Jane, what have you got to say on behalf of the interested

02:43:01.160 --> 02:43:06.480
people who have probably been concerned in the business? Do clear them too, or we shall

02:43:06.480 --> 02:43:12.440
be obliged to think ill of somebody. Laugh as much as you choose, but you will not laugh

02:43:12.440 --> 02:43:18.220
me out of my opinion. My dearest Lizzie, do but consider in what a disgraceful light it

02:43:18.220 --> 02:43:24.420
places Mr. Darcy to be treating his father's favorite in such a manner, one whom his father

02:43:24.420 --> 02:43:31.660
had promised to provide for. It is impossible. No man of common humanity, no man who had

02:43:31.660 --> 02:43:37.500
any value for his character, could be capable of it. Can his most intimate friends be so

02:43:37.500 --> 02:43:45.160
excessively deceived in him? Oh, no. I can much more easily believe Mr. Bingley's being

02:43:45.160 --> 02:43:50.660
imposed on than that Mr. Wickham should invent such a history of himself as he gave me last

02:43:50.660 --> 02:43:57.040
night, names, facts, everything mentioned without ceremony. If it be not so, let Mr.

02:43:57.200 --> 02:44:04.040
Darcy contradict it. Besides, there was truth in his looks. It is difficult indeed, it is

02:44:04.040 --> 02:44:09.620
distressing, one does not know what to think. I beg your pardon, one knows exactly what

02:44:09.620 --> 02:44:16.380
to think. But Jane could think with certainty on only one point, that Mr. Bingley, if he

02:44:16.380 --> 02:44:22.680
had been imposed on, would have much to suffer when the affair became public. The two young

02:44:22.680 --> 02:44:27.940
ladies were summoned from the shrubbery where this conversation passed by the arrival of

02:44:27.940 --> 02:44:33.940
the very persons of whom they had been speaking. Mr. Bingley and his sisters came to give their

02:44:33.940 --> 02:44:39.320
personal invitation for the long-expected ball at Netherfield, which was fixed for the

02:44:39.320 --> 02:44:45.360
following Tuesday. The two ladies were delighted to see their dear friend again, calling it

02:44:45.360 --> 02:44:50.200
an age since they had met, and repeatedly asking what she had been doing with herself

02:44:50.200 --> 02:44:56.100
since their separation. To the rest of the family, they paid little attention, avoiding

02:44:56.100 --> 02:45:02.160
Mrs. Bennet as much as possible, saying not much to Elizabeth, and nothing at all to the

02:45:02.160 --> 02:45:07.840
others. They were soon gone again, rising from their seats with an activity which took

02:45:07.840 --> 02:45:14.160
their brother by surprise, and hurrying off as if eager to escape from Mrs. Bennet's civilities.

02:45:15.680 --> 02:45:22.780
The prospect of the Netherfield ball was extremely agreeable to every female of the family. Mrs.

02:45:23.020 --> 02:45:28.280
Bennet chose to consider it as given in compliment to her eldest daughter, and was particularly

02:45:28.280 --> 02:45:33.720
flattered by receiving the invitation from Mr. Bingley himself instead of a ceremonious

02:45:33.720 --> 02:45:40.500
card. Jane pictured to herself a happy evening in the society of her two friends and the

02:45:40.500 --> 02:45:45.260
attentions of their brother, and Elizabeth thought with pleasure of dancing a great deal

02:45:45.260 --> 02:45:50.880
with Mr. Wickham, and of seeing a confirmation of everything in Mr. Darcy's look and behavior.

02:45:51.940 --> 02:45:57.560
The happiness anticipated by Catherine and Lydia depended less on any single event or

02:45:57.560 --> 02:46:02.700
any particular person, for though they each, like Elizabeth, meant to dance half the evening

02:46:02.700 --> 02:46:08.180
with Mr. Wickham, he was by no means the only partner who could satisfy them, and a ball

02:46:08.180 --> 02:46:14.640
was at any rate a ball, and even Mary could assure her family that she had no disinclination

02:46:14.640 --> 02:46:15.200
for it.

02:46:16.400 --> 02:46:22.380
While I can have my mornings to myself, said she, it is enough. I think it is no sacrifice

02:46:22.380 --> 02:46:28.480
to join occasionally in evening engagements. Society has claims on us all, and I profess

02:46:28.480 --> 02:46:34.280
myself one of those who consider intervals of recreation and amusement as desirable for

02:46:34.280 --> 02:46:40.420
everybody. Elizabeth's spirits were so high on this occasion that though she did not often

02:46:40.420 --> 02:46:46.100
speak unnecessarily to Mr. Collins, she could not help but asking him whether he intended

02:46:46.100 --> 02:46:51.420
to accept Mr. Bingley's invitation, and if he did, whether he would think it proper to

02:46:51.420 --> 02:46:56.420
join in the evening's amusement, and she was rather surprised to find that he entertained

02:46:56.420 --> 02:47:01.760
no scribble whatever on that head, and was very far from dreading a rebuke either from

02:47:01.760 --> 02:47:06.080
the Archbishop or Lady Catherine de Bourgh by venturing to dance.

02:47:06.640 --> 02:47:12.520
I am by no means of the opinion, I assure you, said he, that a ball of this kind, given

02:47:12.520 --> 02:47:18.520
by a young man of character, to respectable people, can have any evil tendency, and I

02:47:18.520 --> 02:47:23.480
am so far from objecting to dancing myself that I shall hope to be honoured with the

02:47:23.480 --> 02:47:28.360
hands of all my fair cousins in the course of the evening. And I take this opportunity

02:47:28.360 --> 02:47:33.960
of soliciting yours, Miss Elizabeth, for the first two dances especially, a preference

02:47:33.960 --> 02:47:38.860
which I trust my cousin Jane will attribute to the right cause, and not to any disrespect

02:47:38.860 --> 02:47:39.640
for her.

02:47:41.240 --> 02:47:46.580
Elizabeth felt herself completely taken in. She had fully proposed being engaged by Mr.

02:47:46.760 --> 02:47:52.480
Wickham for those very dances, and to have Mr. Collins instead, her liveliness had never

02:47:52.480 --> 02:47:58.720
been worse timed. There was no help for it, however. Mr. Wickham's happiness and her own

02:47:58.720 --> 02:48:04.620
were perforce delayed a little longer, and Mr. Collins' proposal accepted with as good

02:48:04.620 --> 02:48:09.600
a grace as she could. She was not the better pleased with his gallantry from the idea it

02:48:09.600 --> 02:48:15.420
suggested of something more. It now first struck her that she was selected from among

02:48:15.420 --> 02:48:21.580
her sisters as worthy of being mistress of Huntsford Parsonage, and of assisting to form

02:48:21.580 --> 02:48:28.340
a quadrille table at Rosings, in the absence of more eligible visitors. The idea soon reached

02:48:28.340 --> 02:48:34.420
to conviction, as she observed his increasing civility toward herself, and heard his frequent

02:48:34.420 --> 02:48:40.620
attempt at a compliment on her wit and vivacity. And though more astonished than gratified

02:48:40.620 --> 02:48:46.620
herself by this effect of her charms, it was not long before her mother gave her to understand

02:48:46.620 --> 02:48:53.220
that the probability of their marriage was extremely agreeable to her. Elizabeth, however,

02:48:53.220 --> 02:48:58.880
did not choose to take the hint, being well aware that a serious dispute must be the

02:48:58.880 --> 02:49:05.260
consequence of any reply. Mr. Collins might never make the offer. Until he did, it was

02:49:05.260 --> 02:49:11.280
useless to quarrel about him. If there had not been another field ball to prepare for

02:49:11.280 --> 02:49:16.520
and talk of, the younger Miss Bennetts would have been in a very pitiable state at this time,

02:49:16.900 --> 02:49:22.780
for from the day of the invitation to the day of the ball there was such a succession of rain

02:49:22.780 --> 02:49:30.380
as prevented their walking to Maryton once. No aunt, no officers, no news could be sought after.

02:49:30.740 --> 02:49:37.700
The very shoe roses for Netherfield were got by proxy. Even Elizabeth might have found some trial

02:49:37.700 --> 02:49:42.800
of her patience and weather, which totally suspended the improvement of her acquaintance

02:49:42.800 --> 02:49:49.480
with Mr. Wickham, and nothing less than a dance on Tuesday could have made such a Friday, Saturday,

02:49:49.480 --> 02:49:53.960
Sunday, and Monday, endurable to Kitty and Lydia.

02:50:27.100 --> 02:50:38.860
Till Elizabeth entered the drawing-room at Netherfield, and looked in vain for Mr. Wickham among the cluster of redcoats there assembled, a doubt of his being present had never occurred to her.

02:50:39.900 --> 02:50:47.180
The certainty of meeting him had not been checked by any of those recollections that might not unreasonably have alarmed her.

02:50:47.180 --> 02:51:00.780
She had dressed with more than usual care, and prepared in the highest spirits for the conquest of all that remained unsubdued in his heart, trusting that it was not more than might be won in the course of the evening.

02:51:01.840 --> 02:51:10.780
But in an instant arose the dreadful suspicion of his being purposely omitted for Mr. Darcy's pleasure in the Bingley's invitation to the officers.

02:51:11.380 --> 02:51:30.620
And though this was not exactly the case, the absolute fact of his absence was pronounced by his friend Denny, to whom Lydia eagerly applied, and who told them that Wickham had been obliged to go to town on business the day before, and was not yet returned, adding, with a significant smile,

02:51:30.620 --> 02:51:38.120
I do not imagine his business would have called him away just now, if he had not wanted to avoid a certain gentleman here.

02:51:39.440 --> 02:52:06.640
This part of his intelligence, though unheard by Lydia, was caught by Elizabeth, and as it assured her that Darcy was not less answerable for Wickham's absence than if her first surmise had been just, every feeling of displeasure against the former was so sharpened by immediate disappointment that she could hardly reply with tolerable civility to the polite inquiries which he directly afterwards approached to make.

02:52:08.860 --> 02:52:26.360
Attendance, forbearance, patience with Darcy was injury to Wickham. She was resolved against any sort of conversation with him, and turned away with a degree of ill-humour which she could not wholly surmount even in speaking to Mr. Bingley, whose blind partiality provoked her.

02:52:27.880 --> 02:52:49.660
But Elizabeth was not formed for ill-humour, and though every prospect of her own was destroyed for the evening, it could not dwell long on her spirits, and having told all her griefs to Charlotte Lucas, whom she had not seen for a week, she was soon able to make a voluntary transition to the oddities of her cousin, and to point him out to her particular notice.

02:52:51.080 --> 02:53:17.220
The first two dances, however, brought a return of distress. They were dances of mortification. Mr. Collins, awkward and solemn, apologizing instead of attending, and often moving wrong without being aware of it, gave her all the shame and misery which a disagreeable partner for a couple of dances can give. The moment of her release from him was ecstasy.

02:53:18.220 --> 02:53:43.860
She danced next with an officer, and had the refreshment of talking of Wickham, and of hearing that he was universally liked. When those dances were over she returned to Charlotte Lucas, and was in conversation with her, when she found herself suddenly addressed by Mr. Darcy, who took her so much by surprise in his application for her hand that, without knowing what she did, she accepted him.

02:53:44.740 --> 02:53:53.400
He walked away again immediately, and she was left to fret over her own want of presence of mind. Charlotte tried to console her.

02:53:54.680 --> 02:54:07.620
I dare say you will find him very agreeable. Heaven forbid! that would be the greatest misfortune of all, to find a man agreeable whom one is determined to hate. Do not wish me such an evil.

02:54:09.080 --> 02:54:24.580
When the dancing recommenced, however, and Darcy approached to claim her hand, Charlotte could not help cautioning her in a whisper not to be a simpleton, and allow her fancy for Wickham to make her appear unpleasant in the eyes of a man ten times his consequence.

02:54:26.860 --> 02:54:40.040
Elizabeth made no answer, and took her place in the set, amazed at the dignity to which she was arrived in being allowed to stand opposite Mr. Darcy, and reading in her neighbour's looks their equal amazement in beholding it.

02:54:41.060 --> 02:55:00.320
They stood for some time without speaking a word, and she began to imagine that their silence was to last through the two dances, and at first was resolved not to break it, till suddenly fancying that it would be the greater punishment to her partner to oblige him to talk, she made some slight observation on the dance.

02:55:01.600 --> 02:55:04.260
He replied, and was again silent.

02:55:05.620 --> 02:55:09.800
After a pause of some minutes, she addressed him a second time with,

02:55:10.660 --> 02:55:21.600
It is your turn to say something now, Mr. Darcy. I talked about the dance, and you ought to make some sort of remark on the size of the room or the number of couples.

02:55:22.780 --> 02:55:27.320
He smiled and assured her that whatever she wished him to say should be said.

02:55:28.960 --> 02:55:40.300
Very well. That reply will do for the present. Perhaps by and by I may observe that private balls are much pleasanter than public ones. But now we may be silent.

02:55:41.480 --> 02:55:44.360
Do you talk by rule, then, while you are dancing?

02:55:46.220 --> 02:56:01.000
Sometimes one must speak a little, you know. It would look odd to be entirely silent for half an hour together, and yet for the advantage of some, conversation ought to be so arranged as that they may have the trouble of saying as little as possible.

02:56:02.160 --> 02:56:07.880
Are you consulting your own feelings in the present case, or do you imagine that you are gratifying mine?

02:56:09.380 --> 02:56:16.640
Both, replied Elizabeth archly. For I have always seen a great similarity in the turn of our minds.

02:56:17.500 --> 02:56:29.820
We are each of an unsocial taciturn disposition, unwilling to speak unless we expect to say something that will amaze the whole room, and be handed down to posterity with all the eclat of a proverb.

02:56:30.960 --> 02:56:43.400
This is no very striking resemblance of your own character, I am sure, said he. How near it may be to mine I cannot pretend to say. You think it a faithful portrait, undoubtedly.

02:56:44.660 --> 02:56:47.180
I must not decide on my own performance.

02:56:48.440 --> 02:56:57.860
He made no answer, and they were again silent till they had gone down the dance, when he asked her if she and her sisters did not very often walk to Meryton.

02:56:58.980 --> 02:57:04.020
She answered in the affirmative, and, unable to resist the temptation, added,

02:57:04.820 --> 02:57:09.640
When you met us there the other day, we had just been forming a new acquaintance.

02:57:11.240 --> 02:57:24.080
The effect was immediate. A deeper shade of hauteur overspread his features, but he said not a word, and Elizabeth, though blaming herself for her own weakness, could not go on.

02:57:24.080 --> 02:57:29.200
At length Darcy spoke, and in a constrained manner said,

02:57:30.040 --> 02:57:39.920
Mr. Wickham is blessed with such happy manners as may ensure his making friends. Whether he may be equally capable of retaining them is less certain.

02:57:41.220 --> 02:57:51.380
He has been so unlucky as to lose your friendship, replied Elizabeth with emphasis, and in a manner which he is likely to suffer from all his life.

02:57:52.900 --> 02:57:57.240
Darcy made no answer, and seemed desirous of changing the subject.

02:57:58.400 --> 02:58:04.500
At that moment Sir William Lucas appeared close to them, meaning to pass through the set to the other side of the room,

02:58:04.760 --> 02:58:12.500
but, on perceiving Mr. Darcy, he stopped with a bow of superior courtesy to compliment him on his dancing and his partner.

02:58:13.420 --> 02:58:21.180
I have been most highly gratified indeed, my dear sir. Such very superior dancing is not often seen.

02:58:21.640 --> 02:58:29.360
It is evident that you belong to the first circles. Allow me to say, however, that your fair partner does not disgrace you,

02:58:29.600 --> 02:58:37.940
and that I must hope to have this pleasure often repeated, especially when a certain desirable event, my dear Eliza,

02:58:37.940 --> 02:58:42.480
glancing at her sister and Bingley, shall take place.

02:58:43.480 --> 02:58:50.700
What congratulations will then flow in! I appeal to Mr. Darcy. But let me not interrupt you, sir.

02:58:51.040 --> 02:58:58.060
You will not thank me for detaining you from the bewitching converse of that young lady, whose bright eyes are also upbraiding me.

02:58:59.040 --> 02:59:07.400
The latter part of this address was scarcely heard by Darcy, but Sir William's allusion to his friend seemed to strike him forcibly,

02:59:08.300 --> 02:59:14.520
and his eyes were directed with a very serious expression towards Bingley and Jane, who were dancing together.

02:59:16.120 --> 02:59:20.860
Recovering himself, however, shortly, he turned to his partner, and said,

02:59:20.860 --> 02:59:25.260
Sir William's interruption has made me forget what we were talking of.

02:59:26.760 --> 02:59:33.460
I do not think we were speaking at all. Sir William could not have interrupted two people in the room who had less to say for themselves.

02:59:34.620 --> 02:59:41.140
We have tried two or three subjects already without success, and what we are to talk of next I cannot imagine.

02:59:42.580 --> 02:59:45.440
What think you of books? said he, smiling.

02:59:46.620 --> 02:59:52.420
Books? Oh, no! I am sure we never read the same, or not with the same feelings.

02:59:54.140 --> 03:00:02.060
I am sorry you think so, but if that be the case, there can at least be no want of subject. We may compare our different opinions.

03:00:03.260 --> 03:00:08.220
No, I cannot talk of books in a ballroom. My head is always full of something else.

03:00:09.300 --> 03:00:15.580
The present always occupies you in such scenes, does it? said he, with a look of doubt.

03:00:17.240 --> 03:00:24.060
Yes, always, she replied, without knowing what she said, for her thoughts had wandered far from the subject,

03:00:24.620 --> 03:00:27.360
as soon afterwards appeared by her suddenly exclaiming,

03:00:27.360 --> 03:00:37.160
I remember hearing you once say, Mr. Darcy, that you hardly ever forgave, that your resentment once created was unappeasable.

03:00:37.760 --> 03:00:41.660
You are very cautious, I suppose, as to its being created.

03:00:42.940 --> 03:00:46.180
I am, said he, with a firm voice.

03:00:47.340 --> 03:00:50.700
And never allow yourself to be blinded by prejudice?

03:00:51.840 --> 03:00:53.180
I hope not.

03:00:54.140 --> 03:01:01.280
It is particularly incumbent on those who never change their opinion to be secure of judging properly at first.

03:01:02.500 --> 03:01:05.120
May I ask to what these questions tend?

03:01:06.120 --> 03:01:11.920
Merely to the illustration of your character, said she, endeavouring to shake off her gravity.

03:01:12.400 --> 03:01:14.020
I am trying to make it out.

03:01:15.280 --> 03:01:17.060
And what is your success?

03:01:18.160 --> 03:01:19.580
She shook her head.

03:01:19.840 --> 03:01:21.520
I do not get on at all.

03:01:21.740 --> 03:01:25.420
I hear such different accounts of you as puzzle me exceedingly.

03:01:26.040 --> 03:01:33.560
I can readily believe, answered he gravely, that reports may vary greatly with respect to me.

03:01:33.740 --> 03:01:39.240
And I could wish, Miss Bennet, that you were not to sketch my character at the present moment,

03:01:39.720 --> 03:01:44.260
as there is reason to fear that the performance would reflect no credit on either.

03:01:45.820 --> 03:01:50.360
But if I do not take your likeness now, I may never have another opportunity.

03:01:51.760 --> 03:01:56.640
I would by no means suspend any pleasure of yours, he coldly replied.

03:01:57.280 --> 03:02:02.000
She said no more, and they went down the other dance, and parted in silence,

03:02:02.720 --> 03:02:06.780
and on each side dissatisfied, though not to an equal degree,

03:02:07.360 --> 03:02:13.900
for in Darcy's breast there was a tolerable powerful feeling towards her, which soon procured her pardon.

03:02:14.260 --> 03:02:16.680
And directed all his anger against another.

03:02:18.260 --> 03:02:22.080
They had not long separated when Miss Bingley came towards her,

03:02:22.160 --> 03:02:25.620
and with an expression of civil disdain accosted her.

03:02:26.780 --> 03:02:31.400
So, Miss Eliza, I hear you are quite delighted with George Wickham.

03:02:31.880 --> 03:02:35.980
Your sister has been talking to me about him, and asking me a thousand questions.

03:02:36.520 --> 03:02:41.360
And I find that the young man quite forgot to tell you, among his other communication,

03:02:41.360 --> 03:02:46.260
that he was the son of old Wickham, the late Mr. Darcy's steward.

03:02:47.420 --> 03:02:53.480
Let me recommend you, however, as a friend, not to give implicit confidence to all his assertions,

03:02:53.860 --> 03:02:57.940
for as to Mr. Darcy's using him ill, it is perfectly false,

03:02:58.400 --> 03:03:02.400
for on the contrary, he has always been remarkably kind to him,

03:03:02.720 --> 03:03:06.700
though George Wickham has treated Mr. Darcy in a most infamous manner.

03:03:08.000 --> 03:03:14.120
I do not know the particulars, but I know very well that Mr. Darcy is not in the least to blame,

03:03:14.540 --> 03:03:17.320
that he cannot bear to hear George Wickham mentioned,

03:03:17.440 --> 03:03:23.400
and that though my brother thought that he could not well avoid including him in his invitation to the officers,

03:03:23.800 --> 03:03:28.000
he was excessively glad to find that he has taken himself out of the way.

03:03:29.140 --> 03:03:35.760
His coming into the country at all is a most insolent thing, indeed, and I wonder how he could presume to do it.

03:03:36.700 --> 03:03:40.880
I pity you, Miss Eliza, for this discovery of your favourite's guilt,

03:03:41.240 --> 03:03:45.540
but really, considering his descent, one could not expect much better.

03:03:47.100 --> 03:03:53.400
His guilt and his descent appear by your account to be the same, said Elizabeth angrily,

03:03:53.700 --> 03:03:58.400
for I have heard you accuse him of nothing worse than of being the son of Mr. Darcy's steward,

03:03:58.740 --> 03:04:02.480
and of that, I can assure you, he informed me himself.

03:04:02.480 --> 03:04:08.660
I beg your pardon, replied Miss Bingley, turning away with a sneer.

03:04:09.620 --> 03:04:12.800
Excuse my interference, it was kindly meant.

03:04:14.460 --> 03:04:17.400
Insolent girl, said Elizabeth to herself,

03:04:18.380 --> 03:04:23.760
you are much mistaken if you expect to influence me by such a paltry attack as this.

03:04:24.700 --> 03:04:30.020
I see nothing in it but your own willful ignorance and the malice of Mr. Darcy.

03:04:31.220 --> 03:04:37.300
She then sought her eldest sister, who had undertaken to make inquiries on the same subject of Bingley.

03:04:39.400 --> 03:04:44.960
Jane met her with a smile of such sweet complacency, a glow of such happy expression,

03:04:45.140 --> 03:04:49.640
as sufficiently marked how well she was satisfied with the occurrences of the evening.

03:04:51.680 --> 03:04:56.340
Elizabeth instantly read her feelings, and at that moment solicitude for Wickham,

03:04:56.340 --> 03:05:03.740
resentment against his enemies, and everything else, gave way before the hope of Jane's being in the fairest way for happiness.

03:05:05.500 --> 03:05:10.580
I want to know, said she, with a countenance no less smiling than her sister's,

03:05:11.580 --> 03:05:18.120
what you have learnt about Mr. Wickham, but perhaps you have been too pleasantly engaged to think of any third person,

03:05:18.380 --> 03:05:20.680
in which case you may be sure of my pardon.

03:05:22.020 --> 03:05:28.260
No, replied Jane, I have not forgotten him, but I have nothing satisfactory to tell you.

03:05:29.440 --> 03:05:36.740
Mr. Bingley does not know the whole of his history, and is quite ignorant of the circumstances which have principally offended Mr. Darcy,

03:05:37.040 --> 03:05:41.800
but he will vouch for the good conduct, the probity, and honour of his friend,

03:05:42.160 --> 03:05:48.360
and is perfectly convinced that Mr. Wickham has deserved much less attention from Mr. Darcy than he has received,

03:05:48.360 --> 03:05:56.560
and I am sorry to say, by his account as well as his sister's, Mr. Wickham is by no means a respectable young man.

03:05:57.140 --> 03:06:02.240
I am afraid he has been very imprudent, and has deserved to lose Mr. Darcy's regard.

03:06:04.000 --> 03:06:06.480
Mr. Bingley does not know Mr. Wickham himself?

03:06:07.780 --> 03:06:10.940
No, he never saw him till the other morning at Meryton.

03:06:11.920 --> 03:06:15.320
This account, then, is what he has received from Mr. Darcy.

03:06:15.860 --> 03:06:19.100
I am satisfied, but what does he say of the living?

03:06:20.540 --> 03:06:26.400
He does not exactly recollect the circumstances, though he has heard them from Mr. Darcy more than once,

03:06:26.800 --> 03:06:30.020
but he believes that it was left to him conditionally only.

03:06:31.280 --> 03:06:36.460
I have not a doubt of Mr. Bingley's sincerity, said Elizabeth warmly,

03:06:36.880 --> 03:06:40.920
but you must excuse my not being convinced by assurances only.

03:06:42.000 --> 03:06:45.940
Mr. Bingley's defence of his friend was a very able one, I dare say,

03:06:46.340 --> 03:06:52.420
but since he is unacquainted with several parts of the story, and has learnt the rest from that friend himself,

03:06:52.940 --> 03:06:56.680
I shall venture to still think of both gentlemen as I did before.

03:06:58.300 --> 03:07:02.280
She then changed the discourse to one more gratifying to each,

03:07:02.620 --> 03:07:05.120
and on which there could be no difference of sentiment.

03:07:06.900 --> 03:07:12.980
Elizabeth listened with delight to the happy, though modest, hopes which Jane entertained of Bingley's regard,

03:07:13.500 --> 03:07:17.000
and said all in her power to heighten her confidence in it.

03:07:18.480 --> 03:07:23.360
On their being joined by Mr. Bingley himself, Elizabeth withdrew to Miss Lucas,

03:07:23.360 --> 03:07:30.640
to whose inquiry after the pleasantness of her last partner she had scarcely replied before Mr. Collins came up to them,

03:07:31.000 --> 03:07:36.480
and told her with great exultation that he had just been so fortunate as to make a most important discovery.

03:07:38.360 --> 03:07:46.680
I have found out, said he, by a singular accident, that there is now in the room a near relation of my patroness.

03:07:47.400 --> 03:07:53.040
I happened to overhear the gentleman himself mentioning to the young lady who does the honours of the house,

03:07:53.360 --> 03:07:58.280
the names of his cousin Miss de Bourgh, and of her mother Lady Catherine.

03:07:59.560 --> 03:08:02.020
How wonderfully these sort of things occur!

03:08:02.440 --> 03:08:08.480
Who would have thought of my meeting with, perhaps, a nephew of Lady Catherine de Bourgh in this assembly?

03:08:09.840 --> 03:08:15.060
I am most thankful that the discovery is made in time for me to pay my respects to him,

03:08:15.320 --> 03:08:20.160
which I am now going to do, and trust he will excuse my not having done it before.

03:08:20.160 --> 03:08:24.400
My total ignorance of the connexion must plead my apology.

03:08:25.860 --> 03:08:29.520
You are not going to introduce yourself to Mr. Darcy.

03:08:30.640 --> 03:08:35.100
Indeed I am. I shall entreat his pardon for not having done it earlier.

03:08:36.080 --> 03:08:38.680
I believe him to be Lady Catherine's nephew.

03:08:39.500 --> 03:08:44.840
It will be in my power to assure him that her ladyship was quite well yesterday night.

03:08:46.960 --> 03:08:50.040
Elizabeth tried hard to dissuade him from such a scheme.

03:08:50.160 --> 03:08:56.560
Assuring him that Mr. Darcy would consider his addressing him without introduction as an impertinent freedom,

03:08:57.080 --> 03:09:03.800
rather than a compliment to his aunt, that it was not in the least necessary there should be any notice on either side,

03:09:04.180 --> 03:09:10.460
and that if it were, it must belong to Mr. Darcy, the superior in consequence, to begin the acquaintance.

03:09:11.980 --> 03:09:18.900
Mr. Collins listened to her with the determined air of following his own inclination, and, when she ceased speaking,

03:09:18.900 --> 03:09:19.980
replied thus.

03:09:21.300 --> 03:09:30.240
My dear Miss Elizabeth, I have the highest opinion in the world in your excellent judgment in all matters within the scope of your understanding.

03:09:30.780 --> 03:09:37.920
But permit me to say that there must be a wide difference between the established forms of ceremony amongst the laity,

03:09:38.300 --> 03:09:40.360
and those which regulate the clergy.

03:09:41.200 --> 03:09:48.680
For give me leave to observe that I consider the clerical office as equal in point of dignity with the highest rank in the kingdom.

03:09:48.900 --> 03:09:53.560
Provided that a proper humility of behaviour is at the same time maintained.

03:09:54.940 --> 03:10:03.520
You must therefore allow me to follow the dictates of my conscience on this occasion, which leads me to perform what I look on as a point of duty.

03:10:04.660 --> 03:10:10.860
Pardon me for neglecting to profit by your advice, which on every other subject shall be my constant guide,

03:10:10.860 --> 03:10:20.940
though in the case before us I consider myself more fitted by education and habitual study to decide on what is right than a young lady like yourself.

03:10:22.120 --> 03:10:33.300
And with a low bow he left her to attack Mr. Darcy, whose reception of his advances she eagerly watched, and whose astonishment at being so addressed was very evident.

03:10:35.140 --> 03:10:45.640
Her cousin prefaced his speech with a solemn bow, and though she could not hear a word of it, she felt as if hearing it all, and saw in the motion of his lips the words

03:10:52.660 --> 03:10:56.360
It vexed her to see him expose himself to such a man.

03:10:57.400 --> 03:11:07.340
Mr. Darcy was eyeing him with unrestrained wonder, and when at last Mr. Collins allowed him time to speak, replied with an air of distant civility.

03:11:08.760 --> 03:11:26.300
Mr. Collins, however, was not discouraged from speaking again, and Mr. Darcy's contempt seemed abundantly increasing with the length of his second speech, and at the end of it he only made him a slight bow, and moved another way. Mr. Collins then returned to Elizabeth.

03:11:28.320 --> 03:11:50.360
I have no reason, I assure you, said he, to be dissatisfied with my reception. Mr. Darcy seemed much pleased with the attention. He answered me with the utmost civility, and even paid me the compliment of saying that he was so well convinced of Lady Catherine's discernment, as to be certain she could never bestow a favour unworthily.

03:11:50.360 --> 03:11:55.980
It was really a very handsome thought. Upon the whole, I am much pleased with him.

03:11:57.500 --> 03:12:13.480
As Elizabeth had no longer any interest of her own to pursue, she turned her attention almost entirely on her sister and Mr. Bingley, and the train of agreeable reflections which her observations gave birth to made her perhaps almost as happy as Jane.

03:12:14.900 --> 03:12:29.660
She saw her in idea settled in that very house, in all the felicity which a marriage of true affection could bestow, and she felt capable, under such circumstances, of endeavouring even to like Bingley's two sisters.

03:12:31.300 --> 03:12:39.780
Her mother's thoughts, she plainly saw, were bent the same way, and she determined not to venture near her, lest she might hear too much.

03:12:40.620 --> 03:13:02.560
When they sat down to supper, therefore, she considered it a most unlucky perverseness which placed them within one of each other, and deeply was she vexed to find that her mother was talking to that one person, Lady Lucas, freely, openly, and of nothing else but her expectation that Jane would soon be married to Mr. Bingley.

03:13:04.300 --> 03:13:12.380
It was an animating subject, and Mrs. Bennet seemed incapable of fatigue while enumerating the advantages of the match.

03:13:13.300 --> 03:13:31.620
His being such a charming young man, and so rich, and living but three miles from them, were the first points of self-gratulation, and then it was such a comfort to think how fond the two sisters were of Jane, and to be certain that they must desire the connection as much as she could do.

03:13:32.560 --> 03:13:40.860
It was, moreover, such a promising thing for her younger daughters, as Jane's marrying so greatly must throw them in the way of other rich men.

03:13:41.480 --> 03:13:53.340
And lastly, it was so pleasant at her time of life to be able to consign her single daughters to the care of their sister, that she might not be obliged to go into company more than she liked.

03:13:53.340 --> 03:14:06.360
It was necessary to make this circumstance a matter of pleasure, because on such occasions it is the etiquette, but no one was less likely than Mrs. Bennet to find comfort in staying home at any period of her life.

03:14:08.140 --> 03:14:17.500
She concluded with many good wishes that Lady Lucas might soon be equally fortunate, though evidently and triumphantly believing there was no chance of it.

03:14:19.240 --> 03:14:37.040
In vain did Elizabeth endeavour to check the rapidity of her mother's words, or persuade her to describe her felicity in a less audible whisper, for to her inexpressible vexation she could perceive that the chief of it was overheard by Mr. Darcy, who sat opposite to them.

03:14:38.520 --> 03:14:41.420
Her mother only scolded her for being nonsensical.

03:14:42.360 --> 03:14:53.180
What is Mr. Darcy to me, pray, that I should be afraid of him? I am sure we owe him no such particular civility as to be obliged to say nothing he may not like to hear.

03:14:55.160 --> 03:15:04.180
For heaven's sake, madam, speak lower! What advantage can it be for you to offend Mr. Darcy? You will never recommend yourself to his friend by so doing.

03:15:05.760 --> 03:15:13.480
Nothing that she could say, however, had any influence. Her mother would talk of her views in the same intelligible tone.

03:15:14.960 --> 03:15:18.820
Elizabeth blushed, and blushed again with shame and vexation.

03:15:20.260 --> 03:15:34.320
She could not help frequently glancing her eye at Mr. Darcy, though every glance convinced her of what she dreaded, for though he was not always looking at her mother, she was convinced that his attention was invariably fixed by her.

03:15:35.860 --> 03:15:42.860
The expression of his face changed gradually from indignant contempt to a composed and steady gravity.

03:15:44.520 --> 03:15:58.140
At length, however, Mrs. Bennet had no more to say, and Lady Lucas, who had been long yawning at the repetition of delights, which she saw no likelihood of sharing, was left to the comforts of cold ham and chicken.

03:16:00.020 --> 03:16:16.160
Elizabeth now began to revive, but not long was the interval of tranquillity, for when supper was over singing was talked of, and she had the mortification of seeing Mary, after very little entreaty, preparing to oblige the company.

03:16:17.320 --> 03:16:25.100
By many significant looks and silent entreaties did she endeavour to prevent such a proof of complacence, but in vain.

03:16:26.060 --> 03:16:33.180
Mary would not understand them. Such an opportunity of exhibiting was delightful to her, and she began her song.

03:16:35.480 --> 03:16:58.020
Elizabeth's eyes were fixed on her with most painful sensations, and she watched her progress through the several stanzas with an impatience which was very ill-rewarded at their close, for Mary, on receiving, amongst the thanks of the table, the hint of a hope that she might be prevailed on to favour them again, after the pause of half a minute began another.

03:16:59.940 --> 03:17:06.440
Mary's powers were by no means fitted for such a display. Her voice was weak, and her manner affected.

03:17:07.680 --> 03:17:14.980
Elizabeth was in agonies. She looked at Jane to see how she bore it, but Jane was very composedly talking to Bingley.

03:17:16.480 --> 03:17:25.280
She looked at his two sisters, and saw them making signs of derision at each other, and at Darcy, who continued, however, imperturbably grave.

03:17:26.600 --> 03:17:37.180
She looked at her father to entreat his interference, lest Mary should be singing all night. He took the hint, and when Mary had finished her second song, said aloud,

03:17:38.620 --> 03:17:45.720
That will do extremely well, child. You have delighted us long enough. Let the other young ladies have time to exhibit.

03:17:47.580 --> 03:18:02.560
Mary, though pretending not to hear, was somewhat disconcerted, and Elizabeth, sorry for her and sorry for her father's speech, was afraid her anxiety had done no good. Others of the party were now applied to.

03:18:03.780 --> 03:18:20.900
If I, said Mr. Collins, were so fortunate as to be able to sing, I should have great pleasure, I am sure, in obliging the company with an heir, for I consider music as a very innocent diversion, and perfectly compatible with the profession of a clergyman.

03:18:22.100 --> 03:18:31.920
I do not mean, however, to assert that we can be justified in devoting too much of our time to music, for there are certainly other things to be attended to.

03:18:32.780 --> 03:18:43.080
The rector of a parish has much to do. In the first place, he must make such an agreement for tithes, as may be beneficial to himself, and not offensive to his patron.

03:18:44.380 --> 03:18:57.300
He must write his own sermons, and the time that remains will not be too much for his parish duties, and the care and improvement of his dwelling, which he cannot be excused from making as comfortable as possible.

03:18:58.380 --> 03:19:08.560
And I do not think it of light importance that he should have attentive and conciliatory manner towards everybody, especially towards those to whom he owes his preferment.

03:19:09.580 --> 03:19:19.200
I cannot acquit him of that duty, nor could I think well of the man who should omit an occasion of testifying his respect towards anybody connected with the family.

03:19:20.460 --> 03:19:28.100
And, with a bow to Mr. Darcy, he concluded his speech, which had been spoken so loud as to be heard by half the room.

03:19:29.240 --> 03:19:47.580
Many stared, many smiled, but no one looked more amused than Mr. Bennet himself, while his wife seriously commended Mr. Collins for having spoken so sensibly, and observed in a half whisper to Lady Lucas, that he was a remarkably clever, good kind of young man.

03:19:48.840 --> 03:20:01.750
To Elizabeth it appeared that, had her family made an agreement to expose themselves as much as they could during the evening, it would have been impossible for them to play their parts with more spirit or finer success.

03:20:02.590 --> 03:20:14.910
And happy did she think it for Bingley and her sister that some of the exhibition had escaped his notice, and that his feelings were not of a sort to be much distressed by the folly which he must have witnessed.

03:20:15.750 --> 03:20:31.090
That his two sisters and Mr. Darcy, however, should have such an opportunity of ridiculing her relations was bad enough, and she could not determine whether the silent contempt of the gentlemen or the insolent smiles of the ladies were more intolerable.

03:20:32.450 --> 03:20:47.430
The rest of the evening brought her little amusement. She was teased by Mr. Collins, who continued most perseveringly by her side, and, though he could not prevail on her to dance with him again, put it out of her power to dance with others.

03:20:49.210 --> 03:21:11.330
In vain did she entreat him to stand up with somebody else, and offer to introduce him to any young lady in the room. He assured her that, as to dancing, he was perfectly indifferent to it, that his chief object was by delicate attentions to recommend himself to her, and that he should therefore make a point of remaining close to her the whole evening.

03:21:12.450 --> 03:21:24.770
There was no arguing upon such a project. She owed her greatest relief to her friend Miss Lucas, who often joined them, and good-naturedly engaged Mr. Collins's conversation to herself.

03:21:26.530 --> 03:21:44.290
She was at least free from the offence of Mr. Darcy's further notice, though often standing within a very short distance of her, quite disengaged, he never came near enough to speak. She felt it to be the probable consequence of her allusions to Mr. Wickham, and rejoiced in it.

03:21:45.690 --> 03:22:01.470
The Longbourn party were the last of all accompanied to depart, and, by a maneuver of Mrs. Bennet, had to wait for their carriage a quarter of an hour after everybody else was gone, which gave them time to see how heartily they were wished away by some of the family.

03:22:02.870 --> 03:22:12.110
Mrs. Hurst and her sister scarcely opened their mouths, except to complain of fatigue, and were evidently impatient to have the house to themselves.

03:22:13.570 --> 03:22:35.430
They repulsed every attempt of Mrs. Bennet at conversation, and by so doing threw a languor over the whole party, which was very little relieved by the long speeches of Mr. Collins, who was complimenting Mr. Bingley and his sisters on the elegance of their entertainment, and the hospitality and politeness which had marked their behaviour to their guests.

03:22:37.330 --> 03:22:39.210
Darcy said nothing at all.

03:22:40.390 --> 03:22:51.290
Mr. Bennet, in equal silence, was enjoying the scene. Mr. Bingley and Jane were standing together, a little detached from the rest, and talked only to each other.

03:22:52.790 --> 03:23:03.970
Elizabeth preserved as steady a silence as either Mrs. Hurst or Miss Bingley, and even Lydia was too much fatigued to utter more than the occasional exclamation of,

03:23:03.970 --> 03:23:09.450
''Lord, how tired I am!'' accompanied by a violent yawn.

03:23:11.730 --> 03:23:31.850
When at length they arose to take leave, Mrs. Bennet was most pressingly civil in her hope of seeing the whole family soon at Longbourn, and addressed herself especially to Mr. Bingley, to assure him how happy he would make them by eating a family dinner with them at any time, without the ceremony of a formal invitation.

03:23:33.830 --> 03:23:45.950
Bingley was all grateful pleasure, and he readily engaged for taking the earliest opportunity of waiting on her, after his return from London, whither he was obliged to go the next day for a short time.

03:23:47.270 --> 03:24:04.550
Mrs. Bennet was perfectly satisfied, and quitted the house under the delightful persuasion that, allowing for the necessary preparations of settlements, new carriages, and wedding clothes, she should undoubtedly see her daughter settled at Netherfield in the course of three or four months.

03:24:05.930 --> 03:24:14.130
Of having another daughter married to Mr. Collins, she thought with equal certainty, and with considerable, though not equal, pleasure.

03:24:15.450 --> 03:24:27.270
Elizabeth was the least dear to her of all her children, and though the man and the match were quite good enough for her, the worth of each was eclipsed by Mr. Bingley and Netherfield.

03:24:35.890 --> 03:24:42.870
The next day opened a new scene at Longbourn. Mr. Collins made his declaration in form.

03:24:43.870 --> 03:25:03.910
Having resolved to do it without loss of time, as his leave of absence extended only to the following Saturday, and having no feelings of diffidence to make it distressing to himself even at the moment, he said about it in a very orderly manner, with all the observances which he supposed a regular part of the business.

03:25:05.850 --> 03:25:14.870
On finding Mrs. Bennet, Elizabeth, and one of the younger girls together, soon after breakfast, he addressed the mother in these words.

03:25:16.170 --> 03:25:25.410
May I hope, madam, for your interest with your fair daughter Elizabeth, when I solicit for the honour of a private audience with her in the course of this morning?

03:25:27.450 --> 03:25:33.290
Before Elizabeth had time for anything but a blush of surprise, Mrs. Bennet answered instantly.

03:25:34.630 --> 03:25:43.810
Oh, dear, yes, certainly! I am sure Lizzie will be very happy. I am sure she can have no objection. Come, Kitty, I want you upstairs.

03:25:44.970 --> 03:25:49.990
And, gathering her work together, she was hastening away, when Elizabeth called out.

03:25:50.970 --> 03:26:01.610
Dear madam, do not go. I beg you will not go. Mr. Collins must excuse me. He can have nothing to say to me that anybody need not hear. I am going away myself.

03:26:03.230 --> 03:26:07.290
No, no, nonsense, Lizzie. I desire you to stay where you are.

03:26:08.130 --> 03:26:15.270
And upon Elizabeth's seeming really, with vexed and embarrassed looks, about to escape, she added,

03:26:16.030 --> 03:26:20.470
Lizzie, I insist upon your staying and hearing Mr. Collins.

03:26:22.530 --> 03:26:33.010
Elizabeth would not oppose such an injunction, and a moment's consideration making her also sensible that it would be wisest to get it over as soon and as quietly as possible.

03:26:33.010 --> 03:26:42.030
She sat down again, and tried to conceal, by incessant employment, the feelings which were divided between distress and diversion.

03:26:43.710 --> 03:26:49.310
Mrs. Bennet and Kitty walked off, and as soon as they were gone, Mr. Collins began.

03:26:50.830 --> 03:27:00.510
Believe me, my dear Miss Elizabeth, that your modesty, so far from doing you any disservice, rather adds to your other perfections.

03:27:01.450 --> 03:27:12.190
You would have been less amiable in my eyes had there not been this little unwillingness, but allow me to assure you that I have your respected mother's permission for this address.

03:27:13.270 --> 03:27:23.150
You can hardly doubt the purport of my discourse, however your natural delicacy may lead you to dissemble, my attentions have been too marked to be mistaken.

03:27:24.810 --> 03:27:30.830
Almost as soon as I entered the house, I singled you out as the companion of my future life.

03:27:31.930 --> 03:27:46.310
But before I am run away with by my feelings on this subject, perhaps it would be advisable for me to state my reasons for marrying, and, moreover, for coming into Hertfordshire with the design of selecting a wife, as I certainly did.

03:27:47.410 --> 03:28:02.070
The idea of Mr. Collins, with all his solemn composure being run away with by his feelings, made Elizabeth so near laughing that she could not use the short pause he allowed in any attempt to stop him further, and he continued.

03:28:03.470 --> 03:28:21.190
My reasons for marrying are, first, that I think it a right thing for every clergyman in easy circumstances, like myself, to set the example of matrimony in his parish, secondly, that I am convinced that it will add very greatly to my happiness,

03:28:21.190 --> 03:28:33.530
and, thirdly, which perhaps I ought to have mentioned earlier, that it is the particular advice and recommendation of the very noble lady whom I have the honour of calling patroness.

03:28:34.650 --> 03:28:52.350
Twice has she condescended to give me her opinion—unasked, too, on this subject—and it was but the very Saturday night before I left Hunsford, between our pools at Quadrill, while Mrs. Jenkinson was arranging Miss de Bourgh's footstool, that she said,

03:28:53.190 --> 03:29:10.990
Mr. Collins, you must marry. A clergyman like you must marry. Choose properly, choose a gentlewoman for my sake, and for your own let her be an active, useful sort of person, not brought up high, but able to make a small income go a good way.

03:29:11.930 --> 03:29:19.570
This is my advice. Find such a woman as soon as you can, bring her to Hunsford, and I will visit her.

03:29:20.570 --> 03:29:32.330
Allow me, by the way, to observe, my fair cousin, that I do not reckon the notice and kindness of Lady Catherine de Bourgh as among the least of the advantages in my power to offer.

03:29:33.310 --> 03:29:46.830
You will find her manners beyond anything I can describe, and your wit and vivacity, I think, must be acceptable to her, especially when tempered with the silence and respect which her rank will inevitably excite.

03:29:48.190 --> 03:30:01.290
Thus much for my general intention in favour of matrimony. It remains to be told why my views were directed towards Longbourn, instead of my own neighbourhood, where I can assure you there are many amiable young women.

03:30:02.190 --> 03:30:28.730
But the fact is that being as I am to inherit this estate after the death of your honoured father, who, however, may live many years longer, I could not satisfy myself without resolving to choose a wife from among his daughters, that the loss to them might be as little as possible when the melancholy event takes place, which, however, as I have already said, may not be for several years.

03:30:29.610 --> 03:30:44.970
This has been my motive, my fair cousin, and I flatter myself it will not sink me in your esteem. And now nothing remains but for me to assure you in the most animated language of the violence of my affection.

03:30:45.710 --> 03:31:03.710
To fortune I am perfectly indifferent, and shall make no demand of that nature on your father, since I am well aware that it could not be complied with, and that one thousand pounds, in the four percents, which will not be yours till after your mother's decease, is all that you may ever be entitled to.

03:31:03.710 --> 03:31:14.730
On that head, therefore, I shall be uniformly silent, and you may assure yourself that no ungenerous reproach shall ever pass my lips when we are married.

03:31:15.730 --> 03:31:19.710
It was absolutely necessary to interrupt him now.

03:31:20.750 --> 03:31:41.610
You are too hasty, sir," she cried. You forget that I have made no answer. Let me do it without further loss of time. Accept my thanks for the compliment you are paying me. I am very sensible of the honour of your proposals, but it is impossible for me to do otherwise than to decline them.

03:31:43.030 --> 03:32:09.670
I am not now to learn, replied Mr. Collins, with a formal wave of the hand, that it is usual with young ladies to reject the addresses of the man whom they secretly mean to accept, when he applies for their favour, and that sometimes the refusal is repeated a second or even a third time. I am therefore by no means discouraged by what you have just said, and shall hope to lead you to the altar ere long.

03:32:11.610 --> 03:32:31.330
Upon my word, sir," cried Elizabeth,--"your hope is a rather extraordinary one after my declaration. I do assure you that I am not one of those young ladies, if such young ladies there are, who are so daring as to risk their happiness on the chance of being asked a second time.

03:32:31.330 --> 03:32:50.330
I am perfectly serious in my refusal. You could not make me happy, and I am convinced that I am the last woman in the world who could make you so. Nay, were your friend Lady Catherine to know me, I am persuaded she would find me in every respect ill-qualified for the situation."

03:32:51.510 --> 03:33:13.650
Were it certain that Lady Catherine would think so," said Mr. Collins very gravely,--"but I cannot imagine that her ladyship would at all disapprove of you, and you may be certain when I have the honour of seeing her again, I shall speak in the very highest terms of your modesty, economy, and other amiable qualifications.

03:33:15.410 --> 03:33:33.150
Indeed, Mr. Collins, all praise of me will be unnecessary. You must give me leave to judge for myself, and pay me the compliment of believing what I say. I wish you very happy and very rich, and by refusing your hand do all in my power to prevent your being otherwise.

03:33:33.150 --> 03:33:46.390
In making me the offer, you must have satisfied the delicacy of your feelings with regard to my family, and may take possession of long-born estate whenever it falls, without any self-reproach.

03:33:47.590 --> 03:33:59.270
This matter may be considered, therefore, as finally settled." And rising as she thus spoke, she would have quitted the room, had Mr. Collins not thus addressed her.

03:34:00.370 --> 03:34:27.610
When I do myself the honour of speaking to you next on the subject, I shall hope to receive a more favourable answer than you have now given me, though I am far from accusing you of cruelty at present, because I know it to be the established custom of your sex to reject a man on the first application, and perhaps you have even now said as much to encourage my suit as would be consistent with the true delicacy of the female character.

03:34:28.850 --> 03:34:45.550
Really, Mr. Collins," cried Elizabeth with some warmth, you puzzle me exceedingly. If what I have hitherto said can appear to you in the form of encouragement, I know not how to express my refusal in such a way as to convince you of its being one.

03:34:46.870 --> 03:35:07.510
You must give me leave to flatter myself, my dear cousin, that your refusal of my addresses is merely words of course. My reasons for believing it are briefly these. It does not appear to me that my hand is unworthy your acceptance, or that the establishment I can offer would be any other than highly desirable.

03:35:08.390 --> 03:35:27.750
My situation in life, my connections with the family of de Bourgh, and my relationship to your own are circumstances highly in my favour, and you should take it into further consideration that in spite of your manifold attractions, it is by no means certain that another offer of marriage may ever be made you.

03:35:27.750 --> 03:35:50.970
Your portion is unhappily so small that it will in all likelihood undo the effects of your loveliness and amiable qualifications. As I must therefore conclude that you are not serious in your rejection of me, I shall choose to attribute it to your wish of increasing my love by suspense, according to the usual practice of elegant females.

03:35:52.150 --> 03:36:05.090
I do assure you, sir, that I have no pretensions whatever to that kind of elegance which consists in tormenting a respectable man. I would rather be paid the compliment of being believed sincere.

03:36:06.150 --> 03:36:28.210
I thank you again and again for the honour you have done me in your proposals, but to accept them is absolutely impossible. My feelings in every respect forbid it. Can I speak plainer? Do not consider me now as an elegant female, intending to plague you, but as a rational creature speaking the truth from her heart.

03:36:29.270 --> 03:36:45.230
You are uniformly charming, cried he, with an air of awkward gallantry, and I am persuaded that when sanctioned by the express authority of both your excellent parents, my proposals will not fail of being acceptable.

03:36:46.690 --> 03:37:14.690
To such perseverance in willful self-deception Elizabeth would make no reply, and immediately and in silence withdrew, determined, if he persisted in considering her repeated refusals as flattering encouragement, to apply to her father, whose negative might be uttered in such a manner as to be decisive, and whose behaviour at least could not be mistaken for the affectation and coquetry of an elegant female.

03:37:48.410 --> 03:37:49.010
XX.

03:37:51.310 --> 03:37:56.410
Mr. Collins was not left long to the silent contemplation of his successful love.

03:37:56.410 --> 03:38:01.750
For Mrs. Bennet, having dawdled about in the vestibule to watch for the end of the conference,

03:38:02.610 --> 03:38:08.390
no sooner saw Elizabeth open the door, and with quick steps pass her towards the staircase,

03:38:09.070 --> 03:38:15.630
than she entered the breakfast-room, and congratulated both him and herself in warm terms on the

03:38:15.630 --> 03:38:18.410
happy prospect of their nearer connexion.

03:38:19.590 --> 03:38:25.210
Mr. Collins received and returned these felicitations with equal pleasure, and then proceeded to

03:38:25.210 --> 03:38:30.030
relate the particulars of their interview, with the result of which he trusted he had

03:38:30.030 --> 03:38:35.950
every reason to be satisfied, since the refusal which his cousin had steadfastly given him

03:38:35.950 --> 03:38:41.930
would naturally flow from her bashful modesty and the genuine delicacy of her character.

03:38:44.150 --> 03:38:47.350
This information, however, startled Mrs. Bennet.

03:38:48.150 --> 03:38:52.610
She would have been glad to be equally satisfied that her daughter had meant to encourage him

03:38:52.610 --> 03:38:58.070
by protesting against his proposals, but she dared not to believe it, and she could

03:38:58.070 --> 03:38:59.470
not help saying so.

03:39:00.210 --> 03:39:03.830
"'But depend upon it, Mr. Collins,' she added,

03:39:04.510 --> 03:39:06.670
"'that Lizzie shall be brought to reason.

03:39:07.430 --> 03:39:10.230
I will speak to her about it myself directly.

03:39:11.010 --> 03:39:17.270
She is a very headstrong, foolish girl, and does not know her own interest, but I will

03:39:17.270 --> 03:39:19.710
make her know it.'

03:39:20.230 --> 03:39:24.710
"'Pardon me for interrupting you, madam,' cried Mr. Collins.

03:39:25.550 --> 03:39:30.650
But if she is really headstrong and foolish, I know not whether she would altogether be

03:39:30.650 --> 03:39:36.890
a very desirable wife to a man in my situation who naturally looks for happiness in the marriage

03:39:36.890 --> 03:39:37.350
state.

03:39:38.390 --> 03:39:44.630
If, therefore, she actually persists in rejecting my suit, perhaps it were better not to force

03:39:44.630 --> 03:39:51.950
accepting me, because, if liable to such defects of temper, she could not contribute much to

03:39:51.950 --> 03:39:52.830
my felicity.'

03:39:54.270 --> 03:39:59.570
"'Sir, you quite misunderstand me,' said Mrs. Bennet, alarmed.

03:40:00.470 --> 03:40:03.610
"'Lizzie is only headstrong in such matters as these.

03:40:04.010 --> 03:40:07.470
In everything else she is as good-natured a girl as ever lived.

03:40:08.690 --> 03:40:14.510
"'I will go directly to Mr. Bennet, and we shall very soon settle it with her, I am sure.'

03:40:15.050 --> 03:40:21.070
She would not give him time to reply, but hurrying instantly to her husband, called

03:40:21.070 --> 03:40:22.850
out as she entered the library,

03:40:23.890 --> 03:40:26.870
"'Oh, Mr. Bennet, you are wanted immediately.

03:40:27.450 --> 03:40:29.270
We are all in an uproar.

03:40:29.890 --> 03:40:35.370
You must come and make Lizzie marry Mr. Collins, for she vows she will not have him, and if

03:40:35.370 --> 03:40:40.790
you do not make haste, he will change his mind and not have her.'

03:40:40.790 --> 03:40:46.130
Mr. Bennet raised his eyes from his book as she entered, and fixed them on her face with

03:40:46.130 --> 03:40:51.110
a calm unconcern, which was not in the least altered by her communication.

03:40:52.730 --> 03:40:59.130
"'I have not the pleasure of understanding you,' said he, when she had finished her speech.

03:40:59.790 --> 03:41:01.330
"'Of what are you talking?'

03:41:02.550 --> 03:41:04.710
"'Of Mr. Collins and Lizzie.

03:41:05.210 --> 03:41:10.330
Lizzie declares she will not have Mr. Collins, and Mr. Collins begins to say that he will

03:41:10.330 --> 03:41:11.750
not have Lizzie.'

03:41:12.630 --> 03:41:14.930
"'And what am I to do on this occasion?

03:41:15.470 --> 03:41:17.250
It seems a hopeless business.'

03:41:18.810 --> 03:41:20.770
"'Speak to Lizzie about it yourself.

03:41:21.430 --> 03:41:24.870
Tell her that you insist upon her marrying him.'

03:41:24.870 --> 03:41:27.010
"'Let her be called down.

03:41:27.370 --> 03:41:29.010
She shall hear my opinion.'

03:41:30.590 --> 03:41:35.330
Mrs. Bennet rang the bell, and Miss Elizabeth was summoned to the library.

03:41:36.970 --> 03:41:40.770
"'Come here, child,' cried her father, as she appeared.

03:41:41.630 --> 03:41:44.350
"'I have sent for you on an affair of importance.

03:41:45.270 --> 03:41:48.770
I understand that Mr. Collins has made you an offer of marriage.

03:41:49.370 --> 03:41:51.390
Is it true?'

03:41:52.170 --> 03:41:54.190
Elizabeth replied that it was.

03:41:55.730 --> 03:42:00.370
"'Very well, and this offer of marriage you have refused?'

03:42:00.370 --> 03:42:03.290
"'I have, sir.'

03:42:03.290 --> 03:42:06.730
"'Very well, we now come to the point.

03:42:07.390 --> 03:42:10.410
Your mother insists upon your accepting it.

03:42:10.550 --> 03:42:12.590
Is it not so, Mrs. Bennet?'

03:42:13.190 --> 03:42:16.550
"'Yes, or I will never see her again.'

03:42:17.350 --> 03:42:20.850
"'An unhappy alternative is before you, Elizabeth.

03:42:21.770 --> 03:42:25.630
"'From this day you must be a stranger to one of your parents.

03:42:26.410 --> 03:42:35.150
Your mother will never see you again if you do not marry Mr. Collins, and I will never see you again if you do.'

03:42:35.750 --> 03:42:39.530
Elizabeth could not but smile at such a conclusion of such a beginning.

03:42:40.410 --> 03:42:48.150
But Mrs. Bennet, who had persuaded herself that her husband regarded the affair as she wished, was excessively disappointed.

03:42:49.270 --> 03:42:52.850
"'What do you mean, Mr. Bennet, by talking in this way?

03:42:53.070 --> 03:42:57.250
You promised me to insist upon her marrying him.'

03:42:57.250 --> 03:42:59.990
"'My dear,' replied her husband,

03:43:00.650 --> 03:43:03.830
"'I have two small favors to request.

03:43:04.670 --> 03:43:12.670
First, that you will allow me the free use of my understanding on the present occasion, and secondly, of my room.

03:43:12.670 --> 03:43:18.670
I shall be glad to have the library to myself as soon as may be.'

03:43:20.170 --> 03:43:26.950
Not yet, however, in spite of her disappointment in her husband, did Mrs. Bennet give up the point.

03:43:27.690 --> 03:43:33.470
She talked to Elizabeth again and again, coaxed and threatened her by turns.

03:43:33.470 --> 03:43:42.410
She endeavoured to secure Jane in her interest, but Jane, with all possible mildness, declined interfering,

03:43:43.370 --> 03:43:50.850
and Elizabeth, sometimes with real earnestness, and sometimes with playful gaiety, replied to her attacks.

03:43:52.210 --> 03:43:56.730
Though her manner varied, however, her determination never did.

03:43:58.270 --> 03:44:03.550
Mr. Collins, meanwhile, was meditating in solitude on what had passed.

03:44:04.410 --> 03:44:09.570
He thought too well of himself to comprehend on what motive his cousin could refuse him,

03:44:10.050 --> 03:44:14.410
and though his pride was hurt, he suffered in no other way.

03:44:15.490 --> 03:44:23.610
His regard for her was quite imaginary, and the possibility of her deserving her mother's reproach prevented his feeling any regret.

03:44:25.730 --> 03:44:31.250
While the family were in this confusion, Charlotte Lucas came to spend the day with them.

03:44:31.750 --> 03:44:37.930
She was met in the vestibule by Lydia, who, flying to her, cried in a half whisper,

03:44:38.770 --> 03:44:45.310
"'I am glad you are come, for there is such fun here. What do you think has happened this morning?

03:44:45.990 --> 03:44:49.750
Mr. Collins has made an offer to Lizzy, and she will not have him.'

03:44:51.210 --> 03:44:57.210
Charlotte had hardly time to answer before they were joined by Kitty, who came to tell the same news,

03:44:57.990 --> 03:45:05.470
and no sooner had they entered the breakfast-room, where Mrs. Bennet was alone, than she likewise began on the subject,

03:45:06.410 --> 03:45:13.930
calling on Miss Lucas for her compassion, and entreating her to persuade her friend Lizzy to comply with the wishes of all her family.

03:45:14.850 --> 03:45:19.710
Pray do, my dear Miss Lucas," she added in a melancholy tone,

03:45:20.250 --> 03:45:29.930
"'for nobody is on my side, nobody takes part with me. I am cruelly used, nobody feels for my poor nerves.'"

03:45:31.010 --> 03:45:34.670
Charlotte's reply was spared by the entrance of Jane and Elizabeth.

03:45:36.290 --> 03:45:42.410
"'Aye, there she comes,' continued Mrs. Bennet, looking as unconcerned as may be,

03:45:42.730 --> 03:45:48.230
and caring no more for us than if we were at York, provided she can have her own way.

03:45:49.010 --> 03:45:56.670
But I tell you what, Miss Lizzy, if you take it into your head to go on refusing every offer of marriage in this way,

03:45:56.950 --> 03:46:03.710
you will never get a husband at all. And I am sure I do not know who is to maintain you when your father is dead.

03:46:03.710 --> 03:46:11.210
I shall not be able to keep you, and so I warn you. I have done with you from this very day.

03:46:12.010 --> 03:46:19.310
I told you in the library, you know, that I should never speak to you again, and you will find me as good as my word.

03:46:20.110 --> 03:46:27.450
I have no pleasure in talking to untutiful children. Not that I have much pleasure, indeed, in talking to anybody.

03:46:27.450 --> 03:46:34.750
People who suffer as I do from nervous complaints can have no great inclination for talking.

03:46:35.910 --> 03:46:44.450
Nobody can tell what I suffer. But it is always so. Those who do not complain are never pitied.'"

03:46:46.170 --> 03:46:55.370
Her daughters listened in silence to this effusion, sensible that any attempt to reason with or soothe her would only increase the irritation.

03:46:56.070 --> 03:47:06.010
She talked on, therefore, without interruption from any of them, till they were joined by Mr. Collins, who entered with an air more stately than usual.

03:47:07.130 --> 03:47:10.510
And on perceiving whom, she said to the girls,

03:47:11.170 --> 03:47:20.370
"'Now I do insist upon it that you, all of you, hold your tongues, and let Mr. Collins and me have a little conversation together.'"

03:47:21.730 --> 03:47:30.890
Elizabeth passed quietly out of the room. Jane and Kitty followed. But Lydia stood her ground, determined to hear all she could.

03:47:31.670 --> 03:47:48.730
And Charlotte, detained first by the facility of Mr. Collins, whose inquiries after herself and all her family were very minute, and then, by a little curiosity, satisfied herself with walking to the window and pretending not to hear.

03:47:50.770 --> 03:47:55.830
In a doleful voice Mrs. Bennet thus began the projected conversation.

03:47:56.410 --> 03:47:59.590
"'Oh! Mr. Collins!'

03:48:00.550 --> 03:48:03.710
"'My dear madam,' replied he.

03:48:04.370 --> 03:48:08.630
"'Let us be forever silent on this point.'

03:48:08.630 --> 03:48:15.150
"'Far be it from me,' he presently continued, in a voice that marked his displeasure.

03:48:15.730 --> 03:48:18.430
"'To resent the behaviour of your daughter.

03:48:19.930 --> 03:48:36.890
"'Resignation to inevitable evils is the duty of us all, the peculiar duty of a young man who has been so fortunate as I have been, in early preferment. And I trust I am resigned.'

03:48:36.890 --> 03:48:56.610
"'Perhaps the not less so, from feeling a doubt of my positive happiness, had my fair cousin honoured me with her hand. For I have often observed that resignation is never so perfect as when the blessing denied begins to lose somewhat of its value in our estimation.

03:48:56.610 --> 03:49:18.210
"'You will not, I hope, consider me as showing any disrespect to your family, my dear madam, by thus withdrawing my pretensions to your daughter's favour, without having paid yourself and Mr. Bennet the compliment of requesting you to interpose your authority in my behalf.

03:49:19.510 --> 03:49:35.110
"'My conduct may, I fear, be objectionable in having accepted my dismissal from your daughter's lips instead of your own. But we are all liable to error. I have certainly meant well through the whole affair.

03:49:35.110 --> 03:49:55.410
"'My object has been to secure an amiable companion for myself, with due consideration for the advantage of all your family. And if my manner has been at all reprehensible, I herebeg leave to apologise.'

03:50:26.870 --> 03:50:40.470
The discussion of Mr. Colin's offer was now nearly at an end, and Elizabeth had only to suffer from the uncomfortable feelings necessarily attending it, and occasionally from some peevish illusion of her mother.

03:50:42.450 --> 03:51:07.190
As for the gentleman himself, his feelings were chiefly expressed, not by embarrassment or dejection, or by trying to avoid her, but by stiffness of manner and resentful silence. He scarcely ever spoke to her, and the assiduous attentions which he had been so sensible of himself were transferred for the rest of the day to Miss Lucas.

03:51:09.090 --> 03:51:15.610
Whose civility in listening to him was a seasonable relief to them all, and especially to her friend.

03:51:17.970 --> 03:51:27.510
The morrow produced no abatement of Mrs. Bennet's ill-humour or ill-health. Mr. Collins was also in the same state of angry pride.

03:51:29.750 --> 03:51:42.650
Elizabeth had hoped that his resentment might shorten his visit, but his plan did not appear in the least affected by it. He was always to have gone on Saturday, and to Saturday he still meant to stay.

03:51:44.470 --> 03:52:05.410
After breakfast, the girls walked to Meryton to inquire if Mr. Wickham were returned, and to lament over his absence from the Netherfield ball. He joined them on their entering the town, and attended them to their aunts, where his regret and vexation, and the concern of everybody, were well talked over.

03:52:06.770 --> 03:52:13.830
To Elizabeth, however, he voluntarily acknowledged that the necessity of his absence had been self-imposed.

03:52:16.510 --> 03:52:36.210
I found, said he, as the time drew near, that I had better not meet Mr. Darcy, that to be in the same room, the same party with him, for so many hours together, might be more than I could bear, and that scenes might arise unpleasant to more than myself.

03:52:38.270 --> 03:52:55.830
She highly approved his forbearance, and they had leisure for a full discussion of it, and for all the commendation which they civilly bestowed on each other, as Wickham and another officer walked back with them to Longbourn, and during the walk he particularly attended to her.

03:52:57.350 --> 03:53:09.290
His accompanying them was a double advantage. She felt all the compliment it offered to herself, and it was most acceptable, as an occasion of introducing him to her father and mother.

03:53:11.510 --> 03:53:36.610
Soon after their return, a letter was delivered to Miss Bennet. It came from Netherfield, and was opened immediately. The envelope contained a sheet of elegant little hot-pressed paper, well covered with a lady's fair flowing hand. And Elizabeth saw her sister's countenance change as she read it, and saw her dwelling intently on some particular passages.

03:53:38.330 --> 03:54:02.610
Jane recollected herself soon, and putting the letter away, tried to join with her usual cheerfulness in the general conversation. But Elizabeth felt an anxiety on the subject which drew off her attention even from Wickham. And no sooner had he and his companion taken leave, than a glance from Jane invited her to follow her upstairs.

03:54:04.890 --> 03:54:11.110
When they had gained their own room, Jane, taking out her letter, said,

03:54:12.010 --> 03:54:29.830
This is from Caroline Bingley. What it contains has surprised me a good deal. The whole party have left Netherfield by this time, and are on their way to town. And without any intention of coming back again. You shall hear what she says.

03:54:32.250 --> 03:54:49.050
She then read the first sentence aloud, which comprised the information of their having just resolved to follow their brother to town directly, and of their meaning to dine that day in Grosvenor Street, where Mr. Hurst had a house. The next was in these words,

03:54:50.190 --> 03:55:16.850
I do not pretend to regret anything I shall leave in Hertfordshire, except your society, my dearest friend. But we will hope, at some future period, to enjoy many returns of that delightful intercourse we have known, and in the meanwhile may lessen the pain of separation by a very frequent and most unreserved correspondence. I depend on you for that.

03:55:19.470 --> 03:55:45.570
To these high-flown expressions Elizabeth listened with all the insensibility of distrust, and though the suddenness of their removal surprised her, she saw nothing in it really to lament. It was not to be supposed that their absence from Netherfield would prevent Mr. Bingley's being there. And as to the loss of their society, she was persuaded that Jane must soon cease to regard it in the enjoyment of his.

03:55:48.130 --> 03:56:15.550
It is unlucky, said she, after a short pause, that you should not be able to see your friends before they leave the country. But may we not hope that the period of future happiness, to which Miss Bingley looks forward, may arrive earlier than she is aware, and that the delightful intercourse you have known as friends will be renewed with yet greater satisfaction as sisters. Mr. Bingley will not be detained in London by the time he arrives.

03:56:19.210 --> 03:56:25.490
Caroline decidedly says that none of the party will return into Hertfordshire this winter. I will read it to you.

03:56:45.570 --> 03:57:08.030
We have determined on following him thither, that he may not be obliged to spend his vacant hours in a comfortless hotel. Many of my acquaintance are already there for the winter. I wish I could hear that you, my dearest friend, had any intention of making one in the crowd. But of that I despair.

03:57:09.270 --> 03:57:23.890
I sincerely hope your Christmas in Hertfordshire may abound in the gaieties which that season generally brings, and that your beau will be so numerous as to prevent your feeling the loss of the three of whom we shall deprive you.

03:57:25.490 --> 03:57:32.290
It is evident by this, added Jane, that he comes back no more this winter.

03:57:33.590 --> 03:57:37.490
It is only evident that Miss Bingley does not mean he should.

03:57:39.090 --> 03:57:55.230
Why will you think so? It must be his own doing. He is his own master. But you do not know all. I will read you the passage which particularly hurts me. I will have no reserves from you.

03:57:57.190 --> 03:58:23.670
Mr. Darcy is impatient to see his sister, and to confess the truth we are scarcely less eager to meet her again. I really do not think Georgiana Darcy has her equal for beauty, elegance and accomplishments, and the affection she inspires in Louisa and myself is heightened into something still more interesting, from the hope we dare to entertain of her being hereafter our sister.

03:58:24.510 --> 03:58:35.810
I do not know whether I ever before mentioned to you my feelings on this subject, but I will not leave the country without confiding them, and I trust you will not esteem them unreasonable.

03:58:36.990 --> 03:58:59.010
My brother greatly admires her already. He will have frequent opportunity now of seeing her on the most intimate footing. Her relations all wish the connection as much as his own, and a sister's partiality is not misleading me, I think, when I call Charles most capable of engaging any woman's heart.

03:58:59.750 --> 03:59:13.230
With all these circumstances to favour an attachment, and nothing to prevent it, am I wrong, my dearest Jane, in indulging the hope of an event which will secure the happiness of so many?

03:59:14.970 --> 03:59:20.730
What think you of this sentence, my dear Lizzie?" said Jane, as she finished it.

03:59:20.730 --> 03:59:40.370
Is it not clear enough? Does it not expressly declare that Caroline neither expects nor wishes me to be her sister, that she is perfectly convinced of her brother's indifference, and that if she suspects the nature of my feelings for him, she means, most kindly, to put me on my guard?

03:59:41.610 --> 03:59:44.410
Can there be any other opinion on the subject?

03:59:45.950 --> 03:59:51.290
Yes, there can, for mine is totally different. Will you hear it?

03:59:52.350 --> 03:59:53.290
Most willingly.

03:59:55.030 --> 04:00:10.450
You shall have it in a few words. Miss Bingley sees that her brother is in love with you, and wants him to marry Miss Darcy. She follows him to town in the hope of keeping him there, and tries to persuade you that he does not care about you.

04:00:11.750 --> 04:00:13.150
Jane shook her head.

04:00:14.590 --> 04:00:37.990
Indeed, Jane, you ought to believe me. No one who has ever seen you together can doubt his affection. Miss Bingley, I am sure, cannot. She is not such a simpleton. Could she have seen half as much love in Mr. Darcy for herself? She would have ordered her wedding clothes. But the case is this. We are not rich enough or grand enough for them.

04:00:37.990 --> 04:00:54.850
And she is the more anxious to get Miss Darcy for her brother, from the notion that when there has been one intermarriage, she may have less trouble in achieving a second, in which there is certainly some ingenuity, and I dare say it would succeed if Mr. Berg were out of the way.

04:00:56.730 --> 04:01:19.310
But, my dearest Jane, you cannot seriously imagine that because Miss Bingley tells you her brother greatly admires Miss Darcy, he is in the smallest degree less sensible of your merit than when he took leave of you on Tuesday, or that it would be in her power to persuade him that instead of being in love with you, he is very much in love with her friend.

04:01:21.250 --> 04:01:42.310
If we thought alike of Miss Bingley," replied Jane,--"her representation of all this might make me quite easy. But I know the foundation is unjust. Caroline is incapable of willfully deceiving any one. And all that I can hope for in this case is that she is deceived herself."

04:01:43.810 --> 04:01:56.990
That is right. You could not have stated a more happy idea since you will not take comfort in mine. Believe her to be deceived by all means. You have now done your duty by her, and must fret no longer.

04:01:59.250 --> 04:02:09.910
But, my dearest sister, can I be happy, even supposing the best, in accepting a man whose sisters and friends are all wishing him to marry elsewhere?

04:02:12.350 --> 04:02:29.130
You must decide for yourself," said Elizabeth,--"and if, upon mature deliberation, you find that the misery of disobliging his two sisters is more than equivalent to the happiness of being his wife, I advise you by all means to refuse him."

04:02:31.430 --> 04:02:35.410
How can you talk so?" said Jane, faintly smiling.

04:02:37.310 --> 04:02:43.810
You must know that though I should be exceedingly grieved at their disapprobation, I could not hesitate.

04:02:45.210 --> 04:02:51.790
I did not think you would, and that being the case, I cannot consider your situation with much compassion.

04:02:54.130 --> 04:03:02.950
But if he returns no more this winter, my choice will ever be required. A thousand things may arise in six months.

04:03:04.610 --> 04:03:25.590
The idea of his returning no more Elizabeth treated with the utmost contempt. It appeared to her merely the suggestion of Caroline's interested wishes, and she could not for a moment suppose that those wishes, however openly or artfully spoken, could influence a young man so totally independent of every one.

04:03:28.110 --> 04:03:51.250
She represented to her sister as forcibly as possible what she felt on the subject, and had soon the pleasure of seeing its happy effect. Jane's temper was not desponding, and she was gradually led to hope, though the diffidence of affections sometimes overcame the hope, that Bingley would return to Netherfield and answer every wish of her heart.

04:03:52.910 --> 04:04:14.430
They agreed that Mrs. Bennet should only hear of the departure of the family, without being alarmed on the score of the gentleman's conduct. But even this partial communication gave her a great deal of concern, and she bewailed it as exceedingly unlucky that the ladies should happen to go away, just as they were all getting so intimate together.

04:04:15.810 --> 04:04:37.350
After lamenting it, however, at some length, she had the consolation of thinking Mr. Bingley would be soon down again, and soon dining at Longbourn. And the conclusion of all was the comfortable declaration, that though he had been invited only to a family dinner, she would take care to have two full courses.

04:04:46.910 --> 04:04:59.350
The Bennets were engaged to dine with the Lucas's, and again during the chief of the day was Miss Lucas so kind as to listen to Mr. Collins. Elizabeth took an opportunity of thanking her.

04:05:00.950 --> 04:05:16.190
"'It keeps him in good humour,' said she, "'and I am more obliged to you than I can express.' Charlotte assured her friend of her satisfaction in being useful, and that it amply repaid her for the little sacrifice of her time.

04:05:17.230 --> 04:05:44.770
This was very amiable, but Charlotte's kindness extended farther than Elizabeth had any conception of. Its object was nothing less than to secure her from any return of Mr. Collins' addresses by engaging them towards herself. Such was Miss Lucas's scheme. And appearances were so favourable, that when they parted at night she would have felt almost sure of success if he had not been leaving Hertfordshire so very soon.

04:05:45.590 --> 04:06:00.590
But here she did an injustice to the fire and independence of his character, for it led him to escape out of Longbourn House the next morning with admirable slyness, and hasten to Lucas's lodge to throw himself at her feet.

04:06:01.290 --> 04:06:27.370
He was anxious to avoid the notice of his cousins, from a conviction that if they saw him depart they could not fail to conjecture his design, and he was not willing to have the attempt known till its success could be known likewise, for though feeling almost secure, and with reason, for Charlotte had been tolerably encouraging, he was comparatively diffident since the adventure of Wednesday.

04:06:28.430 --> 04:06:47.790
His reception, however, was of the most flattering kind. Miss Lucas perceived him from an upper window as he walked towards the house, and instantly set out to meet him accidentally in the lane. But little had she dared to hope that so much love and eloquence awaited her there.

04:06:49.210 --> 04:07:12.810
In as short a time as Mr. Collins's long speeches would allow, everything was settled between them to the satisfaction of both, and as they entered the house he earnestly entreated her to name the day that was to make him the happiest of men. And though such a solicitation must be waived for the present, the lady felt no inclination to trifle with his happiness.

04:07:12.810 --> 04:07:33.430
The stupidity with which he was favoured, by nature, must guard his courtship from any charm that could make a woman wish for its continuance. And Miss Lucas, who accepted him solely from the pure and disinterested desire of an establishment, cared not how soon that establishment were gained.

04:07:35.830 --> 04:07:57.150
Sir William and Lady Lucas were speedily applied to for their consent, and it was bestowed with a most joyful alacrity. Mr. Collins's present circumstances made it a most eligible match for their daughter, to whom they could give little fortune, and his prospects of future wealth were exceedingly fair.

04:07:58.350 --> 04:08:23.650
Lady Lucas began directly to calculate, with more interest than the matter had ever excited before, how many years longer Mr. Bennet was likely to live. And Sir William gave it as his decided opinion, that whenever Mr. Collins should be in possession of the long-born estate, it would be highly expedient that both he and his wife should make their appearance at St. James.

04:08:24.670 --> 04:08:42.090
The whole family, in short, were properly overjoyed on the occasion. The younger girls formed hopes of coming out a year or two sooner than they might otherwise have done, and the boys were relieved from their apprehension of Charlotte's dying an old maid.

04:08:43.710 --> 04:09:10.690
Charlotte herself was tolerably composed. She had gained her point, and had time to consider of it. Her reflections were in general satisfactory. Mr. Collins, to be sure, was neither sensible nor agreeable. His society was irksome, and his attachment to her must be imaginary. But still he would be her husband.

04:09:12.090 --> 04:09:32.350
Without thinking highly either of men or matrimony, marriage had always been her object. It was the only honourable provision for well-educated young women of small fortune. And however uncertain of giving happiness, must be their pleasantest preservative from want.

04:09:35.070 --> 04:09:56.330
This preservative she had now obtained, and at the age of twenty-seven, without having ever been handsome, she felt all the good luck of it. The least agreeable circumstance in the business was the surprise it must occasion to Elizabeth Bennet, whose friendship she valued beyond that of any other person.

04:09:57.790 --> 04:10:23.010
Elizabeth would wonder, and probably would blame her. And though her resolution was not to be shaken, her feelings must be hurt by such disapprobation. She resolved to give her the information herself, and therefore charge Mr. Collins, when he returned to Longbourn to dinner, to drop no hint of what had passed before any of the family.

04:10:24.130 --> 04:10:50.110
A promise of secrecy was of course very dutifully given, but it could not be kept without difficulty, for the curiosity excited by his long absence burst forth in such very direct questions on his return as required some ingenuity to evade. And he was at the same time exercising great self-denial, for he was longing to publish his prosperous love.

04:10:52.310 --> 04:11:15.770
As he was to begin his journey too early on the morrow to see any of the family, the ceremony of leave-taking was performed when the ladies moved for the night. And Mrs. Bennet, with great politeness and cordiality, said how happy they should be to see him at Longbourn again, whenever his other engagements might allow him to visit them.

04:11:17.610 --> 04:11:34.770
"'My dear madam,' he replied, "'this invitation is particularly gratifying, because it is what I have been hoping to receive, and you may be very certain that I shall avail myself of it as soon as possible.'"

04:11:34.770 --> 04:11:44.710
They were all astonished, and Mr. Bennet, who could by no means wish for so speedy a return, immediately said,

04:11:46.110 --> 04:11:56.450
"'But is there not danger of Lady Catherine's disapprobation here, my good sir? You had better neglect your relations than run the risk of offending your patroness.'

04:11:57.450 --> 04:12:12.990
"'My dear sir,' replied Mr. Collins, "'I am particularly obliged to you for this friendly caution, and you may depend upon my not taking so material a step without her ladyship's concurrence.

04:12:14.510 --> 04:12:33.990
"'You cannot be too much on your guard. Risk anything rather than her displeasure. And if you find it likely to be raised by your coming to us again, which I should think exceedingly probable, stay quietly at home, and be satisfied that we shall take no offence.'

04:12:34.870 --> 04:12:53.290
"'Believe me, my dear sir, my gratitude is warmly excited by such affectionate attention, and depend upon it you will speedily receive from me a letter of thanks for this, as well as for every other mark of your regard during my stay in Hertfordshire.

04:12:54.450 --> 04:13:08.290
"'As for my fair cousins, though my absence may not be long enough to render it necessary, I shall take the liberty of wishing them health and happiness, not accepting my cousin Elizabeth.'

04:13:10.690 --> 04:13:29.530
"'With proper civilities the ladies then withdrew, all of them equally surprised to find that he meditated a quick return. Mrs. Bennet wished to understand by it that he thought of paying his addresses to one of her younger girls, and Mary might have been prevailed on to accept him.

04:13:30.470 --> 04:13:51.250
"'She rated his abilities much higher than any of the others. There was a solidity in his reflections which often struck her. And though by no means so clever as herself, she thought that if encouraged to read and improve himself by such an example as hers, he might become a very agreeable companion.

04:13:53.170 --> 04:14:06.070
"'But on the following morning every hope of this kind was done away. Miss Lucas called soon after breakfast, and in a private conference with Elizabeth related the event of the day before.

04:14:07.970 --> 04:14:32.690
"'The possibility of Mr. Collins fancying himself in love with her friend had once occurred to Elizabeth within the last day or two. But that Charlotte could encourage him seemed almost as far from possibility as that she could encourage him herself. And her astonishment was consequently so great as to overcome at first the bounds of decorum. And she could not help crying out,

04:14:33.670 --> 04:14:38.990
"'Engage to Mr. Collins? My dear Charlotte! Impossible!'

04:14:39.690 --> 04:14:57.150
"'The steady countenance which Miss Lucas had commanded in telling her story gave way to a momentary confusion here on receiving so direct a reproach. Though, as it was no more than she expected, she soon regained her composure, and calmly replied,

04:14:58.170 --> 04:15:10.150
"'Why should you be surprised, my dear Eliza? Do you think it incredible that Mr. Collins should be able to procure any woman's good opinion because he was not so happy as to succeed with you?'

04:15:11.130 --> 04:15:28.210
"'But Elizabeth had now recollected herself, and making a strong effort for it, was able to assure her with tolerable firmness that the prospect of their relationship was highly grateful to her, and that she wished her all imaginable happiness.'

04:15:29.270 --> 04:15:32.270
"'I see what you are feeling,' replied Charlotte.

04:15:32.910 --> 04:15:58.190
"'You must be surprised, very much surprised, so lately as Mr. Collins was wishing to marry you. But when you have time to think it all over, I hope you will be satisfied with what I have done. I am not romantic, you know. I never was. I ask only a comfortable home. And considering Mr. Collins' character, connections, and situation in life,

04:15:58.210 --> 04:16:06.210
"'I am convinced that my chance of happiness with him is as fair as most people can boast on entering the marriage state.'

04:16:07.810 --> 04:16:11.210
"'Elizabeth quietly answered, "'Undoubtedly.'

04:16:11.930 --> 04:16:16.450
"'And after an awkward pause, they returned to the rest of the family.

04:16:17.630 --> 04:16:23.790
"'Charlotte did not stay much longer, and Elizabeth was then left to reflect on what she had heard.

04:16:24.530 --> 04:16:39.550
"'It was a long time before she became at all reconciled to the idea of so unsuitable a match. The strangeness of Mr. Collins making two offers of marriage within three days was nothing in comparison of his being now accepted.

04:16:39.550 --> 04:16:54.790
"'She had always felt that Charlotte's opinion of matrimony was not exactly like her own. But she could not have supposed it possible that when called into action she would have sacrificed every better feeling to worldly advantage.

04:16:55.910 --> 04:17:13.790
"'Charlotte, the wife of Mr. Collins, was a most humiliating picture. And to the pang of a friend disgracing herself and sunk in her esteem was added the distressing conviction that it was impossible for that friend to be tolerably happy in the lot she had chosen.'

04:17:39.810 --> 04:17:41.210
XXIII.

04:17:41.210 --> 04:17:46.150
Elizabeth was sitting with her mother and sisters, reflecting on what she had heard,

04:17:46.910 --> 04:17:52.330
and doubting whether she were authorized to mention it, when Sir William Lucas himself appeared,

04:17:53.010 --> 04:17:56.290
sent by his daughter to announce her engagement to the family.

04:17:57.210 --> 04:18:02.010
With many compliments to them, and much self-congratulation on the prospect of a

04:18:02.010 --> 04:18:08.110
connection between the houses, he unfolded the matter. To an audience not merely wondering,

04:18:08.110 --> 04:18:16.050
but incredulous. For Mrs. Bennet, with more perseverance than politeness, protested he must

04:18:16.050 --> 04:18:24.770
be entirely mistaken. And Lydia, always unguarded and often uncivil, boisterously exclaimed,

04:18:25.670 --> 04:18:32.110
Good Lord! Sir William, how can you tell such a story? Do you not know that Mr. Collins wants

04:18:32.110 --> 04:18:39.050
to marry Lizzie? Nothing less than the complacence of a courtier could have borne without anger such

04:18:39.050 --> 04:18:46.590
treatment. But Sir William's good breeding carried him through it all, and though he begged leave to

04:18:46.590 --> 04:18:52.630
be positive as to the truth of his information, he listened to all their impertinence with the

04:18:52.630 --> 04:19:00.050
most forbearing courtesy. Elizabeth, feeling it incumbent on her to relieve him from so

04:19:00.050 --> 04:19:07.430
unpleasant a situation, now put herself forward to confirm his account by mentioning her prior

04:19:07.430 --> 04:19:12.990
knowledge of it from Charlotte herself, and endeavoured to put a stop to the exclamations

04:19:12.990 --> 04:19:19.190
of her mother and sisters by the earnestness of her congratulations to Sir William, in which she

04:19:19.190 --> 04:19:25.790
was readily joined by Jane, and by making a variety of remarks on the happiness that might be expected

04:19:25.790 --> 04:19:32.170
from the match, the excellent character of Mr. Collins, and the convenient distance of Hunsford

04:19:32.170 --> 04:19:40.110
from London. Mrs. Bennet was in fact too much overpowered to say a great deal while Sir William

04:19:40.110 --> 04:19:47.570
remained, but no sooner had he left them than her feelings found a rapid vent. In the first place,

04:19:48.030 --> 04:19:53.970
she persisted in disbelieving the whole of the matter. Secondly, she was very sure that Mr.

04:19:53.970 --> 04:20:00.970
Collins had been taken in. Thirdly, she trusted that they would never be happy together. And

04:20:00.970 --> 04:20:08.830
fourthly, that the match might be broken off. Two inferences, however, were plainly deduced from the

04:20:08.830 --> 04:20:17.170
whole. One, that Elizabeth was the real cause of all the mischief, and the other, that she herself

04:20:17.170 --> 04:20:23.730
had been barbarously used by them all. And on these two points she principally dwelt during the rest

04:20:23.730 --> 04:20:31.870
of the day. Nothing could console and nothing appease her. Nor did that day wear out her

04:20:31.870 --> 04:20:38.630
resentment. A week collapsed before she could see Elizabeth without scolding her, a month passed

04:20:38.630 --> 04:20:44.350
away before she could speak to Sir William or Lady Lucas without being rude, and many months were

04:20:44.350 --> 04:20:50.710
gone before she could at all forgive their daughter. Mr. Bennet's emotions were much more

04:20:50.710 --> 04:20:56.650
tranquil on the occasion. And such as he did experience, he pronounced to be of a most agreeable

04:20:56.650 --> 04:21:03.990
sort. For it gratified him, he said, to discover that Charlotte Lucas, whom he had used to think

04:21:03.990 --> 04:21:09.990
tolerably sensible, was as foolish as his wife, and more foolish than his daughter.

04:21:12.330 --> 04:21:18.630
Jane confessed herself a little surprised at the match. But she said less of her astonishment

04:21:18.630 --> 04:21:21.990
than of her earnest desire for their happiness.

04:21:23.990 --> 04:21:31.590
Nor could Elizabeth persuade her to consider it as improbable. Kitty and Lydia were far from

04:21:31.590 --> 04:21:39.010
envying Miss Lucas, for Mr. Collins was only a clergyman. And it affected them in no other way

04:21:39.010 --> 04:21:46.290
than as a piece of news to spread at Meryton. Lady Lucas could not be insensible of triumph

04:21:46.290 --> 04:21:50.750
on being able to retort on Mrs. Bennet the comfort of having a daughter well married.

04:21:51.690 --> 04:21:56.210
And she called it long-born rather oftener than usual to say how happy she was,

04:21:57.410 --> 04:22:03.810
though Mrs. Bennet's sour looks and ill-natured remarks might have been enough to drive happiness

04:22:03.810 --> 04:22:12.280
away. Between Elizabeth and Charlotte there was a restraint which kept them mutually silent on the

04:22:12.280 --> 04:22:18.500
subject, and Elizabeth felt persuaded that no real confidence could ever subsist between them again.

04:22:19.780 --> 04:22:23.880
Her disappointment in Charlotte made her turn with fonder regard to her sister,

04:22:24.640 --> 04:22:29.760
of whose rectitude and delicacy she was sure her opinion could never be shaken,

04:22:30.480 --> 04:22:35.980
and for whose happiness she grew daily more anxious, as Bingley had now been gone a week,

04:22:36.540 --> 04:22:38.480
and nothing was heard of his return.

04:22:40.080 --> 04:22:45.900
Jane had sent Caroline an early answer to her letter, and was counting the days till she might

04:22:45.900 --> 04:22:52.800
reasonably hope to hear again. The promised letter of thanks for Mr. Collins arrived on Tuesday,

04:22:53.840 --> 04:22:59.620
addressed to their father, and written with all the solemnity of gratitude which a twelve months

04:22:59.620 --> 04:23:06.720
abode with the family might have prompted. After discharging his conscience on that head,

04:23:07.340 --> 04:23:11.640
he proceeded to inform them, with many rapturous expressions,

04:23:12.380 --> 04:23:17.060
of his happiness in having obtained the affection of their amiable neighbour Miss Lucas,

04:23:18.620 --> 04:23:24.920
and then explained that it was merely with the view of enjoying her society that he had been

04:23:24.920 --> 04:23:30.940
so ready to close with their kind wish of seeing him again at Longbourn, whither he hoped to be

04:23:30.940 --> 04:23:37.440
able to return on Monday fortnight, for Lady Catherine, he added, so heartily approved his

04:23:37.440 --> 04:23:44.060
marriage that she wished it to take place as soon as possible, which he trusted would be an

04:23:44.060 --> 04:23:50.320
unanswerable argument with his amiable Charlotte to name an early day for making him the happiest

04:23:50.320 --> 04:23:58.060
of men. Mr. Collins' return into Hertfordshire was no longer a matter of pleasure to Mrs. Bennet.

04:23:58.660 --> 04:24:06.300
On the contrary, she was as much disposed to complain of it as her husband. It was very strange

04:24:06.300 --> 04:24:12.640
that he should come to Longbourn instead of Lucas Lodge. It was also very inconvenient and

04:24:12.640 --> 04:24:20.160
exceedingly troublesome. She hated having visitors in the house while her health was so indifferent,

04:24:20.740 --> 04:24:25.360
and lovers were, of all people, the most disagreeable.

04:24:27.280 --> 04:24:30.260
Such were the gentle murmurs of Mrs. Bennet,

04:24:30.720 --> 04:24:35.920
and they gave way only to the greater distress of Mr. Bingley's continued absence.

04:24:38.060 --> 04:24:44.680
Neither Jane nor Elizabeth was comfortable on the subject. Day after day passed away without

04:24:44.680 --> 04:24:50.120
bringing any other tidings of him than the report, which shortly prevailed in Meryton,

04:24:50.680 --> 04:24:57.620
of his coming no more to Netherfield the whole winter, a report which highly incensed Mrs. Bennet

04:24:57.620 --> 04:25:02.480
and which she never failed to contradict as a most scandalous falsehood.

04:25:04.640 --> 04:25:08.140
Even Elizabeth began to fear not that Bingley was indifferent,

04:25:08.660 --> 04:25:12.260
but that his two sisters would be successful in keeping him away.

04:25:13.740 --> 04:25:18.100
Unwilling as she was to admit an idea so destructive to Jane's happiness,

04:25:18.820 --> 04:25:25.100
and so dishonourable to the stability of her lover, she could not prevent its frequently recurring.

04:25:26.560 --> 04:25:32.520
The united efforts of his two unfeeling sisters and of his overpowering friend,

04:25:33.600 --> 04:25:37.820
assisted by the attractions of Miss Darcy and the amusements of London,

04:25:38.720 --> 04:25:42.540
might be too much, she feared, for the strength of his attachment.

04:25:44.620 --> 04:25:51.560
As for Jane, her anxiety under this suspense was, of course, more painful than Elizabeth's.

04:25:53.580 --> 04:26:00.040
But whatever she felt she was desirous of concealing, and between herself and Elizabeth,

04:26:00.040 --> 04:26:07.600
therefore, the subject was never alluded to. But as no such delicacy restrained her mother,

04:26:08.240 --> 04:26:14.580
an hour seldom passed in which she did not talk of Bingley, express her impatience for his arrival,

04:26:15.180 --> 04:26:22.860
or even require Jane to confess that if he did not come back, she should think herself very ill used.

04:26:24.960 --> 04:26:31.180
It needed all Jane's steady mildness to bear these attacks with tolerable tranquillity.

04:26:32.760 --> 04:26:39.080
Mr. Collins returned most punctually on the Monday fortnight, but his reception at Longbourn was not

04:26:39.080 --> 04:26:46.060
so gracious as it had been on his first introduction. He was too happy, however, to need

04:26:46.060 --> 04:26:52.740
much attention, and luckily for the others, the business of love-making relieved them from a

04:26:52.740 --> 04:27:00.260
great deal of his company. The chief of every day was spent by him at Lucas' Lodge, and he

04:27:00.260 --> 04:27:05.560
sometimes returned to Longbourn only in time to make an apology for his absence before the family

04:27:05.560 --> 04:27:14.480
went to bed. Mrs. Bennet was really in a most pitiable state. The very mention of anything

04:27:14.480 --> 04:27:21.200
concerning the match threw her into an agony of ill-humour, and wherever she went she was

04:27:21.200 --> 04:27:30.080
of hearing it talked of. The sight of Miss Lucas was odious to her. As her successor in that house,

04:27:30.920 --> 04:27:38.000
she regarded her with jealous abhorrence. Whenever Charlotte came to see them, she concluded

04:27:38.000 --> 04:27:44.660
her to be anticipating the hour of possession, and whenever she spoke in a low voice to Mr. Collins,

04:27:45.540 --> 04:27:48.620
was convinced that they were talking of the Longbourn estate,

04:27:49.180 --> 04:27:54.820
and resolving to turn herself and her daughters out of the house as soon as Mr. Bennet was dead.

04:27:56.120 --> 04:27:59.140
She complained bitterly of all this to her husband.

04:28:00.960 --> 04:28:08.200
Indeed, Mr. Bennet, said she, it is very hard to think that Charlotte Lucas should ever be

04:28:08.200 --> 04:28:15.020
mistress of this house, that I should be forced to make way for her, and live to see her take my

04:28:15.020 --> 04:28:23.380
place in it. My dear, do not give way to such gloomy thoughts. Let us hope for better things.

04:28:24.540 --> 04:28:28.840
Let us flatter ourselves that I may be the survivor.

04:28:30.340 --> 04:28:37.500
This was not very consoling to Mrs. Bennet, and therefore, instead of making any answer,

04:28:38.280 --> 04:28:44.260
she went on as before. I cannot bear to think that they should have all this estate.

04:28:45.020 --> 04:28:48.200
If it was not for the entail, I should not mind it.

04:28:49.400 --> 04:28:55.420
What should you not mind? I should not mind anything at all.

04:28:57.860 --> 04:29:02.040
Let us be thankful that you are preserved from a state of such insensibility.

04:29:03.700 --> 04:29:10.420
I can never be thankful, Mr. Bennet, for anything about the entail. How anyone could have the

04:29:10.420 --> 04:29:15.340
conscience to entail away an estate from one's own daughters I cannot understand,

04:29:15.800 --> 04:29:22.000
and all for the sake of Mr. Collins, too. Why should he have it more than anybody else?

04:29:23.120 --> 04:29:28.500
I leave it to yourself to determine, said Mr. Bennet.

04:29:38.620 --> 04:29:42.640
Miss Bingley's letter arrived, and put an end to doubt.

04:29:44.140 --> 04:29:49.300
The very first sentence conveyed the assurance of their all being settled in London for the winter,

04:29:50.180 --> 04:29:55.420
and concluded with her brother's regret at not having had time to pay his respects to his

04:29:55.420 --> 04:30:03.140
friends in Hertfordshire before he left the country. Hope was over, entirely over,

04:30:03.960 --> 04:30:10.580
and when Jane could attend to the rest of the letter, she found little, except the professed

04:30:10.580 --> 04:30:17.860
affection of the writer, that could give her any comfort. Miss Darcy's praise occupied the

04:30:17.860 --> 04:30:24.620
chief of it. Her many attractions were again dwelt on, and Caroline boasted joyfully of

04:30:24.620 --> 04:30:30.080
their increasing intimacy, and ventured to predict the accomplishment of the wishes which

04:30:30.080 --> 04:30:36.960
had been unfolded in her former letter. She wrote also with great pleasure of her brother's being

04:30:36.960 --> 04:30:42.780
an inmate of Mr. Darcy's house, and mentioned with raptures some plans of the latter with

04:30:42.780 --> 04:30:50.820
regard to new furniture. Elizabeth, to whom Jane very soon communicated the chief of all this,

04:30:51.460 --> 04:30:58.300
heard it in silent indignation. Her heart was divided between concern for her sister and

04:30:58.300 --> 04:31:04.780
resentment against all the others. To Caroline's assertion of her brother's being partial to Miss

04:31:04.780 --> 04:31:12.660
Darcy, she paid no credit. That he was really fond of Jane, she doubted no more than she had ever done,

04:31:13.500 --> 04:31:19.080
and much as she had always been disposed to like him, she could not think without anger,

04:31:19.800 --> 04:31:26.820
hardly without contempt. On that easiness of temper, that want of proper resolution,

04:31:27.540 --> 04:31:33.640
which now made him the slave of his designing friends, and led him to sacrifice his own

04:31:33.640 --> 04:31:40.720
happiness to the caprice of their inclinations. Had his own happiness, however, been the only

04:31:40.720 --> 04:31:46.780
sacrifice, he might have been allowed to sport with it in whatever manner he thought best.

04:31:47.800 --> 04:31:53.080
But her sister's was involved in it, as she thought he must be sensible himself.

04:31:53.080 --> 04:32:01.220
It was a subject, in short, on which reflection would be long indulged, and must be unavailing.

04:32:03.000 --> 04:32:08.520
She could think of nothing else, and yet whether Bingley's regard had really died away,

04:32:09.540 --> 04:32:15.600
or were suppressed by his friend's interference, whether he had been aware of Jane's attachment,

04:32:16.340 --> 04:32:22.620
or whether it had escaped his observation, whichever were the case, though her opinion

04:32:22.620 --> 04:32:28.120
of him must be materially affected by the difference, her sister's situation remained

04:32:28.120 --> 04:32:37.160
the same, her peace equally wounded. A day or two passed before Jane had

04:32:37.160 --> 04:32:44.080
courage to speak of her feelings to Elizabeth, but at last, on Mrs. Bennet's leaving them together,

04:32:44.700 --> 04:32:50.880
after a longer irritation than usual about Netherfield and its master, she could not help

04:32:50.880 --> 04:32:58.140
saying, Oh, that my dear mother had more command over herself!

04:32:59.860 --> 04:33:05.380
She can have no idea of the pain she gives me by her continual reflections on him.

04:33:06.200 --> 04:33:15.920
But I will not repine. It cannot last long. He will be forgot, and we shall all be as we were before.

04:33:17.860 --> 04:33:22.860
Elizabeth looked at her sister with incredulous solicitude, but said nothing.

04:33:24.140 --> 04:33:33.180
You doubt me, cried Jane, slightly colouring. Indeed, you have no reason. He may live in my

04:33:33.180 --> 04:33:40.380
memory as the most amiable man of my acquaintance, but that is all. I have nothing either to hope

04:33:40.380 --> 04:33:48.000
or fear, and nothing to reproach him with. Thank God I have not that pain.

04:33:49.040 --> 04:33:53.780
A little time, therefore. I shall certainly try to get the better.

04:33:55.400 --> 04:34:01.560
With a stronger voice, she soon added, I have this comfort immediately,

04:34:02.720 --> 04:34:09.320
that it has not been more than an error of fancy on my side, and that it has done no harm to anyone

04:34:09.320 --> 04:34:19.180
but myself. My dear Jane, exclaimed Elizabeth, you are too good. Your sweetness and disinterestedness

04:34:19.180 --> 04:34:26.100
are really angelic. I do not know what to say to you. I feel as if I had never done you justice

04:34:26.100 --> 04:34:32.980
or loved you as you deserve. Miss Bennet eagerly disclaimed all extraordinary merit,

04:34:33.540 --> 04:34:36.860
and threw back the praise on her sister's warm affection.

04:34:38.180 --> 04:34:45.240
Nay, said Elizabeth, this is not fair. You wish to think all the world respectable

04:34:45.240 --> 04:34:52.740
and are hurt if I speak ill of anybody. I only want to think you perfect, and you set yourself

04:34:52.740 --> 04:35:00.080
against it. Do not be afraid of my running into any excess, of my encroaching on your privilege of

04:35:00.080 --> 04:35:08.900
universal goodwill. You need not. There are few people whom I really love, and still fewer of whom

04:35:08.900 --> 04:35:16.520
I think well. The more I see of the world, the more am I dissatisfied with it, and every day

04:35:16.520 --> 04:35:22.580
confirms my belief of the inconsistency of all human characters, and of the little dependence

04:35:22.580 --> 04:35:29.560
that can be placed on the appearance of either merit or sense. I have met with two instances lately,

04:35:30.080 --> 04:35:37.420
one I will not mention. The other is Charlotte's marriage. It is unaccountable. In every view,

04:35:37.500 --> 04:35:44.420
it is unaccountable. My dear Lizzie, do not give way to such feelings as these.

04:35:45.540 --> 04:35:52.400
They will ruin your happiness. You do not make allowance enough for difference of situation and

04:35:52.400 --> 04:35:59.820
temper. Consider Mr. Collins' respectability and Charlotte's prudent, steady character.

04:36:01.240 --> 04:36:08.460
Remember that she is one of a large family, that, as to fortune, it is a most eligible match,

04:36:09.260 --> 04:36:15.640
and be ready to believe, for everybody's sake, that she may feel something like regard and

04:36:15.640 --> 04:36:21.640
esteem for our cousin. To oblige you, I would try to believe almost anything,

04:36:22.220 --> 04:36:28.140
but no one else could be benefited by such a belief as this. For where I persuaded that

04:36:28.140 --> 04:36:33.300
Charlotte had any regard for him, I should only think worse of her understanding than I now do

04:36:33.300 --> 04:36:41.220
of her heart. My dear Jane, Mr. Collins is a conceited, pompous, narrow-minded, silly man.

04:36:41.220 --> 04:36:47.320
You know he is, as well as I do, and you must feel, as well as I do,

04:36:47.700 --> 04:36:51.080
that the woman who marries him cannot have a proper way of thinking.

04:36:52.340 --> 04:36:58.380
You shall not defend her, though it is Charlotte Lucas. You shall not, for the sake of one

04:36:58.380 --> 04:37:05.140
individual, change the meaning of principle and integrity, nor endeavour to persuade yourself or

04:37:05.140 --> 04:37:13.620
me that selfishness is prudent, and insensibility of danger, security for happiness.

04:37:15.970 --> 04:37:23.420
I must think your language too strong in speaking of both, replied Jane, and I hope you will be

04:37:23.420 --> 04:37:31.080
convinced of it by seeing them happy together. But enough of this. You alluded to something else.

04:37:31.680 --> 04:37:38.800
You mentioned two instances. I cannot understand you, but I entreat you, dear Lizzie,

04:37:39.400 --> 04:37:45.100
not to pain me by thinking that person to blame, and saying your opinion of him is sunk.

04:37:45.880 --> 04:37:49.420
We must not be so ready to fancy ourselves intentionally injured.

04:37:50.680 --> 04:37:55.840
We must not expect a lively young man to be always so guarded and circumspect.

04:37:57.360 --> 04:38:01.640
It is very often nothing but our own vanity that deceives us.

04:38:02.500 --> 04:38:09.360
Women fancy admiration means more than it does, and men take care that they should.

04:38:11.320 --> 04:38:14.400
If it is designedly done, they cannot be justified,

04:38:15.040 --> 04:38:20.280
but I have no idea of there being so much design in the world as some persons imagine.

04:38:22.420 --> 04:38:28.760
I am far from attributing any part of Mr. Bingley's conduct to design, said Elizabeth.

04:38:30.000 --> 04:38:35.660
But without scheming to do wrong or to make others unhappy, there may be error and there may be

04:38:35.660 --> 04:38:42.180
misery. Thoughtlessness, want of attention to other people's feelings, and want of resolution

04:38:42.180 --> 04:38:47.880
will do the business. And do you impute it to either of these?

04:38:49.760 --> 04:38:57.340
Yes, to the last. But if I go on, I shall displease you by saying what I think of persons you esteem.

04:38:57.740 --> 04:38:59.060
Stop me whilst you can.

04:39:00.640 --> 04:39:04.020
You persist, then, in supposing his sisters influence him?

04:39:05.160 --> 04:39:07.620
Yes, in conjunction with his friend.

04:39:09.040 --> 04:39:15.240
I cannot believe it. Why should they try to influence him? They can only wish for his

04:39:15.240 --> 04:39:20.940
happiness, and if he is attached to me, no other woman can secure it.

04:39:22.520 --> 04:39:27.540
Your first position is false. They may wish many things besides his happiness.

04:39:28.540 --> 04:39:34.500
They may wish his increase of wealth and consequence. They may wish him to marry a

04:39:34.500 --> 04:39:39.300
girl who has all the importance of money, great connections, and pride.

04:39:41.060 --> 04:39:47.000
Beyond a doubt. They do wish him to choose Miss Darcy, replied Jane.

04:39:48.620 --> 04:39:51.560
But this may be from better feelings than you are supposing.

04:39:52.880 --> 04:39:58.400
They have known her much longer than they have known me. No wonder if they love her better.

04:40:00.300 --> 04:40:05.520
But whatever may be their own wishes, it is very unlikely they should have opposed their brothers.

04:40:06.700 --> 04:40:12.900
What sister would think herself at liberty to do it, unless there was something very objectionable?

04:40:13.820 --> 04:40:20.200
If they believed him attached to me, they would not try to part us. If he were so,

04:40:20.480 --> 04:40:26.860
they could not succeed. By supposing such an affection, you make everybody acting

04:40:26.860 --> 04:40:30.820
unnaturally and wrong, and me most unhappy.

04:40:32.080 --> 04:40:37.620
Do not distress me by the idea. I am not ashamed of having been mistaken.

04:40:39.040 --> 04:40:44.120
Or at least it is slight. It is nothing in comparison of what I should feel

04:40:44.120 --> 04:40:49.460
in thinking ill of him or his sisters. Let me take it in the best light,

04:40:50.260 --> 04:40:52.300
in the light in which it may be understood.

04:40:54.660 --> 04:41:00.800
Elizabeth could not oppose such a wish, and from this time Mr. Bingley's name was scarcely ever

04:41:00.800 --> 04:41:08.360
mentioned between them. Mrs. Bennet still continued to wonder and repine at his returning no more,

04:41:09.300 --> 04:41:13.540
and though a day seldom passed in which Elizabeth did not account for it clearly,

04:41:14.580 --> 04:41:19.200
there seemed little chance of her ever considering it with less perplexity.

04:41:20.320 --> 04:41:24.040
Her daughter endeavoured to convince her of what she did not believe herself,

04:41:24.760 --> 04:41:31.300
that his attentions to Jane had been merely the effect of a common and transient liking,

04:41:32.220 --> 04:41:37.520
which ceased when he saw her no more. But though the probability of this

04:41:37.520 --> 04:41:43.660
statement was admitted at the time, she had the same story to repeat every day.

04:41:45.080 --> 04:41:49.880
Mrs. Bennet's best comfort was that Mr. Bingley must be down again in the summer.

04:41:51.480 --> 04:41:53.860
Mr. Bennet treated the matter differently.

04:41:55.420 --> 04:42:04.430
So, Lizzy, said he one day, your sister is crossed in love, I find. I congratulate her.

04:42:05.640 --> 04:42:10.520
Next to being married, a girl likes to be crossed in love a little now and then.

04:42:11.200 --> 04:42:16.640
It is something to think of, and gives her a sort of distinction among her companions.

04:42:17.660 --> 04:42:23.700
When is your turn to come? You will hardly bear to be long outdone by Jane.

04:42:24.920 --> 04:42:30.960
Now is your time. Here are officers enough at Meryton to disappoint all the young ladies in

04:42:30.960 --> 04:42:38.440
the county. Let Wickham be your man. He is a pleasant fellow, and would jilt you creditably.

04:42:40.280 --> 04:42:47.720
Thank you, sir, but a less agreeable man would satisfy me. We must not all expect Jane's good

04:42:47.720 --> 04:42:57.500
fortune. True, said Mr. Bennet, but it is a comfort to think that whatever of that kind may

04:42:57.500 --> 04:43:02.800
befall you, you have an affectionate mother who will always make the most of it.

04:43:05.360 --> 04:43:10.000
Mr. Wickham's society was of material service in dispelling the gloom,

04:43:10.940 --> 04:43:15.620
which the late perverse occurrences had thrown on many of the Longbourn family.

04:43:16.560 --> 04:43:23.780
They saw him often, and to his other recommendations was now added that of general unreserve.

04:43:24.760 --> 04:43:31.940
The whole of what Elizabeth had already heard, his claims on Mr. Darcy, and all that he had

04:43:31.940 --> 04:43:40.300
offered from him, was now openly acknowledged and publicly canvassed. And everybody was pleased

04:43:40.300 --> 04:43:46.260
to think how much they had always disliked Mr. Darcy before they had known anything of the matter.

04:43:48.440 --> 04:43:52.760
Miss Bennet was the only creature who could suppose there might be any extenuating

04:43:52.760 --> 04:44:00.320
circumstances in the case unknown to the society of Hertfordshire. Her mild and steady candour

04:44:00.320 --> 04:44:05.800
always pleaded for allowances and urged the possibility of mistakes.

04:44:07.240 --> 04:44:16.080
But by everybody else, Mr. Darcy was condemned as the worst of men.

04:44:20.100 --> 04:44:26.960
After a week spent in professions of love and schemes of felicity,

04:44:26.960 --> 04:44:32.120
Mr. Collins was called from his amiable Charlotte by the arrival of Saturday.

04:44:33.820 --> 04:44:39.280
The pain of separation, however, might be alleviated on his side by preparations for

04:44:39.280 --> 04:44:45.180
the reception of his bride, as he had reason to hope that shortly after his next return

04:44:45.180 --> 04:44:50.500
into Hertfordshire the day would be fixed that was to make him the happiest of men.

04:44:51.700 --> 04:44:58.580
He took leave of his relations at Longbourn with as much solemnity as before, wished his fair

04:44:58.580 --> 04:45:04.160
cousin's health and happiness again, and promised their father another letter of thanks.

04:45:05.900 --> 04:45:11.300
On the following Monday, Mrs. Bennet had the pleasure of receiving her brother and his wife,

04:45:11.780 --> 04:45:14.740
who came as usual to spend the Christmas at Longbourn.

04:45:16.380 --> 04:45:23.640
Mr. Gardiner was a sensible gentleman-like man, greatly superior to his sister, as well by nature

04:45:23.640 --> 04:45:30.480
as education. The Netherfield ladies would have had difficulty in believing that a man who lived

04:45:30.480 --> 04:45:37.780
by trade, and within view his own warehouses, could have been so well-bred and agreeable.

04:45:39.360 --> 04:45:44.600
Mrs. Gardiner, who was several years younger than Mrs. Bennet and Mrs. Phillips, was an

04:45:44.600 --> 04:45:50.440
amiable, intelligent, elegant woman, and a great favourite with all her Longbourn nieces.

04:45:51.600 --> 04:45:57.140
Between the two eldest and herself especially, there subsisted a very particular regard.

04:45:58.280 --> 04:46:01.020
They had frequently been staying with her in town.

04:46:03.280 --> 04:46:08.700
The first part of Mrs. Gardiner's business on her arrival was to distribute her presence and

04:46:08.700 --> 04:46:14.680
describe the newest fashions. When this was done, she had a less active part to play.

04:46:15.480 --> 04:46:17.400
It became her turn to listen.

04:46:18.840 --> 04:46:26.360
Mrs. Bennet had many grievances to relate, and much to complain of. They had been very ill-used

04:46:26.360 --> 04:46:31.940
since she last saw her sister. Two of her girls had been on the point of marriage,

04:46:31.940 --> 04:46:35.100
and after all, there was nothing in it.

04:46:36.420 --> 04:46:43.020
I do not blame Jane, she continued, for Jane would have got Mr. Bingley if she could.

04:46:43.720 --> 04:46:50.460
But Lizzie, oh sister, it is very hard to think that she might have been Mr. Colin's wife by this

04:46:50.460 --> 04:46:57.240
time, had it not been for her own perverseness. He made her an offer in this very room, and she

04:46:57.240 --> 04:47:04.120
refused him. The consequence of it is that Lady Lucas will have a daughter married before I have,

04:47:04.560 --> 04:47:08.300
and that long-born estate is just as much entailed as ever.

04:47:09.240 --> 04:47:15.180
The Lucases are very artful people indeed, sister. They are all for what they can get.

04:47:16.060 --> 04:47:22.660
I am sorry to say it of them, but so it is. It makes me very nervous and poorly to be thwarted

04:47:22.660 --> 04:47:28.560
in my own family, and to have neighbours who think of themselves before anybody else.

04:47:29.280 --> 04:47:33.300
However, your coming just at this time is the greatest of comforts,

04:47:34.040 --> 04:47:38.300
and I am very glad to hear what you tell us of long sleeves.

04:47:41.460 --> 04:47:45.800
Mrs. Gardiner, to whom the chief of this news had been given before,

04:47:46.060 --> 04:47:49.200
in the course of Jane and Elizabeth's correspondence with her,

04:47:49.200 --> 04:47:56.800
made her sister a slight answer, and in compassion to her nieces, turned the conversation.

04:47:59.240 --> 04:48:03.140
When alone with Elizabeth afterwards, she spoke more on the subject.

04:48:04.440 --> 04:48:11.580
It seems likely to have been a desirable match for Jane, said she. I am sorry it went off,

04:48:12.320 --> 04:48:17.760
but these things happen so often. A young man, such as you describe Mr. Bingley,

04:48:18.260 --> 04:48:24.260
so easily falls in love with a pretty girl for a few weeks, and when accident separates them,

04:48:24.500 --> 04:48:29.340
so easily forgets her, that these sort of inconstancies are very frequent.

04:48:30.900 --> 04:48:37.760
An excellent consolation in its way, said Elizabeth. But it will not do for us.

04:48:38.340 --> 04:48:44.180
We do not suffer by accident. It does not often happen that the interference of friends will

04:48:44.180 --> 04:48:49.520
persuade a young man of independent fortune to think no more of a girl whom he was violently

04:48:49.520 --> 04:48:57.440
in love with only a few days before. But that expression of violently in love is so hackneyed,

04:48:57.620 --> 04:49:05.500
so doubtful, so indefinite, that it gives me very little idea. It is as often applied to feelings

04:49:05.500 --> 04:49:13.260
which arise only from a half-hour's acquaintance as to a real, strong attachment. Pray, how violent

04:49:13.260 --> 04:49:21.000
was Mr. Bingley's love? I never saw a more promising inclination. He was growing quite

04:49:21.000 --> 04:49:27.980
inattentive to other people, and wholly engrossed by her. Every time they met it was more decided

04:49:27.980 --> 04:49:34.280
and remarkable. At his own ball he offended two or three young ladies by not asking them to dance,

04:49:34.920 --> 04:49:41.860
and I spoke to him twice myself without receiving an answer. Could there be finer symptoms? Is not

04:49:41.860 --> 04:49:49.920
general incivility the very essence of love? Oh, yes, of that kind of love which I suppose

04:49:49.920 --> 04:49:57.500
him to have felt. Poor Jane! I am sorry for her, because with such a disposition she may not get

04:49:57.500 --> 04:50:03.480
over it immediately. It had better have happened to you, Lizzie. You would have laughed yourself

04:50:03.480 --> 04:50:10.940
out of it sooner. But do you think she would be prevailed on to go back with us? Change of

04:50:10.940 --> 04:50:17.460
might be of service, and perhaps a little relief from home may be as useful as anything.

04:50:19.880 --> 04:50:25.380
Elizabeth was exceedingly pleased with this proposal, and felt persuaded of her sister's

04:50:25.380 --> 04:50:33.580
ready acquiescence. I hope, added Mrs. Gardiner, that no consideration with regard to this young

04:50:33.580 --> 04:50:40.000
man will influence her. We live in so different a part of town, all our connections are so different,

04:50:40.000 --> 04:50:45.760
and as you well know we go out so little that it is very improbable they should meet at all,

04:50:46.400 --> 04:50:53.920
unless he really comes to see her. And that is quite impossible, for he is now in the custody

04:50:53.920 --> 04:50:59.520
of his friend, and Mr. Darcy would no more suffer him to call on Jane in such a part of London.

04:51:00.340 --> 04:51:06.860
My dear aunt, how could you think of it? Mr. Darcy may perhaps have heard of such a place as

04:51:06.860 --> 04:51:12.060
Grace Church Street, but he would hardly think a month's ablution enough to cleanse him from its

04:51:12.060 --> 04:51:19.080
impurities where he wants to enter it. And depend upon it, Mr. Bingley never stirs without him.

04:51:20.420 --> 04:51:26.800
So much the better. I hope they will not meet at all. But does Jane not correspond with the

04:51:26.800 --> 04:51:33.360
sister? She will not be able to help calling. She will drop the acquaintance entirely.

04:51:36.360 --> 04:51:42.700
But in spite of the certainty in which Elizabeth affected to place this point, as well as the still

04:51:42.700 --> 04:51:49.060
more interesting one of Bingley's being withheld from seeing Jane, she felt a solicitude on the

04:51:49.060 --> 04:51:55.220
subject which convinced her, on examination, that she did not consider it entirely hopeless.

04:51:56.700 --> 04:52:03.340
It was possible, and sometimes she thought it probable, that his affection might be reanimated.

04:52:04.040 --> 04:52:10.160
And the influence of his friend successfully combated by the more natural influence of Jane's

04:52:10.160 --> 04:52:18.580
attractions. Miss Bennet accepted her aunt's invitation with pleasure, and the Bingleys were

04:52:18.580 --> 04:52:23.880
no otherwise in her thoughts at the same time than as she hoped that by Carolyn's not living

04:52:23.880 --> 04:52:29.040
in the same house with her brother, she might occasionally spend a morning with her without

04:52:29.040 --> 04:52:36.960
any danger of seeing him. The gardeners stayed a week at Longbourn, and what with the Philipses,

04:52:36.980 --> 04:52:44.220
the Lucases, and the officers, there was not a day without its engagement. Mrs. Bennet had so

04:52:44.220 --> 04:52:49.800
carefully provided for the entertainment of her brother and sister that they did not once sit down

04:52:49.800 --> 04:52:57.280
to a family dinner. When the engagement was for home, some of the officers always made part of it,

04:52:58.060 --> 04:53:05.480
of which officers Mr. Wickham was sure to be one. And on these occasions, Mrs. Gardiner,

04:53:06.160 --> 04:53:12.220
rendered suspicious by Elizabeth's warm commendations of him, narrowly observed them both,

04:53:13.460 --> 04:53:20.520
without supposing them, from what she saw, to be very seriously in love. Their preference of each

04:53:20.520 --> 04:53:25.900
other was plain enough to make her a little uneasy, and she resolved to speak to Elizabeth

04:53:25.900 --> 04:53:31.720
on the subject before she left Hertfordshire, and represent to her the imprudence of encouraging

04:53:31.720 --> 04:53:40.040
such an attachment. To Mrs. Gardiner, Wickham had one means of affording pleasure, unconnected with

04:53:40.040 --> 04:53:48.460
his general powers. About ten or a dozen years ago, before her marriage, she had spent a considerable

04:53:48.460 --> 04:53:54.740
time in that very part of Derbyshire to which she belonged. They had, therefore, many acquaintance

04:53:54.740 --> 04:54:00.820
in common, and though Wickham had been little there since the death of Darcy's father five years

04:54:00.820 --> 04:54:06.700
before, it was yet in his power to give her fresher intelligence of her former friends

04:54:07.220 --> 04:54:15.000
than she had been in the way of procuring. Mrs. Gardiner had seen Pemberley, and known the late

04:54:15.000 --> 04:54:22.000
Mr. Darcy by character perfectly well. Here, consequently, was an inexhaustible subject of

04:54:22.000 --> 04:54:28.200
discourse. In comparing her recollection of Pemberley with the minute description which

04:54:28.200 --> 04:54:34.140
Wickham could give, and in bestowing her tribute of praise on the character of its late possessor,

04:54:34.900 --> 04:54:41.080
she was delighting both him and herself. On being made acquainted with the present Mr.

04:54:41.300 --> 04:54:46.820
Darcy's treatment of him, she tried to remember something of that gentleman's reputed disposition

04:54:46.820 --> 04:54:53.720
when quite a lad, which might agree with it, and was confident at last that she recollected

04:54:53.720 --> 04:55:00.240
having heard Mr. Fitzwilliam Darcy formally spoken of as a very proud, ill-natured boy.

04:55:19.960 --> 04:55:20.560
26.

04:55:22.680 --> 04:55:28.240
Mrs. Gardiner's caution to Elizabeth was punctually and kindly given on the first favourable opportunity

04:55:28.240 --> 04:55:29.480
of speaking to her alone.

04:55:29.880 --> 04:55:32.900
After honestly telling her what she thought, she thus went on,

04:55:33.540 --> 04:55:38.400
You are too sensible a girl, Lizzie, to fall in love merely because you're warned against it,

04:55:38.640 --> 04:55:40.920
and therefore I'm not afraid of speaking openly.

04:55:41.660 --> 04:55:44.020
Seriously, I would have you be on your guard.

04:55:44.500 --> 04:55:48.100
Do not involve yourself or endeavour to involve him in an affection

04:55:48.100 --> 04:55:51.220
which the want of fortune would make so very imprudent.

04:55:51.940 --> 04:55:53.980
I have nothing to say against him.

04:55:54.300 --> 04:55:58.300
He is a most interesting young man, and if he had the fortune he ought to have,

04:55:58.600 --> 04:56:00.160
I should think you could not do better.

04:56:00.160 --> 04:56:03.980
But as it is, you must not let your fancy run away with you.

04:56:04.640 --> 04:56:07.520
You have sense, and we all expect you to use it.

04:56:07.840 --> 04:56:11.080
Your father would depend on your resolution and good conduct, I am sure.

04:56:11.640 --> 04:56:13.280
You must not disappoint your father.

04:56:14.860 --> 04:56:17.180
My dear Anne, this is being serious indeed.

04:56:18.840 --> 04:56:21.640
Yes, and I hope to engage you to be serious likewise.

04:56:22.820 --> 04:56:25.340
Well then, you need not be under any alarm.

04:56:25.700 --> 04:56:28.860
I will take care of myself and of Mr. Wickham, too.

04:56:28.860 --> 04:56:31.820
He shall not be in love with me if I can prevent it.

04:56:33.340 --> 04:56:35.240
Elizabeth, you're not serious now.

04:56:36.480 --> 04:56:38.380
I beg your pardon, I'll try again.

04:56:39.200 --> 04:56:41.500
At present, I am not in love with Mr. Wickham.

04:56:41.760 --> 04:56:43.440
No, I certainly am not.

04:56:44.100 --> 04:56:48.620
But he is, beyond all comparison, the most agreeable man I ever saw.

04:56:49.000 --> 04:56:53.640
And if he becomes really attached to me, I will believe it better that he should not.

04:56:54.180 --> 04:56:55.960
I see the imprudence of it.

04:56:55.960 --> 04:56:58.180
Oh, that abominable Mr. Darcy.

04:56:58.780 --> 04:57:03.500
My father's opinion of me does the greatest honor, and I should be miserable to forfeit it.

04:57:04.220 --> 04:57:06.720
My father, however, is partial to Mr. Wickham.

04:57:07.120 --> 04:57:11.460
In short, my dear Anne, I should be very sorry to be the means of making any of you unhappy.

04:57:11.920 --> 04:57:16.600
But since we see every day that where there is affection, young people are seldom withheld

04:57:16.600 --> 04:57:20.100
by immediate want of fortune from entering into engagements with each other,

04:57:20.360 --> 04:57:24.320
how can I promise to be wiser than so many of my fellow creatures if I'm tempted?

04:57:24.320 --> 04:57:27.580
Or how am I even to know that there would be wisdom to resist?

04:57:28.100 --> 04:57:31.200
All that I can promise you, therefore, is not to be in a hurry.

04:57:31.720 --> 04:57:34.720
I will not be in a hurry to believe myself his first object.

04:57:35.160 --> 04:57:37.880
When I am in company with him, I will not be wishing.

04:57:38.440 --> 04:57:40.660
In short, I will do my best.

04:57:42.180 --> 04:57:45.460
Perhaps it will be as well if you discourage his coming here so often.

04:57:45.780 --> 04:57:48.760
At least you should not remind your mother of inviting him.

04:57:49.140 --> 04:57:52.600
As I did the other day, said Elizabeth, with a conscious smile.

04:57:52.600 --> 04:57:55.940
Very true, it will be wise of me to refrain from that.

04:57:56.380 --> 04:57:58.780
But do not imagine that he is always here so often.

04:57:59.180 --> 04:58:02.100
It's on your account that he's been so frequently invited this week.

04:58:02.380 --> 04:58:06.460
You know my mother's ideas as to the necessity of constant company for her friends.

04:58:07.080 --> 04:58:10.900
But really, and upon my honor, I will try to do what I think to be the wisest.

04:58:11.200 --> 04:58:12.700
And now I hope you're satisfied.

04:58:13.820 --> 04:58:16.200
Her aunt assured her that she was, and Elizabeth,

04:58:16.200 --> 04:58:19.260
having thanked her for the kindness of her hints, they parted.

04:58:19.260 --> 04:58:23.400
A wonderful instance of advice being given on such a point without being resented.

04:58:24.420 --> 04:58:29.380
Mr. Collins returned into Hertfordshire soon after it had been quitted by the gardeners and

04:58:29.380 --> 04:58:31.960
Jane, but as he took up his abode with the Lucas's,

04:58:32.140 --> 04:58:34.920
his arrival was no great inconvenience to Mrs. Bennet.

04:58:35.480 --> 04:58:38.820
His marriage was now fast approaching, and she was at length so

04:58:38.820 --> 04:58:42.500
far resigned as to think it inevitable, and even repeatedly to say,

04:58:42.560 --> 04:58:46.380
in an ill-natured tone, that she wished they might be happy.

04:58:47.340 --> 04:58:51.760
Thursday was to be the wedding day, and on Wednesday, Miss Lucas paid her farewell visit,

04:58:52.040 --> 04:58:55.680
and when she rose to take leave, Elizabeth, ashamed of her mother's

04:58:55.680 --> 04:58:59.460
ungracious and reluctant good wishes, and sincerely affected herself,

04:58:59.860 --> 04:59:01.180
accompanied her out of the room.

04:59:01.900 --> 04:59:04.160
As they went downstairs together, Charlotte said,

04:59:04.820 --> 04:59:08.020
I shall depend upon hearing from you very often, Eliza.

04:59:08.480 --> 04:59:09.780
That you certainly shall.

04:59:10.280 --> 04:59:12.080
And I have another favor to ask you.

04:59:12.300 --> 04:59:13.460
Will you come and see me?

04:59:14.320 --> 04:59:16.360
We shall often meet, I hope, in Hertfordshire.

04:59:16.940 --> 04:59:19.360
I'm not likely to leave Kent for some time.

04:59:19.520 --> 04:59:21.380
Promise me, therefore, to come to Huntsford?

04:59:22.680 --> 04:59:26.160
Elizabeth could not refuse, though she foresaw a little pleasure in the visit.

04:59:27.160 --> 04:59:30.580
My father and Maria are coming to me in March, added Charlotte.

04:59:31.080 --> 04:59:32.980
And I hope you will consent to be at the party.

04:59:33.160 --> 04:59:35.680
Indeed, Eliza, you will be as welcome as either of them.

04:59:36.200 --> 04:59:37.360
The wedding took place.

04:59:37.560 --> 04:59:40.260
The bride and bridegroom set off for Kent from the church door,

04:59:40.560 --> 04:59:44.140
and everybody had as much to say or to hear on the subject as usual.

04:59:44.700 --> 04:59:46.540
Elizabeth soon heard from her friend,

04:59:46.920 --> 04:59:50.140
and their correspondence was as regular and frequent as it had ever been.

04:59:50.500 --> 04:59:53.180
That it should be equally unreserved was impossible.

04:59:53.900 --> 04:59:58.780
Elizabeth could never address her without feeling that all the comfort of intimacy was over.

04:59:59.240 --> 05:00:01.580
And though determined not to slacken as a correspondent,

05:00:02.020 --> 05:00:05.260
it was for the sake of what had been rather than what was.

05:00:06.060 --> 05:00:09.040
Charlotte's first letters were received with a good deal of eagerness.

05:00:09.340 --> 05:00:12.800
There could not but be curiosity to know how she would speak of her new home,

05:00:12.800 --> 05:00:17.260
how she would like Lady Catherine, and how happy she would dare pronounce herself to be.

05:00:17.660 --> 05:00:19.420
Though when these letters were read,

05:00:19.980 --> 05:00:24.380
Elizabeth felt that Charlotte expressed herself on every point exactly as she might have foreseen.

05:00:24.860 --> 05:00:27.820
She wrote cheerfully, seemed surrounded with comforts,

05:00:27.820 --> 05:00:29.700
and mentioned nothing which she could not praise.

05:00:30.140 --> 05:00:33.480
The house, furniture, neighborhood, and roads were all to her taste,

05:00:33.760 --> 05:00:37.020
and Lady Catherine's behavior was most friendly and obliging.

05:00:37.320 --> 05:00:41.100
It was Mr. Collins' picture of Hunsford and Rosings rationally softened,

05:00:41.100 --> 05:00:45.440
and Elizabeth perceived that she must wait for her own visit there to know the rest.

05:00:46.460 --> 05:00:50.680
Jane had already written a few lines to her sister to announce their safe arrival in London,

05:00:50.940 --> 05:00:55.520
and when she wrote again, Elizabeth hoped it would be in her power to say something of the Bingleys.

05:00:55.980 --> 05:01:00.660
Her impatience for this second letter was as well rewarded as impatience generally is.

05:01:01.120 --> 05:01:04.620
Jane had been a week in town without either seeing or hearing from Caroline.

05:01:05.100 --> 05:01:09.500
She accounted for it, however, by supposing her last letter to her friend from Longbourn

05:01:09.500 --> 05:01:11.420
had by some accident been lost.

05:01:12.160 --> 05:01:15.820
My aunt, she continued, is going tomorrow into that part of the town,

05:01:16.080 --> 05:01:19.060
and I shall take the opportunity of calling in Grosvenor Street.

05:01:19.640 --> 05:01:22.740
She wrote again when the visit was paid, and she had seen Miss Bingley.

05:01:23.240 --> 05:01:27.720
I did not think Caroline in spirits, were her words, but she was very glad to see me,

05:01:27.760 --> 05:01:30.520
and reproached me for giving her no notice of my coming to London.

05:01:31.000 --> 05:01:33.800
I was right, therefore, my last letter had never reached her.

05:01:33.960 --> 05:01:35.960
I inquired after their brother, of course.

05:01:35.960 --> 05:01:40.440
He was well, but so much engaged with Mr. Darcy that they scarcely ever saw him.

05:01:41.040 --> 05:01:43.180
I found that Miss Darcy was expected to dinner.

05:01:43.460 --> 05:01:44.680
I wish I could see her.

05:01:45.160 --> 05:01:48.420
My visit was not long, as Caroline and Mrs. Hurst were going out.

05:01:48.640 --> 05:01:50.540
I dare say I shall see them soon here.

05:01:51.840 --> 05:01:53.460
Elizabeth shook her head over this letter.

05:01:53.800 --> 05:01:58.400
It convinced her that accident only could discover to Mr. Bingley her sister's being in town.

05:01:59.120 --> 05:02:02.100
Four weeks passed away, and Jane saw nothing of him.

05:02:02.540 --> 05:02:05.480
She endeavored to persuade herself that she did not regret it,

05:02:05.480 --> 05:02:08.820
but she could no longer be blind to Miss Bingley's inattention.

05:02:09.440 --> 05:02:12.060
After waning at home every morning for a fortnight,

05:02:12.300 --> 05:02:14.760
and inventing every evening a fresh excuse for her,

05:02:15.120 --> 05:02:18.740
the visit did at last appear that the shortness of her stay,

05:02:18.960 --> 05:02:23.400
and yet more the alteration of her manner, would allow Jane to deceive herself no longer.

05:02:24.200 --> 05:02:27.640
The letter which she wrote on this occasion to her sister will prove what she felt.

05:02:28.720 --> 05:02:34.240
My dearest Lizzy Will, I am sure, being capable of triumphing in her better judgment at my expense,

05:02:34.240 --> 05:02:39.280
when I confess myself to have been entirely deceived in Miss Bingley's regard for me.

05:02:39.660 --> 05:02:42.760
But, my dear sister, though the event has proved you right,

05:02:43.000 --> 05:02:47.120
do not think me obstinate if I still assert that, considering what her behaviour was,

05:02:47.380 --> 05:02:49.880
my confidence was as natural as your suspicion.

05:02:50.620 --> 05:02:54.340
I do not at all comprehend her reason for wishing to be intimate with me,

05:02:54.540 --> 05:02:59.020
but if the same circumstances were to happen again, I am sure I should be deceived again.

05:02:59.780 --> 05:03:02.060
Caroline did not return my visit till yesterday,

05:03:02.060 --> 05:03:05.260
and not a note, not a line, did I receive in the meantime.

05:03:05.840 --> 05:03:09.420
When she did come, it was very evident that she had no pleasure in it.

05:03:09.560 --> 05:03:12.580
She made a slight formal apology for not calling before,

05:03:13.040 --> 05:03:18.080
said not a word of wishing to see me again, and was in every respect so altered a creature

05:03:18.080 --> 05:03:22.480
that when she went away I was perfectly resolved to continue the acquaintance no longer.

05:03:23.340 --> 05:03:25.740
I pity, though I cannot help blaming her.

05:03:26.300 --> 05:03:28.920
She was very wrong in singling me out as she did.

05:03:28.920 --> 05:03:32.880
I can safely say that every advance to intimacy began on her side.

05:03:33.440 --> 05:03:37.000
But I pity her, because she must feel that she has been acting wrong,

05:03:37.340 --> 05:03:40.660
and because I am very sure that anxiety for her brother is the cause of it.

05:03:41.020 --> 05:03:46.100
I need not explain myself farther, and though we know this anxiety to be quite needless,

05:03:46.460 --> 05:03:49.600
yet if she feels it, it will easily account for her behaviour to me.

05:03:50.060 --> 05:03:52.700
And so deservedly dear is he to his sister,

05:03:53.080 --> 05:03:57.220
whatever anxiety she must feel on his behalf is natural and amiable.

05:03:57.780 --> 05:04:01.680
I cannot but wonder, however, at her having any such fears now,

05:04:01.920 --> 05:04:05.880
because if he had at all cared about me, we must have met long ago.

05:04:06.300 --> 05:04:09.780
He knows of my being in town, I am certain, from something she said herself,

05:04:09.980 --> 05:04:12.220
and yet it would seem, by her manner of talking,

05:04:12.520 --> 05:04:16.180
as if she wanted to persuade herself that he really is partial to Miss Darcy.

05:04:16.760 --> 05:04:18.400
I cannot understand it.

05:04:18.860 --> 05:04:20.880
If I were not afraid of judging harshly,

05:04:21.000 --> 05:04:25.020
I should be almost tempted to say that there is a strong appearance of duplicity in all this.

05:04:25.660 --> 05:04:28.140
But I will endeavour to banish every painful thought,

05:04:28.440 --> 05:04:30.160
and think only of what will make me happy,

05:04:30.380 --> 05:04:34.040
your affection and the invariable kindness of my dear uncle and aunt.

05:04:34.560 --> 05:04:36.100
Let me hear from you very soon.

05:04:36.460 --> 05:04:39.740
Miss Bingley said something of his never returning to Netherfield again,

05:04:40.000 --> 05:04:42.280
of giving up the house, but not with any certainty.

05:04:42.880 --> 05:04:44.360
We'd better not mention it.

05:04:44.440 --> 05:04:48.020
I'm extremely glad that you had such pleasant accounts from our friends at Huntsford.

05:04:48.460 --> 05:04:50.660
Pray go and see them with Sir William and Maria.

05:04:50.880 --> 05:04:53.000
I'm sure you will be very comfortable there.

05:04:53.260 --> 05:04:54.120
Yours, etc.

05:04:55.020 --> 05:04:56.660
This letter gave Elizabeth some pain,

05:04:56.920 --> 05:05:00.240
but her spirits returned as she considered that Jane would no longer be duped,

05:05:00.280 --> 05:05:01.460
by the sister at least.

05:05:02.100 --> 05:05:05.420
All expectation from the brother was now absolutely over.

05:05:05.860 --> 05:05:08.540
She would not even wish for a renewal of his attentions.

05:05:09.000 --> 05:05:11.200
His character sunk on every review of it,

05:05:11.480 --> 05:05:15.120
and as a punishment for him, as well as a possible advantage to Jane,

05:05:15.500 --> 05:05:19.160
she seriously hoped he might really soon marry Mr. Darcy's sister,

05:05:19.460 --> 05:05:23.660
as by Wickham's account she would make him abundantly regret what he had thrown away.

05:05:25.080 --> 05:05:26.840
Mrs. Gardiner, about this time,

05:05:27.060 --> 05:05:29.560
reminded Elizabeth of her promise concerning that gentleman,

05:05:29.860 --> 05:05:31.140
and required information,

05:05:31.600 --> 05:05:36.000
and Elizabeth had such to send as might rather give contentment to her aunt than to herself.

05:05:36.280 --> 05:05:38.240
His apparent partiality had subsided.

05:05:38.280 --> 05:05:39.420
His attentions were over.

05:05:39.760 --> 05:05:41.800
He was the admirer of someone else.

05:05:42.360 --> 05:05:44.300
Elizabeth was watchful enough to see it all,

05:05:44.320 --> 05:05:46.900
but she could see it and write of it without material pain.

05:05:47.500 --> 05:05:49.360
Her heart had been but slightly touched,

05:05:49.520 --> 05:05:51.960
and her vanity was satisfied with believing that

05:05:51.960 --> 05:05:54.720
she would have been his only choice had fortune permitted it.

05:05:55.020 --> 05:05:58.920
The sudden acquisition of £10,000 was the most remarkable charm

05:05:58.920 --> 05:06:01.840
of the young lady to whom he was now rendering himself agreeable.

05:06:02.300 --> 05:06:06.240
But Elizabeth, less clear-sighted perhaps in this case than in Charlotte's,

05:06:06.240 --> 05:06:08.760
did not quarrel with him for his wish of independence.

05:06:09.440 --> 05:06:11.800
Nothing, on the contrary, could be more natural,

05:06:12.200 --> 05:06:16.120
and while able to suppose that it cost him a few struggles to relinquish her,

05:06:16.340 --> 05:06:19.580
she was ready to allow it a wise and desirable measure for both,

05:06:19.720 --> 05:06:21.780
and could very sincerely wish him happy.

05:06:22.760 --> 05:06:24.780
All this was acknowledged to Mrs. Gardiner,

05:06:24.780 --> 05:06:27.880
and after relating the circumstances she thus went on,

05:06:28.300 --> 05:06:32.080
I am now convinced, my dear aunt, that I have never been much in love,

05:06:32.440 --> 05:06:35.580
for had I really experienced that pure and elevating passion,

05:06:36.000 --> 05:06:39.240
I should at present detest his very name and wish him all manner of evil.

05:06:39.640 --> 05:06:42.320
But my feelings are not only cordial towards him,

05:06:42.560 --> 05:06:44.340
they are even impartial towards Miss King.

05:06:44.900 --> 05:06:47.180
I cannot find out that I hate her at all,

05:06:47.300 --> 05:06:50.240
or that I am in the least unwilling to think her a very good sort of girl.

05:06:50.840 --> 05:06:52.420
There can be no love in all this.

05:06:52.420 --> 05:06:54.540
My watchfulness has been effectual,

05:06:54.760 --> 05:06:56.940
and though I certainly should be a more interesting object

05:06:56.940 --> 05:06:59.840
to all my acquaintances where I distractedly in love with him,

05:07:00.160 --> 05:07:03.240
I cannot say that I regret my comparative insignificance.

05:07:03.880 --> 05:07:06.200
Importance may sometimes be purchased too dearly.

05:07:06.960 --> 05:07:09.960
Kitty and Lydia take his defection to heart much more than I do.

05:07:10.340 --> 05:07:11.920
They are young in the ways of the world,

05:07:12.100 --> 05:07:15.360
and not yet open to the mortifying conviction that handsome young men

05:07:15.360 --> 05:07:17.760
must have something to live on as well as the plane.

05:07:41.080 --> 05:07:41.680
XXVII.

05:07:41.940 --> 05:07:46.380
With no greater events than these in the Longbourn family, and otherwise diversified by little

05:07:46.380 --> 05:07:51.820
beyond walks to Meryton, sometimes dirty and sometimes cold, did January and February pass

05:07:51.820 --> 05:07:52.220
away.

05:07:52.800 --> 05:07:54.660
March was to take Elizabeth to Hunsford.

05:07:55.060 --> 05:07:59.060
She had not at first thought very seriously of going thither, but Charlotte, she soon

05:07:59.060 --> 05:08:03.380
found, was depending on the plan, and she gradually learned to consider it herself with

05:08:03.380 --> 05:08:05.460
greater pleasure, as well as greater certainty.

05:08:06.320 --> 05:08:10.240
Absence had increased her desire of seeing Charlotte again, and weakened her disgust

05:08:10.240 --> 05:08:11.100
of Mr. Collins.

05:08:11.940 --> 05:08:16.380
There was novelty in the scheme, and as with such a mother and such uncompanionable sisters,

05:08:16.800 --> 05:08:18.120
home could not be faultless.

05:08:18.520 --> 05:08:20.860
A little change was not unwelcome for its own sake.

05:08:21.320 --> 05:08:26.100
The journey would moreover give her a peep at Jane, and in short, as the time drew near,

05:08:26.340 --> 05:08:28.380
she would have been very sorry for any delay.

05:08:29.520 --> 05:08:33.440
Everything however went smoothly, and was finally settled according to Charlotte's first

05:08:33.440 --> 05:08:33.800
sketch.

05:08:34.220 --> 05:08:36.680
She was to accompany Sir William and his second daughter.

05:08:37.100 --> 05:08:41.360
The improvement of spending a night in London was added in time, and the plan became perfect

05:08:41.360 --> 05:08:42.360
as plan could be.

05:08:43.460 --> 05:08:50.840
The only pain was in leaving her father, who would certainly miss her, and who, when it

05:08:50.840 --> 05:08:53.440
to him, had almost promised to answer her letter.

05:08:54.460 --> 05:08:59.280
The farewell between herself and Mr. Wickham was perfectly friendly, on his side even more.

05:08:59.720 --> 05:09:03.880
His present pursuit could not make him forget that Elizabeth had been the first to excite

05:09:03.880 --> 05:09:08.660
and to deserve his attention, the first to listen and to pity, the first to be admired,

05:09:08.940 --> 05:09:13.520
and in his manner of bidding her adieu, wishing her every enjoyment, reminding her of what

05:09:13.520 --> 05:09:18.320
she was to expect in Lady Catherine de Beauvoir, and trusting their opinion of her, their opinion

05:09:18.320 --> 05:09:24.800
would always coincide, there was a solicitude, an interest which she felt must ever attach

05:09:24.800 --> 05:09:29.660
her to him with a most sincere regard, and she parted from him convinced that, whether

05:09:29.660 --> 05:09:33.680
married or single, he must always be her model of the amiable and pleasing.

05:09:34.760 --> 05:09:39.220
Her fellow travellers the next day were not of a kind to make her think him less agreeable.

05:09:39.620 --> 05:09:43.520
Sir William Lucas and his daughter Maria, a good-humoured girl, but as empty-headed

05:09:43.520 --> 05:09:48.080
as himself, had nothing to say that could be worth hearing, and were listened to with

05:09:48.080 --> 05:09:50.600
about as much delight as the rattle of the chaise.

05:09:50.940 --> 05:09:54.320
Elizabeth loved absurdities, but she had known Sir William's too long.

05:09:54.740 --> 05:09:58.640
He could tell her nothing new of the wonders of his presentation in Knighthood, and his

05:09:58.640 --> 05:10:00.920
civilities were worn out like his information.

05:10:01.460 --> 05:10:06.120
It was a journey of only twenty-four miles, and they began it so early as to be in Grace

05:10:06.120 --> 05:10:07.440
Church straight by noon.

05:10:07.800 --> 05:10:12.160
As they drove to Mr. Gardiner's door, Jane was at a drawing-room window watching their

05:10:12.160 --> 05:10:12.580
arrival.

05:10:12.920 --> 05:10:17.380
When they entered the passage, she was there to welcome them, and Elizabeth, looking earnestly

05:10:17.380 --> 05:10:20.960
in her face, was pleased to see it healthful and lovely as ever.

05:10:21.500 --> 05:10:25.640
On the stairs were a troupe of little boys and girls, whose eagerness for their cousin's

05:10:25.640 --> 05:10:29.520
appearance would not allow them to wait in the drawing-room, and whose shyness, as they

05:10:29.520 --> 05:10:32.460
had not seen her for twelve months, prevented their coming lower.

05:10:33.080 --> 05:10:34.500
All was joy and kindness.

05:10:35.040 --> 05:10:39.600
The day passed most pleasantly away, the morning in bustle and shopping, and the evening at

05:10:39.600 --> 05:10:40.540
one of the theatres.

05:10:41.320 --> 05:10:43.480
Elizabeth then contrived to sit by her aunt.

05:10:43.480 --> 05:10:48.100
Their first object was her sister, and she was more grieved than astonished to hear,

05:10:48.340 --> 05:10:53.100
in reply to her minute inquiries, that although Jane always struggled to support her spirits,

05:10:53.320 --> 05:10:55.020
there were periods of dejection.

05:10:55.700 --> 05:10:58.980
It was reasonable, however, to hope that they would not continue long.

05:10:59.500 --> 05:11:04.000
Mrs. Gardiner gave her the particulars also of Miss Bingley's visit in Grace Church Street,

05:11:04.480 --> 05:11:09.200
and repeated conversations occurring at different times between Jane and herself, which proved

05:11:09.200 --> 05:11:12.860
that the former had, from her heart, given up the acquaintance.

05:11:13.880 --> 05:11:18.300
Mrs. Gardiner then rallied her niece on Wickham's desertion, and complimented her in bearing

05:11:18.300 --> 05:11:19.040
it so well.

05:11:19.660 --> 05:11:23.680
But, my dear Elizabeth, she added, what sort of girl is Miss King?

05:11:23.960 --> 05:11:26.100
I should be sorry to think our friend mercenary.

05:11:27.100 --> 05:11:31.120
Pray, my dear aunt, what is the difference in matrimonial affairs between the mercenary

05:11:31.120 --> 05:11:32.240
and the prudent motive?

05:11:32.720 --> 05:11:35.280
Where does discretion end and avarice begin?

05:11:35.820 --> 05:11:40.240
Last Christmas you were afraid of his marrying me, because it would be imprudent, and now,

05:11:40.340 --> 05:11:44.040
because he's trying to get a girl with only ten thousand pounds, you want to find out

05:11:44.040 --> 05:11:45.060
that he's mercenary.

05:11:46.000 --> 05:11:49.940
If you will only tell me what sort of girl Miss King is, I shall know what to think.

05:11:50.920 --> 05:11:52.820
She's a very good kind of girl, I believe.

05:11:53.020 --> 05:11:54.360
I know no harm of her.

05:11:55.320 --> 05:11:59.120
But he paid her not the smallest attention till her grandfather's death made her mistress

05:11:59.120 --> 05:11:59.880
of this fortune.

05:12:00.860 --> 05:12:02.260
No, what should he?

05:12:02.440 --> 05:12:07.160
If it were not allowable for him to gain my affections because I had no money, what occasion

05:12:07.160 --> 05:12:10.880
could there be for making love to a girl whom he did not care about, and who was equally

05:12:10.880 --> 05:12:11.480
poor?

05:12:12.520 --> 05:12:16.740
There seems an indelicacy in directing his attentions towards her so soon after this

05:12:16.740 --> 05:12:17.120
event.

05:12:18.280 --> 05:12:22.820
A man in distressed circumstances does not have time for all those elegant decorums which

05:12:22.820 --> 05:12:23.960
other people may observe.

05:12:24.220 --> 05:12:26.660
If she does not object to it, why should we?

05:12:26.660 --> 05:12:29.540
Well, her not objecting does not justify him.

05:12:29.900 --> 05:12:33.440
It only shows her being deficient in something herself, sense or feeling.

05:12:34.320 --> 05:12:37.120
Well, cried Elizabeth, have it as you choose.

05:12:37.360 --> 05:12:39.660
He shall be mercenary, and she shall be foolish.

05:12:40.900 --> 05:12:43.140
No, Lizzie, that's what I do not choose.

05:12:43.520 --> 05:12:47.240
I should be sorry, you know, to think ill of a young man who's lived so long in Derbyshire.

05:12:48.060 --> 05:12:52.720
Oh, if that is all, I have a very poor opinion of young men who live in Derbyshire, and their

05:12:52.720 --> 05:12:55.420
intimate friends who live in Hertfordshire are not much better.

05:12:55.420 --> 05:12:56.980
I'm sick of them all.

05:12:57.340 --> 05:13:01.840
Thank heaven I'm going tomorrow, where I shall find a man who has not one agreeable quality,

05:13:02.120 --> 05:13:04.780
who has neither manner nor sense to recommend him.

05:13:05.300 --> 05:13:08.540
Stupid men are the only ones worth knowing, after all.

05:13:09.520 --> 05:13:12.880
Oh, take care, Lizzie, that speech savours strongly of disappointment.

05:13:14.120 --> 05:13:18.480
Before they were separated by the conclusion of the play, she had the unexpected happiness

05:13:18.480 --> 05:13:23.320
of an invitation to accompany her uncle and aunt on a tour of pleasure which they proposed

05:13:23.320 --> 05:13:24.220
taking in the summer.

05:13:24.220 --> 05:13:29.780
We have not determined how far it shall carry us, said Mrs. Gardiner, but perhaps to the lakes.

05:13:30.660 --> 05:13:35.000
No scheme could have been more agreeable to Elizabeth, and her acceptance of the invitation

05:13:35.000 --> 05:13:36.300
was most ready and grateful.

05:13:36.760 --> 05:13:39.320
Oh, my dear, dear aunt, she rapturously cried.

05:13:39.800 --> 05:13:41.540
What delight, what felicity!

05:13:41.720 --> 05:13:45.580
You give me fresh life and vigour, adieu to disappointment and spleen.

05:13:46.180 --> 05:13:48.340
What are young men to rocks and mountains?

05:13:48.980 --> 05:13:53.620
Oh, what hours of transport we shall spend, and when we do return, it shall not be like

05:13:53.620 --> 05:13:57.820
other travellers, without being able to give one accurate idea of anything.

05:13:58.200 --> 05:14:01.660
We will know where we have gone, we will recollect what we have seen.

05:14:02.080 --> 05:14:07.160
Lakes, mountains and rivers shall not be jumbled together in our imaginations, nor, when we

05:14:07.160 --> 05:14:10.840
attempt to describe any particular scene, will we begin quarrelling about its relative

05:14:10.840 --> 05:14:11.560
situation.

05:14:12.140 --> 05:14:16.600
Let our first effusions be less insupportable than those of the generality of travellers.

05:14:48.420 --> 05:14:49.060
28.

05:14:50.880 --> 05:14:56.160
Every object in the next day's journey was new and interesting to Elizabeth, and her

05:14:56.160 --> 05:15:01.280
spirits were in a state of enjoyment, for she had seen her sister looking so well as

05:15:01.280 --> 05:15:06.900
to banish all fear for her health, and the prospect of her northern tour was a constant

05:15:06.900 --> 05:15:07.920
source of delight.

05:15:08.760 --> 05:15:14.240
When they left the high road for the lane to Huntsford, every eye was in search of the

05:15:14.240 --> 05:15:18.360
parsonage, and every turning expected to bring it in view.

05:15:19.080 --> 05:15:23.400
The palings of Rosings Park was their boundary on one side.

05:15:23.400 --> 05:15:28.520
Elizabeth smiled at the recollection of all that she had heard of its inhabitants.

05:15:29.760 --> 05:15:32.640
At length the parsonage was discernible.

05:15:32.920 --> 05:15:38.940
The garden sloping to the road, the house standing in it, the green pails, and the laurel

05:15:38.940 --> 05:15:41.720
hedge, everything declared they were arriving.

05:15:42.680 --> 05:15:47.620
Mr. Collins and Charlotte appeared at the door, and the carriage stopped at the small

05:15:47.620 --> 05:15:53.560
gate, which led by a short gravel walk to the house, admits the nods and smiles of

05:15:53.560 --> 05:15:54.600
the whole party.

05:15:55.520 --> 05:16:01.020
In a moment they were all out of the chase, in rejoicing at the sight of each other.

05:16:02.360 --> 05:16:07.440
Mrs. Collins welcomed her friend with the liveliest pleasure, and Elizabeth was more

05:16:07.440 --> 05:16:12.720
and more satisfied with coming when she found herself so affectionately received.

05:16:13.500 --> 05:16:18.120
She saw instantly that her cousin's manners were not altered by his marriage.

05:16:18.880 --> 05:16:25.360
His formal civility was just what it had been, and he detained her some minutes at the gate

05:16:25.360 --> 05:16:29.920
to hear and satisfy his inquiries after all her family.

05:16:30.880 --> 05:16:35.520
They were then with no other delay than his pointing out the neatness of the entrance

05:16:35.520 --> 05:16:41.600
taken into the house, and as soon as they were in the parlour he welcomed them a second

05:16:41.600 --> 05:16:49.100
time, with ostentatious formality to his humble abode, and punctually repeated all his wife's

05:16:49.100 --> 05:16:50.760
offers of refreshment.

05:16:52.000 --> 05:16:57.720
Elizabeth was prepared to see him in his glory, and she could not help in fancying that in

05:16:57.720 --> 05:17:03.960
displaying the good proportion of the room, its aspect, and its furniture, he addressed

05:17:03.960 --> 05:17:10.260
himself particularly to her as if wishing to make her feel what she had lost in refusing

05:17:10.260 --> 05:17:10.620
him.

05:17:11.340 --> 05:17:17.960
But though everything seemed neat and comfortable, she was not able to gratify him by any sigh

05:17:17.960 --> 05:17:24.040
of repentance, and rather looked with wonder at her friend that she could have so cheerful

05:17:24.040 --> 05:17:26.180
an air with such a companion.

05:17:28.000 --> 05:17:34.040
When Mr. Collins said anything of which his wife might reasonably be ashamed, which certainly

05:17:34.040 --> 05:17:38.840
was not unseldom, she involuntarily turned her eye to Charlotte.

05:17:39.620 --> 05:17:46.560
Once or twice she could discern a faint blush, but in general Charlotte wisely did not hear.

05:17:47.160 --> 05:17:52.660
After sitting long enough to admire every article of furniture in the room, from the

05:17:52.660 --> 05:17:58.740
sideboard to the fender, to give an account of their journey, and of all that had happened

05:17:58.740 --> 05:18:04.820
in London, Mr. Collins invited them to take a stroll in the garden, which was large and

05:18:04.820 --> 05:18:09.280
well laid out, and to the cultivation of which he attended himself.

05:18:10.480 --> 05:18:16.240
To work in this garden was one of his most respectable pleasures, and Elizabeth admired

05:18:16.240 --> 05:18:22.400
the command of countenance with which Charlotte talked of the healthfulness of the exercise,

05:18:23.040 --> 05:18:26.280
and owned she encouraged it as much as possible.

05:18:26.900 --> 05:18:33.520
Here leading the way through every walk and crosswalk, and scarcely allowing them an interval

05:18:33.520 --> 05:18:40.480
to utter the praises he asked for, every view was pointed out with a minuteness which left

05:18:40.480 --> 05:18:42.540
beauty entirely behind.

05:18:44.260 --> 05:18:49.460
He could number the fields in every direction, and could tell how many trees there were in

05:18:49.460 --> 05:18:56.160
the most distant clump, but of all the views which his garden, or which the country or

05:18:56.160 --> 05:19:02.960
kingdom could boast, none were to be compared with a prospect of rosings, afforded by an

05:19:02.960 --> 05:19:08.260
opening in the trees that bordered the park nearly opposite the front of his house.

05:19:08.780 --> 05:19:14.100
It was a handsome modern building, well situated on rising ground.

05:19:15.220 --> 05:19:21.640
From his garden Mr. Collins would have fled them round his two meadows, but the ladies

05:19:21.640 --> 05:19:27.880
not having shoes to encounter the remains of a white frost turned back, and while Sir

05:19:27.880 --> 05:19:34.440
William accompanied him, Charlotte took her sister and friend over the house, extremely

05:19:34.440 --> 05:19:40.300
well pleased probably, to have the opportunity of showing out without her husband's help.

05:19:40.300 --> 05:19:47.060
It was rather small but well built and convenient, and everything was fitted up and arranged

05:19:47.060 --> 05:19:52.440
with a neatness and consistency of which Elizabeth gave Charlotte all the credit.

05:19:53.300 --> 05:19:59.200
When Mr. Collins could be forgotten, there was really an air of great comfort throughout,

05:19:59.440 --> 05:20:06.280
and by Charlotte's evident enjoyment of it, Elizabeth supposed he must be often forgotten.

05:20:07.100 --> 05:20:10.480
She had already learnt that Lady Catherine was still in the country.

05:20:10.900 --> 05:20:15.660
It was spoken of again while they were at dinner, when Mr. Collins, joining in, observed,

05:20:16.200 --> 05:20:21.280
Yes, Miss Elizabeth, you will have the honour of seeing Lady Catherine de Bourgh on the

05:20:21.280 --> 05:20:26.200
ensuing Sunday at church, and I need not say you will be delighted with her.

05:20:26.500 --> 05:20:32.740
She is all affability and condescension, and I doubt not but you will be honoured with

05:20:32.740 --> 05:20:35.760
portion of her notice when service is over.

05:20:36.500 --> 05:20:43.920
I have scarcely any hesitation in saying she will include you and my sister Mariah in every

05:20:43.920 --> 05:20:47.880
invitation with which she honours us during your stay here.

05:20:48.540 --> 05:20:51.480
Her behaviour to my dear Charlotte is charming.

05:20:51.900 --> 05:20:56.580
We dine at Rosings twice every week and are never allowed to walk home.

05:20:56.980 --> 05:21:00.180
Her ladyship's carriage is regularly ordered for us.

05:21:00.180 --> 05:21:05.660
I should say one of her ladyship's carriages, for she has several.

05:21:07.000 --> 05:21:13.200
Lady Catherine is a very respectable, sensible woman indeed, added Charlotte, and a most

05:21:13.200 --> 05:21:14.360
attentive neighbour.

05:21:15.180 --> 05:21:18.240
Very true, my dear, that is exactly what I say.

05:21:18.660 --> 05:21:23.280
She is the sort of woman whom one cannot regard with too much deference.

05:21:24.280 --> 05:21:30.420
The evening was spent cheerfully in taking over Hurtfisher News and telling again what

05:21:30.420 --> 05:21:36.140
had already been written, and when it closed, Elizabeth, in the solitude of her chamber,

05:21:36.460 --> 05:21:41.660
had to meditate upon Charlotte's degree of contentment, to understand her addressing

05:21:41.660 --> 05:21:48.080
in guiding and composure in bearing with her husband, and to acknowledge that it was all

05:21:48.080 --> 05:21:49.360
done very well.

05:21:49.700 --> 05:21:56.100
She had also to anticipate how her visit would pass, the quiet tenor of their usual employments,

05:21:56.640 --> 05:22:01.880
the vexatious interruptions of Mr. Collins, and the gaieties of their intercourse with

05:22:01.880 --> 05:22:02.400
Rosings.

05:22:02.900 --> 05:22:06.180
A lively imagination soon settled it all.

05:22:06.760 --> 05:22:12.260
About the middle of the next day, as she was in her room getting ready for a walk, a sudden

05:22:12.260 --> 05:22:18.880
noise below seemed to speak the whole house in confusion, and after listening a moment,

05:22:18.880 --> 05:22:25.460
she heard somebody running upstairs in a violent hurry and calling loudly after her.

05:22:26.120 --> 05:22:32.660
She opened the door and met Maria in the landing place, who breathless with agitation cried

05:22:32.660 --> 05:22:39.060
out, Oh, my dear Eliza, pray make haste and come into the dining room, for there is such

05:22:39.060 --> 05:22:40.380
a sight to be seen.

05:22:40.800 --> 05:22:45.160
I will not tell you what it is, make haste and come down this moment.

05:22:45.940 --> 05:22:48.140
Elizabeth asked questions in vain.

05:22:48.920 --> 05:22:53.580
Maria would tell her nothing more, and down they ran into the dining room, which fronted

05:22:53.580 --> 05:22:55.940
the lane in quest of this wonder.

05:22:56.580 --> 05:23:01.080
It was two ladies stopping in a low fayton at the garden gate.

05:23:01.720 --> 05:23:03.720
And is this all? cried Elizabeth.

05:23:04.100 --> 05:23:09.460
I expected at least that the pigs were got into the garden, and here is nothing but Lady

05:23:09.460 --> 05:23:10.620
Catherine and her daughter.

05:23:10.620 --> 05:23:14.480
La, my dear, said Maria, quite shocked at the mistake.

05:23:14.840 --> 05:23:16.260
It is not Lady Catherine.

05:23:16.620 --> 05:23:20.080
The old lady is Mrs. Jenkinson, who lives with them.

05:23:20.460 --> 05:23:22.620
The other is Miss de Bourgh.

05:23:22.920 --> 05:23:24.060
Only look at her.

05:23:24.060 --> 05:23:25.820
She is quite a little creature.

05:23:26.340 --> 05:23:29.680
Who would have thought that she could be so thin and small?

05:23:30.620 --> 05:23:35.160
She is abominably rude to keep Charlotte out of doors in all this wind.

05:23:35.480 --> 05:23:36.840
Why does she not come in?

05:23:37.600 --> 05:23:40.320
Oh, Charlotte says she hardly ever does.

05:23:40.820 --> 05:23:44.080
It is the greatest of favours when Miss de Bourgh comes in.

05:23:45.240 --> 05:23:48.820
I like her appearance, said Elizabeth, struck with other ideas.

05:23:49.160 --> 05:23:50.780
She looks sickly and cross.

05:23:51.140 --> 05:23:53.020
She will do for him very well.

05:23:53.120 --> 05:23:55.880
She will make him a very proper wife.

05:23:57.140 --> 05:24:01.760
Mr. Collins and Charlotte were both standing at the gate in conversation with the ladies,

05:24:01.760 --> 05:24:09.300
and Sir William, to Elizabeth's high diversion, was stationed in the doorway in earnest contemplation

05:24:09.300 --> 05:24:14.880
of the greatness before him, and constantly bowing whenever Miss de Bourgh looked that

05:24:14.880 --> 05:24:15.240
way.

05:24:15.580 --> 05:24:17.800
At length there was nothing more to be said.

05:24:18.120 --> 05:24:21.200
The ladies drove on, and the others returned to the house.

05:24:21.800 --> 05:24:27.700
Mr. Collins no sooner saw the two girls than he began to congratulate them on their good

05:24:28.400 --> 05:24:33.460
which Charlotte explained by letting them know that the whole party was asked to dine

05:24:33.460 --> 05:24:35.300
at Rosings the next day.

05:24:42.740 --> 05:24:47.500
Mr. Collins's triumph in consequence of this invitation was complete.

05:24:48.340 --> 05:24:54.480
The power of displaying the grandeur of his patroness to his wandering visitors, and of

05:24:54.480 --> 05:25:00.480
letting them see her civility towards himself and his wife was exactly what he had wished

05:25:00.480 --> 05:25:07.760
for, and that an opportunity of doing it should be given so soon was such an instance of Lady

05:25:07.760 --> 05:25:12.540
Catherine's condescension, as he knew not how to admire enough.

05:25:14.520 --> 05:25:20.120
I confess, said he, that I should not have been at all surprised by her ladyships asking

05:25:20.120 --> 05:25:24.380
us on Sunday to drink tea and spending the evening at Rosings.

05:25:24.620 --> 05:25:29.240
I rather expected from my knowledge of her affability that it would happen.

05:25:29.720 --> 05:25:33.140
But who could have foreseen such an attention as this?

05:25:33.640 --> 05:25:39.180
Who could have imagined that we should receive an invitation to dine there, an invitation

05:25:39.180 --> 05:25:44.440
moreover including the whole party, so immediately after your arrival?

05:25:45.140 --> 05:25:50.780
I am the less surprised at what has happened, replied Sir William, from that knowledge of

05:25:50.780 --> 05:25:56.000
what the manners of the great really are, which my situation in life has allowed me

05:25:56.000 --> 05:25:56.600
to acquire.

05:25:57.200 --> 05:26:02.240
About the court such instances of elegant breeding are not uncommon.

05:26:03.520 --> 05:26:09.420
Scarcely anything was talked of the whole day or next morning but their visit to Rosings.

05:26:10.060 --> 05:26:15.060
Mr. Collins was carefully instructing them in what they were to expect that the sight

05:26:15.060 --> 05:26:22.080
of such rooms, so many servants, and so splendid a dinner, might not wholly overpower them.

05:26:22.700 --> 05:26:26.720
When the ladies were separating for the toilette, he said to Elizabeth,

05:26:27.660 --> 05:26:31.380
Do not make yourself uneasy, my dear cousin, about your apparel.

05:26:31.880 --> 05:26:37.860
Lady Catherine is far from requiring that elegance of dress in us which becomes herself

05:26:37.860 --> 05:26:38.700
and her daughter.

05:26:39.160 --> 05:26:44.080
I would advise you merely to put on whatever of your clothes is superior to the rest.

05:26:44.620 --> 05:26:47.200
There is no occasion for anything more.

05:26:48.480 --> 05:26:52.300
Lady Catherine will not think the worse of you for being simply dressed.

05:26:52.760 --> 05:26:56.240
She likes to have the distinction of rank preserved.

05:26:57.520 --> 05:27:02.380
While they were dressing he came two or three times to their different doors to recommend

05:27:02.380 --> 05:27:07.580
their being quick as Lady Catherine very much objected to being kept waiting for her

05:27:07.580 --> 05:27:07.940
dinner.

05:27:08.860 --> 05:27:15.140
Such formidable accounts of her ladyship and her manner of living quite frightened Mariah

05:27:15.140 --> 05:27:20.620
Lucas, who had been little used to company, and she looked forward to her introduction

05:27:20.620 --> 05:27:27.520
at Rosings with as much apprehension as her father had done to his presentation at St.

05:27:28.580 --> 05:27:29.260
James'.

05:27:29.260 --> 05:27:34.560
As the weather was fine they had a pleasant walk of about half a mile across the park.

05:27:35.300 --> 05:27:40.740
Every park has its beauty and its prospects, and Elizabeth saw much to be pleased with,

05:27:41.160 --> 05:27:47.060
though she could not be in such raptures as Mr. Collins expected the scene to inspire,

05:27:47.580 --> 05:27:53.960
and was but slightly affected by his enumeration of the windows in front of the house, and

05:27:53.960 --> 05:28:00.500
relation of what the glazing altogether had originally cost Sir Louis de Bourgh.

05:28:02.200 --> 05:28:07.520
When they ascended the steps to the hall, Mariah's alarm was every moment increasing,

05:28:07.860 --> 05:28:11.060
and even Sir William did not look perfectly calm.

05:28:11.960 --> 05:28:14.200
Elizabeth's courage did not fail her.

05:28:14.440 --> 05:28:20.200
She had heard nothing of Lady Catherine that spoke of her awful from any extraordinary

05:28:20.200 --> 05:28:27.240
talents or miraculous virtue, and the mere stateliness of money or rank she thought she

05:28:27.240 --> 05:28:29.440
could witness without trepidation.

05:28:30.020 --> 05:28:36.120
From the entrance hall of which Mr. Collins pointed out, with a rapturous air, the fine

05:28:36.120 --> 05:28:41.640
proportion and the finished ornaments, they followed the servants through an antechamber

05:28:41.640 --> 05:28:46.600
to the room where Lady Catherine, her daughter and Mrs. Jenkinson were sitting.

05:28:47.420 --> 05:28:53.640
Her ladyship, with great condescension, arose to receive them, and as Mrs. Collins had settled

05:28:53.640 --> 05:28:59.440
it with her husband that the office of introduction should be hers, it was performed in a proper

05:28:59.440 --> 05:29:05.260
manner, without any of those apologies and thanks which he would have thought necessary.

05:29:06.440 --> 05:29:13.020
In spite of having been at St. James's, Sir William was so completely awed by the grandeur

05:29:13.020 --> 05:29:19.080
surrounding him that he had but just courage enough to make a very low bow and take his

05:29:19.080 --> 05:29:25.840
seat without saying a word, and his daughter, frightened almost out of her senses, sat on

05:29:25.840 --> 05:29:29.160
the edge of her chair, not knowing which way to look.

05:29:29.980 --> 05:29:35.700
Elizabeth found herself quite equal to the scene, and could observe the three ladies before

05:29:35.700 --> 05:29:36.980
her compositely.

05:29:37.820 --> 05:29:43.900
Lady Catherine was a tall, large woman with strongly marked features which might once

05:29:43.900 --> 05:29:44.860
have been handsome.

05:29:45.760 --> 05:29:51.740
Her air was not conciliating, nor was her manner of receiving them such as to make her

05:29:51.740 --> 05:29:54.220
visitors forget their inferior rank.

05:29:55.600 --> 05:30:02.800
She was not rendered formidable by silence, but whatever she said was spoken in so authoritative

05:30:02.800 --> 05:30:09.880
a tone as marked her self-importance and brought Mr. Wickham immediately to Elizabeth's mind,

05:30:10.220 --> 05:30:15.560
and from the observation of the day altogether she believed Lady Catherine to be exactly

05:30:15.560 --> 05:30:16.900
what he represented.

05:30:17.540 --> 05:30:23.320
When after examining the mother, in whose countenance and deportment she soon found

05:30:23.320 --> 05:30:27.740
some resemblance of Mr. Darcy, she turned her eyes on the daughter.

05:30:28.030 --> 05:30:34.120
She could almost have joined in Maria's astonishment at her being so thin and so small.

05:30:34.540 --> 05:30:39.300
There was neither in figure nor face any likeness between the ladies.

05:30:40.000 --> 05:30:45.940
Mr. Berg was pale and sickly, her features, though not plain, were insignificant, and

05:30:45.940 --> 05:30:52.920
she spoke very little except in a low voice to Mrs. Jenkinson, in whose appearance there

05:30:52.920 --> 05:30:58.660
was nothing remarkable, and who was entirely engaged in listening to what she said and

05:30:58.660 --> 05:31:02.420
placing a screen in the proper direction before her eyes.

05:31:04.160 --> 05:31:09.040
After sitting a few minutes they were all sent to one of the windows to admire the view,

05:31:09.540 --> 05:31:15.460
Mr. Collins attending them to point out its beauties, and Lady Catherine kindly informing

05:31:15.460 --> 05:31:19.220
them that it was much better worth looking at in the summer.

05:31:20.060 --> 05:31:24.940
The dinner was exceedingly handsome, and there were all the servants and all the articles

05:31:24.940 --> 05:31:30.800
of plate which Mr. Collins had promised, and as he had likewise foretold, he took his seat

05:31:30.800 --> 05:31:36.260
at the bottom of the table, by her ladyship's desire, and looked as if he felt that life

05:31:36.260 --> 05:31:37.840
could furnish nothing greater.

05:31:38.400 --> 05:31:45.500
He carved and ate and praised with delighted alacrity, and every dish was commended, first

05:31:45.500 --> 05:31:51.080
by him, and then by Sir William, who was now enough recovered to echo whatever his

05:31:51.080 --> 05:31:56.360
son-in-law said, in a manner which Elizabeth wondered Lady Catherine could bear.

05:31:56.940 --> 05:32:02.700
But Lady Catherine seemed gratified by their excessive admiration, and gave most gracious

05:32:02.700 --> 05:32:07.640
smiles, especially when any dish on the table proved a novelty to them.

05:32:08.940 --> 05:32:11.660
The party did not supply much conversation.

05:32:12.400 --> 05:32:17.520
Elizabeth was ready to speak whenever there was an opening, but she was seated between

05:32:17.520 --> 05:32:23.040
Charlotte and Mr. Berg, the former of whom was engaged in listening to Lady Catherine,

05:32:23.440 --> 05:32:26.800
and the latter said not a word to her all dinner-time.

05:32:27.680 --> 05:32:33.900
Mrs. Jenkinson was chiefly employed in watching how little Mr. Berg ate, pressing her to try

05:32:33.900 --> 05:32:37.300
some other dish, and fearing she was indisposed.

05:32:37.300 --> 05:32:42.860
Maria thought speaking out of the question, and the gentleman did nothing but eat and

05:32:42.860 --> 05:32:43.260
admire.

05:32:44.160 --> 05:32:49.080
When the ladies returned to the drawing-room, there was little to be done but to hear Lady

05:32:49.080 --> 05:32:55.020
Catherine talk, which she did without any intermission till coffee came in, delivering

05:32:55.020 --> 05:33:02.100
her opinion on every subject in so decisive a manner as proved that she was not used to

05:33:02.100 --> 05:33:04.080
having her judgment controverted.

05:33:05.260 --> 05:33:12.640
She inquired into Charlotte's domestic concerns familiarly and minutely, gave her a great

05:33:12.640 --> 05:33:18.820
deal of advice as to the management of them all, told her how everything ought to be regulated

05:33:18.820 --> 05:33:25.520
in so small a family as hers, and instructed her as to the care of her cows and her poultry.

05:33:26.960 --> 05:33:31.960
Elizabeth found that nothing was beneath this great lady's attention which could furnish

05:33:31.960 --> 05:33:34.680
her with an occasion of dictating to others.

05:33:35.580 --> 05:33:41.300
In the intervals of her discourse with Mrs. Collins, she addressed a variety of questions

05:33:41.300 --> 05:33:46.760
to Maria and Elizabeth, but especially to the latter, of whose connections she knew

05:33:46.760 --> 05:33:52.740
the least, and who she observed to Mrs. Collins was a very genteel, pretty sort of girl.

05:33:53.100 --> 05:33:58.320
She asked her at different times how many sisters she had, whether they were older or

05:33:58.320 --> 05:34:03.060
younger than herself, whether any of them were likely to be married, whether they were

05:34:03.060 --> 05:34:08.780
handsome, where they had been educated, what carriage her father kept, and what had been

05:34:08.780 --> 05:34:10.280
her mother's maiden name.

05:34:11.080 --> 05:34:16.580
Elizabeth felt all the impertinence of her questions, but answered them very composedly.

05:34:17.060 --> 05:34:18.680
Lady Catherine then observed,

05:34:28.320 --> 05:34:32.780
Otherwise I see no occasion for entailing estates from the female line.

05:34:33.160 --> 05:34:36.960
It was not thought necessary in Sir Louis de Bourgh's family.

05:34:37.480 --> 05:34:39.780
Do you play and sing, Miss Bennet?

05:34:39.980 --> 05:34:40.840
A little.

05:34:41.400 --> 05:34:45.660
Oh, then some time or other we shall be happy to hear you.

05:34:45.940 --> 05:34:50.400
Our instrument is a capital one, probably superior to...

05:34:50.400 --> 05:34:52.320
You shall try it some day.

05:34:52.660 --> 05:34:54.520
Do your sisters play and sing?

05:34:55.360 --> 05:34:56.500
One of them does.

05:34:57.280 --> 05:34:59.020
Why did you not all learn?

05:34:59.340 --> 05:35:01.080
You ought all to have learned.

05:35:01.480 --> 05:35:06.240
The Miss Webb's all play, and their father has not so good an income as yours.

05:35:06.620 --> 05:35:07.420
Do you draw?

05:35:07.900 --> 05:35:09.140
No, not at all.

05:35:09.400 --> 05:35:10.780
What, none of you?

05:35:11.320 --> 05:35:12.120
Not one.

05:35:12.900 --> 05:35:14.260
That is very strange.

05:35:14.640 --> 05:35:16.800
But I suppose you had no opportunity.

05:35:17.320 --> 05:35:21.760
Your mother should have taken you to town every spring for the benefit of masters.

05:35:22.460 --> 05:35:27.080
My mother would have had no objection, but my father hates London.

05:35:28.140 --> 05:35:29.860
Has your governess left you?

05:35:30.280 --> 05:35:32.000
We never had any governess.

05:35:32.460 --> 05:35:33.500
No governess?

05:35:33.740 --> 05:35:35.100
How is that possible?

05:35:35.600 --> 05:35:38.740
Five daughters brought up at home without a governess?

05:35:39.160 --> 05:35:41.320
I have never heard of such a thing.

05:35:41.940 --> 05:35:45.320
Your mother must have been quite a slave to your education.

05:35:46.720 --> 05:35:51.840
Elizabeth could hardly help smiling as she assured her that she had not been the case.

05:35:52.840 --> 05:35:53.940
Then who taught you?

05:35:54.040 --> 05:35:55.520
Who attended to you?

05:35:55.760 --> 05:35:58.740
Without a governess, you must have been neglected.

05:36:00.600 --> 05:36:03.080
Compared with some families, I believe we were.

05:36:03.580 --> 05:36:07.140
But such of us as wished to learn never wanted the means.

05:36:07.620 --> 05:36:11.760
We were always encouraged to read and had all the masters that were necessary.

05:36:12.340 --> 05:36:15.240
Those who chose to be idols certainly might.

05:36:15.980 --> 05:36:19.040
I, no doubt, but that is what a governess will prevent.

05:36:19.420 --> 05:36:24.340
And if I had known your mother, I would have advised her most strenuously to engage one.

05:36:24.700 --> 05:36:30.680
I always say that nothing is to be done in education without steady and regular instruction.

05:36:31.460 --> 05:36:33.860
And nobody but a governess can give it.

05:36:34.300 --> 05:36:39.080
It is wonderful how many families I have been the means of supplying in that way.

05:36:39.080 --> 05:36:43.380
I am always glad to get a young person well placed out.

05:36:43.900 --> 05:36:49.300
Four nieces of Mrs. Jenkinson's are most delightfully situated through my means,

05:36:49.700 --> 05:36:53.460
and it was but the other day that I recommended another young person,

05:36:53.820 --> 05:36:59.920
who was merely accidentally mentioned to me, and the family are quite delighted with her.

05:37:00.600 --> 05:37:05.180
Mrs. Collins, did I tell you of Lady Metcalfe's calling yesterday to thank me?

05:37:05.460 --> 05:37:07.660
She finds Miss Pope a treasure.

05:37:08.300 --> 05:37:12.600
Lady Catherine, she said, you have given me a treasure.

05:37:13.940 --> 05:37:16.500
Are any of your younger sisters out, Miss Bennet?

05:37:17.200 --> 05:37:18.440
Yes, ma'am, all.

05:37:19.540 --> 05:37:22.700
All? What? All five out at once?

05:37:23.260 --> 05:37:26.260
Very odd. And you only the second.

05:37:26.700 --> 05:37:29.900
The younger ones out before the elder ones are married?

05:37:30.340 --> 05:37:32.760
Your younger sisters must be very young.

05:37:33.460 --> 05:37:35.880
Yes, my youngest is not sixteen.

05:37:36.320 --> 05:37:39.600
Perhaps she is a full young to be much in company.

05:37:39.880 --> 05:37:44.140
But really, ma'am, I think it would be very hard upon younger sisters

05:37:44.140 --> 05:37:48.220
that they should not have their share of society and amusement,

05:37:48.580 --> 05:37:52.880
because the elder may not have the means or inclination to marry early.

05:37:53.520 --> 05:37:58.240
The last born has as good a right to the pleasures of youth as the first,

05:37:58.500 --> 05:38:01.220
and to be kept back on such a motive.

05:38:01.220 --> 05:38:07.440
I think it would not be very likely to promote sisterly affection or delicacy of mind.

05:38:08.400 --> 05:38:10.420
Upon my words, said her ladyship,

05:38:10.740 --> 05:38:14.480
you give your opinion very decidedly for so young a person.

05:38:14.940 --> 05:38:16.480
Pray, what is your age?

05:38:17.260 --> 05:38:20.760
With three younger sisters grown up, replied Elizabeth, smiling,

05:38:21.240 --> 05:38:23.980
your ladyship can hardly expect me to own it.

05:38:24.640 --> 05:38:28.860
Lady Catherine seemed quite astonished at not receiving a direct answer,

05:38:28.860 --> 05:38:32.500
and Elizabeth suspected herself to be the first creature

05:38:32.500 --> 05:38:37.800
who had ever dared to trifle with so much dignified impertinence.

05:38:38.780 --> 05:38:41.080
You cannot be more than twenty, I am sure.

05:38:41.140 --> 05:38:43.640
Therefore, you need not conceal your age.

05:38:44.280 --> 05:38:46.040
I am not one in twenty.

05:38:47.560 --> 05:38:52.820
When the gentleman had joined them and tea was over, the card tables were placed.

05:38:53.220 --> 05:38:56.680
Lady Catherine, Sir William, and Mr. and Mrs. Collins

05:38:56.680 --> 05:39:01.760
sat down to quadrille, and Mrs. de Bourgh chose to play at casino.

05:39:02.240 --> 05:39:06.800
The two girls had the honour of assisting Mrs. Jenkinson to make up her party.

05:39:07.520 --> 05:39:10.500
Their table was superlatively stupid.

05:39:11.380 --> 05:39:15.020
Scarcely a syllable was uttered that did not relate to the game,

05:39:15.360 --> 05:39:20.300
except when Mrs. Jenkinson expressed her fears of Mr. Bourgh's being too hot,

05:39:20.680 --> 05:39:24.400
or too cold, or having too much or too little light.

05:39:24.960 --> 05:39:27.580
A great deal more passed at the other table.

05:39:27.960 --> 05:39:33.060
Lady Catherine was generally speaking, stating the mistakes of the three others,

05:39:33.400 --> 05:39:36.020
or relating some anecdote of herself.

05:39:36.860 --> 05:39:41.240
Mr. Collins was employed in agreeing to everything her ladyship said,

05:39:41.700 --> 05:39:47.320
thanking her for every fish he won, and apologizing if he thought he won too many.

05:39:48.200 --> 05:39:50.200
Mr. William did not say much.

05:39:50.600 --> 05:39:54.220
He was storing his memory with anecdotes and noble names.

05:39:55.660 --> 05:39:59.760
When Lady Catherine and her daughter had played as long as they chose,

05:40:00.160 --> 05:40:03.740
the tables were broken up, the carriage was offered to Mrs. Collins,

05:40:04.260 --> 05:40:06.800
gratefully accepted, and immediately ordered.

05:40:07.280 --> 05:40:11.300
The party then gathered round the fire to hear Lady Catherine determine

05:40:11.300 --> 05:40:13.740
what weather they were to have on the moral.

05:40:14.440 --> 05:40:17.980
From these instructions they were summoned by the arrival of the coach,

05:40:18.300 --> 05:40:22.060
and with many speeches of thankfulness on Mr. Collins's side,

05:40:22.060 --> 05:40:25.320
and as many bows on Sir William's they departed.

05:40:26.100 --> 05:40:30.780
As soon as they'd driven from the door, Elizabeth was called on by her cousin

05:40:30.780 --> 05:40:34.260
to give her opinion of all that she had seen at Rosings,

05:40:34.520 --> 05:40:39.000
which for Charlotte's sake she made more favourable than it really was.

05:40:39.480 --> 05:40:42.860
But her commendation, though costing her some trouble,

05:40:43.200 --> 05:40:46.160
could by no means satisfy Mr. Collins,

05:40:46.440 --> 05:40:51.700
and he was very soon obliged to take her ladyship's praise into his own hands.

05:41:14.520 --> 05:41:18.560
Sir William stayed only a week at Hunsford, but his visit was long enough to convince

05:41:18.560 --> 05:41:23.360
him of his daughter's being most comfortably settled, and of her possessing such a husband

05:41:23.360 --> 05:41:26.500
and such a neighbour as we're not often met with.

05:41:26.500 --> 05:41:31.320
While Sir William was with them, Mr. Collins devoted his morning to driving him out in

05:41:31.320 --> 05:41:32.880
his gig and showing him the country.

05:41:33.320 --> 05:41:38.200
But when he went away, the whole family returned to their usual employments, and Elizabeth

05:41:38.200 --> 05:41:42.360
was thankful to find that they did not see more of her cousin by the alteration, for

05:41:42.360 --> 05:41:46.720
the chief of the time between breakfast and dinner was now passed by him either at work

05:41:46.720 --> 05:41:50.880
in the garden, or in reading and writing, and looking out of the window in his own bookroom

05:41:50.880 --> 05:41:51.960
which fronted the road.

05:41:52.740 --> 05:41:54.880
The room in which the ladies sat was backwards.

05:41:54.880 --> 05:41:59.800
Elizabeth, at first, rather wondered that Charlotte should not prefer the dining parlor

05:41:59.800 --> 05:42:00.620
for common use.

05:42:00.940 --> 05:42:05.420
It was a better-sized room and had a more pleasant aspect, but she soon saw that her

05:42:05.420 --> 05:42:09.700
friend had an excellent reason for what she did, for Mr. Collins would undoubtedly have

05:42:09.700 --> 05:42:14.700
been much less in his own apartment had they sat in one equally lively, and she gave Charlotte

05:42:14.700 --> 05:42:15.840
credit for the arrangement.

05:42:16.480 --> 05:42:20.320
From the drawing-room they could distinguish nothing in the lane, and were indebted to

05:42:20.320 --> 05:42:24.940
Mr. Collins for the knowledge of what carriages went along and how often, especially, Miss

05:42:24.940 --> 05:42:30.020
Debord drove by in her Phaeton, which he never failed coming to inform them of, though it

05:42:30.020 --> 05:42:31.160
happened almost every day.

05:42:31.740 --> 05:42:36.440
She not unfrequently stopped at the parsonage, and had a few minutes' conversation with Charlotte,

05:42:36.460 --> 05:42:39.060
but was scarcely ever prevailed upon to get out.

05:42:40.060 --> 05:42:44.880
Very few days passed in which Mr. Collins did not walk to Rosings, and not many in which

05:42:44.880 --> 05:42:49.260
his wife did not think it necessary to go likewise, till Elizabeth recollected that

05:42:49.260 --> 05:42:51.680
there might be other family livings to be disposed of.

05:42:51.940 --> 05:42:54.560
She could not understand the sacrifice of so many hours.

05:42:55.260 --> 05:42:59.180
Now and then they were honoured with a call from her ladyship, and nothing escaped her

05:42:59.180 --> 05:43:01.740
observation that was passing in the room during these visits.

05:43:02.160 --> 05:43:06.940
She examined into their employments, looked at their work, and advised them to do it differently,

05:43:07.500 --> 05:43:12.520
found fault with the arrangement of the furniture, or detected the housemaid in negligence, and

05:43:12.520 --> 05:43:17.100
if she accepted any refreshment, seemed to do it only for the sake of finding out that

05:43:17.100 --> 05:43:20.600
Mrs. Collins's joints of meat were too large for her family.

05:43:21.320 --> 05:43:25.200
Elizabeth soon perceived that, though this great lady was not in commission of the piece

05:43:25.200 --> 05:43:30.640
of the county, she was a most active magistrate in her own parish, the minutest concerns of

05:43:30.640 --> 05:43:34.900
which were carried to her by Mr. Collins, and whenever any of the cottagers were disposed

05:43:34.900 --> 05:43:39.760
to be quarrelsome, discontented, or too poor, she sallied forth into the village to settle

05:43:39.760 --> 05:43:43.860
their differences, silence their complaints, and scold them into harmony and plenty.

05:43:43.860 --> 05:43:49.540
The entertainment of dining at Rosings was repeated about twice a week, and, allowing

05:43:49.540 --> 05:43:54.200
for the loss of Sir William, and there being only one card-table in the evening, every

05:43:54.200 --> 05:43:56.700
such entertainment was the counterpart of the first.

05:43:57.200 --> 05:44:01.820
Their other engagements were few, as the style of living in the neighbourhood in general was

05:44:01.820 --> 05:44:03.400
beyond Mr. Collins's reach.

05:44:04.060 --> 05:44:08.420
This, however, was no evil to Elizabeth, and upon the whole she spent her time comfortably

05:44:08.420 --> 05:44:08.920
enough.

05:44:09.260 --> 05:44:13.400
There were half-hours of pleasant conversation with Charlotte, and the weather was so fine

05:44:13.400 --> 05:44:16.860
for the time of year that she had often great enjoyment out of doors.

05:44:17.480 --> 05:44:21.340
Her favourite walk, and where she frequently went while the others were calling on Lady

05:44:21.340 --> 05:44:26.000
Catherine, was along the open grove which edged that side of the park, where there was

05:44:26.000 --> 05:44:30.480
a nice sheltered path which no one seemed to value but herself, and where she felt beyond

05:44:30.480 --> 05:44:32.460
the reach of Lady Catherine's curiosity.

05:44:33.340 --> 05:44:38.520
In this quiet way, the first fortnight of her visit soon passed away, Easter was approaching,

05:44:38.840 --> 05:44:42.780
and the week preceding it was to bring an addition to the family at Rosings, which,

05:44:42.780 --> 05:44:44.860
in so small a circle, must be important.

05:44:45.720 --> 05:44:50.200
Elizabeth had heard soon after her arrival that Mr. Darcy was expected there in the course

05:44:50.200 --> 05:44:54.420
of a few weeks, and though there were not many of her acquaintances whom she did not

05:44:54.420 --> 05:44:59.840
prefer, his coming would furnish one comparatively new to look at in their Rosings parties, and

05:44:59.840 --> 05:45:04.280
she might be amused in seeing how hopeless Miss Bingley's designs on him were by his

05:45:04.280 --> 05:45:09.480
behaviour to his cousin, for whom he was evidently destined by Lady Catherine, who talked of his

05:45:09.480 --> 05:45:13.660
coming with the greatest satisfaction, spoke of him in terms of the highest admiration,

05:45:14.000 --> 05:45:18.520
and seemed almost angry to find that he had already been frequently seen by Miss Lucas

05:45:18.520 --> 05:45:19.180
and herself.

05:45:20.060 --> 05:45:24.360
His arrival was soon known at the parsonage, for Mr. Collins was walking the whole morning

05:45:24.360 --> 05:45:29.020
within view of the lodges opening into Huntsford Lane, in order to have the earliest assurance

05:45:29.020 --> 05:45:33.900
of it, and after making his bow as the carriage turned into the park, hurried home with the

05:45:33.900 --> 05:45:34.640
great intelligence.

05:45:34.640 --> 05:45:40.940
On the following morning he hastened to Rosings to pay his respects. There were two nephews

05:45:40.940 --> 05:45:45.340
of Lady Catherine to require them, for Mr. Darcy had brought with him a Colonel Fitzwilliam,

05:45:45.500 --> 05:45:50.480
the younger son of his lord, and, to the great surprise of all the party, when Mr. Collins

05:45:50.480 --> 05:45:56.020
returned, the gentleman accompanied him. Charlotte had seen them from her husband's room crossing

05:45:56.020 --> 05:46:00.360
the road, and immediately, running into the other, told the girls what an honour they

05:46:00.360 --> 05:46:01.320
might expect, adding,

05:46:01.640 --> 05:46:05.920
I may thank you, Eliza, for this piece of civility. Mr. Darcy would never have come

05:46:05.920 --> 05:46:07.500
so soon to wait upon me.

05:46:08.540 --> 05:46:12.780
Elizabeth had scarcely time to disclaim all right to the compliment, before their approach

05:46:12.780 --> 05:46:16.860
was announced by the doorbell, and shortly afterwards the three gentlemen entered the

05:46:16.860 --> 05:46:22.300
room. Colonel Fitzwilliam, who led the way, was about thirty, not handsome, but in person

05:46:22.300 --> 05:46:27.120
and addressed most truly the gentleman. Mr. Darcy looked just as he had been used to look

05:46:27.120 --> 05:46:32.440
in Hertfordshire, paid his compliments with the usual reserve to Mrs. Collins, and, whatever

05:46:32.440 --> 05:46:36.940
might be his feelings towards her friend, met her with every appearance of composure.

05:46:37.340 --> 05:46:40.480
Elizabeth merely curtsied to him without saying a word.

05:46:41.400 --> 05:46:45.560
Colonel Fitzwilliam entered into a conversation directly with the readiness and ease of a

05:46:45.560 --> 05:46:50.980
well-bred man, and talked very pleasantly, but his cousin, after having addressed a slight

05:46:50.980 --> 05:46:55.520
observation on the house and garden to Mrs. Collins, sat for some time without speaking

05:46:55.520 --> 05:46:56.140
to anybody.

05:46:56.900 --> 05:47:01.320
At length, however, his civility was so far awakened as to inquire of Elizabeth after

05:47:01.320 --> 05:47:05.820
the health of her family. She answered him in the usual way, and after a moment's pause,

05:47:05.860 --> 05:47:06.160
added,

05:47:06.740 --> 05:47:10.720
My oldest sister has been in town these three months. Have you never happened to see her

05:47:10.720 --> 05:47:11.000
there?

05:47:11.980 --> 05:47:16.640
She was perfectly sensible that he never had, but she wished to see whether he would betray

05:47:16.640 --> 05:47:20.620
any consciousness of what had passed between the Bingleys and Jane, and she thought he

05:47:20.620 --> 05:47:24.600
looked a little confused as he answered that he had never been so fortunate as to meet

05:47:24.600 --> 05:47:29.720
Miss Bennet. The subject was pursued no farther, and the gentleman soon afterwards went away.

05:47:49.200 --> 05:47:53.480
Colonel Fitzwilliam's manners were very much admired at the Parsonage, and the ladies all

05:47:53.480 --> 05:47:57.180
felt that he must add considerably to the pleasures of their engagements at Rosings.

05:47:57.180 --> 05:48:02.340
It was some days, however, before they received any invitation, dither, for while there were

05:48:02.340 --> 05:48:07.260
visitors in the house, they could not be necessary, and it was not till Easter day, almost a week

05:48:07.260 --> 05:48:11.660
after the gentleman's arrival, that they were honoured by such an attention, and then they

05:48:11.660 --> 05:48:14.460
were merely asked on leaving church to come there in the evening.

05:48:15.400 --> 05:48:18.840
For the last week they had seen very little of Lady Catherine or her daughter.

05:48:19.240 --> 05:48:23.600
Colonel Fitzwilliam had called at the Parsonage more than once during the time, but Mr. Darcy

05:48:23.600 --> 05:48:24.960
they had only seen at church.

05:48:25.520 --> 05:48:30.720
The invitation was accepted, of course, and at a proper hour they joined the party in

05:48:30.720 --> 05:48:32.060
Lady Catherine's drawing-room.

05:48:32.620 --> 05:48:36.860
Her ladyship received them civilly, but it was plain that their company was by no means

05:48:36.860 --> 05:48:39.400
so acceptable as when she could get nobody else.

05:48:39.820 --> 05:48:45.080
And she was, in fact, almost engrossed by her nephews, speaking to them, especially

05:48:45.080 --> 05:48:48.440
to Darcy, much more than to any other person in the room.

05:48:49.600 --> 05:48:52.140
Colonel Fitzwilliam seemed really glad to see them.

05:48:52.140 --> 05:48:57.440
Anything was a welcome relief to him at Rosings, and Mrs. Collins's pretty friend had moreover

05:48:57.440 --> 05:48:58.800
caught his fancy very much.

05:48:59.340 --> 05:49:04.740
He now seated himself by her, and talked so agreeably of Kent and Hertfordshire, of travelling

05:49:04.740 --> 05:49:09.480
and staying at home, of new books and music, that Elizabeth had never been half so well

05:49:09.480 --> 05:49:14.000
entertained in that room before, and they conversed with so much spirit and flow as

05:49:14.000 --> 05:49:17.820
to draw the attention of Lady Catherine herself, as well as of Mr. Darcy.

05:49:18.360 --> 05:49:23.760
His eyes had been soon and repeatedly turned toward them, with a look of curiosity, and

05:49:23.760 --> 05:49:28.460
that her ladyship, after a while, shared the feeling, was more openly acknowledged, for

05:49:28.460 --> 05:49:30.020
she did not scruple to call out,

05:49:30.360 --> 05:49:32.520
"'What is that you are saying, Fitzwilliam?

05:49:32.560 --> 05:49:34.180
What is it you are talking of?

05:49:34.220 --> 05:49:35.640
What are you telling Miss Bennet?

05:49:35.800 --> 05:49:37.740
Let me hear what it is.'

05:49:37.740 --> 05:49:42.540
"'We are speaking of music, madam,' he said, when no longer able to avoid a reply.

05:49:42.940 --> 05:49:44.020
"'Of music!

05:49:44.040 --> 05:49:45.660
Then pray, speak aloud.

05:49:45.660 --> 05:49:47.960
"'It is of all subjects my delight.

05:49:48.160 --> 05:49:51.680
I must have my share in the conversation if you are speaking of music.

05:49:52.380 --> 05:49:57.000
There are few people in England, I suppose, who have more true enjoyment of music than

05:49:57.000 --> 05:49:59.640
myself, or a better natural taste.

05:49:59.900 --> 05:50:02.940
If I had ever learnt, I should have been a great proficient.

05:50:03.460 --> 05:50:06.120
And so would Anne, if her health had allowed her to apply.

05:50:06.640 --> 05:50:09.400
I am confident that she would have performed delightfully.

05:50:09.620 --> 05:50:12.360
How does Georgiana get on, Darcy?'

05:50:12.360 --> 05:50:15.920
Mr. Darcy spoke with affectionate praise of his sister's proficiency.

05:50:17.060 --> 05:50:20.280
"'I am very glad to hear such a good account of her,' said Lady Catherine,

05:50:20.320 --> 05:50:25.280
"'and pray, tell her for me that she cannot expect to excel if she does not practice a

05:50:25.280 --> 05:50:26.120
good deal.'

05:50:27.180 --> 05:50:31.260
"'I assure you, madam,' he replied, that she does not need such advice.

05:50:31.520 --> 05:50:33.480
She practices very constantly.

05:50:34.140 --> 05:50:35.420
"'So much the better.

05:50:35.620 --> 05:50:40.460
It cannot be done too much, and when I next write to her, I shall charge her not to neglect

05:50:40.460 --> 05:50:41.500
it on any account.

05:50:42.020 --> 05:50:46.680
"'I often tell young ladies that no excellence in music is to be acquired without constant

05:50:46.680 --> 05:50:47.240
practice.

05:50:47.520 --> 05:50:52.240
"'I have told Miss Bennet several times that she will never play really well unless she

05:50:52.240 --> 05:50:53.080
practices more.

05:50:53.200 --> 05:50:57.880
And though Mrs. Collins has no instrument, she is very welcome, as I have often told

05:50:57.880 --> 05:51:02.780
her, to come to Rosings every day and play on the pianoforte in Mrs. Jenkinson's room.

05:51:02.960 --> 05:51:06.700
She would be a nobody's way, you know, in that part of the house.'

05:51:06.700 --> 05:51:11.460
Mr. Darcy looked a little ashamed of his aunt's ill-breeding, and made no answer.

05:51:12.240 --> 05:51:16.680
When coffee was over, Colonel Fitzwilliam reminded Elizabeth of having promised to play

05:51:16.680 --> 05:51:19.380
to him, and she sat down directly to the instrument.

05:51:19.880 --> 05:51:21.320
He drew a chair near her.

05:51:21.700 --> 05:51:26.700
Lady Catherine listened to half a song, and then talked, as before, to her other nephew,

05:51:27.140 --> 05:51:31.260
till the latter walked away from her, and, making with his usual deliberation towards

05:51:31.260 --> 05:51:36.480
the pianoforte, stationed himself so as to command a full view of the fair performer's

05:51:37.000 --> 05:51:37.320
continence.

05:51:37.660 --> 05:51:42.500
Elizabeth saw what he was doing, and at the first convenient pause, turned to him, with

05:51:42.500 --> 05:51:44.080
an arched smile, and said,

05:51:44.560 --> 05:51:48.400
"'Do you mean to frighten me, Mr. Darcy, by coming all in this state to hear me?

05:51:48.400 --> 05:51:51.760
I will not be alarmed, though your sister does play so well.

05:51:52.140 --> 05:51:56.340
There is a stubbornness about me that never can bear to be frightened at the will of others.

05:51:56.720 --> 05:52:00.200
My courage always rises at every attempt to intimidate me.'

05:52:01.260 --> 05:52:05.780
"'I shall not say you are mistaken,' he replied, "'because you could not really believe me

05:52:05.780 --> 05:52:10.100
to entertain any design of alarming you, and I have had the pleasure of your acquaintance

05:52:10.100 --> 05:52:14.860
long enough to know that you find great enjoyment in occasionally professing opinions which

05:52:14.860 --> 05:52:17.880
are, in fact, not your own.'"

05:52:17.880 --> 05:52:22.140
Elizabeth laughed heartily at this picture of herself, and said to Colonel Fitzwilliam,

05:52:22.260 --> 05:52:26.400
"'Your cousin will give you a very pretty notion of me, and teach you not to believe

05:52:26.400 --> 05:52:27.280
a word I say.

05:52:27.740 --> 05:52:32.520
I'm particularly unlucky in meeting with a person so able to expose my real character

05:52:32.520 --> 05:52:36.820
in a part of the world where I'd hope to pass myself off with some degree of credit.

05:52:37.540 --> 05:52:43.120
Indeed, Mr. Darcy, it is very ungenerous in you to mention all that you knew to my disadvantage

05:52:43.120 --> 05:52:49.000
in Hertfordshire, and give me leave to say very impolitic, too, for it's provoking me

05:52:49.000 --> 05:52:53.450
to retaliate, and such things may come out as will shock your relations to hear.'

05:52:54.580 --> 05:52:57.540
"'I'm not afraid of you,' he said, smilingly.

05:52:58.380 --> 05:53:02.420
"'Pray let me hear what you have to accuse him of,' cried Colonel Fitzwilliam.

05:53:02.420 --> 05:53:04.900
"'I should like to know how he behaves among strangers.'

05:53:05.780 --> 05:53:10.440
"'Oh, you shall hear then, but prepare yourself for something very dreadful.

05:53:10.700 --> 05:53:16.040
The first time of my ever seeing him in Hertfordshire, you must know, was at a ball.

05:53:16.380 --> 05:53:19.320
And at this ball, what do you think he did?

05:53:19.720 --> 05:53:25.220
He danced only four dances, though gentlemen were scarce, and to my certain knowledge,

05:53:25.280 --> 05:53:28.060
more than one young lady was sitting down in want of a partner.

05:53:28.620 --> 05:53:30.560
Mr. Darcy, you cannot deny the fact.'

05:53:31.760 --> 05:53:37.080
"'I had not at that time the honour of knowing any lady in the assembly beyond my own party.'

05:53:38.480 --> 05:53:42.320
"'True, and nobody can ever be introduced in a ballroom.

05:53:42.780 --> 05:53:45.100
Well, Colonel Fitzwilliam, what do I play next?

05:53:45.120 --> 05:53:46.340
My fingers wait your orders.'

05:53:48.000 --> 05:53:51.460
"'Perhaps,' said Darcy, I should have judged better had I sought an introduction,

05:53:51.940 --> 05:53:54.640
but I'm ill-qualified to recommend myself to strangers.'

05:53:55.540 --> 05:53:58.800
"'Shall we ask your cousin the reason of this?' said Elizabeth,

05:53:58.940 --> 05:54:00.380
still addressing Colonel Fitzwilliam.

05:54:00.380 --> 05:54:04.800
"'Shall we ask him why a man of sense and education, who's lived in the world,

05:54:04.840 --> 05:54:07.760
is ill-qualified to recommend himself to strangers?'

05:54:07.760 --> 05:54:12.080
"'Oh, I can answer your question,' said Fitzwilliam, without applying to him.

05:54:12.360 --> 05:54:14.240
It's because he will not give himself the trouble.'

05:54:15.540 --> 05:54:19.460
"'I certainly have not the talent which some people possess,' said Darcy,

05:54:19.880 --> 05:54:22.860
of conversing easily with those I have never seen before.

05:54:23.040 --> 05:54:27.160
I cannot catch their tone of conversation, or appear interested in their concerns,

05:54:27.180 --> 05:54:28.420
as I often see done.'

05:54:30.380 --> 05:54:35.260
"'My fingers,' said Elizabeth, do not move over this instrument in the masterly manner

05:54:35.260 --> 05:54:36.900
which I see so many women's do.

05:54:37.320 --> 05:54:41.320
They have not the same force of rapidity, and do not produce the same expression.

05:54:41.880 --> 05:54:44.200
But then I have always supposed it to be my own fault,

05:54:44.460 --> 05:54:46.340
because I will not take the trouble of practicing.

05:54:46.960 --> 05:54:52.140
It is not that I do not believe my fingers as capable as any other woman's of superior execution.'

05:54:53.460 --> 05:54:55.280
Darcy smiled, and said,

05:54:55.660 --> 05:54:56.960
"'You are perfectly right.

05:54:57.160 --> 05:54:59.060
You have employed your time much better.

05:54:59.060 --> 05:55:02.760
No one admitted to the privilege of hearing you can think anything wanting.

05:55:03.680 --> 05:55:05.700
We neither of us perform to strangers.'

05:55:07.100 --> 05:55:09.020
Here they were interrupted by Lady Catherine,

05:55:09.340 --> 05:55:11.300
who called out to know what they were talking of.

05:55:11.780 --> 05:55:13.900
Elizabeth immediately began playing again.

05:55:14.440 --> 05:55:17.840
Lady Catherine approached, and after listening for a few minutes, said to Darcy,

05:55:18.980 --> 05:55:22.260
"'Miss Bennet would not play all of this if she practiced more,

05:55:22.340 --> 05:55:24.500
and could have the advantage of a London master.

05:55:24.880 --> 05:55:28.580
She has a very good notion of fingering, though her taste is not equal to Anne's.

05:55:28.580 --> 05:55:32.420
Anne would have been a delightful performer had her health allowed her to learn.'

05:55:33.740 --> 05:55:37.720
Elizabeth looked at Darcy to see how cordially he assented to his cousin's praise.

05:55:38.300 --> 05:55:42.680
But neither at that moment nor at any other could she discern any symptom of love.

05:55:42.900 --> 05:55:45.400
And from the whole of his behaviour to Miss de Bourgh,

05:55:45.600 --> 05:55:47.480
she derived discomfort from Miss Bingley,

05:55:47.940 --> 05:55:52.220
that he might have been just as likely to marry her had she been his relation.

05:55:53.380 --> 05:55:56.460
Lady Catherine continued her remarks on Elizabeth's performance,

05:55:56.460 --> 05:55:59.900
mixing them with many instructions on execution and taste.

05:56:00.540 --> 05:56:03.280
Elizabeth received them all with the forbearance of civility,

05:56:03.600 --> 05:56:05.160
and at the request of the gentleman,

05:56:05.500 --> 05:56:09.440
remained at the instrument till her ladyship's carriage was ready to take them all home.

05:56:30.640 --> 05:56:36.660
Elizabeth was sitting by herself the next morning, and writing to Jane, while Mrs Collins

05:56:36.660 --> 05:56:41.460
and Maria were gone on business into the village, when she was startled by a ring at the door,

05:56:41.680 --> 05:56:47.040
the certain signal of a visitor. As she had heard no carriage, she thought it not unlikely

05:56:47.040 --> 05:56:52.040
to be Lady Catherine, and under that apprehension was putting away her half-finished letter

05:56:52.040 --> 05:56:57.560
that she might escape all impertinent questions, when the door opened, and, to her very great

05:56:57.560 --> 05:57:04.980
surprise, Mr Darcy, and Mr Darcy only, entered the room. He seemed astonished, too, on finding

05:57:04.980 --> 05:57:09.780
her alone, and apologised for his intrusion by letting her know that he had understood

05:57:09.780 --> 05:57:16.100
all the ladies were to be within. They then sat down, and when her enquiries after rosings

05:57:16.100 --> 05:57:21.520
were made, seemed in danger of sinking into total silence. It was absolutely necessary,

05:57:21.720 --> 05:57:25.840
therefore, to think of something, and in this emergence, recollecting when she had seen

05:57:25.840 --> 05:57:30.440
him last in Hertfordshire, and feeling curious to know what he would say on the subject of

05:57:30.440 --> 05:57:32.580
departure, she observed,

05:57:33.380 --> 05:57:38.500
How very suddenly you all quitted Netherfield last November, Mr Darcy. It must have been

05:57:38.500 --> 05:57:44.060
a most agreeable surprise to Mr Bingley to see you all after him so soon, for if I recollect

05:57:44.060 --> 05:57:49.040
right, he went about the day before. He and his sisters were well, I hope, when you left

05:57:49.040 --> 05:57:49.420
London?

05:57:50.620 --> 05:57:52.340
Perfectly so. I thank you.

05:57:52.960 --> 05:57:57.480
She found that she was to perceive no other answer, and after a short pause, added,

05:57:58.120 --> 05:58:02.860
I think I have understood that Mr Bingley has not much idea of ever returning to Netherfield

05:58:02.860 --> 05:58:08.140
again. I have never heard him say so, but it is probable that he may spend very little

05:58:08.140 --> 05:58:13.420
of his time there in the future. He has many friends, and is at a time of life when friends

05:58:13.420 --> 05:58:18.060
and engagements are continually increasing. If he means to be but little at Netherfield,

05:58:18.340 --> 05:58:22.480
it would be better for the neighbourhood that should give up the place entirely, for then

05:58:22.480 --> 05:58:27.920
we might possibly get a settled family there. But perhaps Mr Bingley did not take the house

05:58:27.920 --> 05:58:32.620
so much for the convenience of the neighbourhood as for his own, and we must expect him to

05:58:32.620 --> 05:58:35.220
keep it, or quit it, on the same principle.

05:58:36.080 --> 05:58:40.300
I should not be surprised, said Darcy, if he were to give it up as soon as any eligible

05:58:40.300 --> 05:58:46.900
purchase offers. Elizabeth made no answer. She was afraid of talking longer of his friend,

05:58:47.200 --> 05:58:51.740
and having nothing else to say, was now determined to leave the trouble of finding a subject

05:58:51.740 --> 05:58:58.760
to him. He took the hint, and soon began with, This seems a very comfortable house. Lady

05:58:58.760 --> 05:59:03.200
Catherine, I believe, did a great deal to it when Mr Collins first came to Hunsford.

05:59:03.840 --> 05:59:08.820
I believe she did. I am sure she could not have bestowed her kindness on a more grateful

05:59:08.820 --> 05:59:15.900
object. Mr Collins appears to be very fortunate in his choice of a wife. Yes, indeed, his

05:59:15.900 --> 05:59:20.600
friend may well rejoice in his having met with one of the very few sensible women who

05:59:20.600 --> 05:59:26.400
would have accepted him, or made him happy if they had. My friend has an excellent understanding,

05:59:26.960 --> 05:59:30.980
though I am not certain that I consider her marrying Mr Collins as the wisest thing she

05:59:30.980 --> 05:59:36.500
ever did. She seems perfectly happy, however, and in a prudential light it is certainly

05:59:36.500 --> 05:59:42.280
a very good match for her. It must be very agreeable for her to be settled within so

05:59:42.280 --> 05:59:48.480
easy a distance of her own family and friends. An easy distance, do you call it? It is nearly

05:59:48.480 --> 05:59:55.040
50 miles. And what is 50 miles of good road? Little more than half a day's journey. Yes,

05:59:55.140 --> 06:00:01.160
I call it a very easy distance. I should never have considered the distance as one of the

06:00:01.160 --> 06:00:04.960
advantages of the match, cried Elizabeth. I should never have said Mrs Collins were

06:00:04.960 --> 06:00:10.780
settled near her family. It is proof of your own attachment to Hertfordshire. Anything

06:00:10.780 --> 06:00:16.420
beyond the neighbourhood of Longbourn, I suppose, would appear far. As he spoke, there was a

06:00:16.420 --> 06:00:21.020
sort of smile which Elizabeth fancied she understood. He must be supposing her to be

06:00:21.020 --> 06:00:26.380
thinking of Jane and Netherfield, and she blushed as she answered. I do not mean to

06:00:26.380 --> 06:00:31.360
say that a woman may not be settled too near her family. The far and the near must be relative

06:00:31.360 --> 06:00:37.040
and depend on many varying circumstances. Where there is fortune to make the expenses

06:00:37.040 --> 06:00:43.720
of travelling unimportant, distance becomes no evil. But that is not the case here. Mr

06:00:43.720 --> 06:00:48.120
and Mrs Collins have a comfortable income, but not such a one as will allow frequent

06:00:48.120 --> 06:00:53.280
journeys. And I am persuaded my friend would not call herself near her family under less

06:00:53.280 --> 06:01:00.960
than half the present distance. Mr Darcy drew his chair a little towards her and said, You

06:01:00.960 --> 06:01:06.140
cannot have a right to such a very strong local attachment. You cannot have always been

06:01:06.140 --> 06:01:12.100
at Longbourn. Elizabeth looked surprised. The gentleman experienced some change of feeling.

06:01:12.100 --> 06:01:17.700
He drew back his chair, took a newspaper from a table, and glancing over it said, in a colder

06:01:17.700 --> 06:01:23.920
voice, Are you pleased with Kent? A short dialogue on the subject of the country ensued,

06:01:24.240 --> 06:01:28.980
on either side calm and concise, and soon put an end to by the entrance of Charlotte

06:01:28.980 --> 06:01:35.440
and her sister just returned from her walk. The tete-a-tete surprised them. Mr Darcy related

06:01:35.440 --> 06:01:39.700
the mistake, which had occasioned his intruding on Miss Bennet, and after sitting a few minutes

06:01:39.700 --> 06:01:45.660
longer without saying much to anybody, went away. What can be the meaning of this, said

06:01:45.660 --> 06:01:50.200
Charlotte as soon as he was gone? My dear Eliza, he must be in love with you, or he

06:01:50.200 --> 06:01:55.860
would never have called us in this familiar way. But when Elizabeth told of his silence,

06:01:56.160 --> 06:02:00.940
it did not seem very likely, even to Charlotte's wishes, to be the case, and after various

06:02:00.940 --> 06:02:05.520
conjectures they could at last only suppose his visit to proceed from the difficulty of

06:02:05.520 --> 06:02:11.240
to do, which was the more probable from the time of year. All field sports were over.

06:02:11.920 --> 06:02:16.120
Within doors there was Lady Catherine, books, and a billiard table, but gentlemen cannot

06:02:16.120 --> 06:02:21.420
always be within doors, and in the nearness of the parsonage, or the pleasantness of the

06:02:21.420 --> 06:02:26.200
walk to it, or of the people who lived in it, the two cousins found a temptation from

06:02:26.200 --> 06:02:31.340
this period of walking thither almost every day. They called at various times of the morning,

06:02:31.340 --> 06:02:35.600
sometimes separately, sometimes together, and now and then accompanied by their aunt.

06:02:36.360 --> 06:02:41.140
It was plain to them all that Colonel Fitzwilliam came because he had pleasure in their society,

06:02:41.740 --> 06:02:46.260
a persuasion which of course recommended him still more, and Elizabeth was reminded by

06:02:46.260 --> 06:02:51.300
her own satisfaction in being with him, as well as by her evident admiration of her,

06:02:51.920 --> 06:02:56.860
of her former favourite George Wickham, and though in comparing them she saw there was

06:02:56.860 --> 06:03:02.020
less captivating softness in Colonel Fitzwilliam's manners, she believed he might have the best

06:03:02.020 --> 06:03:08.340
informed mind. But why Mr Darcy came so often to the parsonage, it was more difficult to

06:03:08.340 --> 06:03:13.380
understand. It could not be for society, as he frequently sat there ten minutes together

06:03:13.380 --> 06:03:18.540
without opening his lips, and when he did speak, it seemed the effort of necessity rather

06:03:18.540 --> 06:03:24.200
than of choice, a sacrifice to propriety, not a pleasure to himself. He seldom appeared

06:03:24.200 --> 06:03:30.000
really animated. Mrs Collins knew not what to make of him. Colonel Fitzwilliam's occasionally

06:03:30.000 --> 06:03:34.220
laughing at his stupidity proved that he was generally different, which her own knowledge

06:03:34.220 --> 06:03:39.040
of him could not have told her. And as she would like to believe that this changed the

06:03:39.040 --> 06:03:44.380
effect of love, and the object of that love, her friend Eliza, she set herself seriously

06:03:44.380 --> 06:03:49.560
to work to find it out. She watched him whenever they were at Rosings, and whenever he came

06:03:49.560 --> 06:03:55.240
to Hunsford, but without much success. He certainly looked at her friend a great deal,

06:03:55.420 --> 06:04:01.620
but the expression of that look was disputable. It was an earnest, steadfast gaze, but she

06:04:01.620 --> 06:04:06.340
often doubted whether there was much admiration in it, and sometimes it seemed nothing but

06:04:06.340 --> 06:04:12.220
absence of mind. She had once or twice suggested to Elizabeth the possibility of his being

06:04:12.220 --> 06:04:16.960
partial to her, but Elizabeth always laughed at the idea, and Mrs Collins did not think

06:04:16.960 --> 06:04:21.840
it right to press the subject from the danger of raising expectations which might only end

06:04:21.840 --> 06:04:27.160
in disappointment, for in her opinion it admitted not a doubt that all her friend's dislike

06:04:27.160 --> 06:04:33.360
would vanish if she could suppose him to be in her power. In her kind schemes for Elizabeth,

06:04:33.620 --> 06:04:37.740
she sometimes planned her marrying Colonel Fitzwilliam. He was beyond comparison the

06:04:37.740 --> 06:04:42.860
most pleasant man. He certainly admired her, and his situation in life was most eligible.

06:04:43.420 --> 06:04:48.920
But to counterbalance these advantages, Mr Darcy had considerable patronage in the church,

06:04:49.100 --> 06:04:55.180
and his cousin could have none at all

06:04:56.740 --> 06:05:01.780
More than once did Elizabeth, in her ramble within the park, unexpectedly meet Mr Darcy.

06:05:02.560 --> 06:05:07.280
She felt all the perverseness of the mischance that should bring him when no one else was brought,

06:05:07.580 --> 06:05:12.220
and, to prevent its ever happening again, took care to inform him at first that it was

06:05:12.220 --> 06:05:18.760
her favourite haunt of hers. How it could occur a second time, therefore, was very odd. Yet it did,

06:05:19.140 --> 06:05:25.580
and even a third. It seemed like wilful ill-nature, or a voluntary penance, for on those occasions it

06:05:25.580 --> 06:05:30.380
was not merely a few formal inquiries and an awkward pause and then away, but he actually

06:05:30.380 --> 06:05:36.140
thought it necessary to turn back and walk with her. He never said a great deal, nor did she give

06:05:36.140 --> 06:05:40.900
herself the trouble of talking or of listening much, but it struck her in the course of their

06:05:40.900 --> 06:05:46.180
third rencontre that he was asking some odd, unconnected questions about her pleasure in being

06:05:46.180 --> 06:05:51.860
at Hunsford, her love of solitary walks, and her opinion of Mr and Mrs Collins's happiness,

06:05:52.320 --> 06:05:56.460
and that in speaking of Rosings and her not perfectly understanding the house,

06:05:56.760 --> 06:06:01.320
he seemed to expect that whenever she came into Kent again she would be staying there too.

06:06:01.840 --> 06:06:06.340
His words seemed to imply it. Could he have Colonel Fitzwilliam in his thoughts?

06:06:06.900 --> 06:06:12.720
She supposed, if he meant anything, he must mean an allusion to what might arise in that quarter.

06:06:13.320 --> 06:06:17.780
It distressed her a little, and she was quite glad to find herself at the gate in the pails

06:06:17.780 --> 06:06:24.400
opposite the parsonage. She was engaged one day, she walked, in perusing Jane's last letter

06:06:24.400 --> 06:06:28.740
and dwelling on some passages which proved that Jane had not written in spirits,

06:06:29.320 --> 06:06:34.520
when instead of being again surprised by Mr Darcy, she saw one looking up that Colonel Fitzwilliam

06:06:34.520 --> 06:06:39.120
was meeting her. Putting away the letter immediately and forcing a smile, she said,

06:06:39.800 --> 06:06:42.840
I did not know before that you ever walked this way.

06:06:43.560 --> 06:06:47.780
I have been making a turn of the park, he replied, as I generally do every year,

06:06:48.160 --> 06:06:53.740
and intend to close it with a call at the parsonage. Are you going much farther? No,

06:06:53.740 --> 06:06:58.700
I should have turned in a moment. And accordingly she did turn, and they walked towards the

06:06:58.700 --> 06:06:59.700
parsonage together.

06:07:00.400 --> 06:07:06.420
Do you certainly leave Kent on Saturday? said she. Yes, if Darcy does not put it off again,

06:07:06.820 --> 06:07:10.360
but I am at his disposal. He arranges the business just as he pleases.

06:07:11.120 --> 06:07:14.920
And if not able to please himself in the arrangement, he has at least pleasure in

06:07:14.920 --> 06:07:20.180
the great power of choice. I do not know anybody who seems to enjoy the power of doing what he

06:07:20.180 --> 06:07:25.720
likes more than Mr Darcy. He likes to have his own way very well, replied Colonel Fitzwilliam,

06:07:25.720 --> 06:07:31.040
but so we all do. It is only that he has better means of having it than many others,

06:07:31.280 --> 06:07:36.680
because he is rich and many others are poor. I speak feelingly, a younger son, you know,

06:07:37.140 --> 06:07:43.720
must be inured to self-denial and dependence. In my opinion, the younger son of an earl can

06:07:43.720 --> 06:07:49.360
know very little of either. Now seriously, what have you ever known of self-denial and dependence?

06:07:50.040 --> 06:07:53.660
When have you been prevented by want of money from going wherever you choose,

06:07:53.660 --> 06:07:59.960
or procuring anything you had a fancy for? These are home questions and perhaps I cannot

06:07:59.960 --> 06:08:05.440
say that I have experienced many hardships of that nature, but in matters of greater weight,

06:08:05.940 --> 06:08:12.240
I may suffer from want of money. Younger sons cannot marry where they like, unless where they

06:08:12.240 --> 06:08:17.800
like women of fortune, which I think they very often do. Our habits of expense make us too

06:08:17.800 --> 06:08:23.240
dependent and there are too many in my rank of life who can afford to marry without some attention

06:08:23.240 --> 06:08:29.960
to money. Is this, thought Lisbeth, meant for me? And she coloured at the idea, but recovering

06:08:29.960 --> 06:08:35.800
herself said in a lively tone, and pray, what is the usual price of an earl's younger son,

06:08:36.380 --> 06:08:41.880
unless the elder brother is very sickly, I suppose you would not ask above fifty thousand pounds?

06:08:42.620 --> 06:08:48.440
He answered her in the same style and the subject dropped. To interrupt a silence which might make

06:08:48.440 --> 06:08:53.980
him fancy her affected with what had passed, she soon afterwards said, I imagine your cousin

06:08:53.980 --> 06:08:58.840
brought you down with him chiefly for the sake of having someone at his disposal. I wonder he does

06:08:58.840 --> 06:09:04.560
not marry to secure a lasting convenience of that kind, but perhaps his sister does as well for the

06:09:04.560 --> 06:09:10.840
present, and as she is under his sole care, he may do what he likes with her. No, said Colonel Fitz

06:09:10.840 --> 06:09:16.520
William, that is an advantage which he must divide with me. I am joined with him in the guardianship

06:09:16.520 --> 06:09:23.720
of Miss Darcy. Are you indeed? And pray, what sort of guardians do you make? Does your charge give

06:09:23.720 --> 06:09:28.900
you much trouble? Young ladies of her age are sometimes a little difficult to manage, and if

06:09:28.900 --> 06:09:34.720
she has the true Darcy spirit, she may like to have her own way. As she spoke, she observed him

06:09:34.720 --> 06:09:39.540
looking at her earnestly, and the manner in which he immediately asked her why she supposed Miss

06:09:39.540 --> 06:09:45.540
Darcy likely to give them any uneasiness convinced her that she had somehow or other got pretty near

06:09:45.540 --> 06:09:51.800
the truth. She directly replied, you need not be frightened, I never heard any harm of her,

06:09:52.080 --> 06:09:56.800
and I dare say she is one of the most tractable creatures in the world. She is a very great

06:09:56.800 --> 06:10:01.600
favourite with some ladies of my acquaintance, Mrs Hurst and Miss Bingley, I think I have heard

06:10:01.600 --> 06:10:07.820
you say that you know them. I know them a little, their brother is a pleasant gentleman-like man,

06:10:08.100 --> 06:10:14.880
he is a great friend of Darcy's. Oh yes, said Elizabeth Dryley, Mr Darcy is uncommonly kind

06:10:14.880 --> 06:10:21.460
to Mr Bingley, and takes a prodigious deal of care of him. Care of him? Yes, I really believe

06:10:21.460 --> 06:10:27.400
Darcy does take care of him in those points where he most wants care. From something that he told me

06:10:27.400 --> 06:10:32.740
in our journey hither, I have reason to think Bingley very much indebted to him. But I want

06:10:32.740 --> 06:10:37.360
to beg his pardon, for I have no right suppose that Bingley was the person meant, it was all

06:10:37.360 --> 06:10:44.060
conjecture. What is it that you mean? It's a circumstance which Darcy would not wish to be

06:10:44.060 --> 06:10:48.820
known, because if it were to get round to the ladies' family it would be an unpleasant thing.

06:10:49.540 --> 06:10:54.580
You may depend on my not mentioning it. And remember that I have not much reason for

06:10:54.580 --> 06:10:59.760
supposing it to be Bingley? What he told me was merely this, that he congratulated himself on

06:10:59.760 --> 06:11:05.620
having lately saved a friend from the inconveniences of a most imprudent marriage, but without

06:11:05.620 --> 06:11:11.080
mentioning names or any other particulars. And I only suspected it to be Bingley from believing him

06:11:11.080 --> 06:11:16.020
the kind of young man to get into a scrape of that sort, and from knowing them to have been

06:11:16.020 --> 06:11:21.440
together the whole of last summer. Did Mr Darcy give you reasons for this interference?

06:11:22.460 --> 06:11:28.300
I understand there were some very strong objections against the lady. And what art did he use to

06:11:28.300 --> 06:11:33.820
separate them? He did not talk to me of his own art, said Fitzwilliam smiling, he only told me what

06:11:33.820 --> 06:11:40.420
I have now told you. Elizabeth made no answer and walked on, her heart swelling with indignation.

06:11:40.420 --> 06:11:44.460
After watching her a little, Fitzwilliam asked her why she was so thoughtful.

06:11:45.400 --> 06:11:50.120
I am thinking of what you have been telling me, said she. Your cousin's conduct does not suit

06:11:50.120 --> 06:11:56.120
my feelings. Why was he to be the judge? You are rather disposed to call his interference

06:11:56.120 --> 06:12:02.940
officious? I do not see what right Mr Darcy had to decide on the propriety of his friend's inclination,

06:12:03.300 --> 06:12:08.680
or why, upon his judgment alone, he was to determine and direct in what manner his friend

06:12:08.680 --> 06:12:14.980
was to be happy. But, she continued, recollecting herself, as we know none of the particulars,

06:12:15.280 --> 06:12:19.940
it is not fair to condemn him, it is not to be supposed that there was much affection in the case.

06:12:21.040 --> 06:12:26.600
That is not an unnatural surmise, said Fitzwilliam, but it is a lessening of the honour of my cousin's

06:12:26.600 --> 06:12:32.980
triumph, very sadly. This was spoken jestingly, but it appeared to her so just a picture of Mr

06:12:32.980 --> 06:12:37.820
Darcy that she would not trust herself with an answer, and therefore abruptly changing the

06:12:37.820 --> 06:12:43.240
conversation, talked on indifferent matters until they reached the parsonage. There, shut into her

06:12:43.240 --> 06:12:47.640
own room, as soon as their visitor left them, she would think without interruption of all that she

06:12:47.640 --> 06:12:52.580
had heard. It was not to be supposed that any other people could be men than those with whom

06:12:52.580 --> 06:12:58.580
she was connected. There could not exist in the world two men over whom Mr Darcy could have such

06:12:58.580 --> 06:13:03.760
boundless influence. That he had been concerned in the measures taken to separate Bingley and

06:13:03.760 --> 06:13:08.560
Jane she had never doubted, but she had always attributed to Miss Bingley the principal design

06:13:08.560 --> 06:13:14.100
and arrangement of them. If his own vanity, however, did not mislead him, he was the cause,

06:13:14.480 --> 06:13:20.260
his pride and caprice were the cause of all that Jane had suffered, and still continued to suffer.

06:13:21.000 --> 06:13:26.220
He had ruined for a while every hope of happiness for the most affectionate, most generous heart in

06:13:26.220 --> 06:13:32.880
the world, and no one could say how lasting an evil he might have inflicted. There were some very

06:13:32.880 --> 06:13:38.460
strong objections against the lady, were Colonel Fitzwilliam's words, and those strong objections

06:13:38.460 --> 06:13:43.580
probably were her having one uncle who was a country attorney and another who was in business

06:13:43.580 --> 06:13:49.140
in London. To Jane herself, she exclaimed, there could be no possibility of objection,

06:13:49.660 --> 06:13:54.660
or loveliness and goodness as she is, her understanding excellent, her mind improved,

06:13:54.720 --> 06:13:59.840
and her manners captivating. Neither could anything be urged against my father, who,

06:13:59.840 --> 06:14:05.040
though with some peculiarities, has abilities Mr Darcy himself need not disdain,

06:14:05.260 --> 06:14:10.580
and respectability which he will probably never each. When he thought of her mother,

06:14:10.940 --> 06:14:15.740
her confidence gave away a little, but she would not allow that any objections there had material

06:14:15.740 --> 06:14:20.780
weight with Mr Darcy, whose pride, she was convinced, would receive a deeper wound from

06:14:20.780 --> 06:14:26.140
the want of importance in his friend's connections than from their want of sense, and she was quite

06:14:26.140 --> 06:14:31.840
excited at last that he had been partly governed by this worst kind of pride, and partly by the

06:14:31.840 --> 06:14:37.880
wish of retaining Mr Bingley for his sister. The agitation and tears which the subject occasioned

06:14:37.880 --> 06:14:43.400
brought on a headache, and it grew so much worse towards the evening that, added to her unwillingness

06:14:43.400 --> 06:14:48.900
to see Mr Darcy, it determined her not to attend her cousins to Rosings, where they were engaged

06:14:48.900 --> 06:14:54.840
to drink tea. Mrs Collins, seeing that she was really unwell, did not press her to go,

06:14:54.840 --> 06:15:00.040
and as much as possible prevented her husband from pressing her, but Mr Collins could not

06:15:00.040 --> 06:15:05.580
conceal his apprehension at Lady Catherine's being rather displeased by her staying at home.

06:15:41.980 --> 06:15:57.160
When they were gone, Elizabeth, as if intending to exasperate herself as much as possible against Mr. Darcy, chose for her employment the examination of all the letters which Jane had written to her since being in Kent.

06:15:58.220 --> 06:16:26.840
They contained no actual complaint, nor was there any revival of past occurrences, or any communication of present suffering, but in all, and in almost every line of each, there was a want of that cheerfulness which had been used to characterize her style, and which, proceeding from the serenity of a mind at ease with itself, and kindly disposed towards every one, had been scarcely ever clouded.

06:16:28.440 --> 06:16:37.680
Elizabeth noticed every sentence conveying the idea of uneasiness with an attention which it had hardly received on the first perusal.

06:16:38.960 --> 06:16:46.420
Mr. Darcy's shameful boast of what misery he had been able to inflict gave her a keener sense of her sister's sufferings.

06:16:47.200 --> 06:17:04.120
It was some consolation to think that his visit to Rosings was to end on the day after the next, and, a still greater, that in less than a fortnight she should herself be with Jane again, and enabled to contribute to the recovery of her spirits by all that affection could do.

06:17:04.860 --> 06:17:19.560
She could not think of Darcy's leaving Kent without remembering that his cousin was to go with him, but Colonel Fitzwilliam had made it clear that he had no intentions at all, and, agreeable as he was, she did not mean to be unhappy about him.

06:17:20.480 --> 06:17:36.740
While settling this point she was suddenly roused by the sound of the door-bell, and her spirits were a little fluttered by the idea of its being Colonel Fitzwilliam himself, who had once before called late in the evening, and might now come to inquire particularly after her.

06:17:38.260 --> 06:17:47.680
But this idea was soon banished, and her spirits were very differently affected when, to her utter amazement, she saw Mr. Darcy walk into the room.

06:17:48.680 --> 06:17:56.700
In an hurried manner he immediately began an inquiry after her health, imputing his visit to a wish of hearing that she were better.

06:17:57.880 --> 06:18:00.180
She answered him with cold civility.

06:18:01.560 --> 06:18:06.040
He sat down for a few moments, and then, getting up, walked about the room.

06:18:07.580 --> 06:18:10.720
Elizabeth was surprised, but said not a word.

06:18:11.740 --> 06:18:18.260
After a silence of several minutes he came towards her in an agitated manner, and thus began.

06:18:31.780 --> 06:18:35.020
Elizabeth's astonishment was beyond expression.

06:18:35.520 --> 06:18:39.780
She stared, coloured, doubted, and was silent.

06:18:40.840 --> 06:18:49.780
This he considered sufficient encouragement, and the avowal of all that he felt, and had long felt for her, immediately followed.

06:18:51.160 --> 06:19:00.900
He spoke well, but there were feelings besides those of the heart to be detailed, and he was not more eloquent on the subject of tenderness than of pride.

06:19:02.220 --> 06:19:19.080
His sense of her inferiority, of its being a degradation, of the family obstacles which had always opposed to inclination, were dwelt on with a warmth which seemed due to the consequence he was wounding, but was very unlikely to recommend his suit.

06:19:20.200 --> 06:19:41.480
In spite of her deeply rooted dislike, she could not be insensible to the compliment of such a man's affection, and though her intentions did not vary for an instant, she was at first sorry for the pain he was to receive, till, roused to resentment by his subsequent language, she lost all compassion in anger.

06:19:42.720 --> 06:19:48.460
She tried, however, to compose herself to answer him with patience, when he should have done.

06:19:50.280 --> 06:20:04.360
He concluded with representing to her the strength of that attachment which, in spite of all his endeavours, he had found impossible to conquer, and with expressing his hope that it would now be rewarded by her acceptance of his hand.

06:20:05.220 --> 06:20:10.860
As he said this, she could easily see that he had no doubt of a favourable answer.

06:20:11.880 --> 06:20:17.700
He spoke of apprehension and anxiety, but his countenance expressed real security.

06:20:18.840 --> 06:20:26.060
Such a circumstance could only exasperate farther, and, when he ceased, the collar rose into her cheeks, and she said,

06:20:47.700 --> 06:20:53.100
I have never desired your good opinion, and you have certainly bestowed it most unwillingly.

06:20:53.780 --> 06:21:02.520
I am sorry to have occasioned pain to any one. It has been most unconsciously done, however, and I hope will be of short duration.

06:21:03.540 --> 06:21:12.340
The feelings which, you tell me, have long prevented the acknowledgement of your regard, can have little difficulty in overcoming it, after this explanation.

06:21:13.900 --> 06:21:23.520
Mr. Darcy, who was leaning against the mantelpiece with his eyes fixed on her face, seemed to catch her words with no less resentment than surprise.

06:21:25.100 --> 06:21:31.120
His complexion became pale with anger, and the disturbance of his mind was visible in every feature.

06:21:32.220 --> 06:21:38.860
He was struggling for the appearance of composure, and would not open his lips till he believed himself to have attained it.

06:21:39.900 --> 06:21:47.400
The pause was to Elizabeth's feelings dreadful. At length, with a voice of forced calmness, he said,

06:21:49.280 --> 06:21:53.320
And this is all the reply which I am to have the honour of expecting.

06:21:54.000 --> 06:22:02.520
I might, perhaps, wish to be informed why, with so little endeavour at civility, I am thus rejected, but it is of small importance.

06:22:03.560 --> 06:22:11.760
I might as well inquire, replied she, why, with so evident a desire of offending and insulting me,

06:22:12.160 --> 06:22:18.460
you chose to tell me that you liked me against your will, against your reason, and even against your character.

06:22:19.560 --> 06:22:27.060
Was not this some excuse for incivility, if I was uncivil? But I have other provocations, you know I have.

06:22:27.060 --> 06:22:33.460
Had not my feelings decided against you, had they been indifferent, or had they even been favourable,

06:22:33.740 --> 06:22:44.140
do you think that any consideration would tempt me to accept the man who has been the means of ruining, perhaps for ever, the happiness of a most beloved sister?

06:22:45.140 --> 06:22:54.660
As she pronounced these words, Mr. Darcy changed colour, but the emotion was short, and he listened without attempting to interrupt her, while she continued.

06:22:55.780 --> 06:23:04.900
I have every reason in the world to think ill of you. No motive can excuse the unjust and ungenerous part you acted there.

06:23:06.140 --> 06:23:13.380
You dare not, you cannot deny that you have been the principle, if not the only means, of dividing them from each other,

06:23:13.760 --> 06:23:21.980
of exposing one to the censure of the world for caprice and instability, and the other to its derision for disappointed hopes,

06:23:21.980 --> 06:23:25.900
and involving them both in misery of the acutest kind.

06:23:27.240 --> 06:23:36.160
She paused, and saw with no slight indignation that he was listening with an air which proved him wholly unmoved by any feeling of remorse.

06:23:37.360 --> 06:23:40.840
He even looked at her with a smile of affected incredulity.

06:23:42.560 --> 06:23:46.180
Can you deny that you have done it? she repeated.

06:23:47.560 --> 06:23:50.980
With assumed tranquillity, he then replied,

06:23:52.020 --> 06:24:01.100
I have no wish of denying that I did everything in my power to separate my friend from your sister, or that I rejoice in my success.

06:24:01.900 --> 06:24:05.140
Towards him I have been kinder than towards myself.

06:24:07.060 --> 06:24:15.360
Elizabeth disdained the appearance of noticing this civil reflection, but its meaning did not escape, nor was it likely to conciliate her.

06:24:16.780 --> 06:24:22.240
But it is not merely this affair, she continued, on which my dislike is founded.

06:24:23.300 --> 06:24:32.760
Long before it had taken place, my opinion of you was decided. Your character was unfolded in the recital which I received many months ago from Mr. Wickham.

06:24:34.060 --> 06:24:45.920
On this subject, what can you have to say, in what imaginary act of friendship can you here defend yourself, or under what misrepresentation can you here impose upon others?

06:24:47.100 --> 06:24:55.420
You take an eager interest in that gentleman's concerns, said Darcy, in a less tranquil tone, and with a heightened colour.

06:24:56.900 --> 06:25:01.200
Who that knows what his misfortunes have been can help feeling an interest in him.

06:25:02.640 --> 06:25:09.880
His misfortunes, repeated Darcy contemptuously. Yes, his misfortunes have been great indeed.

06:25:10.880 --> 06:25:20.260
And of your infliction, cried Elizabeth with energy, you have reduced him to his present state of poverty, comparative poverty.

06:25:20.540 --> 06:25:25.960
You have withheld the advantages which you must know to have been designed for him.

06:25:25.960 --> 06:25:33.280
You have deprived the best years of his life of that independence which was no less his due than his dessert.

06:25:34.880 --> 06:25:41.060
You have done all this, and yet you can treat the mention of his misfortune with contempt and ridicule.

06:25:42.100 --> 06:25:49.420
And this, cried Darcy, as he walked with quick steps across the room, is your opinion of me.

06:25:49.960 --> 06:25:55.120
This is the estimation in which you hold me. I thank you for explaining it so fully.

06:25:55.560 --> 06:25:59.820
My faults, according to this calculation, are heavy indeed.

06:26:00.420 --> 06:26:09.300
But perhaps, added he, stopping in his walk and turning towards her, these offences might have been overlooked,

06:26:09.300 --> 06:26:17.140
had not your pride been hurt by my honest confession of the scruples that had long prevented my forming any serious design.

06:26:18.360 --> 06:26:25.160
These bitter accusations might have been suppressed, had I, with greater policy, concealed my struggles,

06:26:25.540 --> 06:26:35.280
and flattered you into the belief of my being impelled by unqualified, unalloyed inclination, by reason, by reflection, by everything.

06:26:36.400 --> 06:26:44.360
But disguise of every sort is my abhorrence, nor am I ashamed of the feelings I related, they were natural and just.

06:26:45.480 --> 06:26:55.880
Could you expect me to rejoice in the inferiority of your connections, to congratulate myself on the hope of relations whose condition in life is so decidedly beneath my own?

06:26:57.840 --> 06:27:05.620
Elizabeth felt herself growing more angry every moment, yet she tried to the utmost to speak with composure when she said,

06:27:07.040 --> 06:27:14.240
You are mistaken, Mr. Darcy, if you suppose that the mode of your declaration affected me in any other way,

06:27:14.620 --> 06:27:21.420
than as it spared the concern which I might have felt in refusing you had you behaved in a more gentlemanlike manner.

06:27:22.340 --> 06:27:27.380
She saw him start at this, but he said nothing, and she continued,

06:27:29.160 --> 06:27:35.580
You could not have made the offer of your hand in any possible way that would have tempted me to accept it.

06:27:36.940 --> 06:27:46.300
Again his astonishment was obvious, and he looked at her with an expression of mingled incredulity and mortification. She went on,

06:27:47.440 --> 06:27:53.620
From the very beginning, from the first moment, I may almost say, of my acquaintance with you,

06:27:53.980 --> 06:28:02.500
your manners, impressing me with the fullest belief of your arrogance, your conceit, and your selfish disdain for the feelings of others,

06:28:02.980 --> 06:28:10.360
were such as to form the groundwork of disapprobation on which succeeding events have built so immovable a dislike.

06:28:10.960 --> 06:28:19.000
And I had not known you a month before I felt that you were the last man in the world whom I could ever be prevailed on to marry.

06:28:20.860 --> 06:28:28.660
You have said quite enough, madam. I perfectly comprehend your feelings, and have now only to be ashamed of what my own have been.

06:28:29.180 --> 06:28:35.300
Forgive me for having taken up so much of your time, and accept my best wishes for your health and happiness.

06:28:36.760 --> 06:28:44.840
And with these words he hastily left the room, and Elizabeth heard him the next moment open the front door and quit the house.

06:28:46.580 --> 06:28:56.880
The tumult of her mind was now painfully great. She knew not how to support herself, and from actual weakness sat down and cried for half an hour.

06:28:58.180 --> 06:29:04.240
Her astonishment, as she reflected on what had passed, was increased by every review of it.

06:29:05.200 --> 06:29:13.100
That she should receive an offer of marriage from Mr. Darcy. That he should have been in love with her for so many months.

06:29:13.860 --> 06:29:21.220
So much in love as to wish to marry her in spite of all the objections which had made him prevent his friends marrying her sister,

06:29:21.500 --> 06:29:26.840
and which must appear at least with equal force in his own case, was almost incredible.

06:29:27.960 --> 06:29:40.720
It was gratifying to have inspired unconsciously so strong an affection. But his pride, his abominable pride, his shameless avowal of what he had done with respect to Jane,

06:29:41.320 --> 06:29:49.600
his unpardonable assurance in acknowledging, though he could not justify it, and the unfeeling manner in which he had mentioned Mr. Wickham,

06:29:49.600 --> 06:29:59.740
his cruelty towards whom he had not attempted to deny, soon overcame the pity which the consideration of his attachment had for a moment excited.

06:30:01.300 --> 06:30:13.180
She continued in very agitated reflections till the sound of Lady Catherine's carriage made her feel how unequal she was to encounter Charlotte's observation, and hurried her away to her room.

06:30:21.300 --> 06:30:28.260
Elizabeth awoke the next morning to the same thoughts and meditations which had at length closed her eyes.

06:30:29.460 --> 06:30:35.800
She could not yet recover from the surprise of what had happened. It was impossible to think of anything else.

06:30:36.440 --> 06:30:44.240
And totally indisposed for employment, she resolved, soon after breakfast, to indulge herself in air and exercise.

06:30:45.320 --> 06:30:59.180
She was proceeding directly to her favourite walk, when the recollection of Mr. Darcy's sometimes coming there stopped her, and instead of entering the park she turned up the lane, which led farther from the Turnpike Road.

06:31:00.480 --> 06:31:06.660
The park paling was still the boundary on one side, and she soon passed one of the gates into the ground.

06:31:08.120 --> 06:31:17.320
After walking two or three times along that part of the lane she was tempted, by the pleasantness of the morning, to stop at the gates and look into the park.

06:31:18.540 --> 06:31:28.220
The five weeks which she had now passed in Kent had made a great difference in the country, and every day was adding to the verdure of the early trees.

06:31:28.960 --> 06:31:37.120
She was on the point of continuing her walk when she caught a glimpse of a gentleman within the sort of grove which edged the park.

06:31:37.960 --> 06:31:44.400
He was moving that way, and, fearful of its being Mr. Darcy, she was directly retreating.

06:31:45.780 --> 06:31:52.340
But the person who advanced was now near enough to see her, and, stepping forward with eagerness, pronounced her name.

06:31:52.980 --> 06:32:01.360
She had turned away, but on hearing herself called, though in a voice which proved it to be Mr. Darcy, she moved again towards the gate.

06:32:02.780 --> 06:32:10.820
He had by that time reached it also, and, holding out a letter, which she instinctively took, said, with a look of haughty composure,

06:32:12.000 --> 06:32:18.820
I have been walking in the grove some time in the hope of meeting you. Will you do me the honor of reading that letter?

06:32:20.240 --> 06:32:26.360
And then, with a slight bow, turned again into the plantation, and was soon out of sight.

06:32:28.120 --> 06:32:43.660
With no expectation of pleasure, but with the strongest curiosity, Elizabeth opened the letter, and, to her still increasing wonder, perceived an envelope, containing two sheets of letter paper, written quite through, in a very close hand.

06:32:45.260 --> 06:32:58.000
The envelope itself was likewise full. Pursuing her way along the lane, she then began it. It was dated from Rosings, at eight o'clock in the morning, and was as follows.

06:32:59.480 --> 06:33:12.480
Be not alarmed, madam, on receiving this letter, by the apprehension of its containing any repetition of those sentiments, or renewal of those offers, which were last night so disgusting to you.

06:33:13.500 --> 06:33:23.320
I write without any intention of paining you, or humbling myself, by dwelling on wishes which, for the happiness of both, cannot be too soon forgotten.

06:33:24.280 --> 06:33:34.300
And the effort which the formation and the perusal of this letter must occasion, should have been spared, had not my character required it to be written and read.

06:33:35.800 --> 06:33:46.100
You must therefore pardon the freedom with which I demand your attention. Your feelings, I know, will bestow it unwillingly, but I demand it of your justice.

06:33:47.780 --> 06:33:55.200
Two offences of a very different nature, and by no means of equal magnitude, you last night laid to my charge.

06:33:55.200 --> 06:34:15.780
The first mentioned was that, regardless of the sentiments of either, I had detached Mr. Bingley from your sister, and the other that I had, in defiance of various claims, in defiance of honour and humanity, ruined the immediate prosperity, and blasted the prospects of Mr. Wickham.

06:34:17.260 --> 06:34:41.180
Willfully and wantonly to have thrown off the companion of my youth, the acknowledged favourite of my father, a young man who had scarcely any other dependence than on our patronage, and who had been brought up to expect its exertion, would be a depravity to which the separation of two young persons, whose affection could be the growth of only a few weeks, could bear no comparison.

06:34:42.220 --> 06:34:56.920
But from the severity of that blame which was last night so liberally bestowed, respecting each circumstance, I shall hope to be in the future secured, when the following account of my actions and their motives has been read.

06:34:58.120 --> 06:35:13.640
If, in the explanation of them which is due to myself, I am under the necessity of relating feelings which may be offensive to yours, I can only say that I am sorry. The necessity must be obeyed, and further apology would be absurd.

06:35:15.260 --> 06:35:25.040
I had not been long in Hertfordshire before I saw, in common with others, that Bingley preferred your elder sister to any other young woman in the country.

06:35:26.420 --> 06:35:52.860
But it was not till the evening of the dance at Netherfield that I had any apprehension of his feeling a serious attachment. I had often seen him in love before. At that ball, while I had the honour of dancing with you, I was first made acquainted by Sir William Lucas's accidental information, that Bingley's attentions to your sister had given rise to a general expectation of their marriage.

06:35:54.480 --> 06:36:13.920
He spoke of it as a certain event, of which the time alone could be undecided. From that moment I observed my friend's behaviour attentively, and I could then perceive that his partiality for Miss Bennet was beyond what I had ever witnessed in him. Your sister I also watched.

06:36:15.400 --> 06:36:32.940
Her look and manners were open, cheerful, and engaging as ever, but without any symptom of peculiar regard, and I remained convinced from the evening's scrutiny that though she received his attentions with pleasure, she did not invite them by any participation of sentiment.

06:36:33.860 --> 06:36:51.580
If you have not been mistaken here, I must have been in error. Your superior knowledge of your sister must make the latter probable. If it be so, if I have been misled by such error to inflict pain on her, your resentment has not been unreasonable.

06:36:51.580 --> 06:37:07.700
But I shall not scruple to assert that the serenity of your sister's countenance and air was such as might have given the most acute observer a conviction that, however amiable her temper, her heart was not likely to be easily touched.

06:37:08.960 --> 06:37:20.000
That I was desirous of believing her indifferent is certain, but I will venture to say that my investigation and decisions are not usually influenced by my hopes or fears.

06:37:21.180 --> 06:37:40.600
I did not believe her to be indifferent because I wished it. I believed it on impartial conviction, as truly as I wished it in reason. My objections to the marriage were not merely those which I last night acknowledged to have the utmost force of passion to put aside, in my own case.

06:37:40.600 --> 06:38:00.740
The want of connexion could not be so great and evil to my friend as to me. But there were other causes of repugnance, causes which, though still existing, and existing to an equal degree in both instances, I had myself endeavoured to forget, because they were not immediately before me.

06:38:01.620 --> 06:38:04.940
These causes must be stated, though briefly.

06:38:04.940 --> 06:38:23.220
The situation of your mother's family, though objectionable, was nothing in comparison to that total want of propriety so frequently, so almost uniformly betrayed by herself, by your three younger sisters, and occasionally even by your father.

06:38:23.840 --> 06:38:50.140
Pardon me, it pains me to offend you, but amidst your concern for the defects of your nearest relations, and your displeasure at this representation of them, let it give you consolation to consider that, to have conducted yourselves so as to avoid any share of the like censure, is praise no less generally bestowed on you and your elder sister, than it is honourable to the sense and disposition of both.

06:38:50.140 --> 06:39:06.640
I will only say farther, that from what passed that evening, my opinion of all parties was confirmed, and every inducement heightened which could have led me before to preserve my friend from what I esteemed a most unhappy connexion.

06:39:08.080 --> 06:39:15.140
He left Netherfield for London on the day following, as you I am certain remember, with the design of soon returning.

06:39:16.060 --> 06:39:37.300
The part which I acted is now to be explained. His sister's uneasiness had been equally excited with my own. Our coincidence of feeling was soon discovered, and, alike sensible that no time was to be lost in detaching their brother, we shortly resolved on joining him directly in London.

06:39:38.500 --> 06:39:50.740
We accordingly went, and there I readily engaged in the office of pointing out to my friend the certain evils of such a choice. I described, and enforced them earnestly.

06:39:51.520 --> 06:40:07.020
But, however this remonstrance might have staggered or delayed his determination, I do not suppose that it would ultimately have prevented the marriage, had it not been seconded by the assurance that I hesitated not in giving, of your sister's indifference.

06:40:08.040 --> 06:40:21.880
He had before believed her to return his affection with sincere, if not with equal regard. But Bingley has great natural modesty, with a stronger dependence on my judgment than on his own.

06:40:23.140 --> 06:40:36.500
To convince him, therefore, that he had deceived himself was no very difficult point. To persuade him against returning into Hertfordshire, when that conviction had been given, was scarcely the work of a moment.

06:40:37.460 --> 06:40:56.480
I cannot blame myself for having done thus much. There is but one part of my conduct in the whole affair on which I do not reflect with satisfaction. It is that I condescended to adopt the measures of art so far as to conceal from him your sister's being in town.

06:40:57.300 --> 06:41:15.840
I knew it myself, as it was known to Miss Bingley, but her brother is even yet ignorant of it. That they might have met without ill consequence is perhaps probable, but his regard did not appear to me enough extinguished for him to see her without some danger.

06:41:17.840 --> 06:41:44.240
Perhaps this concealment, this disguise, was beneath me. It is done, however, and it was done for the best. On this subject I have nothing more to say, no other apology to offer. If I have wounded your sister's feelings, it was unknowingly done, and though the motives which governed me may to you very naturally appear insufficient, I have not yet learnt to condemn them.

06:41:45.380 --> 06:42:08.320
With respect to that other, more weighty accusation of having injured Mr. Wickham, I can only refute it by laying before you the whole of his connection with my family. Of what he has particularly accused me I am ignorant, but of the truth of what I shall relate I can summon more than one witness of undoubted veracity.

06:42:09.640 --> 06:42:31.820
Mr. Wickham is the son of a very respectable man, who had for many years the management of all the Pemberley estates, and whose good conduct in the discharge of his trust naturally inclined my father to be of service to him. And on George Wickham, who was his godson, his kindness was therefore liberally bestowed.

06:42:33.040 --> 06:42:47.740
My father supported him at school, and afterwards at Cambridge, most important assistance, as his own father, always poor from the extravagance of his wife, would have been unable to give him a gentleman's education.

06:42:49.120 --> 06:43:03.820
My father was not only fond of this young man's society, whose manners were always engaging, he had also the highest opinion of him, and, hoping the church would be his profession, intended to provide for him in it.

06:43:05.040 --> 06:43:11.520
As for myself, it is many, many years since I first began to think of him in a very different manner.

06:43:13.200 --> 06:43:31.800
The vicious propensities, the want of principle, which he was careful to guard from the knowledge of his best friend, could not escape the observation of a young man of nearly the same age with himself, and who had opportunities of seeing him in unguarded moments, which Mr. Darcy could not have.

06:43:33.020 --> 06:43:50.620
Here again I shall give you pain, to what degree you only can tell. But, whatever may be the sentiments which Mr. Wickham has created, a suspicion of their nature shall not prevent me from unfolding his real character. It adds even another motive.

06:43:51.700 --> 06:44:15.260
My excellent father died about five years ago, and his attachment to Mr. Wickham was to the last so steady, that in his will he particularly recommended it to me, to promote his advancement in the best manner that his profession might allow, and, if he took orders, desired that a valuable family living might be his as soon as it became vacant.

06:44:16.700 --> 06:44:42.740
There was also a legacy of one thousand pounds. His own father did not long survive mine, and within half a year from these events Mr. Wickham wrote to inform me that, having finally resolved against taking orders, he hoped I should not think it unreasonable for him to expect some more immediate pecuniary advantage, in lieu of the preferment by which he could not be benefited.

06:44:44.660 --> 06:44:55.540
He had some intention, he added, of studying law, and I must be aware that the interest of one thousand pounds would be a very insufficient support therein.

06:44:56.880 --> 06:45:22.780
I rather wished than believed him to be sincere, but at any rate was perfectly ready to accede to his proposal. I knew that Mr. Wickham ought not to be a clergyman. The business was therefore soon settled. He resigned all claim to assistance in the church, were it possible that he could ever be in a situation to receive it, and accepted in return three thousand pounds.

06:45:24.400 --> 06:45:46.840
All connection between us seemed now dissolved. I thought too ill of him to invite him to Pemberley, or admit his society in town. In town I believe he chiefly lived, but his studying the law was a mere pretense, and being now free from all restraint, his life was a life of idleness and dissipation.

06:45:48.200 --> 06:46:08.540
For about three years I heard little of him, but on the decease of the incumbent of the living which had been designed for him, he applied to me again by letter for the presentation. His circumstances, he assured me, and I had no difficulty in believing it, were exceedingly bad.

06:46:09.480 --> 06:46:29.520
He had found the law a most unprofitable study, and was now absolutely resolved on being ordained, if I would present him to the living in question, of which he trusted there could be little doubt, as he was well assured that I had no other person to provide for, and I could not have forgotten my revered father's intentions.

06:46:30.400 --> 06:46:49.800
You will hardly blame me for refusing to comply with this entreaty, or for resisting every repetition to it. His resentment was in proportion to the distress of his circumstances, and he was doubtless as violent in his abuse of me to others as in his reproaches to myself.

06:46:50.520 --> 06:47:01.760
After this period every appearance of acquaintance was dropped. How he lived I know not, but last summer he was again most painfully obtruded on my notice.

06:47:02.900 --> 06:47:19.600
I must now mention a circumstance which I would wish to forget myself, and which no obligation less than the present should induce me to unfold to any human being. Having said thus much, I feel no doubt of your secrecy.

06:47:20.960 --> 06:47:30.240
My sister, who is more than ten years my junior, was left to the guardianship of my mother's nephew, Colonel Fitzwilliam, and myself.

06:47:31.560 --> 06:47:55.820
About a year ago she was taken from school, and an establishment formed for her in London, and last summer she went with the lady who presided over it to Ramsgate, and thither also went Mr. Wickham, undoubtedly by design, for there proved to have been a prior acquaintance between him and Mrs. Young, in whose character we were most unhappily deceived.

06:47:55.820 --> 06:48:13.020
And by her connivance and aid he so far recommended himself to Georgiana, whose affectionate heart retained a strong impression of his kindness to her as a child, that she was persuaded to believe herself in love, and to consent to an elopement.

06:48:14.120 --> 06:48:23.160
She was then but fifteen, which must be her excuse, and after stating her imprudence I am happy to add that I owed the knowledge of it to herself.

06:48:24.020 --> 06:48:40.020
I joined them unexpectedly a day or two before the intended elopement, and then Georgiana, unable to support the idea of grieving and offending a brother whom she almost looked up to as a father, acknowledged the whole to me.

06:48:40.020 --> 06:48:43.540
You may imagine what I felt and how I acted.

06:48:44.680 --> 06:48:56.620
Regard for my sister's credit and feelings prevented any public exposure, but I wrote to Mr. Wickham, who left the place immediately, and Mrs. Young was of course removed from her charge.

06:48:57.600 --> 06:49:10.960
Mr. Wickham's chief object was unquestionably my sister's fortune, which is thirty thousand pounds, but I cannot help supposing that the hope of revenging himself on me was a strong inducement.

06:49:12.420 --> 06:49:15.380
His revenge would have been complete, indeed.

06:49:17.320 --> 06:49:31.680
This, madam, is a faithful narrative of every event in which we have been concerned together, and if you do not absolutely reject it as false, you will, I hope, acquit me henceforth of cruelty towards Mr. Wickham.

06:49:32.900 --> 06:49:41.940
I know not in what manner, under what form of falsehood he has imposed on you, but his success is not perhaps to be wondered at.

06:49:43.160 --> 06:49:53.020
Ignorant as you previously were of everything concerning either, detection could not be in your power, and suspicions certainly not in your inclination.

06:49:54.880 --> 06:50:04.880
You may possibly wonder why all this was not told you last night, but I was not then master enough of myself to know what could or ought to be revealed.

06:50:05.560 --> 06:50:26.120
For the truth of everything here related, I can appeal more particularly to the testimony of Colonel Fitzwilliam, who, from our near relationship and constant intimacy, and still more as one of the executors of my father's will, has been unavoidably acquainted with every particular of these transactions.

06:50:26.120 --> 06:50:45.980
If your abhorrence of me should make my assertions valueless, you cannot be prevented by the same cause from confiding in my cousin, and that there may be the possibility of consulting him, I shall endeavour to find some opportunity of putting this letter in your hands in the course of the morning.

06:50:47.340 --> 06:50:50.360
I will only add, God bless you.

06:50:50.360 --> 06:50:52.460
Fitzwilliam Darcy

06:51:13.480 --> 06:51:13.980
36.

06:51:16.840 --> 06:51:22.280
If Elizabeth, when Mr. Darcy gave her the letter, did not expect it to contain a renewal

06:51:22.280 --> 06:51:29.200
of his offers, she had formed no expectation at all of its contents. But such as they were,

06:51:29.420 --> 06:51:35.240
it may well be supposed how eagerly she went through them, and what a contrarity of emotion

06:51:35.240 --> 06:51:42.420
they excited. Her feelings, as she read, were scarcely to be defined. With amazement did she

06:51:42.420 --> 06:51:48.800
first understand that he believed any apology to be in his power, and steadfastly was she persuaded

06:51:48.800 --> 06:51:55.200
that he could have no explanation to give which a just sense of shame would not conceal.

06:51:56.440 --> 06:52:02.140
With a strong prejudice against everything he might say, she began his account of what had

06:52:02.140 --> 06:52:07.900
happened at Netherfield. She read with an eagerness which hardly left her power of comprehension,

06:52:08.320 --> 06:52:11.760
and from impatience of knowing what the next sentence might bring,

06:52:12.240 --> 06:52:16.500
was incapable of attending to the sense of the one before her eyes.

06:52:17.460 --> 06:52:23.580
His belief of her sister's insensibility she instantly resolved to be false,

06:52:24.060 --> 06:52:30.940
and his account of the real, the worst objections the match, made her too angry to have any wish

06:52:30.940 --> 06:52:37.080
of doing him justice. He expressed no regret for what he had done which satisfied her.

06:52:37.540 --> 06:52:43.340
His style was not penitent, but haughty. It was all pride and insolence.

06:52:44.700 --> 06:52:51.160
But when this subject was succeeded by his account of Mr. Wickham, when she read with somewhat

06:52:51.160 --> 06:52:58.300
clearer attention a relation of events which, if true, must overthrow every cherished opinion

06:52:58.300 --> 06:53:04.840
of his worth, and which bore so alarming an affinity to his own history of himself,

06:53:05.480 --> 06:53:12.980
her feelings were yet more acutely painful and more difficult of definition. Astonishment,

06:53:12.980 --> 06:53:19.760
apprehension, and even horror oppressed her. She wished to discredit it entirely,

06:53:20.400 --> 06:53:27.100
repeatedly exclaiming, This must be false. This cannot be. This must be the grossest falsehood.

06:53:27.560 --> 06:53:32.900
And when she had gone through the whole letter, though scarcely knowing anything of the last

06:53:32.900 --> 06:53:40.740
page or two, put it hastily away, protesting that she would not regard it, that she would

06:53:40.740 --> 06:53:47.500
never look at it again. In this perturbed state of mind, with thoughts that could rest on nothing,

06:53:47.700 --> 06:53:53.600
she walked on, but it would not do. In half a minute the letter was unfolded again,

06:53:53.920 --> 06:54:00.000
and collecting herself as well as she could, she again began the mortifying perusal of all

06:54:00.000 --> 06:54:06.520
that related to Wickham, and commanded herself so far as to examine the meaning of every sentence.

06:54:07.220 --> 06:54:13.720
The account of his connection with the Pemberley family was exactly what he had related himself.

06:54:15.000 --> 06:54:21.340
And the kindness of the late Mr. Darcy, though she had not before known its extent, agreed

06:54:21.340 --> 06:54:28.500
equally well with his own words. So far each recital confirmed the other, but when she came

06:54:28.500 --> 06:54:34.320
to the will the difference was great. What Wickham had said of the living was fresh in her memory,

06:54:34.320 --> 06:54:39.800
and as she recalled his very words, it was impossible not to feel that there was gross

06:54:39.800 --> 06:54:46.900
duplicity on one side or the other, and for a few moments she flattered herself that her wishes did

06:54:46.900 --> 06:54:54.220
not err. But when she read and re-read with the closest attention the particulars immediately

06:54:54.220 --> 06:55:01.640
following of Wickham's resigning all pretensions to the living, of his receiving in lieu so

06:55:01.640 --> 06:55:09.300
considerable a sum as three thousand pounds, again she was forced to hesitate. She put down

06:55:09.300 --> 06:55:17.280
the letter, weighed every circumstance with what she meant to be impartiality, deliberated on the

06:55:17.280 --> 06:55:24.460
probability of each statement, but with little success. On both sides it was only assertion.

06:55:25.040 --> 06:55:31.340
Again she read on, but every line proved more clearly that the affair, which she had believed

06:55:31.340 --> 06:55:37.900
it impossible that any contrivance could so represent as to render Mr. Darcy's conduct in

06:55:37.900 --> 06:55:44.420
it less than infamous, was capable of a turn which must make him entirely blameless throughout the

06:55:44.420 --> 06:55:52.040
whole. The extravagance and general profligacy which he scrupled not to lay at Mr. Wickham's

06:55:52.040 --> 06:55:58.900
charge exceedingly shocked her, the more so as she could bring no proof of its injustice.

06:55:59.660 --> 06:56:06.240
She had never heard of him before his entrance into the shire militia in which he had engaged

06:56:06.240 --> 06:56:13.780
at the persuasion of the young man who, on meeting him accidentally in town, had there renewed a

06:56:13.780 --> 06:56:20.080
slight acquaintance. Of his former way of life nothing had been known in Hertfordshire but what

06:56:20.080 --> 06:56:28.320
he told himself. As to his real character, had information been in her power, she had never felt

06:56:28.320 --> 06:56:35.780
wish of inquiring. His countenance, voice, and manner had established him at once in the possession

06:56:35.780 --> 06:56:43.920
of every virtue. She tried to recollect some instance of goodness, some distinguished trait

06:56:43.920 --> 06:56:51.760
of integrity or benevolence that might rescue him from the attacks of Mr. Darcy, or at least by the

06:56:52.650 --> 06:56:59.540
virtue, atone for those casual errors under which she would endeavour to class what Mr. Darcy had

06:56:59.540 --> 06:57:07.420
described as the idleness and vice of many years continuing. But no such recollection

06:57:07.420 --> 06:57:14.100
refriended her. She could see him instantly before her in every charm of air and address,

06:57:14.500 --> 06:57:20.020
but she could remember no more substantial good than the general approbation of the neighbourhood,

06:57:20.020 --> 06:57:24.960
and the regard which his social powers had gained him in the mess.

06:57:26.260 --> 06:57:33.460
After pausing on this point a considerable while, she once more continued to read, but alas,

06:57:33.720 --> 06:57:40.940
the story which followed, of his designs on Miss Darcy, received some confirmation from what had

06:57:40.940 --> 06:57:48.540
passed between Colonel Fitzwilliam and herself only the morning before, and at last she was

06:57:48.540 --> 06:57:55.080
referred for the truth of every particular to Colonel Fitzwilliam himself, from whom she had

06:57:55.080 --> 06:58:01.840
previously received the information of his near concern in all his cousin's affairs, and whose

06:58:01.840 --> 06:58:09.440
character she had no reason to question. At one time she had almost resolved on applying to him,

06:58:09.780 --> 06:58:15.860
but the idea was checked by the awkwardness of the application, and at length wholly banished

06:58:15.860 --> 06:58:22.700
by the conviction that Mr. Darcy would never have hazarded such a proposal he had not been

06:58:22.700 --> 06:58:29.540
well assured of his cousin's corroboration. She perfectly remembered everything that had

06:58:29.540 --> 06:58:36.040
passed in conversation between Wickham and herself in their first evening at Mr. Phillips's.

06:58:36.700 --> 06:58:43.400
Many of his expressions were still fresh in her memory. She was now struck with the impropriety

06:58:43.400 --> 06:58:51.600
such communications to a stranger, and wonder it had escaped her before. She saw the indelicacy

06:58:51.600 --> 06:58:58.000
of putting himself forward as he had done, and the inconsistency of his professions with his conduct.

06:58:58.840 --> 06:59:05.360
She remembered that he had boasted of having no fear of seeing Mr. Darcy, that Mr. Darcy must

06:59:05.360 --> 06:59:11.780
leave the country, but that he should stand his ground, yet he had avoided the Netherfield ball

06:59:11.780 --> 06:59:18.060
the very next week. She remembered also that till the Netherfield family had quitted the country,

06:59:18.580 --> 06:59:24.460
he had told a story to no one but herself, but that after their removal it had been everywhere

06:59:24.460 --> 06:59:30.440
discussed, that he had then no reserves, no scruples in sinking Mr. Darcy's character,

06:59:30.840 --> 06:59:36.800
though he had assured her that respect for the father would always prevent his exposing the son.

06:59:37.580 --> 06:59:44.220
How differently did everything now appear in that he was concerned. His attentions to Miss King were

06:59:44.220 --> 06:59:51.520
now the consequence of views solely and hatefully mercenary, and the mediocrity of her fortune proved

06:59:51.520 --> 06:59:59.260
no longer the moderation of his wishes, but his eagerness to grasp at anything. His behaviour to

06:59:59.260 --> 07:00:06.200
herself could now have had no tolerable motive. He had either been deceived with regard to her fortune,

07:00:06.200 --> 07:00:13.400
or had been gratifying his vanity by encouraging the preference which she believed she had most

07:00:13.400 --> 07:00:20.300
incautiously shown. Every lingering struggle in his favour grew fainter and fainter.

07:00:21.300 --> 07:00:27.760
And in farther justification of Mr. Darcy, she could not but allow Mr. Bingley, when questioned

07:00:27.760 --> 07:00:35.580
by Jane, had long ago asserted his blamelessness in the affair. That proud and repulsive as were

07:00:35.580 --> 07:00:42.120
his manners, she had never in the whole course of their acquaintance, an acquaintance which had

07:00:42.120 --> 07:00:48.900
latterly brought them much together, and given her a sort of intimacy with his ways, seen anything

07:00:48.900 --> 07:00:57.200
that betrayed him to be unprincipled or unjust, anything that spoke him of irreligious or immoral

07:00:57.200 --> 07:01:04.800
habits, that among his own connections he was esteemed and valued, that even Wickham had allowed

07:01:04.800 --> 07:01:10.600
him merit as a brother, and that she had often heard him speak so affectionately of his sister

07:01:10.600 --> 07:01:17.960
as to prove him capable of some amiable feeling. That had his actions been what Mr. Wickham

07:01:17.960 --> 07:01:24.080
represented them, so gross a violation of everything right could hardly have been concealed

07:01:24.080 --> 07:01:30.840
from the world, and that friendship between a person capable of it and such an amiable man

07:01:30.840 --> 07:01:39.260
as Mr. Bingley was incomprehensible. She grew absolutely ashamed of herself, of neither Darcy

07:01:39.260 --> 07:01:45.700
nor Wickham could she think without feeling she had been blind, partial, prejudiced, absurd.

07:01:46.260 --> 07:01:52.660
How despicably I have acted, she cried, I who have prided myself on my discernment,

07:01:53.060 --> 07:02:00.040
I who have valued myself on my abilities. From herself to Jane, from Jane to Bingley,

07:02:00.040 --> 07:02:06.680
her thoughts were in a line which soon brought to her recollection that Mr. Darcy's explanation

07:02:06.680 --> 07:02:13.940
there had appeared very insufficient, and she read it again. Widely different was the effect

07:02:13.940 --> 07:02:20.060
of the second perusal. How could she deny that credit to his assertions, in one instance,

07:02:20.640 --> 07:02:27.040
which she had been obliged to give in the other? He declared himself to be totally unsuspicious

07:02:27.040 --> 07:02:32.620
of her sister's attachment, and she could not help remembering what Charlotte's opinion had

07:02:32.620 --> 07:02:39.740
always been. Neither could she deny the justice of his description of Jane. She felt that Jane's

07:02:39.740 --> 07:02:47.380
feelings, though fervent, were little displayed, and that there was a constant complacency in her

07:02:47.380 --> 07:02:55.400
air and manner not often united with great sensibility. When she came to that part of the

07:02:55.400 --> 07:03:02.060
letter, in which her family were mentioned in terms of such mortifying, yet merited reproach,

07:03:02.220 --> 07:03:09.180
her sense of shame was severe. The justice of the charge struck her too forcibly for denial,

07:03:09.560 --> 07:03:15.620
and the circumstances to which he particularly alluded as having passed at the Netherfield ball,

07:03:15.820 --> 07:03:22.800
and as confirming all his first disapprobation, could not have made a stronger impression on his

07:03:22.800 --> 07:03:30.040
than on hers. The compliment to herself and her sister was not unfelt. It soothed,

07:03:30.040 --> 07:03:35.660
but it could not console her for the contempt which had thus been self-attracted by the rest

07:03:35.660 --> 07:03:42.600
of her family. And as she considered that Jane's disappointment had in fact been the work of her

07:03:42.600 --> 07:03:50.640
nearest relations, and reflected how materially the credit of both must be hurt by such impropriety of

07:03:51.400 --> 07:03:59.000
she felt depressed beyond anything she had ever known. After wandering along the lane for two

07:03:59.000 --> 07:04:06.100
hours, giving way to every variety of thought, reconsidering events, determining probabilities,

07:04:06.520 --> 07:04:13.200
and reconciling herself, as well as she could, to a change so sudden and so important,

07:04:13.900 --> 07:04:18.980
fatigue and a recollection of her long absence made her at length return home,

07:04:18.980 --> 07:04:23.020
and she entered the house with the wish of appearing cheerful as usual,

07:04:23.440 --> 07:04:29.800
and the resolution of repressing such reflections as must make her unfit for conversation.

07:04:31.560 --> 07:04:37.040
She was immediately told that the two gentlemen from Rosings had each called during her absence,

07:04:37.580 --> 07:04:43.380
Mr. Darcy only for a few minutes to take leave, but that Colonel Fitzwilliam had been sitting

07:04:43.380 --> 07:04:49.200
with them at least an hour, hoping for her return, and almost resolving to walk after

07:04:49.200 --> 07:04:55.180
her till she could be found. Elizabeth could but just affect concern in missing him.

07:04:55.820 --> 07:05:03.280
She really rejoiced at it. Colonel Fitzwilliam was no longer an object. She could think only of her

07:05:03.280 --> 07:05:03.720
better.

07:05:09.820 --> 07:05:16.880
The two gentlemen left Rosings the next morning, and Mr. Collins, having been in waiting near the

07:05:16.880 --> 07:05:23.440
lodges to make them his parting obeisance, was able to bring home the pleasing intelligence of

07:05:23.440 --> 07:05:29.460
their appearing in very good health and in as tolerable spirits as could be expected

07:05:30.020 --> 07:05:36.860
after the melancholy scenes so lately gone through at Rosings. To Rosings he then hastened

07:05:36.860 --> 07:05:43.300
to console Lady Catherine and her daughter, and on his return brought back with great satisfaction

07:05:43.300 --> 07:05:50.060
a message from her ladyship, importing that she felt herself so dull as to make her very

07:05:50.060 --> 07:05:56.320
desirous of having them all to dine with her. Elizabeth could not see Lady Catherine without

07:05:56.320 --> 07:06:01.900
recollecting that, had she chosen it, she might by this time have been presented to her as her

07:06:01.900 --> 07:06:07.940
future niece, nor could she think without a smile of what her ladyship's indignation would have been.

07:06:08.420 --> 07:06:14.300
What would she have said? How would she have behaved? Were questions with which she amused

07:06:14.300 --> 07:06:19.780
herself. Their first subject was the diminution of the Rosings party.

07:06:20.420 --> 07:06:26.700
I assure you I feel it exceedingly, said Lady Catherine. I believe no one feels the loss of

07:06:26.700 --> 07:06:33.180
friends as much as I do, but I am particularly attached to these young men and know them to be

07:06:33.180 --> 07:06:40.800
so much attached to me. They were excessively sorry to go, but so they always are. The dear

07:06:40.800 --> 07:06:47.700
Colonel rallied his spirits tolerably till just at last, but Darcy seemed to feel it more acutely,

07:06:48.260 --> 07:06:53.780
I think than last year. His attachment to Rosings certainly increases.

07:06:55.360 --> 07:07:01.720
Mr. Collins had a compliment and an allusion to throw in here, which were kindly smiled on by the

07:07:01.720 --> 07:07:08.240
mother and daughter. Lady Catherine observed after dinner that Miss Bennet seemed out of spirits

07:07:08.240 --> 07:07:14.640
and immediately accounted for it by herself by supposing that she did not like to go home again

07:07:14.640 --> 07:07:21.400
so soon, she added. But if that is the case, you must write to your mother and beg that you may

07:07:21.400 --> 07:07:27.360
stay a little longer. Mrs. Collins will be very glad of your company, I am sure.

07:07:28.460 --> 07:07:33.440
I am much obliged to your ladyship for your kind invitation, replied Elizabeth,

07:07:33.840 --> 07:07:38.740
but it is not in my power to accept it. I must be in town next Saturday.

07:07:39.620 --> 07:07:46.400
Why, at that rate, you will have been here only six weeks. I expected you to stay two months,

07:07:46.640 --> 07:07:52.960
I told Mrs. Collins so before you came. There can be no occasion for your going so soon.

07:07:53.300 --> 07:07:56.700
Mrs. Bennet could certainly spare you for another fortnight.

07:07:58.040 --> 07:08:02.100
But my father cannot. He wrote last week to hurry my return.

07:08:02.880 --> 07:08:08.360
Oh, your father of course may spare you if your mother can. Daughters are never of so

07:08:08.360 --> 07:08:14.860
consequence to a father, and if you will stay another month complete, it will be in my power

07:08:14.860 --> 07:08:21.300
to take one of you as far as London, for I am going there early in June for a week, and as

07:08:21.300 --> 07:08:27.720
Dawson does not object to the baroque box, there will be very good room for one of you, and indeed,

07:08:27.820 --> 07:08:33.680
if the weather should happen to be cool, I should not object to taking you both, as you are neither

07:08:33.680 --> 07:08:40.760
of you large. You are all kindness, ma'am, but I believe we must abide by our original plan.

07:08:41.700 --> 07:08:47.760
Lady Catherine seemed resigned. Mrs. Collins, you must send a servant for them. You know,

07:08:47.780 --> 07:08:53.300
I always speak my mind, and I cannot bear the idea of two young women travelling post by

07:08:53.300 --> 07:09:00.880
themselves. It is highly improper. You must contrive to send somebody. I have the greatest

07:09:00.880 --> 07:09:05.920
dislike in the world to that sort of thing. Young women should always be properly guarded

07:09:05.920 --> 07:09:12.280
and attended, according to their situation in life. When my niece Georgina went to Ramsgate

07:09:12.280 --> 07:09:18.380
last summer, I made a point of having two men servants go with her. Miss Darcy, the daughter

07:09:18.380 --> 07:09:24.940
of Mr. Darcy of Pemberley and Lady Anne, could not have appeared with propriety in a different manner.

07:09:24.940 --> 07:09:31.540
I am excessively attentive to all those things. You must send John with the young ladies, Mrs.

07:09:31.800 --> 07:09:38.060
Collins. I am glad it occurred to me to mention it, for it would really be discreditable to you

07:09:38.060 --> 07:09:46.740
to let them go alone. My uncle is to send a servant for us. Oh, your uncle? He keeps a man

07:09:46.740 --> 07:09:53.520
servant, does he? I am very glad you have somebody who thinks of these things. Where shall you change

07:09:54.060 --> 07:09:58.840
Oh, Bromley, of course. If you mention my name at the bell, you will be attended to.

07:09:59.920 --> 07:10:05.600
Lady Catherine had many other questions to ask, respecting their journey, and as she did not answer

07:10:05.600 --> 07:10:11.220
them all herself, attention was necessary, which Elizabeth believed to be lucky for her.

07:10:11.840 --> 07:10:18.240
Or, with a mind so occupied, she might have forgotten where she was. Reflection must be

07:10:18.240 --> 07:10:24.520
reserved for solitary hours. Whenever she was alone, she gave way to it as the greatest relief.

07:10:25.100 --> 07:10:31.680
And not a day went by without a solitary walk, in which she might indulge in all the delight of

07:10:31.680 --> 07:10:39.040
unpleasant recollections. Mr. Darcy's letter she was in a fair way of soon knowing by heart.

07:10:39.600 --> 07:10:46.180
She studied every sentence, and her feelings towards its writer were at times widely different.

07:10:46.840 --> 07:10:53.520
When she remembered the style of his address, she was still full of indignation. But when she

07:10:53.520 --> 07:11:00.380
considered how unjustly she had condemned and upbraided him, her anger was turned against herself,

07:11:00.780 --> 07:11:08.360
and his disappointed feelings became the object of compassion. His attachment excited gratitude,

07:11:08.780 --> 07:11:14.820
his general character respect, but she could not approve him, nor could she for a moment

07:11:14.820 --> 07:11:20.380
repent her refusal or feel the slightest inclination ever to see him again.

07:11:21.360 --> 07:11:27.220
In her own past behaviour, there was a constant source of vexation and regret,

07:11:27.620 --> 07:11:34.400
and in the unhappy defects of her family a subject of yet heavier chagrin. They were

07:11:34.400 --> 07:11:40.900
hopeless of remedy. Her father, contented with laughing at them, would never exert himself to

07:11:40.900 --> 07:11:47.260
restrain the wild giddiness of his youngest daughters, and her mother, with manners so far

07:11:47.260 --> 07:11:54.420
from right herself, was entirely insensible to the evil. Elizabeth had frequently united with

07:11:54.420 --> 07:12:00.280
Jane in an endeavour to check the imprudence of Catherine and Lydia, but while they were supported

07:12:00.280 --> 07:12:08.260
by their mother's indulgence, what chance could there be of improvement? Catherine, weak-spirited,

07:12:08.260 --> 07:12:14.640
irritable and completely under Lydia's guidance, had always been affronted by their advice,

07:12:15.100 --> 07:12:22.280
and Lydia, self-willed and careless, would scarcely give them a hearing. They were ignorant,

07:12:22.680 --> 07:12:27.880
idle and vain. While there was an officer in Meryton, they would flirt with him,

07:12:28.020 --> 07:12:32.940
and while Meryton was within a walk of Longbourn, they would be going there forever.

07:12:34.100 --> 07:12:37.780
Anxiety on Jane's behalf was another prevailing concern,

07:12:38.200 --> 07:12:43.740
and Mr. Darcy's explanation, by restoring Bingley to all her former good opinion,

07:12:44.280 --> 07:12:50.820
heightened the sense of what Jane had lost. His affection was proved to have been sincere,

07:12:51.200 --> 07:12:57.700
and his conduct cleared of all blame, unless any could attach to the implicitness of his confidence

07:12:57.700 --> 07:13:04.220
in his friend. How grievous, then, was the thought that, of a situation so desirable

07:13:04.220 --> 07:13:10.740
in every respect, so replete with advantage, so promising for her happiness,

07:13:11.240 --> 07:13:16.700
Jane had been deprived by the folly and indecorum of her own family.

07:13:17.320 --> 07:13:22.220
When to these recollections was added the development of Wickham's character,

07:13:22.220 --> 07:13:28.320
it may be easily believed that the happy spirits, which had seldom been depressed before,

07:13:28.620 --> 07:13:34.460
were now so much affected as to make it impossible for her to appear tolerably cheerful.

07:13:35.560 --> 07:13:40.180
Their engagements at Rosings were as frequent during the last week of their stay

07:13:40.180 --> 07:13:46.820
as they had been at first. The very last evening was spent there, and her ladyship again inquired

07:13:46.820 --> 07:13:52.660
minutely into the particulars of their journey, gave them directions as to the best method of

07:13:52.660 --> 07:13:59.540
packing, and was so urgent on the necessity of placing gowns in the only right way that

07:13:59.540 --> 07:14:06.140
Maria thought herself obliged on her return to undo all the work of the morning and pack her

07:14:06.140 --> 07:14:13.220
trunk afresh. When they parted, Lady Catherine, with great condescension, wished them a good

07:14:13.220 --> 07:14:19.460
journey, and invited them to come to Huntsford again next year, and Miss de Bourgh exerted herself

07:14:19.460 --> 07:14:27.420
so far as to curtsy and hold out her hand to both.

07:14:49.720 --> 07:14:54.760
On Saturday morning Elizabeth and Mr. Collins met for breakfast a few minutes before the

07:14:54.760 --> 07:15:00.720
appeared, and he took the opportunity of paying the parting civilities which he deemed

07:15:00.720 --> 07:15:02.680
indispensable necessary.

07:15:04.100 --> 07:15:09.560
I know not, Miss Elizabeth, said he, whether Mrs. Collins has yet expressed her sense of

07:15:09.560 --> 07:15:14.680
your kindness in coming to us, but I am very certain you will not leave the house without

07:15:14.680 --> 07:15:16.640
receiving her thanks for it.

07:15:17.740 --> 07:15:21.440
The favour of your company has been much felt, I assure you.

07:15:21.440 --> 07:15:27.200
We know how little there is to tempt anyone in our humble abode, our plain manner of

07:15:27.200 --> 07:15:32.940
living, our small rooms and few domestics, and the little we see of the world must make

07:15:32.940 --> 07:15:38.900
Hunsford extremely dull to a young lady like yourself, but I hope you will believe us grateful

07:15:38.900 --> 07:15:44.600
for the condescension, and that we have done everything in our power to prevent your spending

07:15:44.600 --> 07:15:46.280
your time unpleasantly.

07:15:47.160 --> 07:15:50.880
Elizabeth was eager with her thanks and assurances of happiness.

07:15:51.440 --> 07:15:56.360
She had spent six weeks with great enjoyment, and the pleasure of being with Charlotte

07:15:56.360 --> 07:16:01.220
and the kind attentions she had received must make her feel the obliged.

07:16:02.480 --> 07:16:09.640
Mr. Collins was gratified, and with more smiling solemnity replied, It gives me great pleasure

07:16:09.640 --> 07:16:12.700
to hear that you have passed your time not disagreeably.

07:16:13.180 --> 07:16:19.020
We have certainly done our best, and most fortunately having it in our power to introduce

07:16:19.020 --> 07:16:25.200
you to very superior society, and from our connections with Rosings, the frequent means

07:16:25.200 --> 07:16:30.920
of varying the humble home scene, I think we may flatter ourselves that your Hunsford

07:16:30.920 --> 07:16:33.700
visit cannot have been entirely irksome.

07:16:34.360 --> 07:16:40.280
Our situation with regard to Lady Catherine's family is indeed the sort of extraordinary

07:16:40.280 --> 07:16:43.480
advantage and blessing which few can boast.

07:16:43.800 --> 07:16:46.100
You see on what a footing we are.

07:16:46.100 --> 07:16:49.340
You see how continually we are engaged there.

07:16:49.700 --> 07:16:54.660
In truth I must acknowledge that with all the disadvantages of this humble parsonage

07:16:54.660 --> 07:17:00.820
I should not think anyone abiding in it an object of compassion while they are shares

07:17:00.820 --> 07:17:03.300
of our intimacy at Rosings.

07:17:04.720 --> 07:17:09.960
Words were insufficient for the elevation of his feelings, and he was obliged to walk

07:17:09.960 --> 07:17:16.900
about the room while Elizabeth tried to unite civility and truth in a few short sentences.

07:17:18.420 --> 07:17:24.460
You may in fact carry a very favourable report of us into Hertfordshire, my dear cousin.

07:17:24.900 --> 07:17:28.440
I flatter myself at least that you will be able to do so.

07:17:29.040 --> 07:17:34.020
Lady Catherine's great attentions to Mrs. Collins you have been a daily witness of,

07:17:34.020 --> 07:17:39.760
and altogether I trust it does not appear that your friend has drawn an unfortunate,

07:17:40.180 --> 07:17:43.200
but on this point it will be as well to be silent.

07:17:43.680 --> 07:17:49.300
Only let me assure you, my dear Elizabeth, that I can from my heart most cordially wish

07:17:49.300 --> 07:17:51.500
you equal physicality in marriage.

07:17:51.920 --> 07:17:55.960
My dear Charlotte and I have but one mind and one way of thinking.

07:17:56.640 --> 07:18:02.300
There is in everything a most remarkable resemblance of character and ideas between us.

07:18:02.940 --> 07:18:05.880
We seem to have been designed for each other.

07:18:06.920 --> 07:18:11.460
Elizabeth could safely say that it was a great happiness where that was the case,

07:18:11.680 --> 07:18:18.380
and with equal sincerity could add that she firmly believed and rejoiced in his domestic comforts.

07:18:19.380 --> 07:18:23.240
She was not sorry, however, to have the recital of them interrupted

07:18:23.240 --> 07:18:25.680
by the lady from whom they sprang.

07:18:26.480 --> 07:18:27.760
Poor Charlotte!

07:18:28.420 --> 07:18:31.620
It was melancholy to leave her to such society.

07:18:32.300 --> 07:18:36.480
But she had chosen it with her eyes open, and though evidently regretting

07:18:36.480 --> 07:18:41.120
that her visitors were to go, she did not seem to ask for compassion.

07:18:41.980 --> 07:18:45.540
Her home and her housekeeping, her parish and her poultry,

07:18:45.900 --> 07:18:50.220
and all their dependent concerns had not yet lost their charms.

07:18:51.080 --> 07:18:55.140
At length the chaise arrived, the trunks were fastened on,

07:18:55.280 --> 07:18:58.460
the parcels placed within, and it was pronounced to be ready.

07:18:59.100 --> 07:19:02.020
After an affectionate parting between the friends,

07:19:02.560 --> 07:19:05.580
Elizabeth was attended to the carriage by Mr. Collins,

07:19:06.140 --> 07:19:09.380
and as they walked down the garden he was commissioning her

07:19:09.380 --> 07:19:15.120
with his best respects to all her family, not forgetting his thanks for the kindness

07:19:15.120 --> 07:19:20.940
he had received at Longburn in the winter, and his compliments to Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner,

07:19:21.460 --> 07:19:22.440
though unknown.

07:19:23.280 --> 07:19:25.020
He then handed her in.

07:19:25.020 --> 07:19:28.820
Maria followed, and the door was on the point of being closed,

07:19:29.100 --> 07:19:32.900
when he suddenly reminded them, with some consternation,

07:19:33.160 --> 07:19:38.940
that they had hitherto forgotten to leave any messages for the ladies at Rosings.

07:19:39.680 --> 07:19:44.980
But, he added, you will of course wish to have your humble respects delivered to them,

07:19:45.200 --> 07:19:48.960
with your grateful thanks for their kindness to you while you have been here.

07:19:49.820 --> 07:19:51.600
Elizabeth made no objection.

07:19:51.600 --> 07:19:56.080
The door was then allowed to be shut, and the carriage drove off.

07:19:56.700 --> 07:20:00.360
Good gracious! cried Maria after a few minutes' silence.

07:20:00.920 --> 07:20:06.680
It seems but a day or two since we first came, and yet how many things have happened!

07:20:07.680 --> 07:20:10.920
A great many indeed, said her companion with a sigh.

07:20:11.500 --> 07:20:17.080
We have dined nine times at Rosings, besides drinking tea there twice!

07:20:17.480 --> 07:20:19.220
How much I shall have to tell!

07:20:20.180 --> 07:20:21.780
Elizabeth added privately.

07:20:22.340 --> 07:20:24.620
And how much I shall have to conceal!

07:20:26.120 --> 07:20:30.420
Their journey was performed without much conversation or any alarm,

07:20:30.640 --> 07:20:35.560
and within four hours of their leaving Huntsford they reached Mr. Gardiner's house,

07:20:35.860 --> 07:20:37.960
where they were to remain a few days.

07:20:39.240 --> 07:20:43.720
Jane looked well, and Elizabeth had little opportunity of studying her spirits,

07:20:44.120 --> 07:20:48.940
amidst the various engagements which the kindness of her aunt had reserved for them.

07:20:49.540 --> 07:20:55.460
But Jane was to go home with her, and at Longbourn there would be leisure enough for observation.

07:20:56.660 --> 07:21:01.120
It was not without an effort, meanwhile, that she could wait even for Longbourn,

07:21:01.160 --> 07:21:04.360
before she told her sister of Mr. Darcy's proposals.

07:21:05.360 --> 07:21:10.900
To know that she had the power of revealing what would so exceedingly astonish Jane,

07:21:11.160 --> 07:21:16.520
and must at the same time so highly gratify whatever of her own vanity

07:21:16.520 --> 07:21:23.020
she had not yet been able to reason away, was such a temptation to openness as nothing could

07:21:23.020 --> 07:21:28.860
have been conquered but the state of indecision in which she remained as to the extent of what

07:21:28.860 --> 07:21:34.820
she should communicate, and her fear if she once entered on the subject of being hurried

07:21:34.820 --> 07:21:39.880
into repeating something of Bingley which might only grieve her sister further.

07:21:46.440 --> 07:21:51.160
It was the second week in May in which the three young ladies set out together

07:21:51.160 --> 07:21:56.740
from Grace Church Street for the town in Hertfordshire, and as they drew near the

07:21:56.740 --> 07:22:01.420
approved inn where Mr. Bennet's carriage was to meet them, they quickly perceived,

07:22:01.560 --> 07:22:08.380
in token of the coachman's punctuality, both Kitty and Lydia looking out of a dining room upstairs.

07:22:08.380 --> 07:22:15.040
These two girls had been above an hour in the place, happily employed in visiting an opposite

07:22:15.040 --> 07:22:20.000
milliner, watching the sentinel on guard, and dressing a salad and cucumber.

07:22:20.860 --> 07:22:26.580
After welcoming their sisters, they triumphantly displayed a table set out with such cold meat as

07:22:26.580 --> 07:22:33.580
an inn larder usually affords, exclaiming, Is this not nice? Is not this an agreeable surprise?

07:22:34.140 --> 07:22:38.880
And we mean to treat you all, added Lydia, but you must lend us the money for we have

07:22:38.880 --> 07:22:44.020
just spent ours at the shop out there. Then, showing her purchases, look here,

07:22:44.100 --> 07:22:48.780
I have bought this bonnet. I do not think it is very pretty, but I thought I might as well

07:22:48.780 --> 07:22:54.960
buy it as not. I shall pull it to pieces as soon as I get home, and see if I can make it up any better.

07:22:55.600 --> 07:23:00.040
And when her sisters abused it as ugly, she added, with perfect unconcern,

07:23:00.040 --> 07:23:05.940
Oh, but there were two or three much uglier in the shop, and when I have bought some prettier

07:23:05.940 --> 07:23:11.760
coloured satin to trim it with, fresh, I think it will be very tolerable. Besides,

07:23:11.760 --> 07:23:17.300
it will not much signify what one wears this summer, after the militia have left Meryton,

07:23:17.380 --> 07:23:23.480
and they are going in a fortnight. Are they indeed? cried Elizabeth with great satisfaction.

07:23:24.300 --> 07:23:30.020
They are going to be encamped near Brighton, and I do so want Papa to take us there for the summer.

07:23:30.040 --> 07:23:36.660
It would be such a delicious scheme, and I dare say would cost hardly anything at all. Mama would

07:23:36.660 --> 07:23:43.320
like to go two of all things. Only think what a miserable summer else we shall have. Yes,

07:23:43.320 --> 07:23:49.380
thought Elizabeth, that would be a delightful scheme indeed, and completely due for us at once.

07:23:49.840 --> 07:23:56.680
Good Heaven! Brighton and a whole campful of soldiers, to us who have been overset already

07:23:56.680 --> 07:24:01.500
by one poor regiment of militia and the monthly balls of Meryton.

07:24:02.320 --> 07:24:06.460
Now I have got some news for you, said Lydia, as they sat down at the table.

07:24:06.940 --> 07:24:13.720
What do you think? It is excellent news, capital news, and about a certain person we all like.

07:24:15.440 --> 07:24:19.920
Jane and Elizabeth looked at each other, and the waiter was told he need not stay.

07:24:20.700 --> 07:24:25.760
Lydia laughed and said, Aye, that is just like your formality and discretion.

07:24:25.760 --> 07:24:32.180
You thought the waiter must not hear, as if he cared. I dared say he often hears worse things

07:24:32.180 --> 07:24:38.600
said than what I am going to say. But he is an ugly fellow. I am glad he is gone. I never saw

07:24:38.600 --> 07:24:45.860
such a long chin in my life. Well, but now for my news. It is about dear Wickham. Too good for the

07:24:45.860 --> 07:24:53.220
waiter, is it not? There is no danger of Wickham's marrying Mary King. There's for you. She has gone

07:24:53.220 --> 07:25:00.580
down to her uncle at Liverpool, gone to stay. Wickham is safe. And Mary King is safe, added

07:25:00.580 --> 07:25:07.860
Elizabeth, safe from a connection imprudent as to fortune. She is a great fool for going away if she

07:25:07.860 --> 07:25:15.080
liked him. But I am sure there is no strong attachment on either side, said Jane. I am sure

07:25:15.080 --> 07:25:21.280
there is not on his. I will answer for it. He never cared three straws about her. Who could

07:25:21.280 --> 07:25:27.140
care about such a nasty little freckled thing? Elizabeth was shocked to think that, however

07:25:27.140 --> 07:25:32.720
incapable of such coarseness of expression herself, the coarseness of the sentiment was

07:25:32.720 --> 07:25:39.240
little other than her own breast had harboured and fancied liberal. As soon as all had ate,

07:25:39.540 --> 07:25:45.800
and the elder ones paid, the carriage was ordered, and after some contrivance the whole party with

07:25:45.800 --> 07:25:52.580
all their boxes, work bags, and parcels, and the unwelcome addition of Kitty's and Lydia's purchases

07:25:52.580 --> 07:25:59.580
were seated in it. How nicely we are all crammed in, cried Lydia. I am glad I bought my bonnet,

07:25:59.620 --> 07:26:05.920
if it is only for the fun of having another band box. Well now, let us be quite comfortable and snug

07:26:05.920 --> 07:26:12.180
and talk and laugh all the way home. And in the first place, let us hear what has happened

07:26:13.100 --> 07:26:19.080
To you all, since you went away, have you seen any pleasant men? Have you had any flirting?

07:26:19.760 --> 07:26:24.040
I was in great hopes that one of you would have got a husband before you came back.

07:26:24.460 --> 07:26:29.020
Jane will be quite an old maid soon, I declare. She is almost twenty-three.

07:26:29.620 --> 07:26:34.340
Lord, how ashamed I should be of not being married before twenty and three.

07:26:34.880 --> 07:26:39.720
My Aunt Phillips wants you so to get husbands. You can't think.

07:26:40.280 --> 07:26:45.760
She says Lizzie had better have taken Mr. Collins, and I do not think there would have been any fun

07:26:45.760 --> 07:26:51.540
in it. Lord, how I should like to be married before any of you, and then I would chaperone

07:26:51.540 --> 07:26:58.200
you about to all the balls. Dear me, we had such a good piece of fun the other day at Colonel Foster's.

07:26:59.020 --> 07:27:04.080
Kitty and me were to spend the day there, and Mrs. Foster promised to have a little dance in

07:27:04.840 --> 07:27:11.340
By the by, Mrs. Foster and me are such friends. And so she asked the two Harringtons to come.

07:27:11.700 --> 07:27:15.700
But Harriet was ill, and so Penn was forced to come by herself.

07:27:15.940 --> 07:27:21.300
And then what do you think we did? We dressed up chamberlains in women's clothes

07:27:21.300 --> 07:27:28.120
on purpose to pass for a lady. Only think what fun! Not a soul knew of it, but Colonel and Mrs.

07:27:28.360 --> 07:27:33.660
Foster and Kitty and me, except my Aunt, for we were forced to borrow one of her gowns.

07:27:33.660 --> 07:27:40.400
And you could not imagine how well he looked. When Denny and Wickham and Pratt and two or

07:27:40.400 --> 07:27:46.600
three more of the men came in, they did not know him in the least. Lord, how I laughed!

07:27:46.920 --> 07:27:52.960
And so did Mrs. Foster. I thought I should have died. And that made the men suspect something,

07:27:52.960 --> 07:27:59.740
and then they soon found out what was the matter. With such kinds of histories of their parties and

07:27:59.740 --> 07:28:06.400
jokes, Delidia, assisted by Kitty's hints and additions, endeavoured to amuse her companions

07:28:06.400 --> 07:28:12.380
all the way to Longbourn. Elizabeth listened as little as she could, but there was no escaping

07:28:12.380 --> 07:28:19.060
the frequent mention of Wickham's name. The reception at home was most kind. Mrs. Bennet

07:28:19.060 --> 07:28:25.520
rejoiced to see Jane in undiminished beauty, and more than once during dinner did Mr. Bennet say

07:28:25.980 --> 07:28:32.720
to Elizabeth, I am glad you are back, Lizzie. Their party in the dining room was large,

07:28:32.840 --> 07:28:39.340
for almost all the Lucas's came to meet Maria and hear the news, and various were the subjects that

07:28:39.340 --> 07:28:46.820
occupied them. Lady Lucas was inquiring of Maria after the welfare and poultry of her eldest daughter.

07:28:47.540 --> 07:28:53.060
Mrs. Bennet was doubly engaged, on one hand collecting an account of the present fashions

07:28:53.060 --> 07:29:00.340
from Jane, who sat way below her, and on the other retailing them all to the younger Lucas's.

07:29:00.740 --> 07:29:07.180
And Lydia, in a voice louder than any other person's, was enumerating the various pleasures

07:29:07.180 --> 07:29:14.180
of the morning to anybody who would hear her. Oh, Mary, said she, I wish you had gone with us,

07:29:14.360 --> 07:29:21.700
for we had such fun. As we went along Kitty and I drew up the blinds and pretended there was nobody

07:29:21.700 --> 07:29:27.900
in the coach, and I should have gone so all the way if Kitty had not been sick, and when we got

07:29:27.900 --> 07:29:34.520
to the George I do think we behaved very handsomely, for we treated the other three with the nicest

07:29:34.520 --> 07:29:41.400
cold luncheon in the world, and if you would have gone we would have treated you too, and then when

07:29:41.400 --> 07:29:48.160
we came away it was such fun. I thought we never should have got into the coach. I was ready to die

07:29:48.160 --> 07:29:55.320
of laughter, and then we were so merry all the way home. We talked and laughed so loud that anybody

07:29:55.320 --> 07:30:03.120
might have heard us ten miles off. To this Mary very gravely replied, Far be it from me, my dear

07:30:03.120 --> 07:30:09.440
sister, to depreciate such pleasures. They would doubtless be congenial with the generality of

07:30:09.440 --> 07:30:16.100
female minds, but I confess they would have no charms for me. I should infinitely prefer a book.

07:30:17.040 --> 07:30:23.420
But all of this answer Lydia heard not a word. She seldom listened to anybody for more than half a

07:30:23.420 --> 07:30:29.980
minute and never attended to Mary at all. In the afternoon Lydia was urgent with the rest of the

07:30:29.980 --> 07:30:36.800
girls to walk to Meryton and to see how everybody went on, but Elizabeth steadily opposed the scheme.

07:30:37.240 --> 07:30:43.720
It should not be said that the Miss Bennets could not be home half a day before they were in pursuit

07:30:43.720 --> 07:30:50.120
of the officers. There was another reason too for her opposition. She dreaded seeing Mr. Wickham

07:30:50.120 --> 07:30:56.220
again and was resolved to avoid it as long as possible. The comfort to her of the regiments

07:30:56.220 --> 07:31:02.900
approaching removal was indeed beyond expression. In a fortnight they were to go, and once gone she

07:31:02.900 --> 07:31:08.980
hoped there could be nothing more to plague her on his account. She had not been many hours at home

07:31:08.980 --> 07:31:15.640
before she found that the Brighton scheme of which Lydia had given them a hint at the inn was under

07:31:15.640 --> 07:31:22.600
frequent discussion between her parents. Elizabeth saw directly that her father had not the smallest

07:31:22.600 --> 07:31:30.140
intention of yielding, but his answers were at the same time so vague and equivocal that her mother,

07:31:30.240 --> 07:31:35.620
though often disheartened, had never yet despaired of succeeding at the last.

07:32:04.020 --> 07:32:06.900
PRIDE AND PREJUDICE

07:32:06.900 --> 07:32:08.900
by Jane Austen

07:32:12.280 --> 07:32:29.640
Elizabeth's impatience to acquaint Jane with what had happened could no longer be overcome, and at length resolving to suppress every particular in which her sister was concerned and preparing her to be surprised, she related to her the next morning the chief of the scene between Mr. Darcy and herself.

07:32:30.400 --> 07:32:56.600
Miss Bennet's astonishment was soon lessened by the strong sisterly partiality which made any admiration of Elizabeth appear perfectly natural, and all surprise was shortly lost in other feelings. She was sorry that Mr. Darcy should have delivered his sentiments in a manner so little suited to recommend them, but still more was she grieved for the unhappiness which her sister's refusal must have given him.

07:32:57.660 --> 07:33:08.020
His being so sure of succeeding was wrong, said she, and certainly ought not to have appeared, but consider how much it must increase his disappointment.

07:33:09.680 --> 07:33:22.700
Indeed, replied Elizabeth, I am heartily sorry for him, but he has other feelings which will probably soon drive away his regard for me. You do not blame me, however, for refusing him.

07:33:23.440 --> 07:33:29.780
Blame you? Oh, no! But you blame me for having spoken so warmly of Wickham?

07:33:31.920 --> 07:33:41.360
No, I do not know that you were wrong in saying what you did. But you will know it when I tell you what happened the very next day.

07:33:41.360 --> 07:34:03.540
She then spoke of the letter, repeating the whole of its contents as far as they concerned George Wickham. What a stroke this was for poor Jane, who would willingly have gone through the world without believing that so much wickedness existed in the whole race of mankind, as was here collected in one individual.

07:34:03.540 --> 07:34:20.620
Nor was Darcy's vindication, though grateful to her feelings, capable of consoling her for such discovery. Most earnestly did she labor to prove the probability of error, and seek to clear the one without involving the other.

07:34:21.500 --> 07:34:47.420
This will not do, said Elizabeth. You never will be able to make both of them good for anything. Take your choice, but you must be satisfied with only one. There is but such a quantity of merit between them, just enough to make one good sort of man. And of late it has been shifting about, pretty much. For my part I am inclined to believe it all Darcy's, but you shall do as you choose.

07:34:47.420 --> 07:34:51.640
It was some time, however, before a smile could be extorted from Jane.

07:34:52.500 --> 07:35:18.200
I do not know when I have been more shocked, said she. Wickham, so very bad! It is almost past belief. And poor Mr. Darcy. Dear Lizzy, only consider what he must have suffered. Such a disappointment, and with the knowledge of your ill opinion too, and having to relate such a thing of his sister.

07:35:18.200 --> 07:35:23.460
It is really too distressing. I am sure you must feel it so.

07:35:24.980 --> 07:35:44.500
Oh no, my regret and compassion are all done away by seeing you so full of both. I know you will do him such ample justice that I am growing every moment more unconcerned and indifferent. Your profusion makes me saving, and if you lament over him much longer my heart will be as light as a feather.

07:35:46.840 --> 07:35:56.240
Poor Wickham. There is such an expression of goodness in his countenance, such an openness and gentleness in his manner.

07:35:58.540 --> 07:36:07.540
There certainly was some great mismanagement in the education of those two young men. One has got all the goodness, and the other all the appearance of it.

07:36:09.440 --> 07:36:25.520
I never thought Mr. Darcy so deficient in the appearance of it as you used to do, and yet I meant to be uncommonly clever in taking so decided a dislike to him without any reason.

07:36:25.520 --> 07:36:43.240
It is such a spur to one's genius, such an opening for wit, to have a dislike of that kind. One may be continually abusive without saying anything just, but one cannot always be laughing at a man without now and then stumbling on something witty.

07:36:45.840 --> 07:36:52.780
Lizzie, when you first read that letter I am sure you could not treat the matter as you do now.

07:36:54.440 --> 07:37:16.780
Indeed, I could not. I was uncomfortable enough, I may say unhappy, and with no one to speak to about what I felt, no Jane to comfort me and say that I had not been so very weak and vain and nonsensical as I knew I had. Oh, how I wanted you.

07:37:18.400 --> 07:37:39.180
How unfortunate that you should have used such very strong expressions in speaking of Wickham to Mr. Darcy, for now they do appear wholly undeserved. Certainly, but the misfortune of speaking with bitterness is a most natural consequence of the prejudices I had been encouraging.

07:37:40.440 --> 07:37:54.400
There is one point on which I want your advice. I want to be told whether I ought or ought not to make our acquaintances in general understand Wickham's character.

07:37:56.160 --> 07:37:59.480
Miss Bennet paused a little and then replied,

07:38:00.580 --> 07:38:07.620
Shortly there can be no occasion for exposing him so dreadfully. What is your opinion?

07:38:09.180 --> 07:38:23.040
That it ought not to be attempted. Mr. Darcy has not authorized me to make his communication public. On the contrary, every particular relative to his sister was meant to be kept as much as possible to myself.

07:38:23.680 --> 07:38:42.280
And if I endeavour to undeceive people as to the rest of his conduct, who will believe me? The general prejudice against Mr. Darcy is so violent that it would be the death of half the good people in Meryton to attempt to place him in an amiable light. I am not equal to it.

07:38:42.860 --> 07:39:00.740
Wickham will soon be gone, and therefore it will not signify to anyone here what he really is. Sometime hence it will be all found out, and we may laugh at their stupidity in not knowing it before. At present, I will say nothing about it.

07:39:00.740 --> 07:39:15.200
You are quite right. To have his errors made public might ruin him forever. He is now, perhaps, sorry for what he has done, and anxious to re-establish a character. We must not make him desperate.

07:39:15.900 --> 07:39:38.340
The tumult of Elizabeth's mind was allayed by this conversation. She had got rid of two of the secrets which had weighed on her for a fortnight, and was certain of a willing listener in Jane, whenever she might wish to talk again of either. But there was still something lurking behind, of which prudence forbade the disclosure.

07:39:39.260 --> 07:40:02.060
She dared not relate the other half of Mr. Darcy's letter, nor explain to her sister how sincerely she had been valued by her friend. Here was knowledge in which no one could partake, and she was sensible that nothing less than a perfect understanding between the parties could justify her in throwing off this last encumbrance of mystery.

07:40:03.140 --> 07:40:28.780
And then, said she, if that very improbable event should ever take place, I shall merely be able to tell what Bingley may tell in a much more agreeable manner himself. The liberty of communication cannot be mine till it has lost all its value. She was now, on being settled at home, at leisure to observe the real state of her sister's spirits.

07:40:29.580 --> 07:40:50.340
Jane was not happy. She still cherished a very tender affection for Bingley. Having never even fancied herself in love before, her regard had all the warmth of first attachment, and from her age and disposition greater steadiness than most first attachments often boast.

07:40:50.340 --> 07:41:12.520
And so fervently did she value his remembrance, and prefer him to every other man, that all her good sense and all her attention to the feelings of her friends were requisite to check the indulgence of those regrets which must have been injurious to her own health and their tranquillity.

07:41:13.400 --> 07:41:42.500
"'Well, Lizzy,' said Mrs. Bennet one day, "'what is your opinion now of this sad business of Jane's? For my part I am determined never to speak of it again to anybody. I told my sister Philip so the other day, but I cannot find out that Jane saw anything of him in London. Well, he is a very undeserving young man, and I do not suppose there's the least chance in the world of her ever getting him now.

07:41:42.520 --> 07:41:53.520
There is no talk of his coming to Netherfield again in the summer, and I have inquired of everybody too who is likely to know. I do not believe he will ever live at Netherfield any more.'

07:41:54.800 --> 07:42:22.520
"'Oh, well, it is just as he chooses. Nobody wants him to come, though I shall always say he used my daughter extremely ill, and if I was her I would not have put up with it. Well, my comfort is I am sure Jane will die of a broken heart, and then he will be sorry for what he has done.' But as Elizabeth could not receive comfort from any such expectation, she made no answer.'

07:42:23.740 --> 07:42:48.960
"'Well, Lizzy,' continued her mother soon afterwards, "'and so the Collins's live very comfortably, do they? Well, well, I only hope it will last. And what sort of table do they keep? Charlotte is an excellent manager, I dare say. If she is half as sharp as her mother, she is saving enough. There is nothing extravagant in their house, I dare say.'

07:42:48.960 --> 07:43:18.140
"'No, nothing at all. A great deal of good management depend upon it. Yes, yes, they will take care not to outrun their income. They will never be distressed for money. Well, much good may it do them. And so I suppose they often talk of having long-born when your father is dead. They look upon it quite as their own, I dare say, whenever that happens.'

07:43:19.640 --> 07:43:23.460
It was a subject which they could not mention before me.

07:43:24.700 --> 07:43:41.960
No, it would have been strange if they had, but I make no doubt they often talk of it between themselves. Well, if they can be easy with an estate that is not lawfully their own so much the better, I should be ashamed of having one that was only entailed on me.'

07:43:49.520 --> 07:44:01.080
The first week of their return was soon gone. The second began. It was the last of the regiment's stay in Meryton, and all the young ladies in the neighborhood were drooping apace.

07:44:01.080 --> 07:44:24.900
The dejection was almost universal. The elder Miss Bennets alone were still able to eat, drink, and sleep and pursue the usual course of their employments. Very frequently were they reproached for this insensibility by Kitty and Lydia, whose own misery was extreme and who could not comprehend such hard-heartedness in any of the family.

07:44:25.680 --> 07:44:28.980
Good Heaven! What is to become of us? What are we to do?

07:44:30.060 --> 07:44:33.080
Would they often exclaim in the bitterness of woe,

07:44:33.480 --> 07:44:36.000
How can you be smiling so, Lizzy?

07:44:36.820 --> 07:44:45.840
Their affectionate mother shared all their grief. She remembered what she had herself endured on a similar occasion five and twenty years ago.

07:44:45.840 --> 07:44:55.520
I am sure, said she. I cried for two days together when Colonel Miller's regiment went away. I thought I should have broken my heart.

07:44:56.760 --> 07:44:59.900
I am sure I shall break mine, said Lydia.

07:45:01.880 --> 07:45:06.160
If one could but go to Brighton, observed Mrs. Bennet.

07:45:06.940 --> 07:45:12.280
Oh, yes, if one could but go to Brighton! But Papa is so disagreeable.

07:45:13.000 --> 07:45:15.820
A little sea-bathing would set me up forever.

07:45:16.960 --> 07:45:22.060
And my Aunt Phillips is sure it would do me a great deal of good, added Kitty.

07:45:23.160 --> 07:45:27.760
Such were the kind of lamentations resounding perpetually through Long-Born House.

07:45:28.760 --> 07:45:33.900
Elizabeth tried to be diverted by them, but all sense of pleasure was lost in shame.

07:45:33.900 --> 07:45:37.720
She felt anew the justice of Mr. Darcy's objections,

07:45:38.640 --> 07:45:44.480
and never had she been so much disposed to pardon his interference in the views of his friend.

07:45:46.080 --> 07:45:50.120
But the gloom of Lydia's prospect was shortly cleared away,

07:45:50.540 --> 07:45:57.960
for she received an invitation from Mrs. Forster, the wife of the Colonel of the regiment, to accompany her to Brighton.

07:45:58.460 --> 07:46:03.460
This invaluable friend was a very young woman, and very lately married.

07:46:03.900 --> 07:46:09.860
A resemblance in good humor and good spirits had recommended her and Lydia to each other,

07:46:10.280 --> 07:46:15.380
and out of their three months' acquaintance they had been intimate, too.

07:46:16.440 --> 07:46:21.400
The rapture of Lydia on this occasion, her adoration of Mrs. Forster,

07:46:21.880 --> 07:46:28.620
the delight of Mrs. Bennet, and the mortification of Kitty, are scarcely to be described.

07:46:28.620 --> 07:46:35.880
Wholly inattentive to her sister's feelings, Lydia flew about the house in restless ecstasy,

07:46:36.340 --> 07:46:42.620
calling for everyone's congratulations, and laughing and talking with more violence than ever,

07:46:43.160 --> 07:46:53.320
whilst the luckless Kitty, continued in the parlour, repined at her fate in terms as unreasonable as her accent was peevish.

07:46:54.200 --> 07:47:03.940
I cannot see why Mrs. Forster should not ask me as well as Lydia, said she, though I am not her particular friend.

07:47:04.600 --> 07:47:09.580
I have just as much right to be asked as she has, and more, too, for I am two years older.

07:47:10.520 --> 07:47:15.640
In vain did Elizabeth attempt to make her reasonable, and Jane to make her resigned.

07:47:16.600 --> 07:47:22.760
As for Elizabeth herself this invitation was so far from exciting in her the same feelings as in her mother and Lydia,

07:47:23.320 --> 07:47:28.240
that she considered it as the death warrant of all possibility of common sense for the latter,

07:47:28.980 --> 07:47:38.200
and detestable as such a step must make her were it known, she could not help secretly advising her father not to let her go.

07:47:38.760 --> 07:47:43.180
She represented to him all the improprieties of Lydia's general behaviour,

07:47:43.740 --> 07:47:48.060
the little advantage she could derive from the friendship of such a woman as Mrs. Forster,

07:47:48.060 --> 07:47:57.300
and the probability of her being yet more imprudent with such a companion at Brighton, where the temptations must be greater than at home.

07:47:58.280 --> 07:48:01.280
He heard her attentively, and then said,

07:48:02.440 --> 07:48:08.160
Lydia will never be easy until she has exposed herself in some public place or other,

07:48:08.700 --> 07:48:14.320
and we can never expect her to do it with so little expense or inconvenience to her family as under the present circumstances.

07:48:14.320 --> 07:48:26.040
If you were aware, said Elizabeth, of the very great disadvantage to us all which must arise from the public notice of Lydia's unguarded and imprudent manner,

07:48:26.960 --> 07:48:32.000
nay, which has already arisen from it, I am sure you would judge differently on the affair.

07:48:33.700 --> 07:48:40.140
Already arisen? repeated Mr. Bennet. What, has she frightened away some of your lovers?

07:48:40.960 --> 07:48:44.340
Poor little Lizzie! What do not be cast down?

07:48:45.340 --> 07:48:50.760
Such squeamish youths as cannot bear to be connected with a little absurdity are not worth a regret.

07:48:51.560 --> 07:48:56.860
Come, let me see the list of pitiful fellows who have been kept aloof by Lydia's folly.

07:48:58.160 --> 07:49:01.440
Indeed you are mistaken. I have no such injuries to resent.

07:49:02.240 --> 07:49:05.480
It is not of particular but of general evils which I am now complaining.

07:49:06.120 --> 07:49:15.600
Our importance, our respectability in the world must be affected by the wild volatility, the assurance and disdain of all restraint which mark Lydia's character.

07:49:16.740 --> 07:49:19.180
Excuse me, for I must speak plainly.

07:49:19.920 --> 07:49:29.080
If you, my dear father, will not take the trouble of checking her exuberant spirits and of teaching her that her present pursuits are not to be the business of her life,

07:49:29.940 --> 07:49:32.480
she will soon be beyond the reach of amendment.

07:49:32.480 --> 07:49:41.500
Her character will be fixed, and she will, at sixteen, be the most determined flirt that ever made herself or her family ridiculous.

07:49:42.120 --> 07:49:50.100
A flirt, too, in the worst and meanest degree of flirtation, without any attraction beyond youth and a tolerable person,

07:49:50.640 --> 07:50:01.760
and, from the ignorance and emptiness of her mind, wholly unable to ward off any portion of that universal contempt which her rage for admiration will excite.

07:50:02.520 --> 07:50:08.040
In this danger Kitty also is comprehended. She will follow wherever Lydia leads.

07:50:09.080 --> 07:50:12.920
Vain, ignorant, idle, and absolutely uncontrolled.

07:50:13.780 --> 07:50:24.480
Oh, my dear father, can you suppose it possible that they will not be censured and despised wherever they are known, and that their sisters will not be often involved in the disgrace?

07:50:25.420 --> 07:50:32.360
Mr. Bennet saw that her whole heart was in the subject, and affectionately, taking her hand, said in reply,

07:50:33.520 --> 07:50:36.500
Do not make yourself uneasy, my love.

07:50:37.480 --> 07:50:50.120
Wherever you and Jane are known, you must be respected and valued, and you will not appear to less advantage for having a couple of, or, I may say, three very silly sisters.

07:50:50.900 --> 07:51:01.080
We shall have no peace at Longbourn if Lydia does not go to Brighton. Let her go, then. Colonel Forster is a sensible man, and will keep her out of any real mischief.

07:51:01.860 --> 07:51:06.040
And she is, luckily, too poor to be an object of prey to anybody.

07:51:07.260 --> 07:51:15.120
At Brighton she will be of less importance even as a common flirt than she has been here. The officers will find women better worth their notice.

07:51:15.120 --> 07:51:28.160
Let us hope, therefore, that her being there may teach her her own insignificance. At any rate, she cannot grow many degrees worse without authorizing us to lock her up for the rest of her life.

07:51:29.720 --> 07:51:38.800
With this answer Elizabeth was forced to be content. But her own opinion continued the same, and she left him disappointed and sorry.

07:51:39.720 --> 07:51:54.860
It was not in her nature, however, to increase her vexations by dwelling on them. She was confident of having performed her duty, and to fret over unavoidable evils, or augment them by anxiety, was no part of her disposition.

07:51:56.160 --> 07:52:04.700
Had Lydia and her mother known the substance of her conference with her father, their indignation would hardly have found expression in their united volubility.

07:52:04.700 --> 07:52:11.980
In Lydia's imagination a visit to Brighton comprised every possibility of earthly happiness.

07:52:13.020 --> 07:52:21.340
She saw, with the creative eye of fancy, the streets of that gay bathing place covered with officers.

07:52:22.000 --> 07:52:28.880
She saw herself, the object of attention, to tens and to scores of them at present unknown.

07:52:28.880 --> 07:52:42.560
She saw all the glories of the camp, its tents stretched forth in beauteous uniformity of lines, crowded with the young and the gay, and dazzling with scarlet.

07:52:43.140 --> 07:52:51.180
And to complete the view she saw herself seated beneath a tent, tenderly flirting with at least six officers at once.

07:52:51.880 --> 07:53:01.020
Had she known her sister sought to tear her from such prospects and such realities as these, what would have been her sensations?

07:53:02.040 --> 07:53:07.080
They could have been understood only by her mother, who might have felt nearly the same.

07:53:08.180 --> 07:53:15.800
Lydia's going to Brighton was all that consoled her for her melancholic conviction of her husband's never intending to go there himself.

07:53:15.800 --> 07:53:25.800
But they were entirely ignorant of what had passed, and their raptures continued, with little intermission to the very day of Lydia's leaving home.

07:53:27.540 --> 07:53:30.700
Elizabeth was now to see Mr. Wickham for the last time.

07:53:31.520 --> 07:53:37.460
Having been frequently in company with him since her return, agitation was pretty well over.

07:53:38.240 --> 07:53:42.640
The agitations of formal partiality entirely so.

07:53:43.380 --> 07:53:53.840
She had even learnt to detect, in the very gentleness which had first delighted her, an affectation and a sameness to disgust and weary.

07:53:54.760 --> 07:54:00.040
In his present behaviour to herself, moreover, she had a fresh source of displeasure.

07:54:00.600 --> 07:54:12.240
For the inclination he soon testified of renewing those intentions which had marked the early part of their acquaintance could only serve, after what had since passed, to provoke her.

07:54:12.640 --> 07:54:20.940
She lost all concern for him in finding herself thus selected as the object of such idle and frivolous gallantry.

07:54:21.520 --> 07:54:32.840
And while she steadily repressed it, could not but feel the reproof contained in his believing that however long and for whatever cause his attentions had been withdrawn,

07:54:33.640 --> 07:54:39.560
her vanity would be gratified and her preference secured at any time by their renewal.

07:54:40.220 --> 07:54:46.740
On the very last day of the regiment's remaining at Maryton he dined with other of the officers at Longbourn.

07:54:47.980 --> 07:54:57.900
And so little was Elizabeth disposed to part from him in good humour that on his making some inquiry as to the manner in which her time had passed at Hunsford,

07:54:58.740 --> 07:55:07.720
she mentioned Colonel Fitzwilliams and Mr. Darcy's having both spent three weeks at Rosings and asked him if he was acquainted with the former.

07:55:08.740 --> 07:55:19.740
He looked surprised, displeased, alarmed, but with a moment's recollection and a returning smile, replied that he had formerly seen him often,

07:55:19.800 --> 07:55:28.320
and after observing that he was a very gentlemanly-like man, asked her how she had liked him. Her answer was warmly in his favour.

07:55:29.300 --> 07:55:31.680
With an air of indifference he soon afterwards added,

07:55:32.560 --> 07:55:35.620
How long did you say he was at Rosings?

07:55:36.860 --> 07:55:38.000
Nearly three weeks.

07:55:39.560 --> 07:55:40.940
And you saw him frequently?

07:55:42.380 --> 07:55:44.260
Yes, almost every day.

07:55:45.440 --> 07:55:48.160
His manners are very different from his cousin's.

07:55:48.920 --> 07:55:54.720
Yes, very different. But I think Mr. Darcy improves upon acquaintance.

07:55:55.360 --> 07:56:01.420
Indeed, cried Mr. Wickham, with a look which did not escape her. And pray, may I ask?

07:56:02.180 --> 07:56:04.700
But checking himself, he added in a gayer tone,

07:56:05.440 --> 07:56:20.840
Is it in a dress that he improves? Has he dined to add aught of civility to his ordinary style? For I dare not hope, he continued in a lower and more serious tone, that he has improved in essentials.

07:56:22.660 --> 07:56:31.280
Oh no! said Elizabeth. In essentials I believe he is very much what he ever was.

07:56:32.620 --> 07:56:40.120
While she spoke, Wickham looked as if, scarcely knowing whether to rejoice over her words, or to distrust their meaning,

07:56:40.880 --> 07:56:46.720
there was something in her countenance which made him listen with an apprehensive and anxious attention while she added,

07:56:47.700 --> 07:56:55.360
When I said that he improved on acquaintance, I did not mean that his mind or his manners were in a state of improvement,

07:56:55.580 --> 07:57:02.140
but that, from knowing him better, his disposition was better understood.

07:57:04.320 --> 07:57:08.600
Wickham's alarm now appeared in a heightened complexion and agitated look.

07:57:09.220 --> 07:57:16.340
For a few minutes he was silent. Till, shaking off his embarrassment, he turned to her again and said in the gentlest of accents,

07:57:17.520 --> 07:57:30.400
You, who so well know my feeling toward Mr. Darcy, will readily comprehend how sincerely I must rejoice that he is wise enough to assume even the appearance of what is right.

07:57:31.060 --> 07:57:42.240
His pride in that direction may be of service, if not to himself, to many others, for it must only deter him from such foul misconduct as I have suffered by.

07:57:42.840 --> 07:57:56.040
I only fear that the sort of cautionness to which you, I imagine, have been alluding is merely adopted on his visits to his aunt, of which, good opinion and judgment, he stands much in awe.

07:57:56.640 --> 07:58:09.200
His fear of her has always operated, I know, when they were together, and a good deal is to be imputed to his wish of forwarding the match with Miss de Bourgh, which I am certain he has very much at heart.

07:58:10.240 --> 07:58:16.500
Elizabeth could not repress a smile at this, but she answered only by a slight inclination of the head.

07:58:17.340 --> 07:58:24.160
She saw that he wanted to engage her on the old subject of his grievances, and she was in no humor to indulge him.

07:58:24.160 --> 07:58:42.380
The rest of the evening passed with the appearance, on his side, of useful cheerfulness, but with no further attempt to distinguish Elizabeth, and they parted at last with mutual civility and, possibly, a mutual desire of never meeting again.

07:58:42.380 --> 07:58:50.800
When the party broke up, Lydia returned with Mrs. Forster to Maryton, from whence they were to set out early the next morning.

07:58:51.180 --> 07:59:02.620
The separation between her and her family was rather noisy than pathetic. Kitty was the only one who shed tears, but she did weep from vexation and envy.

07:59:02.620 --> 07:59:15.160
Mrs. Bennet was diffuse in her good wishes for the felicity of her daughter, and impressive in her injunctions, that she should not miss the opportunity of enjoying herself as much as possible.

07:59:15.620 --> 07:59:30.300
Advice which there was every reason to believe would be well attended to, and in the clamorous happiness of Lydia herself, in bidding farewell, the more gentle adduce of her sisters were uttered without being heard.

08:00:07.000 --> 08:00:12.340
HAD ELIZABETH'S OPINION BEEN ALL DRAWN FROM HER OWN FAMILY, SHE COULD NOT HAVE FORMED

08:00:12.340 --> 08:00:16.600
A VERY PLEASING OPINION OF CONJUGAL FELLICITY OR DOMESTIC COMFORT.

08:00:17.700 --> 08:00:23.720
HER FATHER, CAPTIVATED BY YOUTH AND BEAUTY, AND THAT APPEARANCE OF GOOD HUMOUR WHICH YOUTH

08:00:23.720 --> 08:00:28.940
AND BEAUTY GENERALLY GIVE, HAD MARRIED A WOMAN WHOSE WEAK UNDERSTANDING AND ILIBERAL

08:00:28.940 --> 08:00:34.400
MIND, HAD VERY EARLY IN THEIR MARRIAGE PUT AN END TO ALL REAL AFFECTION FOR HER.

08:00:35.440 --> 08:00:41.100
RESPECT, ESTEEM, AND CONFIDENCE HAD VANISHED FOREVER, AND ALL HIS VIEWS OF DOMESTIC HAPPINESS

08:00:41.100 --> 08:00:42.000
WERE OVER-THROWN.

08:00:43.060 --> 08:00:43.680
BUT MR.

08:00:43.760 --> 08:00:48.020
BENNETT WAS NOT OF A DISPOSITION TO SEEK COMFORT FOR THE DISAPPOINTMENT WHICH HIS OWN

08:00:48.020 --> 08:00:53.440
IMPRUDENCE HAD BROUGHT ON IN ANY OF THOSE PLEASURES WHICH TOO OFTEN CONSOLLED THE UNFORTUNATE

08:00:53.440 --> 08:00:55.380
FOR THEIR FOLLY OR THEIR VICE.

08:00:56.220 --> 08:01:01.700
He was fond of the country and of books, and from these tastes had arisen his principal

08:01:01.700 --> 08:01:02.400
enjoyments.

08:01:03.740 --> 08:01:09.860
To his wife he was very little otherwise indebted, than as her ignorance and folly had contributed

08:01:09.860 --> 08:01:10.980
to his amusement.

08:01:11.760 --> 08:01:16.620
This is not the sort of happiness which a man would in general wish to owe to his wife,

08:01:16.920 --> 08:01:21.780
but where other powers of entertainment are wanting, the true philosopher will derive

08:01:21.780 --> 08:01:23.660
benefit from such as are given.

08:01:25.980 --> 08:01:30.760
Elizabeth, however, had never been blind to the impropriety of her father's behavior

08:01:30.760 --> 08:01:31.540
as a husband.

08:01:32.500 --> 08:01:38.000
She had always seen it with pain, but respecting his abilities, and grateful for his affectionate

08:01:38.000 --> 08:01:43.780
treatment of herself, she endeavoured to forget what she could not overlook, and to banish

08:01:43.780 --> 08:01:49.480
from her thoughts that continual breach of conjugal obligation and decorum which, in

08:01:49.480 --> 08:01:54.100
exposing his wife to the contempt of her own children, was so highly reprehensible.

08:01:55.760 --> 08:02:00.900
But she had never felt so strongly as now the disadvantages which must attend the children

08:02:00.900 --> 08:02:07.140
of so unsuitable a marriage, nor ever been so fully aware of the evils arising from so

08:02:07.140 --> 08:02:14.180
ill-judged a direction of talents, talents which, rightly used, might at least have preserved

08:02:14.180 --> 08:02:19.280
the respectability of his daughters, even if incapable of enlarging the mind of his

08:02:19.280 --> 08:02:19.780
wife.

08:02:21.420 --> 08:02:26.460
When Elizabeth had rejoiced over Wickham's departure, she found little other cause for

08:02:26.460 --> 08:02:28.600
satisfaction in the loss of the regiment.

08:02:29.720 --> 08:02:34.840
Their parties abroad were less varied than before, and at home she had a mother and sister

08:02:34.840 --> 08:02:40.400
whose constant repinings at the dullness of everything around them threw a real gloom

08:02:40.400 --> 08:02:41.900
over their domestic circle.

08:02:43.240 --> 08:02:49.140
And, though Kitty might in time regain her natural degree of sense, since the disturbers

08:02:49.140 --> 08:02:54.680
of her brain were removed, her other sister, from whose disposition greater evil might

08:02:54.680 --> 08:03:00.240
be apprehended, was likely to be hardened in all her folly and assurance by a situation

08:03:00.240 --> 08:03:04.040
of such double danger as a watering-place and a camp.

08:03:05.440 --> 08:03:11.680
Upon the whole, therefore, she found, what has sometimes been found before, that an event

08:03:11.680 --> 08:03:17.060
to which she had been looking with impatient desire did not, in taking place, bring all

08:03:17.060 --> 08:03:19.300
the satisfaction she had promised herself.

08:03:20.620 --> 08:03:25.440
It was consequently necessary to name some other period for the commencement of actual

08:03:25.440 --> 08:03:31.680
felicity, to have some other point on which her wishes and hopes might be fixed, and by

08:03:31.680 --> 08:03:37.080
again enjoying the pleasure of anticipation, console herself for the present, and prepare

08:03:37.080 --> 08:03:38.420
for another disappointment.

08:03:39.960 --> 08:03:44.000
Her tour to the lakes was now the object of her happiest thoughts.

08:03:44.480 --> 08:03:50.160
It was her best consolation for all the uncomfortable hours which the discontentedness of her mother

08:03:50.160 --> 08:03:51.740
and Kitty made inevitable.

08:03:52.860 --> 08:03:58.100
And could she have included Jane in the scheme, every part of it would have been perfect.

08:03:59.460 --> 08:04:04.000
But it is fortunate, thought she, that I have something to wish for.

08:04:04.000 --> 08:04:07.940
Were the whole arrangement complete, my disappointment would be certain.

08:04:08.160 --> 08:04:14.420
But here, by carrying with me one ceaseless source of regret in my sister's absence, I

08:04:14.420 --> 08:04:18.800
may reasonably hope to have all my expectations of pleasure realized.

08:04:19.640 --> 08:04:25.720
A scheme of which every part promises delight can never be successful, and general disappointment

08:04:25.720 --> 08:04:29.900
is only warded off by the defence of some little peculiar vexation.

08:04:31.300 --> 08:04:36.340
When Lydia went away she promised to write very often and very minutely to her mother

08:04:36.340 --> 08:04:41.300
and Kitty, but her letters were always long expected, and always very short.

08:04:42.300 --> 08:04:46.940
Those to her mother contained little else than that they were just returned from the

08:04:46.940 --> 08:04:51.720
library, where such and such officers had attended them, and where she had seen such

08:04:51.720 --> 08:04:54.180
beautiful ornaments as made her quite wild.

08:04:55.200 --> 08:04:59.760
That she had a new gown, or a new parasol, which she would have described more fully,

08:05:00.060 --> 08:05:05.260
but was obliged to leave off in a violent hurry, as Mrs. Forster called her, and they

08:05:05.260 --> 08:05:06.460
were going off to the camp.

08:05:07.260 --> 08:05:12.860
And from her correspondence with her sister there was still less to be learned, for her

08:05:12.860 --> 08:05:18.260
letters to Kitty, though rather longer, were much too full of lines under the words to

08:05:18.260 --> 08:05:19.080
be made public.

08:05:20.700 --> 08:05:26.640
After the first fortnight, or three weeks of her absence, health, good humour, and cheerfulness

08:05:26.640 --> 08:05:29.100
began to reappear at Longbourn.

08:05:30.240 --> 08:05:32.140
Everything wore a happier aspect.

08:05:32.820 --> 08:05:37.820
The families who had been in town for the winter came back again, and summer finery

08:05:37.820 --> 08:05:39.780
and summer engagements arose.

08:05:41.240 --> 08:05:47.160
Mrs. Bennet was restored to her usual quarrelous serenity, and by the middle of June Kitty

08:05:47.160 --> 08:05:53.140
was so much recovered as to be able to enter Meryton without tears, an event of such happy

08:05:53.140 --> 08:05:58.880
promise as to make Elizabeth hope that, by the following Christmas, she might be so tolerably

08:05:58.880 --> 08:06:05.160
reasonable as not to mention an officer above once a day, unless, by some cruel and malicious

08:06:05.160 --> 08:06:10.160
arrangement at the war-office, another regiment should be quartered in Meryton.

08:06:11.240 --> 08:06:16.060
The time fixed for the beginning of their northern tour was now fast approaching, and

08:06:16.060 --> 08:06:21.240
the fortnight only was wanting of it, when a letter arrived from Mrs. Gardiner, which

08:06:21.240 --> 08:06:24.860
at once delayed its commencement and curtailed its extent.

08:06:25.600 --> 08:06:30.120
Mr. Gardiner would be prevented by business from setting out till a fortnight later in

08:06:30.120 --> 08:06:33.660
July, and must be in London again within a month.

08:06:34.740 --> 08:06:40.300
And as that left too short a period for them to go so far and see so much as they had proposed,

08:06:40.760 --> 08:06:45.840
or at least to see it with the leisure and comfort they had built on, they were obliged

08:06:45.840 --> 08:06:51.280
to give up the lakes and substitute a more contracted tour, and, according to the present

08:06:51.280 --> 08:06:54.940
plan, were to go no farther northwards than Derbyshire.

08:06:56.440 --> 08:07:00.820
In that county there was enough to be seen to occupy the chief of their three weeks,

08:07:01.180 --> 08:07:04.920
and to Mrs. Gardiner it had a peculiarly strong attraction.

08:07:06.000 --> 08:07:10.580
The town where she had formerly passed some years of her life, and where they were now

08:07:10.580 --> 08:07:16.560
spend a few days, was probably as great an object of her curiosity as all the celebrated

08:07:16.560 --> 08:07:21.100
beauties of Matlock, Chatsworth, Dovedale, or the Peak.

08:07:22.520 --> 08:07:24.920
Elizabeth was excessively disappointed.

08:07:25.380 --> 08:07:29.940
She had set her heart on seeing the lakes, and still thought there might have been time

08:07:29.940 --> 08:07:30.360
enough.

08:07:30.960 --> 08:07:36.620
But it was her business to be satisfied, and certainly her temper to be happy, and all

08:07:36.620 --> 08:07:37.820
was soon right again.

08:07:38.720 --> 08:07:42.140
With the mention of Derbyshire there were many ideas connected.

08:07:42.860 --> 08:07:47.540
It was impossible for her to see the word without thinking of Pemberley and its owner.

08:07:48.580 --> 08:07:55.700
But surely, said she, I may enter his county without impunity, and rob it of a few petrified

08:07:55.700 --> 08:07:58.180
spars without his perceiving me.

08:07:59.240 --> 08:08:01.740
The period of expectation was now doubled.

08:08:02.620 --> 08:08:06.220
Four weeks were to pass away before her uncle and aunt's arrival.

08:08:06.220 --> 08:08:13.380
But they did pass away, and Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner, with their four children, did at length appear

08:08:13.380 --> 08:08:14.640
at Longbourn.

08:08:15.340 --> 08:08:21.300
The children, two girls of six and eight years old, and two younger boys, were to be left

08:08:21.300 --> 08:08:26.460
under the particular care of their cousin Jane, who was the general favourite, and whose

08:08:26.460 --> 08:08:31.780
steady sense and sweetness of temper exactly adapted her for attending to them in every

08:08:31.780 --> 08:08:36.060
way, teaching them, playing with them, and loving them.

08:08:37.660 --> 08:08:42.680
The gardeners stayed only one night at Longbourn, and set off the next morning with Elizabeth

08:08:42.680 --> 08:08:44.960
in pursuit of novelty and amusement.

08:08:45.780 --> 08:08:52.260
One enjoyment was certain, that of suitableness of companions, a suitableness which comprehended

08:08:52.260 --> 08:08:58.260
health and temper to bear inconveniences, cheerfulness to enhance every pleasure, and

08:08:58.260 --> 08:09:03.340
affection and intelligence which might supply it among themselves if there were disappointments

08:09:03.340 --> 08:09:03.780
abroad.

08:09:05.320 --> 08:09:10.060
It is not the object of this work to give a description of Derbyshire, nor of any of

08:09:10.060 --> 08:09:13.380
the remarkable places through which their route thither lay.

08:09:13.940 --> 08:09:20.680
Oxford, Plenham, Warwick, Camelworth, Birmingham, etc., are sufficiently known.

08:09:21.700 --> 08:09:24.700
A small part of Derbyshire is all the present concern.

08:09:25.340 --> 08:09:30.720
To the little town of Lambton, the scene of Mrs. Gardiner's former residence, and where

08:09:30.720 --> 08:09:34.660
she had lately learned some acquaintance still remained, they bent their steps.

08:09:36.260 --> 08:09:41.580
After having seen all the principal wonders of the country, and within five miles of Lambton,

08:09:41.920 --> 08:09:44.780
Elizabeth found from her aunt that Pemberley was situated.

08:09:45.800 --> 08:09:50.000
It was not in their direct road, nor more than a mile or two out of it.

08:09:50.340 --> 08:09:55.300
In talking over their route the evening before, Mrs. Gardiner expressed an inclination to

08:09:55.300 --> 08:09:56.480
see the place again.

08:09:56.980 --> 08:10:02.320
Mr. Gardiner declared his willingness, and Elizabeth was applied to for her approbation.

08:10:03.840 --> 08:10:08.600
"'My love, should you not like to see a place of which you have heard so much?' said her

08:10:08.600 --> 08:10:08.900
aunt.

08:10:09.480 --> 08:10:13.500
"'A place, too, with which so many of your acquaintances are connected.

08:10:14.400 --> 08:10:17.680
Wickham passed all his youth there, you know?'

08:10:17.680 --> 08:10:19.520
Elizabeth was distressed.

08:10:20.040 --> 08:10:25.720
She felt that she had no business at Pemberley, and was obliged to assume a disinclination

08:10:25.720 --> 08:10:26.660
for seeing it.

08:10:27.360 --> 08:10:30.180
She must own that she was tired of seeing great houses.

08:10:30.620 --> 08:10:35.460
After going over so many, she really had no pleasure in fine carpets or satin curtains.

08:10:37.140 --> 08:10:39.240
Mrs. Gardiner abused her stupidity.

08:10:40.020 --> 08:10:46.360
"'If it were merely a fine house richly furnished,' said she, "'I should not care about it myself,

08:10:46.360 --> 08:10:48.600
but the grounds are delightful.

08:10:49.080 --> 08:10:52.520
They have some of the finest woods in the country.'

08:10:52.800 --> 08:10:56.360
Elizabeth said no more, but her mind could not acquiesce.

08:10:56.700 --> 08:11:00.940
The possibility of meeting Mr. Darcy while viewing the place instantly occurred.

08:11:01.240 --> 08:11:02.440
It would be dreadful.

08:11:02.900 --> 08:11:07.140
She blushed at the very idea, and thought it would be better to speak openly to her

08:11:07.140 --> 08:11:08.800
aunt than to run such a risk.

08:11:09.780 --> 08:11:14.980
But against this there were objections, and she finally resolved that it could be the

08:11:14.980 --> 08:11:19.900
last resource, if her private inquiries to the absence of the family were unfavourably

08:11:19.900 --> 08:11:20.480
answered.

08:11:22.100 --> 08:11:26.860
Accordingly, when she retired at night, she asked the chambermaid whether Pemberley were

08:11:26.860 --> 08:11:33.120
not a very fine place, what was the name of its proprietor, and, with no little alarm,

08:11:33.580 --> 08:11:35.680
whether the family were down for the summer.

08:11:36.820 --> 08:11:42.420
A most welcome negative followed the last question, and her alarms now being removed,

08:11:42.420 --> 08:11:46.920
she was at leisure to feel a great deal of curiosity to see the house herself.

08:11:47.240 --> 08:11:51.980
And when the subject was revived the next morning, and she was again applied to, could

08:11:51.980 --> 08:11:57.980
readily answer, and with a proper air of indifference, that she had not really any dislike to the

08:11:57.980 --> 08:11:58.260
scheme.

08:11:59.340 --> 08:12:03.400
To Pemberley, therefore, they were to go.

08:12:12.700 --> 08:12:17.600
Elizabeth, as they drove along, watched for the first appearance of Pemberley woods with

08:12:17.600 --> 08:12:22.800
some perturbation, and when at length they turned in at the lodge, her spirits were in

08:12:22.800 --> 08:12:23.560
a high flutter.

08:12:25.260 --> 08:12:29.300
The park was very large, and contained great variety of ground.

08:12:29.860 --> 08:12:34.860
They entered it in one of its lowest points, and drove for some time through a beautiful

08:12:34.860 --> 08:12:36.860
wood stretching over a wide extent.

08:12:38.520 --> 08:12:44.660
Elizabeth's mind was too full for conversation, but she saw and admired every remarkable spot

08:12:44.660 --> 08:12:45.660
and point of view.

08:12:46.520 --> 08:12:51.880
They gradually ascended for half a mile, and then found themselves at the top of a considerable

08:12:51.880 --> 08:12:58.220
eminence, where the wood ceased, and the eye was instantly caught by Pemberley house, situated

08:12:58.220 --> 08:13:03.240
on the opposite side of a valley, into which the road, with some abruptness, wound.

08:13:03.240 --> 08:13:03.400
Elizabeth.

08:13:04.560 --> 08:13:11.220
It was a large, handsome stone building, standing well on rising ground, and backed by a ridge

08:13:11.220 --> 08:13:12.640
of high woody hills.

08:13:13.200 --> 08:13:19.280
And in front, a stream of some natural importance was swelled into greater, but without any

08:13:19.280 --> 08:13:20.440
artificial appearance.

08:13:21.900 --> 08:13:25.240
Its banks were neither formal nor falsely adorned.

08:13:25.800 --> 08:13:27.120
Elizabeth was delighted.

08:13:27.600 --> 08:13:32.620
She had never seen a place for which nature had done more, or where natural beauty had

08:13:32.620 --> 08:13:35.340
been so little counteracted by an awkward taste.

08:13:36.540 --> 08:13:42.640
They were all of them warm in their admiration, and at that moment she felt that to be mistress

08:13:42.640 --> 08:13:44.640
of Pemberley might be something.

08:13:46.020 --> 08:13:51.660
They descended the hill, crossed the bridge, and drove to the door, and, while examining

08:13:51.660 --> 08:13:56.540
the nearer aspect of the house, all her apprehension of meeting its owner returned.

08:13:57.300 --> 08:13:59.960
She dreaded lest the chambermaid had been mistaken.

08:14:00.840 --> 08:14:06.140
On applying to see the place they were admitted into the hall, and Elizabeth, as they waited

08:14:06.140 --> 08:14:10.480
for the housekeeper, had leisure to wonder at her being where she was.

08:14:12.080 --> 08:14:18.240
The housekeeper came, a respectable-looking elderly woman, much less fine and more civil

08:14:18.240 --> 08:14:20.800
than she had any notion of finding her.

08:14:21.340 --> 08:14:23.700
They followed her into the dining-parlor.

08:14:23.920 --> 08:14:28.000
It was a large, well-proportioned room, handsomely fitted up.

08:14:29.300 --> 08:14:34.220
Elizabeth, after slightly surveying it, went to a window to enjoy its prospect.

08:14:35.160 --> 08:14:40.720
The hill, crowned with wood, which they had descended, receiving increased abruptness

08:14:40.720 --> 08:14:43.060
from the distance, was a beautiful object.

08:14:44.480 --> 08:14:49.740
Every disposition of the ground was good, and she looked on the whole scene—the river,

08:14:49.920 --> 08:14:54.820
the trees scattered on its banks, and the winding of the valley, as far as she could

08:14:54.820 --> 08:14:56.160
trace it, with delight.

08:14:57.080 --> 08:15:02.480
As they passed into other rooms, these objects were taking different positions, but from

08:15:02.480 --> 08:15:05.200
every window there were beauties to be seen.

08:15:06.560 --> 08:15:12.200
The rooms were lofty and handsome, and their furniture suitable to the fortune of its proprietor,

08:15:12.380 --> 08:15:18.320
but Elizabeth saw, with admiration of his taste, that it was neither gaudy nor uselessly

08:15:18.320 --> 08:15:23.440
fine, with less of splendour and more real elegance than the furniture of Rosings.

08:15:24.420 --> 08:15:29.120
And of this place, thought she, I might have been mistress.

08:15:29.900 --> 08:15:33.940
With these rooms I might now have been familiarly acquainted.

08:15:34.740 --> 08:15:39.640
Instead of viewing them as a stranger, I might have rejoiced in them as my own, and welcomed

08:15:39.640 --> 08:15:41.960
to them as visitors, my uncle and aunt.

08:15:42.420 --> 08:15:47.480
But no—recollecting herself—that could never be.

08:15:47.680 --> 08:15:50.440
My uncle and aunt would have been lost to me.

08:15:50.440 --> 08:15:52.820
I should not have been allowed to invite them.

08:15:53.700 --> 08:15:55.600
This was a lucky recollection.

08:15:55.960 --> 08:15:58.740
It saved her from something very like regret.

08:16:00.160 --> 08:16:05.540
She longed to inquire of the housekeeper whether her master was really absent, but had not

08:16:05.540 --> 08:16:06.620
the courage for it.

08:16:07.500 --> 08:16:11.900
At length, however, the question was asked by her uncle, and she turned away with alarm,

08:16:12.120 --> 08:16:15.200
while Mrs. Reynolds replied that he was, adding,

08:16:15.200 --> 08:16:19.300
But we expect him to-morrow, with a large party of friends.

08:16:20.540 --> 08:16:26.060
How rejoiced was Elizabeth that their own journey had not by any circumstance been delayed

08:16:26.060 --> 08:16:26.680
a day!

08:16:28.200 --> 08:16:30.400
Her aunt now called her to look at a picture.

08:16:30.840 --> 08:16:35.920
She approached and saw the likeness of Mr. Wickham, suspended, amongst several other

08:16:35.920 --> 08:16:37.480
miniatures over the mantelpiece.

08:16:38.680 --> 08:16:41.620
Her aunt asked her, smilingly, how she liked it.

08:16:42.180 --> 08:16:46.940
The housekeeper came forward and told them it was a picture of a young gentleman, the

08:16:46.940 --> 08:16:51.580
son of her late master's steward, who had been brought up by him at his own expense.

08:16:52.780 --> 08:16:55.660
He has now gone into the army, she added.

08:16:56.560 --> 08:16:59.500
But I am afraid he has turned out very wild.

08:17:00.860 --> 08:17:05.480
Mrs. Gardiner looked at her niece with a smile, but Elizabeth could not return it.

08:17:06.180 --> 08:17:12.160
And that, said Mrs. Reynolds, pointing to another of the miniatures, is my master, and

08:17:12.160 --> 08:17:13.060
very like him.

08:17:13.520 --> 08:17:17.440
It was drawn at the same time as the other, about eight years ago.

08:17:18.380 --> 08:17:23.640
I have heard much of your master's fine person, said Mrs. Gardiner, looking at the picture.

08:17:24.280 --> 08:17:29.380
It is a handsome face, but, Lizzy, you can tell us whether it is like or not.

08:17:30.780 --> 08:17:35.700
Mrs. Reynolds' respect for Elizabeth seemed to increase on this intimation of her knowing

08:17:35.700 --> 08:17:36.480
her master.

08:17:37.980 --> 08:17:40.340
Does that young lady know Mr. Darcy?

08:17:42.080 --> 08:17:44.480
Elizabeth coloured and said, A little.

08:17:45.760 --> 08:17:49.000
And do you not think him a very handsome gentleman, ma'am?

08:17:49.940 --> 08:17:51.540
Yes, very handsome.

08:17:52.660 --> 08:17:58.200
I am sure I know none so handsome, but in the gallery upstairs you will see a finer,

08:17:58.200 --> 08:18:00.160
larger picture of him than this.

08:18:00.760 --> 08:18:05.800
This room was my late master's favourite room, and these miniatures are just as they used

08:18:05.800 --> 08:18:06.400
to be then.

08:18:06.480 --> 08:18:07.880
He was very fond of them.

08:18:08.820 --> 08:18:12.300
This accounted to Elizabeth for Mr. Wickham's being among them.

08:18:13.040 --> 08:18:17.820
Mrs. Reynolds then directed their attention to one of Miss Darcy, drawn when she was only

08:18:17.820 --> 08:18:18.800
eight years old.

08:18:20.640 --> 08:18:24.520
And is Miss Darcy as handsome as her brother, said Mrs. Gardiner?

08:18:25.260 --> 08:18:30.660
Oh, yes, the handsomest young lady that ever was seen, and so accomplished.

08:18:31.060 --> 08:18:33.520
She plays and sings all day long.

08:18:34.060 --> 08:18:39.100
In the next room is a new instrument just come down for her, a present from my master.

08:18:39.560 --> 08:18:41.320
She comes here to morrow with him.

08:18:43.080 --> 08:18:48.840
Mr. Gardiner, whose manners were very easy and pleasant, encouraged her communicativeness

08:18:48.840 --> 08:18:50.640
by his questions and remarks.

08:18:51.280 --> 08:18:56.940
Mrs. Reynolds, either by pride or attachment, had evidently great pleasure in talking of

08:18:56.940 --> 08:18:58.460
her master and his sister.

08:18:59.840 --> 08:19:03.240
Is your master much at Pemberley in the course of the year?

08:19:04.700 --> 08:19:10.300
Not so much as I could wish, sir, but I dare say he may spend half his time here, and Miss

08:19:10.300 --> 08:19:12.460
Darcy is always down for the summer months.

08:19:13.900 --> 08:19:17.400
Except, thought Elizabeth, when she goes to Ramsgate.

08:19:18.620 --> 08:19:22.040
If your master would marry, you might see more of him.

08:19:22.860 --> 08:19:25.720
Yes, sir, but I do not know when that will be.

08:19:25.920 --> 08:19:27.980
I do not know who is good enough for him.

08:19:29.480 --> 08:19:31.160
Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner smiled.

08:19:31.920 --> 08:19:33.440
Elizabeth could not help saying,

08:19:34.400 --> 08:19:38.360
It is very much to his credit, I am sure, that you should think so.

08:19:39.560 --> 08:19:45.220
I say no more than the truth, and everybody will say that knows him, replied the other.

08:19:46.300 --> 08:19:50.840
Elizabeth thought this was going pretty far, and she listened with increasing astonishment,

08:19:50.980 --> 08:19:52.320
as the housekeeper added,

08:19:53.100 --> 08:19:57.980
I have never known a crossword from him in my life, and I have known him ever since he

08:19:57.980 --> 08:19:59.420
was four years old.

08:20:01.040 --> 08:20:06.500
This was praise of all others most extraordinary, most opposite to her ideas.

08:20:07.100 --> 08:20:10.640
That he was not a good-tempered man had been her firmest opinion.

08:20:12.000 --> 08:20:14.020
Her keenest attention was awakened.

08:20:14.320 --> 08:20:17.720
She longed to hear more, and was grateful to her uncle for saying,

08:20:18.660 --> 08:20:21.680
There are very few people of whom so much can be said.

08:20:21.880 --> 08:20:23.660
You are lucky in having such a master.

08:20:25.020 --> 08:20:26.720
Yes, sir, I know I am.

08:20:27.080 --> 08:20:31.260
If I were to go through the world I could not meet with a better, but I have always

08:20:31.260 --> 08:20:36.500
observed that they who are good-natured when children are good-natured when they grow up,

08:20:36.500 --> 08:20:42.180
and he was always the sweetest-tempered, most generous-hearted boy in the world.

08:20:43.820 --> 08:20:45.680
Elizabeth almost stared at her.

08:20:46.300 --> 08:20:49.220
Can this be Mr. Darcy? thought she.

08:20:50.480 --> 08:20:53.900
His father was an excellent man, said Mrs. Gardiner.

08:20:55.160 --> 08:21:00.960
Yes, ma'am, that he was indeed, and his son will be just like him, just as affable to

08:21:00.960 --> 08:21:01.440
the poor.

08:21:03.840 --> 08:21:09.200
Elizabeth listened, wondered, doubted, and was impatient for more.

08:21:09.940 --> 08:21:12.440
Mrs. Reynolds could interest her on no other point.

08:21:13.040 --> 08:21:17.800
She related the subjects of the pictures, the dimensions of the rooms, and the price

08:21:17.800 --> 08:21:19.120
of the furniture in vain.

08:21:19.860 --> 08:21:24.880
Mr. Gardiner, highly amused by the kind of family prejudice to which she attributed her

08:21:24.880 --> 08:21:29.980
excessive commendation of her master, soon led again to the subject, and she dwelt with

08:21:29.980 --> 08:21:34.360
energy on his many merits as they proceeded together up the great staircase.

08:21:36.340 --> 08:21:42.960
He is the best landlord and the best master, said she, that ever lived, not like the wild

08:21:42.960 --> 08:21:45.820
young men nowadays who think of nothing but themselves.

08:21:46.440 --> 08:21:50.120
There is not one of his tenants or servants but will give him a good name.

08:21:50.740 --> 08:21:55.060
Some people call him proud, but I am sure I never saw any thing of it.

08:21:55.060 --> 08:21:59.580
To my fancy it is only because he does not rattle away like other young men.

08:22:01.160 --> 08:22:05.220
In what an amiable light does this place him, thought Elizabeth.

08:22:06.620 --> 08:22:12.480
This fine account of him, whispered her aunt as they walked, is not quite consistent with

08:22:12.480 --> 08:22:14.440
his behaviour to our poor friend.

08:22:16.480 --> 08:22:18.060
Perhaps we might be deceived.

08:22:19.080 --> 08:22:20.380
That is not very likely.

08:22:20.820 --> 08:22:22.540
Our authority was too good.

08:22:23.740 --> 08:22:28.780
On reaching the spacious lobby above they were shown into a very pretty sitting-room,

08:22:29.120 --> 08:22:34.300
lately fitted up with greater elegance and lightness than the apartments below, and were

08:22:34.300 --> 08:22:39.720
informed that it was but just done to give pleasure to Miss Darcy, who had taken a liking

08:22:39.720 --> 08:22:41.880
to the room when last at Pemberley.

08:22:43.260 --> 08:22:48.520
He is certainly a good brother, said Elizabeth, as she walked towards one of the windows.

08:22:49.920 --> 08:22:54.200
Mrs. Reynolds anticipated Miss Darcy's delight when she should enter the room.

08:22:55.220 --> 08:22:58.140
And this is always the way with him, she added.

08:22:58.600 --> 08:23:02.720
Whatever can give his sister any pleasure is sure to be done in a moment.

08:23:03.100 --> 08:23:05.120
There is nothing he would not do for her.

08:23:06.880 --> 08:23:10.980
The picture gallery and two or three of the principal bedrooms were all that remained

08:23:10.980 --> 08:23:11.740
to be shown.

08:23:13.120 --> 08:23:19.040
In the former were many good paintings, but Elizabeth knew nothing of the art, and from

08:23:19.040 --> 08:23:23.940
such as had been already visible below she had willingly turned to look at some drawings

08:23:23.940 --> 08:23:29.960
of Miss Darcy's in crayons, whose subjects were usually more interesting and also more

08:23:29.960 --> 08:23:30.680
intelligible.

08:23:32.120 --> 08:23:36.760
In the gallery there were many family portraits, but they could have little to fix the attention

08:23:36.760 --> 08:23:37.480
of a stranger.

08:23:38.480 --> 08:23:42.960
Elizabeth walked in quest of the only face whose features would be known to her.

08:23:43.560 --> 08:23:49.160
At last it arrested her, and she beheld a striking resemblance to Mr. Darcy, with such

08:23:49.160 --> 08:23:54.000
a smile over the face as she remembered to have sometimes seen when he looked at her.

08:23:55.360 --> 08:24:00.500
She stood several minutes before the picture, in earnest contemplation, and returned to

08:24:00.500 --> 08:24:02.560
it again before they quitted the gallery.

08:24:03.420 --> 08:24:07.660
Mrs. Reynolds informed them that it had been taken in his father's lifetime.

08:24:09.700 --> 08:24:16.220
There was certainly at this moment in Elizabeth's mind a more gentle sensation towards the original

08:24:16.220 --> 08:24:19.200
than she had ever felt at the height of their acquaintance.

08:24:19.960 --> 08:24:24.260
The commendation bestowed on him by Mrs. Reynolds was of no trifling nature.

08:24:25.200 --> 08:24:29.040
What praise is more valuable than the praise of an intelligent servant?

08:24:29.900 --> 08:24:37.720
As a brother, a landlord, a master, she considered how many people's happiness were in his guardianship.

08:24:38.100 --> 08:24:42.160
How much of pleasure and pain was it in his power to bestow?

08:24:42.840 --> 08:24:45.940
How much of good or evil must be done by him?

08:24:46.900 --> 08:24:51.980
Every idea that had been brought forward by the housekeeper was favourable to his character,

08:24:52.380 --> 08:24:57.200
and as she stood before the canvas on which he was represented, and fixed his eyes upon

08:24:57.200 --> 08:25:02.680
herself, she thought of his regard with a deeper sentiment of gratitude than it had

08:25:02.680 --> 08:25:03.820
ever raised before.

08:25:04.740 --> 08:25:09.080
She remembered its warmth, and softened its impropriety of expression.

08:25:10.680 --> 08:25:15.620
When all of the house that was open to general inspection had been seen, they returned downstairs,

08:25:15.860 --> 08:25:21.000
and, taking leave of the housekeeper, were consigned over to the gardener, who met them

08:25:21.000 --> 08:25:21.860
at the hall door.

08:25:23.100 --> 08:25:28.360
As they walked across the hall towards the river, Elizabeth turned back to look again.

08:25:28.820 --> 08:25:33.880
Her uncle and aunt stopped also, and while the former was conjecturing as to the date

08:25:33.880 --> 08:25:39.660
of the building, the owner of it himself suddenly came forward from the road which led behind

08:25:39.660 --> 08:25:40.560
it to the stables.

08:25:41.760 --> 08:25:46.260
They were within twenty yards of each other, and so abrupt was his appearance that it was

08:25:46.260 --> 08:25:48.000
impossible to avoid his sight.

08:25:48.540 --> 08:25:53.860
Their eyes instantly met, and the cheeks of both were overspread with the deepest blush.

08:25:54.640 --> 08:26:00.800
He absolutely started, and for a moment seemed immovable from surprise, but shortly recovering

08:26:00.800 --> 08:26:07.320
himself, advanced towards the party, and spoke to Elizabeth, if not in terms of perfect composure,

08:26:07.580 --> 08:26:09.440
at least of perfect civility.

08:26:10.860 --> 08:26:16.000
She had instinctively turned away, but stopping on his approach, received his compliments

08:26:16.000 --> 08:26:18.800
with an embarrassment impossible to be overcome.

08:26:20.280 --> 08:26:24.980
Had his first appearance, or his resemblance to the picture they had just been examining,

08:26:25.260 --> 08:26:30.680
been insufficient to assure the other two that they now saw Mr. Darcy, the gardener's

08:26:30.680 --> 08:26:35.100
expression of surprise on beholding his master must immediately have told it.

08:26:36.040 --> 08:26:41.500
They stood a little aloof while he was talking to their niece, who, astonished and confused,

08:26:42.180 --> 08:26:47.280
scarcely dared lift her eyes to his face, and knew not what answer she returned to his

08:26:47.280 --> 08:26:49.160
civil inquiries after her family.

08:26:51.800 --> 08:26:57.460
Amazed at the alteration of his manner since they last parted, every sentence that he uttered

08:26:57.460 --> 08:27:03.280
was increasing her embarrassment, and every idea of the impropriety of her being found

08:27:03.280 --> 08:27:08.600
there recurring to her mind, the few minutes in which they continued were some of the most

08:27:08.600 --> 08:27:10.200
uncomfortable in her life.

08:27:11.460 --> 08:27:13.640
Nor did he seem much more at ease.

08:27:14.040 --> 08:27:19.320
When he spoke, his accent had none of its usual sedateness, and he repeated his inquiries

08:27:19.320 --> 08:27:24.140
as to the time of her having left Longbourn, and of her having stayed in Derbyshire so

08:27:24.140 --> 08:27:29.160
often, and in so hurried a way, as plainly spoke the distraction of his thoughts.

08:27:30.240 --> 08:27:35.700
At length every idea seemed to fail him, and, after standing a few moments without saying

08:27:35.700 --> 08:27:39.200
a word, he suddenly recollected himself and took leave.

08:27:41.180 --> 08:27:45.780
The others then joined her, and expressed admiration of his figure, but Elizabeth heard

08:27:45.780 --> 08:27:50.780
not a word, and, wholly engrossed by her own feelings, followed them in silence.

08:27:51.940 --> 08:27:54.660
She was overpowered by shame and vexation.

08:27:55.220 --> 08:27:59.900
Her coming there was the most unfortunate, the most ill-judged thing in the world.

08:28:00.240 --> 08:28:02.200
How strange it must appear to him!

08:28:02.600 --> 08:28:06.260
In what a disgraceful light might it not strike so vain a man?

08:28:06.860 --> 08:28:10.840
It might seem as if she had purposely thrown herself in his way again.

08:28:11.080 --> 08:28:12.600
Oh, why did she come?

08:28:12.840 --> 08:28:16.080
Or why did he thus come a day before he was expected?

08:28:16.840 --> 08:28:21.460
Had they been only ten minutes sooner, they should have been beyond the reach of his discrimination,

08:28:22.040 --> 08:28:27.660
for it was plain that he was that moment arrived, that moment alighted from his horse or his

08:28:27.660 --> 08:28:27.940
carriage.

08:28:28.800 --> 08:28:32.460
She blushed again and again over the perverseness of the meeting.

08:28:33.420 --> 08:28:37.400
And his behaviour so strikingly altered, what could it mean?

08:28:38.120 --> 08:28:43.400
That he should even speak to her was amazing, but to speak with such civility, to inquire

08:28:43.400 --> 08:28:44.400
after her family.

08:28:45.680 --> 08:28:50.960
Never in her life had she seen his manners so little dignified, never had he spoken with

08:28:50.960 --> 08:28:53.900
such gentleness as on this unexpected meeting.

08:28:54.680 --> 08:29:00.080
What a contrast did it offer to his last address in Rosings Park, when he put his letter into

08:29:00.080 --> 08:29:00.720
her hand!

08:29:01.220 --> 08:29:04.960
She knew not what to think, or how to account for it.

08:29:06.060 --> 08:29:11.320
They had now entered a beautiful walk by the side of the water, and every step was bringing

08:29:11.320 --> 08:29:16.560
forward a nobler fall of ground, or a finer reach of the woods to which they were approaching.

08:29:17.100 --> 08:29:22.080
But it was some time before Elizabeth was sensible of any of it, and, though she answered

08:29:22.080 --> 08:29:27.320
mechanically to the repeated appeals of her uncle and aunt, and seemed to direct her eyes

08:29:27.320 --> 08:29:32.260
to such objects as they pointed out, she distinguished no part of the scene.

08:29:32.900 --> 08:29:38.400
Her thoughts were all fixed on that one spot of Pemberley House, whichever it might be,

08:29:38.740 --> 08:29:40.560
where Mr. Darcy then was.

08:29:41.860 --> 08:29:47.180
She longed to know what at the moment was passing in his mind, in what manner he thought

08:29:47.180 --> 08:29:51.920
of her, and whether, in defiance of every thing, she was still dear to him.

08:29:52.580 --> 08:29:55.980
Perhaps he had been civil only because he felt himself at ease.

08:29:56.700 --> 08:30:01.100
Yet there had been that in his voice which was not like ease.

08:30:02.180 --> 08:30:06.640
Whether he had felt more of pain or of pleasure in seeing her, she could not tell.

08:30:07.200 --> 08:30:09.620
But he certainly had not seen her with composure.

08:30:11.220 --> 08:30:16.640
At length, however, the remarks of her companions on her absence of mind aroused her, and she

08:30:16.640 --> 08:30:19.320
felt the necessity of appearing more like herself.

08:30:20.720 --> 08:30:25.660
They entered the woods, and bidding adieu to the river for a while, ascended some of

08:30:25.660 --> 08:30:31.080
the higher grounds, when, in spots where the opening of the trees gave the eye power to

08:30:31.080 --> 08:30:37.800
wander, were many charming views of the valley, the opposite hills, with the long range of

08:30:37.800 --> 08:30:41.240
woods overspreading many, and occasionally part of the stream.

08:30:42.420 --> 08:30:47.960
Mr. Gardiner expressed a wish of going round the whole park, but feared it might be beyond

08:30:47.960 --> 08:30:48.480
a walk.

08:30:49.600 --> 08:30:53.300
With a triumphant smile they were told that it was ten miles round.

08:30:54.020 --> 08:30:58.920
It settled the matter, and they pursued the accustomed circuit, which brought them again,

08:30:59.040 --> 08:31:04.460
after some time, in a descent among hanging woods to the edge of the water, and one of

08:31:04.460 --> 08:31:05.820
its narrowest parts.

08:31:06.820 --> 08:31:11.960
They crossed it by a simple bridge, in character with the general air of the scene.

08:31:12.600 --> 08:31:18.660
It was a spot less adorned than any they had yet visited, and the valley, here contracted

08:31:18.660 --> 08:31:24.720
into a glen, allowed room only for the stream, and a narrow walk amidst the rough coppice-wood

08:31:24.720 --> 08:31:25.860
which bordered it.

08:31:27.260 --> 08:31:32.140
Elizabeth longed to explore its windings, but when they had crossed the bridge, and

08:31:32.140 --> 08:31:37.380
their distance from the house, Mrs. Gardiner, who was not a great walker, could go no farther,

08:31:37.800 --> 08:31:41.060
and thought only of returning to the carriage as quickly as possible.

08:31:42.580 --> 08:31:47.240
Her niece was, therefore, obliged to submit, and they took their way towards the house

08:31:47.240 --> 08:31:52.160
on the opposite side of the river, in the nearest direction, but their progress was

08:31:52.160 --> 08:31:57.520
slow, for Mr. Gardiner, though seldom able to indulge the taste, was very fond of fishing,

08:31:57.520 --> 08:32:03.180
and was so much engaged in watching the occasional appearance of some trout in the water, and

08:32:03.180 --> 08:32:06.400
talking to the man about them, that he advanced but little.

08:32:08.000 --> 08:32:13.660
Whilst wandering on in this slow manner, they were again surprised, and Elizabeth's astonishment

08:32:13.660 --> 08:32:19.200
was quite equal to what it had been at first, by the sight of Mr. Darcy approaching them,

08:32:19.460 --> 08:32:20.860
and at no great distance.

08:32:22.080 --> 08:32:27.160
The walk here being less sheltered than on the other side, allowed them to see him before

08:32:27.160 --> 08:32:27.660
they met.

08:32:28.940 --> 08:32:33.520
Elizabeth, however astonished, was at least more prepared for an interview than before,

08:32:33.920 --> 08:32:39.080
and resolved to appear, and to speak with calmness, if he really intended to meet them.

08:32:40.220 --> 08:32:44.780
For a few moments, indeed, she felt that he would probably strike into some other path.

08:32:45.480 --> 08:32:49.540
The idea lasted, while a turning in the walk concealed him from their view.

08:32:49.960 --> 08:32:53.200
The turning passed, he was immediately before them.

08:32:54.160 --> 08:33:00.120
With a glance, she saw that he had lost none of his recent civility, and, to imitate his

08:33:00.120 --> 08:33:04.040
politeness, she began, as they met, to admire the beauty of the place.

08:33:04.700 --> 08:33:12.140
But she had not got beyond the words, delightful, and charming, when some unlucky recollections

08:33:12.140 --> 08:33:18.380
obtruded, and she fancied that praise of Pemberley from her might be mischievously construed.

08:33:18.760 --> 08:33:21.660
Her colour changed, and she said no more.

08:33:23.680 --> 08:33:29.240
Mrs. Gardiner was standing a little behind, and, on her pausing, he asked her if she would

08:33:29.240 --> 08:33:31.940
do him the honour of introducing him to her friends.

08:33:33.460 --> 08:33:38.140
This was a stroke of civility for which she was quite unprepared, and she could hardly

08:33:38.140 --> 08:33:42.840
suppress a smile at his being now seeking the acquaintance of some of those very people

08:33:42.840 --> 08:33:46.220
against whom his pride had revolted in his offer to herself.

08:33:47.380 --> 08:33:51.420
What will be his surprise, thought she, when he knows who they are?

08:33:51.680 --> 08:33:53.640
He takes them now for people of fashion.

08:33:54.960 --> 08:33:59.500
The introduction, however, was immediately made, and, as she named their relationship

08:33:59.500 --> 08:34:05.200
to herself, she stole a sly look at him, to see how he bore it, and was not without the

08:34:05.200 --> 08:34:09.800
expectation of his decamping as fast as he could from such disgraceful companions.

08:34:10.800 --> 08:34:13.900
That he was surprised by the connexion was evident.

08:34:14.480 --> 08:34:19.560
He sustained it, however, with fortitude, and, so far from going away, turned back with

08:34:19.560 --> 08:34:22.680
them, and entered into conversation with Mr. Gardiner.

08:34:24.420 --> 08:34:27.920
Elizabeth could not but be pleased, could not but triumph.

08:34:28.500 --> 08:34:32.720
It was consoling that he should know she had some relations for whom there was no need

08:34:32.720 --> 08:34:33.240
to blush.

08:34:34.200 --> 08:34:39.160
She listened most attentively to all that passed between them, and gloried in every

08:34:39.160 --> 08:34:45.120
expression every sentence of her uncle which marked his intelligence, his taste, or his

08:34:45.120 --> 08:34:45.760
good manners.

08:34:47.480 --> 08:34:52.820
The conversation soon turned upon fishing, and she heard Mr. Darcy invite him, with the

08:34:52.820 --> 08:34:57.860
greatest civility, to fish there as often as he chose, while he continued in the neighbourhood,

08:34:58.520 --> 08:35:03.300
offering at the same time to supply him with fishing tackle, and pointing out those parts

08:35:03.300 --> 08:35:06.680
of the stream where there was usually most sport.

08:35:08.300 --> 08:35:13.180
Mrs. Gardiner, who was walking arm in arm with Elizabeth, gave her a look expressive

08:35:13.180 --> 08:35:13.800
of wonder.

08:35:15.200 --> 08:35:18.320
Elizabeth said nothing, but it gratified her exceedingly.

08:35:19.020 --> 08:35:21.480
The compliment must be all for herself.

08:35:22.480 --> 08:35:27.040
Her astonishment, however, was extreme, and continually was she repeating,

08:35:27.760 --> 08:35:29.340
Why is he so altered?

08:35:29.800 --> 08:35:31.160
From what can it proceed?

08:35:31.380 --> 08:35:32.720
It cannot be for me.

08:35:33.220 --> 08:35:36.600
It cannot be for my sake that his manners are thus softened.

08:35:36.980 --> 08:35:40.240
My reproofs at Hunsford could not work such a change as this.

08:35:40.500 --> 08:35:42.960
It is impossible that he should still love me.

08:35:44.420 --> 08:35:49.320
After walking some time in this way, the two ladies in front, the two gentlemen behind,

08:35:49.940 --> 08:35:54.760
On resuming their places, after descending to the brink of the river for the better inspection

08:35:54.760 --> 08:35:59.440
of some curious water plant, there chanced to be a little alteration.

08:36:00.220 --> 08:36:06.220
It originated in Mrs. Gardiner, who, fatigued by the exercise of the morning, found Elizabeth's

08:36:06.220 --> 08:36:10.800
arm inadequate to her support, and consequently preferred her husband's.

08:36:11.240 --> 08:36:15.040
Mr. Darcy took her place by her niece, and they walked on together.

08:36:16.040 --> 08:36:19.020
After a short silence the lady first spoke.

08:36:19.560 --> 08:36:24.060
She wished him to know that she had been assured of his absence before she came to the place,

08:36:24.740 --> 08:36:28.960
and accordingly began by observing that his arrival had been very unexpected.

08:36:30.820 --> 08:36:36.040
For your housekeeper, she added, informed us that you would certainly not be here till

08:36:36.040 --> 08:36:41.580
to-morrow, and, indeed, before we left Bakewell we understood that you were not immediately

08:36:41.580 --> 08:36:42.740
expected in the country.

08:36:44.220 --> 08:36:49.080
He acknowledged the truth of it all, and said that business with his steward had occasioned

08:36:49.080 --> 08:36:53.280
his coming forward a few hours before the rest of the party with whom he had been travelling.

08:36:54.560 --> 08:37:00.200
They will join me early to-morrow, he continued, and among them are some who will claim an

08:37:00.200 --> 08:37:02.920
acquaintance with you, Mr. Bingley and his sisters.

08:37:04.320 --> 08:37:06.420
Elizabeth answered only by a slight bow.

08:37:06.920 --> 08:37:11.380
Her thoughts were instantly driven back to the time when Mr. Bingley's name had been

08:37:11.380 --> 08:37:17.380
the last mentioned between them, and, if she might judge by his complexion, his mind

08:37:17.380 --> 08:37:19.440
was not very differently engaged.

08:37:21.440 --> 08:37:28.120
There is also one other person in the party, he continued after a pause, who more particularly

08:37:28.120 --> 08:37:29.660
wishes to be known to you.

08:37:29.880 --> 08:37:35.580
Will you allow me, or do I ask too much, to introduce my sister to your acquaintance during

08:37:35.580 --> 08:37:36.660
your stay at Lambton?

08:37:37.740 --> 08:37:40.960
The surprise of such an application was great indeed.

08:37:41.400 --> 08:37:44.980
It was too great for her to know in what manner she acceded to it.

08:37:45.780 --> 08:37:50.180
She immediately felt that whatever desire Miss Darcy might have of being acquainted

08:37:50.180 --> 08:37:55.320
with her must be the work of her brother, and without looking farther it was satisfactory.

08:37:55.980 --> 08:38:01.040
It was gratifying to know that his resentment had not made him think really ill of her.

08:38:01.760 --> 08:38:05.900
They now walked on in silence, each of them deep in thought.

08:38:06.680 --> 08:38:08.260
Elizabeth was not comfortable.

08:38:08.840 --> 08:38:12.100
That was impossible, but she was flattered and pleased.

08:38:13.080 --> 08:38:17.400
His wish of introducing his sister to her was a compliment of the highest kind.

08:38:18.680 --> 08:38:23.400
They soon outstripped the others, and when they had reached the carriage Mr. and Mrs.

08:38:23.660 --> 08:38:25.940
Gardiner were half a quarter of a mile behind.

08:38:26.920 --> 08:38:32.560
He then asked her to walk into the house, but she declared herself not tired, and they

08:38:32.560 --> 08:38:33.860
stood together on the lawn.

08:38:35.420 --> 08:38:39.900
At such a time much might have been said, and silence was very awkward.

08:38:40.860 --> 08:38:44.920
She wanted to talk, but there seemed to be an embargo on every subject.

08:38:45.580 --> 08:38:50.540
At last she recollected that she had been travelling, and they talked of Matlock and

08:38:50.540 --> 08:38:52.400
Dovedale with great perseverance.

08:38:53.760 --> 08:38:59.980
Yet time and her aunt moved slowly, and her patience and her ideas were nearly worn out

08:38:59.980 --> 08:39:01.640
before the tete-a-tete was over.

08:39:02.840 --> 08:39:06.880
On Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner's coming up they were all pressed to go into the house and

08:39:06.880 --> 08:39:12.560
take some refreshment, but this was declined, and they parted on each side with utmost politeness.

08:39:13.440 --> 08:39:19.040
Mr. Darcy handed the ladies into the carriage, and when it drove off Elizabeth saw him walking

08:39:19.040 --> 08:39:20.640
slowly towards the house.

08:39:21.800 --> 08:39:26.600
The observations of her uncle and aunt now began, and each of them pronounced him to

08:39:26.600 --> 08:39:29.580
be infinitely superior to anything they had expected.

08:39:30.700 --> 08:39:35.660
He is perfectly well behaved, polite, and unassuming, said her uncle.

08:39:36.960 --> 08:39:42.920
There is something a little stately in him to be sure, replied her aunt, but it is confined

08:39:42.920 --> 08:39:44.940
to his air, and is not unbecoming.

08:39:45.520 --> 08:39:50.620
I can now say with the housekeeper that, though some people may call him proud, I have seen

08:39:50.620 --> 08:39:51.480
nothing of it.

08:39:52.400 --> 08:39:56.060
I was never more surprised than by his behaviour to us.

08:39:56.220 --> 08:40:01.520
It was more than civil, it was really attentive, and there was no necessity for such attention.

08:40:01.920 --> 08:40:04.380
His acquaintance with Elizabeth was very trifling.

08:40:05.600 --> 08:40:11.700
To be sure, Lizzy, said her aunt, he is not so handsome as Wickham, or rather, he has

08:40:11.700 --> 08:40:15.020
not Wickham's countenance, for his features are perfectly good.

08:40:15.360 --> 08:40:18.560
But how came you to tell me that he was so disagreeable?

08:40:20.060 --> 08:40:24.440
Elizabeth excused herself as well as she could, said that she had liked him better

08:40:24.440 --> 08:40:29.220
when they had met in Kent than before, and that she had never seen him so pleasant as

08:40:29.220 --> 08:40:29.860
this morning.

08:40:30.980 --> 08:40:35.560
But perhaps he may be a little whimsical in his civilities, replied her uncle.

08:40:36.020 --> 08:40:40.620
Your great men often are, and therefore I shall not take him at his word, as he might

08:40:40.620 --> 08:40:43.520
change his mind another day and warn me off his grounds.

08:40:45.480 --> 08:40:50.020
Elizabeth felt that they had entirely misunderstood his character, but said nothing.

08:40:51.380 --> 08:40:56.520
"'From what we have seen of him,' continued Mrs. Gardiner, "'I really should not have

08:40:56.520 --> 08:41:01.480
thought that he could have behaved in so cruel a way by anybody as he has done by poor Wickham.

08:41:02.100 --> 08:41:04.100
He has not an ill-natured look.

08:41:04.540 --> 08:41:08.420
On the contrary, there is something pleasing about his mouth when he speaks.

08:41:08.420 --> 08:41:14.440
And there is something of dignity in his countenance that would not give one an unfavourable idea

08:41:14.440 --> 08:41:15.180
of his heart.

08:41:16.060 --> 08:41:20.720
But to be sure, the good lady who showed us his house did give him a most flaming character.

08:41:21.140 --> 08:41:23.400
I could hardly help laughing aloud sometimes.

08:41:23.900 --> 08:41:29.060
But he is a liberal master, I suppose, and that, in the eye of a servant, comprehends

08:41:29.060 --> 08:41:31.540
every virtue.'

08:41:31.960 --> 08:41:36.360
Elizabeth here felt herself called on to say something in vindication of his behaviour

08:41:36.360 --> 08:41:43.080
to Wickham, and therefore gave them to understand, in as guarded a manner as she could, that

08:41:43.080 --> 08:41:48.640
by what she had heard from his relations in Kent, his actions were capable of a very different

08:41:48.640 --> 08:41:54.720
construction, and that his character was by no means so faulty nor Wickham's so amiable

08:41:54.720 --> 08:41:56.900
as they had been considered in Hertfordshire.

08:41:58.140 --> 08:42:03.260
In confirmation of this, she related the particulars of all the pecuniary transactions

08:42:03.260 --> 08:42:08.240
in which they had been connected, without actually naming her authority, but stating

08:42:08.240 --> 08:42:10.360
it to be such as might be relied on.

08:42:12.120 --> 08:42:16.820
Mrs. Gardiner was surprised and concerned, but as they were now approaching the scene

08:42:16.820 --> 08:42:22.280
of her former pleasures, every idea gave way to the charm of recollection, and she was

08:42:22.280 --> 08:42:27.260
too much engaged in pointing out to her husband all the interesting spots in its environs

08:42:27.260 --> 08:42:28.580
to think of anything else.

08:42:30.180 --> 08:42:34.760
Fatigued as she had been by the morning's walk, they had no sooner dined than she set

08:42:34.760 --> 08:42:40.560
off again in quest of her former acquaintance, and the evening was spent in the satisfactions

08:42:40.560 --> 08:42:43.900
of an intercourse renewed after many years' discontinuance.

08:42:45.300 --> 08:42:50.120
The occurrences of the day were too full of interest to leave Elizabeth much attention

08:42:50.120 --> 08:42:55.180
for any of these new friends, and she could do nothing but think, and think with wonder,

08:42:55.180 --> 08:43:01.940
of Mr. Darcy's civility, and, above all, of his wishing her to be acquainted with his sister.

08:43:29.160 --> 08:43:33.140
ELIZABETH had settled it that Mr. Darcy would bring his sister to visit her the very day

08:43:33.140 --> 08:43:38.040
after her reaching Pemberley, and was consequently resolved not to be out of sight of the inn

08:43:38.040 --> 08:43:39.200
the whole of that morning.

08:43:40.060 --> 08:43:45.240
But her conclusion was false, for on the very morning after their arrival at Lambton these

08:43:45.240 --> 08:43:46.240
visitors came.

08:43:47.620 --> 08:43:51.700
They had been walking about the place with some of their new friends, and were just returning

08:43:51.700 --> 08:43:56.180
to the inn to dress themselves for dining with the same family, when the sound of a

08:43:56.180 --> 08:44:00.820
carriage drew them to a window, and they saw a gentleman and a lady in a coracle driving

08:44:00.820 --> 08:44:01.500
up the street.

08:44:02.800 --> 08:44:07.720
Elizabeth, immediately recognizing the livery, guessed what it meant, and imparted no small

08:44:07.720 --> 08:44:11.760
degree of her surprise to her relations by acquainting them with the honor which she

08:44:11.760 --> 08:44:12.140
expected.

08:44:13.480 --> 08:44:18.220
Her uncle and aunt were all amazement, and the embarrassment of her manner, as she spoke,

08:44:18.680 --> 08:44:23.400
joined to the circumstance itself, and many of the circumstances of the preceding day,

08:44:23.900 --> 08:44:26.220
opened to them a new idea on the business.

08:44:27.300 --> 08:44:31.820
Nothing had ever suggested it before, but they felt that there was no other way of accounting

08:44:31.820 --> 08:44:36.560
for such attentions from such a quarter than by supposing a partiality for their niece.

08:44:38.000 --> 08:44:42.400
While these newly born notions were passing in their heads, the perturbation of Elizabeth's

08:44:42.400 --> 08:44:44.900
feelings was at every moment increasing.

08:44:45.720 --> 08:44:52.060
She was quite amazed at her own discomposure, but amongst other causes of disquiet she dreaded

08:44:52.060 --> 08:44:56.720
Unless the partiality of the brother should have said too much in her favor, and more

08:44:56.720 --> 08:45:02.200
than commonly anxious to please, she naturally suspected that every power of pleasing would

08:45:02.200 --> 08:45:03.000
fail her.

08:45:04.140 --> 08:45:09.200
She retreated from the window, fearful of being seen, and as she walked up and down

08:45:09.200 --> 08:45:15.140
the room, endeavoring to compose herself, saw such looks of inquiring surprise in her

08:45:15.140 --> 08:45:17.700
uncle and aunt as made everything worse.

08:45:19.400 --> 08:45:24.400
Miss Darcy and her brother appeared, and this formidable introduction took place.

08:45:25.340 --> 08:45:30.220
With astonishment did Elizabeth see that her new acquaintance was at least as much embarrassed

08:45:30.220 --> 08:45:31.060
as herself.

08:45:32.320 --> 08:45:37.860
Since her being at Lambton, she had heard that Miss Darcy was exceedingly proud, but

08:45:37.860 --> 08:45:42.520
the observation of a very few minutes convinced her that she was only exceedingly shy.

08:45:43.300 --> 08:45:49.640
She found it difficult to obtain even a word from her beyond a monosyllable.

08:45:50.780 --> 08:45:55.940
Miss Darcy was tall and on a larger scale than Elizabeth, and, though little more than

08:45:55.940 --> 08:46:00.720
sixteen, her figure was formed and her appearance womanly and graceful.

08:46:01.660 --> 08:46:05.900
She was less handsome than her brother, but there was sense and good humor in her face,

08:46:06.140 --> 08:46:08.620
and her manners were perfectly unassuming and gentle.

08:46:09.860 --> 08:46:14.580
Elizabeth, who had expected to find in her as a cute and unembarrassed an observer as

08:46:14.580 --> 08:46:19.260
ever Mr. Darcy had been, was much relieved by discerning such different feelings.

08:46:20.240 --> 08:46:24.840
They had not long been together before Mr. Darcy told her that Bingley was also coming

08:46:24.840 --> 08:46:29.720
to wait on her, and she had barely time to express her satisfaction and prepare for such

08:46:29.720 --> 08:46:34.800
a visitor, when Bingley's quick step was heard on the stairs, and in a moment he entered

08:46:34.800 --> 08:46:35.360
the room.

08:46:36.860 --> 08:46:42.320
All Elizabeth's anger against him had been long done away, but had she still felt any,

08:46:42.720 --> 08:46:47.080
it could hardly have stood its ground against the unaffected cordiality with which he expressed

08:46:47.080 --> 08:46:48.780
himself on seeing her again.

08:46:49.560 --> 08:46:54.980
He inquired in a friendly, though general, way after her family, and looked and spoke

08:46:54.980 --> 08:46:57.980
with the same good-humored ease that he had ever done.

08:46:59.200 --> 08:47:03.800
To Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner he was scarcely a less interesting personage than to herself.

08:47:04.520 --> 08:47:06.520
They had long wished to see him.

08:47:07.060 --> 08:47:10.660
The whole party before them, indeed, excited a lively attention.

08:47:11.920 --> 08:47:16.720
The suspicions which had just arisen of Mr. Darcy and their niece directed their observation

08:47:16.720 --> 08:47:21.980
towards each with an earnest, though guarded inquiry, and they soon drew from those inquiries

08:47:21.980 --> 08:47:26.080
the full conviction that one of them, at least, knew what it was to love.

08:47:27.280 --> 08:47:31.920
Of the ladies' sensations they remained a little in doubt, but that the gentleman was

08:47:31.920 --> 08:47:34.300
overflowing with admiration was evident enough.

08:47:35.920 --> 08:47:38.120
Elizabeth on her side had much to do.

08:47:38.880 --> 08:47:41.780
She wanted to ascertain the feelings of each of her visitors.

08:47:42.500 --> 08:47:46.280
She wanted to compose her own, and to make herself agreeable to all.

08:47:46.860 --> 08:47:51.860
And in the latter object, where she feared most to fail, she was most sure of success,

08:47:52.480 --> 08:47:56.400
for those to whom she endeavored to give pleasure were prepossessed in her favor.

08:47:57.180 --> 08:48:02.060
Bingley was ready, Georgiana was eager, and Darcy determined to be pleased.

08:48:04.080 --> 08:48:09.660
In seeing Bingley her thoughts naturally flew to her sister, and, oh, how ardently did she

08:48:09.660 --> 08:48:12.780
long to know whether any of his were directed in a like manner.

08:48:13.960 --> 08:48:19.020
Sometimes she could fancy that he talked less than on former occasions, and once or twice

08:48:19.020 --> 08:48:23.940
pleased herself with the notion that, as he looked at her, he was trying to trace a resemblance.

08:48:24.880 --> 08:48:30.140
But, though this might be imaginary, she could not be deceived as to his behavior to Miss

08:48:30.140 --> 08:48:32.800
Darcy, who had been set up as a rival to Jane.

08:48:34.160 --> 08:48:37.560
No look appeared on either side that spoke particular regard.

08:48:38.820 --> 08:48:41.960
Nothing occurred between them that could justify the hopes of his sister.

08:48:43.080 --> 08:48:48.020
On this point she was soon satisfied, and two or three little circumstances occurred

08:48:48.020 --> 08:48:54.680
ere they parted, which, in her anxious interpretation, denoted a recollection of Jane not untinctured

08:48:54.680 --> 08:49:00.000
by tenderness, and a wish of saying more that might lead to the mention of her, had he dared.

08:49:01.020 --> 08:49:05.800
He observed to her, at a moment when the others were talking together, and in a tone which

08:49:05.800 --> 08:49:10.920
had something of real regret, that it was a very long time since he had had the pleasure

08:49:10.920 --> 08:49:14.680
of seeing her, and, before she could reply, he added,

08:49:14.680 --> 08:49:16.680
It is above eight months.

08:49:16.960 --> 08:49:21.660
We have not met since the 26th of November, when we were all dancing together at Netherfield.

08:49:24.020 --> 08:49:28.700
Elizabeth was pleased to find his memory so exact, and he afterwards took occasion to

08:49:28.700 --> 08:49:34.160
ask her, when unattended to by any of the rest, whether all her sisters were at Longbourn.

08:49:35.060 --> 08:49:39.260
There was not much in the question, nor in the preceding remark, but there was a look

08:49:39.260 --> 08:49:41.060
and a manner which gave them meaning.

08:49:42.980 --> 08:49:48.080
It was not often that she could turn her eyes on Mr. Darcy himself, but whenever she did

08:49:48.080 --> 08:49:53.160
catch a glimpse, she saw an expression of general complacence, and in all that he said,

08:49:53.400 --> 08:49:58.360
she heard an accent so removed from hauteur or disdain of his companions, as convinced

08:49:58.360 --> 08:50:02.580
her that the improvement of manners which she had yesterday witnessed, however temporary

08:50:02.580 --> 08:50:06.460
its existence might prove, had at least outlived one day.

08:50:07.400 --> 08:50:12.080
When she saw him thus seeking the acquaintance and courting the good opinion of people with

08:50:12.080 --> 08:50:17.140
whom any intercourse a few months ago would have been a disgrace, when she saw him thus

08:50:17.140 --> 08:50:22.240
civil not only to herself but to the very relations whom he had openly disdained, and

08:50:22.240 --> 08:50:27.420
recollected their last lively scene in Hunsford Parsonage, the difference, the change was

08:50:27.420 --> 08:50:32.180
so great and struck so forcibly on her mind that she could hardly restrain her astonishment

08:50:32.180 --> 08:50:33.020
from being visible.

08:50:33.800 --> 08:50:38.680
Never, even in the company of his dear friends at Netherfield, or his dignified relations

08:50:38.680 --> 08:50:44.640
at Rosings, had she seen him so desirous to please, so free from self-consequence or unbending

08:50:44.640 --> 08:50:49.660
reserve, as now, when no importance could result from the success of his endeavours,

08:50:49.980 --> 08:50:54.020
and when even the acquaintance of those to whom his attentions were addressed would draw

08:50:54.020 --> 08:50:58.540
down the ridicule and censure of the ladies both of Netherfield and Rosings.

08:50:59.960 --> 08:51:05.160
Their visitors stayed with them above half an hour, and when they arose to depart, Mr.

08:51:05.340 --> 08:51:09.640
Darcy called on his sister to join him in expressing their wish of seeing Mr. and Mrs.

08:51:09.780 --> 08:51:14.160
Gardiner and Miss Bennet to dinner at Pemberley before they left the country.

08:51:15.220 --> 08:51:19.500
Miss Darcy, though with a diffidence which marked her little in the habit of giving invitations,

08:51:19.980 --> 08:51:21.360
readily obeyed.

08:51:21.760 --> 08:51:26.500
Mrs. Gardiner looked at her niece, desirous of knowing how she, whom the invitation most

08:51:26.500 --> 08:51:31.660
concerned, felt disposed as to its acceptance, but Elizabeth had turned away her head.

08:51:33.120 --> 08:51:37.260
Presuming, however, that this studied avoidance spoke rather a momentary embarrassment than

08:51:37.260 --> 08:51:42.720
any dislike of the proposal, and seeing in her husband, who was fond of society, a perfect

08:51:42.720 --> 08:51:47.680
willingness to accept it, she ventured to engage for her attendance, and the day after

08:51:47.680 --> 08:51:48.920
the next was fixed on.

08:51:50.880 --> 08:51:56.480
Bingley expressed great pleasure in the certainty of seeing Elizabeth again, having still a

08:51:56.960 --> 08:52:00.460
and many inquiries to make after all their hurtful sure friends.

08:52:01.520 --> 08:52:06.060
Elizabeth, construing all this into a wish of hearing her speak of her sister, was pleased,

08:52:06.540 --> 08:52:11.480
and on this account, as well as some others, found herself, when their visitors left them,

08:52:11.900 --> 08:52:16.500
capable of considering the last half hour with some satisfaction, though while it was

08:52:16.500 --> 08:52:18.720
passing the enjoyment of it had been little.

08:52:20.260 --> 08:52:25.180
Eager to be alone, and fearful of inquiries or hints from her uncle and aunt, she stayed

08:52:25.180 --> 08:52:29.560
with them only long enough to hear their favorable opinion of Bingley, and then hurried

08:52:29.560 --> 08:52:30.580
away to dress.

08:52:32.140 --> 08:52:35.660
But she had no reason to fear Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner's curiosity.

08:52:36.340 --> 08:52:38.420
It was not their wish to force her communication.

08:52:39.420 --> 08:52:44.400
It was evident that she was much better acquainted with Mr. Darcy than they had before any idea

08:52:44.400 --> 08:52:44.860
of.

08:52:45.180 --> 08:52:47.920
It was evident that he was very much in love with her.

08:52:48.360 --> 08:52:51.780
They saw much to interest, but nothing to justify inquiry.

08:52:53.560 --> 08:52:59.400
Of Mr. Darcy it was now a matter of anxiety to think well, and, as far as their acquaintance

08:52:59.400 --> 08:53:01.340
reached, there was no fault to find.

08:53:02.460 --> 08:53:06.500
They could not be untouched by his politeness, and had they drawn his character from their

08:53:06.500 --> 08:53:12.000
own feelings in his servant's report without any reference to any other account, the circle

08:53:12.000 --> 08:53:16.300
in hurtful sure to which he was known would not have recognized it for Mr. Darcy.

08:53:17.120 --> 08:53:23.140
There was now an interest, however, in believing the housekeeper, and they soon became sensible

08:53:23.140 --> 08:53:27.380
that the authority of a servant who had known him since he was four years old, and whose

08:53:27.380 --> 08:53:31.540
own manners indicated respectability, was not to be hastily rejected.

08:53:32.760 --> 08:53:37.100
Neither had anything occurred in the intelligence of their Lambton friends that could materially

08:53:37.100 --> 08:53:37.980
lessen its weight.

08:53:38.980 --> 08:53:41.100
They had nothing to accuse him of but pride.

08:53:41.600 --> 08:53:46.700
Pride he probably had, and if not, it would certainly be imputed by the inhabitants of

08:53:46.700 --> 08:53:49.140
a small market town where the family did not visit.

08:53:50.140 --> 08:53:54.620
It was acknowledged, however, that he was a liberal man, and did much good among the poor.

08:53:56.520 --> 08:54:01.220
With respect to Wickham, the travellers soon found that he was not held there in much estimation.

08:54:01.820 --> 08:54:05.900
For though the chief of his concerns with the son of his patron were imperfectly understood,

08:54:05.900 --> 08:54:11.180
it was yet a well-known fact that, on his quitting derbyshire, he had left many debts

08:54:11.180 --> 08:54:14.100
behind him, which Mr. Darcy afterwards discharged.

08:54:16.460 --> 08:54:22.100
As for Elizabeth, her thoughts were at Pemberley this evening more than the last, and the evening,

08:54:22.320 --> 08:54:27.560
though as it passed seemed long, was not long enough to determine her feelings towards one

08:54:27.560 --> 08:54:32.760
in that mansion, and she lay awake two whole hours endeavouring to make them out.

08:54:33.620 --> 08:54:35.940
She certainly did not hate him.

08:54:36.360 --> 08:54:41.600
No, hatred had vanished long ago, and she had almost as long been ashamed of ever feeling

08:54:41.600 --> 08:54:43.940
a dislike against him that could be so called.

08:54:45.120 --> 08:54:50.320
The respect created by the conviction of his valuable qualities, though at first unwillingly

08:54:50.320 --> 08:54:55.700
admitted, had for some time ceased to be repugnant to her feeling, and it was now heightened

08:54:55.700 --> 08:55:01.080
into somewhat of a friendlier nature by the testimony so highly in his favour, and bringing

08:55:01.080 --> 08:55:05.160
forward his disposition in so amiable a light which yesterday had produced.

08:55:06.540 --> 08:55:11.740
But above all, above respect and esteem, there was a motive within her of good will which

08:55:11.740 --> 08:55:12.780
could not be overlooked.

08:55:13.680 --> 08:55:19.200
It was gratitude, gratitude not merely for having once loved her, but for loving her

08:55:19.200 --> 08:55:23.900
still well enough to forgive all the petulance and acrimony of her manner in rejecting him,

08:55:23.900 --> 08:55:27.520
and all the unjust accusations accompanying her rejection.

08:55:28.740 --> 08:55:34.740
He who, she had been persuaded, would avoid her as his greatest enemy, seemed on this

08:55:34.740 --> 08:55:39.840
accidental meeting most eager to preserve the acquaintance, and without any indelicate

08:55:39.840 --> 08:55:45.420
display of regard or any peculiarity of manner where their two selves only were concerned,

08:55:46.040 --> 08:55:51.060
was soliciting the good opinion of her friends, and bent on making her known to his sister.

08:55:52.180 --> 08:55:58.360
Such a change in a man of so much pride, exciting not only astonishment but gratitude, for to

08:55:58.360 --> 08:56:03.920
love ardent love it must be attributed, and as such its impression on her was of a sort

08:56:03.920 --> 08:56:08.800
to be encouraged, as by no means unpleasing, though it could not be exactly defined.

08:56:09.940 --> 08:56:15.840
She respected, she esteemed, she was grateful to him, she felt a real interest in his welfare,

08:56:16.320 --> 08:56:22.760
and she only wanted to know how far she wished that welfare to depend upon herself, and how

08:56:22.760 --> 08:56:27.440
far it would be for the happiness of both that she should employ the power, which her fancy told

08:56:27.440 --> 08:56:31.220
her she still possessed, of bringing on her the renewal of his addresses.

08:56:33.060 --> 08:56:37.580
It had been settled in the evening between the aunt and the niece that such a striking

08:56:37.580 --> 08:56:42.340
civility as Miss Darcy's in coming to see them on the very day of her arrival at Pemberley,

08:56:42.340 --> 08:56:47.480
for she had reached it only to a late breakfast, ought to be imitated, though it could not be

08:56:47.480 --> 08:56:53.600
equaled, by some exertion of politeness on their side, and consequently that it would be highly

08:56:53.600 --> 08:57:00.060
expedient to wait on her at Pemberley the following morning. They were, therefore, to go. Elizabeth

08:57:00.060 --> 08:57:04.700
was pleased, though when she asked herself the reason she had very little to say in reply.

08:57:06.340 --> 08:57:11.400
Mr. Gardiner left them soon after breakfast. The fishing scheme had been renewed the day before,

08:57:11.400 --> 08:57:15.880
and a positive engagement made of his meeting some of the gentlemen at Pemberley before noon.

08:57:22.120 --> 08:57:27.000
Convinced, as Elizabeth now was that Miss Bingley's dislike of her had originated in jealousy,

08:57:27.820 --> 08:57:31.980
she could not help feeling how unwelcome her appearance at Pemberley must be to her,

08:57:32.140 --> 08:57:36.640
and was curious to know with how much civility on that lady's side the acquaintance would now

08:57:36.640 --> 08:57:37.260
be renewed.

08:57:39.620 --> 08:57:44.520
On reaching the house they were shown through the hall into the saloon, whose northern aspect

08:57:44.520 --> 08:57:50.300
rendered it delightful for summer. Its windows, opening to the ground, admitted a most refreshing

08:57:50.300 --> 08:57:55.240
view of the high woody hills behind the house, and of the beautiful oaks and Spanish chestnuts

08:57:55.240 --> 08:58:01.160
which were scattered over the intermediate lawn. In this house they were received by Miss Darcy,

08:58:01.440 --> 08:58:05.460
who was sitting there with Mrs. Hurst and Miss Bingley, and the lady with whom she lived in

08:58:05.460 --> 08:58:11.360
London. Georgiana's reception of them was very civil, but attended with all the embarrassment

08:58:11.360 --> 08:58:16.400
which, though proceeding from shyness and the fear of doing wrong, would easily give to those who

08:58:16.400 --> 08:58:22.160
felt themselves inferior the belief of her being proud and reserved. Mrs. Gardiner and her niece,

08:58:22.640 --> 08:58:28.180
however, did her justice and pitied her. By Mrs. Hurst and Miss Bingley they were noticed

08:58:28.180 --> 08:58:35.020
only by a curtsy, and, on their being seated, a pause. Awkward as such pauses must always be,

08:58:35.020 --> 08:58:41.900
succeeded for a few moments. It was first broken by Mrs. Ansley, a genteel, agreeable-looking woman,

08:58:42.440 --> 08:58:46.840
whose endeavor to introduce some kind of discourse proved her to be more truly well-bred than

08:58:46.840 --> 08:58:52.040
either of the others, and between her and Mrs. Gardiner, with occasional help from Elizabeth,

08:58:52.360 --> 08:58:57.560
the conversation was carried on. Miss Darcy looked as if she wished for courage enough

08:58:57.560 --> 08:59:02.480
to join in it, and sometimes did venture a short sentence when there was least danger of its being

08:59:02.480 --> 08:59:09.180
heard. Elizabeth soon saw that she was herself closely watched by Miss Bingley, and that she

08:59:09.180 --> 08:59:15.440
could not speak a word, especially to Miss Darcy, without calling her attention. This observation

08:59:15.440 --> 08:59:20.180
would not have prevented her from trying to talk to the latter had they not been seated at an

08:59:20.180 --> 08:59:25.080
inconvenient distance, but she was not sorry to be spared the necessity of saying much.

08:59:25.880 --> 08:59:32.440
Her own thoughts were employing her. She expected every moment that some of the

08:59:32.440 --> 08:59:38.300
she feared that the master of the house might be amongst them, and whether she wished or feared

08:59:38.300 --> 08:59:43.980
it most, she could scarcely determine. After sitting in this manner a quarter of an hour

08:59:43.980 --> 08:59:49.420
without hearing Miss Bingley's voice, Elizabeth was roused by receiving from her a cold inquiry

08:59:49.420 --> 08:59:54.860
after the health of her family. She answered with equal indifference and brevity, and the others

08:59:54.860 --> 09:00:01.660
said no more. The next variation which their visit afforded was produced by the entrance of servants

09:00:01.660 --> 09:00:07.120
with cold meat, cake, and a variety of all the finest fruits in season. But this did not take

09:00:07.120 --> 09:00:12.000
place till after many a significant look and smile from Mrs. Ansley to Miss Darcy had been given

09:00:12.000 --> 09:00:18.020
to remind her of her post. There was now employment for the whole party, for though they could not all

09:00:18.020 --> 09:00:22.940
talk, they could all eat, and the beautiful pyramids of grapes, nectarines, and peaches

09:00:22.940 --> 09:00:29.840
soon collected them round the table. While thus engaged, Elizabeth had a fair opportunity of

09:00:29.840 --> 09:00:34.920
deciding whether she most feared or wished for the appearance of Mr. Darcy by the feelings

09:00:34.920 --> 09:00:40.500
which prevailed on his entering the room. And then, though but a moment before she had believed her

09:00:40.500 --> 09:00:47.260
wishes to predominate, she began to regret that he came. He had been some time with Mr. Gardiner,

09:00:47.580 --> 09:00:52.860
who, with two or three other gentlemen from the house, was engaged by the river, and had left him

09:00:52.860 --> 09:00:57.140
only on learning that the ladies of the family intended a visit to Georgiana that morning.

09:00:58.200 --> 09:01:04.180
No sooner did he appear than Elizabeth wisely resolved to be perfectly easy and unembarrassed,

09:01:04.420 --> 09:01:10.100
a resolution the more necessary to be made, but perhaps not the more easily kept, because she saw

09:01:10.100 --> 09:01:14.600
that the suspicions of the whole party were awakened against them, and that there was scarcely

09:01:14.600 --> 09:01:21.180
an eye which did not watch his behavior when he first came into the room. In no countenance was

09:01:21.180 --> 09:01:25.900
a tint of curiosity so strongly marked as in Miss Bingley's, in spite of the smiles which

09:01:25.900 --> 09:01:30.720
overspread her face whenever she spoke to one of its objects, for jealousy had not yet made her

09:01:30.720 --> 09:01:37.180
desperate, and her attentions to Mr. Darcy were by no means over. Miss Darcy, on her brother's

09:01:37.180 --> 09:01:42.640
entrance, exerted herself much more to talk, and Elizabeth saw that he was anxious for his sister

09:01:42.640 --> 09:01:47.940
and herself to get acquainted, and forwarded, as much as possible, every attempt at conversation

09:01:47.940 --> 09:01:54.520
on either side. Miss Bingley saw all this likewise, and, in the imprudence of anger,

09:01:54.520 --> 09:01:58.300
took the first opportunity of saying, with sneering civility,

09:01:59.060 --> 09:02:03.260
Pray, Miss Eliza, are not the blankshire militia removed from Meryton?

09:02:03.800 --> 09:02:06.060
They must be a great loss to your family.

09:02:08.220 --> 09:02:13.020
In Darcy's presence she dared not mention Wickham's name, but Elizabeth instantly

09:02:13.020 --> 09:02:17.420
comprehended that he was uppermost in her thoughts, and the various recollections

09:02:17.420 --> 09:02:22.920
connected with him gave her a moment's distress. But, exerting herself vigorously to repel the

09:02:22.920 --> 09:02:27.500
natured attack, she presently answered the question in a tolerably detached tone.

09:02:28.840 --> 09:02:33.900
While she spoke, an involuntary glance showed her Darcy, with a heightened complexion,

09:02:34.300 --> 09:02:39.960
earnestly looking at her, and his sister overcome with confusion and unable to lift up her eyes.

09:02:41.440 --> 09:02:45.140
Had Miss Bingley known what pain she was then giving her beloved friend,

09:02:45.560 --> 09:02:49.680
she undoubtedly would have refrained from the hint. But she had merely intended to

09:02:49.680 --> 09:02:54.340
compose Elizabeth by bringing forth the idea of a man to whom she believed her partial,

09:02:54.780 --> 09:03:00.180
to make her betray a sensibility which might injure her in Darcy's opinion, and, perhaps,

09:03:00.580 --> 09:03:04.440
to remind the latter of all the follies and absurdities by which some part of

09:03:04.440 --> 09:03:09.660
her family were connected with that core. Not a syllable had ever reached her of Miss

09:03:09.660 --> 09:03:15.380
Darcy's meditated elopement. To no creature had it been revealed where secrecy was possible,

09:03:15.380 --> 09:03:20.380
except to Elizabeth. And from all Bingley's connections her brother was particularly

09:03:20.380 --> 09:03:25.780
anxious to conceal it, from the very wish which Elizabeth had long ago attributed to him,

09:03:25.940 --> 09:03:31.320
of their becoming hereafter her own. He had certainly formed such a plan,

09:03:31.600 --> 09:03:35.520
and without meaning that it should affect his endeavour to separate him from Miss Bennet,

09:03:35.860 --> 09:03:40.460
it is probable that it might add something to his lively concern for the welfare of his friend.

09:03:41.880 --> 09:03:48.080
Elizabeth's collected behaviour, however, soon quieted his emotion, and as Miss Bingley, vexed

09:03:48.080 --> 09:03:53.920
and disappointed, dared not approach nearer to Wickham, Georgiana also recovered in time,

09:03:54.180 --> 09:04:00.260
though not enough to be able to speak any more. Her brother, whose eye she feared to meet,

09:04:00.900 --> 09:04:05.820
scarcely recollected her interest in the affair, and the very circumstance which had been designed

09:04:05.820 --> 09:04:10.320
turn his thoughts from Elizabeth seemed to affix them on her more and more cheerfully.

09:04:12.300 --> 09:04:15.900
Their visit did not continue long after the question and answer above mentioned,

09:04:16.460 --> 09:04:20.740
and while Mr. Darcy was attending them to their carriage, Miss Bingley was venting her feelings

09:04:20.740 --> 09:04:26.540
and criticisms on Elizabeth's person, behaviour and dress. But Georgiana would not join her.

09:04:27.100 --> 09:04:33.220
Her brother's recommendation was enough to ensure her favour. His judgment could not err. And he

09:04:33.220 --> 09:04:37.560
spoke in such terms of Elizabeth as to leave Georgiana without the power of finding her

09:04:37.560 --> 09:04:43.280
otherwise than lovely and amiable. When Darcy returned to the saloon, Miss Bingley could not

09:04:43.280 --> 09:04:46.320
help repeating to him some part of what she had been saying to his sister.

09:04:46.740 --> 09:04:52.460
How very ill Miss Eliza Bennet looks this morning, Mr. Darcy, she cried. I never in my life saw

09:04:52.460 --> 09:04:57.320
anyone so much altered as she is since the winter. She has grown so brown and coarse.

09:04:58.260 --> 09:05:01.340
Louisa and I were agreeing that we should not have known her again.

09:05:03.520 --> 09:05:08.720
However little Mr. Darcy might have liked such an address, he contented himself with coolly replying

09:05:08.720 --> 09:05:13.540
that he perceived no other alteration than her being rather tanned, no miraculous consequence

09:05:13.540 --> 09:05:20.240
of travelling in the summer. For my own part, she rejoined, I must confess that I never could

09:05:20.240 --> 09:05:25.660
see any beauty in her. Her face is too thin, her complexion has no brilliancy, and her features

09:05:25.660 --> 09:05:32.240
are not at all handsome. Her nose wants character, there is nothing marked in its lines. Her teeth

09:05:32.240 --> 09:05:37.280
are tolerable, but not out of the common way, and as for her eyes, which have sometimes been

09:05:37.280 --> 09:05:42.160
called so fine, I could never see anything extraordinary in them. They have a sharp,

09:05:42.380 --> 09:05:47.180
shrewish look, which I do not like at all, and in her air altogether there is a self-sufficiency

09:05:47.180 --> 09:05:54.280
without fashion which is intolerable. Persuaded as Miss Bingley was that Darcy admired Elizabeth,

09:05:54.620 --> 09:05:59.600
this was not the best method of recommending herself. But angry people are not always wise,

09:05:59.600 --> 09:06:04.220
and in seeing him at last look somewhat nettled, she had all the success she expected.

09:06:05.460 --> 09:06:10.220
He was resolutely silent, however, and from a determination of making him speak she continued,

09:06:11.200 --> 09:06:15.520
I remember when we first knew her in Hertfordshire how amazed we all were to find that she was a

09:06:15.520 --> 09:06:20.700
reputed beauty, and I particularly recollect your saying one night after they had been dining at

09:06:20.700 --> 09:06:26.820
Netherfield, she a beauty, I should as soon call her mother a wit. But afterwards she seemed to

09:06:26.820 --> 09:06:29.620
on you, and I believe you thought her rather pretty at one time.

09:06:31.500 --> 09:06:37.120
Yes, replied Darcy, who could contain himself no longer, but that was only when I first saw her,

09:06:37.300 --> 09:06:41.560
for it is many months since I have considered her as one of the handsomest women of my acquaintance.

09:06:43.520 --> 09:06:47.800
He then went away, and Miss Bingley was left to all the satisfaction of having forced him

09:06:47.800 --> 09:06:53.840
to say what gave no one any pain but herself. Mrs. Gardiner and Elizabeth talked of all that

09:06:53.840 --> 09:06:59.500
occurred during their visit, as they returned, except what had particularly interested them both.

09:07:00.340 --> 09:07:04.880
The look and behaviour of everybody they had seen were discussed, except of the person who

09:07:04.880 --> 09:07:11.400
had mostly engaged their attention. They talked of his sister, his friends, his house, his fruit,

09:07:11.820 --> 09:07:17.140
of everything but himself. Yet Elizabeth was longing to know what Mrs. Gardiner thought of him,

09:07:17.440 --> 09:07:21.560
and Mrs. Gardiner would have been highly gratified by her nieces beginning the subject.

09:07:48.920 --> 09:07:51.700
Recorded by Ife Currid.

09:07:52.540 --> 09:07:55.980
Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen.

09:08:03.820 --> 09:08:07.940
Elizabeth had been a good deal disappointed in not finding a letter from Jane on their

09:08:07.940 --> 09:08:13.760
first arrival at Lambdon, and this disappointment had been renewed on each of the mornings that

09:08:13.760 --> 09:08:19.660
had now been spent there, but on the third her repining was over and her sister justified

09:08:19.660 --> 09:08:25.800
by the receipt of two letters from her at once, on one of which was marked that it had

09:08:25.800 --> 09:08:27.200
been missent elsewhere.

09:08:28.120 --> 09:08:33.680
Elizabeth was not surprised at it, as Jane had written the direction remarkably ill.

09:08:35.080 --> 09:08:40.720
They had just been preparing to walk as the letters came in, and her uncle and aunt, leaving

09:08:40.720 --> 09:08:43.960
her to enjoy them in quiet, set off by themselves.

09:08:44.800 --> 09:08:49.980
The one missent must first be attended to, it had been written five days ago.

09:08:50.680 --> 09:08:55.940
The beginning contained an account of all their little parties and engagements, with

09:08:55.940 --> 09:09:02.140
such news as the country afforded, but the latter half, which was dated a day later and

09:09:02.140 --> 09:09:06.720
written in evident agitation, gave more important intelligence.

09:09:07.480 --> 09:09:08.940
It was to this effect.

09:09:10.280 --> 09:09:16.660
Since writing the above, dearest Lizzie, something has occurred of a most unexpected and serious

09:09:16.660 --> 09:09:21.680
nature, but I am afraid of alarming you, be assured that we are all well.

09:09:22.450 --> 09:09:24.820
What I have to say relates to poor Lydia.

09:09:25.580 --> 09:09:31.000
An express came at twelve last night, just as we were all gone to bed, from Colonel Forster,

09:09:31.500 --> 09:09:36.560
to inform us that she was gone off to Scotland with one of his officers, to own the truth

09:09:36.560 --> 09:09:37.640
with Wickham.

09:09:38.320 --> 09:09:39.700
Imagine our surprise!

09:09:40.360 --> 09:09:43.800
To Kitty, however, it does not seem so wholly unexpected.

09:09:44.440 --> 09:09:51.240
I am very, very sorry, so imprudent a match on both sides, but I am willing to hope the

09:09:51.240 --> 09:09:54.080
best, and that his character has been misunderstood.

09:09:54.880 --> 09:10:01.020
Thoughtless and indiscreet, I can easily believe him, but this step, and let us rejoice over

09:10:01.020 --> 09:10:03.460
it, marks nothing bad at heart.

09:10:03.960 --> 09:10:09.260
His choice is disinterested at least, for he must know my father can give her nothing.

09:10:09.900 --> 09:10:12.060
Our poor mother is sadly grieved.

09:10:12.480 --> 09:10:14.160
My father bears it better.

09:10:14.860 --> 09:10:18.960
How thankful I am that we never let them know what has been said against him.

09:10:19.560 --> 09:10:21.440
We must forget it ourselves.

09:10:22.540 --> 09:10:27.780
They were off Saturday night about twelve, as is conjectured, but were not missed till

09:10:27.780 --> 09:10:29.400
yesterday morning at eight.

09:10:30.020 --> 09:10:32.040
The express was sent off directly.

09:10:32.520 --> 09:10:36.520
My dear Lizzy, they must have passed within ten miles of us.

09:10:37.080 --> 09:10:40.340
Colonel Forster gives us reason to expect him here soon.

09:10:41.080 --> 09:10:45.100
Lydia left a few lines for his wife, informing her of their intention.

09:10:45.500 --> 09:10:48.740
I must conclude, for I cannot be long for my poor mother.

09:10:49.280 --> 09:10:53.520
I am afraid you will not be able to make it out, but I hardly know what I have written.

09:10:55.520 --> 09:11:02.080
Without allowing herself time for consideration, and scarcely knowing what she felt, Elizabeth,

09:11:02.320 --> 09:11:07.200
on finishing this letter, instantly seized the other, and opening it with the utmost

09:11:07.200 --> 09:11:09.240
impatience, read as follows.

09:11:09.640 --> 09:11:13.180
It had been written a day later than the conclusion of the first.

09:11:14.260 --> 09:11:18.760
By this time, my dearest sister, you have received my hurried letter.

09:11:19.560 --> 09:11:24.820
I wish this may be more intelligible, but though not confined for time, my head is so

09:11:24.820 --> 09:11:27.540
bewildered that I cannot answer for being coherent.

09:11:28.260 --> 09:11:33.400
Dearest Lizzy, I hardly know what I would write, but I have bad news for you, and it

09:11:33.400 --> 09:11:34.300
cannot be delayed.

09:11:35.220 --> 09:11:40.560
Imprudent as the marriage between Mr. Wickham and our poor Lydia would be, we are now anxious

09:11:40.560 --> 09:11:46.040
to be assured it has taken place, for there is but too much reason to fear they are not

09:11:46.040 --> 09:11:46.920
gone to Scotland.

09:11:47.520 --> 09:11:52.780
Colonel Forster came yesterday, having left Brighton the day before, not many hours after

09:11:52.780 --> 09:11:53.600
the express.

09:11:54.240 --> 09:11:58.500
Though Lydia's short letter to Mrs. F gave them to understand that they were going to

09:11:58.500 --> 09:12:04.940
Gretna Green, something was dropped by Denny expressing his belief that W never intended

09:12:04.940 --> 09:12:11.720
or to marry Lydia at all, which was repeated to Colonel F, who, instantly taking the alarm,

09:12:12.180 --> 09:12:14.840
set off from B intending to trace their route.

09:12:15.320 --> 09:12:21.700
He did trace them easily to Clapham, but no further, for on entering that place they removed

09:12:21.700 --> 09:12:25.640
into a hackney coach and dismissed the shades that brought them from Epsom.

09:12:26.400 --> 09:12:30.700
All that is known after this that they were seen to continue the London road.

09:12:31.040 --> 09:12:32.740
I know not what to think.

09:12:33.400 --> 09:12:39.240
After making every possible enquiry on that side London, Colonel F came on into Hertfordshire,

09:12:39.600 --> 09:12:44.820
anxiously renewing them at all the turnpikes and at the inns in Barnet and Hatfield, but

09:12:44.820 --> 09:12:46.040
without any success.

09:12:46.460 --> 09:12:48.940
No such people had been seen to pass through.

09:12:49.660 --> 09:12:55.040
With the kindest concern he came on to Longbourn and broke his apprehensions to us in a manner

09:12:55.040 --> 09:12:56.760
most creditable to his heart.

09:12:56.760 --> 09:13:02.780
I am sincerely grieved for him and Mrs F, but no one can throw any blame on them.

09:13:03.320 --> 09:13:06.460
Our distress, my dear Lizzie, is very great.

09:13:06.900 --> 09:13:11.140
My father and mother believe the worst, but I cannot think so ill of him.

09:13:11.780 --> 09:13:16.760
Many circumstances might make it more eligible for them to be married privately in town than

09:13:16.760 --> 09:13:18.240
to pursue their first plan.

09:13:18.740 --> 09:13:24.620
And even if he could form such a design against a young woman of Lydia's connections, which

09:13:24.620 --> 09:13:28.580
is not likely, can I suppose her soul lost to everything?

09:13:29.520 --> 09:13:30.120
Impossible!

09:13:30.800 --> 09:13:36.720
I grieve to find, however, that Colonel F is not disposed to depend upon their marriage.

09:13:37.180 --> 09:13:42.940
He shook his head when I expressed my hopes and said he feared W was not a man to be trusted.

09:13:43.740 --> 09:13:46.860
My poor mother is really ill and keeps her room.

09:13:47.480 --> 09:13:51.680
Could she exert herself it would be better, but this is not to be expected.

09:13:51.680 --> 09:13:56.300
And as to my father, I never in my life saw him so affected.

09:13:56.960 --> 09:14:01.920
Poor Kitty has anger for having concealed their attachment, but as it was a matter of

09:14:01.920 --> 09:14:03.540
confidence one cannot wonder.

09:14:04.200 --> 09:14:09.080
I am truly glad, dearest Lizzie, that you have been spared something of these distressing

09:14:09.080 --> 09:14:09.580
scenes.

09:14:09.900 --> 09:14:14.100
But now, as the first shock is over, I shall own that I long for your return.

09:14:14.800 --> 09:14:18.380
I am so selfish, however, as to press for it, if inconvenient.

09:14:19.180 --> 09:14:19.700
Adieu!

09:14:20.340 --> 09:14:26.140
I take up my pen again to do what I have just told you I would not, but circumstances are

09:14:26.140 --> 09:14:30.440
such that I cannot help earnestly begging you all to come here as soon as possible.

09:14:31.120 --> 09:14:36.080
I know my dear uncle and aunt so well that I am not afraid of requesting it, though I

09:14:36.080 --> 09:14:38.320
have still something more to ask of the former.

09:14:39.000 --> 09:14:44.440
My father is going to London with Colonel Forster instantly to try to discover her.

09:14:44.440 --> 09:14:50.440
What he means to do I am sure I know not, but his excessive distress will not allow

09:14:50.440 --> 09:14:55.800
him to pursue any measure in the best and safest way, and Colonel Forster is obliged

09:14:55.800 --> 09:14:57.940
to be at Brighton again tomorrow evening.

09:14:58.880 --> 09:15:03.740
In such an exigence, my uncle's advice and assistance would be everything in the world.

09:15:04.200 --> 09:15:08.740
He will immediately comprehend what I must feel, and I rely upon his goodness.

09:15:10.440 --> 09:15:13.080
Oh, where, where is my uncle?

09:15:13.580 --> 09:15:18.120
cried Elizabeth, darting from her seat as she finished the letter, in eagerness to

09:15:18.120 --> 09:15:21.100
follow him without losing a moment of the time so precious.

09:15:21.680 --> 09:15:26.800
But as she reached the door, it was opened by a servant, and Mr. Darcy appeared.

09:15:27.460 --> 09:15:30.720
Her pale face and impetuous manner made him start.

09:15:31.360 --> 09:15:37.420
And before he could recover himself to speak, she, in whose mind every idea was superseded

09:15:37.420 --> 09:15:40.360
by Lydia's situation, hastily exclaimed,

09:15:41.240 --> 09:15:43.560
I beg your pardon, but I must leave you.

09:15:43.640 --> 09:15:47.840
I must find Mr. Gardiner this moment, a business that cannot be delayed.

09:15:48.160 --> 09:15:49.820
I have not an instant to lose.

09:15:50.880 --> 09:15:52.860
Good God, what is the matter?

09:15:53.320 --> 09:15:56.020
cried he, with more feeling than politeness.

09:15:57.240 --> 09:15:58.900
Then, recollecting himself,

09:15:59.440 --> 09:16:04.840
I will not detain you a minute, but let me, or let the servant, go after Mr. and Mrs.

09:16:05.040 --> 09:16:05.400
Gardiner.

09:16:05.400 --> 09:16:09.540
You are not well enough, you cannot go yourself.

09:16:10.700 --> 09:16:14.020
Elizabeth hesitated, but her knees trembled under her,

09:16:14.200 --> 09:16:18.200
and she felt how little would be gained by her attempting to pursue them.

09:16:18.800 --> 09:16:22.140
Calling back the servant, therefore, she commissioned him,

09:16:22.260 --> 09:16:26.460
though in so breathless an accent as made her almost unintelligible,

09:16:26.960 --> 09:16:29.720
to fetch his master and mistress home instantly.

09:16:31.400 --> 09:16:35.380
On his quitting the room, she sat down, unable to support herself.

09:16:35.400 --> 09:16:40.700
And looking so miserably ill that it was impossible for Darcy to leave her,

09:16:40.880 --> 09:16:45.220
or to refrain from saying, in a tone of gentleness and commiseration,

09:16:46.220 --> 09:16:47.420
Let me call your maid.

09:16:47.940 --> 09:16:50.900
Is there nothing you could take to give you present relief?

09:16:51.360 --> 09:16:52.420
A glass of wine?

09:16:52.800 --> 09:16:53.800
Shall I get you one?

09:16:54.220 --> 09:16:55.760
You are very ill.

09:16:56.500 --> 09:17:00.920
No, I thank you, she replied, endeavouring to recover herself.

09:17:01.700 --> 09:17:03.520
There is nothing the matter with me.

09:17:03.520 --> 09:17:04.840
I am quite well.

09:17:04.840 --> 09:17:09.320
I am only distressed by some dreadful news which I have just received from Longbourn.

09:17:10.260 --> 09:17:13.060
She burst into tears as she alluded to it,

09:17:13.220 --> 09:17:15.780
and for a few minutes could not speak another word.

09:17:16.860 --> 09:17:22.060
Darcy, in wretched suspense, could only say something indistinctly of his concern,

09:17:22.400 --> 09:17:24.980
and observe her in compassionate silence.

09:17:25.980 --> 09:17:28.040
At length she spoke again.

09:17:28.840 --> 09:17:32.780
I have just had a letter from Jane, with such dreadful news.

09:17:32.780 --> 09:17:34.960
It cannot be concealed from anyone.

09:17:35.760 --> 09:17:39.000
My youngest sister has left all her friends, has eloped,

09:17:39.620 --> 09:17:43.200
has thrown herself into the power of Mr Wickham.

09:17:43.660 --> 09:17:45.540
They are gone off together from Brighton.

09:17:45.960 --> 09:17:48.180
You know him too well to doubt the rest.

09:17:48.520 --> 09:17:52.340
She has no money, no connections, nothing that can tempt him to.

09:17:52.700 --> 09:17:54.160
She is lost forever.

09:17:55.520 --> 09:17:57.660
Darcy was fixed in astonishment.

09:17:58.880 --> 09:18:02.760
When I consider, she added in a yet more agitated voice,

09:18:02.780 --> 09:18:05.040
that I might have prevented it.

09:18:05.260 --> 09:18:07.180
I, who knew what he was.

09:18:07.700 --> 09:18:10.100
Had I but explained some part of it only,

09:18:10.360 --> 09:18:13.000
some part of what I learnt to my own family.

09:18:13.680 --> 09:18:16.340
Had his character been known, this could not have happened.

09:18:17.320 --> 09:18:19.720
But it is all too late now.

09:18:22.080 --> 09:18:27.020
I am grieved indeed, cried Darcy, grieved, shocked.

09:18:27.460 --> 09:18:30.040
But is it certain, absolutely certain?

09:18:30.680 --> 09:18:34.080
Oh yes, they left Brighton together on Sunday night,

09:18:34.120 --> 09:18:36.980
and were traced almost to London, but not beyond.

09:18:37.300 --> 09:18:39.080
They are certainly not gone to Scotland.

09:18:40.040 --> 09:18:41.160
And what has been done?

09:18:41.240 --> 09:18:43.340
What has been attempted to recover her?

09:18:44.300 --> 09:18:46.000
My father has gone to London,

09:18:46.280 --> 09:18:49.320
and Jane has written to beg my uncle's immediate assistance.

09:18:49.440 --> 09:18:52.300
And we shall be off, I hope, in half an hour.

09:18:52.720 --> 09:18:54.040
But nothing can be done.

09:18:54.220 --> 09:18:56.200
I know very well that nothing can be done.

09:18:56.500 --> 09:18:58.460
How is such a man to be worked on?

09:18:59.100 --> 09:19:01.040
How are they even to be discovered?

09:19:01.680 --> 09:19:03.540
I have not the smallest hope.

09:19:03.880 --> 09:19:05.480
It is every way horrible.

09:19:06.240 --> 09:19:09.300
Darcy shook his head in silent acquiescence.

09:19:12.440 --> 09:19:15.420
When my eyes were opened to his real character.

09:19:16.020 --> 09:19:19.760
Oh, had I known what I ought, what I dared to do.

09:19:20.040 --> 09:19:22.940
But I knew not, I was afraid of doing too much.

09:19:23.280 --> 09:19:25.140
Wretched, wretched mistake.

09:19:26.200 --> 09:19:27.840
Darcy made no answer.

09:19:27.840 --> 09:19:30.320
He seemed scarcely to hear her,

09:19:30.520 --> 09:19:33.800
and was walking up and down the room in earnest meditation,

09:19:34.180 --> 09:19:37.000
his brow contracted, his air gloomy.

09:19:37.940 --> 09:19:41.100
Elizabeth soon observed and instantly understood it.

09:19:41.520 --> 09:19:42.780
Her power was sinking.

09:19:43.540 --> 09:19:46.960
Everything must sink under such a proof of family weakness,

09:19:47.660 --> 09:19:49.860
such an assurance of the deepest disgrace.

09:19:50.640 --> 09:19:52.820
She could neither wonder nor condemn,

09:19:53.120 --> 09:19:55.180
but the belief of his self-conquest

09:19:55.180 --> 09:19:57.920
brought nothing consolatory to her bosom,

09:19:58.220 --> 09:20:00.580
afforded no palatation of her distress.

09:20:01.400 --> 09:20:04.600
It was, on the contrary, exactly calculated

09:20:04.600 --> 09:20:06.580
to make her understand her own wishes,

09:20:07.000 --> 09:20:10.280
and never had she so honestly felt that she could have loved him,

09:20:10.400 --> 09:20:12.960
as now, when all love must be vain.

09:20:14.160 --> 09:20:17.900
But self, though it would intrude, could not engross her.

09:20:18.380 --> 09:20:22.600
Lydia, the humiliation, the misery she was bringing on them all,

09:20:22.840 --> 09:20:25.080
soon swallowed up every private care.

09:20:25.740 --> 09:20:28.100
And covering her face with her handkerchief,

09:20:28.640 --> 09:20:30.760
Elizabeth was soon lost to everything else,

09:20:31.400 --> 09:20:33.940
and, after a pause of several minutes,

09:20:34.220 --> 09:20:36.780
was only recalled to a sense of her situation

09:20:36.780 --> 09:20:38.360
by the voice of her companion,

09:20:38.840 --> 09:20:41.680
who, in a manner which, though it spoke compassion,

09:20:42.220 --> 09:20:44.420
spoke likewise restraint, said,

09:20:45.120 --> 09:20:48.340
I am afraid you have been long desiring my absence,

09:20:48.660 --> 09:20:51.600
nor have I anything to plead an excuse of my stay,

09:20:51.900 --> 09:20:54.500
but a real, though unavailing concern.

09:20:54.500 --> 09:20:59.660
Would to heaven that anything could be either said or done on my part

09:20:59.660 --> 09:21:02.580
that might offer consolation to such distress.

09:21:03.700 --> 09:21:06.320
But I will torment you not with vain wishes,

09:21:06.580 --> 09:21:09.360
which may seem purposely to ask for your thanks.

09:21:10.100 --> 09:21:13.060
This unfortunate affair will, I fear,

09:21:13.720 --> 09:21:17.680
prevent my sisters having the pleasure of seeing her at Pemberley today.

09:21:18.600 --> 09:21:22.780
Oh yes, be so kind as to apologize for us to Miss Darcy.

09:21:22.780 --> 09:21:25.980
Say that urgent business calls us home immediately.

09:21:26.560 --> 09:21:29.640
Conceal the unhappy truth as long as it is possible.

09:21:30.120 --> 09:21:31.740
I know it cannot be long.

09:21:32.680 --> 09:21:34.980
He readily assured her of his secrecy,

09:21:35.680 --> 09:21:38.200
again expressed his sorrow for her distress,

09:21:38.940 --> 09:21:42.220
wished it a happier conclusion than there was at present reason to hope,

09:21:42.680 --> 09:21:45.160
and, leaving his compliments for her relations

09:21:45.160 --> 09:21:49.360
with only one serious parting look, went away.

09:21:50.500 --> 09:21:52.040
As he quitted the room,

09:21:52.040 --> 09:21:56.660
Elizabeth felt how improbable it was that they should ever see each other again

09:21:56.660 --> 09:22:01.300
on such terms of cordiality as had marked their several meetings in Derbyshire.

09:22:02.120 --> 09:22:05.800
And as she threw a retrospective glance over the whole of their acquaintance,

09:22:06.580 --> 09:22:08.880
so full of contradictions and varieties,

09:22:09.920 --> 09:22:12.300
sighed at the perseverance of those feelings

09:22:12.300 --> 09:22:15.400
which would now have promoted its continuance

09:22:15.400 --> 09:22:18.440
and would formally have rejoiced in its termination.

09:22:19.200 --> 09:22:23.060
If gratitude and esteem are good foundations of affection,

09:22:23.740 --> 09:22:27.780
Elizabeth's change of sentiment will be neither improbable nor faulty.

09:22:28.480 --> 09:22:34.340
But if otherwise, if regard springing from such sources is unreasonable or unnatural,

09:22:34.860 --> 09:22:37.340
in comparison of what is so often described

09:22:37.340 --> 09:22:40.040
as arising on a first interview with its object,

09:22:40.580 --> 09:22:43.400
and even before two words have been exchanged,

09:22:44.080 --> 09:22:45.900
nothing can be said in her defense,

09:22:45.900 --> 09:22:50.020
except that she had given somewhat of a trial to the latter method

09:22:50.020 --> 09:22:51.940
in her partiality for Wickham,

09:22:52.640 --> 09:22:55.460
and that its ill-success might, perhaps,

09:22:55.980 --> 09:22:59.660
authorize her to seek the other less interesting mode of attachment.

09:23:00.820 --> 09:23:03.780
Be that as it may, she saw him go with regret,

09:23:04.620 --> 09:23:08.500
and in this early example of what Lydia's infamy must produce,

09:23:09.200 --> 09:23:12.880
found additional anguish as she reflected on that wretched business.

09:23:13.440 --> 09:23:15.980
Never since reading Jane's second letter

09:23:15.980 --> 09:23:19.160
had she entertained a hope of Wickham's meaning to marry her.

09:23:19.680 --> 09:23:21.380
No one but Jane, she thought,

09:23:21.640 --> 09:23:23.920
could flatter herself with such an expectation.

09:23:25.060 --> 09:23:27.720
Surprise was the least of her feelings on this development.

09:23:28.620 --> 09:23:31.720
While the contents of the first letter remained in her mind,

09:23:32.140 --> 09:23:35.060
she was all surprise, all astonishment,

09:23:35.380 --> 09:23:39.280
that Wickham should marry a girl whom it was impossible he could marry for money,

09:23:39.760 --> 09:23:42.120
and how Lydia could ever have attached him

09:23:42.120 --> 09:23:43.940
had appeared incomprehensible.

09:23:44.640 --> 09:23:46.620
But now it was all too natural.

09:23:47.300 --> 09:23:50.940
For such an attachment as this, she might have sufficient charms,

09:23:51.480 --> 09:23:55.860
and though she did not suppose Lydia to be deliberately engaging in elopement

09:23:55.860 --> 09:23:57.440
without the intention of marriage,

09:23:57.900 --> 09:24:02.940
she had no difficulty in believing that neither her virtue nor her understanding

09:24:02.940 --> 09:24:05.900
would preserve her from falling an easy prey.

09:24:07.040 --> 09:24:10.700
She had never perceived, while the regiment was in Hertfordshire,

09:24:10.700 --> 09:24:13.640
that Lydia had any partiality for him,

09:24:14.020 --> 09:24:16.940
but she was convinced that Lydia wanted only encouragement

09:24:16.940 --> 09:24:18.700
to attach herself to anybody.

09:24:19.460 --> 09:24:21.900
Sometimes one officer, sometimes another,

09:24:22.300 --> 09:24:26.220
had been her favourite, as their attentions raised them in her opinion.

09:24:27.060 --> 09:24:31.500
Her affections had continually been fluctuating, but never without an object.

09:24:32.380 --> 09:24:35.920
The mischief of neglect and mistaken indulgence towards such a girl,

09:24:36.360 --> 09:24:39.100
oh, how acutely did she now feel it!

09:24:39.720 --> 09:24:43.660
She was wild to be at home, to hear, to see,

09:24:43.860 --> 09:24:48.940
to be upon the spot to share with Jane in the cares that must now fall wholly upon her.

09:24:49.380 --> 09:24:54.940
In a family so deranged, a father absent, a mother incapable of exertion

09:24:54.940 --> 09:24:56.900
and requiring constant attendance,

09:24:57.440 --> 09:25:00.560
and though almost persuaded that nothing could be done for Lydia,

09:25:01.020 --> 09:25:04.100
her uncle's interference seemed of the utmost importance.

09:25:04.520 --> 09:25:07.340
Until he entered the room, her impatience was severe.

09:25:07.980 --> 09:25:10.820
Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner had hurried back in alarm,

09:25:11.360 --> 09:25:15.340
supposing by the servants' account that their niece was taken suddenly ill.

09:25:15.960 --> 09:25:18.420
But satisfying them instantly on that head,

09:25:18.740 --> 09:25:21.780
she eagerly communicated the calls of their summons,

09:25:21.920 --> 09:25:27.200
reading the two letters aloud and dwelling on the postscript of the last with trembling energy.

09:25:27.540 --> 09:25:29.760
Though Lydia had never been a favourite with them,

09:25:30.020 --> 09:25:32.940
Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner could not but be deeply afflicted.

09:25:33.840 --> 09:25:37.200
Not Lydia only, but all were concerned in it,

09:25:37.440 --> 09:25:40.760
and after the first exclamations of surprise and horror,

09:25:41.200 --> 09:25:44.060
Mr. Gardiner promised every assistance in his power.

09:25:44.980 --> 09:25:49.120
Elizabeth, though expecting no less, thanked him with tears of gratitude,

09:25:49.620 --> 09:25:52.300
and all three being actuated by one spirit,

09:25:52.800 --> 09:25:55.540
everything relating to their journey was speedily settled.

09:25:56.100 --> 09:25:58.120
They were to be off as soon as possible.

09:25:59.240 --> 09:26:03.280
"'But what is to be done about Pemberley?' cried Mrs. Gardiner.

09:26:03.760 --> 09:26:07.900
"'John told us Mr. Darcy was here when you sent for us. Was it so?'

09:26:08.980 --> 09:26:13.400
"'Yes, and I told him we should not be able to keep our engagement. That is all settled.'

09:26:15.060 --> 09:26:19.520
"'What is all settled?' repeated the other as she ran into the room to prepare.

09:26:20.220 --> 09:26:24.120
"'And are they upon such terms as for her to disclose the real truth?'

09:26:24.700 --> 09:26:28.820
"'Oh, that I knew how it was.' But wishes were vain,

09:26:29.240 --> 09:26:33.820
or at least could only serve to amuse her in the hurry and confusion of the following hour.

09:26:34.780 --> 09:26:39.300
Had Elizabeth been at leisure to be idle, she would have remained certain that all employment

09:26:39.300 --> 09:26:45.540
was impossible to one so wretched as herself. But she had her share of business as well as her aunt,

09:26:46.100 --> 09:26:50.500
and amongst the rest there were notes to be written to all their friends at Lambden,

09:26:50.860 --> 09:26:53.360
with false excuses for their sudden departure.

09:26:54.220 --> 09:26:58.560
An hour, however, saw the whole complete it, and Mr. Gardiner,

09:26:58.780 --> 09:27:03.340
meanwhile having settled his account at the inn, nothing remained to be done but to go.

09:27:03.680 --> 09:27:09.060
And Elizabeth, after all the misery of the morning, found herself, in a shorter space

09:27:09.060 --> 09:27:14.120
of time than she could have supposed, seated in the carriage and on the road to Longbourn.

09:27:44.120 --> 09:27:49.500
I have been thinking it over again, Elizabeth, said her uncle, as they drove from the town.

09:27:49.860 --> 09:27:55.560
And really, upon serious consideration, I am much more inclined than I was to judge

09:27:55.560 --> 09:27:57.660
as your eldest sister does on the matter.

09:27:58.400 --> 09:28:03.440
It appears to me so very unlikely that any young man should form such a design against

09:28:03.440 --> 09:28:10.060
a girl who is by no means unprotected or friendless, and who is actually staying in his colonel's

09:28:10.060 --> 09:28:13.760
family, that I am strongly inclined to hope the best.

09:28:14.440 --> 09:28:17.220
Could he expect that her friends would not step forward?

09:28:17.740 --> 09:28:22.700
Could he expect to be noticed again by the regiment after such an affront to Colonel

09:28:22.700 --> 09:28:23.160
Forster?

09:28:23.780 --> 09:28:26.380
His temptation is not adequate to the risk.

09:28:27.280 --> 09:28:28.780
Do you really think so?

09:28:28.900 --> 09:28:31.260
cried Elizabeth, brightening up for a moment.

09:28:32.280 --> 09:28:37.200
Upon my word, said Mrs. Gardiner, I begin to be of your uncle's opinion.

09:28:37.500 --> 09:28:43.500
It is really too great a violation of decency, honor, and interest for him to be guilty of.

09:28:43.840 --> 09:28:46.180
I cannot think so very ill of Wickham.

09:28:46.840 --> 09:28:52.340
Can you yourself, Lizzie, so wholly give him up as to believe him capable of it?

09:28:53.400 --> 09:28:58.500
Not perhaps of neglecting his own interest, but of every other neglect I can believe him

09:28:58.500 --> 09:28:59.020
capable.

09:28:59.680 --> 09:29:01.880
If, indeed, it should be so.

09:29:02.260 --> 09:29:04.180
But I dare not hope it.

09:29:04.180 --> 09:29:07.660
Why should they not go on to Scotland, if that had been the case?

09:29:08.360 --> 09:29:13.620
In the first place, replied Mr. Gardiner, there is no absolute proof that they are not

09:29:13.620 --> 09:29:14.600
gone to Scotland.

09:29:15.680 --> 09:29:20.880
Oh, but their removing from the Shays into a Hackney coach is such a presumption, and

09:29:20.880 --> 09:29:24.680
besides, no traces of them were to be found on the Barnet Road.

09:29:25.940 --> 09:29:30.960
Well then, supposing them to be in London, they may be there, though for the purpose

09:29:30.960 --> 09:29:34.100
of concealment, for no more exceptional purpose.

09:29:34.540 --> 09:29:39.400
It is not likely that money should be very abundant on either side, and it might strike

09:29:39.400 --> 09:29:44.720
them that they could be more economically, though less expeditiously, married in London

09:29:44.720 --> 09:29:46.040
than in Scotland.

09:29:47.180 --> 09:29:48.980
But why all this secrecy?

09:29:49.320 --> 09:29:50.820
Why any fear of detection?

09:29:51.480 --> 09:29:53.460
Why must their marriage be private?

09:29:54.160 --> 09:29:56.560
Oh, no, no, this is not likely.

09:29:56.560 --> 09:30:02.100
His most particular friend, you see, by Jane's account, was persuaded of his never intending

09:30:02.100 --> 09:30:03.140
to marry her.

09:30:03.840 --> 09:30:06.480
Wickham will never marry a woman without some money.

09:30:06.680 --> 09:30:08.000
He cannot afford it.

09:30:08.360 --> 09:30:09.760
And what claims has Lydia?

09:30:10.280 --> 09:30:16.500
What attraction has she beyond youth, health, and good humor that could make him, for her

09:30:16.500 --> 09:30:20.380
sake, forego every chance of benefiting himself by marrying well?

09:30:21.220 --> 09:30:26.540
As to what restraint the apprehensions of disgrace in the core might throw on a dishonorable

09:30:26.540 --> 09:30:31.900
elopement with her, I am not able to judge, for I know nothing of the effects that such

09:30:31.900 --> 09:30:33.240
a step might produce.

09:30:33.820 --> 09:30:38.540
But as to your other objection, I am afraid it will hardly hold good.

09:30:39.220 --> 09:30:44.380
Lydia has no brothers to step forward, and he might imagine, from my father's behavior,

09:30:44.820 --> 09:30:49.180
from his indolence and the little attention he has ever seemed to give to what was going

09:30:49.180 --> 09:30:54.740
forward in his family, that he would do as little, and think as little about it, as any

09:30:54.740 --> 09:30:56.520
father could do in such a matter.

09:30:57.600 --> 09:31:02.680
But can you think that Lydia is so lost to everything but love of him as to consent to

09:31:02.680 --> 09:31:04.940
live with him on any terms other than marriage?

09:31:05.820 --> 09:31:11.720
It does seem, and it is most shocking indeed, replied Elizabeth with tears in her eyes,

09:31:12.200 --> 09:31:16.920
that a sister's sense of decency and virtue in such a point should admit of doubt.

09:31:17.600 --> 09:31:20.000
But really, I know not what to say.

09:31:20.580 --> 09:31:24.380
Perhaps I am not doing her justice, but she is very young.

09:31:24.800 --> 09:31:30.340
She has never been taught to think on serious subjects, and for the last half year, nay,

09:31:30.380 --> 09:31:34.520
for a twelve month, she has been given up to nothing but amusement and vanity.

09:31:35.080 --> 09:31:39.500
She has been allowed to dispose of her time in the most idle and frivolous manner, and

09:31:39.500 --> 09:31:41.800
to adopt any opinions that came in her way.

09:31:42.420 --> 09:31:47.760
Since the blank shear were first quartered in Maryton, nothing but love, flirtation,

09:31:47.760 --> 09:31:49.540
officers have been in her head.

09:31:50.000 --> 09:31:54.460
She has been doing everything in her power by thinking and talking on the subject to

09:31:54.460 --> 09:32:01.600
give greater, what shall I call it, susceptibility to her feelings, which are naturally lively

09:32:01.600 --> 09:32:07.260
enough, and we all know that Wickham has every charm of person and a dress that can captivate

09:32:07.260 --> 09:32:07.840
a woman.

09:32:08.900 --> 09:32:14.100
But you see that Jane, said her aunt, does not think so very ill of Wickham as to believe

09:32:14.100 --> 09:32:15.560
him capable of the attempt.

09:32:16.280 --> 09:32:22.500
Of whom does Jane ever think ill, and who is there, whatever might be their former conduct,

09:32:22.860 --> 09:32:27.080
that she would think capable of such an attempt till it were proved against them?

09:32:27.500 --> 09:32:31.520
But Jane knows, as well as I do, what Wickham really is.

09:32:31.980 --> 09:32:36.880
We both know that he has been profligate in every sense of the word, that he has neither

09:32:36.880 --> 09:32:42.520
integrity nor honor, that he is as false and deceitful as he is insinuating.

09:32:43.140 --> 09:32:49.400
And do you really know all this, cried Mrs. Gardiner, whose curiosity as to the mode of

09:32:49.400 --> 09:32:51.520
her intelligence was all alive?

09:32:52.380 --> 09:32:55.320
I do indeed, replied Elizabeth, coloring.

09:32:56.160 --> 09:33:02.020
I told you the other day of his infamous behavior to Mr. Darcy, and you yourself, when last

09:33:02.020 --> 09:33:07.220
at Longbourn, heard in what manner he spoke of the man who had behaved with such forbearance

09:33:07.220 --> 09:33:09.000
and liberality towards him.

09:33:09.470 --> 09:33:14.440
And there are other circumstances which I am not at liberty, which it is not worth while

09:33:14.440 --> 09:33:15.080
to relate.

09:33:15.760 --> 09:33:19.020
But his lies about the whole Pemberley family are endless.

09:33:19.680 --> 09:33:25.160
From what he said of Miss Darcy, I was thoroughly prepared to see a proud, reserved, disagreeable

09:33:25.160 --> 09:33:25.620
girl.

09:33:26.220 --> 09:33:28.480
Yet he knew to the contrary himself.

09:33:29.020 --> 09:33:33.440
He must know that she was as amiable and unpretending as we have found her.

09:33:34.120 --> 09:33:36.260
But does Lydia know nothing of this?

09:33:36.260 --> 09:33:40.380
Can she be ignorant of what you and Jane seem so well to understand?

09:33:41.720 --> 09:33:44.840
Oh, yes, that, that is the worst of all.

09:33:45.160 --> 09:33:51.100
Till I was in Kent, and saw so much both of Mr. Darcy and his relation, Colonel Fitzwilliam,

09:33:51.420 --> 09:33:53.520
I was ignorant of the truth myself.

09:33:53.980 --> 09:33:58.920
And when I returned home, the blank shear was to leave Mariton in a week or for its

09:33:58.920 --> 09:33:59.600
night time.

09:34:00.180 --> 09:34:05.980
As that was the case, neither Jane, to whom I related the whole, nor I, thought it necessary

09:34:05.980 --> 09:34:07.340
to make our knowledge public.

09:34:07.820 --> 09:34:10.440
For of what use could it apparently be to any one?

09:34:10.860 --> 09:34:16.020
That the good opinion which all the neighborhood had of him should then be overthrown.

09:34:16.360 --> 09:34:21.600
And even when it was settled that Lydia should go with Mrs. Forster, the necessity of opening

09:34:21.600 --> 09:34:24.180
her eyes to his character never occurred to me.

09:34:24.440 --> 09:34:28.580
That she could be in any danger from the deception never entered my head.

09:34:29.160 --> 09:34:34.760
That such a consequence as this could ensue, you may easily believe, was far enough from

09:34:34.760 --> 09:34:35.460
my thoughts.

09:34:36.540 --> 09:34:40.800
When they are all removed to Brighton, therefore you had no reason, I suppose, to believe them

09:34:40.800 --> 09:34:41.820
fond of each other.

09:34:42.560 --> 09:34:43.840
Not the slightest.

09:34:44.200 --> 09:34:47.280
I can remember no symptom of affection on either side.

09:34:47.600 --> 09:34:52.740
And had anything of the kind been perceptible, you must be aware that ours is not a family

09:34:52.740 --> 09:34:54.340
on which it could be thrown away.

09:34:54.920 --> 09:34:58.980
When he first entered the corps, she was ready enough to admire him.

09:34:59.080 --> 09:35:00.460
But so we all were.

09:35:00.460 --> 09:35:05.800
Every girl in or near Merryton was out of her senses about him for the first two months.

09:35:06.280 --> 09:35:09.660
But he never distinguished her by any particular attention.

09:35:10.320 --> 09:35:16.000
And consequently, after a moderate period of extravagant and wild admiration, her fancy

09:35:16.000 --> 09:35:21.540
for him gave way, and others of the regiment, who treated her with more distinction, again

09:35:21.540 --> 09:35:22.680
became her favorites.

09:35:24.160 --> 09:35:29.520
It may be easily believed that however little of novelty could be added to their fears,

09:35:29.520 --> 09:35:35.980
hopes, and conjectures on this interesting subject by its repeated discussion, no other

09:35:35.980 --> 09:35:39.420
could detain them from it long during the whole of the journey.

09:35:40.200 --> 09:35:43.220
From Elizabeth's thoughts it was never absent.

09:35:43.880 --> 09:35:49.840
Fixed there by the keenest of all anguish, self-reproach, she could find no interval

09:35:49.840 --> 09:35:51.640
of ease or forgetfulness.

09:35:52.540 --> 09:35:58.380
They traveled as expeditiously as possible, and sleeping one night on the road, reached

09:35:58.380 --> 09:36:00.460
long borne by dinnertime the next day.

09:36:01.160 --> 09:36:05.940
It was a comfort to Elizabeth to consider that Jane could not have been wearied by long

09:36:05.940 --> 09:36:06.900
expectations.

09:36:08.140 --> 09:36:12.820
The little gardeners, attracted by the sight of a chaise, were standing on the steps of

09:36:12.820 --> 09:36:14.620
the house as they entered the paddock.

09:36:15.000 --> 09:36:19.760
And when the carriage drove up to the door, the joyful surprise that lighted up their

09:36:19.760 --> 09:36:26.160
faces and displayed itself over their whole bodies in a variety of capers and frisks was

09:36:26.160 --> 09:36:28.560
the first pleasing earnest of their welcome.

09:36:29.840 --> 09:36:35.300
Elizabeth jumped out, and after giving each of them a hasty kiss, hurried into the vestibule,

09:36:35.660 --> 09:36:40.520
where Jane, who came running down from her mother's apartment, immediately met her.

09:36:41.780 --> 09:36:47.520
Elizabeth as she affectionately embraced her, whilst tears filled the eyes of both, lost

09:36:47.520 --> 09:36:51.400
not a moment in asking whether anything had been heard of the fugitives.

09:36:52.380 --> 09:36:57.180
"'Not yet,' replied Jane, "'but now that my dear uncle is come, I hope everything will

09:36:57.180 --> 09:36:58.360
be well.'

09:36:58.360 --> 09:37:00.240
"'Is my father in town?'

09:37:00.240 --> 09:37:03.200
"'Yes, he went on Tuesday, as I wrote you word.

09:37:03.480 --> 09:37:05.580
And have you heard from him often?'

09:37:05.580 --> 09:37:07.460
"'We have heard only twice.

09:37:07.660 --> 09:37:12.200
He wrote me a few lines on Wednesday to say that he had arrived in safety, and to give

09:37:12.200 --> 09:37:15.680
me his directions, which I particularly begged him to do.

09:37:16.080 --> 09:37:20.480
He merely added that he should not write again till he had something of importance to mention.'

09:37:21.160 --> 09:37:23.060
"'And my mother, how is she?

09:37:23.140 --> 09:37:24.700
How are you all?'

09:37:24.700 --> 09:37:29.260
"'My mother is tolerably well, I trust, though her spirits are greatly shaken.

09:37:29.680 --> 09:37:33.540
She is upstairs, and will have great satisfaction in seeing you all.

09:37:33.980 --> 09:37:35.960
She does not yet leave her dressing-room.

09:37:36.600 --> 09:37:38.980
Mary and Kitty, thank Heaven, are quite well.'

09:37:40.440 --> 09:37:42.340
"'But you, how are you?'

09:37:42.340 --> 09:37:43.180
cried Elizabeth.

09:37:43.380 --> 09:37:44.560
"'You look pale.

09:37:44.940 --> 09:37:47.300
How much you must have gone through!'

09:37:47.300 --> 09:37:52.440
Her sister, however, assured her of being perfectly well, and their conversation, which

09:37:52.440 --> 09:37:57.660
had been passing while Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner were engaged with their children, was now

09:37:57.660 --> 09:38:00.200
put an end to by the approach of the whole party.

09:38:01.320 --> 09:38:06.660
Jane ran to her uncle and aunt, and welcomed and thanked them both, with alternate smiles

09:38:06.660 --> 09:38:07.620
and tears.

09:38:08.560 --> 09:38:12.780
When they were all in the drawing-room, the questions which Elizabeth had already asked

09:38:12.780 --> 09:38:17.300
were of course repeated by the others, and they soon found that Jane had no intelligence

09:38:17.300 --> 09:38:17.900
to give.

09:38:18.700 --> 09:38:23.400
The sanguine hope of good, however, which the benevolence of her heart suggested, had

09:38:23.400 --> 09:38:24.680
not yet deserted her.

09:38:25.140 --> 09:38:29.920
She still expected that it would all end well, and that every morning would bring some letter,

09:38:30.220 --> 09:38:36.060
either from Lydia or her father, to explain their proceedings, and, perhaps, announce

09:38:36.060 --> 09:38:36.920
their marriage.

09:38:37.720 --> 09:38:43.580
Mrs. Bennet, to whose apartment they all repaired, after a few minutes' conversation together,

09:38:44.140 --> 09:38:51.120
received them exactly as might be expected, with tears and lamentations of regret, invectives

09:38:51.120 --> 09:38:56.400
against the villainous conduct of Wickham, and complaints of her own sufferings and ill

09:38:56.400 --> 09:39:02.420
usage, blaming everybody but the person to whose ill-judging indulgence the errors of

09:39:02.420 --> 09:39:04.540
her daughter must principally be owing.

09:39:05.340 --> 09:39:10.440
"'If I had been able,' said she, "'to carry my point, and going to brighten with all

09:39:10.440 --> 09:39:15.760
my family, this would not have happened,' but poor dear Lydia had nobody to take care

09:39:15.760 --> 09:39:16.340
of her.

09:39:16.740 --> 09:39:19.480
Why did the Forsters ever let her go out of their sight?

09:39:19.820 --> 09:39:24.160
I am sure there was some great neglect or other on their side, for she is not the kind

09:39:24.160 --> 09:39:27.260
of girl to do such a thing if she had been well looked after.

09:39:27.600 --> 09:39:32.700
I always thought they were very unfit to have the charge of her, but I was overruled, as

09:39:32.700 --> 09:39:33.720
I always am.

09:39:34.240 --> 09:39:35.800
Poor dear child!

09:39:36.300 --> 09:39:41.400
And now here is Mr. Bennet gone away, and I know he will fight Wickham, wherever he

09:39:41.400 --> 09:39:44.760
meets him, and then he will be killed, and what is to become of us all?

09:39:45.120 --> 09:39:49.300
The Collinses will turn us out before he is cold in his grave, and if you are not kind

09:39:49.300 --> 09:39:52.840
to us, brother, I do not know what we shall do.'

09:39:52.840 --> 09:39:59.520
They all exclaimed against such terrific ideas, and Mr. Gardiner, after general assurances

09:39:59.520 --> 09:40:04.420
of his affection for her and all her family, told her that he meant to be in London the

09:40:04.420 --> 09:40:09.600
very next day, and would assist Mr. Bennet in every endeavour for recovering Lydia.

09:40:10.680 --> 09:40:16.080
"'Do not give way to useless alarm,' added he, though it is right to be prepared for

09:40:16.080 --> 09:40:19.480
the worst, there is no occasion to look on it as certain.

09:40:20.140 --> 09:40:25.360
It is not quite a week since they left Brighton, and a few days more we may gain some news

09:40:25.360 --> 09:40:25.860
of them.

09:40:26.460 --> 09:40:31.440
And till we know that they are not married, and have no design of marrying, do not let

09:40:31.440 --> 09:40:33.360
us give the matter over as lost.

09:40:33.980 --> 09:40:38.180
As soon as I get to town I shall go to my brother, and make him come home with me to

09:40:38.180 --> 09:40:42.240
Grace Church Street, and then we may consult together as to what is to be done.'

09:40:43.600 --> 09:40:49.540
"'Oh, my dear brother,' replied Mrs. Bennet, that is exactly what I could most wish for.

09:40:49.940 --> 09:40:55.040
And now do, when you get to town, find them out wherever they may be, and if they are

09:40:55.040 --> 09:40:57.160
not married already, make them marry.

09:40:57.600 --> 09:41:01.360
And as for wedding clothes, do not let them wait for that, but tell Lydia she shall have

09:41:01.360 --> 09:41:04.620
as much money as she chooses to buy them, after they are married.

09:41:05.120 --> 09:41:07.740
And above all, keep Mr. Bennet from fighting.

09:41:08.300 --> 09:41:13.040
Tell him what a dreadful state I am in, that I am frightened out of my wits, and have such

09:41:13.040 --> 09:41:18.840
tremblings, such flutterings all over me, such spasms in my side, and pains in my head,

09:41:19.220 --> 09:41:23.140
and such beatings at heart, that I can get no rest by night nor by day.

09:41:23.740 --> 09:41:28.680
And tell my dear Lydia not to give any directions about her clothes till she has seen me, for

09:41:28.680 --> 09:41:30.720
she does not know which are the best warehouses.

09:41:31.500 --> 09:41:33.240
Oh, brother, how kind you are!

09:41:33.480 --> 09:41:36.280
I know you will contrive it all.'

09:41:36.280 --> 09:41:41.680
But Mr. Gardiner, though he assured her again of his earnest endeavours in the cause, could

09:41:41.680 --> 09:41:46.500
not avoid recommending moderation to her, as well in her hopes as her fear.

09:41:47.060 --> 09:41:51.240
And after talking with her in this manner till dinner was on the table, they all left

09:41:51.240 --> 09:41:56.080
her to vent all her feelings on the housekeeper, who attended in the absence of her daughters.

09:41:57.180 --> 09:42:02.160
Though her brother and sister were persuaded that there was no real occasion for such a

09:42:02.160 --> 09:42:07.520
seclusion from the family, they did not attempt to oppose it, for they knew that she had not

09:42:07.520 --> 09:42:12.140
prudence enough to hold her tongue before the servants while they waited at table, and

09:42:12.140 --> 09:42:17.660
judged it better that one only of the household, and the one whom they could most trust, should

09:42:17.910 --> 09:42:20.880
all her fears and solicitude on the subject.

09:42:22.160 --> 09:42:28.280
In the dining-room they were soon joined by Mary and Kitty, who had been too busily engaged

09:42:28.280 --> 09:42:31.680
in their separate apartments to make their appearance before.

09:42:32.380 --> 09:42:35.980
One came from her books, and the other from her toilette.

09:42:36.520 --> 09:42:42.120
The faces of both, however, were tolerably calm, and no change was visible in either,

09:42:42.620 --> 09:42:47.720
except that the loss of her favorite sister, or the anger which she had herself incurred

09:42:47.720 --> 09:42:53.360
in this business, had given more of fretfulness than usual to the accents of Kitty.

09:42:54.480 --> 09:43:00.200
As for Mary, she was mistress enough of herself to whisper to Elizabeth, with a countenance

09:43:00.200 --> 09:43:03.900
of grave reflection, soon after they were seated at the table.

09:43:04.800 --> 09:43:11.100
This is a most unfortunate affair, and will probably be much talked of, but we must stem

09:43:11.100 --> 09:43:17.500
the tide of malice, and pour into the wounded bosoms of each other the balm of sisterly

09:43:17.500 --> 09:43:18.520
consolation.

09:43:19.400 --> 09:43:24.340
Then, perceiving in Elizabeth no inclination of replying, she added,

09:43:25.120 --> 09:43:31.860
Unhappy as the event must be for Lydia, we may draw from it this useful lesson, that

09:43:31.860 --> 09:43:38.260
loss of virtue in a female is irretrievable, that one false step involves her in endless

09:43:38.260 --> 09:43:44.420
ruin, that her reputation is no less brittle than it is beautiful, and that she cannot

09:43:44.420 --> 09:43:49.320
be too much guarded in her behavior towards the undeserving of the other sex.

09:43:50.580 --> 09:43:55.940
Elizabeth lifted up her eyes in amazement, but was too much oppressed to make any reply.

09:43:56.940 --> 09:44:02.860
Mary, however, continued to console herself with such kind of moral extractions from the

09:44:02.860 --> 09:44:03.920
evil before them.

09:44:04.620 --> 09:44:10.340
In the afternoon the two elder Miss Bennet's were able to be for half an hour by themselves,

09:44:10.820 --> 09:44:16.640
and Elizabeth instantly availed herself of the opportunity of making any inquiries, which

09:44:16.640 --> 09:44:18.880
Jane was equally eager to satisfy.

09:44:20.020 --> 09:44:26.020
After joining in general lamentations over the dreadful sequel of this event, which Elizabeth

09:44:26.020 --> 09:44:31.120
considered as all but certain, and Miss Bennet could not assert to be wholly impossible,

09:44:31.610 --> 09:44:34.260
the former continued the subject by saying,

09:44:34.880 --> 09:44:39.920
But tell me all and everything about it which I have not already heard. Give me further

09:44:39.920 --> 09:44:45.320
particulars. What did Colonel Forster say? Had they no apprehension of anything before

09:44:45.320 --> 09:44:49.420
the elopement took place? They must have seen them together for ever.

09:44:50.640 --> 09:44:56.440
Colonel Forster did own that he had often suspected some partiality, especially on Lydia's

09:44:56.440 --> 09:45:02.660
side, but nothing to give him any alarm. I am so grieved for him. His behavior was

09:45:02.660 --> 09:45:09.380
attentive and kind to the utmost. He was coming to us in order to assure us of his concern

09:45:09.380 --> 09:45:15.060
before he had any idea of their not being gone to Scotland. When that apprehension first

09:45:15.060 --> 09:45:17.560
got abroad, it hastened his journey.

09:45:18.580 --> 09:45:22.740
And was Denny convinced that Wickham would not marry? Did he know of their intending

09:45:22.740 --> 09:45:26.300
to go off? Had Colonel Forster seen Denny himself?

09:45:27.280 --> 09:45:32.860
Yes, but when questioned by him, Denny denied knowing anything of their plans, and would

09:45:32.860 --> 09:45:37.900
not give his real opinion about it. He did not repeat his persuasion of their not marrying,

09:45:38.240 --> 09:45:42.740
and from that I am inclined to hope he might have been misunderstood before.

09:45:43.860 --> 09:45:48.600
Until Colonel Forster came himself, not one of you entertained a doubt, I suppose, of

09:45:48.600 --> 09:45:49.980
their being really married.

09:45:50.740 --> 09:45:56.020
How was it possible that such an idea could enter our brains? I felt a little uneasy,

09:45:56.540 --> 09:46:00.820
a little fearful of my sister's happiness with him in marriage, because I knew that

09:46:00.820 --> 09:46:05.900
his conduct had not been always quite right. My father and mother knew nothing of that.

09:46:06.180 --> 09:46:11.960
They only felt how imprudent a match it must be. Kitty then owned, with a very natural

09:46:11.960 --> 09:46:17.340
triumph, on knowing more than the rest of us, that in Lydia's last letter she had prepared

09:46:17.340 --> 09:46:22.380
her for such a step. She had known, it seems, of their being in love with each other many

09:46:22.380 --> 09:46:29.300
weeks. But not before they went to Brighton? No, I believe not. And did Colonel Forster

09:46:29.300 --> 09:46:33.300
appear to think well of Wickham himself? Does he know his real character?

09:46:34.140 --> 09:46:39.840
I must confess that he did not speak so well of Wickham as he formerly did. He believed

09:46:39.840 --> 09:46:46.060
him to be imprudent and extravagant, and since this sad affair has taken place, it is said

09:46:46.060 --> 09:46:53.140
that he left Merryton greatly in debt. But I hope this may be false. Oh, Jane, had we

09:46:53.140 --> 09:46:57.820
been less secret, had we told what we knew of him, this could not have happened.

09:46:58.940 --> 09:47:04.340
Perhaps it would have been better, replied her sister. But to expose the former faults

09:47:04.340 --> 09:47:09.620
of any person, without knowing what their present feelings were, seemed unjustifiable.

09:47:10.180 --> 09:47:16.040
We acted with the best intentions. Could Colonel Forster repeat the particulars of Lydia's

09:47:16.040 --> 09:47:22.320
note to his wife? He brought it with him for us to see. Jane then took it from her

09:47:22.320 --> 09:47:26.540
pocket-book, and gave it to Elizabeth. These were the contents.

09:47:27.560 --> 09:47:33.000
My dear Harriet, you will laugh when you know where I am gone, and I cannot help laughing

09:47:33.000 --> 09:47:38.580
myself at your surprise to-morrow morning, as soon as I am missed. I am going to Gretna

09:47:38.580 --> 09:47:43.580
Green, and if you cannot guess with who, I shall think you as simpleton, for there is

09:47:43.580 --> 09:47:48.880
but one man in the world I love, and he is an angel. I should never be happy without

09:47:48.880 --> 09:47:54.300
him, so think it no harm to be off. You need not send them word at Longbourn of my going,

09:47:54.480 --> 09:47:58.460
if you do not like it, for it will make the surprise the greater when I write to them

09:47:58.460 --> 09:48:04.700
and sign my name Lydia Wickham. What a good joke it will be! I can hardly write for laughing.

09:48:05.600 --> 09:48:10.420
Pray make my excuses to Pratt for not keeping my engagement and dancing with him to-night.

09:48:10.860 --> 09:48:14.880
Tell him I hope he will excuse me when he knows all, and tell him I will dance with

09:48:14.880 --> 09:48:20.040
him at the next ball we meet, with great pleasure. I shall send for my clothes when I get to

09:48:20.040 --> 09:48:24.800
Longbourn, but I wish you would tell Sally to mend a great slit in my worked muslin gown

09:48:24.800 --> 09:48:30.260
before they are packed up. Good-bye. Give my love to Colonel Forster. I hope you will

09:48:30.260 --> 09:48:34.760
drink to our good journey. Your affectionate friend, Lydia Bennet.

09:48:36.220 --> 09:48:42.540
Oh, thoughtless, thoughtless Lydia! cried Elizabeth when she had finished it. What a

09:48:42.540 --> 09:48:47.960
letter is this to be written at such a moment! But at least it shows that she was serious

09:48:47.960 --> 09:48:53.360
on the subject of their journey. Whatever he might afterwards persuade her to, it was

09:48:53.360 --> 09:48:59.980
not on her side a scheme of infamy. My poor father! How he must have felt it!

09:49:00.680 --> 09:49:07.020
I never saw anyone so shocked. He could not speak a word for full ten minutes. My mother

09:49:07.020 --> 09:49:11.100
was taken ill immediately, and the whole house in such confusion.

09:49:12.060 --> 09:49:17.900
Oh, Jane! cried Elizabeth. Was there a servant belonging to it who did not know the whole

09:49:17.900 --> 09:49:24.100
story before the end of the day? I do not know. I hope there was. But to be guarded

09:49:24.100 --> 09:49:29.760
at such a time is very difficult. My mother was in hysterics, and though I endeavoured

09:49:29.760 --> 09:49:35.220
to give her every assistance in my power, I am afraid I did not do so much as I might

09:49:35.220 --> 09:49:42.240
have done. But the horror of what might possibly happen almost took me from my faculties. Your

09:49:42.240 --> 09:49:47.600
attendance upon her has been too much for you. You do not look well. Oh, that I had

09:49:47.600 --> 09:49:52.440
been with you! You have had every care and anxiety upon yourself alone.

09:49:53.720 --> 09:49:59.240
Mary and Kitty have been very kind, and would have shared in every fatigue, I am sure. But

09:49:59.240 --> 09:50:05.140
I did not think it right for either of them. Kitty is slight and delicate, and Mary studies

09:50:05.140 --> 09:50:10.860
so much that her hours of repose should not be broken in on. My aunt Phillips came to

09:50:10.860 --> 09:50:15.780
Longbourn on Tuesday after my father went away, and was so good as to stay till Thursday

09:50:15.780 --> 09:50:21.920
with me. She was of great use and comfort to us all, and Lady Lucas has been very kind.

09:50:22.280 --> 09:50:27.380
She walked here on Wednesday morning to condole with us, and offered her services, or any

09:50:27.380 --> 09:50:30.160
of her daughters, if they should be of use to us.

09:50:30.840 --> 09:50:36.880
She had better have stayed at home, cried Elizabeth. Perhaps she meant well, but under

09:50:36.880 --> 09:50:42.280
such a misfortune as this, one cannot see too little of one's neighbours. Assistance

09:50:42.280 --> 09:50:47.980
is impossible, condolence insufferable. Let them triumph over us at a distance and be

09:50:47.980 --> 09:50:53.880
satisfied. She then proceeded to inquire into the measures which her father had intended

09:50:54.660 --> 09:50:57.960
while in town for the recovery of his daughter.

09:50:58.660 --> 09:51:04.760
He meant, I believe, replied Jane, to go to Epsom, the place where they last changed horses,

09:51:05.280 --> 09:51:10.860
see the postillians, and try, if anything, could be made out from them. His principal

09:51:10.860 --> 09:51:15.640
object must be to discover the number of the hackney-coach which took them from Clapham.

09:51:16.240 --> 09:51:20.860
It had come with a fare from London, and as he thought that the circumstance of a gentleman

09:51:20.860 --> 09:51:26.280
and a lady's removing from one carriage into another might be remarked, he meant to make

09:51:26.280 --> 09:51:31.680
inquiries at Clapham. If he could anyhow discover at what house the coachman had before set

09:51:31.680 --> 09:51:36.840
down his fare, he determined to make inquiries there, and hoped it might not be impossible

09:51:36.840 --> 09:51:42.480
to find out the stand and number of the coach. I do not know of any other designs that he

09:51:42.480 --> 09:51:48.220
had formed, but he was in such a hurry to be gone, and his spirit so greatly discomposed

09:51:48.220 --> 09:51:52.720
that I had difficulty in finding out even so much as this.

09:51:59.960 --> 09:52:04.520
The whole party were in hopes of a letter

09:52:04.520 --> 09:52:09.320
from Mr. Bennet the next morning, but the post came in without bringing a single line

09:52:09.320 --> 09:52:16.580
from him. His family knew him to be, on all common occasions, a most negligent and dilatory

09:52:16.580 --> 09:52:22.320
correspondent, but at such a time they had hoped for exertion. They were forced to conclude

09:52:22.320 --> 09:52:27.300
that he had no pleasing intelligence to send, but even of that they would have been glad

09:52:27.300 --> 09:52:33.780
to be certain. Mr. Gardiner had only waited for the letters before he set off. When he

09:52:33.780 --> 09:52:39.020
was gone they were certain at least of receiving constant information of what was going on,

09:52:39.460 --> 09:52:45.420
and their uncle promised, at parting, to prevail on Mr. Bennet to return to Longbourn as soon

09:52:45.420 --> 09:52:51.080
as he could, to the great consolation of his sister, who considered it as the only security

09:52:51.080 --> 09:52:57.240
for her husband's not being killed in a duel. Mrs. Gardiner and the children were to remain

09:52:57.240 --> 09:53:02.280
in Hertfordshire a few days longer, as the former thought her presence might be serviceable

09:53:02.280 --> 09:53:07.980
to her nieces. She shared in their attendance on Mrs. Bennet, and was a great comfort to

09:53:07.980 --> 09:53:13.760
them in their hours of freedom. Their other aunt, who visited them frequently and always,

09:53:13.760 --> 09:53:19.280
as she said, with the design of cheering and heartening them up, though as she never came

09:53:19.280 --> 09:53:25.700
without reporting some fresh instant of Wickham's extravagance or irregularity, she seldom went

09:53:25.700 --> 09:53:31.900
away without leaving them more dispirited than she found them. All Maryton seemed striving

09:53:31.900 --> 09:53:38.860
to blacken the man who, but three months before, had been almost an angel of light. He was

09:53:38.860 --> 09:53:44.420
declared to be in debt to every tradesman in the place, and his intrigues, all honoured

09:53:44.420 --> 09:53:51.000
with the title of seduction, had been extended into every tradesman's family. Everybody declared

09:53:51.000 --> 09:53:56.040
that he was the wickedest young man in the world, and everybody began to find out that

09:53:56.040 --> 09:54:01.260
they had always distrusted the appearance of his goodness. Elizabeth, though she did

09:54:01.260 --> 09:54:06.880
not credit above half of what was said, believed enough to make her former assurance of her

09:54:06.880 --> 09:54:13.000
sister's ruin more certain, and even Jane, who believed still less of it, became almost

09:54:13.000 --> 09:54:18.800
hopeless, more especially as the time was now come when, if they had gone to Scotland,

09:54:19.160 --> 09:54:24.800
which she had never before entirely despaired of, they must in all probability have gained

09:54:24.800 --> 09:54:26.000
some news of them.

09:54:27.280 --> 09:54:33.060
Mr. Gardiner left Longbourn on Sunday. On Tuesday his wife received a letter from him.

09:54:33.060 --> 09:54:38.560
It told them that, on his arrival, he had immediately found out his brother, and persuaded

09:54:38.560 --> 09:54:43.720
him to come to Grace Church Street, that Mr. Bennet had been to Epsom and Clapham before

09:54:43.720 --> 09:54:49.700
his arrival, but without gaining any satisfactory information, and that he was now determined

09:54:49.700 --> 09:54:54.840
to inquire at all the principal hotels in town, as Mr. Bennet thought it possible they

09:54:54.840 --> 09:55:00.680
might have gone to one of them on their first coming to London before they procured lodgings.

09:55:01.480 --> 09:55:07.000
Mr. Gardiner himself did not expect any success from this measure, but as his brother was

09:55:07.000 --> 09:55:13.240
eager in it, he meant to assist him in pursuing it. He added that Mr. Bennet seemed wholly

09:55:13.240 --> 09:55:17.780
disinclined at present to leave London, and promised to write again very soon.

09:55:18.720 --> 09:55:21.540
There was also a postscript to this effect.

09:55:22.360 --> 09:55:27.940
I have written to Colonel Forster to desire him to find out, if possible, from some of

09:55:27.940 --> 09:55:33.000
the young man's intimates in the regiment, whether Wickham has any relations or connections,

09:55:33.380 --> 09:55:38.380
who would be likely to know in what part of town he has now concealed himself. If there

09:55:38.380 --> 09:55:43.780
were anyone that one could apply to with a probability of gaining such a clue as that,

09:55:44.040 --> 09:55:50.080
it might be of essential consequence. At present we have nothing to guide us. Colonel Forster

09:55:50.080 --> 09:55:56.160
will, I dare say, do everything in his power to satisfy us on this head. But, on second

09:55:56.160 --> 09:56:00.900
thoughts, perhaps Lizzie could tell us what relations he has now living better than any

09:56:00.900 --> 09:56:07.340
other person. Elizabeth was at no loss to understand from where this deference to her

09:56:07.340 --> 09:56:13.080
authority proceeded, but it was not in her power to give any information of so satisfactory

09:56:13.080 --> 09:56:18.320
a nature as the compliment deserved. She had never heard of his having had any relations

09:56:18.320 --> 09:56:24.580
except a father and mother, both of whom had been dead many years. It was possible, however,

09:56:24.580 --> 09:56:29.660
that some of his companions, in the blank sheer, might be able to give more information,

09:56:30.200 --> 09:56:35.880
and though she was not very sanguine in expecting it, the application was a something to look

09:56:35.880 --> 09:56:42.260
forward to. Every day at Longbourn was now a day of anxiety, but the most anxious part

09:56:42.260 --> 09:56:48.040
of each was when the post was expected. The arrival of letters was the grand object of

09:56:48.040 --> 09:56:53.920
every morning's impatience. Through letters, whatever of good or bad was to be told would

09:56:53.920 --> 09:56:59.300
be communicated, and every succeeding day was expected to bring some news of importance.

09:57:00.020 --> 09:57:05.520
But before they heard again from Mr. Gardiner, a letter arrived for their father from a different

09:57:05.520 --> 09:57:11.680
quarter, from Mr. Collins, which, as Jane had received directions to open all that came

09:57:11.680 --> 09:57:18.180
for him in his absence, she accordingly read, and Elizabeth, who knew what curiosities his

09:57:18.180 --> 09:57:23.720
letters always were, looked over her and read it likewise. It was as follows.

09:57:24.800 --> 09:57:31.860
My dear sir, I feel myself called upon by our relationship and my situation in life

09:57:31.860 --> 09:57:37.860
to condole with you on the grievous affliction you are now suffering under, of which we were

09:57:37.860 --> 09:57:45.690
yesterday informed by a letter from Hartfordshire. Be assured, my dear sir, that Mrs. Collins and

09:57:45.690 --> 09:57:51.910
myself sincerely sympathise with you and all your respectable family in your present distress,

09:57:52.430 --> 09:57:59.550
which must be of the bitterest kind, because proceeding from a cause which no time can remove.

09:58:00.470 --> 09:58:06.490
No arguments shall be wanting on my part that can alleviate so severe a misfortune,

09:58:06.930 --> 09:58:13.090
or that may comfort you under a circumstance that must be of all others the most afflicting

09:58:13.090 --> 09:58:18.890
to a parent's mind. The death of your daughter would have been a blessing in comparison to

09:58:18.890 --> 09:58:25.850
this, and it is the more to be lamented, because there is reason to suppose, as my dear Charlotte

09:58:25.850 --> 09:58:32.430
informs me, that this licentiousness of behaviour in your daughter has proceeded from a faulty

09:58:32.430 --> 09:58:38.630
degree of indulgence, though, at the same time, for the consolation of yourself and

09:58:38.630 --> 09:58:45.190
Mrs. Bennet, I am inclined to think that her own disposition must be naturally bad, or

09:58:45.190 --> 09:58:52.010
she could not be guilty of such an enormity at so early an age. Howsoever that may be,

09:58:52.330 --> 09:58:57.510
you are grievously to be pitied, in which opinion I am not only joined by Mrs. Collins,

09:58:57.970 --> 09:59:04.250
but likewise by Lady Catherine and her daughter, to whom I have related the affair. They agree

09:59:04.250 --> 09:59:10.030
with me in apprehending that this false step in one daughter will be injurious to the fortunes

09:59:10.030 --> 09:59:16.310
of all the others, for who, as Lady Catherine herself condescendingly says, will connect

09:59:16.310 --> 09:59:23.910
themselves with such a family. And this consideration leads me moreover to reflect, with augmented

09:59:23.910 --> 09:59:30.490
satisfaction, on a certain event of last November, for had it been otherwise, I must have been

09:59:30.490 --> 09:59:36.770
involved in all your sorrow and disgrace. Let me then advise you, dear sir, to console

09:59:36.770 --> 09:59:41.850
yourself as much as possible, to throw off your unworthy child from your affection for

09:59:41.850 --> 09:59:49.890
ever, and leave her to reap the fruits of her own heinous offence. I am, dear sir, etc.,

09:59:49.890 --> 09:59:57.210
etc. Mr. Gardiner did not write again till he had received an answer from Colonel Forster,

09:59:57.210 --> 10:00:02.690
and then he had nothing of a pleasant nature to send. It was not known that Wickham had

10:00:02.690 --> 10:00:07.530
a single relationship with whom he kept up any connection, and it was certain that he

10:00:07.530 --> 10:00:13.910
had no near one living. His former acquaintances had been numerous, but since he had been in

10:00:13.910 --> 10:00:18.770
the militia, it did not appear that he was on terms of particular friendship with any

10:00:18.770 --> 10:00:24.090
of them. There was no one, therefore, who could be pointed out as likely to give any

10:00:24.090 --> 10:00:29.810
news of him, and in the wretched state of his own finances, there was a very powerful

10:00:29.810 --> 10:00:35.590
motive for secrecy, in addition to his fear of discovery by Lydia's relations, for it

10:00:35.590 --> 10:00:41.430
had just transpired that he had left gaming debts behind him to a very considerable amount.

10:00:42.350 --> 10:00:46.950
Colonel Forster believed that more than a thousand pounds would be necessary to clear

10:00:46.950 --> 10:00:53.230
his expenses at Brighton. He owed a good deal in town, but his debts of honor were still

10:00:53.230 --> 10:00:58.950
more formidable. Mr. Gardiner did not attempt to conceal these particulars from the Long

10:00:58.950 --> 10:01:02.050
Born family. Jane heard them with horror.

10:01:02.590 --> 10:01:08.810
A gamester, she cried. This is wholly unexpected. I had not an idea of it.

10:01:09.790 --> 10:01:14.370
Mr. Gardiner added in his letter that they might expect to see their father at home on

10:01:14.370 --> 10:01:20.310
the following day, which was Saturday. Rendered spiritless by the ill success of all their

10:01:20.310 --> 10:01:25.710
endeavors, he had yielded to his brother-in-law's entreaty that he would return to his family,

10:01:26.050 --> 10:01:30.670
and leave it to him to do whatever occasion might suggest to be advisable for continuing

10:01:30.670 --> 10:01:36.190
their pursuit. When Mrs. Bennet was told of this, she did not express so much satisfaction

10:01:36.190 --> 10:01:41.470
as her children expected, considering what her anxiety for his life had been before.

10:01:42.390 --> 10:01:47.950
What, is he coming home and without poor Lydia? she cried. Sure, he will not leave London

10:01:47.950 --> 10:01:52.370
before he has found them. Who is to fight Wickham and make him marry her if he comes

10:01:52.370 --> 10:01:56.830
away? As Mrs. Gardiner began to wish to be at home,

10:01:57.170 --> 10:02:02.150
it was settled that she and the children should go to London at the same time that Mr. Bennet

10:02:02.150 --> 10:02:07.010
came from it. The coach, therefore, took them the first stage of their journey, and brought

10:02:07.010 --> 10:02:12.830
its master back to Long Born. Mrs. Gardiner went away in all the perplexity

10:02:12.830 --> 10:02:17.490
about Elizabeth and her Derbyshire friend that had attended her from that part of the

10:02:17.490 --> 10:02:23.030
world. His name had never been voluntarily mentioned before them by her niece, and the

10:02:23.030 --> 10:02:28.650
kind of half-expectation which Mrs. Gardiner had formed of their being followed by a letter

10:02:28.650 --> 10:02:34.710
from him had ended in nothing. Elizabeth had received none since her return that could

10:02:34.710 --> 10:02:39.410
come from Pemberley. The present unhappy state of the family rendered

10:02:39.410 --> 10:02:45.350
any other excuse for the lowness of her spirits unnecessary. Nothing, therefore, could be

10:02:45.350 --> 10:02:51.210
fairly conjectured from that, though Elizabeth, who was by this time tolerably well acquainted

10:02:51.210 --> 10:02:57.090
with her own feelings, was perfectly aware that, had she known nothing of Darcy, she

10:02:57.090 --> 10:03:02.370
could have borne the dread of Lydia's infamy somewhat better. It would have spared her,

10:03:02.370 --> 10:03:08.990
she thought, one sleepless night out of two. When Mr. Bennet arrived, he had all the appearance

10:03:08.990 --> 10:03:14.270
of his usual philosophic composure. He said as little as he had ever been in the habit

10:03:14.270 --> 10:03:19.750
of saying, made no mention of the business that had taken him away, and it was some time

10:03:19.750 --> 10:03:24.950
before his daughters had courage to speak of it. It was not till the afternoon when

10:03:24.950 --> 10:03:30.890
he had joined them at tea that Elizabeth ventured to introduce the subject, and then, on her

10:03:30.890 --> 10:03:36.410
briefly expressing her sorrow for what he must have endured, he replied, Say nothing

10:03:36.410 --> 10:03:41.890
of that. Who should suffer but myself? It has been my own doing, and I ought to feel

10:03:41.890 --> 10:03:42.290
it.

10:03:42.890 --> 10:03:48.910
"'You must not be too severe upon yourself,' replied Elizabeth. "'You may well warn me

10:03:48.910 --> 10:03:55.570
against such an evil. Human nature is so prone to fall into it.' No, Lizzie, let me once

10:03:55.570 --> 10:04:00.770
in my life feel how much I have been to blame. I am not afraid of being overpowered by the

10:04:00.770 --> 10:04:03.210
impression. It will pass away soon enough.'

10:04:04.350 --> 10:04:06.750
"'Do you suppose them to be in London?'

10:04:06.750 --> 10:04:10.350
"'Yes. Where else can they be so well concealed?'

10:04:10.350 --> 10:04:13.490
"'And Lydia used to want to go to London,' added Kitty.'

10:04:14.550 --> 10:04:19.910
"'She is happy then,' said her father dryly, and her residence there will probably be of

10:04:19.910 --> 10:04:20.770
some duration.'

10:04:21.890 --> 10:04:28.230
Then, after short silence, he continued, "'Lizzie, I bear you no ill will for being justified

10:04:28.230 --> 10:04:33.670
in your advice to me last May, which, considering the event, shows some greatness of mind.'

10:04:34.870 --> 10:04:38.690
They were interrupted by Miss Bennet, who came to fetch her mother's tea.

10:04:39.450 --> 10:04:45.290
"'This is a parade,' he cried, "'which does one good. It gives such an elegance to misfortune.

10:04:46.030 --> 10:04:50.890
Another day I will do the same. I will sit in my library, in my nightcap and powdering

10:04:50.890 --> 10:04:56.310
gown, and give as much trouble as I can. Or perhaps I may defer it till Kitty runs away.'

10:04:57.210 --> 10:05:02.610
"'I am not going to run away, Papa,' said Kitty fretfully. If I should ever go to Brighton,

10:05:02.870 --> 10:05:04.230
I would behave better than Lydia.'

10:05:05.270 --> 10:05:10.390
"'You go to Brighton. I would not trust you so near it as you spawn for fifty pounds.

10:05:11.030 --> 10:05:16.010
No, Kitty, I have at least learnt to be cautious, and you will feel the effects of it.

10:05:16.650 --> 10:05:20.990
No officer is ever to enter into my house again, nor even to pass through the village.

10:05:21.670 --> 10:05:25.910
Balls will be absolutely prohibited unless you stand up with one of your sisters.

10:05:26.310 --> 10:05:29.150
And you are never to stir out of doors till you can prove

10:05:29.150 --> 10:05:32.550
that you have spent ten minutes of every day in a rational manner.'

10:05:33.870 --> 10:05:38.130
Kitty, who took all these threats in a serious light, began to cry.

10:05:39.410 --> 10:05:42.870
"'Well, well,' said he, "'do not make yourself unhappy.

10:05:43.530 --> 10:05:48.590
If you are a good girl for the next ten years, I will take you to a review at the end of them.'

10:06:23.690 --> 10:06:28.870
Two days after Mr. Bennet's return, as Jane and Elizabeth were walking together in the

10:06:28.870 --> 10:06:34.150
shrubbery behind the house, they saw the housekeeper coming towards them, and, concluding that

10:06:34.150 --> 10:06:37.150
she came to call them to their mother, went forward to meet her.

10:06:37.830 --> 10:06:42.170
But instead of the expected summons, when they approached her she said to Miss Bennet,

10:06:42.710 --> 10:06:46.870
"'I beg your pardon, madam, for interrupting you, but I was in the hopes you might have

10:06:46.870 --> 10:06:50.090
got some good news from town, so I took the liberty of coming to ask.'

10:06:52.410 --> 10:06:53.590
"'What do you mean, Hill?

10:06:53.930 --> 10:06:55.510
We have heard nothing from town.'

10:06:56.730 --> 10:07:01.770
"'Dear madam,' cried Mrs. Hill, in great astonishment, "'don't you know there is an

10:07:01.770 --> 10:07:04.030
express come for Master, from Mr. Gardiner?

10:07:04.710 --> 10:07:10.610
He has been here this half hour, and Master has had a letter.'"

10:07:10.610 --> 10:07:14.610
Away ran the girls, too eager to get in to have time for speech.

10:07:15.830 --> 10:07:20.570
They ran through the vestibule into the breakfast-room, from thence to the library.

10:07:21.010 --> 10:07:24.770
Their father was in neither, and they were on the point of seeking him upstairs with

10:07:24.770 --> 10:07:29.930
their mother, when they were met by the butler who said, "'If you are looking for my master,

10:07:30.070 --> 10:07:35.230
ma'am, he is walking towards the little cops.'"

10:07:35.770 --> 10:07:40.350
Upon this information they instantly passed through the hall once more, and ran across

10:07:40.350 --> 10:07:45.310
the lawn after their father, who was deliberately pursuing his way towards the small wood on

10:07:45.310 --> 10:07:46.670
one side of the paddock.

10:07:48.970 --> 10:07:53.790
Jane, who was not so light nor so much in the habit of running as Elizabeth, soon lagged

10:07:53.790 --> 10:07:59.970
behind, while her sister, panting for breath, came up with him, and eagerly cried out, "'Oh,

10:07:59.990 --> 10:08:00.450
papa!

10:08:00.910 --> 10:08:01.550
What news?

10:08:01.610 --> 10:08:02.270
What news?

10:08:02.890 --> 10:08:05.670
Have you heard from my uncle?'

10:08:06.290 --> 10:08:08.910
"'Yes, I have had a letter from him by express.'

10:08:09.750 --> 10:08:13.810
"'Well, and what news does it bring, good or bad?'

10:08:13.810 --> 10:08:19.630
"'What is there of good to be expected?' said he, taking the letter from his pocket.

10:08:20.130 --> 10:08:24.450
"'But perhaps he would like to read it.'

10:08:25.090 --> 10:08:27.250
Elizabeth impatiently caught it from his hand.

10:08:27.910 --> 10:08:29.270
Jane now came up.

10:08:30.430 --> 10:08:38.510
"'Read it aloud,' said the father, for I hardly know myself what it is about.'

10:08:38.510 --> 10:08:42.010
Grace Church Street, Monday, August 2.

10:08:43.390 --> 10:08:49.310
My dear brother, at last I am able to send you some tidings of my niece, and such as,

10:08:49.310 --> 10:08:52.150
upon the whole, I hope it will give you satisfaction.

10:08:54.390 --> 10:08:59.170
Soon after you left me on Saturday, I was fortunate enough to find out in what part

10:08:59.170 --> 10:09:00.290
of London they were.

10:09:01.190 --> 10:09:05.410
The particulars I reserved till we meet, it is enough to know they are discovered.

10:09:06.370 --> 10:09:08.190
"'I have seen them both.'

10:09:08.190 --> 10:09:13.330
"'Then it is as I always hoped,' cried Jane, they are married.'

10:09:13.950 --> 10:09:15.510
"'I have seen them both.

10:09:15.830 --> 10:09:21.890
They are not married, nor can I find there was any intention of being so, but if you

10:09:21.890 --> 10:09:26.810
are willing to perform the engagements which I have ventured to make on your side, I hope

10:09:26.810 --> 10:09:28.630
it will not be long before they are.

10:09:30.870 --> 10:09:36.370
"'All that is required of you is to assure to your daughter by settlement her equal

10:09:36.370 --> 10:09:41.350
share of the five thousand pounds secured among your children after the disease of yourself

10:09:41.350 --> 10:09:47.090
and my sister, and moreover to enter into an engagement of allowing her, during your

10:09:47.090 --> 10:09:49.930
life, one hundred pounds per annum.

10:09:51.230 --> 10:09:56.510
These are conditions which, considering everything, I had no hesitation in complying with, as

10:09:56.510 --> 10:09:59.410
far as I thought myself privileged, for you.

10:10:01.230 --> 10:10:05.610
I shall send this by express that no time may be lost in bringing me your answer.

10:10:06.790 --> 10:10:11.890
You will easily comprehend from these particulars that Mr. Wickham's circumstances are not so

10:10:11.890 --> 10:10:14.130
hopeless as they are generally believed to be.

10:10:15.250 --> 10:10:19.870
The world has been deceived in that respect, and I am happy to say there will be some little

10:10:19.870 --> 10:10:25.050
money, even when all his debts are discharged, to settle on my niece, in addition to her

10:10:25.050 --> 10:10:25.770
own fortune.

10:10:27.810 --> 10:10:32.910
If, as I conclude will be the case, you send me full powers to act in your name throughout

10:10:32.910 --> 10:10:38.390
the whole of this business, I will immediately give directions to Hagerston for preparing

10:10:38.390 --> 10:10:39.370
a proper settlement.

10:10:40.810 --> 10:10:45.390
There will not be the smallest occasion for you coming to town again, therefore stay quiet

10:10:45.390 --> 10:10:48.290
at Longbourn and depend on my diligence and care.

10:10:49.990 --> 10:10:54.450
Send back your answer as fast as you can, and be careful to write explicitly.

10:10:56.210 --> 10:11:01.130
We have judged it best that my niece should be married from this house, of which I hope

10:11:01.130 --> 10:11:01.930
you will approve.

10:11:02.790 --> 10:11:04.050
She comes to us to-day.

10:11:04.690 --> 10:11:07.890
I shall write again as soon as anything more is determined on.

10:11:08.590 --> 10:11:10.430
Yours, etc., Edward Gardiner.

10:11:11.830 --> 10:11:17.990
Is it possible, cried Elizabeth when she had finished, can it be possible that he will

10:11:17.990 --> 10:11:18.830
marry her?

10:11:20.690 --> 10:11:25.230
Wickham is not so undeserving, then, as we thought him, said her sister.

10:11:25.490 --> 10:11:27.830
My dear father, I congratulate you.

10:11:28.590 --> 10:11:31.450
And have you answered the letter, cried Elizabeth?

10:11:32.390 --> 10:11:34.470
No, but it must be done soon.

10:11:36.130 --> 10:11:40.250
Most earnestly did she then entreat to him to lose no more time before he wrote.

10:11:40.830 --> 10:11:45.210
Oh, my dear father, she cried, come back and write immediately.

10:11:45.930 --> 10:11:49.390
Consider how important every moment is in such a case.

10:11:51.570 --> 10:11:55.630
Let me write for you, said Jane, if you dislike the trouble yourself.

10:11:56.590 --> 10:12:00.410
I dislike it very much, he replied, but it must be done.

10:12:01.990 --> 10:12:06.830
And so saying, he turned back with them, and walked towards the house.

10:12:08.390 --> 10:12:14.930
And may I ask, said Elizabeth, but the terms, I suppose, must be complied with.

10:12:16.210 --> 10:12:17.170
Complied with?

10:12:17.770 --> 10:12:20.370
I am only ashamed of his asking so little.

10:12:21.750 --> 10:12:25.910
And they must marry, yet he is such a man.

10:12:27.330 --> 10:12:28.690
Yes, yes, they must marry.

10:12:29.110 --> 10:12:30.730
There is nothing else to be done.

10:12:32.470 --> 10:12:35.430
But there are two things that I want very much to know.

10:12:35.430 --> 10:12:40.730
One is, how much money your uncle has laid down to bring it about, and the other, how

10:12:40.730 --> 10:12:42.230
am I ever to pay him?

10:12:44.110 --> 10:12:49.370
Money, my uncle, cried Jane, what do you mean, sir?

10:12:50.470 --> 10:12:56.570
I mean that no man in his senses would marry Lydia on so slight a temptation as one hundred

10:12:56.570 --> 10:12:59.410
a year during my life, and fifty after I am gone.

10:13:00.290 --> 10:13:05.470
That is very true, said Elizabeth, though it had not occurred to me before.

10:13:06.530 --> 10:13:09.470
His debts to be discharged, and something still to remain.

10:13:10.490 --> 10:13:12.910
Oh, it must be my uncle's doings.

10:13:13.030 --> 10:13:16.470
Generous good man, I am afraid he has distressed himself.

10:13:17.570 --> 10:13:19.850
A small sum could not do all this.

10:13:22.590 --> 10:13:27.770
No, said her father, wiccums a fool if he takes her with a farthing less than ten thousand

10:13:27.770 --> 10:13:28.090
pounds.

10:13:29.170 --> 10:13:33.470
I should be sorry to think so ill of him in the very beginning of our relationship.

10:13:36.230 --> 10:13:39.210
Ten thousand pounds, heaven forbid!

10:13:40.650 --> 10:13:43.090
How is half such a sum to be repaid?

10:13:45.710 --> 10:13:51.310
Mr. Bennet made no answer, and each of them, deep in thought, continued silent till they

10:13:51.310 --> 10:13:52.350
reached the house.

10:13:53.950 --> 10:13:59.270
Their father then went on to the library to write, and the girls walked into the breakfast

10:13:59.270 --> 10:13:59.730
room.

10:14:01.350 --> 10:14:07.010
And they are really to be married, cried Elizabeth, as soon as they were by themselves.

10:14:08.310 --> 10:14:10.090
How strange this is!

10:14:10.630 --> 10:14:16.230
And for this we are to be thankful, that they should marry, small as is their chance of

10:14:16.230 --> 10:14:18.630
happiness, and wretched as is his character.

10:14:18.630 --> 10:14:20.450
We are forced to rejoice.

10:14:21.050 --> 10:14:21.890
O Lydia!

10:14:24.370 --> 10:14:30.650
I comfort myself with thinking, replied Jane, that he certainly would not marry Lydia if

10:14:30.650 --> 10:14:32.690
he had not a real regard for her.

10:14:33.630 --> 10:14:39.070
Though our kind uncle has done something towards clearing him, I cannot believe that ten thousand

10:14:39.070 --> 10:14:41.650
pounds, or anything like it, has been advanced.

10:14:42.490 --> 10:14:45.330
He has children of his own, and may have more.

10:14:45.330 --> 10:14:48.350
How could he spare half ten thousand pounds?

10:14:50.270 --> 10:14:55.630
If we were ever able to learn what Wickham's debts have been, said Elizabeth, and how much

10:14:55.630 --> 10:15:00.510
is settled on his side on our sister, we shall exactly know what Mr. Gardiner has done for

10:15:00.510 --> 10:15:03.350
them, because Wickham has not sixpence of his own.

10:15:04.270 --> 10:15:07.190
The kindness of my uncle and aunt can never be requited.

10:15:08.690 --> 10:15:13.730
Their taking her home, and affording her their personal protection and countenance, is such

10:15:13.730 --> 10:15:18.690
a sacrifice to her advantage, as years of gratitude cannot enough acknowledge.

10:15:20.270 --> 10:15:22.470
By this time she is actually with them.

10:15:23.050 --> 10:15:27.750
If such goodness does not make her miserable now, she will never deserve to be happy.

10:15:28.790 --> 10:15:31.870
What a meeting for her when she first sees my aunt!

10:15:33.670 --> 10:15:37.990
We must endeavour to forget all that has passed on either side, said Jane.

10:15:38.670 --> 10:15:40.890
I hope and trust they will yet be happy.

10:15:41.870 --> 10:15:46.690
His consenting to marry her is a proof, I will believe, that he has come to a right

10:15:46.690 --> 10:15:47.430
way of thinking.

10:15:49.210 --> 10:15:54.010
Their mutual affection will steady them, and I flatter myself they will settle so quietly

10:15:54.010 --> 10:15:59.230
and live in so rational a manner as may in time make their past imprudence forgotten.

10:16:01.250 --> 10:16:07.410
Their conduct has been such, replied Elizabeth, as neither you nor I nor anybody can ever

10:16:07.410 --> 10:16:07.890
forget.

10:16:08.710 --> 10:16:11.050
It is useless to talk of it.

10:16:13.910 --> 10:16:18.730
It now occurred to the girls that their mother was in all likelihood perfectly ignorant of

10:16:18.730 --> 10:16:19.570
what had happened.

10:16:20.510 --> 10:16:25.270
They went to the library, therefore, and asked their father whether he would not wish them

10:16:25.270 --> 10:16:26.470
to make it known to her.

10:16:27.070 --> 10:16:30.890
He was writing, and, without raising his head, coolly replied,

10:16:31.470 --> 10:16:33.150
Just as you please.

10:16:35.390 --> 10:16:37.670
May we take my uncle's letter to read to her?

10:16:38.650 --> 10:16:40.790
Take whatever you like, and get away!

10:16:44.250 --> 10:16:48.410
Elizabeth took the letter from his writing-table, and they went upstairs together.

10:16:49.930 --> 10:16:52.170
Mary and Kitty were both with Mrs. Bennet.

10:16:52.630 --> 10:16:55.390
One communication would, therefore, do for all.

10:16:56.370 --> 10:17:00.250
After a slight preparation for good news, the letter was read aloud.

10:17:01.470 --> 10:17:03.950
Mrs. Bennet could hardly contain herself.

10:17:05.130 --> 10:17:10.930
As soon as Jane had read Mr. Gardiner's hope of Lydia's being soon married, her joy burst

10:17:10.930 --> 10:17:14.730
forth, and every following sentence added to its exuberance.

10:17:16.070 --> 10:17:21.650
She was now in an irritation as violent from delight as she had ever been fidgety from

10:17:21.650 --> 10:17:23.230
alarm and vexation.

10:17:24.830 --> 10:17:27.790
To know that her daughter would be married was enough.

10:17:28.670 --> 10:17:34.970
She was disturbed by no fear for her felicity, nor humbled by any remembrance of her misconduct.

10:17:37.390 --> 10:17:39.870
My dear, dear Lydia! she cried.

10:17:40.730 --> 10:17:42.290
This is delightful indeed.

10:17:42.650 --> 10:17:43.750
She will be married.

10:17:43.930 --> 10:17:45.070
I shall see her again.

10:17:45.250 --> 10:17:47.030
She will be married at sixteen!

10:17:47.650 --> 10:17:49.130
My good, kind brother!

10:17:49.270 --> 10:17:50.790
I knew how it would be.

10:17:50.790 --> 10:17:52.890
I knew he would manage everything.

10:17:53.650 --> 10:17:56.810
How I longed to see her, and to see dear Wickham too!

10:17:57.370 --> 10:17:58.990
But the clothes, the wedding clothes!

10:18:00.450 --> 10:18:03.050
I will write to my sister Gardiner about them directly.

10:18:03.510 --> 10:18:07.010
Lizzy, my dear, run down to your father and ask him how much he will give her.

10:18:07.130 --> 10:18:08.850
Stay, stay, I will go myself.

10:18:09.530 --> 10:18:10.870
Ring the bell, Kitty, for Hill.

10:18:11.270 --> 10:18:13.010
I will put on my things in a moment.

10:18:13.550 --> 10:18:14.750
My dear, dear Lydia!

10:18:15.010 --> 10:18:17.370
How merry we shall be together when we meet!

10:18:20.150 --> 10:18:25.090
Her eldest daughter endeavoured to give some relief to the violence of these transports,

10:18:25.190 --> 10:18:29.710
by leading her thoughts to the obligations which Mr. Gardiner's behaviour laid them all

10:18:29.710 --> 10:18:30.170
under.

10:18:31.870 --> 10:18:37.670
For we must attribute this happy conclusion, she added, in a great measure to his kindness.

10:18:38.270 --> 10:18:43.130
We are persuaded that he has pledged himself to assist Mr. Wickham with money.

10:18:44.730 --> 10:18:48.210
Well, cried her mother, it is all very right.

10:18:48.650 --> 10:18:50.630
Who should do it but her own uncle?

10:18:51.530 --> 10:18:56.390
If he had not had a family of his own, I and my children must have had all his money, you

10:18:56.390 --> 10:19:01.230
know, and it is the first time we have ever had anything from him, except a few presents.

10:19:02.270 --> 10:19:04.030
Well, I am so happy!

10:19:04.590 --> 10:19:07.070
In a short time I shall have a daughter married.

10:19:07.670 --> 10:19:10.150
Mrs. Wickham, how well it sounds!

10:19:10.150 --> 10:19:12.790
And she was only sixteen last June.

10:19:13.530 --> 10:19:17.210
My dear Jane, I am in such a flutter that I am sure I can't write.

10:19:17.930 --> 10:19:19.970
So I will dictate, and you will write for me.

10:19:20.490 --> 10:19:24.570
We will settle with your father about the money afterwards, but the things should be

10:19:24.570 --> 10:19:25.530
ordered immediately.

10:19:28.710 --> 10:19:33.930
She was then proceeding to all the particulars of Calico, Muslin, and Cambric, and would

10:19:33.930 --> 10:19:36.630
shortly have dictated some very plentiful orders.

10:19:36.630 --> 10:19:42.150
Had not Jane, though with some difficulty, persuaded her to wait till her father was

10:19:42.150 --> 10:19:43.370
at leisure to be consulted.

10:19:44.970 --> 10:19:50.350
One day's delay, she observed, would be of small importance, and her mother was too happy

10:19:50.350 --> 10:19:52.330
to be quite so obstinate as usual.

10:19:53.330 --> 10:19:55.410
Other schemes too came into her head.

10:19:56.890 --> 10:20:02.130
I will go to Meryton, said she, as soon as I am dressed, and tell the good, good news

10:20:02.130 --> 10:20:03.250
to my sister Phillips.

10:20:03.930 --> 10:20:07.810
And as I come back, I can call on Lady Lucas and Mrs. Long.

10:20:08.970 --> 10:20:11.270
Kitty, run down and order the carriage.

10:20:11.970 --> 10:20:15.070
An airing would do me a great deal of good, I am sure.

10:20:15.990 --> 10:20:18.430
Girls, can I do anything for you in Meryton?

10:20:19.050 --> 10:20:22.690
Oh, here comes Hill, my dear Hill, have you heard the good news?

10:20:23.450 --> 10:20:27.890
Miss Lydia is going to be married, and you shall all have a bowl of punch to make merry

10:20:27.890 --> 10:20:28.650
at her wedding.

10:20:32.150 --> 10:20:35.050
Mrs. Hill began instantly to express her joy.

10:20:35.990 --> 10:20:41.630
Elizabeth received her congratulations amongst the rest, and then, sick of this folly, took

10:20:41.630 --> 10:20:44.770
refuge in her own room, that she might think with freedom.

10:20:47.570 --> 10:20:53.630
Poor Lydia's situation must at best be bad enough, but that it was no worse she had need

10:20:53.630 --> 10:20:54.370
to be thankful.

10:20:54.990 --> 10:21:02.150
She felt it so, and though, in looking forward, neither rational happiness nor worldly prosperity

10:21:02.150 --> 10:21:07.750
could be justly expected for her sister, in looking back to what they had feared only

10:21:07.750 --> 10:21:11.710
two hours ago, she felt all the advantages of what they had gained.

10:21:37.850 --> 10:21:51.470
Mr. Bennet had very often wished before this period of his life that, instead of spending his whole income, he had laid by an annual sum for the better provision of his children and of his wife if she survived him.

10:21:52.050 --> 10:22:02.630
He now wished it more than ever. Had he done his duty in that respect, Lydia need not have been indebted to her uncle, for whatever of honor or credit could now be purchased for her.

10:22:03.550 --> 10:22:11.790
The satisfaction of prevailing on one of the most worthless young men in Great Britain to be her husband might then have rested in its proper place.

10:22:12.830 --> 10:22:26.570
He was seriously concerned that a cause of so little advantage to anyone should be forwarded at the sole expense of his brother-in-law, and he was determined, if possible, to find out the extent of his assistance, and to discharge the obligation as soon as he could.

10:22:28.570 --> 10:22:35.270
When first Mr. Bennet had married, economy was held to be perfectly useless, for, of course, they were to have a son.

10:22:36.190 --> 10:22:44.430
The son was to join in cutting off the entail, as soon as he should be of age, and the widow and younger children would by that means be provided for.

10:22:45.230 --> 10:22:54.250
Five daughters successively entered the world, and yet the son was to come, and Mrs. Bennet, for many years after Lydia's birth, had been certain that he would.

10:22:54.990 --> 10:22:59.470
This event had at last been despaired of, but it was then too late to be saving.

10:23:00.390 --> 10:23:06.830
Mrs. Bennet had no turn for economy, and her husband's love of independence had alone prevented their exceeding their income.

10:23:08.530 --> 10:23:17.170
Five thousand pounds was settled by marriage articles on Mrs. Bennet and the children, but in what proportions it should be divided amongst the latter depended on the will of the parents.

10:23:17.730 --> 10:23:26.170
This was one point, with regard to Lydia, at least, which was now to be settled, and Mr. Bennet could have no hesitation in acceding to the proposal before him.

10:23:27.050 --> 10:23:39.370
In terms of grateful acknowledgement for the kindness of his brother, though expressed most concisely, he then delivered on paper his perfect approbation of all that was done, and his willingness to fulfill the engagements that had been made for him.

10:23:39.850 --> 10:23:48.890
He had never before supposed that, could Wickham be prevailed on to marry his daughter, it would be done with so little inconvenience to himself as by the present arrangement.

10:23:49.750 --> 10:23:54.070
He would scarcely be ten pounds a year the loser by the hundred that was to be paid for them.

10:23:54.470 --> 10:24:04.030
For, let with her board and pocket allowance, and the continual presence in money which passed to her through her mother's hands, Lydia's expenses had been very little within that sum.

10:24:06.310 --> 10:24:15.690
That it would be done with such trifling exertion on his side, too, was another very welcome surprise, for his wish at present was to have as little trouble in the business as possible.

10:24:16.310 --> 10:24:23.170
When the first transports of rage which had produced his activity in seeking her were over, he naturally returned to old's former indolence.

10:24:23.950 --> 10:24:30.030
His letter was soon dispatched, for, though dilatory in entertaining king business, he was quick in its execution.

10:24:30.030 --> 10:24:36.970
He begged to know further particulars of what he was indebted to his brother, but was too angry with Lydia to send any message to her.

10:24:38.150 --> 10:24:42.310
The good news spread quickly through the house, and with proportionate speed through the neighborhood.

10:24:42.890 --> 10:24:44.990
It was borne in the latter with decent philosophy.

10:24:45.450 --> 10:24:51.030
To be sure it would have been far more for the advantage of conversation had Miss Lydia Bennet come upon the town.

10:24:51.670 --> 10:24:56.130
Or, as the happiest alternative, been secluded from the world in some distant farmhouse.

10:24:56.690 --> 10:25:05.010
But there was much to be talked of in marrying her, and the good-natured wishes for her well-doing, which had proceeded before from all the spiteful ladies in Meryton,

10:25:05.590 --> 10:25:11.870
lost but a little of their spirit in this change of circumstances, because with such a husband her misery was considered certain.

10:25:12.750 --> 10:25:20.370
It was a fortnight since Mrs. Bennet had been downstairs, but on this happy day she again took her seat at the head of her table, and in spirits oppressively high.

10:25:21.110 --> 10:25:23.510
No sentiment of shame gave a damp to her triumph.

10:25:23.990 --> 10:25:30.430
The marriage of a daughter, which had been the first object of her wishes since Jane was sixteen, was now on the point of accomplishment,

10:25:30.870 --> 10:25:38.470
and her thoughts and her words ran wholly on those attendants of elegant nuptials, fine muslins, new carriages, and servants.

10:25:39.390 --> 10:25:43.190
She was busily searching through the neighborhood for a proper situation for her daughter,

10:25:43.190 --> 10:25:49.310
and, without knowing or considering what their income might be, rejected many as deficient in size and importance.

10:25:50.930 --> 10:25:53.590
"'Hey, Park, my do,' said she.

10:25:53.950 --> 10:26:01.890
"'If the Goldings could quit it, or the great house at Stoke, if the drawing-room were larger—but Ashworth is too far off.

10:26:02.190 --> 10:26:08.190
I could not bear to have her ten miles from me, and as for Pulvis Lodge the attics are dreadful.'

10:26:08.190 --> 10:26:15.130
Her husband allowed her to talk on without interruption while the servants remained, but when they had withdrawn he said to her,

10:26:15.910 --> 10:26:22.290
"'Mrs. Bennet, before you take any or all of these houses for your son and daughter, let us come to a right understanding.

10:26:22.970 --> 10:26:27.030
Into one house in this neighborhood they shall never have admittance.

10:26:27.410 --> 10:26:33.030
I will not encourage the impudence of either by receiving them at Longbourn.'

10:26:33.030 --> 10:26:37.170
A long dispute followed this declaration, but Mr. Bennet was firm.

10:26:37.770 --> 10:26:45.170
It soon led to another, and Mrs. Bennet found, with amazement and horror, that her husband would not advance a guinea to buy clothes for his daughter.

10:26:46.150 --> 10:26:51.030
He protested that she should receive from him no mark of affection whatever on the occasion.

10:26:52.050 --> 10:26:57.910
Mrs. Bennet could hardly comprehend it, that his anger could be carried to such a point of inconceivable resentment

10:26:57.910 --> 10:27:05.110
as to refuse his daughter a privilege without which her marriage would scarcely seem valid, exceeded all she could believe possible.

10:27:05.990 --> 10:27:10.550
She was more alive to the disgrace which her want of new clothes must reflect on her daughter's nuptials

10:27:10.550 --> 10:27:15.510
than to any sense of shame at her eloping and living with Wickham a fortnight before they took place.

10:27:17.910 --> 10:27:25.410
Elizabeth was now hardly sorry that she had, from the distress of the moment, been led to make Mr. Darcy acquainted with their fears for her sister,

10:27:25.410 --> 10:27:29.770
for since her marriage would so shortly give the proper termination to the elopement,

10:27:30.170 --> 10:27:34.790
they might hope to conceal its unfavourable beginning from all those who were not immediately on the spot.

10:27:35.650 --> 10:27:38.130
She had no fear of it spreading farther through his means.

10:27:38.610 --> 10:27:42.370
There were few people on whose secrecy she would have more confidently depended.

10:27:43.010 --> 10:27:48.630
But at the same time there was no one whose knowledge of a sister's frailty would have mortified her so much.

10:27:49.170 --> 10:27:53.010
Not, however, from any fear of disadvantage from it individually to herself,

10:27:53.570 --> 10:27:56.730
for at any rate there seemed a gulf impassable between them.

10:27:57.370 --> 10:28:00.350
Had Lydia's marriage been concluded on the most honourable terms,

10:28:00.710 --> 10:28:04.350
it was not to be supposed that Mr. Darcy would connect himself with the family where,

10:28:04.750 --> 10:28:13.050
to every other objection, would now be added an alliance and a relationship of the nearest kind with the man whom he so justly scorned.

10:28:13.250 --> 10:28:15.970
From such a connection she could not wonder that he would shrink.

10:28:15.970 --> 10:28:20.690
The wish of procuring her regard, which she had assured herself of his feeling in Derbyshire,

10:28:21.190 --> 10:28:24.430
could not in rational expectation survive such a blow as this.

10:28:24.790 --> 10:28:29.270
She was humbled, she was grieved, she repented, though she hardly knew of what.

10:28:29.990 --> 10:28:34.670
She became jealous of his esteem, when she could no longer hope to be benefited by it.

10:28:35.070 --> 10:28:39.370
She wanted to hear of him, when there seemed the least chance of gaining intelligence.

10:28:40.070 --> 10:28:44.690
She was convinced that she could have been happy with him, when it was no longer likely they should meet.

10:28:45.730 --> 10:28:47.950
What a triumph for him, as she often thought.

10:28:48.270 --> 10:28:52.170
Could he know that the proposals which she had proudly spurned only four months ago

10:28:52.170 --> 10:28:54.970
would now have been most gladly and gratefully received?

10:28:55.710 --> 10:28:59.630
He was as generous, she doubted not, as the most generous of his sex.

10:29:00.010 --> 10:29:02.550
But while he was mortal, there must be a triumph.

10:29:04.030 --> 10:29:10.150
She began now to comprehend that he was exactly the man who, in disposition and talents, would most suit her.

10:29:10.150 --> 10:29:15.090
His understanding and temper, though unlike her own, would have answered all her wishes.

10:29:15.970 --> 10:29:18.750
It was a union that must have been to the advantage of both.

10:29:19.530 --> 10:29:23.990
By her ease and liveliness, his mind might have been softened, his manners improved,

10:29:24.230 --> 10:29:29.510
and from his judgment, information, and knowledge of the world, she must have received benefit of greater importance.

10:29:30.870 --> 10:29:36.530
But no such happy marriage could now teach the admiring multitude what connubial felicity really was.

10:29:36.530 --> 10:29:42.970
A union of a different tendency, and precluding the possibility of the other, was soon to be formed in their family.

10:29:44.230 --> 10:29:48.910
How Wickham and Lydia were to be supported in tolerable independence, she could not imagine.

10:29:49.530 --> 10:29:54.030
But how little of permanent happiness could belong to a couple, who were only brought together

10:29:54.030 --> 10:29:58.050
because their passions were stronger than their virtue, she could easily conjecture.

10:30:00.030 --> 10:30:02.350
Mr. Gardiner soon wrote again to his brother.

10:30:02.350 --> 10:30:09.470
To Mr. Bennet's acknowledgments, he briefly replied, with assurance of his eagerness to promote the welfare of any of his family,

10:30:09.970 --> 10:30:13.670
and concluded within treaties that the subject might never be mentioned to him again.

10:30:14.150 --> 10:30:19.410
The principal purport of his letter was to inform them that Mr. Wickham had resolved on quitting the militia.

10:30:20.330 --> 10:30:25.210
It was greatly my wish that he should do so, he added, as soon as his marriage was fixed on.

10:30:25.470 --> 10:30:30.410
And I think you will agree with me, in considering the removal of that corps as highly advisable,

10:30:30.410 --> 10:30:32.890
both on his account and my niece's.

10:30:33.250 --> 10:30:35.970
It is Mr. Wickham's intention to go into the regulars,

10:30:36.250 --> 10:30:40.890
and among his former friends there are still some who are able and willing to assist him in the army.

10:30:42.410 --> 10:30:47.910
He has a promise of an ensigncy in general regiment, now quartered in the north.

10:30:48.610 --> 10:30:51.710
It is an advantage to have so far from this part of the kingdom.

10:30:52.150 --> 10:30:57.950
He promises fairly, and I hope among different people, where they may each have a character to preserve,

10:30:57.950 --> 10:30:59.810
they will both be more prudent.

10:31:00.550 --> 10:31:04.190
I have written to Colonel Forrester to inform him of our present arrangements,

10:31:04.510 --> 10:31:08.930
and to request that he will satisfy the various creditors of Mr. Wickham in and near Brydon,

10:31:09.390 --> 10:31:13.030
with assurance of his speedy payment, for which I have pledged myself.

10:31:13.410 --> 10:31:17.870
And will you give yourself the trouble of carrying similar assurances to his creditors in Meryton,

10:31:18.250 --> 10:31:21.110
of whom I shall subjoin a list according to his information?

10:31:22.230 --> 10:31:26.100
He has given in all his debts. I hope at least he has not deceived us.

10:31:28.050 --> 10:31:31.150
Hackerson has our directions, and all will be completed in a week.

10:31:31.470 --> 10:31:35.050
They will then join his regiment, unless they are first invited to Longbourn.

10:31:35.250 --> 10:31:40.470
And I understand from Mrs. Gardiner that my niece is very desirous of seeing you all before she leaves the south.

10:31:41.090 --> 10:31:48.170
She is well, and begs to be dutifully remembered to you and your mother. Yours, etc. E. Gardiner.

10:31:50.130 --> 10:31:57.530
Mr. Bennet and his daughters saw all the advantages of Wickham's removal from the Shire as clearly as Mr. Gardiner could do.

10:31:58.070 --> 10:32:00.550
But Mrs. Bennet was not so well pleased with it.

10:32:00.870 --> 10:32:05.330
Lydia's being settled in the north, just when she had expected most pleasure and pride in her company,

10:32:05.730 --> 10:32:11.090
for she had by no means given up her plan for their residing in Hertfordshire, was a severe disappointment.

10:32:11.650 --> 10:32:18.030
And besides, it was such a pity that Lydia should be taken from a regiment where she was acquainted with every one, and had so many favourites.

10:32:18.870 --> 10:32:21.490
She is so fond of Mrs. Forster, said she.

10:32:22.010 --> 10:32:27.090
It will be quite shocking to send her away, and there are several of the young men, too, that she likes very much.

10:32:27.510 --> 10:32:30.910
The officers may not be so pleasant in general regiment.

10:32:32.190 --> 10:32:41.110
His daughter's request, for such it might be considered, of being admitted into her family again before she was set off for the north, received at first an absolute negative.

10:32:41.950 --> 10:32:49.190
But Jane and Elizabeth, who agreed in wishing, for the sake of their sister's feelings and consequence, that she should be noticed on her marriage by her parents,

10:32:49.850 --> 10:32:56.090
urged him so earnestly, yet so rationally, and so mildly, to receive her and her husband at Longburn, as soon as they were married,

10:32:56.350 --> 10:33:00.050
that he was revealed on to think as they thought, and act as they wished.

10:33:00.050 --> 10:33:06.710
And their mother had the satisfaction of knowing that she would be able to show her married daughter in the neighbourhood before she was banished to the north.

10:33:07.890 --> 10:33:16.930
When Mr. Bennet wrote again to his brother, therefore, he sent his permission for them to come, and it was settled, that as soon as the ceremony was over, they should proceed to Longburn.

10:33:18.490 --> 10:33:27.610
Elizabeth was surprised, however, that Wickham should consent to such a scheme, and had she consulted only her own inclination, any meeting with him would have been the last object of her wishes.

10:33:32.570 --> 10:33:38.290
The sister's wedding day arrived, and Jane and Elizabeth felt for her properly more than she felt for herself.

10:33:38.870 --> 10:33:43.290
The carriage was sent to meet them at, and they were to return in it by dinner-time.

10:33:43.930 --> 10:33:52.210
Their arrival was dreaded by the elder Miss Bennet's, and Jane more especially, who gave Lydia the feelings which would have attended herself, had she been the culprit,

10:33:52.590 --> 10:33:55.150
and was wretched in the thought of what her sister must endure.

10:33:56.170 --> 10:34:00.250
They came. The family were assembled in the breakfast-room to receive them.

10:34:00.710 --> 10:34:09.430
Smiles decked the face of Mrs. Bennet as the carriage drove up to the door. Her husband looked impenetrably grave. Her daughters, alarmed, anxious, uneasy.

10:34:11.570 --> 10:34:16.130
Lydia's voice was heard in the vestibule. The door was thrown open, and she ran into the room.

10:34:16.130 --> 10:34:23.930
Her mother stepped forwards, embraced her, and welcomed her with rapture, gave her hand with an affectionate smile to Wickham, who followed his lady,

10:34:24.190 --> 10:34:27.750
and wished them both joy with an alacrity which showed no doubt of their happiness.

10:34:29.590 --> 10:34:37.930
Their reception from Mr. Bennet, to whom they then turned, was not quite so cordial. His countenance rather gained in austerity, and he scarcely opened his lips.

10:34:38.470 --> 10:34:41.870
The easy assurance of the young couple, indeed, was enough to provoke him.

10:34:42.490 --> 10:34:45.530
Elizabeth was disgusted, and even Miss Bennet was shocked.

10:34:46.130 --> 10:34:51.710
Lydia was Lydia's still, untamed, unabashed, wild, noisy, and fearless.

10:34:52.470 --> 10:34:59.430
She turned from sister to sister, demanding their congratulations, and when at length they all sat down, looked eagerly around the room,

10:35:00.070 --> 10:35:05.570
took notice of some little alteration in it, and observed, with a laugh, that it was a great while since she had been there.

10:35:06.450 --> 10:35:13.870
Wickham was not at all more distressed than herself, but his manners were always so pleasing, that had his character and his marriage been exactly what they ought,

10:35:13.870 --> 10:35:19.310
his smiles and his easy address, while they claimed to their relationship, would have delighted them all.

10:35:20.510 --> 10:35:29.970
Elizabeth had not before believed him quite equal to such assurance, but she sat down, resolving within herself to draw no limits in future to the impudence of an impudent man.

10:35:30.950 --> 10:35:36.630
She blushed, and Jane blushed, but the cheeks of the two caused their confusion, and suffered no variation of colour.

10:35:38.010 --> 10:35:45.650
There was no want of discourse. The bride and her mother could neither of them talk fast enough, and Wickham, who happened to sit near Elizabeth,

10:35:46.050 --> 10:35:52.150
began inquiring after his acquaintance in that neighbourhood, with a good-humoured ease which she felt very unable to equal in her replies.

10:35:52.810 --> 10:35:57.770
They seemed each of them to have the happiest memories in the world, nothing of the past was recollected with pain,

10:35:58.050 --> 10:36:02.590
and Lydia led voluntarily to subjects which her sisters would not have alluded to for the world.

10:36:03.650 --> 10:36:12.610
Only think of its being three months! she cried. Since I went away, it seems but a fortnight, I declare, and yet there have been things enough happened in the time.

10:36:12.810 --> 10:36:20.010
Good gracious! when I went away, I am sure I had no more idea of being married till I had come back again, though I thought it would be very good fun if I was.

10:36:21.330 --> 10:36:31.950
Her father lifted up his eyes. Jane was distressed. Elizabeth looked expressly at Lydia, but she, who never heard nor saw anything of which she chose to be insensible, gaily continued.

10:36:32.890 --> 10:36:40.110
Oh, mum! do the people hereabouts know I am married to-day? I was afraid they might not, and we overtook William Golding in his curricule.

10:36:40.490 --> 10:36:51.790
So I was determined he should know it, and so I let down the side-glass next to him, and took off my glove, and let my hand just rest upon the window-frame, so that he might see the ring, and then I bowed and smiled like anything.

10:36:53.750 --> 10:37:01.230
Elizabeth could bear it no longer. She got up, and ran out of the room, and returned no more till she heard them passing through the hall into the dining-parlour.

10:37:01.230 --> 10:37:08.870
She then joined them soon enough to see Lydia, with anxious parade, walk up to her mother's right hand, and hear her say to her eldest sister,

10:37:09.730 --> 10:37:15.090
Ah, Jane, I take your place now, and you must go lower, because I am a married woman.

10:37:16.610 --> 10:37:22.190
It was not to be supposed that time would give Lydia that embarrassment from which she had been so wholly free at first.

10:37:22.190 --> 10:37:31.190
Her ease and good spirits increased. She longed to see Mrs. Phillips, Lucas's, and all their other neighbours, and to hear herself called Mrs. Wickham by each of them,

10:37:31.470 --> 10:37:37.190
and in the meantime she went after dinner to show her ring, and boast of being married to Mrs. Hill and the two housemaids.

10:37:40.390 --> 10:37:44.830
Well, mamma, said she, when they were all returned to the breakfast-room.

10:37:45.370 --> 10:37:53.570
And what do you think of my husband? Is not he a charming man? I'm sure my sisters must all envy me. I only hope they have half my good luck.

10:37:53.870 --> 10:37:59.650
They must all go to Brighton. That is the place to get husbands. What a pity it is, mamma, we did not all go.

10:38:01.030 --> 10:38:09.530
Very true, and if I had my will, we should. But, my dear Lydia, I don't at all like your going such a way off, must it be so?

10:38:11.190 --> 10:38:18.810
Oh, Lord, yes, there's nothing in that. I shall like it of all things. You and papa and my sisters must come down to see us.

10:38:19.070 --> 10:38:25.050
We shall be at Newcastle all the winter, and I dare say there will be some falls, and I will take care to get good partners for them all.

10:38:25.890 --> 10:38:28.210
I should like it beyond anything, said her mother.

10:38:29.170 --> 10:38:35.730
And then when you go away, you may leave one or two of my sisters behind you, and I dare say I shall get husbands for them before the winter is over.

10:38:36.290 --> 10:38:42.790
I thank you for my share of the favour, said Elizabeth, but I do not particularly like your way of getting husbands.

10:38:44.730 --> 10:38:53.050
Their visitors were not to remain above ten days with them. Mr. Wickham had received his commission before he left London, and he was to join his regiment at the end of the fortnight.

10:38:54.150 --> 10:39:02.590
No one but Mrs. Bennet regretted that their stay would be so short, and she made the most of the time by visiting about with her daughter and having very frequent parties at home.

10:39:02.590 --> 10:39:10.230
These parties were acceptable to all. To avoid a family circle was even more desirable to such as did think than such as did not.

10:39:12.570 --> 10:39:17.970
Wickham's affection for Lydia was just what Elizabeth had expected to find, not equal to Lydia's for him.

10:39:18.470 --> 10:39:26.710
She had scarcely needed her present observation to be satisfied from the reason of things that their elopement had been brought on by the strength of her love rather than by his,

10:39:26.710 --> 10:39:36.330
and she would have wondered why, without violently caring for her, he chose to elope with her at all, and she not felt certain that his flight was rendered necessary by distressive circumstances,

10:39:36.790 --> 10:39:41.250
and if that were the case, he was not the young man to resist an opportunity of having a companion.

10:39:43.610 --> 10:39:49.770
Lydia was excessively fond of him. He was her dear Wickham on every occasion. No one was to be put in competition with him.

10:39:49.770 --> 10:39:56.330
He did everything best in the world, and she was sure he would kill more birds on the 1st of September than anybody else in the country.

10:39:57.930 --> 10:40:02.590
One morning, soon after their arrival, as she was sitting with her two elder sisters, she said to Elizabeth,

10:40:03.670 --> 10:40:13.070
Lizzie, I never gave you an account of my wedding, I believe. You were not by when I told Mama and the others all about it. Are not you curious to hear how it was managed?

10:40:14.770 --> 10:40:19.530
No, really, replied Elizabeth. I think there cannot be too little said on the subject.

10:40:20.670 --> 10:40:28.990
Ah, you are so strange! But I must tell you how it went off. We were married, you know, at St. Clement's, because Wickham's lodgings were in that parish,

10:40:29.350 --> 10:40:36.270
and it was subtle that we should all be there by eleven o'clock. My uncle and aunt and I were to go together, and the others were to meet us at the church.

10:40:36.270 --> 10:40:44.450
Well, Monday morning came, and I was in such a fuss. I was so afraid, you know, that something would happen to put it off, and then I should have gone quite distracted.

10:40:45.750 --> 10:40:50.670
And there was my aunt, all the time I was dressing, preaching and talking away, just as she was reading a sermon.

10:40:51.390 --> 10:40:59.930
However, I did not hear above one word in ten, and I was thinking, you may suppose, of my dear Wickham. I longed to know whether he would be married in his blue coat.

10:41:01.010 --> 10:41:10.210
Well, and so we breakfast at ten, as usual. I thought it would never be over, for, by the by, you are to understand that my uncle and aunt were horrid and pleasant all the time I was with them.

10:41:10.550 --> 10:41:18.090
And you'll believe me, I did not once put my foot out of doors, though I was there a fortnight. Not one party, or scheme, or anything.

10:41:18.850 --> 10:41:22.530
To be sure, London was rather thin, but, however, the little theatre was open.

10:41:23.110 --> 10:41:32.590
Well, and so just as the carriage came to the door, my uncle was called away upon business to that horrid man, Mr. Stone, and then, you know, when once they got together, there was no end of it.

10:41:32.970 --> 10:41:39.490
Well, I was so frightened, I did not know what to do, for my uncle was to give me away, and if we were beyond the hour, we could not be married all day.

10:41:40.310 --> 10:41:44.170
But luckily, he came back again in ten minutes' time, and then we all set out.

10:41:44.950 --> 10:41:51.090
However, I recollected afterwards that if he had prevented going, the wedding need not be put off, for Mr. Darcy might have done as well.

10:41:52.870 --> 10:41:56.130
Mr. Darcy? repeated Elizabeth, in utter amazement.

10:41:57.150 --> 10:42:07.390
Oh, yes, he was to come there with Wickham, you know. But, gracious me, I quite forgot. I ought not to have said a word about it. I promised them so faithfully. What would Wickham say, if it was to be such a secret?

10:42:08.350 --> 10:42:15.150
If it was to be secret, said Jane, say not another word on the subject. You may depend upon my seeking no further.

10:42:16.850 --> 10:42:22.470
Oh, certainly, said Elizabeth, though burning with curiosity. We will ask you no questions.

10:42:24.110 --> 10:42:29.250
Thank you, said Lydia, for if you did, I should certainly tell you all, and then Wickham would be angry.

10:42:30.910 --> 10:42:35.690
On such encouragement to ask, Elizabeth was forced to put it out of her power by running away.

10:42:37.110 --> 10:42:42.570
But to live in ignorance on such a point was impossible, or at least it was impossible not to try for information.

10:42:43.130 --> 10:42:51.930
Mr. Darcy had been at her sister's wedding. It was exactly a scene, and exactly among people, where he had apparently leased to-do, and leased temptation to go.

10:42:52.750 --> 10:42:59.070
Conjectures as to the meaning of it, rapid and wild, hurried into her brain, but she was satisfied with none.

10:42:59.770 --> 10:43:04.770
Those at best pleased her, as placing his conduct in the noblest light, seemed most improbable.

10:43:04.770 --> 10:43:15.730
She could not bear such suspense, and hastily seizing a sheet of paper, wrote a short letter to her aunt, to request an explanation of what Lydia had dropped, if it were compatible with the secrecy which had been intended.

10:43:17.150 --> 10:43:28.690
You may readily comprehend, she added, but my curiosity must be to know how a person, unconnected with any of us, and comparatively speaking, a stranger to our family, should have been amongst you at such a time.

10:43:29.170 --> 10:43:39.650
Pray write instantly, and let me understand it, unless it is for very cogent reasons, to remain in the secrecy which Lydia seems to think necessary, and then I must endeavour to be satisfied with ignorance.

10:43:41.470 --> 10:43:46.130
Not that I shall, though, she added to herself, as she finished the letter.

10:43:46.810 --> 10:43:52.590
And my dear aunt, if you do not tell me in an honourable manner, I shall certainly be reduced to tricks and stratagems to find it out.

10:43:54.130 --> 10:43:58.810
Jane's delicate sense of honour would not allow her to speak to Elizabeth privately of what Lydia had let fall.

10:43:59.710 --> 10:44:06.780
Elizabeth was glad of it. Till it appeared whether her inquiries would receive any satisfaction, she would rather be without a confidant.

10:44:27.340 --> 10:44:31.340
Elizabeth had the satisfaction of receiving

10:44:31.340 --> 10:44:34.300
an answer to her letter as soon as she possibly could.

10:44:34.300 --> 10:44:42.580
She was no sooner in possession of it than hurrying into the little coves where she was least likely to be interrupted.

10:44:43.080 --> 10:44:46.440
She sat down on one of the benches and prepared to be happy,

10:44:46.720 --> 10:44:51.220
for the length of the letter convinced her that it did not contain a denial.

10:44:55.500 --> 10:45:02.140
My dear niece, I have just received your letter and shall devote this whole morning to answering it,

10:45:02.140 --> 10:45:06.900
as I foresee that a little writing will not comprise what I have to tell you.

10:45:07.140 --> 10:45:10.300
I must confess myself surprised by your application.

10:45:11.280 --> 10:45:13.540
I did not expect it from you.

10:45:14.120 --> 10:45:22.480
Don't make me angry, however, for I only mean to let you know that I had not imagined such inquiries to be necessary on your side.

10:45:23.520 --> 10:45:27.480
If you do not choose to understand me, forgive my impertinence.

10:45:27.820 --> 10:45:37.000
Your uncle is as much surprised as I am, and nothing but the belief of your being a party concerned would have allowed him to act as he has done.

10:45:37.860 --> 10:45:42.320
But if you are really innocent and ignorant, I must be more explicit.

10:45:43.320 --> 10:45:49.020
On the very day of my coming home from Longbourn, your uncle had a most unexpected visitor.

10:45:49.980 --> 10:45:53.400
Mr. Darcy called and was shut up with him several hours.

10:45:53.920 --> 10:46:00.960
It was all over before I arrived, so my curiosity was not so dreadfully wracked as yours seems to be.

10:46:01.980 --> 10:46:09.740
He came to tell Mr. Gardiner that he had found out where your sister and Mr. Wickham were and that he had seen and talked with both.

10:46:10.780 --> 10:46:13.280
Wickham repeatedly, Lydia once.

10:46:13.960 --> 10:46:23.100
From what I can collect, he left Darbyshire only one day after ourselves and came to town with a resolution of hunting for them.

10:46:23.780 --> 10:46:37.560
The motive professed was his conviction of its being owing to himself that Wickham's worthlessness had not been so well known as to make it impossible for any young woman of character to love or confide in him.

10:46:38.180 --> 10:46:48.200
He generously imputed the whole to his mistaken pride and confessed that he had before thought it beneath him to lay his actions open to the world.

10:46:48.840 --> 10:46:51.580
His character was to speak for itself.

10:46:52.090 --> 10:47:00.080
He called it therefore his duty to step forward and endeavour to remedy an evil which he had brought on by himself.

10:47:00.980 --> 10:47:04.880
If he had another motive, I am sure it would never disgrace him.

10:47:05.380 --> 10:47:18.600
He had been some days in town before he was able to discover them, but he had something to direct his search, which was more than we had, and the consciousness of this was another reason for his resolving to follow us.

10:47:19.900 --> 10:47:33.100
There is a lady, it seems, a Mrs. Young, who was some time ago governess to Miss Darcy and was dismissed from her charge on some cause of disapprobation, though he did not say what.

10:47:33.680 --> 10:47:40.200
She then took a large house in Edward Street and has since maintained herself by letting lodgings.

10:47:40.720 --> 10:47:53.900
Mrs. Young was, he knew, intimately acquainted with Wickham, and he went to her for intelligence of him as soon as he got to town, but it was two or three days before he could get from her what he wanted.

10:47:54.400 --> 10:48:01.880
She would not betray her trust, I suppose, without bribery and corruption, for she really did know where her friend was to be found.

10:48:02.940 --> 10:48:09.520
Wickham, indeed, had gone to her on their first arrival in London, and she had been able to receive them into her house.

10:48:09.920 --> 10:48:12.140
They would have taken up their abode with her.

10:48:12.500 --> 10:48:16.420
At length, however, our kind friend procured the wish for direction.

10:48:17.300 --> 10:48:20.960
He saw Wickham and afterwards insisted on seeing Lydia.

10:48:21.720 --> 10:48:35.920
His first object with her, he acknowledged, had been to persuade her to quit her present disgraceful situation and return to her friends as soon as they could be prevailed on to receive her, offering his assistance as far as it would go.

10:48:36.900 --> 10:48:41.240
But he found Lydia absolutely resolved on remaining where she was.

10:48:41.540 --> 10:48:43.180
She cared for none of her friends.

10:48:43.540 --> 10:48:45.160
She wanted no help of his.

10:48:45.460 --> 10:48:47.660
She would not hear of leaving Wickham.

10:48:48.180 --> 10:48:53.800
She was sure they should be married some time or other, and it did not much signify when.

10:48:54.900 --> 10:49:07.120
Since such were her feelings, it only remained, he thought, to secure and expedite a marriage, which, in his very first conversation with Wickham, he easily learned had never been his design.

10:49:07.840 --> 10:49:21.820
He confessed himself obliged to leave the regiment on account of some debts of honour which were very pressing, and scrupled not to lay all the ill consequences of Lydia's flight on her own folly alone.

10:49:22.580 --> 10:49:30.020
He meant to resign his commission immediately, and as to his future situation, he could conjecture very little about it.

10:49:30.240 --> 10:49:35.500
He must go somewhere, but he did not know where, and he knew he should have nothing to live on.

10:49:37.160 --> 10:49:41.120
Mr. Darcy asked him why he had not married your sister at once.

10:49:41.540 --> 10:49:50.640
Though Mr. Bennet was not imagined to be very rich, he would have been able to do something for him, and his situation must have been benefited by marriage.

10:49:51.180 --> 10:50:00.780
But he found in reply to this question that Wickham still cherished the hope of more effectually making his fortune by marriage in some other country.

10:50:01.300 --> 10:50:08.700
Under such circumstances, however, he was not likely to be proof against the temptation of immediate relief.

10:50:09.760 --> 10:50:12.940
They met several times, for there was much to be discussed.

10:50:13.580 --> 10:50:18.880
Wickham, of course, wanted more than he could get, but at length was reduced to being reasonable.

10:50:20.200 --> 10:50:30.500
Everything being settled between them, Mr. Darcy's next step was to make your uncle acquainted with it, and he first called in Grace Church Street the evening before I came home.

10:50:31.320 --> 10:50:40.200
But Mr. Gardiner could not be seen, and Mr. Darcy found, on further inquiry, that your father was still with him, but would quit town the next morning.

10:50:41.400 --> 10:50:47.280
He did not judge your father to be a person whom he could so properly consult as your uncle.

10:50:47.800 --> 10:50:52.980
And therefore readily postponed seeing him till after the departure of the former.

10:50:53.760 --> 10:51:00.100
He did not leave his name, and till the next day it was only known that a gentleman had called on business.

10:51:01.240 --> 10:51:09.520
On Saturday he came again. Your father was gone, your uncle at home, and as I said before, they had a great deal of talk together.

10:51:10.320 --> 10:51:13.900
They met again on Sunday, and then I saw him too.

10:51:14.140 --> 10:51:20.480
It was not all settled before Monday. As soon as it was, the express was sent off to Longbourn.

10:51:20.720 --> 10:51:28.840
But our visitor was very obstinate. I fancy, Lizzie, that obstinacy is the real defect of his character, after all.

10:51:29.160 --> 10:51:34.120
He has been accused of many faults at different times, but this is the true one.

10:51:34.640 --> 10:51:43.720
Nothing was to be done that he did not do himself, though I am sure, and I do not speak it to be faint, therefore say nothing about it,

10:51:44.120 --> 10:51:47.200
your uncle would most readily have settled the whole.

10:51:47.800 --> 10:51:54.980
They battled it together for a long time, which was more than either the gentleman or lady concerned in it deserved.

10:51:55.880 --> 10:52:02.280
But at last your uncle was forced to yield, and instead of being allowed to be of use to his niece,

10:52:02.640 --> 10:52:08.800
was forced to put up with only having the probable credit of it, which went sorely against the grain.

10:52:09.200 --> 10:52:13.220
And I really believe your letter this morning gave him great pleasure,

10:52:13.600 --> 10:52:20.700
because it required an explanation that would rob him of his borrowed feathers, and give the praise where it was due.

10:52:21.220 --> 10:52:26.120
But Lizzie, this must go no farther than yourself or Jane at most.

10:52:27.360 --> 10:52:31.080
You know pretty well, I suppose, what has been done for the young people.

10:52:31.520 --> 10:52:37.140
His debts are to be paid amounting, I believe, to considerably more than a thousand pounds,

10:52:37.720 --> 10:52:43.560
another thousand in addition to her own settled upon her and his commission purchased.

10:52:44.480 --> 10:52:49.800
The reason why all this was to be done by him alone was such as I have given above.

10:52:50.220 --> 10:52:55.780
It was owing to him, to his reserve and want of proper consideration,

10:52:56.160 --> 10:53:03.680
that Wickham's character had not been understood, and consequently that he had been received and noticed as he was.

10:53:04.760 --> 10:53:13.160
Perhaps there was some truth to this, though I doubt whether his reserve or anybody's reserve can be answerable for the event.

10:53:13.980 --> 10:53:18.340
But in spite of all this fine talking, my dear Lizzie,

10:53:18.620 --> 10:53:23.220
you may rest perfectly assured that your uncle would never have yielded

10:53:23.220 --> 10:53:28.180
if we had not given him credit for another interest in the affair.

10:53:29.180 --> 10:53:35.000
When all this was resolved on, he returned again to his friends who were still staying at Pemberley,

10:53:35.260 --> 10:53:39.660
but it was agreed that he should be in London once more when the wedding took place,

10:53:39.920 --> 10:53:43.720
and all money matters were then to receive the last finish.

10:53:45.520 --> 10:53:48.080
I believe I have now told you everything.

10:53:48.560 --> 10:53:52.560
It is a relation which you tell me is to give you great surprise.

10:53:53.040 --> 10:53:56.360
I hope at least it will not afford you any displeasure.

10:53:57.500 --> 10:54:01.180
Lydia came to us and Wickham had constant admission to the house.

10:54:01.660 --> 10:54:05.680
He was exactly what he had been when I knew him in Hertfordshire,

10:54:05.940 --> 10:54:11.760
but I would not tell you how little I was satisfied with her behaviour when she stayed with us

10:54:11.760 --> 10:54:15.580
if I had not perceived by Jane's letter last Wednesday

10:54:15.920 --> 10:54:19.960
that her conduct on coming home was exactly of a piece with it,

10:54:20.200 --> 10:54:24.080
and therefore what I now tell you can give you no fresh pain.

10:54:25.680 --> 10:54:29.140
I talked to her repeatedly in the most serious manner,

10:54:29.640 --> 10:54:32.540
representing to her all the wickedness of what she had done

10:54:32.540 --> 10:54:35.860
and all the unhappiness she had brought on her family.

10:54:36.860 --> 10:54:40.840
If she had heard me it was by good luck, for I am sure she did not listen.

10:54:41.500 --> 10:54:47.120
I was sometimes quite provoked, but then I recollected my dear Elizabeth and Jane,

10:54:47.640 --> 10:54:50.320
and for their sakes had patience with her.

10:54:51.640 --> 10:54:57.540
Mr. Darcy was punctual in his return, and as Lydia informed you, attended the wedding.

10:54:58.060 --> 10:55:03.220
He dined with us the next day and was to leave town again on Wednesday or Thursday.

10:55:04.360 --> 10:55:09.380
Will you be very angry with me, my dear Lizzie, if I take this opportunity of saying

10:55:09.380 --> 10:55:13.660
what I was never bold enough to say before, how much I like him?

10:55:14.300 --> 10:55:20.180
His behaviour to us has, in every respect, been as pleasing as when we were in Derbyshire.

10:55:21.000 --> 10:55:24.220
His understanding and opinions all please me.

10:55:24.470 --> 10:55:27.320
He wants nothing but a little more liveliness,

10:55:27.580 --> 10:55:32.140
and that if he marry prudently his wife may teach him.

10:55:32.580 --> 10:55:34.220
I thought him very sly.

10:55:34.500 --> 10:55:39.720
He hardly ever mentions your name, but slyness seems the fashion.

10:55:40.900 --> 10:55:43.740
Pray forgive me if I have been very presuming,

10:55:43.920 --> 10:55:48.960
or at least do not punish me so far as to exclude me from Pemberley.

10:55:49.340 --> 10:55:54.220
I shall never be quite happy till I have been all around the park.

10:55:54.720 --> 10:55:59.500
A low fayton with a nice little pair of ponies would be the very thing.

10:56:00.020 --> 10:56:01.560
But I must write no more.

10:56:01.580 --> 10:56:04.200
The children have been wanting me this half hour.

10:56:04.660 --> 10:56:07.620
Yours very sincerely, M. Gardiner.

10:56:09.200 --> 10:56:13.200
The contents of this letter threw Elizabeth into a flutter of spirits,

10:56:13.400 --> 10:56:18.740
in which it was difficult to determine whether pleasure or pain bore the greatest share.

10:56:19.880 --> 10:56:24.500
The vague and unsettled suspicions which uncertainty had produced

10:56:24.500 --> 10:56:28.960
of what Mr. Darcy might have been doing to forward her sister's match,

10:56:29.620 --> 10:56:34.780
which she had feared to encourage as an exertion of goodness too great to be probable,

10:56:35.420 --> 10:56:39.860
and at the same time dreaded to be just from the pain of obligation,

10:56:39.860 --> 10:56:44.420
were proved beyond their greatest extent to be true.

10:56:45.420 --> 10:56:47.700
He had followed them purposely to town.

10:56:48.000 --> 10:56:53.480
He had taken on himself all the trouble and mortification attendant on such a research,

10:56:53.980 --> 10:57:00.160
in which supplication had been necessary to a woman whom he must abominate and despise,

10:57:01.100 --> 10:57:07.900
and where he was reduced to meet, frequently meet, reason with, persuade, and finally bribe,

10:57:07.900 --> 10:57:15.180
the men who he always most wished to avoid and whose very name it was punishment to him to pronounce.

10:57:16.220 --> 10:57:21.080
He had done all this for a girl whom he could neither regard nor esteem.

10:57:21.780 --> 10:57:25.120
Her heart did whisper that he had done it for her,

10:57:25.400 --> 10:57:28.880
but it was a hope shortly checked by other considerations,

10:57:29.260 --> 10:57:32.880
and she soon felt that even her vanity was insufficient

10:57:32.880 --> 10:57:36.640
when required to depend on his affection for her.

10:57:36.640 --> 10:57:40.380
For a woman who had already refused him,

10:57:40.740 --> 10:57:47.440
as able to overcome a sentiment so natural as abhorrence against relationship with Wickham,

10:57:48.120 --> 10:57:54.080
brother-in-law of Wickham, every kind of pride must revolt from that connection,

10:57:54.600 --> 10:57:56.660
he had to be sure done much.

10:57:57.580 --> 10:57:59.900
She was ashamed to think how much.

10:57:59.900 --> 10:58:03.120
But he had given a reason for his interference,

10:58:03.860 --> 10:58:07.400
which asked no extraordinary stretch of belief.

10:58:08.460 --> 10:58:11.580
It was reasonable that he should feel he had been wrong.

10:58:12.280 --> 10:58:15.960
He had liberality and he had the means of exercising it,

10:58:16.240 --> 10:58:19.980
and though she would not place herself as his principal inducement,

10:58:21.040 --> 10:58:25.520
she could perhaps believe that remaining partiality for her

10:58:25.520 --> 10:58:31.660
might assist his endeavours in a cause where her peace of mind must be materially concerned.

10:58:33.220 --> 10:58:38.900
It was painful, exceedingly painful to know that they were under obligations

10:58:38.900 --> 10:58:42.260
to a person who could never receive a return.

10:58:43.440 --> 10:58:48.120
They owed the restoration of Lydia, her character, everything to him.

10:58:48.840 --> 10:58:54.880
Oh, how heartily did she grieve over every ungracious sensation she had ever encouraged,

10:58:54.880 --> 10:58:59.060
every saucy speech she had ever directed towards him.

10:59:00.320 --> 10:59:03.980
For herself she was humbled, but she was proud of him,

10:59:04.240 --> 10:59:09.740
proud that in a cause of compassion and honour he had been able to get the better of himself.

10:59:11.080 --> 10:59:14.720
She read over her aunt's commendation of him again and again.

10:59:15.200 --> 10:59:17.620
It was hardly enough, but it pleased her.

10:59:17.880 --> 10:59:22.140
She was even sensible of some pleasure, though mixed with regret,

10:59:22.140 --> 10:59:27.080
on finding how steadfastly both she and her uncle had been persuaded

10:59:27.080 --> 10:59:32.540
that affection and confidence subsisted between Mr. Darcy and herself.

10:59:33.480 --> 10:59:37.840
She was roused from her seat and her reflections by someones approach,

10:59:38.180 --> 10:59:42.800
and before she could strike into another path she was overtaken by Wickham.

10:59:43.960 --> 10:59:49.780
I am afraid I interrupt your solitary ramble, my dear sister, said he as he joined her.

10:59:50.560 --> 10:59:53.360
You certainly do, she replied with a smile,

10:59:53.580 --> 10:59:57.040
but it does not follow that the interruption must be unwelcome.

10:59:57.920 --> 11:00:00.020
I should be sorry indeed if it were.

11:00:00.360 --> 11:00:03.060
We were always good friends, and now we are better.

11:00:04.020 --> 11:00:05.920
True, are the others coming out?

11:00:06.300 --> 11:00:07.620
I do not know.

11:00:07.980 --> 11:00:11.200
Mrs. Bennet and Lydia are going in the carriage to Meryton,

11:00:11.420 --> 11:00:17.200
and so, my dear sister, I find from our uncle and aunt that you have actually seen Pemberley.

11:00:18.000 --> 11:00:19.960
She replied in the affirmative.

11:00:20.860 --> 11:00:25.140
I almost envy you the pleasure, and yet I believe it would be too much for me,

11:00:25.240 --> 11:00:28.440
or else I could take it in my way to Newcastle.

11:00:28.620 --> 11:00:32.360
And you saw the old housekeeper, I suppose, poor Reynolds.

11:00:32.600 --> 11:00:37.440
She was always very fond of me, but of course she did not mention my name to you.

11:00:37.820 --> 11:00:40.540
Yes, she did. And what did she say?

11:00:41.280 --> 11:00:46.580
That you had gone into the army, and she was afraid had not turned out well.

11:00:46.580 --> 11:00:51.140
At such a distance as that, you know, things are strangely misrepresented.

11:00:52.320 --> 11:00:54.840
Certainly, he replied, biting his lips.

11:00:55.520 --> 11:00:59.440
Elizabeth hoped she had silenced him, but a soon afterwards said,

11:00:59.900 --> 11:01:02.600
I was surprised to see Darcy in town last month.

11:01:02.900 --> 11:01:04.900
We passed each other several times.

11:01:05.420 --> 11:01:07.400
I wonder what he can be doing there.

11:01:08.720 --> 11:01:12.420
Perhaps preparing for his marriage with Miss de Bourgh, said Elizabeth,

11:01:12.420 --> 11:01:16.460
It must be something particular to take him there at this time of the year.

11:01:17.580 --> 11:01:20.300
Undoubtedly. Did you see him while you were at Lambton?

11:01:20.900 --> 11:01:23.800
I thought I understood from the gardeners that you had.

11:01:25.200 --> 11:01:27.460
Yes, he introduced us to his sister.

11:01:28.000 --> 11:01:29.460
And do you like her?

11:01:29.640 --> 11:01:30.500
Very much.

11:01:31.020 --> 11:01:35.400
I have heard, indeed, that she is uncommonly improved within this year or two.

11:01:36.100 --> 11:01:38.760
When I last saw her, she was not very promising.

11:01:38.760 --> 11:01:42.680
I am very glad you liked her. I hope she will turn out well.

11:01:43.300 --> 11:01:44.960
I daresay she will.

11:01:45.620 --> 11:01:48.300
She has got over the most trying age.

11:01:49.320 --> 11:01:51.400
Did you go by the village of Kimpton?

11:01:51.760 --> 11:01:53.700
I do not recollect that we did.

11:01:54.060 --> 11:01:57.400
I mention it because it is the living which I ought to have had.

11:01:57.820 --> 11:02:01.500
A most delightful place. Excellent parsonage house.

11:02:01.940 --> 11:02:04.380
It would have suited me in every respect.

11:02:05.460 --> 11:02:08.600
How should you have liked making sermons?

11:02:09.260 --> 11:02:13.280
Exceedingly well. I should have considered it as part of my duty,

11:02:13.560 --> 11:02:15.920
and the exertion would soon have been nothing.

11:02:16.440 --> 11:02:21.680
One ought not to repine, but to be sure it would have been such a thing for me.

11:02:22.960 --> 11:02:28.380
The quiet, the retirement of such a life would have answered all my ideas of happiness.

11:02:28.820 --> 11:02:30.280
But it was not to be.

11:02:30.280 --> 11:02:34.360
Did you ever hear Darcy mention the circumstance when you were in Kent?

11:02:35.660 --> 11:02:38.760
I have heard from authority, which I thought as good,

11:02:39.020 --> 11:02:44.760
that it was left to you conditionally only, and at will of the present patron.

11:02:45.900 --> 11:02:49.100
You have. Yes, there was something in that.

11:02:49.360 --> 11:02:52.260
I told you so from the first you may remember.

11:02:53.680 --> 11:02:59.580
I did hear, too, that there was a time when sermon-making was not so palatable to you,

11:02:59.580 --> 11:03:06.000
as it seems to be at present, that you actually declared your resolution of never taking orders,

11:03:06.180 --> 11:03:08.940
and that the business had been compromised accordingly.

11:03:10.480 --> 11:03:14.340
You did, and it was not wholly without foundation.

11:03:15.100 --> 11:03:19.540
You may remember what I told you on that point, when first we talked of it.

11:03:20.440 --> 11:03:25.640
They were now almost at the door of the house, for she had walked fast to get rid of him,

11:03:25.640 --> 11:03:32.360
and unwilling, for her sister's sake, to provoke him, she only said in reply with a good-humoured smile.

11:03:33.060 --> 11:03:36.420
Come, Mr. Wickham, we are brother and sister, you know.

11:03:36.680 --> 11:03:42.380
Do not let us quarrel about the past. In future, I hope we shall be always of one mind.

11:03:43.120 --> 11:03:47.100
She a held out her hand. He kissed it with affectionate gallantry,

11:03:47.460 --> 11:03:50.800
though he hardly knew how to look, and they entered the house.

11:03:56.440 --> 11:04:03.100
Mr. Wickham was so perfectly satisfied with this conversation that he never again distressed himself,

11:04:03.540 --> 11:04:08.160
or provoked his dear sister Elizabeth by introducing the subject of it,

11:04:08.360 --> 11:04:12.400
and she was pleased to find that she had said enough to keep him quiet.

11:04:13.760 --> 11:04:16.980
The day of his and Lydia's departure soon came,

11:04:16.980 --> 11:04:20.520
and Mrs. Bennet was forced to submit to a separation,

11:04:21.040 --> 11:04:25.980
which, as her husband by no means entered into her scheme of their all going to Newcastle,

11:04:26.740 --> 11:04:30.080
was likely to continue at least a twelfth month.

11:04:31.000 --> 11:04:37.160
Oh, my dear Lydia, she cried. When shall we meet again? Oh, Lord, I don't know.

11:04:37.420 --> 11:04:42.400
Not these two or three years, perhaps. Write to me very often, my dear.

11:04:43.060 --> 11:04:47.920
As often as I can, but you know married women have never much time for writing.

11:04:48.280 --> 11:04:52.200
My sisters may write to me. They will have nothing else to do.

11:04:53.480 --> 11:04:57.380
Mr. Wickham's goodbyes were much more affectionate than his wife's.

11:04:57.520 --> 11:05:01.140
He smiled, looked handsome, and said many pretty things.

11:05:02.260 --> 11:05:07.880
He is as fine a fellow, said Mr. Bennet, as soon as they were out of the house, as ever I saw.

11:05:07.880 --> 11:05:13.300
He simpers and smirks and makes love to us all. I am prodigiously proud of him.

11:05:14.020 --> 11:05:19.380
I defy even Sir William Lucas himself to produce a more valuable son-in-law.

11:05:20.400 --> 11:05:24.280
The loss of her daughter made Mrs. Bennet very dull for several days.

11:05:24.880 --> 11:05:29.460
I often think, said she, that there is nothing so bad as parting with one's friends.

11:05:29.940 --> 11:05:32.240
One seems so forlorn without them.

11:05:32.860 --> 11:05:37.840
This is the consequence, you see, madam, of marrying a daughter, said Elizabeth.

11:05:38.240 --> 11:05:42.040
It must make you better satisfied that your other daughters are single.

11:05:42.800 --> 11:05:47.020
It is no such thing. Lydia does not leave me because she is married,

11:05:47.020 --> 11:05:51.080
but only because her husband's regiment happens to be so far off.

11:05:51.420 --> 11:05:54.580
If that had been nearer, she would not have gone so soon.

11:05:55.300 --> 11:06:00.140
But the spiritless condition which this event threw her into was shortly relieved,

11:06:00.140 --> 11:06:05.040
and her mind opened again to the agitation of hope by an article of news

11:06:05.040 --> 11:06:07.680
which then began to be in circulation.

11:06:09.200 --> 11:06:14.240
The housekeeper at Netherfield had received orders to prepare for the return of her master,

11:06:14.680 --> 11:06:19.080
who was coming down in a day or two to shoot there for several weeks.

11:06:19.580 --> 11:06:21.820
Mrs. Bennet was quite in the fidgets.

11:06:22.420 --> 11:06:26.060
She looked at Jane and smiled, and shook her head by turns.

11:06:26.060 --> 11:06:30.180
Well, well, and so Mr. Bingley is coming down, sister,

11:06:30.500 --> 11:06:32.920
for Mrs. Phillips first brought her the news.

11:06:34.140 --> 11:06:37.980
Well, so much the better. Not that I care about it, though.

11:06:38.140 --> 11:06:42.260
He is nothing to us, you know, and I am sure I never want to see him again.

11:06:42.700 --> 11:06:47.040
But, however, he is very welcome to come to Netherfield if he likes it.

11:06:47.220 --> 11:06:50.940
And who knows what may happen, but that is nothing to us.

11:06:51.200 --> 11:06:55.660
You know, sister, we agreed long ago never to mention a word about it.

11:06:55.660 --> 11:06:58.540
And so is it quite certain he is coming?

11:06:59.540 --> 11:07:04.140
You may depend on it, replied the other, for Mrs. Nichols was in Meryton last night.

11:07:04.540 --> 11:07:08.920
I saw her passing by and went out myself on purpose to know the truth of it,

11:07:09.240 --> 11:07:11.660
and she told me that it was certain true.

11:07:11.980 --> 11:07:16.360
He comes down on Thursday at the latest, very likely on Wednesday.

11:07:16.820 --> 11:07:21.920
She was going to the butcher's, she told me, on purpose to order in some meat on Wednesday,

11:07:21.920 --> 11:07:26.140
and she has got three couple of ducks just fit to be killed.

11:07:27.140 --> 11:07:30.840
Miss Bennet had not been able to hear of his coming without changing colour.

11:07:31.340 --> 11:07:34.500
It was many months since she had mentioned his name to Elizabeth,

11:07:34.900 --> 11:07:37.880
but now, as soon as they were alone together, she said,

11:07:38.740 --> 11:07:42.860
I saw you look at me today, Lizzie, when my aunt told us of the present report,

11:07:43.180 --> 11:07:45.380
and I know I appeared distressed.

11:07:45.740 --> 11:07:48.900
But don't imagine it was from any silly cause.

11:07:48.900 --> 11:07:54.060
I was only confused for the moment because I felt that I should be looked at.

11:07:54.440 --> 11:07:59.220
I do assure you that the news does not affect me either with pleasure or pain.

11:07:59.640 --> 11:08:04.360
I am glad of one thing, that he comes alone, because we shall see less of him.

11:08:04.860 --> 11:08:09.440
Not that I am afraid of myself, but I dread other people's remarks.

11:08:10.880 --> 11:08:13.080
Elizabeth did not know what to make of it.

11:08:13.360 --> 11:08:15.060
Had she not seen him in Derbyshire,

11:08:15.060 --> 11:08:20.920
she might have supposed him capable of coming there with no other view than what was acknowledged.

11:08:21.940 --> 11:08:24.360
But she still thought him partial to Jane,

11:08:24.820 --> 11:08:30.620
and she wavered as to the greater probability of his coming there with his friend's permission,

11:08:30.900 --> 11:08:33.500
or being bold enough to come without it.

11:08:34.100 --> 11:08:36.380
Yet it is hard, she sometimes thought,

11:08:36.580 --> 11:08:43.180
that this poor man cannot come to a house which he has legally hired without raising all this speculation.

11:08:43.180 --> 11:08:46.300
I will leave him to himself.

11:08:47.700 --> 11:08:49.880
In spite of what her sister declared,

11:08:50.000 --> 11:08:54.260
and really believed to be her feelings in the expectation of his arrival,

11:08:54.900 --> 11:08:59.240
Elizabeth could easily perceive that her spirits were affected by it.

11:08:59.620 --> 11:09:04.720
They were more disturbed, more unequal than she had often seen them.

11:09:05.260 --> 11:09:10.290
The subject which had been so warmly canvassed between their parents before,

11:09:10.290 --> 11:09:15.170
about a twelfth month ago, was now brought forward again.

11:09:16.050 --> 11:09:19.730
As soon as ever Mr. Bingley comes, my dear, said Mrs. Bennet,

11:09:19.950 --> 11:09:22.210
you will have to wait on him, of course.

11:09:22.770 --> 11:09:25.890
No, no, you forced me into visiting him last year,

11:09:26.150 --> 11:09:30.350
and promised if I went to see him he should marry one of my daughters.

11:09:30.690 --> 11:09:35.290
But it ended in nothing, and I will not be sent on a fool's errand again.

11:09:36.130 --> 11:09:42.030
His wife represented to him how absolutely necessary such an attention would be

11:09:42.030 --> 11:09:45.930
from all the neighbouring gentlemen on his return to Netherfield.

11:09:46.910 --> 11:09:49.470
"'Tis an etiquette I despise," said he.

11:09:49.650 --> 11:09:52.370
"'If he wants our society, let him seek it.

11:09:52.490 --> 11:09:53.750
He knows where we live.

11:09:53.930 --> 11:09:57.270
I will not spend my hours in running after my neighbours

11:09:57.270 --> 11:09:59.850
every time they go away and come back again.

11:09:59.850 --> 11:10:05.550
Well, all I know is that it will be abominably rude if you do not wait on him.

11:10:06.410 --> 11:10:10.790
But, however, that shan't prevent my asking him to dine here, I am determined.

11:10:11.250 --> 11:10:14.570
We must have Mrs. Long and the goldings soon.

11:10:14.850 --> 11:10:19.860
That will make thirteen with ourselves, so there will be just room at table for him.'

11:10:20.670 --> 11:10:26.030
Consoled by this resolution, she was the better able to bear her husband's incivility,

11:10:26.030 --> 11:10:31.070
though it was very mortifying to know that her neighbours might all see Mr. Bingley

11:10:31.070 --> 11:10:36.790
in consequence of it before they did, as the day of his arrival drew near.

11:10:37.210 --> 11:10:41.390
"'I begin to be sorry that he comes at all,' said Jane to her sister.

11:10:41.690 --> 11:10:42.710
It would be nothing.

11:10:42.790 --> 11:10:49.390
I could see him with perfect indifference, but I can hardly bear to hear it thus perpetually talked of.

11:10:49.770 --> 11:10:52.330
My mother means well, but she does not know.

11:10:52.330 --> 11:10:56.190
No one can know how much I suffer from what she says.

11:10:56.590 --> 11:11:00.670
Happy shall I be when his stay at Netherfield is over.'

11:11:01.210 --> 11:11:04.590
"'I wish I could say anything to comfort you,' replied Elizabeth.

11:11:05.130 --> 11:11:07.230
But it is wholly out of my power.

11:11:07.530 --> 11:11:14.350
You must feel it, and the usual satisfaction of preaching patience to a sufferer is denied me,

11:11:14.450 --> 11:11:17.910
because you have always so much.'

11:11:17.910 --> 11:11:19.710
Mr. Bingley arrived.

11:11:19.710 --> 11:11:25.730
Mrs. Bennet, through the assistance of servants, contrived to have the earliest tidings of it

11:11:25.730 --> 11:11:31.390
that the period of anxiety and fretfulness on her side might be as long as it could.

11:11:31.950 --> 11:11:36.830
She counted the days that must intervene before their invitation could be sent,

11:11:37.150 --> 11:11:38.990
hopeless of seeing him before.

11:11:39.470 --> 11:11:42.770
But on the third morning, after his arrival in Hertfordshire,

11:11:43.170 --> 11:11:48.090
she saw him, from her dressing-room window, enter the paddock and ride towards the house.

11:11:48.090 --> 11:11:51.790
Her daughters were eagerly called to partake of her joy.

11:11:53.130 --> 11:11:59.030
Jane resolutely kept her place at the table, but Elizabeth, to satisfy her mother, went to the window.

11:11:59.510 --> 11:12:04.490
She looked, she saw Mr. Darcy with him, and sat down again by her sister.

11:12:05.630 --> 11:12:08.070
"'There is a gentleman with him, Mama,' said Kitty.

11:12:08.330 --> 11:12:09.810
Who can it be?'

11:12:09.810 --> 11:12:12.470
"'Some acquaintance or other, my dear, I suppose.

11:12:12.550 --> 11:12:14.850
I am sure I do not know.'

11:12:14.850 --> 11:12:16.410
"'La,' replied Kitty,

11:12:16.450 --> 11:12:20.030
"'it looks just like that man that used to be with him before.

11:12:20.550 --> 11:12:23.850
Mr.—what's his name?—that tall, proud man.

11:12:24.250 --> 11:12:26.290
Good gracious, Mr. Darcy!

11:12:26.470 --> 11:12:28.010
And so it does, I vow.

11:12:28.450 --> 11:12:32.850
Well, any friend of Mr. Bingley's will always be welcome here, to be sure,

11:12:33.110 --> 11:12:36.850
but else I must say that I hate the very sight of him.'

11:12:37.510 --> 11:12:40.630
Jane looked at Elizabeth with surprise and concern.

11:12:41.010 --> 11:12:43.670
She knew but little of their meeting in Derbyshire,

11:12:43.670 --> 11:12:48.010
and therefore felt for the awkwardness which must attend her sister

11:12:48.010 --> 11:12:53.390
in seeing him almost for the first time after receiving his explanatory letter.

11:12:54.310 --> 11:12:56.830
Both sisters were uncomfortable enough.

11:12:57.290 --> 11:12:59.830
Each felt for the other, and of course for themselves,

11:13:00.530 --> 11:13:04.010
and their mother talked on of her dislike for Mr. Darcy

11:13:04.010 --> 11:13:08.570
and her resolution to be civil to him only as Mr. Bingley's friend,

11:13:08.870 --> 11:13:11.110
without being heard by either of them.

11:13:12.070 --> 11:13:17.010
But Elizabeth had sources of uneasiness which could not be suspected by Jane

11:13:17.010 --> 11:13:21.050
to whom she had never yet had courage to show Mrs. Gardiner's letter

11:13:21.050 --> 11:13:25.090
or to relate her own change of sentiment towards him.

11:13:25.590 --> 11:13:29.650
To Jane he could be only a man whose proposals she had refused

11:13:29.650 --> 11:13:32.410
and whose merit she had undervalued,

11:13:32.410 --> 11:13:37.250
but to her own more extensive information he was the person

11:13:37.250 --> 11:13:41.350
to whom the whole family were indebted for the first of benefits

11:13:41.350 --> 11:13:46.290
and whom she regarded herself with an interest, if not quite so tender,

11:13:46.970 --> 11:13:51.350
at least as reasonable and just as what Jane felt for Bingley.

11:13:51.910 --> 11:13:55.630
Her astonishment at his coming, at his coming to Netherfield,

11:13:55.690 --> 11:13:59.270
to Longbourn, and voluntarily seeking her again,

11:13:59.550 --> 11:14:02.590
was almost equal to what she had known on first witnessing

11:14:02.590 --> 11:14:04.950
his altered behaviour in Derbyshire.

11:14:04.950 --> 11:14:09.530
The colour which had been driven from her face returned for half a minute

11:14:09.530 --> 11:14:14.450
with an additional glow, and a smile of delight added luster to her eyes,

11:14:14.770 --> 11:14:18.470
as she thought for that space of time that his affection and wishes

11:14:18.470 --> 11:14:20.470
must still be unshaken.

11:14:21.690 --> 11:14:23.430
But she would not be secure.

11:14:24.270 --> 11:14:26.990
Let me first see how he behaves, said she.

11:14:27.230 --> 11:14:29.850
It will then be early enough for expectation.

11:14:30.650 --> 11:14:34.910
She sat intently at work, striving to be composed,

11:14:35.210 --> 11:14:37.630
and without daring to lift up her eyes,

11:14:38.030 --> 11:14:41.630
till anxious curiosity carried them to the face of her sister

11:14:41.630 --> 11:14:43.850
as the servant was approaching the door.

11:14:44.490 --> 11:14:46.710
Jane looked a little paler than usual,

11:14:47.010 --> 11:14:49.610
but more sedate than Elizabeth had expected.

11:14:50.770 --> 11:14:53.730
On the gentleman's appearing her colour increased,

11:14:54.170 --> 11:14:56.670
yet she received them with tolerable ease

11:14:56.670 --> 11:15:01.070
and with a propriety of behaviour equally free from any symptom

11:15:01.070 --> 11:15:04.910
of resentment or any unnecessary complacence.

11:15:05.410 --> 11:15:09.050
Elizabeth said as little to either as civility would allow,

11:15:09.350 --> 11:15:12.110
and sat down again to her at work with an eagerness

11:15:12.110 --> 11:15:14.110
which it did not often command.

11:15:14.730 --> 11:15:17.290
She had ventured only one glance at Darcy.

11:15:17.910 --> 11:15:21.050
He looked serious as usual, and, she thought,

11:15:21.250 --> 11:15:24.670
more as he had been used to look in Hertfordshire

11:15:24.670 --> 11:15:26.850
than she had seen him at Pemberley.

11:15:27.590 --> 11:15:30.370
But perhaps he could not, in her mother's presence,

11:15:30.750 --> 11:15:33.150
be what he was before her uncle and aunt.

11:15:33.650 --> 11:15:37.450
It was a painful but not an improbable conjecture.

11:15:39.250 --> 11:15:41.730
Bingley she had likewise seen for an instant,

11:15:42.010 --> 11:15:46.270
and in that short period saw him looking both pleased and embarrassed.

11:15:46.710 --> 11:15:49.910
He was received by Mrs. Bennet with a civility

11:15:49.910 --> 11:15:52.390
which made her two daughters ashamed,

11:15:53.230 --> 11:15:56.650
especially when contrasted with the cold and ceremonious

11:15:57.030 --> 11:16:00.190
politeness of her curtsy and address to his friend.

11:16:01.450 --> 11:16:05.130
Elizabeth particularly, who knew that her mother owed to the latter

11:16:05.130 --> 11:16:10.410
the perservation of her favourite daughter from irremediable infamy,

11:16:10.790 --> 11:16:13.790
was hurt and distressed to a most painful degree

11:16:13.790 --> 11:16:16.710
by a distinction so ill applied.

11:16:18.270 --> 11:16:21.990
Darcy, after inquiring of her how Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner did,

11:16:21.990 --> 11:16:25.490
a question which she could not answer without confusion,

11:16:25.970 --> 11:16:27.370
said scarcely anything.

11:16:28.550 --> 11:16:32.890
He was not seated by her, perhaps that was the reason of his silence,

11:16:33.230 --> 11:16:35.390
but it had not been so in Derbyshire.

11:16:35.990 --> 11:16:39.870
There he had talked to her friends when he could not to herself,

11:16:40.650 --> 11:16:44.490
but now several minutes elapsed without bringing the sound of his voice,

11:16:44.710 --> 11:16:48.890
and when occasionally unable to resist the impulse of curiosity

11:16:48.890 --> 11:16:52.110
she raised her eyes to his face,

11:16:52.410 --> 11:16:55.590
she has often found him looking at Jane as at herself,

11:16:55.990 --> 11:16:58.970
and frequently on no object but the ground.

11:17:00.270 --> 11:17:03.510
More thoughtfulness and less anxiety to please

11:17:03.510 --> 11:17:07.050
than when they had last met were plainly expressed.

11:17:07.770 --> 11:17:11.250
She was disappointed and angry with herself for being so.

11:17:11.750 --> 11:17:14.410
Could I expect it to be otherwise, said she.

11:17:15.090 --> 11:17:16.630
Yet why did he come?

11:17:16.630 --> 11:17:20.770
She was in no humour for conversation with anyone but himself,

11:17:21.110 --> 11:17:23.710
and to him she had hardly courage to speak.

11:17:24.430 --> 11:17:27.510
She inquired after his sister, but could do no more.

11:17:28.030 --> 11:17:32.430
It is a long time, Mr. Bingley, since you went away, said Mrs. Bennet.

11:17:32.690 --> 11:17:34.230
He readily agreed to it.

11:17:34.450 --> 11:17:37.250
I began to be afraid you would never come back.

11:17:37.630 --> 11:17:41.430
People did say you meant to quit the place entirely at Michaelmas,

11:17:41.490 --> 11:17:44.490
but, however, I hope it is not true.

11:17:44.490 --> 11:17:49.130
A great many changes have happened in the neighbourhood since you went away.

11:17:49.630 --> 11:17:53.330
Miss Lucas is married and settled, and one of my own daughters.

11:17:53.530 --> 11:17:55.410
I suppose you have heard of it.

11:17:55.570 --> 11:17:57.790
Indeed, you must have seen it in the papers.

11:17:58.170 --> 11:18:01.290
It was in the Times and the Courier, I know,

11:18:01.470 --> 11:18:03.950
though it was not put in as it ought to be.

11:18:04.270 --> 11:18:09.450
It was only said lately George Wickham to Miss Lydia Bennet,

11:18:09.590 --> 11:18:12.110
without there being a syllable said of her father

11:18:12.110 --> 11:18:14.370
or the place where she lived or anything.

11:18:14.810 --> 11:18:17.270
It was my brother Gardiner's drawing up too,

11:18:17.430 --> 11:18:21.290
and I wonder how he came to make such an awkward business of it.

11:18:21.430 --> 11:18:22.570
Did you see it?

11:18:22.810 --> 11:18:25.850
Bingley replied that he did, and made his congratulations.

11:18:26.550 --> 11:18:28.830
Elizabeth dare not lift up her eyes.

11:18:29.110 --> 11:18:32.150
How Mr. Darcy looked, therefore, she could not tell.

11:18:33.270 --> 11:18:37.150
It is a delightful thing to be sure to have a daughter well married,

11:18:37.330 --> 11:18:40.550
continued her mother, but at the same time, Mr. Bingley,

11:18:40.550 --> 11:18:44.050
it is very hard to have her taken such away from me.

11:18:44.990 --> 11:18:49.410
They are gone down to Newcastle, a place quite northward, it seems,

11:18:49.470 --> 11:18:52.150
and they are to stay, I do not know how long.

11:18:52.430 --> 11:18:56.750
His regiment is there, for I suppose you have heard of his leaving the militia,

11:18:56.990 --> 11:18:59.590
and of his being gone into the regulars.

11:19:00.110 --> 11:19:05.430
Thank heavens he has some friends, though perhaps not so many as he deserves.

11:19:06.630 --> 11:19:09.390
Elizabeth, who knew this to be levelled at Mr. Darcy,

11:19:09.390 --> 11:19:13.230
was in such misery of shame that she could hardly keep her seat.

11:19:13.750 --> 11:19:16.530
It drew from her, however, the exertion of speaking,

11:19:16.970 --> 11:19:20.350
which nothing else had so effectually done before,

11:19:20.670 --> 11:19:24.710
and she asked Bingley whether he meant to make any stay in the country at present.

11:19:25.310 --> 11:19:26.830
A few weeks, he believed.

11:19:27.750 --> 11:19:31.430
When you have killed all your own birds, Mr. Bingley, said her mother,

11:19:31.610 --> 11:19:36.590
I beg you will come here and shoot as many as you please on Mr. Bennet's manor.

11:19:36.590 --> 11:19:39.890
I am sure he will be vastly happy to oblige you,

11:19:39.990 --> 11:19:42.970
and will save all the best of the covies for you.

11:19:44.450 --> 11:19:49.630
Elizabeth's misery increased at such unnecessary, such officious attention.

11:19:50.230 --> 11:19:55.190
Were the same fair prospect to arise at present as had flattered them a year ago,

11:19:55.570 --> 11:20:00.670
everything she was persuaded would be hastening to the same vexatious conclusion.

11:20:01.090 --> 11:20:04.470
At that instant she felt that years of happiness

11:20:04.470 --> 11:20:09.910
could not make Jane or herself and men's for moments of such painful confusion.

11:20:11.030 --> 11:20:13.510
The first wish of my heart, said she to herself,

11:20:13.590 --> 11:20:16.510
is never more to be in company with either of them.

11:20:16.910 --> 11:20:21.650
Their society can afford no pleasure that will atone for such wretchedness as this.

11:20:22.250 --> 11:20:25.290
Let me never see either one or the other again.

11:20:26.350 --> 11:20:30.630
Yet the misery for which years of happiness were to offer no compensation

11:20:30.630 --> 11:20:35.270
received soon afterwards material relief from observing

11:20:35.270 --> 11:20:40.310
how much the beauty of her sister rekindled the admiration of her former lover.

11:20:41.230 --> 11:20:44.310
When first he came in he had spoken to her but little,

11:20:44.690 --> 11:20:48.910
but every five minutes seemed to be giving her more of his attention.

11:20:50.690 --> 11:20:53.910
He found her as handsome as she had been last year,

11:20:54.210 --> 11:20:59.090
as good-natured and as unaffected, though not quite so chatty.

11:20:59.090 --> 11:21:03.190
Jane was anxious that no difference should be perceived in her at all

11:21:03.190 --> 11:21:06.510
and was really persuaded that she talked as much as ever,

11:21:06.870 --> 11:21:11.950
but her mind was so busily engaged that she did not always know when she was silent.

11:21:12.650 --> 11:21:18.430
When the gentleman rose to go away, Mrs. Bennet was mindful of her intended civility

11:21:18.430 --> 11:21:23.710
and they were invited and engaged to dine at Longbourn in a few days' time.

11:21:23.710 --> 11:21:28.230
You are quite a visit in my debt, Mr. Bingley, she added,

11:21:28.510 --> 11:21:34.530
for when you went to town last winter you promised to take a family dinner with us as soon as you returned.

11:21:35.110 --> 11:21:39.510
I have not forgot you, see, and I assure you I was very disappointed

11:21:39.510 --> 11:21:42.430
that you did not come back and keep your engagement.

11:21:43.470 --> 11:21:47.770
Bingley looked a little silly at this reflection and said something of his concern

11:21:47.770 --> 11:21:51.510
at having been prevented by business. Then they went away.

11:21:52.170 --> 11:21:57.410
Mrs. Bennet had been strongly inclined to ask them to stay and dine there that day,

11:21:57.770 --> 11:22:00.230
but though she always kept a very good table,

11:22:00.630 --> 11:22:04.570
she did not think anything less than two courses would be good enough

11:22:04.570 --> 11:22:07.830
for a man on whom she had such anxious designs

11:22:08.270 --> 11:22:13.170
or satisfy the appetite and pride of one who had ten thousand a year.

11:22:43.430 --> 11:22:53.890
As soon as they were gone, Elizabeth walked out to recover her spirits, or, in other words, to dwell without interruption on those subjects that must deaden them more.

11:22:54.510 --> 11:22:57.510
Mr. Darcy's behavior astonished and vexed her.

11:22:57.930 --> 11:23:07.270
Why, if he came only to be silent, grave, and indifferent, said she, did he come at all? She could settle it in no way that gave her pleasure.

11:23:07.950 --> 11:23:20.730
He could be still amiable, still pleasing, to my uncle and aunt when he was in town, and why not to me? If he fears me, why come hither? If he no longer cares for me, why silent?

11:23:21.450 --> 11:23:25.010
Teasing, teasing, man, I will think no more about him.

11:23:25.010 --> 11:23:37.050
Her resolution was for a short time involuntarily kept by the approach of her sister, who joined her with a cheerful look, which showed her better satisfied with their visitors than Elizabeth.

11:23:38.130 --> 11:23:48.510
Now, said she, that this first meeting is over, I feel perfectly easy. I know my own strength, and I shall never be embarrassed again by his coming.

11:23:48.510 --> 11:23:58.730
I am glad he dines here on Tuesday. It will then be publicly seen that, on both sides, we meet only as common and indifferent acquaintance.

11:23:59.490 --> 11:24:06.070
Yes, very indifferent indeed, said Elizabeth laughingly. Oh, Jane, take care.

11:24:07.030 --> 11:24:17.970
My dear Lizzie, you cannot think me so weak as to be in danger now. I think you are in very great danger of making him as much in love with you as ever.

11:24:18.750 --> 11:24:32.390
They did not see the gentlemen again till Tuesday, and Mrs. Bennet in the meanwhile was giving way to all the happy schemes which the good humor and common politeness of Bingley and half an hour's visit had revived.

11:24:33.110 --> 11:24:44.510
On Tuesday there was a large party assembled at Longbourn, and the two who were most anxiously expected, to the credit of their punctuality as sportsmen, were in very good time.

11:24:44.510 --> 11:24:56.290
When they repaired to the dining room, Elizabeth eagerly watched to see whether Bingley would take the place which, in all their former parties, had belonged to him by her sister.

11:24:56.930 --> 11:25:03.170
Her prudent mother, occupied by the same ideas, forebore to invite him to sit by herself.

11:25:03.170 --> 11:25:14.390
On entering the room he seemed to hesitate, but Jane happened to look round and happened to smile. It was decided. He placed himself by her.

11:25:15.390 --> 11:25:31.170
Elizabeth, with a triumphant sensation, looked towards his friend. He bore it with noble indifference, and she would have imagined that Bingley had received his sanction to be happy had she not seen his eyes likewise turned towards Mr. Darcy,

11:25:31.170 --> 11:25:52.130
with an expression of half-laughing alarm. His behavior to her sister was such, during dinnertime, as showed an admiration of her which, though more guarded than formerly, persuaded Elizabeth that if left wholly to himself, Jane's happiness and his own would be speedily secured.

11:25:52.130 --> 11:26:05.770
Though she dared not depend upon the consequence, she yet received pleasure from observing his behavior. It gave her all the animation that her spirits could boast, for she was in no cheerful humor.

11:26:06.570 --> 11:26:19.090
Mr. Darcy was almost as far from her as the table could divide them. He was on one side of her mother. She knew how little such a situation would give pleasure to either or make either appear to advantage.

11:26:19.090 --> 11:26:29.190
She was not near enough to hear any of their discourse, but she could see how seldom they spoke to each other, and how formal and cold was their manner whenever they did.

11:26:29.830 --> 11:26:44.490
Her mother's ungraciousness made the sense of what they owed him more painful to Elizabeth's mind, and she would at times have given anything to be privileged to tell him that his kindness was neither unknown nor unfelt by the whole of the family.

11:26:44.490 --> 11:27:00.170
She was in hopes that the evening would afford some opportunity of bringing them together, that the whole of the visit would not pass away without enabling them to enter into something more of conversation than the mere ceremonious salutation attending his entrance.

11:27:00.970 --> 11:27:10.450
Anxious and uneasy, the period which passed in the drawing room before the gentleman came was wearisome and dull to a degree that almost made her uncivil.

11:27:11.210 --> 11:27:17.050
She looked forward to their entrance, as the point on which all her chance of pleasure for the evening must depend.

11:27:17.710 --> 11:27:22.750
If he does not come to me then, said she, I shall give him up for ever.

11:27:23.490 --> 11:27:27.930
The gentleman came, and she thought he looked as if he would have answered her hopes.

11:27:28.350 --> 11:27:42.510
But, alas, the ladies had crowded round the table where Miss Bennet was making tea, and Elizabeth pouring out the coffee, in so close a confederacy that there was not a single vacancy near her which would admit of a chair.

11:27:42.510 --> 11:27:49.030
And on the gentleman's approaching, one of the girls moved closer to her than ever, and said in a whisper,

11:27:49.850 --> 11:27:54.730
The men shan't come and part us, I am determined. We want none of them, do we?

11:27:55.910 --> 11:28:10.570
Darcy had walked away to another part of the room. She followed him with her eyes, envied everyone to whom he spoke, had scarcely patience enough to help anybody to coffee, and then was enraged against herself for being so silly.

11:28:10.570 --> 11:28:28.430
A man who has once been refused! How could I ever be foolish enough to expect a renewal of his love? Is there one among the sex who would not protest against such a weakness as a second proposal to the same woman? There is no indignity so abhorrent to their feelings.

11:28:28.430 --> 11:28:45.750
She was a little revived, however, by his bringing back his coffee cup himself, and she seized the opportunity of saying, Is your sister at Pemberley still? Yes, she will remain there till Christmas. And quite alone? Have all her friends left her?

11:28:45.750 --> 11:28:58.810
Mrs. Annesley is with her. The others have been gone on to Scarborough these three weeks. She could think of nothing more to say, but if he wished to converse with her, he might have better success.

11:28:58.810 --> 11:29:08.550
He stood by her, however, for some minutes in silence, and, at last, on the young ladies whispering to Elizabeth again, he walked away.

11:29:08.550 --> 11:29:29.070
When the teethings were removed, and the card tables placed, the ladies all rose, and Elizabeth was then hoping to be soon joined by him, when all her views were overthrown by seeing him fall a victim to her mother's rapacity for wist-players, and in a few moments after, seated with the rest of the party.

11:29:29.070 --> 11:29:45.290
She now lost every expectation of pleasure. They were confined for the evening at different tables, and she had nothing to hope but that his eyes were so often turned towards her side of the room as to make him play as unsuccessfully as herself.

11:29:46.330 --> 11:29:58.150
Mrs. Bennet had designed to keep the two Netherfield gentlemen to supper, but their carriage was unluckily ordered before any of the others, and she had no opportunity of detaining them.

11:29:59.010 --> 11:30:18.230
Well, girls, said she, as soon as they were left to themselves, what say you to the day? I think everything has passed off uncommonly well, I assure you. The dinner was as well dressed as any eye ever saw. The venison was roasted to a turn, and everybody said they never saw so fat a haunch.

11:30:18.230 --> 11:30:30.790
The soup was fifty times better than what we had at the Lucas's last week, and even Mr. Darcy acknowledged that the partridges were remarkably well done, and I suppose he has two or three French cooks at least.

11:30:31.230 --> 11:30:44.910
And, my dear Jane, I never saw you looking greater beauty. Mrs. Long said so too, for I asked her whether you did not, and what do you think she said besides? Ah, Mrs. Bennet, we shall have her at Netherfield at last.

11:30:44.910 --> 11:30:56.890
She did indeed. I do think Mrs. Long is as good a creature as ever lived, and her nieces are very pretty behaved girls, and not at all handsome. I like them prodigiously.

11:30:57.770 --> 11:31:19.950
Mrs. Bennet, in short, was in very great spirits. She had seen enough of Bingley's behavior to Jane to be convinced that she would get him at last, and her expectations of advantage to her family, when in a happy humor, were so far beyond reason that she was quite disappointed at not seeing him there again the next day to make his proposals.

11:31:19.950 --> 11:31:32.890
It has been a very agreeable day, said Miss Bennet to Elizabeth. The party seems so well selected, so suitable one with the other. I hope we may often meet again.

11:31:32.890 --> 11:31:35.250
Elizabeth smiled.

11:32:07.130 --> 11:32:25.770
You are very cruel, said her sister. You will not let me smile and are provoking me to it every moment. How hard it is in some cases to be believed, and how impossible in others. But why should you wish to persuade me that I feel more than I acknowledge?

11:32:25.770 --> 11:32:41.350
That is a question which I hardly know how to answer. We all love to instruct, though we can teach only what is not worth knowing. Forgive me, and if you persist in indifference, do not make me your confidant.

11:33:12.910 --> 11:33:18.390
A few days after this visit, Mr. Bingley called again, and alone.

11:33:19.230 --> 11:33:24.970
His friend had left him that morning for London, but was to return home in ten days' time.

11:33:25.530 --> 11:33:30.130
He sat with them above an hour, and was in remarkably good spirits.

11:33:31.090 --> 11:33:39.150
Mrs. Bennet invited him to dine with them, but, with many expressions of concern, he confessed himself engaged elsewhere.

11:33:40.130 --> 11:33:44.710
Next time you call, said she, I hope we shall be more lucky.

11:33:45.550 --> 11:33:54.690
He should be particularly happy at any time, etc., etc., and if she would give him leave, would take an early opportunity of waiting on them.

11:33:55.290 --> 11:33:56.570
Can you come tomorrow?

11:33:57.550 --> 11:34:03.690
Yes, he had no engagement at all for tomorrow, and her invitation was accepted with alacrity.

11:34:04.330 --> 11:34:09.430
He came, and in such very good time, that the ladies were none of them dressed.

11:34:10.230 --> 11:34:16.930
In ran Mrs. Bennet to her daughter's room, in her dressing gown, and with her hair half finished, crying out,

11:34:17.250 --> 11:34:25.770
My dear Jane, make haste and hurry down, he is come, Mr. Bingley is come, he is indeed, make haste, make haste.

11:34:25.930 --> 11:34:29.350
Here, Sarah, come to Miss Bennet this moment, and help her on with her gown.

11:34:29.910 --> 11:34:31.470
Never mind Miss Lizzie's hair.

11:34:32.350 --> 11:34:41.610
We will be down as soon as we can, said Jane, but I dare say Kitty is forwarder than either of us, for she went upstairs half an hour ago.

11:34:42.550 --> 11:34:48.850
Oh, hang Kitty, what has she to do with it? Come, be quick, be quick, where is your sash, my dear?

11:34:49.930 --> 11:34:55.930
But when her mother was gone, Jane would not be prevailed on to go down without one of her sisters.

11:34:55.930 --> 11:35:01.690
The same anxiety to get them by themselves was visible again in the evening.

11:35:02.690 --> 11:35:10.050
After tea, Mr. Bennet retired to the library, as was his custom, and Mary went upstairs to her instrument.

11:35:10.970 --> 11:35:22.290
Two obstacles of the five being thus removed, Mrs. Bennet sat looking and winking at Elizabeth and Catherine for a considerable time without making any impression on them.

11:35:22.990 --> 11:35:28.790
Elizabeth would not observe her, and when at last Kitty did, she very innocently said,

11:35:29.250 --> 11:35:34.290
What is the matter, mamma? What do you keep winking at me for? What am I to do?

11:35:35.270 --> 11:35:37.930
Nothing, child, nothing. I did not wink at you.

11:35:38.670 --> 11:35:48.070
She then sat still five minutes longer, but, unable to waste such a precious occasion, she suddenly got up and saying to Kitty,

11:35:48.070 --> 11:35:53.030
Come here, my love, I want to speak to you, took her out of the room.

11:35:53.970 --> 11:36:03.090
Jane instantly gave a look at Elizabeth, which spoke her distress at such premeditation, and her entreaty that she would not give in to it.

11:36:03.690 --> 11:36:07.830
In a few minutes Mrs. Bennet half opened the door and called out,

11:36:08.150 --> 11:36:10.550
Lizzy, my dear, I want to speak with you.

11:36:11.590 --> 11:36:13.610
Elizabeth was forced to go.

11:36:13.610 --> 11:36:19.690
We may as well leave them by themselves, you know, said her mother as soon as she was in the hall.

11:36:20.190 --> 11:36:23.010
Kitty and I are going upstairs to sit in my dressing-room.

11:36:24.230 --> 11:36:34.630
Elizabeth made no attempt to reason with her mother, but remained quietly in the hall till she and Kitty were out of sight, then returned into the drawing-room.

11:36:35.590 --> 11:36:39.130
Mrs. Bennet's schemes for this day were ineffectual.

11:36:39.130 --> 11:36:45.010
Bingley was everything that was charming, except the professed lover of her daughter.

11:36:45.830 --> 11:36:55.890
His ease and cheerfulness rendered him a most agreeable addition to their evening party, and he bore with the ill-judged officiousness of the mother,

11:36:56.530 --> 11:37:03.870
and heard all her silly remarks with a forbearance and command of countenance particularly grateful to the daughter.

11:37:03.870 --> 11:37:11.890
He scarcely needed an invitation to stay supper, and before he went away an engagement was formed,

11:37:12.270 --> 11:37:18.150
chiefly through his own and Mrs. Bennet's means for his coming next morning to shoot with her husband.

11:37:19.350 --> 11:37:26.790
After this day Jane said no more of her indifference, not a word passed between the sisters concerning Bingley,

11:37:26.790 --> 11:37:37.030
but Elizabeth went to bed in the happy belief that all must speedily be concluded unless Mr. Darcy returned within the stated time.

11:37:38.030 --> 11:37:45.790
Seriously, however, she felt tolerably persuaded that all this must have taken place with that gentleman's concurrence.

11:37:46.730 --> 11:37:54.210
Bingley was punctual to his appointment, and he and Mr. Bennet spent the morning together, as had been agreed on.

11:37:54.210 --> 11:37:58.750
The latter was much more agreeable than his companion expected.

11:37:59.650 --> 11:38:06.990
There was nothing of presumption or folly in Bingley that could provoke his ridicule or disgust him into silence,

11:38:07.290 --> 11:38:12.850
and he was more communicative and less eccentric than the other had ever seen him.

11:38:13.670 --> 11:38:23.010
Bingley, of course, returned with him to dinner, and in the evening Mrs. Bennet's invention was again at work to get everybody away from him and her daughter.

11:38:24.050 --> 11:38:29.890
Elizabeth, who had a letter to write, went into the breakfast room for that purpose soon after tea,

11:38:30.390 --> 11:38:36.530
for as the others were all going to sit down to cards she could not be wanted to counteract her mother's schemes.

11:38:37.410 --> 11:38:44.110
But on returning to the drawing-room, when her letter was finished, she saw, to her infinite surprise,

11:38:44.530 --> 11:38:48.850
there was reason to fear that her mother had been too ingenious for her.

11:38:48.850 --> 11:38:58.490
On opening the door, she perceived her sister and Bingley standing together over the hearth, as if engaged in earnest conversation,

11:38:58.990 --> 11:39:08.510
and had this led to no suspicion, the faces of both, as they hastily turned round and moved away from each other, would have told it all.

11:39:09.270 --> 11:39:14.410
Their situation was awkward enough, but hers, she thought, was still worse.

11:39:14.410 --> 11:39:24.570
Not a syllable was uttered by either, and Elizabeth was on the point of going away again, when Bingley, who as well as the other had sat down,

11:39:25.010 --> 11:39:31.050
suddenly rose, and, whispering a few words to her sister, ran out of the room.

11:39:32.430 --> 11:39:37.270
Jane could have no reserves from Elizabeth, where confidence would give pleasure,

11:39:37.270 --> 11:39:45.350
and, instantly embracing her, acknowledged, with the liveliest emotion, that she was the happiest creature in the world.

11:39:46.030 --> 11:39:54.270
"'Tis too much," she added, "'by far too much. I do not deserve it. Oh, why is not everybody as happy?'

11:39:56.430 --> 11:40:05.190
Elizabeth's congratulations were given with a sincerity, a warmth, a delight, which words could but poorly express.

11:40:05.730 --> 11:40:10.110
Every sentence of kindness was a fresh source of happiness to Jane.

11:40:10.810 --> 11:40:16.790
But she would not allow herself to stay with her sister, or say half that remained to be said for the present.

11:40:17.250 --> 11:40:27.270
"'I must go instantly to my mother,' she cried. I would not on any account trifle with her affectionate solicitude, or allow her to hear it from anyone but myself.

11:40:27.270 --> 11:40:39.490
He has gone to my father already. Oh, Lizzie, to know what I have to relate will give such pleasure to all my dear family. How shall I bear so much happiness?'

11:40:39.490 --> 11:40:46.750
She then hastened away to her mother, who had purposely broken up the card-party, and was sitting upstairs with Kitty.

11:40:47.870 --> 11:41:00.770
Elizabeth, who was left by herself, now smiled at the rapidity and ease with which an affair was finally settled that had given them so many previous months of suspense and vexation.

11:41:01.370 --> 11:41:15.070
"'And this,' said she, "'is the end of all his friend's anxious circumspection, of all his sister's falsehood and contrivance, the happiest, wisest, most reasonable end.'

11:41:15.950 --> 11:41:22.490
In a few minutes she was joined by Bingley, whose conference with her father had been short and to the purpose.

11:41:22.930 --> 11:41:26.910
"'Where is your sister?' said he hastily as he opened the door.

11:41:27.510 --> 11:41:32.430
"'With my mother, upstairs. She will be down in a moment, I dare say.'

11:41:32.430 --> 11:41:39.090
He then shut the door, and, coming up to her, claimed the good wishes and affection of a sister.

11:41:40.110 --> 11:41:45.030
Elizabeth honestly and heartily expressed her delight in the prospect of their relationship.

11:41:45.830 --> 11:41:56.150
They shook hands with great cordiality, and then, till her sister came down, she had to listen to all he had to say of his own happiness and of Jane's perfections,

11:41:56.150 --> 11:42:12.130
and, in spite of his being a lover, Elizabeth really believed all his expectations of felicity to be rationally founded, because they had for basis the excellent understanding and super-excellent disposition of Jane,

11:42:12.630 --> 11:42:17.430
and the general similarity of feeling and taste between her and himself.

11:42:18.110 --> 11:42:22.330
It was an evening of no common delight to them all.

11:42:22.810 --> 11:42:30.630
The satisfaction of Miss Bennet's mind gave a glow of such sweet animation to her face as made her look handsomer than ever.

11:42:31.810 --> 11:42:36.010
Kitty simpered and smiled, and hoped her turn was coming soon.

11:42:36.690 --> 11:42:47.290
Mrs. Bennet could not give her consent or speak her approbation in terms warm enough to satisfy her feelings, though she talked a bingly of nothing else for half an hour.

11:42:47.850 --> 11:42:54.350
And when Mr. Bennet joined them at supper, his voice and manner plainly showed how really happy he was.

11:42:55.330 --> 11:43:01.050
Not a word, however, passed his lips in allusion to it till their visitor took his leave for the night.

11:43:01.050 --> 11:43:05.490
But as soon as he was gone, he turned to his daughter and said,

11:43:06.130 --> 11:43:10.270
Jane, I congratulate you. You will be a very happy woman.

11:43:11.170 --> 11:43:15.490
Jane went to him instantly, kissed him, and thanked him for his goodness.

11:43:16.230 --> 11:43:22.730
You are a good girl, he replied, and I have great pleasure in thinking you will be so happily settled.

11:43:23.370 --> 11:43:28.890
I have not a doubt of your doing very well together. Your tempers are by no means unlike.

11:43:28.890 --> 11:43:39.570
You are each of you so complying that nothing will ever be resolved on, so easy that every servant will cheat you, and so generous that you will always exceed your income.

11:43:40.550 --> 11:43:46.950
I hope not so. Impudence or thoughtlessness in money matters would be unpardonable in me.

11:43:48.070 --> 11:43:57.690
Exceed their income, my dear Mr. Bennet, cried his wife. What are you talking of? Why, he has four or five thousand a year, and very likely more.

11:43:57.690 --> 11:44:06.770
Then addressing her daughter, Oh, my dear, dear Jane, I am so happy. I am sure I shan't get a wink of sleep all night.

11:44:07.290 --> 11:44:14.610
I knew how it would be. I always said it must be so at last. I was sure you could not be so beautiful for nothing.

11:44:15.250 --> 11:44:23.490
I remember as soon as ever I saw him, when he first came into Hertfordshire last year, I thought how likely it was that you should come together.

11:44:23.490 --> 11:44:28.210
Oh, he is the handsomest young man that ever was seen.

11:44:29.710 --> 11:44:39.530
Wickham, Lydia, were all forgotten. Jane was beyond competition her favourite child. At that moment she cared for no other.

11:44:40.350 --> 11:44:48.710
Her younger sisters soon began to make interest with her for objects of happiness which she might in future be able to dispense.

11:44:48.710 --> 11:44:57.110
Mary petitioned for the use of the library at Netherfield, and Kitty begged very hard for a few balls there every winter.

11:44:58.190 --> 11:45:07.550
Bingley from this time was of course a daily visitor at Longbourn, coming frequently before breakfast and always remaining till after supper

11:45:07.550 --> 11:45:17.190
unless when some barbarous neighbour who could not be enough detested had given him an invitation to dinner which he thought himself obliged to accept.

11:45:18.150 --> 11:45:27.670
Elizabeth had now but little time for conversation with her sister, for while he was present Jane had no attention to bestow on anyone else,

11:45:28.070 --> 11:45:35.190
but she found herself considerably useful to both of them in those hours of separation that must sometimes occur.

11:45:36.170 --> 11:45:42.570
In the absence of Jane he always attached himself to Elizabeth for the pleasure of talking of her,

11:45:42.570 --> 11:45:47.650
and when Bingley was gone Jane constantly sought the same means of relief.

11:45:48.590 --> 11:45:58.010
He has made me so happy, said she one evening, by telling me that he was totally ignorant of my being in town last spring. I had not believed it possible.

11:45:59.170 --> 11:46:04.350
I suspected as much, replied Elizabeth, but how did he account for it?

11:46:04.350 --> 11:46:10.670
It must have been his sister's doing. They were certainly no friends to his acquaintance with me,

11:46:10.870 --> 11:46:16.730
which I cannot wonder at, since he might have chosen so much more advantageously in many respects,

11:46:17.310 --> 11:46:24.470
but when they see, as I trust they will, that their brother is happy with me, they will learn to be contented,

11:46:24.710 --> 11:46:29.730
and we shall be on good terms again, though we can never be what we once were to each other.

11:46:29.730 --> 11:46:36.810
That is the most unforgiving speech, said Elizabeth, that I ever heard you utter. Good girl!

11:46:37.410 --> 11:46:42.730
It would vex me indeed to see you again the dupe of Miss Bingley's pretended regard.

11:46:43.970 --> 11:46:48.990
Would you believe it, Lizzie, that when he went to town last November he really loved me,

11:46:49.190 --> 11:46:54.070
and nothing but a persuasion of my being indifferent would have prevented his coming down again?

11:46:54.690 --> 11:47:00.110
He made a little mistake, to be sure, but it is to the credit of his modesty.

11:47:01.170 --> 11:47:09.230
This naturally introduced a panegyric from Jane on his diffidence and the little value he put on his own good qualities.

11:47:10.270 --> 11:47:15.430
Elizabeth was pleased to find that he had not betrayed the interference of his friend,

11:47:16.030 --> 11:47:20.310
for, though Jane had the most generous and forgiving heart in the world,

11:47:20.310 --> 11:47:24.910
she knew it was a circumstance which must prejudice her against him.

11:47:25.830 --> 11:47:30.510
I am certainly the most fortunate creature that ever existed, cried Jane.

11:47:31.390 --> 11:47:36.890
Oh, Lizzie, why am I thus singled from my family and blessed above them all,

11:47:37.350 --> 11:47:42.530
if I could but see you as happy, if there were but such another man for you?

11:47:43.450 --> 11:47:48.170
If you were to give me forty such men, I could never be so happy as you,

11:47:48.170 --> 11:47:53.470
till I have your disposition, your goodness, I never can have your happiness.

11:47:54.390 --> 11:48:02.650
No, no, let me shift for myself, and perhaps, if I have very good luck, I may meet with another Mr. Collins in time.

11:48:03.550 --> 11:48:08.770
The situation of affairs in the Longbourn family could not belong a secret.

11:48:09.330 --> 11:48:12.670
Mrs. Bennet was privileged to whisper it to Mrs. Phillips,

11:48:12.670 --> 11:48:18.890
and she ventured, without any permission, to do the same by all her neighbours in Maryton.

11:48:19.610 --> 11:48:23.970
The Bennets were speedily pronounced to be the luckiest family in the world,

11:48:24.450 --> 11:48:28.630
though only a few weeks before, when Lydia had first run away,

11:48:29.070 --> 11:48:32.650
they had been generally proved to be marked out for misfortune.

11:48:50.150 --> 11:48:55.110
One morning, about a week after Bingley's

11:48:55.110 --> 11:48:59.630
engagement with Jane had been formed, as he and the females of the family were sitting

11:48:59.630 --> 11:49:04.630
together in the dining room, their attention was suddenly drawn to the window by the sound

11:49:04.630 --> 11:49:08.790
of a carriage, and they perceived a chaise and four driving up the lawn.

11:49:10.130 --> 11:49:15.590
It was too early in the morning for visitors, and besides, the equipage did not answer to

11:49:15.590 --> 11:49:16.850
that of any of their neighbours.

11:49:18.010 --> 11:49:23.410
The horses were post, and neither the carriage nor the livery of the servant who preceded

11:49:23.410 --> 11:49:25.310
it were familiar to them.

11:49:26.670 --> 11:49:31.510
As it was certain, however, that somebody was coming, Bingley instantly prevailed on

11:49:31.880 --> 11:49:36.710
to avoid the confinement of such an intrusion, and walk away with him into the shrubbery.

11:49:37.690 --> 11:49:42.430
They both set off, and the conjectures of the remaining three continued, though with

11:49:42.430 --> 11:49:46.350
little satisfaction, till the door was thrown open and their visitor entered.

11:49:47.190 --> 11:49:49.910
It was Lady Catherine de Bourgh.

11:49:51.010 --> 11:49:55.590
They were, of course, all intending to be surprised, but their astonishment was beyond

11:49:55.590 --> 11:50:00.910
their expectation, and on the part of Miss Bennet and Kitty, though she was perfectly

11:50:00.910 --> 11:50:04.330
unknown to them, even inferior to what Elizabeth felt.

11:50:05.670 --> 11:50:10.970
She entered the room with an air more than usually ungracious, made no other reply to

11:50:10.970 --> 11:50:16.930
Elizabeth's salutation than a slight inclination of the head, and sat down without saying a

11:50:16.930 --> 11:50:17.290
word.

11:50:18.730 --> 11:50:23.410
Elizabeth had mentioned her name to her mother on her ladyship's entrance, though no request

11:50:23.410 --> 11:50:24.870
of introduction had been made.

11:50:25.470 --> 11:50:30.270
Miss Bennet, all amazement, though flattered by having a guest of such high importance,

11:50:31.010 --> 11:50:32.870
received her with the utmost politeness.

11:50:34.030 --> 11:50:38.030
After sitting for a moment in silence, she said very stiffly to Elizabeth,

11:50:38.650 --> 11:50:40.150
I hope you are well, Miss Bennet.

11:50:40.610 --> 11:50:42.150
That lady, I suppose, is your mother.

11:50:43.650 --> 11:50:48.690
Elizabeth replied very concisely that she was, and that, I suppose, is one of your sisters.

11:50:49.850 --> 11:50:53.970
Yes, madame, said Mrs. Bennet, delighted to speak to a Lady Catherine.

11:50:55.090 --> 11:50:56.610
She is my youngest girl but one.

11:50:57.430 --> 11:51:01.350
My youngest of all is lately married, and my eldest is somewhere about the grounds,

11:51:02.070 --> 11:51:05.650
walking with a young man who, I believe, will soon become a part of the family.

11:51:06.850 --> 11:51:11.230
You have a very small park here, returned Lady Catherine after a short silence.

11:51:12.390 --> 11:51:17.310
It is nothing in comparison of Rosings, my lady, I dare say, but I assure you it is much

11:51:17.310 --> 11:51:20.850
larger than St. William Lucas'.

11:51:20.850 --> 11:51:24.150
This must be the most inconvenient sitting room for the evening and summer.

11:51:24.410 --> 11:51:25.470
The windows are full west.

11:51:26.930 --> 11:51:30.990
Mrs. Bennet assured her that they never sat there after dinner, and then added,

11:51:31.610 --> 11:51:36.030
May I take the liberty of asking your ladyship whether you left Mr. and Mrs. Collins well?

11:51:37.110 --> 11:51:40.010
Yes, very well. I saw them the night before last.

11:51:42.090 --> 11:51:45.570
Elizabeth now expected that she would produce a letter for her from Charlotte,

11:51:46.050 --> 11:51:48.730
as it seemed the only probable motive for her calling.

11:51:49.850 --> 11:51:52.970
But no letter appeared, and she was completely puzzled.

11:51:54.430 --> 11:51:58.490
Mrs. Bennet, with great civility, begged her ladyship to take some refreshment.

11:51:59.430 --> 11:52:04.210
But Lady Catherine, very resolutely and not very politely, declined eating anything,

11:52:04.450 --> 11:52:06.670
and then, rising up, said to Elizabeth,

11:52:08.330 --> 11:52:13.750
Miss Bennet, there seemed to be a prettiest kind of a little wilderness on one side of your lawn.

11:52:14.390 --> 11:52:18.830
I should be glad to take a turn in it, if you will favor me with your company.

11:52:19.990 --> 11:52:24.410
Go, my dear, cried her mother, and show her ladyship about the different walks.

11:52:24.990 --> 11:52:27.030
I think she will be pleased with the hermitage.

11:52:27.830 --> 11:52:33.630
Elizabeth O'Bain, and running into her own room for her parasol, attended her noble guest downstairs.

11:52:34.850 --> 11:52:40.650
As they passed through the hall, Lady Catherine opened the doors into the dining parlor and drawing room,

11:52:40.650 --> 11:52:46.150
and pronouncing them, after a short survey, to be decent-looking rooms, walked on.

11:52:47.090 --> 11:52:52.270
Her carriage remained at the door, and Elizabeth saw that her waiting woman was in it.

11:52:53.190 --> 11:52:57.030
They proceeded in silence along the gravel walk that led to the copes.

11:52:58.330 --> 11:53:05.730
Elizabeth was determined to make no effort for conversation with a woman who was now more than usually insolent and disagreeable.

11:53:07.190 --> 11:53:12.710
How could I ever think her like her nephew, said she, as she looked into her face.

11:53:14.490 --> 11:53:18.790
As soon as they entered the copes, Lady Catherine began in the following manner.

11:53:20.450 --> 11:53:24.910
You can be at no loss, Miss Bennet, to understand the reason of my journey hither.

11:53:25.770 --> 11:53:29.290
Your own heart, your own conscience, must tell you why I come.

11:53:30.650 --> 11:53:32.990
Elizabeth looked with unaffected astonishment.

11:53:34.410 --> 11:53:36.070
Indeed, you are mistaken, madam.

11:53:37.290 --> 11:53:41.690
I have not been able at all to account for the honor of seeing you here.

11:53:43.150 --> 11:53:49.250
Miss Bennet, replied her ladyship in an angry tone, you ought to know that I am not to be trifled with.

11:53:49.970 --> 11:53:54.270
But however insincere you may choose to be, you shall not find me so.

11:53:55.150 --> 11:53:59.270
My character has been ever celebrated for her sincerity and frankness.

11:53:59.910 --> 11:54:04.990
And in a cause of such moments as this, I shall certainly not depart from it.

11:54:06.030 --> 11:54:09.390
A report of a most alarming nature reached me two days ago.

11:54:10.210 --> 11:54:15.850
I was told that not only your sister was on the point of being most advantageously married,

11:54:16.430 --> 11:54:26.170
but that you, that Miss Elizabeth Bennet, would, in all likelihood, be soon afterwards united to my nephew, my own nephew, Mr. Darcy.

11:54:26.870 --> 11:54:34.750
Though I know it must be a scandalous falsehood, though I would not injure him so much as to suppose the truth of it possible,

11:54:35.410 --> 11:54:41.290
I instantly resolved on setting off for this place, that I might make my sentiments known to you.

11:54:43.250 --> 11:54:48.670
If you believed it impossible to be true, said Elizabeth, coloring with astonishment and disdain,

11:54:49.090 --> 11:54:51.670
I wonder you took the trouble of coming so far.

11:54:52.370 --> 11:54:54.930
What could your ladyship propose by it?

11:54:56.470 --> 11:55:01.250
At once to insist upon having such a report universally contradicted.

11:55:02.570 --> 11:55:06.070
You're coming to Longburn to see me and my family, said Elizabeth coolly.

11:55:06.710 --> 11:55:11.070
Will rather be a confirmation of it, if, indeed, such a report is in existence.

11:55:12.250 --> 11:55:15.730
If? Do you then pretend to be ignorant of it?

11:55:16.630 --> 11:55:19.370
Has it not been industriously circulated by yourselves?

11:55:20.410 --> 11:55:22.570
Do you not know that such a report is spread abroad?

11:55:23.450 --> 11:55:25.190
I never heard that it was.

11:55:26.150 --> 11:55:29.430
And can you likewise declare that there is no foundation for it?

11:55:30.990 --> 11:55:34.070
I do not pretend to possess equal frankness with your ladyship.

11:55:34.910 --> 11:55:37.410
You may ask questions which I shall not choose to answer.

11:55:39.050 --> 11:55:43.250
This is not to be borne. Miss Bennet, I insist on being satisfied.

11:55:44.290 --> 11:55:47.670
Has he, has my nephew made you an offer of marriage?

11:55:48.970 --> 11:55:50.950
Your ladyship has declared it to be impossible.

11:55:51.870 --> 11:55:56.270
It ought to be so. It must be so, while he retains the use of his reason.

11:55:57.070 --> 11:56:00.410
But your arts and allurements may, in a moment of infatuation,

11:56:00.750 --> 11:56:03.470
have made him forget what he owes to himself and to all his family.

11:56:03.810 --> 11:56:05.330
You may have drawn him into it.

11:56:06.430 --> 11:56:09.290
If I have, I shall be the last person to confess it.

11:56:10.510 --> 11:56:12.290
Miss Bennet, do you know who I am?

11:56:12.990 --> 11:56:15.830
I have not been accustomed to such language as this.

11:56:16.450 --> 11:56:19.170
I am almost the nearest relation he has in the world,

11:56:19.170 --> 11:56:21.710
and I am entitled to know all his dearest concerns.

11:56:22.910 --> 11:56:25.210
But you are not entitled to know mine,

11:56:25.810 --> 11:56:29.250
nor will such behavior as this ever induce me to be explicit.

11:56:30.930 --> 11:56:32.570
Let me be rightly understood.

11:56:33.330 --> 11:56:38.030
This match to which you have the presumption to aspire can never take place.

11:56:38.250 --> 11:56:39.110
No, never.

11:56:40.070 --> 11:56:42.270
Mr. Jersey is engaged to my daughter.

11:56:42.870 --> 11:56:44.050
Now what have you to say?

11:56:45.770 --> 11:56:48.670
Only this, that if he is so,

11:56:49.190 --> 11:56:52.490
you can have no reason to suppose he will make an offer to me.

11:56:53.670 --> 11:56:56.450
Lady Catherine hesitated for a moment, and then replied,

11:56:57.370 --> 11:57:00.690
The engagement between them is of a peculiar kind.

11:57:01.190 --> 11:57:04.290
From their infancy, they have been intended for each other.

11:57:05.530 --> 11:57:08.570
It was the favorite wish of his mother's, as well of hers.

11:57:09.690 --> 11:57:11.710
While in their cradles we planned the union,

11:57:11.710 --> 11:57:15.310
and now, at the moment when the wishes of both sisters

11:57:15.310 --> 11:57:16.870
would be accomplished in their marriage,

11:57:17.270 --> 11:57:20.450
to be prevented by a young woman of inferior birth,

11:57:20.750 --> 11:57:24.450
of no importance to the world, and wholly unaligned to the family?

11:57:25.410 --> 11:57:27.970
Do you pay no regard to the wishes of his friends,

11:57:28.730 --> 11:57:31.770
to his tacit engagement with Mr. Burr?

11:57:32.450 --> 11:57:36.090
Have you lost to every feeling of propriety and delicacy?

11:57:36.710 --> 11:57:39.610
Have you not heard me say that from his earliest hours

11:57:39.610 --> 11:57:41.230
he was destined for his cousin?

11:57:43.470 --> 11:57:45.170
Yes, and I have heard it before.

11:57:45.930 --> 11:57:47.170
But what is that to me?

11:57:47.930 --> 11:57:51.350
If there is no other objection to my marrying your nephew,

11:57:51.830 --> 11:57:53.730
I shall certainly not be kept from it

11:57:53.730 --> 11:57:57.770
by knowing that his mother and aunt wished him to marry Mr. Burr.

11:57:58.450 --> 11:58:01.050
You both did as much as you could in planning the marriage.

11:58:01.810 --> 11:58:03.550
Its completion depended on others.

11:58:04.170 --> 11:58:08.110
If Mr. Darcy is neither by honor nor inclination confined to his cousin,

11:58:08.110 --> 11:58:10.390
why is he not to make another choice?

11:58:11.250 --> 11:58:14.130
And if I am that choice, why may I not accept it?

11:58:15.530 --> 11:58:19.430
Because honor, decorum, prudence, nay, interest, forbid it.

11:58:19.930 --> 11:58:21.750
Yes, Miss Bennett, interest.

11:58:22.250 --> 11:58:24.990
For do not expect to be noticed by his family or friends

11:58:24.990 --> 11:58:27.610
if you willfully act against the inclinations of all.

11:58:27.910 --> 11:58:32.150
You will be censured, cited, and despised by everyone connected with him.

11:58:32.450 --> 11:58:33.870
Your alliance will be a disgrace.

11:58:33.870 --> 11:58:37.650
Your name will never even be mentioned by any of us.

11:58:39.310 --> 11:58:41.970
These are heavy misfortunes, replied Elizabeth.

11:58:42.730 --> 11:58:47.170
But the wife of Mr. Darcy must have such extraordinary sources of happiness

11:58:47.170 --> 11:58:49.230
necessarily attached to her situation

11:58:49.230 --> 11:58:52.870
that she could, upon the whole, have no cause to repine.

11:58:54.510 --> 11:58:57.490
Obstinate headstrong girl, I am ashamed of you.

11:58:57.970 --> 11:59:00.870
Is this your gratitude for my attentions to you last spring?

11:59:01.550 --> 11:59:03.510
Is nothing due to me on that score?

11:59:04.530 --> 11:59:05.490
Let us sit down.

11:59:05.970 --> 11:59:07.570
You are to understand, Miss Bennett,

11:59:08.150 --> 11:59:11.690
that I came here with a determined resolution of caring my purpose,

11:59:12.030 --> 11:59:13.710
nor will I be dissuaded from it.

11:59:14.650 --> 11:59:17.830
I have not been used to submit to any person's whims.

11:59:18.650 --> 11:59:21.150
I have not been in the habit of brooking disappointment.

11:59:23.090 --> 11:59:26.510
That will make your ladyship's situation at present more pitiable,

11:59:26.590 --> 11:59:28.170
but it will have no effect on me.

11:59:28.170 --> 11:59:30.290
I will not be interrupted.

11:59:30.770 --> 11:59:31.650
Hear me in silence.

11:59:32.690 --> 11:59:36.050
My daughter and my nephew are formed for each other.

11:59:36.670 --> 11:59:40.370
They are descended on the maternal side from the same noble line

11:59:40.370 --> 11:59:44.990
and on the fathers from respectable, honorable, and ancient,

11:59:45.430 --> 11:59:47.370
though untitled, families.

11:59:48.710 --> 11:59:50.950
Their fortune on both sides is splendid.

11:59:51.590 --> 11:59:56.110
They are destined for each other by the voice of every member of their respective houses.

11:59:56.110 --> 11:59:58.310
And what is to divide them?

11:59:59.030 --> 12:00:03.010
The upstart pretensions of a young woman without family connections or fortune?

12:00:03.650 --> 12:00:04.730
Is this to be endured?

12:00:05.850 --> 12:00:07.890
But it must not, shall not be.

12:00:08.610 --> 12:00:10.670
If you were sensible of your own good,

12:00:11.170 --> 12:00:14.810
you would not wish to quit this sphere in which you have been brought up.

12:00:16.630 --> 12:00:20.110
In marrying your nephew, I should not consider myself as quitting this sphere.

12:00:20.710 --> 12:00:21.670
He is a gentleman.

12:00:22.050 --> 12:00:23.270
I am a gentleman's daughter.

12:00:23.270 --> 12:00:25.410
So far we are equal.

12:00:26.210 --> 12:00:28.830
True, you are a gentleman's daughter.

12:00:29.330 --> 12:00:30.170
But who was your mother?

12:00:30.670 --> 12:00:31.830
Who were your aunts and uncles?

12:00:32.650 --> 12:00:34.770
Do not imagine me ignorant of their condition.

12:00:37.130 --> 12:00:39.850
Whatever my connections may be, said Elizabeth,

12:00:40.350 --> 12:00:44.030
if your nephew does not object to them, they can be nothing to you.

12:00:45.710 --> 12:00:48.010
Tell me at once for all, are you engaged to him?

12:00:49.750 --> 12:00:53.710
Though Elizabeth would not, for the mere purpose of obliging Lady Catherine,

12:00:53.990 --> 12:00:55.170
have answered this question,

12:00:55.790 --> 12:00:58.990
she could not but say, after a moment's deliberation,

12:00:59.550 --> 12:01:00.770
I am not.

12:01:02.130 --> 12:01:03.790
Lady Catherine seemed pleased.

12:01:05.190 --> 12:01:08.950
And will you promise me never to enter into such an engagement?

12:01:09.790 --> 12:01:11.890
I will make no promise of the kind.

12:01:13.350 --> 12:01:15.090
Miss Bennet, I am shocked and astonished.

12:01:15.090 --> 12:01:17.710
I expect to find a more reasonable young woman.

12:01:18.290 --> 12:01:21.970
But do not deceive yourself into a belief that I will ever recede.

12:01:22.610 --> 12:01:26.210
I shall not go away till you have given me the insurance I require.

12:01:27.710 --> 12:01:29.790
And I certainly never shall give it.

12:01:30.310 --> 12:01:33.970
I am not to be intimidated into anything so wholly unreasonable.

12:01:35.210 --> 12:01:37.750
Your Ladyship wants Mr. Darcy to marry your daughter.

12:01:38.510 --> 12:01:42.510
But would my giving you the wished-for promise make their marriage at all more probable?

12:01:43.550 --> 12:01:45.570
Suppose him to be attached to me.

12:01:46.030 --> 12:01:50.150
Would my refusing to accept his hand make him wish to bestow it on his cousin?

12:01:51.530 --> 12:01:52.910
Allow me to say, Lady Catherine,

12:01:53.550 --> 12:01:57.330
that the arguments with which you have supported this extraordinary application

12:01:57.330 --> 12:02:00.890
have been as frivolous as the application was ill-judged.

12:02:01.390 --> 12:02:03.690
You have widely mistaken my character,

12:02:04.070 --> 12:02:07.330
if you think I can be worked on by such persuasions as these.

12:02:08.590 --> 12:02:11.630
How far your nephew might approve of your interference in his affairs,

12:02:11.630 --> 12:02:12.610
I cannot tell.

12:02:13.230 --> 12:02:16.490
But you most certainly have no right to concern yourself and mine.

12:02:17.850 --> 12:02:22.710
I must beg, therefore, to be importuned no farther on the subject.

12:02:24.410 --> 12:02:26.650
Not so hasty, if you please.

12:02:26.990 --> 12:02:28.850
I have by no means done.

12:02:29.670 --> 12:02:34.170
To all the objections I have already urged, I have still another to add.

12:02:34.790 --> 12:02:40.210
I am no stranger to the particulars of your younger sister's infamous elopement.

12:02:40.210 --> 12:02:45.510
I know it all, that the young man's marrying her was a patched-up business

12:02:45.510 --> 12:02:47.910
at the expense of your father and uncles.

12:02:49.210 --> 12:02:51.710
And is such a girl to be my nephew's sister?

12:02:52.530 --> 12:02:57.470
Is her husband, the son of his late father's steward, to be his brother?

12:02:58.130 --> 12:03:00.230
Heaven and earth, of what are you thinking?

12:03:00.830 --> 12:03:03.230
Are the shades of Pemberley to be thus polluted?

12:03:04.230 --> 12:03:06.690
You can now have nothing further to say.

12:03:06.690 --> 12:03:08.730
She resentfully answered,

12:03:08.990 --> 12:03:11.690
You have insulted me in every possible method.

12:03:12.070 --> 12:03:13.890
I must beg to return to the house.

12:03:14.530 --> 12:03:16.090
And she rose as she spoke.

12:03:17.350 --> 12:03:19.670
Lady Catherine rose also, and they turned back.

12:03:20.190 --> 12:03:22.150
Her ladyship was highly incensed.

12:03:23.530 --> 12:03:26.630
Have you no regard, then, for the honor and credit of my nephew?

12:03:27.670 --> 12:03:29.310
Unfeeling, selfish girl!

12:03:30.150 --> 12:03:34.390
Do you not consider that a connection with you must disgrace him in the eyes of everybody?

12:03:36.490 --> 12:03:39.170
Lady Catherine, I have nothing further to say.

12:03:39.330 --> 12:03:40.450
You know my sentiments.

12:03:41.730 --> 12:03:43.330
You are then resolved to have him?

12:03:44.470 --> 12:03:46.390
I have said no such thing.

12:03:47.190 --> 12:03:51.050
I am only resolved to act in that manner which will, in my own opinion,

12:03:51.650 --> 12:03:52.730
constitute my happiness,

12:03:53.210 --> 12:03:57.430
without reference to you or to any person so wholly unconnected with me.

12:03:59.310 --> 12:03:59.970
It is well.

12:04:00.670 --> 12:04:02.550
You refuse, then, to oblige me.

12:04:02.550 --> 12:04:06.550
You refuse to obey the claims of duty, honor, and gratitude.

12:04:07.270 --> 12:04:10.570
You are determined to ruin him in the opinion of all his friends

12:04:10.570 --> 12:04:12.690
and make him the contempt of the world.

12:04:14.750 --> 12:04:18.650
Neither duty, nor honor, nor gratitude, replied Elizabeth,

12:04:19.390 --> 12:04:22.230
have any possible claim on me in the present instance.

12:04:23.230 --> 12:04:27.050
No principle of either would be violated by my marriage with Mr. Darcy.

12:04:27.890 --> 12:04:32.550
And with regard to the resentment of his family or the indignation of the world,

12:04:33.150 --> 12:04:35.810
if the former were excited by his marrying me,

12:04:36.170 --> 12:04:38.290
it would not give me one moment's concern,

12:04:38.890 --> 12:04:42.250
and the world in general would have too much sense to join in the scorn.

12:04:43.810 --> 12:04:46.350
And this is your real opinion? This is your final resolve?

12:04:46.970 --> 12:04:49.030
Very well. I shall now know how to act.

12:04:49.290 --> 12:04:52.830
Do not imagine, Miss Bennet, that your ambition will ever be gratified.

12:04:53.230 --> 12:04:54.670
I came to try you.

12:04:54.670 --> 12:04:58.490
I hoped to find you reasonable, but depend on it.

12:04:58.630 --> 12:04:59.790
I will carry my point.

12:05:02.310 --> 12:05:04.390
In this manner, Lady Catherine talked on,

12:05:04.750 --> 12:05:09.010
till they were at the door of the carriage when, turning hastily round, she added,

12:05:09.730 --> 12:05:11.570
I shall take no leave of you, Miss Bennet.

12:05:11.730 --> 12:05:13.390
I send no compliments to your mother.

12:05:13.770 --> 12:05:15.050
You deserve no such attention.

12:05:15.630 --> 12:05:18.170
I am most seriously displeased.

12:05:20.150 --> 12:05:21.630
Elizabeth made no answer,

12:05:21.630 --> 12:05:25.750
and without attempting to persuade her ladyship to return into the house,

12:05:26.190 --> 12:05:27.730
walked quietly into it herself.

12:05:28.710 --> 12:05:31.830
She heard the carriage drive away as she proceeded upstairs.

12:05:33.430 --> 12:05:36.230
Her mother impatiently met her at the door of the dressing room

12:05:36.230 --> 12:05:39.750
to ask why Lady Catherine would not come in again and rest herself.

12:05:41.290 --> 12:05:44.710
She did not choose it, said her daughter. She would go.

12:05:46.390 --> 12:05:51.110
She is a very fine-looking woman, and her calling here was prejudicially civil.

12:05:51.810 --> 12:05:55.690
For she only came, I suppose, to tell us the cons as were well.

12:05:56.890 --> 12:05:59.750
She is on her road somewhere, I dare say, and so,

12:06:00.190 --> 12:06:03.290
passing through Meryton, thought she might as well call on you.

12:06:04.090 --> 12:06:06.850
I suppose she had nothing particular to say to you, Lizzie?

12:06:08.750 --> 12:06:12.250
Elizabeth was forced to give into a little falsehood here,

12:06:12.850 --> 12:06:16.370
for to acknowledge the substance of their conversation was impossible.

12:06:25.970 --> 12:06:30.730
The discomposure of spirits, which this extraordinary visit threw Elizabeth into,

12:06:31.150 --> 12:06:32.650
could not be easily overcome.

12:06:33.430 --> 12:06:38.070
Nor could she, for many hours, learn to think of it less than incessantly.

12:06:39.490 --> 12:06:44.430
Lady Catherine, it appeared, had actually taken the trouble of this journey from Rossings

12:06:44.430 --> 12:06:48.830
for the sole purpose of breaking off her supposed engagement with Mr. Darcy.

12:06:49.630 --> 12:06:52.750
It was a rational scheme, to be sure.

12:06:53.670 --> 12:06:55.890
But from what the reports of their engagement could originate,

12:06:57.110 --> 12:06:58.930
Elizabeth was at a loss to imagine.

12:06:59.710 --> 12:07:03.670
Till she recollected that, his being the intimate friend of Bingley,

12:07:04.230 --> 12:07:07.110
and her being the sister of Jane, was enough,

12:07:07.610 --> 12:07:11.510
at a time when the expectation of one wedding made everybody eager for another,

12:07:11.870 --> 12:07:13.050
to supply the idea.

12:07:14.850 --> 12:07:18.270
She had not herself forgotten to feel that the marriage of her sister

12:07:18.270 --> 12:07:20.530
must bring them more frequently together.

12:07:21.650 --> 12:07:24.410
And her neighbors at Lucas Lodge, therefore,

12:07:25.030 --> 12:07:29.290
through their communication with the Collins's, the report, she concluded, had reached Catherine,

12:07:30.470 --> 12:07:33.510
had only set that down as almost certain and immediate,

12:07:34.290 --> 12:07:37.650
which she had looked forward to as possible at some future time.

12:07:39.630 --> 12:07:42.810
In revolving Lady Catherine's expressions, however,

12:07:43.290 --> 12:07:45.550
she could not help feeling some uneasiness

12:07:45.550 --> 12:07:49.490
as to the possible consequence of her persisting in this interference.

12:07:51.150 --> 12:07:54.290
From what she had said of her resolution to prevent their marriage,

12:07:55.010 --> 12:07:59.270
it occurred to Elizabeth that she must mediate an application to her nephew,

12:08:00.270 --> 12:08:05.370
and how he might take a similar representation of the evils attached to a connection with her,

12:08:05.850 --> 12:08:06.950
she dared not pronounce.

12:08:08.930 --> 12:08:12.130
She knew not the exact degree of his affection for his aunt,

12:08:12.590 --> 12:08:14.350
or his dependence on her judgment,

12:08:14.350 --> 12:08:20.750
but it was natural to suppose that he had thought much higher of her ladyship than she could do.

12:08:21.130 --> 12:08:25.790
And it was certain that, in enumerating the miseries of a marriage with one

12:08:25.790 --> 12:08:28.790
whose immediate connections were so unequal with his own,

12:08:29.330 --> 12:08:31.710
his aunt would address him on his weakest side.

12:08:32.690 --> 12:08:36.590
With his notions of dignity, he would probably feel that the arguments,

12:08:37.170 --> 12:08:39.590
which to Elizabeth had appeared weak and ridiculous,

12:08:40.470 --> 12:08:42.850
contained much good sense and solid reasoning.

12:08:44.730 --> 12:08:47.850
If he had been wavering before as to what he should do,

12:08:48.090 --> 12:08:49.510
which had often seemed likely,

12:08:50.170 --> 12:08:54.490
the advice and entreaty of so near a relation might settle every doubt,

12:08:54.970 --> 12:08:59.790
and determine him at once to be as happy as dignity could unblemished could make him.

12:09:00.930 --> 12:09:03.450
In that case, he would return no more.

12:09:04.450 --> 12:09:06.930
Lady Catherine might see him in her way through town,

12:09:07.190 --> 12:09:11.890
and his engagement to Bingley of coming against Netherfield must give way.

12:09:13.710 --> 12:09:19.870
If, therefore, an excuse for not keeping his promise should come to his friend within a few days, she added,

12:09:20.530 --> 12:09:22.650
I shall know how to understand it.

12:09:23.750 --> 12:09:27.990
I shall then give over every expectation, every wish of his constancy.

12:09:28.950 --> 12:09:31.130
If he is satisfied with only regretting me,

12:09:31.470 --> 12:09:33.750
when he might have obtained my affections in hand,

12:09:34.170 --> 12:09:36.210
I shall soon cease to regret him at all.

12:09:38.950 --> 12:09:43.870
The surprise of the rest of the family on hearing who the visitor had been was very great,

12:09:44.570 --> 12:09:50.370
but they obligingly satisfied him with the same kind of supposition which had appeased Miss Bennet's curiosity,

12:09:51.130 --> 12:09:53.450
and spared Elizabeth for much teasing on the subject.

12:09:55.670 --> 12:09:58.710
The next morning, as she was going downstairs, she was met by her father,

12:09:59.250 --> 12:10:01.830
who came out of his library with a letter in his hand.

12:10:02.950 --> 12:10:07.510
Lizzie, said he, I was going to look for you, come into my room.

12:10:09.410 --> 12:10:14.770
She followed him thither, and her curiosity to know what he had to tell her

12:10:14.770 --> 12:10:19.230
was heightened by the supposition of its being in some manner connected with the letter he held.

12:10:20.550 --> 12:10:23.530
It suddenly struck her that it might be from Lady Catherine,

12:10:24.170 --> 12:10:28.230
and she anticipated with dismay all the consequent explanations.

12:10:30.430 --> 12:10:33.970
She followed her father to the fireplace, and they both sat down.

12:10:34.910 --> 12:10:39.910
He then said, I have received a letter this morning that has astonished me exceedingly.

12:10:40.550 --> 12:10:43.690
As it principally concerns yourself, you ought to know its contents.

12:10:44.390 --> 12:10:47.930
I did not know before that I had two daughters on the brink of matrimony.

12:10:48.570 --> 12:10:51.370
Let me congratulate you on a very important conquest.

12:10:52.490 --> 12:10:57.850
The colour now rushed into Elizabeth's cheeks in the instantaneous conviction

12:10:57.850 --> 12:11:01.110
of its being a letter from the nephew instead of the aunt,

12:11:01.650 --> 12:11:06.050
and she was undetermined whether most to be pleased that he explained himself at all,

12:11:06.450 --> 12:11:09.330
or offended that his letter was not rather to address to herself,

12:11:09.890 --> 12:11:13.290
when her father continued, You look conscious.

12:11:13.750 --> 12:11:16.990
Young ladies have a great penetration in such matters as these,

12:11:16.990 --> 12:11:23.110
but I think I may defy even your sagacity to discover the name of your admirer.

12:11:23.530 --> 12:11:25.370
This letter is from Mr. Collins.

12:11:26.490 --> 12:11:27.490
From Mr. Collins.

12:11:28.010 --> 12:11:30.350
And what can he have to say?

12:11:31.810 --> 12:11:33.930
Something very much to the purpose, of course.

12:11:34.770 --> 12:11:38.770
He begins with congratulations on the approaching nuptials of my eldest daughter,

12:11:39.270 --> 12:11:44.030
of which, it seems, he has been told by some of the good-natured gossiping Lucases.

12:11:44.870 --> 12:11:49.370
I shall not sport with your impatience by reading what he says on that point.

12:11:49.990 --> 12:11:51.870
What relates to yourself is as follows.

12:11:53.210 --> 12:11:59.030
Having thus offered you the sincerest congratulations of Mrs. Collins and myself on this happy event,

12:11:59.450 --> 12:12:02.130
let me now add a short hint on the subject of another,

12:12:02.730 --> 12:12:05.210
of which we have been advised by the same authority.

12:12:05.870 --> 12:12:10.250
Your daughter Elizabeth, it is presumed, will not long bear the name of Bennet,

12:12:10.630 --> 12:12:12.810
after her elder sister has resigned it,

12:12:12.810 --> 12:12:16.650
and the chosen partner of her fate may be reasonably looked up to

12:12:16.650 --> 12:12:20.150
as one of the most illustrious personages in the land.

12:12:22.090 --> 12:12:24.530
Can you possibly guess, Lizzie, who is meant by this?

12:12:25.090 --> 12:12:28.070
This young gentleman is blessed, in a peculiar way,

12:12:28.410 --> 12:12:31.030
with everything the heart of a mortal can most desire,

12:12:31.750 --> 12:12:35.490
splendid property, noble kindred, and extensive patronage.

12:12:35.890 --> 12:12:37.990
Yet, in spite of all these temptations,

12:12:37.990 --> 12:12:43.070
let me warn my cousin Elizabeth and yourself of what evils you may incur

12:12:43.650 --> 12:12:46.630
by a precipitous closure with this gentleman's proposal,

12:12:47.470 --> 12:12:51.550
which, of course, you will be inclined to take immediate advantage of.

12:12:52.470 --> 12:12:54.630
Have you any idea, Lizzie, who this gentleman is?

12:12:54.710 --> 12:12:56.350
But now it comes out.

12:12:57.470 --> 12:12:59.590
My motive for cautioning you is as follows.

12:13:00.090 --> 12:13:03.550
We have reason to imagine that his aunt, Lady Catherine de Bourgh,

12:13:03.850 --> 12:13:05.710
does not look on the match with a friendly eye.

12:13:07.010 --> 12:13:09.010
Mr. Darcy, you see, is the man.

12:13:09.150 --> 12:13:12.210
Now, Lizzie, I think I have surprised you.

12:13:12.470 --> 12:13:17.490
Could he or the Lucas's have pitched on any man within the circle of our acquaintance

12:13:17.490 --> 12:13:20.910
whose name would have given the lie more effectively to what they related?

12:13:21.630 --> 12:13:25.230
Mr. Darcy, who never looks at a woman but to see a blemish,

12:13:25.310 --> 12:13:27.770
and who probably never looked at you in his life?

12:13:28.030 --> 12:13:29.290
It is admirable.

12:13:31.770 --> 12:13:34.370
Elizabeth tried to join her father's pleasantry,

12:13:34.370 --> 12:13:37.870
but could only force one most reluctant smile.

12:13:38.630 --> 12:13:42.530
Never had his wit been directed in a manner so little agreeable to her.

12:13:43.370 --> 12:13:44.330
Are you not diverted?

12:13:46.070 --> 12:13:46.930
Are you not diverted?

12:13:47.750 --> 12:13:48.630
Oh, yes.

12:13:48.910 --> 12:13:49.590
Pray read on.

12:13:51.370 --> 12:13:55.150
After mentioning the likelihood of this marriage to her ladyship last night,

12:13:55.750 --> 12:13:58.610
she immediately, with her usual condescension,

12:13:59.330 --> 12:14:00.910
expressed what she felt on the occasion.

12:14:00.910 --> 12:14:07.310
When it became apparent that in the score of some family objections on the part of my cousin

12:14:07.310 --> 12:14:11.950
she would never give her consent to what she termed so disgraceful a match,

12:14:13.030 --> 12:14:16.890
I thought it my duty to give the speediest intelligence of this to my cousin,

12:14:17.430 --> 12:14:21.650
that she and her noble admirer may be aware of what they are about,

12:14:22.170 --> 12:14:26.650
and not run hastily into a marriage that has not been properly sanctioned.

12:14:27.330 --> 12:14:29.090
Mr. Collins moreover adds,

12:14:29.090 --> 12:14:34.470
I am truly rejoiced that my cousin Lydia's sad business has been so well hushed up,

12:14:34.470 --> 12:14:38.750
and am only concerned that their living together before marriage took place

12:14:38.750 --> 12:14:40.270
should be so generally known.

12:14:41.290 --> 12:14:44.430
I must not, however, neglect the duties of my station,

12:14:44.830 --> 12:14:47.270
or refrain from declaring my amazement at hearing

12:14:47.270 --> 12:14:50.890
that she received the young couple into your house as soon as they were married.

12:14:51.550 --> 12:14:53.350
It was an encouragement of vice,

12:14:54.270 --> 12:14:55.950
and I have been the rector of Longburn.

12:14:56.750 --> 12:15:00.190
I should very strenuously have opposed it.

12:15:00.630 --> 12:15:03.110
You ought certainly to forgive them as a Christian,

12:15:03.730 --> 12:15:05.470
but never admit them into your sight,

12:15:05.930 --> 12:15:07.970
or allow their names to be mentioned in your hearing.

12:15:09.470 --> 12:15:11.370
That is his notion of Christian forgiveness?

12:15:12.750 --> 12:15:16.830
The rest of his letter is only about his dear Charlotte's situation,

12:15:17.210 --> 12:15:19.650
and his expectation of a young olive branch.

12:15:20.870 --> 12:15:24.550
But Lizzie, you did not look as if you enjoyed it.

12:15:25.050 --> 12:15:27.390
You are not going to be missus, I hope,

12:15:27.710 --> 12:15:29.910
and pretend to be affronted at an idle report.

12:15:31.190 --> 12:15:33.710
For what do we live but to make support for our neighbors,

12:15:33.910 --> 12:15:35.510
and to laugh at them in our own turn?

12:15:37.750 --> 12:15:41.230
Oh, cried Elizabeth, I am excessively diverted,

12:15:41.790 --> 12:15:43.430
but it is so strange.

12:15:45.850 --> 12:15:47.770
Yes, that is what makes it amusing.

12:15:48.650 --> 12:15:51.470
Had they fixed on any other man, it would have been nothing,

12:15:51.470 --> 12:15:56.190
but his perfect indifference and your pointed dislike

12:15:56.190 --> 12:15:58.770
make it so delightfully absurd.

12:15:59.850 --> 12:16:01.450
Much as I abominate writing,

12:16:01.730 --> 12:16:06.270
I would not give up Mr. Collins's correspondence for any consideration.

12:16:07.390 --> 12:16:09.390
Nay, when I read a letter of his,

12:16:09.810 --> 12:16:13.110
I cannot help giving him the preference, even over Wickham,

12:16:13.510 --> 12:16:16.950
as much as I value the impudence and hypocrisy of my son-in-law.

12:16:17.770 --> 12:16:18.990
And pray, Lizzie,

12:16:18.990 --> 12:16:21.590
what said Lady Catherine about this report?

12:16:22.510 --> 12:16:24.270
Did she call to refuse her consent?

12:16:25.810 --> 12:16:28.630
To this question, his daughter replied only with a laugh,

12:16:29.510 --> 12:16:31.670
and as it had been asked without the least suspicion,

12:16:31.870 --> 12:16:34.030
she was not distressed by his repeating it.

12:16:35.070 --> 12:16:37.130
Elizabeth had never been more at a loss

12:16:37.130 --> 12:16:39.610
to make her feelings appear what they were not.

12:16:40.290 --> 12:16:43.350
It was necessary to laugh, when she would rather have cried.

12:16:44.310 --> 12:16:46.710
Her father had most cruelly mortified her

12:16:46.710 --> 12:16:48.970
by what he said of Mr. Darcy's indifference,

12:16:49.630 --> 12:16:51.830
and she could do nothing but perhaps wonder

12:16:52.310 --> 12:16:54.210
at such a want of penetration,

12:16:55.130 --> 12:16:56.450
or a fear that perhaps,

12:16:56.890 --> 12:16:58.450
instead of his seeing too little,

12:16:58.910 --> 12:17:00.830
she might have fancied too much.

12:17:26.210 --> 12:17:27.610
XVIII.

12:17:28.570 --> 12:17:35.350
Instead of receiving any such letter of excuse from his friend, as Elizabeth half expected Mr. Bingley to do,

12:17:35.830 --> 12:17:41.290
he was able to bring Darcy with him to Longbourn before many days had passed after Lady Catherine's visit.

12:17:42.030 --> 12:17:47.650
The gentlemen arrived early, and before Mrs. Bennet had time to tell him of their having seen his aunt,

12:17:48.010 --> 12:17:53.510
of which her daughter sat in momentary dread, Bingley, who wanted to be alone with Jane,

12:17:53.510 --> 12:18:00.270
proposed they're all walking out. It was agreed to. Mrs. Bennet was not in the habit of walking.

12:18:01.110 --> 12:18:05.550
Mary could never spare time, but the remaining five set off together.

12:18:06.550 --> 12:18:10.410
Bingley and Jane, however, soon allowed the others to outstrip them.

12:18:11.050 --> 12:18:16.410
They lagged behind, while Elizabeth, Kitty, and Darcy were to entertain each other.

12:18:17.230 --> 12:18:22.050
Very little was said by either. Kitty was too much afraid of him to talk.

12:18:22.050 --> 12:18:28.450
Elizabeth was secretly forming a desperate resolution, and perhaps he might be doing the same.

12:18:29.410 --> 12:18:33.530
They walked towards the Lucases, because Kitty wished to call upon Maria,

12:18:34.210 --> 12:18:41.470
and as Elizabeth saw no occasion for making it a general concern, when Kitty left them she went boldly on with him alone.

12:18:42.350 --> 12:18:48.430
Now was the moment for her resolution to be executed, and while her courage was high, she immediately said,

12:18:48.430 --> 12:18:56.110
Mr. Darcy, I am a very selfish creature, and for the sake of giving relief to my own feelings care not how much I may be wounding yours.

12:18:56.710 --> 12:19:01.130
I can no longer help thanking you for your unexampled kindness to my poor sister.

12:19:01.770 --> 12:19:06.830
Ever since I have known it I have been most anxious to acknowledge to you how gratefully I feel it.

12:19:07.350 --> 12:19:11.930
Were it known to the rest of the family, I should not have merely my own gratitude to express.

12:19:12.550 --> 12:19:18.010
I am sorry, exceedingly sorry, replied Darcy, in a tone of surprise and emotion,

12:19:18.470 --> 12:19:22.710
that you have ever been informed of what may, in a mistaken light, have given you uneasiness.

12:19:23.270 --> 12:19:25.990
I did not think Mrs. Gardiner was so little to be trusted.

12:19:26.910 --> 12:19:32.910
You must not blame my aunt. Lydia's thoughtlessness first betrayed to me that you had been concerned in the matter,

12:19:33.410 --> 12:19:36.630
and, of course, I could not rest till I knew the particulars.

12:19:36.630 --> 12:19:44.750
Let me thank you again and again, in the name of all my family, for that generous compassion which induced you to take so much trouble

12:19:44.750 --> 12:19:49.450
and bear so many mortifications for the sake of discovering them.

12:19:50.430 --> 12:19:54.970
If you will thank me, he replied, let it be for yourself alone.

12:19:55.630 --> 12:20:03.390
That the wish of giving happiness to you might add force to the other inducements which led me on I shall not attempt to deny.

12:20:03.390 --> 12:20:09.910
But your family owe me nothing. Much as I respect them, I believe I thought only of you.

12:20:11.470 --> 12:20:17.690
Elizabeth was too much embarrassed to say a word. After a short pause, her companion added,

12:20:18.570 --> 12:20:25.010
You are too generous to trifle with me. If your feelings are still what they were last April, tell me so at once.

12:20:25.510 --> 12:20:31.290
My affections and wishes are unchanged, but one word from you will silence me on this subject forever.

12:20:32.990 --> 12:20:39.950
Elizabeth, feeling all the more than common awkwardness and anxiety of his situation, now forced herself to speak,

12:20:40.490 --> 12:20:48.350
and immediately, though not very fluently, gave him to understand that her sentiments had undergone so material a change

12:20:48.350 --> 12:20:55.170
since the period to which she eluded, as to make her receive with gratitude and pleasure his present assurances.

12:20:55.170 --> 12:21:01.110
The happiness which this reply produced was such as he had probably never felt before,

12:21:01.590 --> 12:21:09.490
and he expressed himself on the occasion as sensibly and as warmly as a man violently in love can be supposed to do.

12:21:10.070 --> 12:21:19.290
Had Elizabeth been able to encounter his eye, she might have seen how well the expression of heartfelt delight diffused over his face became him.

12:21:19.290 --> 12:21:27.690
But though she could not look, she could listen, and he told her of feelings which, in proving of what importance she was to him,

12:21:28.050 --> 12:21:34.550
made his affection every moment more valuable. They walked on without knowing in what direction.

12:21:35.190 --> 12:21:40.550
There was too much to be thought and felt and said for attention to any other objects.

12:21:40.550 --> 12:21:47.110
She soon learnt that they were indebted for their present good understanding to the efforts of his aunt,

12:21:47.470 --> 12:21:53.990
who did call on him in her return through London, and there relate her journey to Longbourn, its motive,

12:21:54.390 --> 12:22:00.950
and the substance of her conversation with Elizabeth, dwelling emphatically on every expression of the latter which,

12:22:01.130 --> 12:22:06.610
in her ladyship's apprehension, peculiarly denoted her perverseness and assurance,

12:22:06.610 --> 12:22:14.330
in the belief that such a relation must assist her endeavours to obtain that promise from her nephew which she had refused to give.

12:22:14.930 --> 12:22:19.930
But unluckily for her ladyship, its effect had been exactly contrary-wise.

12:22:20.570 --> 12:22:26.070
It taught me to hope, said he, as I had scarcely ever allowed myself to hope before.

12:22:26.710 --> 12:22:33.130
I knew enough of your disposition to be certain that, had you been absolutely irrevocably decided against me,

12:22:33.130 --> 12:22:36.730
you would have acknowledged it to Lady Catherine, frankly and openly.

12:22:37.950 --> 12:22:40.310
Elizabeth collared and laughed as she replied,

12:22:40.950 --> 12:22:44.790
Yes, you know enough of my frankness to believe me capable of that.

12:22:45.290 --> 12:22:50.830
After abusing you so abominably to your face, I could have no scruple in abusing you to all your relations.

12:22:51.830 --> 12:22:54.290
What did you say of me that I did not deserve?

12:22:54.850 --> 12:22:59.610
For, though your accusations were ill-founded, formed on mistaken premises,

12:22:59.610 --> 12:23:04.070
my behaviour to you at the time had merited the severest reproof.

12:23:04.550 --> 12:23:07.930
It was unpardonable. I cannot think of it without abhorrence.

12:23:09.070 --> 12:23:13.990
We will not quarrel for the greater share of blame annexed to that evening, said Elizabeth.

12:23:14.610 --> 12:23:17.610
The conduct of neither, if strictly examined, will be irreproachable.

12:23:18.590 --> 12:23:21.690
But since then we have both, I hope, improved in civility.

12:23:22.770 --> 12:23:25.350
I cannot be so easily reconciled to myself.

12:23:25.350 --> 12:23:31.670
The recollection of what I then said, of my conduct, my manners, my expressions during the whole of it,

12:23:31.670 --> 12:23:35.790
is now, and has been many months, inexpressibly painful to me.

12:23:36.410 --> 12:23:39.310
Your reproof so well applied, I shall never forget.

12:23:40.130 --> 12:23:42.730
Had you behaved in a more gentleman-like manner?

12:23:43.410 --> 12:23:49.250
Those were your words. You know not, you can scarcely conceive how they have tortured me,

12:23:49.670 --> 12:23:54.190
though it was some time, I confess, before I was reasonable enough to allow their justice.

12:23:55.010 --> 12:23:59.290
I was certainly very far from expecting them to make so strong an impression.

12:23:59.830 --> 12:24:03.250
I had not the smallest idea of their being ever felt in such a way.

12:24:04.410 --> 12:24:09.970
I can easily believe it. You thought me then devoid of every proper feeling. I am sure you did.

12:24:10.610 --> 12:24:13.290
The turn of your countenance I shall never forget,

12:24:13.610 --> 12:24:18.410
as you said that I could not have addressed you in any possible way that would induce you to accept me.

12:24:19.290 --> 12:24:23.370
Oh, do not repeat what I then said. These recollections will not do at all.

12:24:23.370 --> 12:24:27.150
I assure you that I have long been most heartily ashamed of it.

12:24:28.210 --> 12:24:29.490
Darcy mentioned his letter.

12:24:30.250 --> 12:24:33.850
Did it, said he, did it soon make you think better of me?

12:24:34.290 --> 12:24:37.090
Did you, on reading it, give any credit to its contents?

12:24:37.950 --> 12:24:40.630
She explained what its effect on her had been,

12:24:40.950 --> 12:24:44.470
and how gradually all her former prejudices had been removed.

12:24:45.290 --> 12:24:50.270
I knew, said he, that what I wrote must give you pain, but it was necessary.

12:24:50.270 --> 12:24:52.510
I hope you have destroyed the letter.

12:24:53.010 --> 12:24:55.430
There was one part especially, the opening of it,

12:24:55.550 --> 12:24:58.070
which I should dread your having the power of reading again.

12:24:58.750 --> 12:25:02.390
I can remember some expressions which might justly make you hate me.

12:25:03.450 --> 12:25:08.010
The letter shall certainly be burnt, if you believe it essential to the preservation of my regard.

12:25:08.590 --> 12:25:13.210
But, though we have both reason to think my opinions not entirely unalterable,

12:25:13.730 --> 12:25:17.570
they are not, I hope, quite so easily changed as that implies.

12:25:18.570 --> 12:25:23.690
When I wrote that letter, replied Darcy, I believed myself perfectly calm and cool,

12:25:23.830 --> 12:25:28.170
but I am since convinced that it was written in a dreadful bitterness of spirit.

12:25:29.310 --> 12:25:32.790
The letter perhaps began in bitterness, but it did not end so.

12:25:33.510 --> 12:25:35.250
The adieu is charity itself.

12:25:35.890 --> 12:25:37.090
But think no more of the letter.

12:25:37.290 --> 12:25:40.710
The feelings of the person who wrote, and the person who received it,

12:25:41.050 --> 12:25:43.830
are now so widely different from what they were then,

12:25:43.830 --> 12:25:47.490
that every unpleasant circumstance attending it ought to be forgotten.

12:25:48.090 --> 12:25:49.950
You must learn some of my philosophy.

12:25:50.490 --> 12:25:53.430
Think only of the past, as its remembrance gives you pleasure.

12:25:54.750 --> 12:25:57.850
I cannot give you credit for any philosophy of the kind.

12:25:58.490 --> 12:26:02.250
Your retrospections must be so totally void of reproach

12:26:02.250 --> 12:26:05.290
that the contentment arising from them is not of philosophy,

12:26:05.890 --> 12:26:08.190
but, what is much better, of innocence.

12:26:08.730 --> 12:26:10.410
But with me it is not so.

12:26:10.410 --> 12:26:15.570
Painful recollections will intrude, which cannot, which ought not, to be repelled.

12:26:16.290 --> 12:26:20.530
I have been a selfish being all my life, in practice, though not in principle.

12:26:21.310 --> 12:26:25.610
As a child I was taught what was right, but I was not taught to correct my temper.

12:26:26.310 --> 12:26:30.530
I was given good principles, but left to follow them in pride and conceit.

12:26:31.030 --> 12:26:34.510
Unfortunately, an only son, for many years an only child,

12:26:34.870 --> 12:26:38.630
I was spoiled by my parents, who, though good themselves,

12:26:38.630 --> 12:26:42.630
my father particularly, all that was benevolent and amiable,

12:26:43.550 --> 12:26:47.390
allowed, encouraged, almost taught me to be selfish and overbearing,

12:26:47.750 --> 12:26:50.250
to care for none beyond my own family circle,

12:26:50.750 --> 12:26:52.990
to think meanly of all the rest of the world,

12:26:53.490 --> 12:26:57.470
to wish at least to think meanly of their sense and worth compared with my own.

12:26:58.130 --> 12:27:03.710
Such I was from eight to eight and twenty, and such I might still have been, but for you.

12:27:04.110 --> 12:27:07.770
Dearest, loveliest Elizabeth, what do I not owe you?

12:27:07.770 --> 12:27:12.870
You taught me a lesson, hard indeed at first, but most advantageous.

12:27:13.230 --> 12:27:18.010
By you I was properly humbled. I came to you without a doubt of my reception.

12:27:18.710 --> 12:27:23.830
You showed me how insufficient were all my pretensions to please a woman worthy of being pleased.

12:27:24.850 --> 12:27:27.110
Had you then persuaded yourself that I should?

12:27:28.170 --> 12:27:31.230
Indeed I had. What will you think of my vanity?

12:27:31.770 --> 12:27:34.950
I believed you to be wishing, expecting my addresses.

12:27:35.750 --> 12:27:40.370
My manners must have been in fault, but not intentionally, I assure you.

12:27:40.690 --> 12:27:44.970
I never meant to deceive you, but my spirits might often lead me wrong.

12:27:45.670 --> 12:27:47.790
How you must have hated me after that evening.

12:27:48.830 --> 12:27:54.730
Hate you? I was angry perhaps at first, but my anger soon began to take a proper direction.

12:27:55.810 --> 12:27:59.830
I am almost afraid of asking what you thought of me when we met at Pemberley.

12:28:00.210 --> 12:28:01.590
You blamed me for coming?

12:28:02.210 --> 12:28:05.090
No, indeed, I felt nothing but surprise.

12:28:06.130 --> 12:28:10.030
Your surprise could not be greater than mine in being noticed by you.

12:28:10.530 --> 12:28:14.090
My conscience told me that I deserved no extraordinary politeness,

12:28:14.470 --> 12:28:17.590
and I confess that I did not expect to receive more than my due.

12:28:18.630 --> 12:28:24.130
My object then, replied Darcy, was to show you, by every civility in my power,

12:28:24.510 --> 12:28:27.210
that I was not so mean as to resent the past,

12:28:27.210 --> 12:28:31.770
and I hoped to obtain your forgiveness, to lessen your ill opinion,

12:28:32.050 --> 12:28:35.210
by letting you see that your reproofs had been attended to.

12:28:35.790 --> 12:28:39.330
How soon any other wishes introduced themselves I can hardly tell,

12:28:39.870 --> 12:28:43.170
but I believe in about half an hour after I had seen you.

12:28:43.990 --> 12:28:47.250
He then told her of Georgiana's delight in her acquaintance,

12:28:47.390 --> 12:28:50.090
and of her disappointment at its sudden interruption,

12:28:50.610 --> 12:28:53.410
which naturally leading to the cause of that interruption,

12:28:53.410 --> 12:28:57.570
she soon learned that his resolution of following her from Derbyshire

12:28:57.570 --> 12:29:02.190
in quest of her sister had been formed before he quitted the inn,

12:29:02.450 --> 12:29:07.370
and that his gravity and thoughtfulness there had arisen from no other struggles

12:29:07.370 --> 12:29:09.810
than what such a purpose must comprehend.

12:29:11.050 --> 12:29:13.250
She expressed her gratitude again,

12:29:13.530 --> 12:29:17.250
but it was too painful a subject to each to be dwelt on farther.

12:29:18.150 --> 12:29:21.210
After walking several miles in a leisurely manner,

12:29:21.210 --> 12:29:23.590
and too busy to know anything about it,

12:29:23.830 --> 12:29:26.150
they found at last, on examining their watches,

12:29:26.610 --> 12:29:28.170
that it was time to be at home.

12:29:28.950 --> 12:29:31.330
What would become of Mr. Bingley and Jane

12:29:31.330 --> 12:29:34.990
was a wonder which introduced the discussion of their affairs.

12:29:36.010 --> 12:29:37.830
Darcy was delighted with their engagement.

12:29:38.130 --> 12:29:40.850
His friend had given him the earliest information of it.

12:29:41.430 --> 12:29:45.030
I must ask whether you were surprised, said Elizabeth.

12:29:45.570 --> 12:29:49.030
Not at all. When I went away I felt that it would soon happen.

12:29:49.570 --> 12:29:53.510
That is to say you had given your permission. I guessed as much.

12:29:54.350 --> 12:29:56.050
And though he exclaimed at the term,

12:29:56.130 --> 12:29:58.650
she found that it had been pretty much the case.

12:29:59.530 --> 12:30:02.630
On the evening before my going to London, said he,

12:30:02.910 --> 12:30:06.450
I made a confession to him which I believe I ought to have made long ago.

12:30:06.970 --> 12:30:10.190
I told him of all that had occurred to make my former interference

12:30:10.610 --> 12:30:13.130
in his affairs absurd and impertinent.

12:30:13.850 --> 12:30:17.310
His surprise was great. He had never had the slightest suspicion.

12:30:17.310 --> 12:30:21.010
I told him moreover that I believed myself mistaken

12:30:21.010 --> 12:30:24.930
in supposing, as I had done, that your sister was indifferent to him.

12:30:25.270 --> 12:30:29.150
And as I could easily perceive that his attachment to her was unabated,

12:30:29.550 --> 12:30:31.770
I felt no doubt of their happiness together.

12:30:32.890 --> 12:30:37.070
Elizabeth could not help smiling at his easy manner of directing his friend.

12:30:37.930 --> 12:30:41.030
Did you speak from your own observation, said she,

12:30:41.310 --> 12:30:43.510
when you told him that my sister loved him,

12:30:43.750 --> 12:30:46.070
or merely from my information last spring?

12:30:46.070 --> 12:30:50.170
From the former. I had narrowly observed her

12:30:50.170 --> 12:30:52.670
during the two visits which I had lately made here,

12:30:53.030 --> 12:30:54.730
and I was convinced of her affection.

12:30:55.870 --> 12:31:00.090
And your assurance of it, I suppose, carried immediate conviction to him.

12:31:00.830 --> 12:31:04.290
It did. Bingley is most unaffectedly modest.

12:31:04.850 --> 12:31:09.790
His diffidence had prevented his depending on his own judgment in so anxious a case,

12:31:10.170 --> 12:31:13.150
but his reliance on mine made everything easy.

12:31:13.150 --> 12:31:19.070
I was obliged to confess one thing, which for a time, and not unjustly, offended him.

12:31:19.490 --> 12:31:24.450
I could not allow myself to conceal that your sister had been in town three months last winter,

12:31:24.910 --> 12:31:27.710
that I had known it and purposely kept it from him.

12:31:28.210 --> 12:31:32.110
He was angry, but his anger I am persuaded lest it no longer

12:31:32.110 --> 12:31:34.990
than he remained in any doubt of your sister's sentiments.

12:31:35.790 --> 12:31:37.870
He has heartily forgiven me now.

12:31:39.070 --> 12:31:43.570
Elizabeth longed to observe that Mr. Bingley had been a most delightful friend,

12:31:44.010 --> 12:31:46.890
so easily guided that his worth was invaluable.

12:31:47.570 --> 12:31:48.790
But she checked herself.

12:31:49.430 --> 12:31:52.490
She remembered that he had yet to learn to be laughed at,

12:31:52.650 --> 12:31:54.590
and it was rather too early to begin.

12:31:55.710 --> 12:31:57.730
In anticipating the happiness of Bingley,

12:31:57.990 --> 12:32:00.890
which of course was to be inferior only to his own,

12:32:01.230 --> 12:32:04.070
he continued the conversation till they reached the house.

12:32:04.670 --> 12:32:06.730
In the hall they parted.

12:32:37.530 --> 12:32:40.990
XXXIX My dear Lizzy, where can you have been walking

12:32:40.990 --> 12:32:46.730
to?" was a question which Elizabeth received from Jane as soon as she entered their room,

12:32:46.970 --> 12:32:49.890
and from all the others when they sat down to the table.

12:32:50.830 --> 12:32:55.550
She had only to say in reply that they had wandered about till she was beyond her own

12:32:55.550 --> 12:32:56.010
knowledge.

12:32:56.710 --> 12:33:02.590
She colored as she spoke, but neither that nor anything else awakened a suspicion of

12:33:02.590 --> 12:33:03.170
the truth.

12:33:04.110 --> 12:33:08.230
The evening passed quietly, unmarked by anything extraordinary.

12:33:08.870 --> 12:33:13.630
The acknowledged lovers talked and laughed, the unacknowledged were silent.

12:33:14.410 --> 12:33:21.090
Darcy was not of a disposition in which happiness overflows in mirth, and Elizabeth, agitated

12:33:21.090 --> 12:33:27.710
and confused, rather knew that she was happy than felt herself to be so, for besides the

12:33:27.710 --> 12:33:31.650
immediate embarrassment there were other evils before her.

12:33:32.130 --> 12:33:36.570
She anticipated what would be felt in the family when her situation became known.

12:33:37.000 --> 12:33:42.350
She was aware that no one liked him but Jane, and even feared that with the others it was

12:33:42.350 --> 12:33:46.470
a dislike which not all his fortune and consequence might do away.

12:33:47.590 --> 12:33:50.130
At night she opened her heart to Jane.

12:33:50.870 --> 12:33:56.790
Though suspicion was very far from Miss Bennet's general habits, she was absolutely incredulous

12:33:56.790 --> 12:33:57.310
here.

12:33:57.890 --> 12:33:59.450
"'You are joking, Lizzy.

12:33:59.670 --> 12:34:00.770
This cannot be.

12:34:00.950 --> 12:34:02.480
Engage to Mr. Darcy?'

12:34:02.880 --> 12:34:04.820
No, no, you shall not deceive me.

12:34:04.820 --> 12:34:06.260
I know it to be impossible.

12:34:07.680 --> 12:34:09.580
This is a wretched beginning, indeed.

12:34:10.040 --> 12:34:15.760
My sole dependence was on you, and I am sure nobody else will believe me, if you do not.

12:34:16.320 --> 12:34:18.280
Yet, indeed, I am in earnest.

12:34:18.540 --> 12:34:20.000
I speak nothing but the truth.

12:34:20.420 --> 12:34:23.900
He still loves me, and we are engaged.'

12:34:23.900 --> 12:34:25.640
Jane looked at her doubtingly.

12:34:25.920 --> 12:34:27.740
"'Oh, Lizzy, it cannot be.

12:34:27.860 --> 12:34:30.020
I know how much you dislike him.'

12:34:30.400 --> 12:34:32.020
You know nothing of the matter.

12:34:32.280 --> 12:34:33.700
That is all to be forgot.

12:34:34.300 --> 12:34:39.940
Perhaps I did not always love him so well as I do now, but in such cases as these a

12:34:39.940 --> 12:34:41.640
good memory is unpardonable.

12:34:42.180 --> 12:34:46.320
This is the last time I shall ever remember it myself.'

12:34:46.320 --> 12:34:48.660
Miss Bennet still looked all amazement.

12:34:49.600 --> 12:34:53.660
Elizabeth again and more seriously assured her of its truth.

12:34:54.340 --> 12:34:55.260
"'Good Heaven!

12:34:55.440 --> 12:34:56.960
Can it really be so?

12:34:56.960 --> 12:34:59.720
Yet now I must believe you,' cried Jane.

12:35:00.220 --> 12:35:04.720
"'My dear, dear Lizzy, I would—I do congratulate you.

12:35:04.920 --> 12:35:10.040
But are you certain—forgive the question—are you quite certain that you can be happy with

12:35:10.040 --> 12:35:10.820
him?'

12:35:10.820 --> 12:35:12.900
"'There can be no doubt of that.

12:35:13.000 --> 12:35:16.920
It is settled between us already that we are to be the happiest couple in the world.

12:35:17.440 --> 12:35:21.120
But are you pleased, Jane, shall you like to have such a brother?'

12:35:21.740 --> 12:35:23.060
"'Very, very much.

12:35:23.260 --> 12:35:26.280
Nothing could give either Bingley or myself more delight.

12:35:26.620 --> 12:35:28.000
But we considered it.

12:35:28.140 --> 12:35:29.700
We talked of it as impossible.

12:35:30.560 --> 12:35:32.600
And do you really love him quite well enough?

12:35:32.920 --> 12:35:36.300
Oh, Lizzy, do anything rather than marry without affection.

12:35:36.860 --> 12:35:39.440
Are you quite sure that you feel what you ought to do?'

12:35:40.540 --> 12:35:41.500
"'Oh, yes.

12:35:41.520 --> 12:35:45.320
You will only think I feel more than I ought to do when I tell you all.'

12:35:46.100 --> 12:35:47.740
"'What do you mean?'

12:35:47.740 --> 12:35:51.260
"'Why, I must confess that I love him better than I do Bingley.

12:35:51.520 --> 12:35:53.320
I am afraid you will be angry.'

12:35:54.280 --> 12:35:57.060
"'My dearest sister, now be serious.

12:35:57.160 --> 12:35:59.060
I want to talk very seriously.

12:35:59.560 --> 12:36:02.760
Let me know everything that I am to know without delay.

12:36:03.260 --> 12:36:05.700
Will you tell me how long you have loved him?'

12:36:05.700 --> 12:36:10.040
"'It has been coming on so gradually that I hardly know when it began.

12:36:10.520 --> 12:36:15.580
But I believe I must date it from my first seeing his beautiful grounds at Pemberley.'

12:36:16.300 --> 12:36:21.080
Another entreaty that she would be serious, however, produced the desired effect, and

12:36:21.080 --> 12:36:25.000
She soon satisfied Jane by her solemn assurances of attachment.

12:36:25.840 --> 12:36:29.520
When convinced on that article, Miss Bennet had nothing further to wish.

12:36:30.260 --> 12:36:35.000
"'Now I am quite happy,' said she, "'for you will be as happy as myself.

12:36:35.500 --> 12:36:37.760
I always had a value for him.

12:36:38.320 --> 12:36:42.380
Were it for nothing but his love of you, I must always have esteemed him.

12:36:42.620 --> 12:36:48.520
But now, as Bingley's friend and your husband, there can be only Bingley and yourself more

12:36:48.520 --> 12:36:49.360
dear to me.'

12:36:50.040 --> 12:36:53.740
"'But, Lizzie, you have been very sly, very reserved with me.

12:36:54.080 --> 12:36:57.340
How little did you tell me of what passed at Pemberley and Lambton?

12:36:57.760 --> 12:37:01.820
I owe all that I know of it to another, not to you.'

12:37:02.240 --> 12:37:04.440
Elizabeth told her the motives of her secrecy.

12:37:04.860 --> 12:37:09.600
She had been unwilling to mention Bingley, and the unsettled state of her own feelings

12:37:09.600 --> 12:37:12.200
had made her equally avoid the name of his friend.

12:37:12.780 --> 12:37:17.600
But now she would no longer conceal from her his share in Lydia's marriage.

12:37:17.600 --> 12:37:21.680
All was acknowledged, and half the night spent in conversation.

12:37:24.240 --> 12:37:28.480
"'Good gracious!' cried Mrs. Bennet, as she stood at a window the next morning.

12:37:28.740 --> 12:37:33.080
"'If that disagreeable Mr. Darcy is not coming here again with our dear Bingley.

12:37:33.400 --> 12:37:37.320
What can he mean by being so tiresome as to be always coming here?

12:37:37.600 --> 12:37:41.900
I had no notion that he would go a shooting or something or other and not disturb us with

12:37:41.900 --> 12:37:42.520
his company.

12:37:43.020 --> 12:37:44.720
What shall we do with him?

12:37:44.720 --> 12:37:49.800
Lizzy, you must walk out with him again, that he may not be in Bingley's way.'

12:37:49.800 --> 12:37:55.320
Elizabeth could hardly help laughing at so convenient a proposal, yet was really vexed

12:37:55.320 --> 12:37:58.420
that her mother should be always giving him such an epithet.

12:37:59.280 --> 12:38:04.140
As soon as they entered, Bingley looked at her so expressively, and shook hands with

12:38:04.140 --> 12:38:09.160
such warmth as left no doubt of his good information, and he soon afterwards said aloud,

12:38:09.880 --> 12:38:14.700
"'Mrs. Bennet, have you no more lanes hereabouts, in which Lizzy may lose her way again

12:38:14.700 --> 12:38:16.100
to-day?'

12:38:16.100 --> 12:38:21.720
"'I advise Mr. Darcy and Lizzy and Kitty,' said Mrs. Bennet, "'to walk to Ocom Mount

12:38:21.720 --> 12:38:22.500
this morning.

12:38:22.600 --> 12:38:26.360
It is a nice long walk, and Mr. Darcy has never seen the view.'

12:38:27.340 --> 12:38:32.640
"'It may do very well for the others,' replied Bingley, "'but I am sure it will be too much

12:38:32.640 --> 12:38:33.120
for Kitty.

12:38:33.740 --> 12:38:35.100
Won't it, Kitty?'

12:38:35.100 --> 12:38:37.380
Kitty owned that she had rather stay at home.

12:38:38.180 --> 12:38:43.880
Darcy professed a great curiosity to see the view from the Mount, and Elizabeth silently

12:38:43.880 --> 12:38:44.560
consented.

12:38:45.340 --> 12:38:50.700
As she went upstairs to get ready, Mrs. Bennet followed her, saying, "'I am quite sorry, Lizzy,

12:38:50.720 --> 12:38:55.620
that you should be forced to have that disagreeable man all to yourself, but I hope you will not

12:38:55.620 --> 12:38:56.140
mind it.

12:38:56.260 --> 12:39:00.740
It is all for Jane's sake, you know, and there is no occasion for talking to him except just

12:39:00.740 --> 12:39:04.920
now and then, so do not put yourself to inconvenience.'

12:39:05.560 --> 12:39:09.960
During their walk it was resolved that Mr. Bennet's consent should be asked in the course

12:39:09.960 --> 12:39:10.720
of the evening.

12:39:11.360 --> 12:39:15.240
Elizabeth reserved to herself the application for her mother's.

12:39:15.280 --> 12:39:19.820
She could not determine how her mother would take it, sometimes doubting whether all his

12:39:19.820 --> 12:39:23.720
wealth and grandeur would be enough to overcome her abhorrence of the man.

12:39:24.320 --> 12:39:29.040
But whether she were violently set against the match, or violently delighted with it,

12:39:29.380 --> 12:39:34.380
it was certain that her manner would be equally ill-adapted to do credit to her sons, and

12:39:34.380 --> 12:39:39.320
she could no more bear that Mr. Darcy should hear the first raptures of her joy than the

12:39:39.320 --> 12:39:41.720
first vehemence of her disapprobation.

12:39:43.080 --> 12:39:48.620
In the evening, soon after Mr. Bennet withdrew to the library, she saw Mr. Darcy rise also

12:39:48.620 --> 12:39:52.700
and follow him, and her agitation on seeing it was extreme.

12:39:53.400 --> 12:39:58.320
She did not fear her father's opposition, but he was going to be made unhappy, and that

12:39:58.320 --> 12:40:03.540
it should be through her means that she, his favorite child, should be distressing him

12:40:03.540 --> 12:40:09.260
by her choice, should be filling him with fears and regrets in disposing of her, was

12:40:09.260 --> 12:40:15.100
a wretched reflection, and she sat in misery till Mr. Darcy appeared again, when, looking

12:40:15.100 --> 12:40:18.260
at him, she was a little relieved by his smile.

12:40:19.020 --> 12:40:23.700
In a few minutes he approached the table where she was sitting with Kitty, and while pretending

12:40:23.700 --> 12:40:26.220
to admire her work, said in a whisper,

12:40:27.000 --> 12:40:29.240
Go to your father, he wants you in the library.

12:40:30.120 --> 12:40:31.620
She was gone directly.

12:40:32.560 --> 12:40:36.120
Her father was walking about the room, looking grave and anxious.

12:40:37.020 --> 12:40:39.300
Lizzy, said he, what are you doing?

12:40:39.600 --> 12:40:41.960
Are you out of your senses to be accepting this man?

12:40:42.440 --> 12:40:43.900
Have not you always hated him?

12:40:44.660 --> 12:40:50.660
How earnestly did she then wish that her former opinions had been more reasonable, her expressions

12:40:50.660 --> 12:40:51.620
more moderate.

12:40:52.020 --> 12:40:56.700
It would have spared her from explanations and professions which it was exceedingly awkward

12:40:56.700 --> 12:41:02.180
to give, but they were now necessary, and she assured him, with some confusion, of her

12:41:02.180 --> 12:41:03.560
attachment to Mr. Darcy.

12:41:04.340 --> 12:41:06.940
Or, in other words, you are determined to have him.

12:41:07.100 --> 12:41:12.120
He is rich, to be sure, and you may have more fine clothes and fine carriages than Jane,

12:41:12.680 --> 12:41:14.140
but will they make you happy?

12:41:15.100 --> 12:41:19.580
Have you any other objection, said Elizabeth, than your belief of my indifference?

12:41:20.300 --> 12:41:21.140
None at all.

12:41:21.340 --> 12:41:25.800
We all know him to be a proud, unpleasant sort of man, but this would be nothing if

12:41:25.800 --> 12:41:26.920
you really liked him.

12:41:27.440 --> 12:41:31.580
I do, I do like him, she replied with tears in her eyes.

12:41:31.800 --> 12:41:32.960
I love him.

12:41:32.960 --> 12:41:35.680
Indeed, he has no improper pride.

12:41:36.140 --> 12:41:37.560
He is perfectly amiable.

12:41:38.060 --> 12:41:39.920
You do not know what he really is.

12:41:40.260 --> 12:41:43.660
Then pray do not pain me by speaking of him in such terms.

12:41:44.860 --> 12:41:48.180
Lizzie, said her father, I have given him my consent.

12:41:48.740 --> 12:41:53.500
He is the kind of man, indeed, to whom I should never dare refuse anything which he condescended

12:41:53.500 --> 12:41:54.200
to ask.

12:41:54.760 --> 12:41:58.220
I now give it to you, if you are resolved on having him.

12:41:58.780 --> 12:42:01.060
But let me advise you to think better of it.

12:42:01.060 --> 12:42:03.180
I know your disposition, Lizzie.

12:42:03.580 --> 12:42:08.340
I know that you could be neither happy nor respectable unless you truly esteemed your

12:42:08.340 --> 12:42:11.560
husband, unless you looked up to him as a superior.

12:42:12.300 --> 12:42:16.900
Your lively talents would place you in the greatest danger in an unequal marriage.

12:42:17.480 --> 12:42:20.000
You could scarcely escape discredit and misery.

12:42:20.820 --> 12:42:25.540
My child, let me not have the grief of seeing you unable to respect your partner in life.

12:42:25.960 --> 12:42:27.880
You know not what you are about.

12:42:29.000 --> 12:42:33.540
Elizabeth, still more affected, was earnest and solemn in her reply.

12:42:33.920 --> 12:42:39.360
And at length, by repeated assurances that Mr. Darcy was really the object of her choice,

12:42:39.880 --> 12:42:45.100
by explaining the gradual change which her estimation of him had undergone, relating

12:42:45.100 --> 12:42:50.160
her absolute certainty that his affection was not the work of a day, but had stood the

12:42:50.160 --> 12:42:56.520
test of many months' suspense, and enumerating with energy all his good qualities, she did

12:42:56.520 --> 12:43:00.580
conquer her father's incredulity and reconcile him to the match.

12:43:01.500 --> 12:43:06.120
Well, my dear, said he when she ceased speaking, I have no more to say.

12:43:06.860 --> 12:43:08.820
If this be the case, he deserves you.

12:43:09.120 --> 12:43:12.900
I could not have parted with you, my Lizzie, to any one less worthy.

12:43:14.000 --> 12:43:19.240
To complete the favorable impression, she then told him what Mr. Darcy had voluntarily

12:43:19.240 --> 12:43:20.140
done for Lydia.

12:43:20.860 --> 12:43:22.620
He heard her with astonishment.

12:43:23.320 --> 12:43:25.560
This is an evening of wonders indeed.

12:43:26.120 --> 12:43:31.280
And so Darcy did everything, made up the match, gave them money, paid the fellows' debts,

12:43:31.320 --> 12:43:32.440
and got him his commission.

12:43:33.300 --> 12:43:34.280
So much the better.

12:43:34.800 --> 12:43:37.060
It will save me a world of trouble and economy.

12:43:37.700 --> 12:43:40.880
Had it been your uncle's doing, I must and would have paid him.

12:43:41.220 --> 12:43:44.480
But these violent young lovers carry everything their own way.

12:43:45.100 --> 12:43:46.700
I shall offer to pay him tomorrow.

12:43:47.020 --> 12:43:50.520
He will rant and storm about his love for you, and there will be an end of the matter.

12:43:51.420 --> 12:43:56.680
He then recollected her embarrassment a few days before, on his reading Mr. Collins's

12:43:56.680 --> 12:44:03.040
letter, and after laughing at her some time, allowed her at last to go, saying as she quitted

12:44:03.040 --> 12:44:03.580
the room,

12:44:04.180 --> 12:44:08.860
If any young men come for Mary or Kitty, send them in, for I am quite at leisure.

12:44:10.420 --> 12:44:15.760
Elizabeth's mind was now relieved from a very heavy weight, and after half an hour's quiet

12:44:15.760 --> 12:44:20.600
reflection in her own room, she was able to join the others with tolerable composure.

12:44:21.600 --> 12:44:26.340
Everything was too recent for gaiety, but the evening passed tranquilly away.

12:44:26.820 --> 12:44:32.260
There was no longer anything material to be dreaded, and the comfort of ease and familiarity

12:44:32.260 --> 12:44:33.600
would come in time.

12:44:34.600 --> 12:44:39.760
When her mother went up to her dressing-room at night, she followed her, and made the important

12:44:39.760 --> 12:44:40.560
communication.

12:44:41.360 --> 12:44:47.720
Its effect was most extraordinary, for on first hearing it, Mrs. Bennet sat quite still,

12:44:48.160 --> 12:44:49.760
and unable to utter a syllable.

12:44:50.760 --> 12:44:55.900
Nor was it under many, many minutes that she could comprehend what she heard, though not

12:44:55.900 --> 12:45:00.540
in general backward to credit what was for the advantage of her family, or that came

12:45:00.540 --> 12:45:02.560
in the shape of a lover to any of them.

12:45:03.240 --> 12:45:09.820
She began, at length, to recover, to fidget about in her chair, get up, sit down again,

12:45:09.820 --> 12:45:11.360
wonder, and bless herself.

12:45:12.060 --> 12:45:12.740
Good gracious!

12:45:13.400 --> 12:45:14.200
Lord bless me!

12:45:14.260 --> 12:45:14.980
Only think!

12:45:15.480 --> 12:45:16.320
Dear me!

12:45:16.560 --> 12:45:17.460
Mr. Darcy!

12:45:17.960 --> 12:45:19.020
Who would have thought it?

12:45:19.400 --> 12:45:20.560
And is it really true?

12:45:21.220 --> 12:45:22.600
Oh, my sweetest Lizzie!

12:45:22.840 --> 12:45:24.740
How rich and how great you will be!

12:45:25.080 --> 12:45:25.960
What pin-money!

12:45:26.340 --> 12:45:26.940
What jewels!

12:45:27.120 --> 12:45:28.460
What carriages you will have!

12:45:29.020 --> 12:45:31.040
Jane's is nothing to it, nothing at all!

12:45:31.420 --> 12:45:33.040
I am so pleased, so happy!

12:45:33.680 --> 12:45:34.740
Such a charming man!

12:45:34.800 --> 12:45:35.540
So handsome!

12:45:35.820 --> 12:45:36.560
So tall!

12:45:37.260 --> 12:45:38.320
Oh, my dear Lizzie!

12:45:38.440 --> 12:45:39.800
Pray apologize for my having displeased you!

12:45:39.800 --> 12:45:41.260
so much before.

12:45:41.620 --> 12:45:43.420
I hope he will overlook it.

12:45:43.840 --> 12:45:46.700
Dear, dear Lizzie, a house in town!

12:45:47.220 --> 12:45:48.940
Everything that is charming!

12:45:49.580 --> 12:45:52.560
Three daughters married, ten thousand a year!

12:45:53.120 --> 12:45:53.900
Oh, Lord!

12:45:54.300 --> 12:45:55.380
What will become of me?

12:45:55.520 --> 12:45:56.700
I shall go distracted.

12:45:57.800 --> 12:46:03.800
This was enough to prove that her approbation need not be doubted, and Elizabeth rejoicing

12:46:03.800 --> 12:46:07.920
that such an effusion was heard only by herself, soon went away.

12:46:07.920 --> 12:46:12.860
But before she had been three minutes in her own room, her mother followed her.

12:46:13.280 --> 12:46:16.800
My dearest child, she cried, I can think of nothing else.

12:46:17.220 --> 12:46:19.920
Ten thousand a year, and very likely more.

12:46:20.560 --> 12:46:23.320
This is as good as a lord, and a special license.

12:46:23.840 --> 12:46:26.480
You must and shall be married by a special license.

12:46:27.120 --> 12:46:31.300
But my dearest love, tell me what dish Mr. Darcy is particularly fond of, that I may

12:46:31.300 --> 12:46:32.220
have it to-morrow.

12:46:32.820 --> 12:46:38.960
This was a sad omen of what her mother's behavior to the gentleman himself might be, and Elizabeth

12:46:38.960 --> 12:46:44.500
found that, though in the certain possession of his warmest affection, and secure of her

12:46:44.500 --> 12:46:48.180
relation's consent, there was still something to be wished for.

12:46:48.520 --> 12:46:53.600
But the morrow passed off much better than she expected, for Mrs. Bennet luckily stood

12:46:53.600 --> 12:46:59.020
in such awe of her intended son-in-law, that she ventured not to speak to him, unless it

12:46:59.020 --> 12:47:03.780
was in her power to offer him any attention, or mark her deference for his opinion.

12:47:04.840 --> 12:47:09.320
Elizabeth had the satisfaction of seeing her father taking pains to get acquainted with

12:47:09.320 --> 12:47:14.940
him, and Mr. Bennet soon assured her that he was rising every hour in his esteem.

12:47:15.540 --> 12:47:19.440
I admire all my three son-in-laws highly, said he.

12:47:20.060 --> 12:47:24.680
Wickham perhaps is my favorite, but I think I shall like your husband quite as well as

12:47:24.680 --> 12:47:25.660
Jane's.

12:47:50.460 --> 12:47:55.740
Elizabeth's spirits soon rising to playfulness

12:47:56.300 --> 12:48:00.800
She wanted Mr. Darcy to account for his having ever fallen in love with her.

12:48:01.260 --> 12:48:03.500
How could you begin? said she.

12:48:04.220 --> 12:48:10.840
I can comprehend your going uncharmingly when you had once made a beginning, but what could set you off in the first place?

12:48:11.860 --> 12:48:17.280
I cannot fix on the hour, or the spot, or the look, or the words which laid the foundation.

12:48:17.900 --> 12:48:22.480
It is too long ago. I was in the middle before I knew that I had begun.

12:48:23.460 --> 12:48:31.420
My beauty you had early withstood, and as for my manners, my behaviour to you was at least always bordering on the uncivil,

12:48:31.880 --> 12:48:35.280
and I never spoke to you without rather wishing to give you pain than not.

12:48:35.880 --> 12:48:39.420
Now be sincere. Did you admire me for my impertinence?

12:48:40.160 --> 12:48:42.560
For the liveliness of your mind, I did.

12:48:43.260 --> 12:48:47.440
You may as well call it impertinence at once. It was very little less.

12:48:47.440 --> 12:48:52.820
The fact is that you were sick of civility, of deference, of officious attention.

12:48:53.320 --> 12:48:59.040
You were disgusted with the women who were always speaking and looking and thinking for your approbation alone.

12:48:59.820 --> 12:49:03.360
I roused and interested you, because I was so unlike them.

12:49:04.140 --> 12:49:07.600
Had you not been really amiable, you would have hated me for it.

12:49:07.920 --> 12:49:13.720
But in spite of the pains you took to disguise yourself, your feelings were always noble and just,

12:49:13.720 --> 12:49:19.420
and in your heart you thoroughly despised the persons who so assiduously courted you.

12:49:20.240 --> 12:49:27.040
There I have saved you the trouble of accounting for it, and really all things considered, I begin to think it perfectly reasonable.

12:49:27.780 --> 12:49:33.260
To be sure, you knew no actual good of me, but nobody thinks of that when they fall in love.

12:49:34.560 --> 12:49:38.740
Was there no good in your affectionate behaviour to Jane while she was ill at Netherfield?

12:49:40.140 --> 12:49:45.260
Dearest Jane, who could have done less for her? But make a virtue of it by all means.

12:49:45.700 --> 12:49:50.120
My good qualities are under your protection, and you are to exaggerate them as much as possible,

12:49:50.520 --> 12:49:55.860
and in return it belongs to me to find occasions for teasing and quarrelling with you as often as may be.

12:49:56.340 --> 12:50:01.520
And I shall begin directly by asking you what made you so unwilling to come to the point at last?

12:50:01.980 --> 12:50:06.180
What made you so shy of me when you first called, and afterwards dined here?

12:50:06.180 --> 12:50:11.060
Why, especially when you called, did you look as if you did not care about me?

12:50:11.780 --> 12:50:18.240
Because you were grave and silent, and gave me no encouragement. But I was embarrassed, and so was I.

12:50:19.020 --> 12:50:24.060
You might have talked to me more when you came to dinner. A man who had felt less might.

12:50:25.000 --> 12:50:31.280
How unlucky that you should have a reasonable answer to give, and that I should be so reasonable as to admit it.

12:50:31.280 --> 12:50:35.460
But I wonder how long you would have gone on if you had been left to yourself.

12:50:36.200 --> 12:50:39.380
I wonder when you would have spoken if I had not asked you.

12:50:39.920 --> 12:50:44.240
My resolution of thanking you for your kindness to Lydia had certainly great effect.

12:50:44.720 --> 12:50:50.420
Too much I am afraid. For what becomes of the moral if our comfort springs from a breach of promise?

12:50:50.900 --> 12:50:54.520
For I ought not to have mentioned this subject. This will never do.

12:50:55.500 --> 12:50:59.540
You need not distrust yourself. The moral will be perfectly fair.

12:50:59.540 --> 12:51:05.360
Lady Catherine's unjustifiable endeavors to separate us were the means of removing all my doubts.

12:51:06.140 --> 12:51:11.100
I am not indebted from my present happiness to your eager desire of expressing your gratitude.

12:51:11.660 --> 12:51:14.600
I was not in humor to wait for any opening of yours.

12:51:15.340 --> 12:51:19.880
My aunt's intelligence had given me hope, and I was determined at once to know everything.

12:51:21.220 --> 12:51:26.460
Lady Catherine has been of infinite use, which ought to make her happy, for she loves to be of use.

12:51:26.460 --> 12:51:30.500
But tell me, what did you come down to Netherfield for?

12:51:30.960 --> 12:51:36.800
Was it merely to ride to Longbourn and be embarrassed, or had you intended any more serious consequence?

12:51:37.740 --> 12:51:44.160
My real purpose was to see you, and to judge, if I could, whether I might ever hope to make you love me.

12:51:44.720 --> 12:51:50.660
My avowed one, or what I avowed to myself, was to see whether your sister were still partial to Bingley,

12:51:51.040 --> 12:51:54.840
and if she were, to make the confession to him which I have since made.

12:51:55.860 --> 12:51:59.980
Shall you ever have courage to announce to Lady Catherine what is to befall her?

12:52:00.800 --> 12:52:05.340
I am more likely to want more time than courage, Elizabeth, but it ought to be done,

12:52:05.480 --> 12:52:08.560
and if he will give me a sheet of paper, it shall be done directly.

12:52:09.620 --> 12:52:15.280
And if I had not a letter to write myself, I might sit by you and admire the evenness of your writing,

12:52:15.660 --> 12:52:21.340
as another young lady once did, but I have an aunt, too, who must not be longer neglected.

12:52:22.180 --> 12:52:27.880
From an unwillingness to confess how much her intimacy with Mr. Darcy had been overrated,

12:52:28.440 --> 12:52:31.780
Elizabeth had never yet answered Mrs. Gardiner's long letter.

12:52:32.260 --> 12:52:36.300
But now, having that to communicate which she knew would be most welcome,

12:52:36.700 --> 12:52:41.200
she was almost ashamed to find that her uncle and aunt had already lost three days of happiness,

12:52:41.740 --> 12:52:43.720
and immediately wrote as follows.

12:52:44.500 --> 12:52:48.080
I would have thanked you before, my dear aunt, as I ought to have done,

12:52:48.080 --> 12:52:52.380
for your long, kind, satisfactory detail of particulars,

12:52:52.800 --> 12:52:55.140
but to say the truth I was too cross to write.

12:52:55.820 --> 12:52:57.980
You supposed more than really existed.

12:52:58.620 --> 12:53:00.880
But now, suppose as much as you choose.

12:53:01.380 --> 12:53:03.360
Give a loose rein to your fancy.

12:53:03.920 --> 12:53:08.000
Indulge your imagination in every possible flight which the subject will afford.

12:53:08.680 --> 12:53:12.380
And unless you believe me actually married, you cannot greatly err.

12:53:13.000 --> 12:53:17.260
You must write again very soon and praise him a great deal more than you did in your last.

12:53:17.260 --> 12:53:21.460
I thank you again and again for not going to the lakes.

12:53:22.080 --> 12:53:24.460
How could I be so silly as to wish it?

12:53:24.920 --> 12:53:26.900
Your idea of the ponies is delightful.

12:53:27.520 --> 12:53:29.520
We will go round the park every day.

12:53:30.200 --> 12:53:32.500
I am the happiest creature in the world.

12:53:32.960 --> 12:53:37.160
Perhaps other people have said so before, but not one with such justice.

12:53:37.780 --> 12:53:39.280
I'm happier even than Jane.

12:53:39.900 --> 12:53:42.500
She only smiles. I laugh.

12:53:43.360 --> 12:53:46.980
Mr. Darcy sends you all the love in the world that he can spare from me.

12:53:46.980 --> 12:53:49.580
You are all to come to Pemberley at Christmas.

12:53:50.240 --> 12:53:51.220
Yours, etc.

12:53:52.820 --> 12:53:56.460
Mr. Darcy's letter to Lady Catherine was in a different style,

12:53:56.940 --> 12:54:02.120
and still different from either was what Mr. Bennet sent to Mr. Collins in reply to his last.

12:54:03.100 --> 12:54:07.460
Dear Sir, I must trouble you once more for congratulations.

12:54:08.280 --> 12:54:10.880
Elizabeth will soon be the wife of Mr. Darcy.

12:54:10.880 --> 12:54:13.900
Console Lady Catherine as well as you can.

12:54:14.320 --> 12:54:16.600
But if I were you, I would stand by the nephew.

12:54:17.280 --> 12:54:18.720
He has more to give.

12:54:19.920 --> 12:54:21.860
Yours sincerely, etc.

12:54:23.200 --> 12:54:29.720
Miss Bingley's congratulations to her brother on his approaching marriage were all that was affectionate and insincere.

12:54:30.280 --> 12:54:36.600
She wrote even to Jane on the occasion to express her delight and repeat all her former professions of regard.

12:54:36.600 --> 12:54:42.440
Jane was not deceived, but she was affected, and though feeling no reliance on her,

12:54:42.660 --> 12:54:46.120
could not help writing her a much kinder answer than she knew she deserved.

12:54:47.200 --> 12:54:54.320
The joy which Miss Darcy expressed on receiving similar information was as sincere as her brother's in sending it.

12:54:54.800 --> 12:55:01.820
Four sides of paper were insufficient to contain all her delight and her earnest desire of being loved by her sister.

12:55:02.680 --> 12:55:08.780
Before any answer could arrive from Mr. Collins, or any congratulations to Elizabeth from his wife,

12:55:09.240 --> 12:55:13.240
the Longbourn family heard that the Collinses were coming themselves to Lucas Lodge.

12:55:13.960 --> 12:55:16.600
The reason of this sudden removal was soon evident.

12:55:17.420 --> 12:55:21.980
Lady Catherine had been rendered so exceedingly angry by the contents of her nephew's letter

12:55:21.980 --> 12:55:27.940
that Charlotte, really rejoicing in the match, was anxious to get away till the storm was blown over.

12:55:28.600 --> 12:55:32.960
At such a moment the arrival of her friend was a sincere pleasure to Elizabeth,

12:55:33.520 --> 12:55:37.860
though in the course of their meetings she must sometimes think the pleasure dearly bought

12:55:37.860 --> 12:55:44.020
when she saw Mr. Darcy exposed to all the parading and obsequious civility of her husband.

12:55:44.800 --> 12:55:47.060
He bore it, however, with admirable calmness.

12:55:47.760 --> 12:55:53.920
He could even listen to Sir William Lucas when he complimented him on carrying away the brightest jewel of the country,

12:55:53.920 --> 12:55:59.800
and expressed his hopes of their all meeting frequently at St. James's with very decent composure.

12:56:00.520 --> 12:56:04.320
If he did shrug his shoulders, it was not till Sir William was out of sight.

12:56:05.620 --> 12:56:09.980
Mrs. Phillips's vulgarity was another, and perhaps a greater, tax on his forbearance,

12:56:10.680 --> 12:56:16.120
and though Mrs. Phillips, as well as her sister, stood in too much awe of him to speak with a familiarity

12:56:16.500 --> 12:56:21.920
which Bingley's good humour encouraged, yet whenever she did speak she must be vulgar.

12:56:21.920 --> 12:56:27.760
Nor was her respect for him, though it made her more quiet, at all likely to make her more elegant.

12:56:28.740 --> 12:56:32.420
Elizabeth did all she could to shield him from the frequent notice of either,

12:56:32.780 --> 12:56:39.260
and was ever anxious to keep him to herself, and to those of her family with whom he might converse without mortification,

12:56:39.620 --> 12:56:45.280
and though the uncomfortable feelings arising from all this took from the season of courtship much of its pleasure,

12:56:45.760 --> 12:56:47.540
it added to the hope of the future.

12:56:47.540 --> 12:56:54.300
And she looked forward with delight to the time when they should be removed from society so little pleasing to either,

12:56:54.760 --> 12:56:59.000
to all the comfort and elegance of their family party at Pemberley.

12:57:05.720 --> 12:57:12.100
Happy for all her maternal feelings was the day on which Mrs. Bennet got rid of her two most deserving daughters.

12:57:12.100 --> 12:57:19.220
With what delighted pride she afterwards visited Mrs. Bingley, and talked of Mrs. Darcy, may be guessed.

12:57:19.820 --> 12:57:25.000
I wish I could say, for the sake of her family, that the accomplishment of her earnest desire

12:57:25.000 --> 12:57:28.780
and the establishment of so many of her children produced so happy an effect

12:57:28.780 --> 12:57:33.460
as to make her a sensible, amiable, well-informed woman for the rest of her life,

12:57:33.900 --> 12:57:40.800
though perhaps it was lucky for her husband, who might not have relished domestic felicity in so unusual a form,

12:57:40.800 --> 12:57:45.020
that she still was occasionally nervous and invariably silly.

12:57:46.280 --> 12:57:48.640
Mr. Bennet missed his second daughter exceedingly.

12:57:49.200 --> 12:57:53.400
His affection for her drew him oftener from home than anything else could do.

12:57:54.120 --> 12:57:58.320
He delighted in going to Pemberley, especially when he was least expected.

12:57:59.420 --> 12:58:02.940
Mr. Bingley and Jane remained at Netherfield only a twelve month.

12:58:02.940 --> 12:58:11.800
So near a vicinity to her mother and Maryton relations was not desirable even to his easy temper or her affectionate heart.

12:58:12.520 --> 12:58:15.400
The darling wish of his sisters was then gratified.

12:58:15.680 --> 12:58:20.440
He bought an estate in a neighboring county to Derbyshire, and Jane and Elizabeth,

12:58:20.620 --> 12:58:25.440
in addition to every other source of happiness, were within thirty miles of each other.

12:58:26.720 --> 12:58:31.980
Kitty, to her very material advantage, spent the chief of her time with her two elder sisters.

12:58:31.980 --> 12:58:38.180
In society so superior to what she had generally known, her improvement was great.

12:58:39.000 --> 12:58:45.660
She was not of so ungovernable a temper as Lydia, and removed from the influence of Lydia's example,

12:58:46.160 --> 12:58:52.800
she became, by proper attention and management, less irritable, less ignorant, and less insipid.

12:58:53.460 --> 12:58:58.460
From the further disadvantage of Lydia's society she was of course carefully kept,

12:58:58.460 --> 12:59:02.400
and though Mrs. Wickham frequently invited her to come and stay with her,

12:59:02.680 --> 12:59:07.220
with the promise of balls and young men, her father would never consent to her going.

12:59:08.520 --> 12:59:14.460
Mary was the only daughter who remained at home, and she was necessarily drawn from the pursuit of accomplishments

12:59:14.460 --> 12:59:17.660
by Mrs. Bennet's being quite unable to sit alone.

12:59:18.680 --> 12:59:24.600
Mary was obliged to mix more with the world, but she could still moralize over every morning visit,

12:59:24.600 --> 12:59:29.880
and as she was no longer mortified by comparisons between her sister's beauty and her own,

12:59:30.480 --> 12:59:35.600
it was suspected by her father that she submitted to the change without much reluctance.

12:59:36.480 --> 12:59:41.780
As for Wickham and Lydia, their characters suffered no revolution from the marriage of her sisters.

12:59:42.640 --> 12:59:46.720
He bore with philosophy the conviction that Elizabeth must now become acquainted

12:59:46.720 --> 12:59:51.420
with whatever of his ingratitude and falsehood had before been unknown to her,

12:59:51.420 --> 12:59:57.880
and in spite of everything was not wholly without hope that Darcy might yet be prevailed on to make his fortune.

12:59:58.920 --> 13:00:02.960
The congratulatory letter which Elizabeth received from Lydia on her marriage

13:00:02.960 --> 13:00:08.580
explained to her that, by his wife at least, if not by himself, such a hope was cherished.

13:00:08.980 --> 13:00:10.500
The letter was to this effect.

13:00:12.100 --> 13:00:19.480
My dear Lizzie, I wish you joy. If you love Mr. Darcy half as well as I do, my dear Wickham, you must be very happy.

13:00:19.480 --> 13:00:25.780
It is a great comfort to have you so rich, and when you have nothing else to do, I hope you will think of us.

13:00:26.220 --> 13:00:33.000
I am sure Wickham would like a place at court very much, and I do not think we shall have quite money enough to live upon without some help.

13:00:33.620 --> 13:00:36.400
Any place would do, of about three or four hundred a year.

13:00:36.920 --> 13:00:42.060
But, however, do not speak to Mr. Darcy about it, if you had rather not. Yours, etc.

13:00:43.160 --> 13:00:51.320
As it happened that Elizabeth had much rather not, she endeavoured in her answer to put an end to every entreaty and expectation of the kind.

13:00:52.160 --> 13:01:01.720
Such relief, however, as it was in her power to afford, by the practice of what might be called economy in her own private expenses, she frequently sent them.

13:01:02.300 --> 13:01:11.260
It had always been evident to her that such an income as theirs, under the direction of two persons so extravagant in their wants and heedless of the future,

13:01:11.260 --> 13:01:23.620
must be very insufficient to their support, and whenever they changed their quarters, either Jane or herself were sure of being applied to for some little assistance towards discharging their bills.

13:01:24.440 --> 13:01:31.140
Their manner of living, even when the restoration of peace dismissed them to a home, was unsettled in the extreme.

13:01:31.920 --> 13:01:38.080
They were always moving from place to place in quest of a cheap situation, and always spending more than they ought.

13:01:38.080 --> 13:01:50.780
His affection for her soon sunk into indifference. Hers lasted a little longer, and in spite of her youth and her manners, she retained all the claims of reputation which her marriage had given her.

13:01:52.080 --> 13:01:59.320
Though Darcy could never receive him at Pemberley, yet, for Elizabeth's sake, he assisted him further in his profession.

13:02:00.020 --> 13:02:16.620
Lydia was occasionally a visitor there when her husband was gone to enjoy himself in London or Bath, and with the Bingleys, they both of them frequently stayed so long that even Bingley's good humor was overcome, and he proceeded so far as to talk of giving them a hint to be gone.

13:02:17.320 --> 13:02:36.320
Miss Bingley was very deeply mortified by Darcy's marriage, but as she thought it advisable to retain the right of visiting at Pemberley, she dropped all her resentment, was fonder than ever of Georgiana, almost as attentive to Darcy as heretofore, and paid off every arrear of civility to Elizabeth.

13:02:37.440 --> 13:02:58.580
Pemberley was now Georgiana's home, and the attachment of the sisters was exactly what Darcy had hoped to see. They were able to love each other even as well as they intended. Georgiana had the highest opinion in the world of Elizabeth, though at first she often listened with an astonishment bordering on alarm at her lively, sportive manner of talking to her brother.

13:02:59.200 --> 13:03:23.180
He who had always inspired in herself a respect which almost overcame her affection, she now saw the object of open pleasantry. Her mind received knowledge which had never before fallen in her way. By Elizabeth's instructions, she began to comprehend that a woman may take liberties with her husband, which her brother will not always allow in a sister more than ten years younger than himself.

13:03:24.140 --> 13:03:42.620
Lady Catherine was extremely indignant on the marriage of her nephew, and as she gave way to all the genuine frankness of her character in her reply to the letter which announced its arrangement, she sent him language so very abusive, especially of Elizabeth, that for some time all intercourse was at an end.

13:03:42.620 --> 13:04:02.000
But at length, by Elizabeth's persuasion, he was prevailed on to overlook the offence and seek a reconciliation, and after a little further resistance on the part of his aunt, her resentment gave way, either to her affection for him or her curiosity to see how his wife conducted herself.

13:04:02.000 --> 13:04:13.880
And she condescended to wait on them at Pemberley, in spite of that pollution which its woods had received, not merely from the presence of such a mistress, but the visits of her uncle and aunt from the city.

13:04:14.740 --> 13:04:31.580
With the gardeners, they were always on the most intimate terms. Darcy, as well as Elizabeth, really loved them, and they were both ever sensible of the warmest gratitude towards the persons who, by bringing her into Derbyshire, had been the means of uniting them.
